<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S MORTON EXPECTS TO MISS CAL GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC tailback Chad Morton said it would take a
``miracle'' for his strained back to feel well enough for him to
play against California on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Morton did not practice Wednesday, instead receiving treatment
from the USC trainers. He missed last week's game against Arizona
State and has not played since the third quarter of the Florida
State game.
</P>
<P>
   And even USC coach Paul Hackett was sounding less optimistic
that the Trojans' starting tailback would play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have to play a second game without him,'' Hackett said.
``I don't expect him to practice this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he is beginning to worry about Morton's
conditioning becoming an issue if he misses much more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're getting to that point,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger question is how USC's rushing game, which was
nonexistent against Arizona State, will respond without Morton for
a second straight week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know where we are offensively without Chad,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said either junior Petros Papadakis or freshman Frank
Strong would start. That's a slight change, because Hackett stated
firmly last week that Papadakis would start against Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle Matt Welch also missed practice with some
``bumps and bruises,'' but Hackett said he would practice today and
play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   No-fault play: Hackett said he did not believe Arizona State's
Grey Ruegamer made an illegal block from behind on defensive end
Marc Matock, on the play where Matock broke his ankle last
Saturday. He also said the play was not ``dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hackett said USC will still ask for a rules
interpretation about the play from the Pacific-10.
</P>
<P>
   Fire up the troops: Always searching for a way to motivate the
Trojans, Hackett found some bulletin-board material Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal's made a lot of noise that we are not the premier team,''
Hackett said. ``That we have crumbled and we're no longer a
dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's Oakland Tribune, Cal linebacker Sekou Sanyika
said: ``They're no different than the Beavers or the Ducks or the
Huskies. They're on the rise, trying to restore tradition. But that
all seems to be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Justin Vedder was even more emphatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the team they once were, obviously,'' Vedder said.
``But they're still arrogant. You don't really like playing a team
that already thinks that they're the national champions.... It's
personal with 'SC. It's where I'm from.''
</P>
<P>
   Whither the tight end? With tight end Antoine Harris catching
just four passes so far, Hackett is already being quizzed by
recruits if the Trojans are ever going to start throwing to the
tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   His answer is similar to the one he gives regarding other
players who have rarely seen the ball, like wide receiver Mike
Bastianelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the offense is in its infant stages,'' Hackett
said. ``We haven't figured out how to get him out in the passing
game. It's a reaction to the Florida State game, bringing everyone
in to block. As we feel more comfortable there, we'll throw more to
the tight end. Right now, we need to settle down the offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
