<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-BASELINE-1S     10-08 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BASELINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD DEFENSE EXPOSES MISSED CHANCES 
 (JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS to add quotes, recast emphasis on controversial play.)  By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For six months, baseball lived _ thrived _ on
offense. The Mark and Sammy show epitomized the theme of the season
and captivated the country. Home runs, however, were not the
deciding factor in the latest game. That was the one played
Wednesday at Yankee Stadium, and the outcome turned on bunts and
lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive bunt was Travis Fryman's in the 12th inning. That
was the one that seared Chuck Knoblauch into the minds of everyone
who saw the play as the reincarnation of Fred Merkle, who didn't
touch second base on an ostensible game-winning hit in a 1908
pennant-race game, and Mickey Owen, who missed what would have been
the game-ending strikeout in the 1941 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's blunder will be the play most remembered from the
Cleveland Indians' 4-1 victory over the Yankees that tied the
American League Championship Series at one game each. Forgotten
will be the inability of Tim Raines to put down a sacrifice bunt in
the seventh inning and the unwillingness of Manager Joe Torre to
have Shane Spencer sacrifice in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who squandered another nifty pitching performance
by David Cone, struggled against Charles Nagy and six Indian relief
pitchers. They needed every scoring opportunity they could muster
to keep their post-season unbeaten streak alive.
</P>
<P>
   Sacrifice bunts in those two innings might have helped. They
might even have led to a run or runs that would have precluded the
necessity of extra innings and spared Knoblauch the grief he will
endure for years.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were losing, 1-0, when Bernie Williams led off the
seventh with a single and Tino Martinez walked. Raines, the next
batter, was called on to sacrifice the runners to third and second.
It was an assignment he had not executed since September 1995, and
had not been asked to execute since October 1996. The rust showed.
</P>
<P>
   With one ball, Raines bunted but fouled off the pitch so hard
that it shot back toward the screen behind home plate as a line
drive. He got his bat in position to bunt the next pitch but pulled
the bat back only to have Ted Hendry, the plate umpire (remember
that name), call the pitch a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Raines then struck out for the third time in three times at bat.
Despite his failure to move the runners along, the Yankees scored
the tying run one out later on a double by Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   The game was still tied when Raines began the ninth with a
single. The younger, speedier Homer Bush went in to run for Raines
as Spencer went to the plate. He is the rookie who has hit all of
those home runs recently, and the manager wasn't about to ask him
to bunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not have bunted a whole lot,'' Torre said later. ``A
guy that hits 30 home runs, you don't ask him to bunt.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``That is just a call on my part, and as it turned
out, it was the wrong one.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer said he hadn't been asked to bunt much in recent years,
but, he added, ``I don't mind bunting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spencer was not asked to bunt, not before Bush stole second,
not after. Instead, for the only time in his five at-bats, he
struck out. Brosius was walked purposely, and Jorge Posada grounded
into a double play that sent the game into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th inning of Game 4 of the 1969 World Series, Baltimore
pitcher Pete Richert fielded J.C. Martin's sacrifice bunt, threw to
first and hit Martin on the left wrist. As the ball rolled into the
outfield, Rod Gaspar scored from second, and the New York Mets won
the game, then won the next one, too, and the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of the play subsequently showed that Martin had run to
first base on the fair, or wrong, side of the baseline. But the
Orioles did not notice it or argue it at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees argued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With Enrique Wilson at first running for Jim Thome, Fryman
bunted toward first, Martinez fielded the ball and turned and threw
to Knoblauch, who was covering first. The ball hit Fryman in the
back, right on the 7 of his uniform No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The ball caromed beyond Fryman and Knoblauch onto the infield
dirt. Instead of retrieving the ball to keep Wilson from advancing
too far, Knoblauch stood at the base pointing to where he believed
Fryman had run. Knoblauch was right about Fryman's path _ on the
fair side of the line _ but he was wrong, oh was he wrong, for
ignoring the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't have an idea where the ball was,'' Knoblauch
said. ``My intentions weren't not to chase the ball. You've got to
play the play out. Everything just seemed to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson didn't. He raced all the way home with the tie-breaking
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees blamed Hendry for not calling Fryman out for
interference, but Jim Evans, the crew chief, explained that no
matter what Fryman's path to first was, the ball hit him as he
stepped on or was about to step on the base and he was entitled to
be in fair territory when he reached the base because the base was
in fair territory.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, when he pitched for the Mets, Cone pulled a
Knoblauch, holding the ball, arguing with the umpire about the call
at first and letting not one but two runs score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think much about it anymore,'' Cone said. ``It
was so long ago. At the time I stood up and took responsibility for
the blunder and put it behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   This one won't be behind Knoblauch for a long time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
