<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-1STLD-     10-08 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYT-CBS POLL SHOWS SCHUMER, D'AMATO IN TIGHT RACE FOR SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(subs for additional details throughout; story grows by about 600
words and is now 2 takes)  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``a'') 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY with MARJORIE CONNELLY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato and Democratic Rep. Charles
Schumer are locked in an extraordinarily tight race for the U.S.
Senate in New York. The outcome apparently rests with a small group
of undecided voters, many of whom are not yet paying attention to
the contest, a statewide New York Times/CBS News Poll has found.
</P>
<P>
   With a month to go until the election, the poll found that 60
percent of the respondents were unable to offer an opinion of
Schumer, favorable or unfavorable. At the same time, a sizable
number of voters, including some of the senator's own supporters,
have reservations about D'Amato's ethics and ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Among registered voters, 44 percent favored Schumer and 41
percent D'Amato. Among likely voters, Schumer had 47 percent to
D'Amato's 43 percent. The poll, based on interviews with 1,066
voters, has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The poll's findings suggest two dynamics that will shape the
contest in its final weeks: a competition between both camps to
define Schumer's public personality among voters who do not know
him, and an attempt by the Brooklyn congressman to exploit what the
poll suggests are the liabilities D'Amato has as a three-term
Republican senator in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The race has emerged as one of the most closely watched in the
nation. D'Amato, a Republican senator in a traditionally Democratic
state, faces in Schumer his best-financed opponent since his
election in 1980. Schumer has matched D'Amato's aggressive stance
with his own forceful style.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this contest is shaping up as a replay of the 1992
race, when D'Amato ran against Robert Abrams, then the state
attorney general. A Times poll in the third week of October 1992
found D'Amato in an effective tie with his Democratic challenger.
D'Amato ultimately defeated Abrams by a single percentage point
after a searing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But this latest Times/CBS News poll points to several ways in
which this contest is different from 1992, and that is not
necessarily good news for D'Amato. An equal number of voters now
view D'Amato and Schumer as serious in dealing with crime, evidence
that the nine-term congressman has achieved some success in
neutralizing a traditionally Republican issue.
</P>
<P>
   While D'Amato is widely viewed as ``the kind of person who gets
things done for the voters'' _ clearly one of his biggest
advantages _ a substantial number of respondents said that he was
lacking in honesty and integrity, and that he did not care ``about
the needs and problems of people like you.'' Schumer scored
strongly on both measures.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most strikingly, D'Amato's intense effort to derail
Schumer's campaign with a series of attacks in the last three weeks
_ from portraying him as a liberal to spotlighting votes he has
missed in Washington as he campaigned in New York this year _ has
yet to show any obvious effect on the public's view of the
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 percent of respondents had an unfavorable rating of
Schumer, compared with 22 percent who had a favorable rating. By
contrast, in a poll in the third week of October 1992, Abrams was
viewed unfavorably by 1 in 3 voters.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' support varied by region of the state. Schumer
leads D'Amato two to one, 61 percent to 27 percent, in New York
City, and D'Amato leads Schumer by 48 percent to 35 percent
upstate. But D'Amato, who is from Long Island, is almost tied in
the New York City suburbs, with 46 percent to 41 percent for
Schumer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   D'Amato began broadcasting advertisements this week accusing
Schumer of being hostile to suburban voters, based on votes he had
cast in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   By almost every measure that pollsters use to analyze an
election _ registered voters, likely voters, and taking into
account who undecided New Yorkers might be leaning toward _ this
contest is a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS News statewide telephone poll was conducted from
last Thursday through Tuesday with 1,461 adults, of whom 1,066 said
they were registered to vote. With a margin of sampling error of
plus or minus 3 percentage points, Schumer could be ahead by as
much as nine points among registered voters, or D'Amato could be
ahead by 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of a clear public opinion about Schumer comes
despite months of advertisements by the congressman intended to
improve his credentials among voters, and three weeks of
commercials by D'Amato intended to tear them down. Despite all
that, nearly two-thirds said they did not hold a firm opinion of
Schumer, favorable or unfavorable. Even among those voters,
however, 41 percent said they expected to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The finding that so few people have a well-formed opinion of
Schumer reflects the fact that 39 percent said that they have paid
little attention to the contest for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   If history is a guide, that should start to change, with both
campaigns escalating their media attacks, and the contests
receiving more intense coverage from New York newspapers and
television stations that have largely ignored it so far.
</P>
<P>
   The voters who have yet to form an opinion about Schumer are an
obvious target for both candidates. The need to influence this bloc
accounts for D'Amato's aggressive attempt to discredit his opponent
from the start of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato would appear to have an advantage in that regard, if
only because he has far more money than Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schumer's position today is reminiscent of that of George
Pataki when he was the Republican gubernatorial candidate
challenging Gov. Mario Cuomo, the Democratic incumbent, in 1994. In
October of that year, 49 percent of respondents had no opinion of
Pataki, and at the time, Cuomo was in a dead heat, 44 to 41, with
Pataki, who went on to win.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers continue to have ambivalent feelings about D'Amato,
who has been a dominant figure in state politics since he defeated
Sen. Jacob Javits in the 1980 Republican primary. D'Amato is viewed
favorably by 27 percent and unfavorably by 36 percent, virtually
the same marks he received six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the poll, 51 percent agreed that D'Amato is ``good at getting
things done for voters,'' and that is expected to be a central
argument of his appeal for a fourth term. Only 32 percent said the
same about Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   But 45 percent of D'Amato's own supporters said they were voting
for him with reservations, compared with 24 percent of Schumer's
supporters. More ominously for the senator, among undecided voters,
31 percent said they had an unfavorable view of D'Amato, compared
with 9 percent who viewed him favorably.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato has been there for a long time,'' said Kevin Byrne
of Hempstead, N.Y., a residential property manager who said he was
undecided, and who spoke in a follow-up interview. ``For as many
good things he has done, he's done equally bad.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers are split about whether D'Amato has the ``honesty
and integrity you would like to see in a United States senator'':
41 percent said he did and 44 percent said he did not.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, 44 percent said Schumer had those qualities and 19
percent said he did not. And 40 percent of respondents said that
they believed that D'Amato did not care ``about the needs and
problems of people like yourself,'' and 22 percent had the same
opinion about Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS News poll found several instances in which
opposing views between the candidates might make a difference. For
example, two-thirds of respondents say the sale of handguns should
be banned; Schumer supports gun control while D'Amato opposes it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
