<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-MARTINEZ-1S     10-08 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARTINEZ-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ STUCK IN AUTUMNAL SWOON 
 (JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS to add fresh quotes from Martinez, recast emphasis
throughout.)   By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tino Martinez admitted that the fateful and forgettable sequence
in the 12th inning of Wednesday's game felt as if it were
unraveling in slow motion. Dreary plays that help lose games can
feel that way because players replay them in their minds. Every
time Martinez replayed the bunt that doomed the Yankees, he wished
that he could punch rewind, pause or delete to do something about
Cleveland's 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But it was much too late to erase Travis Fryman's nifty bunt,
Martinez's misplaced throw or Chuck Knoblauch's inexplicable brain
cramp. The game-altering and maybe even series-altering play felt
like slow motion to Martinez, because that is how the usually sharp
Yankees dealt with it.
</P>
<P>
   They were too slow and too sluggish, especially for a critical
Game 2 of the American League Championship Series. As Fryman's bunt
hugged the first-base line, Martinez hesitated before charging in
for it. Once Martinez scooped it up and looked to first, he could
not see if Knoblauch was covering the base because Fryman was
running inside the baseline, obstructing his view. Martinez tried
to throw the ball over Fryman's left shoulder, but it caromed off
the runner's back and rolled toward the outfield. Knoblauch, who
was expecting the umpires to rule interference, amazingly did not
pursue the ball right away and that allowed Enrique Wilson to
scamper home from first base with the second and go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all yelling, `Get the ball, get the ball,''' Martinez
said. ``It's just one of those plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was being diplomatic. It was more than one of those
plays. It was one of those weird plays that has not happened to the
Yankees often and it is the reason why they tumbled to the Indians.
It was one of the reasons Martinez had a glazed look in his brown
eyes. For once, the powerful Yankees were the team that looked
stunned inside the silent clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss,'' Martinez said. ``Any time you're at home
and you go into extra innings, you've got to win those games. This
team fights. One thing we've done is bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees need to bounce back in Game 3 Friday, and they
desperately need Martinez to rebound from his prolonged post-season
funk. Even though the Yankees won the World Series in 1996, the
post-season has not been a personal dance through October for
Martinez. It has been a disaster, and Martinez's throwing error and
0-for-4 game Wednesday fit the disturbing trend.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Martinez batted .409 with one homer and five RBIs for
the Mariners against the Yankees in the 1995 division series, he
has been 19 for 108 (.176 batting average) with 1 homer and 4 RBI
in the post-season. In ALCS play, Martinez is only 7 for 53, and in
his last seven post-season series he has not managed a homer or an
RBI in six of them. Disastrous? Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' said Martinez, who is 0 for his last
10 in the post-season. ``I feel good, I'm relaxed and, all of a
sudden, I'm trying to make things happen that are not there. I'm
swinging at 3-2 pitches that are out of the zone. I'm striking out
on bad pitches. I'm trying to do too much instead of letting things
happen and unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of evidence to prove that Martinez is
uncomfortable at the plate. With Paul O'Neill on third, one out in
the fourth and the infield drawn in, Martinez batted against
Charles Nagy with an opportunity to drive in the Yankees' first
run.
</P>
<P>
   All Martinez needed was a single or a sacrifice fly, hardly an
arduous task for a player who knocked in 123 runs in the regular
season. But Martinez popped a 180-foot fly ball to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the game because we didn't do the job,'' Martinez
said. ``We had a lot of chances to win. I know that I didn't do the
job in the fourth when I had the chance to hit a sacrifice fly.
That play didn't lose it. It was an unfortunate play at the wrong
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had another supreme chance with the score tied, 1-1, in
the eighth, two outs and runners on first and second. All Martinez
needed was a single. All he produced was air. Martinez looked edgy
against Paul Shuey and struck out on a 3-2 pitch that was near his
ankles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of nights here, I've felt like I'm going to
make it all happen now,'' Martinez said. ``I've been forcing things
a little bit. I have to relax and take it one game at a time. I'm
trying too hard. I need to forget about my post-seasons in the past
and go out there and play my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Martinez is a sensitive sort, Joe Torre turned defensive
when he was asked before the game about Martinez's disappearing
offense. He simply said, ``Tino's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he? Not really. Someone asked Martinez how difficult it is to
forget about previous post-season failures, and he candidly said,
``It's not that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   And it just got tougher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
