<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5449 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN     10-08 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS NEED TO GET DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Mighty Ducks executives certainly know how to defend
themselves. They defend controversial front-office personnel moves,
inexplicable coaching changes and, of course, the annual ticket
price increases.
</P>
<P>
   But can the Ducks defend their own goal and return to the
Stanley Cup playoffs next spring?
</P>
<P>
   Few outside the organization believe they can, but that's the
last of new coach Craig Hartsburg's worries as the Ducks prepare
for Saturday's season opener against the Washington Capitals and
former coach Ron Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg has been trying to instill a system that will give his
suspect defense the best possible chance of being competitive. Poor
defense was a factor in the team's slide from fourth in the Western
Conference in 1996-97 to 12th last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no magic wand,'' said Hartsburg, a former all-star
defenseman who was the fall guy for the less-than-talented Chicago
Blackhawks' failure to make the playoffs last year.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Teemu Selanne and a healthy Paul Kariya
figures to be magical, especially since they just completed their
first training camp together.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who played in only 22 games last season, has scored 129
goals and 277 points in 220 career games. Selanne has 119 goals and
231 points in 179 games with Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Selanne put together an amazing season with virtually
no offensive support. He tied Peter Bondra for the goal-scoring
title (52) and became the fourth player in NHL history to score
more than 25 percent of his team's goals (25.4).
</P>
<P>
   The upbeat Selanne insists things aren't as bleak as they might
seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic,'' he said. ``I know we have good players and I
know we don't want to go through what we did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg has tired of answering questions about the Ducks'
defense, saying, ``All everybody talks about is the defense, but we
are just trying to teach the game the way it should be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne admitted defense will be the key to any success Anaheim
might have this season. But he said patience might be in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a new coach comes in, it always takes time to get on the
same page,'' said Selanne of a team that never got on the same page
with Pierre Page last season. ``But when we get on it, (the team)
will take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to remember last year. This team is hungry and
wants to prove more than last year's team.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran goalie Guy Hebert describes Anaheim's 26-43-13 record
last season as a ``disaster,'' but he believes the Ducks have a
great chance to prove their doubters are all wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are picked last in pretty much everything, except for our
big line,'' said Hebert, who is being counted on to rebound from
shoulder surgery and his worst season since arriving in Anaheim.
``It's kind of nice. Now, we'll go out as the underdog in every
game and just try to prove to people we are a solid organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt we can make the playoffs, but we'll have to
play up to our capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hebert will need help from a rag-tag group of
defensemen and an increased defensive commitment on the part of the
Anaheim forwards.
</P>
<P>
   There is no confusing any of the Ducks' defenders with Rob
Blake, Chris Chelios, Ray Bourque or Nicklaus Lidstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Hartsburg _ who coached Chelios for three years _ is
putting the best possible spin on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams don't have a Chelios, but that doesn't mean
they can't have a solid defense,'' Hartsburg said. ``Sometimes
having six solid guys is better than having one star.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg can only hope the approach works better this season.
Last year, the Ducks allowed 261 goals, 28 more than in '96-97.
Only Vancouver (273) and Tampa Bay (269) allowed more.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks scored only 205 goals (a drop of 40), but that number
should rise with the return of Kariya, a healthy year from center
Steve Rucchin, a good year from Travis Green, a possible return to
form by Tomas Sandstrom and the emergence of promising youngsters
like Johan Davidsson, Josef Marha and Frank Banham.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
