<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-GORE-NYT &LR;      10-08 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CAMPAIGNS FOR VALLONE AND ASSAILS PATAKI 
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category `a')  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSVILLE, N.Y. _ Hoping to borrow a little star power from
the White House, gubernatorial nominee Peter Vallone campaigned
with Vice President Al Gore in western New York state Wednesday,
giving Gore a chance to take a few pokes at a possible opponent in
the 2000 presidential race, Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, a Democrat who has in recent days emphatically opposed
calls to impeach President Clinton, hopes that the continuing
popularity of the Clinton-Gore team in New York will rub off on his
struggling campaign for governor. And the vice president helped
Vallone, the New York City Council speaker, with another scarce
commodity, money, speaking at two fund-raisers for him that the
Vallone campaign said would net $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer session with students at Erie County
Community College in this Buffalo suburb, and at a fund-raiser in
nearby Lancaster, Gore, without ever naming the governor,
repeatedly criticized Pataki's vetoes last April of money the
Legislature had approved for schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the vetoes of legislative funding in this state
and it causes you to wonder what is going to happen in the future
if you don't make an investment in education,'' he said. Later, he
said, ``The Republicans in Albany can't even pass a budget on
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki campaign spokesman Michael Marr defended the governor's
commitment to schools, saying, ``Last year, the state budget
increased aid to state schools by a record $850 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, a Republican who enjoys a 2-to-1 lead over Vallone
in most polls, has run a quiet campaign intended to make him appear
above politics, and Wednesday was another quiet day for him, with
low-profile events in Rockland and Westchester counties. But he
picked up the endorsement of the state's largest small-business
group, the New York chapter of the National Federation of
Independent Business, a potent part of his core constituency.
</P>
<P>
   And in an interview published Wednesday in The New York
Observer, the governor was clearly looking past the current contest
toward 2000. He said, ``If you're governor of New York, you can't
help but think about being president of the United States,'' the
closest he has come to expressing outright interest in running for
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's political advisers say that a strong victory in the
Nov. 3 election could position him as the leading presidential
candidate in the moderate wing of the party, which favors abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The aspirations of the governor and the vice president for 2000
were among many political crosscurrents at work in Wednesday's
trip.
</P>
<P>
   At the fund-raiser at Salvatore's Italian Gardens in Lancaster,
Gore, with an oblique reference to Clinton's troubles, appealed to
Democrats not to allow pessimism or indifference to keep them from
voting. In many races around the country, Democrats fear that their
voters, discouraged by the president's problems, will simply stay
home on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party has a lot of ideas that are just dead
wrong, but they're very intensely in favor of those ideas,'' Gore
said. ``Ladies and gentlemen, the real question in this election is
whether or not we're willing to match their intensity with even
more of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone's difficulties were amply on display here. Absent from
the Vallone-Gore events Wednesday was Buffalo Mayor Anthony
Masiello, who has endorsed Pataki. And organizers said they had
difficulty meeting the $50,000 target for Vallone's fund-raiser in
Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   But an unexpected guest did appear: state Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, whose relations with Vallone have been rocky.
Silver, who was in Buffalo for a fund-raiser for Assembly
candidates, has made a public show of mending fences with Vallone,
but some Democrats still complain that he has done nothing to help
his party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Vallone learned that he had won a round in
another struggle, to keep the New York Yankees in the Bronx. A
judge ruled that a referendum on the team's future home, which
Vallone sponsored, must appear on the Nov. 3 ballot, over the
objections of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The ruling is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   If the measure appears on the ballot, polls indicate that voters
will overwhelmingly endorse keeping the team in Yankee Stadium, and
the measure could raise voter turnout in the city, helping Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   Gore flew Wednesday afternoon from Buffalo to New York City,
where he spoke at a fund-raiser for Vallone at the Sheraton New
York Hotel in mid-town Manhattan, that Vallone aides said raised
$250,000. And later in the evening, he spoke at the annual dinner
of the Empire State Pride Agenda, a gay rights group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0010 </DOCNO>
