<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN     10-08 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE HOPES RUNNING IMPROVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Weber State's Morgan Welch ran for 217
yards against Montana. Southern Utah had 493 yards rushing against
the Grizzlies. Both times Montana lost.
</P>
<P>
   Run the ball well and you can beat No.18 Montana (3-2, 1-1 Big
Sky), which is what No.23 Cal State Northridge is thinking.
However, the Matadors (3-1, 2-0) have the worst running game in the
league, which is why the coaching staff continues to tinker with
it.
</P>
<P>
   So Saturday's adjustment for CSUN should mean less time for
running back Melvin Blue and more for Jaumal Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bradley) definitely deserves some reps,'' CSUN coach Ron
Ponciano said. ``He's extremely sound on all his protections, he
catches the ball and does everything right. He deserves that
chance. I wouldn't call it a tailback by committee, but he's
deserves the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN averages 78.8 yards per game and 1.9 yards per carry. Blue,
the Matadors' leading rusher, has 283 yards. Bradley has gained 21
yards on 12 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find out if Bradley can do it because he hasn't had
the opportunity,'' CSUN offensive coordinator Rob Phenicie said.
``We want to see if Jaumal is different than Melvin running the
ball. And it gives Melvin a break and keeps him fresh for the
fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so special teams: When it comes to kicking the ball, the
Matadors are fine. It's the return aspect of the special teams that
needs some special attention.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN is last in the Big Sky returning kickoffs (14.38 yards per
return) and eighth (of nine) in the conference in punt returns
(8.0).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our wedge is bad,'' said CSUN assistant coach Jeff Kearin, who
heads special teams. ``We have to make some serious adjustments.
Our plan was to put bigger guys in the wedge, and it slowed us
down. But they're getting more comfortable with it and doing
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Punter Ethan Beck missed practice Wednesday with a strained
hamstring, though Ponciano expects him to play against Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Reviving a rivalry: Four of the top 12 home crowds in CSUN
history, including the school-record 7,127 eight years ago, came
against Cal Poly of San Luis Obispo. But the schools haven't met
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   However, the rivalry renews in 2000. CSUN athletic director Paul
Bubb said the schools signed a home-and-home contract with Cal Poly
for 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get that rivalry back,'' Ponciano said. ``It's a
good one.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams met every season from 1962-95 with Cal Poly winning 27
of 35 games.
</P>
<P>
   Short yardage: Defensive back James Maldonado (pinched nerve)
and nose guard Jacob Mageo (pinched nerve) both returned to
practice Wednesday.... Defensive lineman Erik Gardner (knee) was in
shoulder pads and shorts for the first time since being injured in
the season opener against Boise State. He said he expects to return
next week at Sacramento State.... Quarterback Marcus Brady and
volleyball player Laura Szymanski were named CSUN's athletes of the
month for September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
