<SLUG> BC-RAC-SKIP-AWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY PURSUES THE GOLD CUP AND THE GHOST OF KELSO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The backstretch at Belmont Park was bristling
Wednesday with horses preparing to run in the five Grade I stakes
scheduled for Breeders' Cup Preview Day on Saturday. And the star
of the show, reigning in Barn 1, remained Skip Away, who can make
history three ways if he wins the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old gray, aiming for his third Gold Cup victory in a
row, would become only the second horse in racing history to win it
more than twice. He would also win his 10th straight race. And he
would pass Cigar with record earnings of $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away's trainer, Sonny Hine, taking note of all the success
within reach for his horse, acknowledged that only Kelso has won
the Gold Cup more times: He won the race five straight years from
1960 through 1964, and was named Horse of the Year for five
straight years. And Hine repeated his theme that Skip Away belonged
in such Olympian company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned,'' he said, ``Skip Away belongs with
the greatest horses. He never had a break in his training. I mean,
this horse hates time off. He laid it on the line every time he
ran.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why, if he can win this race again, he will be
mentioned with Kelso, who was one of my favorite horses. I think he
and Skippy have one big thing in common, and that is their
durability. They ran hard a long time, and they overcame whatever
was put in their way.''
</P>
<P>
   A small but select field appeared likely to be entered Thursday
to challenge Skip Away, including Gentlemen, the horse he outran in
the Woodward three weeks ago. The 6-year-old Argentine star had
been considered a candidate for the Kelso Handicap one week later
than the Gold Cup. But his trainer, Dick Mandella, said Wednesday
that his next target would be the Gold Cup and Skip Away. The
Breeders' Cup with its seven races worth $12 million will be held
on Nov. 7 at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I thought about it,'' Mandella said ``the more we had
nothing to gain by running in the Kelso. It's a one-turn mile, and
that wasn't going to get us ready for anything. I already know that
Gentlemen can run on grass. This way, we have a chance to go for it
all in the Jockey Club Gold Cup and still have our options open, be
it the Breeders' Cup Mile or the Classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag, the British horse who ran third in the Woodward at
48-1 odds behind Skip Away and Gentlemen, held his final tuneup for
the Gold Cup. He breezed half a mile in 51 seconds and drew cheers
from his trainer, Philip Mitchell, who also threw a high salute to
Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skip Away is awesome, isn't he?'' Mitchell said. ``He can do
it all, and he's probably the finest running machine I've seen in a
long time. He is like a top shelf, Formula One car.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Cup will be flanked by rich races run by contenders for
championships at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   For 2-year-old fillies, the $400,000 Frizette at a mile and a
sixteenth will draw a short field headed by Things Change and Oh
What a Windfall. For 2-year-old colts, the $400,000 Champagne at a
mile and a sixteenth, will be led by Lemon Drop Kid and Tactical
Cat. For top grass horses, the $500,000 Turf Classic Invitational
at a mile and a half, will feature Cetewayo and Buck's Boy. And for
fillies and mares, the $400,000 Beldame at a mile and an eighth
will feature those old rivals, Sharp Cat and Tomisue's Delight.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jockey Club Gold Cup at a mile and a quarter for $1
million, it will be Skip Away against Gentlemen and the ghost of
Kelso. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
