<SLUG> BC-NY-EX-CON-PRIEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF PRISON, PRIEST REOPENS SHELTER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To federal agents and prosecutors, the Rev. Patrick
Moloney is a rogue priest who was linked to an audacious robbery
that pumped $5 million into the coffers of Irish Republican Army
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   But back at his home on the Lower East Side of Manhattan after
serving almost four years in prison on charges arising from the
robbery, Moloney basked Wednesday in the warmth of supporters and
neighbors who portray him as a humble defender of the poor who was
unjustly convicted because of his political beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI and the prosecutors think I'm sitting on a stash of $5
million,'' the 66-year-old Melkite Catholic priest said, fingering
a religious ornament that he called his Jesus Beads. ``They would
like people to believe that I'm an international terrorist, a
Pimpernel, a master criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that God knows I was in no way implicated in
that robbery or laundering any of the money,'' he asserted in an
interview in Bonitas House, a shelter for the homeless that he
founded more than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Moloney returned to Bonitas House on Monday after completing 44
months of a maximum 51-month sentence. He will be under supervised
release by federal probation officers for three years.
</P>
<P>
   A man with a slight build, sparse sandy hair turning grey and a
cropped white beard, Moloney was ordained in the Melkite order, a
branch of the Roman Catholic Church that follows an ancient Eastern
Rite but is obedient to the pope.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested in November 1993 on federal charges stemming
from a holdup by masked gunmen in January 1993 at the Brinks car
service depot in Rochester. In November 1994 he was convicted along
with another defendant on charges of conspiracy and hiding $2
million from the robbery in an apartment that he maintained for
Bonitas House in Stuyvesant Town. The remainder of the loot _ $5.2
million _ is still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Moloney did not testify at the trial and has maintained in
interviews that he had sublet the apartment to a volunteer worker
at Bonitas and was unaware that stolen money was being kept there.
He claimed that $168,000 found in a safe at Bonitas House was money
he was safeguarding for illegal aliens, and contributions for
repairs and maintenance of the Bonitas brownstone.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Limerick, Ireland, Moloney is a naturalized citizen
and a self-described Irish nationalist who champions unification of
the Republic of Ireland with Northern Ireland. But he emphasized
that he is opposed to terrorism and is not a supporter of the Irish
Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI and the prosecutors obtained a conviction by
suggesting it was all an IRA plot,'' Moloney said in a dense,
rapid-fire brogue as his supporters listened in the sparsely
furnished Bonitas living room. ``Without terrorism, there was no
case, no motive.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiling at the notion that he has access to huge funds from the
IRA, he said that on Monday, the first day he could shed his
federal prison identification number, 28251-0545, he was able to
scrape up only $150 from his savings and from contributions given
him by supporters to buy groceries for reopening Bonitas House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no terrorist, and what happened to him was a travesty of
justice,'' said Anna Rawle, 84, a Bonitas volunteer who lives on
East Ninth Street. ``It's wonderful to have him back, and it's
amazing that he has no bitterness on how he has been treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lawler, chancellor of the Diocese of Newton, Mass., the
main Melkite Diocese in the United States, said Wednesday that
Moloney remained a priest in good standing and could resume his
clerical duties.
</P>
<P>
   Moloney said he hoped to expand Bonitas House into a study
center and retreat for clergy and other people who are unfamiliar
with the problems of inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would minister to AIDS patients. In 1993,
shortly before his arrest, he said he received a calling to assist
people with AIDS when a patient in a Veterans Administration
hospital praised him for talking to and embracing patients without
wearing a mask as most medical workers do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Padre, thank you for showing me a human face,'''
Moloney recalled. ``Because people are afraid and misinformed about
AIDS, they are turning these victims into lepers.''
</P>
<P>
   The one longtime mission that Moloney will not resume is
officiating at Masses in local jails and prisons and counseling
inmates. He is barred by probation regulations from ministering to
defendants awaiting trial or convicted inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone has firsthand experience about the spiritual needs
of inmates, it certainly is me,'' he added. ``But, that's the very
place the authorities won't let me enter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
