<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-DONORS-INVESTIGATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI'S ECONOMIC ADVISER IS SUBPOENAED IN CONTRACT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors have subpoenaed Gov. George
Pataki's senior economic adviser, Charles Gargano, in their inquiry
into the awarding of a $97 million state contract to a Long Island
company owned by a major Republican political contributor,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors are investigating whether the contracting
process was influenced by a total of $100,000 that donors linked to
the company, Silverite Construction, had given to the New York
Republican State Committee in the days just before and after the
company received the contract to repair the Queens Midtown Tunnel
in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano's office declined to comment, but other Pataki aides
said that in the past week Gargano had received the subpoena to
testify before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn has declined to discuss
the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano was the chief fund-raiser for the Pataki campaign in
1994, after which Pataki appointed him to oversee the state's
economic development agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Gargano has said he no longer raises money for the
Pataki campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Silverite's owner, Angelo Silveri, said in an interview last
March that he was a friend of Gargano and talked to him often.
Silveri said he might have spoken about the tunnel project with
Gargano.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gargano have said there could have been such a
discussion, but they said Gargano had no role in the project, which
is supervised by the Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The authority had originally determined that Silverite and its
partner in the venture lacked the experience for the four-year
project, one of the largest state contracts in recent years. But
Silverite then altered its application and got the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The authority and Silveri have both said that the donations had
nothing to do with the contract. But after The New York Times
disclosed the timing of the donations last March, federal
prosecutors began their investigation and the authority undertook
an internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors have already issued subpoenas to officials at
the transportation authority, Silveri and executives of the
companies that lost the bidding and contended that the process was
biased toward Silverite.
</P>
<P>
   Silveri has been one of the biggest financial backers of the
Pataki campaign and the Republican State Committee. He and donors
connected to him have given roughly $335,000 to the Republican
State Committee and the Pataki campaign since October 1994,
according to campaign finance records.
</P>
</TEXT>
