<HEADLINE>
PASTOR TO VOTE FOR DEMOCRATIC IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
WASHINGTON _ Ed Pastor, Arizona's lone Democratic House member,
will vote Thursday to open a limited impeachment inquiry against
his party's president. The vote has the blessings of the House
Democratic leadership.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pastor's move, announced in a press release Wednesday, is part
of what is being viewed as a Demo cratic strategy to limit the
inevita ble. Faced with the fact Republi cans have enough votes to
pass an impeach ment inquiry to day, some Democrats pressed the
White House Wednesday to drop its opposi tion to an open-ended
probe.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Democratic leaders are encouraging members to back a
more limited investigation, one that would be confined to
allegations contained in special counsel Ken neth Starr's report on
President Clinton's association with former White House intern
Monica Lewin sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the majority of my col leagues, I feel that the inquiry
must continue in order to bring true finality to this situation,''
Pastor said. ``Only by limiting the inquiry in scope and time can
we as a nation move beyond this issue and onto the important
business of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastor's seat is considered rela tively safe. &QL; 
 &UR; Republic news services contributed to this
 &UR; article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
