<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA_MCALISTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS SERIOUS BUSINESS  
 BRUINS' VISIT IS INCENTIVE FOR UA STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toss a compliment at Chris McAlister and he'll knock it down as
if it were just another pass attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Through Arizona's first four victories, the post-game scene near
McAlister's corner of the locker room began to take on a routine.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and teammates would marvel at McAlister's unfailing
ability to exceed expectations. McAlister would say he has yet to
achieve anything.
</P>
<P>
   He has his own standards. Some would say they are impossible.
But Wildcats Coach Dick Tomey admires McAlister's self-imposed
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sign of a player who is always working to
improve,'' Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   It also is the product of a player, a person, who has battled
and lost. Despite his evident talent and preseason credentials as
an All-America cornerback, things have not always been easy for
McAlister.
</P>
<P>
   The latest obstacle came last Saturday. He was declared
ineligible for Arizona's thrilling 31-28 victory at Washington
because of a loan from a bank in Austin. The NCAA ruled that his
potential earning power as a pro allowed him to get $14,000 above
the $10,800 premium for an approved disability insurance policy.
Arizona has aggressively defended him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just sickens me,'' said Tomey, who said McAlister acquired
the loan from a Texas bank at 14.9 percent interest, hardly a
special privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, No. 10 in the Associated Press poll and No. 11 in the
USA Today/ESPN version, has taken its own steps to protect
McAlister. Tomey asked the media not to interview him about the
one-game suspension. And McAlister isn't commenting. He's getting
ready for another battle: third-ranked UCLA on Saturday night at
Arizona Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins always have been something of a war cry for
McAlister, who, despite his absence at Washington, still is
considered a contender for the Jim Thorpe Award as the nation's
best defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   His boyhood dream of playing for UCLA was destroyed by a messy,
complicated controversy about SAT scores. The Bruins challenged his
score on a test taken in 1995. The length of the process forced him
to spend one year in junior college. His family sued the Education
Testing Service, which investigated the challenge. The lawsuit was
eventually dropped. By then, McAlister was at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He had grown up in a UCLA family and not far from the Bruins'
bench. He was a quarterback at Pasadena High School, just around
the corner from the Rose Bowl, the Bruins' home field. His father,
James McAlister, was an All-America running back for the 1973
Bruins and one of the few high school athletes to ever appear on
the cover of ``Sports Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   He can remember great UCLA players dropping by the house. He met
Troy Aikman, Gaston Green and J.J. Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gaston Green, he was No. 1,'' said McAlister, who in 1996
tasted a little revenge with a a 100-yard kickoff return for a
touchdown against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins powder blue once filled his wardrobe. Today, the color is
just another source of motivation for a young man who always seems
to be pushing himself to prove a point.
</P>
<P>
   As an assistant at UCLA, Tomey coached McAlister's father, who
today is a special education teacher and track coach at Pasadena
High.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris' dad and I are friends,'' Tomey said. ``James was a very
good football player. But Chris is unique. There are not too many
defensive backs with his size (6 feet 1, 195 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just special.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend provided another example of that. McAlister didn't
accompany the team to Seattle because of the suspension. But he was
at the Tucson airport to greet his teammates when their charter
landed about 4 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of athletes in that situation would not have come out to
the airport that early in the morning,'' Tomey said. ``They would
have been off somewhere, feeling sorry for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlister's teammates noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just great to see him there,'' said defensive lineman
Eli Wnek, a redshirt freshman from Glendale. ``Chris is more than
just a great player on this team. He's our leader.''
</P>
<P>
   In a larger sense, Wnek explained, McAlister's presence at the
airport was a symbol that he's always going to be there. At the
airport. Or on the field.
</P>
<P>
   This Saturday, the attention shifts to his role on the field
against Bruins quarterback Cade McNown, a Heisman Trophy contender.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the NCAA allowed McAlister to choose which game to
serve his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA never was an option. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
