r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-NOTRED     10-08 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-NOTRE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S COACHING, AND NOTRE DAME 
</HEADLINE>
 DAME-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ara Parseghian achieved Messianic status during his first season
at Notre Dame. The Fighting Irish returned to gridiron glory in
1964, rolling up six, seven, eight wins in a row.
</P>
<P>
   During a late-November game, an unexpected winter storm swept
across Lake Michigan, dumping a heavy snow.
</P>
<P>
   The Notre Dame student body had come to believe their new coach
could do anything. Ask and ye shall receive. So, as the weather
worsened, the huddled students began to chant. ``Ara, stop the
snow! Ara, stop the snow!''
</P>
<P>
   New on the job, Parseghian knew little about protocol at the
school. So as the fans chanted, he turned to an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, what is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Ara rolled his eyes toward the gray sky. ``Well,'' he asked
timidly, ``could I?''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, same thing happened. During a Notre Dame home
game, a winter storm blew in, covering the stadium in a blanket of
white. Again, the student section called upon its coach whose teams
from 1964-74 finished in the Top 10 nine times. ``Ara, stop the
snow!'' they chanted.
</P>
<P>
   The coach looked at an assistant, then playfully turned his eyes
to the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he asked, ``should I?''
</P>
<P>
   If you win, Notre Dame is the best coaching job in the country.
The school has it all. Spirit. Legend. Glorious tradition. A
nationwide following.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame is the Four Horsemen. Rockne. The Gipper. Notre Dame
is Angelo Bertelli, Johnny Lujack, Leon Hart, Paul Hornung. Joe
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   But along with prestige is the pressure, the demand to win. The
three toughest jobs in the world are president of the United
States, the mayor of New York City and the football coach at Notre
Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Cheer, cheer for old Notre Dame. The school's fight song says
Notre Dame will win over all ``what though the odds be great or
small.'' The lyrics say nothing about settling for a tie, or losing
to Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Parseghian tells about the time he checked into a hospital for a
few days of rest at the end of his last season as the Irish coach.
Notre Dame had just lost to USC, 55-24.
</P>
<P>
   While recuperating, Ara expected some communication from the
school's athletic board, which was meeting behind closed doors to
discuss his successor. As Parseghian tells it, the following
telegram arrived at the hospital:
</P>
<P>
   `` Dear Coach'':``''
</P>
<P>
   `` The Athletic Board of the University of Notre Dame wishes you
a very speedy recovery, by a vote'' ``margin of four to
three''.``''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Devine, Parseghian's successor, loved his six years at Notre
Dame. The man who had coached at ASU in the mid-1950s worked
tirelessly. Sometimes, late in the evening, alone in his office,
Devine says he almost could feel the presence of Knute Rockne
making the rounds, like a night watchman, his ghostly footfalls
echoing faintly through the corridors of the old stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Devine's Notre Dame teams won three bowl games and the national
championship in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure to win is probably not much different from what
Bruce Snyder feels,'' Devine said of the ASU coach, whose Sun
Devils play the Irish on Saturday. ``For coaches, most pressure is
self-induced.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last season, Devine took the Fighting Irish to Tucson to
play Arizona. Two minutes before halftime in a close game, the
coach called a play that for him was out of character. His team
deep in its own territory, facing fourth and 5, Devine twirled his
whistle from the sideline, a secret signal for his 18-year-old
quarterback/punter to fake the punt.
</P>
<P>
   Devine's assistant coaches were shocked. So were the Wildcats.
Devine still can see Blair Kiel sprinting down the sideline, ball
tucked under his arm _ 80 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Great call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it worked,'' Devine said of the key play in the 20-3
victory. The old coach chuckled at his own daring. ``If it hadn't,
I'd still be at Notre Dame, hanging from a cross.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
