<HEADLINE>
RUEGAMER CRITICIZED BY USC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A play involving Arizona State center Grey Ruegamer will be
reviewed by the Pac-10 this week at the request of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans want a rules interpretation of a play that resulted
in USC defensive tackle Marc Matock breaking his ankle Saturday at
the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was an aggressive play. It was questionable,'' USC
assistant coach Ed Orgeron told the Los Angeles Daily News. ``There
are a lot of plays that are questionable. We'll probably mention it
because it was questionable. We just want to find out the ruling on
it. I wish it wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Matock told reporters he was unhappy about the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ruegamer) came back and dove toward my ankle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't anything illegal,'' Ruegamer said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder, who has watched the play on film,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Schools file a report to the Pac-10 after games and questionable
plays on both sides are typically submitted. Game films are
reviewed by the conference's coordinator of football officiating,
Verle Sorgen.
</P>
<P>
   Matock is expected to be sidelined at least two months after
undergoing surgery that included having a metal plate inserted in
his ankle with six screws. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Around the Pac &QL; 
 &QL; 
From the department of good news, bad news:
</P>
<P>
   Washington quarterback Brock Huard will be sidelined two weeks
because of a partially separated shoulder, but at least his timing
is good.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have Utah State, California and Oregon State coming
up on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Huard suffered the injury late in the first half Saturday
against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Times are getting tough for Washington State, which has the
chance to accomplish this feat: first to worst.
</P>
<P>
   The defending league champion Cougars, who have lost eight
defensive linemen since the summer due to injuries, academic
ineligibility or transfer, found out they'll be without star
receiver Nian Taylor for two weeks because of a pulled muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State ranks ninth in the league in scoring offense
and eighth in scoring defense. It has committed 19 turnovers, a
Pac-10 high.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Coach Jim Lambright kept reporters out of his locker
room after the Huskies' 31-28 loss to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is hurting, and I will not allow them to be
interviewed to protect them from the stupidity of what went on out
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1991, two Pac-10 teams ranked in the
Top 10 will square off when No. 3 UCLA and No. 10 Arizona meet
Saturday night in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The previous big conference confrontation was when No. 3
Washington knocked off No. 7 California, 24-17. The Huskies went on
to win the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   USC has blocked five kicks in five games. Special teams have
accounted for four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA quarterback and Heisman hopeful Cade McNown isn't putting
up the numbers he did last season.
</P>
<P>
   His efficiency rating is 150.2, 16th-best in the nation. He led
the country last year with a 168.6 mark. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quote of the week &QL; 
 &QL; 
``They're nothing compared to the team they had last year. They
probably think they're good because they just won. 49-17. I might
think I'm pretty good if I just won, 49-17, but they're not that
good.'' _ Washington State receiver Taylor after Saturday's loss to
UCLA. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Who's hot &QL; 
 &QL; 
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats won over some skeptics Saturday with a 31-28
victory over Washington in that hostile environment known as Husky
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They lead the conference in scoring defense and rank third in
total offense. If they can pull out a win against the Bruins on
Saturday, they soon could be 8-0 because Oregon State and Northeast
Louisiana are next up. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Who's not &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   How can we put this? Stanford stinks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal has given up 1,136 yards and 98 points in the past
two weeks. It ranks last in the Pac-10 in scoring defense, rushing
defense, pass defense and total defense.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the defense has done its job. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Paola Boivin can be
reached at
</P>
<P>
   paola.boivin(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
