<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU SET TO HONOR WULK  
 ARENA FLOOR TO BEAR EX-COACH'S NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  STATE-WULK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ned Wulk will be honored by the university that fired him more
than 16 years ago, just short of a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   The floor at the Wells Fargo Arena (formerly the University
Activity Center) will be named Ned Wulk Court after the man who won
more games by far than any other Arizona State basketball coach.
The official announcement is today.
</P>
<P>
   Wulk will be feted at a banquet March 5, and the court will be
dedicated during halftime of the Southern California-ASU game the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   Wulk coached the Sun Devils for 25 years, from 1957-58 until his
controversial firing after the 1981-82 season. He had a 406-272
career record at ASU. Including his record at Xavier (Ohio), Wulk
was five victories short of 500 when he was let go.
</P>
<P>
   Under Wulk, ASU competed in the Border, Western Athletic and
Pac-10 conferences, winning eight league titles and advancing to
the NCAA Tournament eight times. Because of the program's success,
the Activity Center was built and opened in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Before his dismissal, Wulk coached two of his best teams ever.
During the 1979-80 and 1980-81 seasons, the Sun Devils went a
combined 46-11 (31-5 Pac-10), finishing second in the conference to
Oregon State both times. At the end of the 1980-81 season, ASU beat
the then-unbeaten and No. 1-ranked Beavers by 20 points in
Corvallis.
</P>
<P>
   But ASU made early exits from the NCAA Tournament both years,
and that, combined with internal strife on his coaching staff and
the Sun Devils' 13-14 mark in 1981-82, hastened his exit.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's NCAA appearance in 1981 was the last until Bill Frieder's
Sun Devils made the 64-team field 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
   After his contract was not renewed, Wulk remained part of the
ASU faculty and has been a constant presence at Sun Devils games,
witnessing an array of successors. New Coach Rob Evans, the
honorary chairman of the Ned Wulk Court Committee, is the fourth
full-time head coach to follow Wulk. ASU also has had two interim
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a guy who's done more for the Arizona
State basketball program than Ned Wulk,'' said athletic development
officer Jim Phillips, an assistant under Frieder and a member of
the committee. ``He's a legend. His accomplishments are
unparalleled.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who played for Wulk include Joe Caldwell, Art Becker, the
late Tony Cerkvenik, Lionel Hollins, Kurt Nimphius, Alton Lister,
Lafayette Lever and Byron Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Lever and Becker are co-chairmen of the committee. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
