<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS' CHANCES SLIM WITHOUT WARREN MOON ON FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jon Kitna is too green and John Friesz admits he came
as close as he ever has to throwing a pass backwards in last
Sunday's Arrowhead Rain Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the sight of Warren Moon walking gingerly after
practice Wednesday was so disconcerting to the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Moon is sore. He cannot rotate his upper body because of the
cracked rib he suffered against the Chiefs, which means he cannot
easily throw, which means that keeping up with the undefeated
Denver Broncos this Sunday is looking like a longer shot than the
3-2 Seahawks might like.
</P>
<P>
   One positive is that Moon has always healed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of game you wait on, that you want to play,''
Moon said. ``You're playing the best team in the league. This is
the way you measure how good you are, and this team counts on me
for these type of games.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about the Seahawks' splendid depth at
quarterback, the reality is that for a game as important as the one
this week, there is Warren Moon, and then there is a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early for a must-win,'' Moon said. ``But this is a
big game. This is a game we need to win. This is a game we need to
win to get some confidence and feel better about ourselves and to
get ourselves back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   For Moon and the Seahawks' sputtering offense, this is the week
in which a statement could be made.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers' defense muffled any noise Moon and the offense
could have made at Three Rivers. The monsoon and the Chiefs made
the offense moot in Kansas City. Now, the Broncos are coming to the
Kingdome posing problems that only the veteran Moon can solve.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it this way: Whether it's Bubby Brister or John Elway
at quarterback for the Broncos, the Seahawks likely will find
themselves playing catch-up with Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Seahawk defense is tough. Yes, the Broncos have not
really beaten anybody (OK, the Patriots are a somebody). But the
Broncos have shown an uncanny ability to make the first quarter
their personal playground, outscoring their opponents 73-7.
</P>
<P>
   If the Broncos hold true to form, the Seahawks will have to
revert to their old three-wide passing days of yesteryear (1997)
and the ability of the quarterback to put the ball in the air will
become vital again, especially since running back Ricky Watters is
hurting with a deep thigh bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, coach Dennis Erickson sounded optimistic about the
return of his starting quarterback. Moon was not as convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Moon is able to start, the Seahawks have to be concerned
about whether he can finish. The Broncos will no doubt look for a
way to ram a helmet under Moon's flak jacket.
</P>
<P>
   If Moon can't go, or can't finish, Erickson said Wednesday he
will go with Friesz _ a move that anyone who watched Friesz against
the Chiefs Sunday, or against the Ravens last season, will wonder
about.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a howling sound coming from sports talk radio this
week, it is the Seahawk fan base yammering about how Friesz looks
all but washed up in the ninth season of his oft-injured,
never-quite-convincing NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   Friesz did orchestrate the greatest come-from-behind victory in
franchise history. That 1995 game was the last time the Hawks beat
the Broncos. But lately, between the injuries and the
tentativeness, Friesz seems to be embracing too tightly his better
qualities, which are to be conservative and stay within himself.
</P>
<P>
   Should he start against the Broncos, a fast start will require a
flash of adrenaline from Friesz, not to mention him getting a good
handle on the football.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kitna has been relegated to the scout team this fall,
getting few snaps. That is in contrast to this past summer, when
Moon was holding out and Kitna seemed poised to emerge as the
winner in the competition with Friesz.
</P>
<P>
   With his energy, arm and legs, Kitna demonstrated that the Hawks
should put their quarterbacking faith in him, should it become
necessary to start someone other than Moon in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That bubble burst in the final exhibition game, when Kitna threw
an interception against the 49ers, one that just floated out there
for cornerback Marquez Pope _ a miscue so glaring that the Seahawks
could no longer trust him to be their starter.
</P>
<P>
   Not much was different last Sunday in the Hawks' Bellyflop in
the Slop. Kitna threw an interception in the fourth quarter. Then
he made the ill-advised decision to run on fourth-and-15 when the
Seahawks were down to their final possession. He came up short,
which made you think about one thing with the Broncos looming:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone should want Moon to be good to go. This is his season
to make a stand and the time is right, even if the rib is not.
</P>
<P>
   Moon vs. Elway. It is the matchup everybody wants. You. Me.
Erickson. Moon. TV. NFL Films. Even the backups who wouldn't mind
starting would have to agree that things will be better if Moon
makes a speedy recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
