<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS PESSIMISTIC ABOUT NBA LABOR TALKS TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBA owners and players are scheduled to sit down today for their
first formal negotiations since Aug. 6, and if substantial progress
isn't made, the scheduled Nov. 3 start of the regular season is in
peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to sit there and talk all day and all night and
maybe someone will come up with something,'' NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik said. ``Often that's how it happens, but I
have no reason to be optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The seats may not be warm for long at this negotiating session,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if it lasted an hour,'' said one player, who
asked that he not be identified. ``They (the owners) don't won't to
negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the typical union reaction after it received a new set
of proposals from ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they send us a proposal (like) they sent us last time,
that's not even negotiating,'' Houston Rockets guard Eddie Johnson
told the ``Houston Chronicle.'' ``That's what we're disappointed
about. We're trying to address all of their needs (like) salaries
outpacing revenues . . . trying to come up with creative ways to
get them comfortable, but they don't even want to talk about it
unless it's a hard (salary) cap.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners' latest proposal would phase out the so-called Larry
Bird exception and create a hard salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Bird exception allows teams to sign their own players, after
three years of service, to whatever amount the team and player
agree upon without regard to salary cap restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The owners offered an alternative that would keep the Bird
exception intact, but it would provide for protection to the owners
should the money going toward player salaries exceed 54 percent of
gross basketball revenue. That limit would be reduced to 50 percent
by the third year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the owners proposed lengthening the rookie salary
scale from three to five years, with only the first three years
guaranteed. Clubs also would have the right to match an offer from
other clubs after the fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   A player would remain on the scale even longer if he enters the
league directly out of high school or after a few years in college.
It would provide for an additional year for each year the player
was under 20 years of age. An 18-year-old, for example, would be on
the scale for seven years, with the club having the option for two
more years.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would limit player incentive clauses to no more
than 5 percent of their base salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The owners offered to increase minimum salaries slightly, with
increases based on years of service. The minimum for a veteran
would start at $325,000 and go up to $750,000 for a 10-year player.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects include:
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening of the league's ability to discipline players.
</P>
<P>
   Tying all salaries to a percentage of the salary cap. No
contract could exceed the team cap at the time it is signed.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting most contracts to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Requiring players to participate in mandatory off-season
training under the supervision of the club.
</P>
<P>
   Requiring players under guaranteed contract to play in the
Continental Basketball Association if they are waived by their NBA
clubs. A Revamping of the drug policy to include marijuana,
amphetamines and barbiturates as banned substances. Currently, only
cocaine and heroin are banned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0141EDT &QL; 
