</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDELINED ELWAY ITCHING TO PLAY AGAINST SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ When John Elway finally decided to return for
a 16th NFL season, he didn't anticipate spending his Sunday
afternoons standing on the sideline with ailing body parts.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, it was a sore hamstring. Last week, it was a sore
back.
</P>
<P>
   This week? Elway's back is better. He practiced Wednesday for
the first time in a week and only the fifth time in the past three
weeks. Elway is expected to play in Sunday's game against the
Seahawks at the Kingdome, perhaps for the final time in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Elway doesn't just want to play, he needs to play. That's why he
decided to return rather than retire after the Broncos won their
first Super Bowl and there is little, if anything, left for Elway
to achieve or prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back to play. It's no fun being hurt,'' Elway said
Wednesday during his first conference-call interview of the season.
``It's frustrating being hurt. I came back to play football and I
was playing as good a football as I've ever played. So to get set
back like I have is really disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get back in there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The hamstring Elway strained while scrambling in the Broncos'
Week 3 victory at Oakland is fine. It's the back he tweaked while
lifting weights after practice last Wednesday that forced Elway to
miss Sunday's game against Philadelphia and has him listed as
probable for this week's game.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's week has been filled with massages, heat and ice
treatments, ultrasound and stretching exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling better, but I'm not totally back yet,'' he said.
``I'm a lot better than I was Sunday and have been making progress
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Elway practiced without pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Him playing without pain gives me pain,'' Seahawks coach
Dennis Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing as long as he has, and with the reckless abandon
he still flaunts, Elway has missed only 12 games due to injuries.
There were elbow and shoulder injuries and a concussion in his
rookie season in 1983, but none forced him to miss a start. Elway
missed one game in 1984 (shoulder); another in 1988 (sprained
ankle); four in 1992 (bruised shoulder); two in 1994 (strained
knee); and one in 1996 (hamstring).
</P>
<P>
   So this thing with his back is something different _ the injury
and the inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's disappointing, but it's not enough to regret the
fact that I came back,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   In Elway's absence, Bubby Brister has led the Broncos to their
first back-to-back wins without their icon of a quarterback. Of
course, the twin thrashings of the Washington Redskins and
Philadelphia Eagles have come against two teams that are 0-5.
</P>
<P>
   Brister has been downright Elway-esque, passing for four TDs in
a 41-16 rout of the Eagles, two in a 38-16 win over the Redskins
and two after replacing Elway in the Week 3 win at Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   As good as he has been, Brister is no Elway. But then, who is?
Or has been? Or can be?
</P>
<P>
   ``The defining moments have made him special,'' Seahawks
defensive end Michael Sinclair said of Elway's 45 game-saving
drives, with the last coming in his first Super Bowl victory.
``That's what makes any player special. The defining moments that
come in crunch time define those players. That's what makes John
Elway special.''
</P>
<P>
   This is probably Elway's final season, and last appearance at
the Kingdome. He hasn't come right out and said that, but it is the
feeling among his teammates and those who know him best.
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent interview with Fox television's football analyst
and former Steelers quarterback Terry Bradshaw, Elway did say he'd
return for a shot at winning three straight Super Bowls if the
Broncos can pull a repeat this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said `yes' so he'd get off it,'' Elway said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the laughter subsided, Elway added, ``The chances are that
I'll probably retire, but I just didn't want to shut the door. You
hate to walk away from a football team like I'm on now.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is to be it, Elway isn't making a big deal out of it and
doesn't want anyone else doing so, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really trying not to get too sentimental about the whole
deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Seattle is special for Elway. He was born in Port
Angeles. His wife, Janet, is from Tacoma. And the rivalry with the
Seahawks always seems to bring out the best in Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his overpublicized showdowns with former Seahawks
linebacker Brian Bosworth in the late 1980s ranked at the top of
his memory list, Elway cracked, ``No, not really. He wasn't there
long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Elway remembers the noise in the Kingdome and the
nuisance the Seahawks have been over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some great rivalries with them and it will be one
that I'll always remember,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Elway doesn't need football as much as football
needs Elway. Last year, he sold his string of car dealerships in
the Denver area for $86 million. He has a family he longs to spend
more time with _ his wife, whom he starting dating as a freshman at
Stanford and married after his rookie season with the Broncos, and
their children, Jessica, Jordan, Juliana and Jack.
</P>
<P>
   As Janet puts it, ``We are normal people living abnormal
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stop and smell the roses sometimes, and to reflect back
on what it's all about, you're a little bit in awe of it,'' Elway
said. ``We feel pretty lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
