<HEADLINE>
LIKE FATHER, NOT YET LIKE SON  
 YOUNG IRWIN PERSEVERES IN BID TO QUALIFY FOR PRO TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their lives are at opposite ends of the professional golf
spectrum. But Steve Irwin says that when people realize he is the
son of Senior PGA Tour star Hale Irwin, it's mostly a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's a little tough to be compared to my dad. A lot
of preconceived notions,'' said Irwin, 24, who recently moved to
the Valley from St. Louis, where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But being Hale Irwin's kid has its advantages, too, and I'd
sooner look at that side of it. The best part is that I've met so
many people in the golf world. A lot of special things with dad
have happened because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, there's a few other perks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free lessons, free clubs and free balls,'' said Irwin, whose
parents moved to Paradise Valley a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Irwin might need all of those things by the time this week
is over. He is one of 78 hopefuls going through the PGA/Nike Tour
first-stage qualifier at Talking Stick Golf Club in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a golf marathon,'' said Irwin, who had a 1-under 69 in
Tuesday's first round before a wind-blown 80 knocked him back into
a tie for 60th place Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the outlook is bleak for the youngster, who
yearns to be among the top 25 players to advance to the second
stage of qualifying. With 36 holes to play, he'll need more 69s to
have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll probably need more like a couple of 65s, but I'm
not giving up,'' Irwin said. ``I just had one of those days when
everything hit the fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make it past the first stage of qualifying last year,
either. But that is a big part of this process, gaining
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds as if Steve Irwin is well-grounded, that would be a
good observation. Hey, he could be just another rich kid, what with
his father already having won nearly $7.5 million in a little over
three years on the 50-and-older circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what he's done,'' Steve Irwin said. ``I think the
difference between Hale Irwin back when he played on the regular
tour and the one out there today on the senior tour is that he's
much more patient now. His success and the less stressful schedule
as a senior has just boosted him to a different level.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve is obviously light-years from there. But he is not going
to throw in his golf towel and fly off in his father's new
eight-seat Beechjet, which often is anchored at Scottsdale Airpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``My record isn't exactly stellar, but I'm not giving up (a
career in professional golf) even if I don't make it out of here
this week,'' he said. ``I might work for my dad in his golf course
design business some of the time, but I'm going to keep working on
my game, too.''
</P>
<P>
   True grit is another characteristic that Irwin inherited from
his father, who was an All-Big 8 defensive back at Colorado before
he won the NCAA golf championship in 1967, his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a little bit of football in high school. I was a
linebacker,'' said Steve, who is about 4 inches shorter than his
6-foot father. ``But I was too small, and I wanted to concentrate
on golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, about the only things my game has in common with my dad's
is that we both are pretty accurate and have good short games.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really serious about golf, although this week has been
pretty stressful,'' said Irwin, who also played golf for Colorado
but never finished better than runner-up in a college tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``But anything you want badly causes stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you peer at the leader board and find yourself
18 shots off the pace and trailing dozens of former All-Americans
and ex-tour players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just look at the talent, this is an incredible
(first-stage) group of guys to have to go up against. Maybe the
best in the country,'' Irwin said of such players as Rory
Sabbatini, Ted Purdy, Todd Demsey and Bill Lunde _ all former
first-team All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But desire has a lot to do with it, too. If you can get your
heart and your head into it _ and I know it sounds like a cliche _
anything is possible. I just feel like eventually, I'm going to get
it done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
