<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES' MARQUES TUIASOSOPO: ON THE LOOSE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You imagine Utah State defensive coaches in the video
room this week, puzzling over the problem of Marques Tuiasosopo.
</P>
<P>
   Will he throw it, as he did for 270 yards in his Washington
debut against Nebraska last year?
</P>
<P>
   Will he hand it off? Or will he hotfoot it to the perimeter and
create chaos over there, as he did with a 42-yard touchdown run
against Oregon in 1997 and another bolt of 46 yards in September
against BYU?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he makes the defense uncomfortable,'' said UW offensive
guard Tony Coats, recalling a play earlier this season. ``When he
came in, they said, `Option, option, watch the option.' And we ran
it up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   If his unpredictability is frazzling the Utah State braintrust,
Manu and Tina Tuiasosopo can relate. They are Marques' parents, and
he has driven them crazy before, too.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawk fans will remember Manu Tuiasosopo as an undersized but
productive defensive tackle from UCLA who played here from 1979-83.
When he would go home at night, he would often hear of little
Marques' latest indiscretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marques,'' Manu says, ``was our most hyperactive kid.''
</P>
<P>
   There are five Tuiasosopo kids. About every other day, you see
one of their names in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie is a senior volleyball player at the UW, followed by
Marques, a 6-foot-2, 210-pound sophomore quarterback. Then there is
Zach, a football player at Woodinville High; Matt, a 6-foot,
seventh-grade pitcher and shortstop who throws 75 mph and led
Woodinville West to within an out of the Little League World Series
this year; and 8-year-old Ashley, who told Marques the other day
she had a goal and an assist in her soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know she knew what an assist was,'' Marques
says. ``She's pretty good in her terminology.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a model family, everybody agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good, God-lovin' folks,'' says Pat Conniff, the Husky fullback
from Woodinville. ``Christians. They support each other in
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Marques came to Washington a year ago, polite and well-spoken.
He froze sportswriters by addressing them ``Mister ...'' But Manu
says you don't know the half of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I had a lot of out-in-the-shed, father-son type of
deals,'' Manu says. ``He was very, very, very active.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marques was little and the family would go out, restaurant
personnel would cringe at their approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bouncing off walls, breaking lights, climbing over tables,''
Manu recited. ``In three minutes, I'm outside, talking to him.
Tipping over salt shakers, poking fun at Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I at times stayed up at night, wondering where
this came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, Marques grew out of it. He pretty much corroborates his
dad's story, something he wouldn't have done a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd say something, and I'd always have to have the last
word,'' Marques says. ``I didn't (understand) at the time a lot of
things he would do. But now that I look back: You're right, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Conniff knows how different Marques is today from the kid he
made friends with in fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marques and Leslie live together,'' he said. ``I've never
heard of a brother and sister living together. They share a
house.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tuiasosopo parents sensed it might be a long childhood when
Marques was 2 or 3. Somehow, with the house locked up, he exited
through a front window and went off to explore the neighborhood,
leaving them to search.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Marques is just as elusive, only he's channeled it.
He became a three-sport standout at Woodinville, leading the
Falcons to the 1996 state quarterfinals, starting on the basketball
team, playing shortstop well enough to get drafted in the 28th
round by the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   He got seriously recruited, by Washington, Cal, UCLA and Notre
Dame. Some schools saw him as a safety. If the Huskies truly knew
this was a quarterback, they were prescient; he ran an option
offense at Woodinville, throwing only 75 passes as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had a flair for the dynamic,'' said Woodinville
coach Terry Agnew. ``Whether it was picking up a fumble and
returning it 90 yards for a touchdown, or the other team would
score, and he'd break a 60- or 70-yard run on the first or second
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about the first thing Tuiasosopo said when he arrived at
Washington was, ``I'm a quarterback.'' Then he went out and proved
it against Nebraska and Oregon, filling in for an injured Brock
Huard.
</P>
<P>
   Huard's misfortune is now Tuiasosopo's opportunity. Just as the
Huskies enter a softer part of their schedule, Huard is out 2-3
weeks because of a shoulder separation. The chance is there for
Tuiasosopo to shine, and swell the clamor from a segment of Husky
fans who prefer his versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Brock's offense,'' Tuiasosopo insists. ``One or two more
years of Huard can only be good for me and the program. He's been
like, I guess you could say, the toast of this program.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's an energy about Tuiasosopo that seems to infect
his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an exciting football player,'' Conniff says. ``He's
probably up there with the (Donovan) McNabbs and all those exciting
ballplayers that bring another dimension to the game. The crowd
loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the dash he brings, there's something Tuiasosopo hasn't
yet delivered in the three games in which he has played
extensively: a victory. He will try to get it against a team whose
defensive line coach, Mike Tuiasosopo, is his father's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him: `Marques, they're not going to win because of
you,''' Manu says. ``Everybody has a role to play.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Marques Tuiasosopo is listening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
