<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-YOUNG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH IS SERVED, BUT PLAN NOT ATTRACTING NEW HUNTERS  
 PERMITS GOING TO KIDS WHO OFTEN HUNT WITH DAD 
</HEADLINE>
 HUNTERS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ The average age of big-game hunters is about 45.
Does that mean we have a dying breed?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, say those who study such things. Somewhere, they say,
we missed a generation of hunters. Lost was a generation of dads
who hunt and are willing to teach their children. Whether that is
good or bad is a matter of personal opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Most researchers think it happened because of urbanization. It's
expensive and time consuming to take a big-game hunting trip.
Working parents often don't have that time to give. In rural areas,
hunting is a way of life. But rural living also is a dying way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to gain back some of those hunters, about five
years ago the Arizona Game and Fish Commission decided to allow
youths to hunt for doves, elk and javelina without competition from
adults. Deer and waterfowl were added later.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I expected was to see a single mother drive up in a
station wagon with her child and ask directions how to hunt,'' said
Bill Watt, an information specialist for Game and Fish in
Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened. We're still talking about big money.
Big-bore rifles are expensive. So is the ammunition. That's not to
mention the gear for camping out. Then there's the time.
</P>
<P>
   Two new commissioners, Bill Berlat of Tucson and Dennis Manning
of Alpine, are believers in youth hunts. They proposed that 5
percent of all big-game permits go to young hunters.
</P>
<P>
   So let's look at that. A four-day youth hunt for cow elk began
last Friday in Unit 7 near Flagstaff. Young hunters could enter a
computer drawing for 275 cow permits. That was the entire allotment
of cows for that unit. In other words, no other rifle shooters but
youths will hunt cows in that area.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the youth cow elk hunt allowed 100 to 150 young
hunters.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing a number of young hunters and their fathers,
it became apparent that most would have hunted anyway if they were
drawn. In other words, they came from hunting families that would
have hunted even if youth permits didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Pratt and son Loren operate a farm in Maricopa and own a
ranch near Payson. Loren's sons (Edward's grandsons) are David, 4,
and Douglas, 7.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first junior hunt for Douglas. ``He was on a deer
hunt two years ago and got lots of shots, but he couldn't hit
anything,'' Loren said.
</P>
<P>
   This was three generations of hunters. They'd have gone anyway
if drawn, but the youth hunt was a chance to get an easy permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it ought to be automatic that these kids get a
permit,'' Loren said.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Keuer and his son, Aaron, 11, of Tucson were there, too.
Aaron hadn't gotten a shot. They'd seen elk, but circumstances for
a shot had been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Aaron gets a shot, it'll be a good one,'' Kurt said.
``He'll kill it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's sister, Amy, killed an elk three years ago when she was
10.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got some competition there,'' Kurt said. ``That was a
regular hunt, and she hit the elk at 215 yards _ twice. There were
six men on that trip that didn't see an elk.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Gallagher, 11, of Peoria killed his elk the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just walking along, it came over a hill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Alan, said, ``It's a good way to get them going _ a
father and son thing. They (Game and Fish) did it right this year,
giving them the whole unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Both father and son said they'd have hunted together even
without the youth hunt.
</P>
<P>
   John Solares of Tubac had a different point of view.
</P>
<P>
   His son, John Paul, 13, killed a big cow elk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends I hunt with every year,'' the father said.
``This is more time to spend with my kids. If we (the adults) don't
get drawn, we still can go out.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a theory that this youth hunt could be more successful
if the eligible age were raised to 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real barrier to the current system,'' said Tice
Supplee, head of the Game and Fish's Game Branch. ``An older young
person can drive. If we raised the ante on who can play, we have
kids (who can drive) taking kids (who can't).''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Janisch, information specialist for Game and Fish, said the
department's highly successful fishing clinics are different from
youth big-game hunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catching a couple of bluegill on an inadequate rod is a lot
different than big-game hunting,'' he said. ``It's more like
starting a kid fly-fishing at Lees Ferry. Handing a kid a .30-06 is
like handing a kid a fly rod. A .22 would be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Watt agrees. ``Maybe we should put more emphasis on small
game,'' he said. ``What if we had a squirrel hunt? We could get
hunter education instructors to take out the kids. They could use
.410s or 20-gauges to shoot. It would be a good, supervised hunt.
Any kid could come. I'd also like to see the youth dove and duck
hunts expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing very few new hunters at these big-game hunts.
Most of it is hunting families. We need to be introducing
non-hunting kids to the sport. The ones we're seeing here would go
anyway.'' &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
