r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NEDNEY-     10-08 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NEDNEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2ND-GUESSED NEDNEY HASN'T LOST CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're moody. Goofy.
</P>
<P>
   They probably shouldn't be allowed to waltz in and settle an
issue that others have beaten their brains out for three hours
trying to settle.
</P>
<P>
   With one swing of his leg, a professional football kicker can
make a name or be called one.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nedney, who kicks for the Cardinals, lives for those
moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all comes down to, `Are you ready to perform?' '' Nedney
said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been well documented that Nedney didn't get his chance
last Sunday. With 5 seconds to play and the Cardinals needing a
field goal to send Oakland into overtime, Nedney was sent onto the
field for what would have been a 55-yard attempt into a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin thought his offense could complete a
quick out after a Raiders timeout to knock a few yards off the try.
Tobin called Nedney back.
</P>
<P>
   Replays show that the receiver, Eric Metcalf, made the catch and
stepped out of bounds for a two-yard gain with two seconds left,
but the officiating crew ruled that time expired.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney was disappointed the coach didn't leave him out there to
try it from 55. But he said on Wednesday that his confidence is not
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a play that players live for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Next time, Nedney said, he will try to offer input to Tobin,
something he did not do Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lesson learned there,'' Nedney said. ``The next
time we're in a field-goal situation where I think I have the leg
and the conditions are favorable, I'll be standing there next to
Coach Tobin giving him an extra nudge. He was probably looking for
something there to influence his decision. If it's a kick I know I
can make and I see him pondering, I'll let him know.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said after the game he didn't ask for Nedney's input.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably isn't a kicker in the world who wouldn't have
said, `Put me in Coach, I can make it,' '' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   In slightly less than one year with the Cardinals, Nedney has
yet to miss a field goal inside 43 yards (14-14). Beyond, he is two
for nine, including a career-long 47-yarder against Philadelphia
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking legend Jan Stenerud had worked during the summer with
Nedney, who is best known for putting his kickoffs deep into the
end zone with his strong left leg but also known for hooking his
long field-goal tries.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney said Stenerud found him to be technically sound. They
spent most of their time together on the day-to-day preparation in
practice, the mental game of the kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney, 25, who was signed last Oct. 14 to replace Kevin Butler,
acknowledges that his kicks do have a natural draw, similar to the
flight of a golf shot. For the past two weeks, Nedney has offset
the line on his tries beyond 47 yards to the left to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, on the longer field goals a kicker thinks he has to
swing harder,'' Tobin said. ``It's like a golf shot. On the long
ones sometimes you think you have to get more power into it, and
you change your motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe has a strong enough leg that if we can get him to swing
with the same rhythm his consistency level outside 43 yards will
pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedney also has become the defense's buddy with his booming
kickoffs. He had a Cardinals-record 16 touchbacks last season after
being the NFL-co-leader with 20 while with the Miami Dolphins in
1996, his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tells you that he has a strong leg,'' said Cardinals
special teams coach Al Everest. ``The question is consistency. He's
perfect inside 43 yards, which is a pretty good statistic, and no
kicker is perfect beyond that. How far out is he accurate, it
depends on the day, the wind and the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kick on Sunday was a critical kick, not one we were just
going to slap in before halftime. In that situation, you might let
him try one from there. These were different circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said he remains confident in Nedney. It is how far that
confidence extends that was at issue. In pregame, Nedney warms up
out to 53 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel good at 53 we pull it back to 58,'' he said. ``In a
game, inside 55 I feel I definitely have a shot. Outside of that it
depends on conditions.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
