<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-IRISH-CONNECTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEALY SINGS PRAISES OF IRISH KICKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite his critics, from the crackpots and cowards to the more
civil but still manic armchair experts, Notre Dame placekicker Jim
Sanson still has many admirers. One of them was his holder for a
good part of eight football seasons together, from Pop Warner
leagues in Scottsdale through St. Mary's High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an outstanding leg,'' Ryan Kealy said. ``He's so
impressive to hold for and to watch kick. He's a great athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy was the quarterback on the 1995 St. Mary's team that went
14-0 and won the state Class 5A championship. He now is Arizona
State's quarterback, a third-year sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy missed most of last week's loss to Southern California
with his first-ever concussion. But he is back at practice this
week, reporting no ill effects, and will start Saturday against
Notre Dame at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sanson, a junior, will be on the opposite sideline. It's a St.
Mary's reunion of sorts, and it includes ASU sophomore wide
receiver Tariq McDonald and Willie Daniel, a freshman defensive
back.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy and Sanson hung out a lot together as kids, spending time
at each other's homes. Their families remain close, and Kealy went
with his parents to the Sanson's Christmas party last year. Jim,
however, wasn't there because Notre Dame was preparing for the
Independence Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Farrell, the longtime St. Mary's coach, said Kealy and
Sanson showed up practically as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out of the same mold,'' he said. ``Very committed to
the game. Very disciplined. Both became leaders, not just by the
quality of their play but the quality of their efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanson did a lot more for Farrell than just kick. He was a
skilled, versatile player and the captain of the team. He played
defensive back and receiver, catching 10 of Kealy's passes in the
title game against Scottsdale Horizon _ at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did everything,'' said Kealy, who held for a 58-yard field
goal Sanson made against Mesa Westwood in 1994, the longest in the
country that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was such a utilized player out there. He contributed in so
many different ways. I don't think he ever got the credit for how
good an overall athlete he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanson, meanwhile, is just as effusive in his praise of Kealy
and McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brag to everyone out here about Ryan and Tariq,'' said
Sanson, who checks the Internet to keep up with his former
teammates. ``Our team has such high expectations of those two
because of everything I've said.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, who is emerging as a potent weapon for the Sun Devils,
was Kealy's favorite receiver at St. Mary's. Sanson was the
secondary guy. But during his freshman year at Notre Dame, after
winning the kicking job and helping beat No. 6 Texas with a late
field goal, Sanson became a primary target.
</P>
<P>
   He was the subject of anonymous death threats and harassment
after missing a crucial extra point in an overtime loss to USC as a
freshman, then took more abuse and was benched after missing three
field goals in another loss to USC last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanson has reclaimed the job this year and has made five of
six field-goal attempts so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Jimmy is he always comes back,'' Kealy said.
``He's such a great competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kealy might do well to take note. He still tends to get down on
himself, like after the Oregon State game. ASU won, 24-3, but Kealy
had a poor game statistically and was close to being despondent
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read about Kealy struggling and being unhappy,'' Sanson
said. ``Ryan isn't struggling. Ryan is just Ryan. He's always been
hard on himself. I know Ryan, especially in our game, will rise to
the occasion and have one of his best games.'' &QL; 
Republic writer Kent Somers contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
