<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BALDWIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF WATER, DUCKS AT BALDWIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR CITY _ Just when you thought you'd heard the last of El
Nino, waterfowlers might get the final word. For the first time in
three years, Baldwin Lake holds enough water to host hunters for
the opening day of duck season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duck season at Baldwin is based solely on water,'' said Jim
Davis, a Department of Fish and Game associate wildlife biologist
in nearby Big Bear Lake. ``If there is no water, there are no
ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   And most of the time there is no water in this shallow basin
perched high in the San Bernardino Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The area typically doesn't get much runoff; even in years when
it does, streams are diverted for water rights and, for the most
part, Baldwin remains parched. Maps designate this flat spot east
of Big Bear as a dry lake. Not since the fall of 1995 _ the last
time Baldwin was considered huntable _ have waterfowl reports
featured duck counts from the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime last December the lake got water, but usually it
freezes over at night by that time,'' Davis said. ``Guys actually
chopped up the ice and put boats in.''
</P>
<P>
   Their success rate? ``Limited,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   It's all based on what you consider huntable, and Baldwin Lake
will definitely be huntable for Saturday's waterfowl opener ... and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be huntable all season this year,'' said Davis.
``What's going to limit the hunting after November is the cold and
how much it's going to freeze at night. And if it's not frozen
over, you can essentially have it to yourself; we don't get much
hunting pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to El Nino's watershed winter, the lake is between a
third- and half-full, or about 100 to 150 huntable surface acres
out of a 300-acre capacity. (When full, the lake measures 4 feet at
its deepest point.)
</P>
<P>
   However cold it might be, late-season hunting has been fruitful
in years past, when daytime thaws allow for easier access at
Baldwin. Shooting is allowed only from a boat that is completely
surrounded by water. The lake had enough water to attract hunters
during the falls of 1994 and 1995; shotguns were silent during the
drought of 1989-93, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   At present, he reports strictly resident populations of birds _
``mostly mallards, a few gadwalls and ruddy ducks and a ton of
coots'' _ and no migratory movement at all. No geese, either. The
biologist expects to see plenty of pintails, shovelers and teals,
along with flocks of Canada geese, by mid-December and on through
season's end Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get out on the lake anywhere and expect to see birds
flying over and get good pass-shooting,'' Davis said. ``The problem
is cover is very limited and you have to be pretty camouflaged out.
Bring a portable blind system - some sort of camo over a frame on
the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Permanent blinds are not permitted at the lake and shooting is
forbidden in certain spots, particularly near the west-end
launching area, due to the proximity of the Big Bear City
municipality, adjacent highways and private property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a wilderness experience, but it is a remote area,''
Davis said. ``You can spend a couple of days exploring the area for
deer and quail hunts and do a waterfowl hunt someplace in the
middle of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Entry permits are required for the season's first seven shoot
days, which are on Wednesdays and Saturdays only; the requisite is
lifted after Oct. 31. Only 17 permits may be issued per shoot day
during the quota period, and applications must be received by the
DFG's state headquarters 17 days prior to a desired shoot day. That
means if you haven't already applied, it's too late to hunt at
Baldwin Lake before Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   To apply to hunt on Oct. 28 or Oct. 31, applications must be in
by Saturday or Wednesday, respectively. The application fee is
$1.05 per hunt day; mail it with your request to the DFG's License
and Revenue Branch, 3211 S St., Sacramento, CA 95816.
</P>
<P>
   For additional permit information, call (916) 227-2244. For
questions specifically regarding Baldwin Lake, contact Davis at
(909) 866-1549.
</P>
</TEXT>
