<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5564 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-B     10-08 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ARE RULED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They still may go down as authors of the greatest
season ever, but while Wednesday night's detour from immortality
will be blamed on an umpire's call, the New York Yankees also must
hold one of their own accountable for ignoring a lesson first
learned in Little League:
</P>
<P>
   Don't argue a play while it's still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, blinded by his horror
that plate umpire Ted Hendry didn't call Cleveland's Travis Fryman
out for running inside the first-base line after his 12th-inning
bunt, failed to retrieve the ball, which had trickled no more than
30 feet behind him after Tino Martinez's throw struck Fryman in the
back.
</P>
<P>
   While Knoblauch pointed and pleaded his case with the umpires,
pinch runner Enrique Wilson first sprinted, then staggered home
with the go-ahead run all the way from first while Fryman made it
to third, from where he eventually scored on Kenny Lofton's two-run
single that capped underdog Cleveland's 4-1 win over the Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no clean sweep through the playoffs for the
Yankees, who had eliminated Texas in three straight and whipped the
Indians in Game 1 of the American League Championship Series before
losing an extra-inning postseason game in Yankee Stadium for the
first time since Game 5 of the 1964 World Series. This
best-of-seven series is now tied, 1-1, and headed for three games
in Cleveland as certainly as Wilson and Fryman circled the bases
while Knoblauch struck a pose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea where the ball was to begin with,'' Knoblauch
said, ``and I expected (Fryman) to be called out. It was so loud,
so crazy, there was no question in my mind (that he was out).''
</P>
<P>
   But while Knoblauch chose to debate the issue on the spot,
Fryman spotted his chance to flee a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd keep running until somebody told me to stop,''
said Fryman, who had been asked to attempt a sacrifice just one
other time this season by manager Mike Hargrove and didn't get that
bunt down because he was hit by a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman's last successful sacrifice had come on Aug. 25, 1996 _
338 games and 1,300 at-bats ago _ but Hargrove asked the third
baseman to try again after Jim Thome led off the 12th with a single
off Jeff Nelson, one of five Yankee pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   This time Fryman laid down a beauty just inside the first-base
line, then sprinted past the ball on the grass as first baseman
Tino Martinez charged in to make the play. Fryman was clearly
running inside the first-base line all the way to the bag, ignoring
the 3-foot ``runner's channel'' that spans the last 45 feet to the
base and is marked by an additional line on the edge of the infield
dirt in foul territory.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he reached the base, Martinez's throw struck Fryman
between the numbers. First base umpire John Shulock made a ``safe''
signal as Fryman crossed the bag, and while Knoblauch had a nutty,
rookie Wilson made a madcap dash around the bases that ended with
him stumbling the last 30 feet to the plate, just beating
Knoblauch's afterthought of a throw.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, watching from the visitors' dugout on the third-base
side, said he paid no heed to the Knoblauch summit meeting with the
men in blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the ball roll free,'' Hargrove said, ``I picked up
our lead runner, Wilson, and tried to help him stand up. I thought
we'd have to get a wheelbarrow out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians now had a lead in what had begun as a wonderful
pitchers' duel between Charles Nagy (who left after 6 2/3 innings
when the Yankees tied it, 1-1, on Scott Brosius's double) and David
Cone (who went eight innings, allowing only David Justice's home
run in the fourth), then turned into a tense standoff between
bullpens. Soon they would have an insurmountable one.
</P>
<P>
   But first, more talk: Hendry explained to an incredulous Yankees
manager Joe Torre that Fryman was not guilty of interference
because he was entitled to the bag, the throw did not strike him
until he was already there, and he had not impeded Martinez's
throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on the grass, it was so blatant,'' Torre said. ``I
don't know what to say. It was a terrible call.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, umpiring crew chief Jim Evans _ yes, the same
man who was Jimy Williams's nemesis all season _ launched into an
elaborate explanation of the rule, though when asked point-blank if
his colleague had made the right call, he seemed to hedge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he was right on the base, the fact that he was
at the base, makes it a very tough judgment call for the plate
umpire,'' Evans said. ``I thought the call could have gone either
way. But I think it was a proper call probably in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians parlayed Fryman's presence at third into two
insurance runs. Sandy Alomar was hit by a pitch, Joey Cora walked,
and Lofton, hitless in nine previous at-bats in the series, lined a
bases-loaded single to left, scoring Alomar and Cora.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton was cut down trying to advance to second, but no matter.
The Yankees, 1 for 12 Wednesday night with runners in scoring
position, went down meekly in the bottom of the inning against
Indians closer Mike Jackson, who saved three games against the Red
Sox in the AL Division Series and picked up his fourth of the
postseason Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland's a good team,'' Torre said, ``but you'd have liked
to have them beat us clean. They got the other base hit to make it
4-1, but you've got to have better umpiring than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It leaves a bad taste and it's bad for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But what's bad for baseball isn't necessarily bad for the
Indians. Hargrove, while demurring that he didn't watch Fryman's
path to first, said he thought the umpires made the right call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to belittle that play, the importance of that
play,'' Hargrove said, ``but honest to goodness, we don't care how
we got the win as long as it's ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, meanwhile, said he was ``dumbfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a no-doubter,'' he said. ``When you play four
hours out there and it's decided that way, it's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of dumbfounded, really. It was a mistake, maybe. I
don't know. I reacted to the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre readily acknowledged that Knoblauch's reaction was the
wrong one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the replay,'' he said. ``He was yelling at the
umpire. You can't do that. You've got to make the play, then argue
the call. I think he was just so shocked that (Hendry) didn't make
the call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
