</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-OPENERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATURDAY IS OPENING OF SEASONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Saturday marks the regional opening of deer-,
bear- and waterfowl- hunting seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Duck shooters will target their favorite sites across most of
the state, including the Southern California and Southern San
Joaquin Valley waterfowl zones. The Colorado River Zone opens
Friday. (The Northeastern California Zone kicked off Oct. 3.)
</P>
<P>
   The most popular Southland locales are San Jacinto Wildlife
Area, (909) 654-0580, and Imperial Wildlife Area, (760) 359-0577,
where water coverage is spread well and should attract large
numbers of quackers.
</P>
<P>
   Five deer zones are opening in a range that includes Los
Angeles, Orange and San Bernardino counties, Northern Ventura
County and parts of Kern, Riverside and San Diego counties.
</P>
<P>
   Deer are scattered throughout the San Bernardino Mountains due
to ample grass and other forage, and the general advice is to scour
off-road sites normally not scouted. ``Walk someplace you have
never been before,'' said Jim Davis, a Department of Fish and Game
associate wildlife biologist in Big Bear Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation to bear hunters is to get out soon. The zones
that encompass L.A. County, Northern Ventura County and
Southwestern San Bernardino County are among the latest to open in
the state, and biologists anticipate an early closure.
</P>
<P>
   Bear season is slated to end Dec. 27, unless the state kill
quota of 1,500 is reached before then. As of Wednesday, 294 bears
had been shot statewide in zones already open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is there are more and more bear out there, including
in Southern California, where they are expanding their natural
range from the San Gabriel and San Bernardino mountains,'' said
Doug Updike, senior wildlife biologist with the DFG's Wildlife
Management Division in Sacramento. ``It appears to be tracking last
season, in that it we're looking at an early closure.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information, consult the DFG's hunting-regulation
handbooks for waterfowl and for mammals and furbearers, or call the
department's Long Beach office at (562) 590-5126. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
