u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-BOS     10-08 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMINITI GIVES PADRES JUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hold off on those Yankees-Braves World Series wagers.
The Yankees are no guarantee to get out of the American League. And
the San Diego Padres have something to say about which is the best
team in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   They refused to be intimidated Wednesday night by the team with
the best record in the league, earning a 3-2, 10-inning victory at
Turner Field in the rain-delayed opener of the best-of-seven NL
Championship Series on Ken Caminiti's homer off Kerry Ligtenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the 10th, Caminiti victimized rookie closer
Ligtenberg with a shot over the fence in left-center field and took
San Diego closer Trevor Hoffman off the hook after he'd allowed the
tying run in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   For seven innings, this was a duel between the starters.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Andy Ashby gave up a home run to Andruw Jones in the
third inning, but that was his only lapse. The Padres tied the game
on a run-scoring single by Tony Gwynn with two out in the fifth
against the winningest pitcher in postseason history, John Smoltz,
and went ahead in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, who has won 11 postseason games, ran out of gas after
throwing 117 pitches. Ruben Rivera led off the eighth with a double
to left-center. Lefthander John Rocker was called in to face
Caminiti, who lined to right. After the catch, Rivera reached
third, but not without controversy. The throw from Andruw Jones
beat him to the bag. But he was called safe on a close play by
umpire Greg Bonin, even though it appeared he had slid past the
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz, the former Red Sox malcontent and current
postseason poster boy, was sent up to pinch hit for Wally Joyner.
Leyritz had become something of a cult figure with three homers in
the NL Division Series against Houston, but this time he barely got
the ball off his bat. No matter _ it did the trick.
</P>
<P>
   His chopper between the mound and third was grabbed by ancient
reliever Dennis Martinez. The 43-year-old veteran didn't look the
runner back and threw to first _ while Rivera came barreling to the
plate. Andres Galarraga first dropped Martinez's throw, then made a
hurried throw that skipped past catcher Javy Lopez, and the Padres
had the edge. Briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was done after seven innings, and Hoffman, author of 53
saves in 54 chances during the regular season, was brought in as
the third pitcher in the eighth, stranding a runner at second.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves got to him in the ninth after he struck out
Galarraga on a 3-2 pitch. Ryan Klesko drew a walk, and when Javy
Lopez singled to left, Klesko slammed headfirst into third,
bloodying his nose in the process. Andruw Jones's fly to left
brought Klesko in with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   But then it was the turn of Atlanta's closer, Ligtenberg, to
fail.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of hours, it appeared that the Braves and Padres
would have to postpone their initial showdown. Rain delayed the
start 2 hours 1 minute, and by then, many of the tomahawk choppers
were headed home. Those who stayed saw Smoltz pitch his way into
and out of trouble as the Padres squandered an excellent scoring
chance in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Quilvio Veras led off the game with a walk and
moved to third on a throwing error by Smoltz. The Braves
righthander fielded a grounder by Gwynn and attempted to start a
double play. But his throw to second got past shortstop Walt Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, however, is a master of escape in such situations. He
threw out the next hitter, Greg Vaughn, with Veras holding and
Gwynn moving to second. Caminiti struck out. And when Joyner
grounded harmlessly to first, Smoltz covering, he was out of the
inning unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego also had runners in the second and third but again had
nothing to show for it. Not so Atlanta, which began chipping away
at Ashby. In the third inning, leadoff batter Andruw Jones hit a
1-0 pitch into the left-field seats. Michael Tucker then doubled,
and Smoltz sacrificed him to third.
</P>
<P>
   But the rally fizzled. Braves manager Bobby Cox tried a suicide
squeeze, and it backfired as Weiss popped to the pitcher and Ashby
easily doubled Tucker off third, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves threatened again in the fourth as Keith Lockhart led
off with a double to the wall in right-center. But Chipper Jones
lined to left; Galarraga grounded to short, moving Lockhart to
third; and Ashby threw out Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Padre bats finally came to life in the fifth, when they tied the
score. And it took a sensational over-the-shoulder catch by Tucker
to save another two runs. Smoltz, who had breezed through the
previous inning, gave up a leadoff single to Carlos Hernandez. A
sacrifice bunt by Ashby put him in scoring position after Chris
Gomez struck out. But the second walk of the game, to Veras,
brought up Gwynn, who dumped an opposite-field single to left,
scoring Hernandez. Tucker took a sure double away from Vaughn with
a circus catch in right to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The near miss was costly to San Diego. Vaughn suffered a
strained left quadriceps muscle while running and left the game in
favor of Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz pitched out of another jam in the sixth. With two out,
Steve Finley and Hernandez worked him for walks. But Smoltz made
Gomez his fourth strikeout victim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
