<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5598 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--ROBERTSONCOL-HNS     10-08 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--ROBERTSONCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ Had the Astros won just four more regular-season games
and two more Division Series games, there would have been NLCS
baseball played at a reasonable hour Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston. Under glass.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, one more reason to be bitter about the events of the past
weekend in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening's two-hour rain delay was, in many ways,
inevitable, a function of the law of averages. The Braves have
played host to 39 playoff games in the 1990s, which must surely be
the major-league record for a single decade. None of them had been
postponed or, to my memory, even appreciably delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, since it's still 1998, you know where the blame
rests.
</P>
<P>
   El Nio.
</P>
<P>
   But also, I think, on the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The nasty storm system that wreaked soggy havoc on our inaugural
CART race Sunday afternoon is the same one that caused Game 1 of
the NLCS to be pushed back, waaay back, to the ungodly hour of
10:16 p.m. EDT. By the time of the first pitch, some of the beer
vendors were already drained of product. But because even heavier
rain is forecast for today, we had no choice other than to
patiently wait out the drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   A Friday doubleheader in lieu of a much-needed travel day _
Atlanta and San Diego are more than 4{ hours apart _ was a grim
option to contemplate considering that Game 3 will start at 1:15
p.m. on the West Coast on Saturday, as TV says it must.
</P>
<P>
   And what TV says goes. Remember that bizarre 48-hour break
between the two Astros-Padres games in Houston?
</P>
<P>
   I figured you might.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres clearly profited from said hiatus, getting to throw
Kevin Brown twice in three games and thereby mask their inferior
pitching depth. So there will be a definite poetic justice meted
out if San Diego ends up in a pitching pickle.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves can withstand almost any imaginable disruption save
for another pass-through by General Sherman. As things stand, if
the NLCS script goes according to their plan, they will be
hard-pressed to ever use their latest phenom, Kevin Millwood, who
won 17 games. Year after year, it seems, theirs remains an
embarrassment of riches.
</P>
<P>
   Yet also the other, bad kind of embarrassment. Atlanta is a
franchise increasingly victimized by its inevitable regular-season
success in tandem with its predictable postseason shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Braves fans, as rabid a bunch of tomahawk choppers as could be
found six or seven autumns ago, have lost their edge. While the
chopping and chanting continues, you sense an underlying lack of
conviction, overtly manifested by the thousands of empty upper-deck
seats.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of participation in the NLCS and one piddling
World Series victory to show for it, the appeal of Turner Field's
high-altitude ``cheap'' seats at $45 per has dwindled
precipitously. You might not see every one of those tickets used _
or even sold _ until the Braves are nine innings shy of a world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, though, the Braves won't admit they are rankled by the
apparently tepid interest in playoff matchups that have become
downright mundane. As Game 2 starter Tom Glavine said: ``Who are we
to say (Atlantans) should be spending their money on baseball
tickets?
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, you don't draw over 3 million fans without a lot of
support, and we were able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Albeit before the prices got jacked through the non-roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the city is very excited,'' argues manager Bobby Cox.
`` The seats that are available they're not exactly the best in the
world. But we're still going to get 46,000 to 48,000 in here, if
not more, and that's a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But several thousand more, it turns out, than would purchase
tickets. Official paid attendance was 42,117, by far the smallest
Atlanta postseason crowd of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, an air of palpable anticipation was lacking in the
stadium. No doubt the long wait, the late hour and alcohol-dulled
senses contributed to the muted emotions, but you sensed a
been-there-done-that attitude among the many jaded, with good
reason, locals.
</P>
<P>
   In these parts, playoff ball has become only slightly more of an
event than, well, watching rain fall.
</P>
<P>
   And given how the interminable evening concluded, the rain was
about the best part. The Padres finagled a cheap go-ahead run in
the top of the eighth, endured Atlanta's battling back to tie the
score in the bottom of the ninth, then won it anyway 3-2 on Ken
Caminiti's home run in the top of the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   For the 20,000 or so insomniac Atlantans dedicated enough to the
home team's increasingly quixotic cause to have hung on through
such a protracted, ultimately bitter end _ it finally came at 1:43
a.m. local time with two Braves stranded on base _ the cynicism and
ennui surely deepened.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder how many will return tonight?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
