A5650 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUATEMALA-BISHOP-SFCH     10-08 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA-BISHOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY 2 ATTACKERS KILLED GUATEMALAN BISHOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL WALLACE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team of U.S. forensic experts has concluded that at least two
attackers were responsible for the killing of Guatemalan Bishop
Juan Jose Gerardi _ a finding that undercuts the official
government explanation of the slaying as a ``crime of passion''
committed by a single suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The experts _ San Francisco private investigator Jack Palladino,
San Diego forensic dentist Norman Sperber and San Antonio deputy
medical examiner Robert Bux _ based their opinion on an examination
of the evidence collected by Guatemalan authorities after Gerardi
was bludgeoned to death April 26 and after an autopsy that was
conducted last month.
</P>
<P>
   After a careful review of the evidence, they concluded that the
official theory _ that Gerardi was slain by his assistant, the Rev.
Mario Orantes _ is simply not credible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a crime of passion,'' Palladino said during an
interview this week from his San Francisco office. ``It is a
political crime. I don't say that because it is simply the more
likely explanation. I say it because it is the only possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerardi was killed two days after he oversaw the release of a
landmark report on war crimes committed by the military and rebels
during Guatemala's 36-year civil war, which ended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Palladino, Bux and Guatemalan human rights officials have
planned a press conference in Washington Thursday to reveal
previously undisclosed information linking the Guatemalan military
to the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemalan authorities have concluded that Orantes, who lived
with Gerardi and discovered his body, beat the bishop to death with
a large piece of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   But Palladino said Bux, a forensic pathologist with 14 years of
experience who has performed more than 4,000 autopsies, concluded
that two different types of weapons were involved: the chunk of
blood-stained concrete recovered by police at the scene and a thin,
hard smooth object used to strike a powerful blow that fractured
the sockets of both of Gerardi's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The thin object has never been recovered and appears to have
been removed from the scene by Gerardi's killers. Palladino said
Bux's finding that two different weapons had been used to kill the
bishop makes it unlikely that only one person was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that Gerardi's body had been moved during the
assault. The bishop was more than six feet tall and weighed 240
pounds, and the condition of his clothing indicates that he was
lifted physically off the ground by two people working together.
</P>
<P>
   In the official explanation of Gerardi's death, Guatemalan
authorities say that the bishop appeared to have been bitten by
Orantes' German shepherd, Baloo, who was sleeping beside the priest
on the night of the bishop's death.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sperber and Bux analyzed the dog's teeth and the wounds
on the bishop's face, and concluded that it was not possible that
the injuries were caused by a dog bite.
</P>
<P>
   Palladino, whose past investigations include a seven-year probe
into the mass murder-suicide of People's Temple members in Guyana,
said that the viciousness of the assault and the nature of the
injuries lead him to conclude that the bishop's death was
premeditated by two intruders, not a spur-of-the-moment attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were guys who knew what they wanted to do,'' he said.
``They wanted to kill him and they wanted to mutilate him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
