<HEADER>
A5655 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-SFCHR     10-08 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS FOR VOTES OF CONSCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton made a final plea to lawmakers
Wednesday to cast ``a vote of principle and conscience'' on the eve
of Thursday's House vote, which is all but certain to authorize the
third impeachment inquiry in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to others to decide what happens to me, and ultimately
it's going to be up to the American people to make a clear
statement there,'' Clinton told reporters in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   With passage of a Republican resolution calling for an
open-ended inquiry considered inevitable, attention is focused on
how many Democrats will support a process that could lead to the
nation's first presidential impeachment since Andrew Johnson in
1868.
</P>
<P>
   Each Democratic defection will make it harder for the White
House to dismiss the procedure as a partisan witch-hunt. As of last
night, estimates of Democratic votes ranged from 10 to 60, with
Southern and moderate lawmakers regarded as most likely to join
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Among San Francisco Bay Area Democrats, only Rep. Ellen Tauscher
said she expects to vote in favor of the Republican version of the
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher said in an interview that she favors a Democratic
alternative that would set strict time limits and parameters on the
investigation. But if that measure fails, as expected, she intends
to vote for the GOP resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the only way to move this forward is to have an
inquiry initiated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment inquiry _ which could begin as soon as this
month _ would be the first since Watergate. In 1974, President
Richard Nixon resigned shortly after the House Judiciary Committee
approved articles of impeachment. The only other impeachment
proceedings against a president took place more than a hundred
years ago when the House voted to impeach Johnson. He was later
acquitted by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings will be based on the evidence compiled by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr, who concluded that Clinton lied
under oath, obstructed justice and tampered with witnesses in an
effort to conceal an extramarital affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. Republicans have set an informal deadline
of New Year's Day but have kept open the possibility that the
inquiry might run longer or be expanded to include other matters,
such as Whitewater or campaign finance violations.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was caught in an awkward position of hoping
Democrats will vote against the resolution while trying to avoid
the appearance that it was trying to influence the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that it is not proper for us . . . to aggressively
try to impact or lobby people on this,'' said White House Press
Secretary Joe Lockhart. ``While we understand the politics and the
political pressures, we hope (members will) do what they believe is
right for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the president had made about a dozen calls to
members of Congress on the matter and insisted that there has been
no horse-trading on legislation with those who offer their support
or threats against those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Hillary Rodham Clinton met with about 25
freshman Democrats and made the case that the procedure embraced by
Republicans _ based on the Watergate model used 24 years ago _ is
unfair. Vice President Al Gore has made about a dozen calls to
lawmakers to make a similar argument, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats, including some who have sharply disagreed with
the president in the past, echoed the White House's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, of San Francisco, decried what she regards as
the inconsistencies between the heavy-handed, open inquiry into
Clinton and the discreet investigation into House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi noted that the same Republicans who voted for Gingrich as
their speaker after he lied under oath to a congressional committee
about his political practices are now seeking to impeach a
president for lying about a extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hypocrisy is raging here,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats urged a radically different approach and
suggested that Clinton give party members the go-ahead to support
the Republican plan. Since approval of the Republican resolution is
a foregone conclusion, some Democrats argue, the president should
eliminate what may become a damaging issue in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Moran, D-Va., told reporters that if the vote breaks
down along partisan lines, ``then the November election is likely
to be a referendum on the president's conduct.'' That, he added, is
not in the ``long-term best interests of the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be in the best interest of Democrats, Moran said, if
the election turns on issues such as education, health care and the
future of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also received a stern warning from Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., who said on the Senate floor: ``Don't tamper with
this jury.'' Senators would decide whether to convict Clinton and
remove him from office if the House approves articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher, a freshman, is the only Bay Area member for whom the
vote is expected to be an election issue. Her challenger, Charles
Ball, has questioned her close ties to the president and sought to
make Clinton's troubles an issue in the campaign. Wednesday,
Tauscher chastised Clinton's behavior as ``deplorable,
self-indulgent, reckless and just plain wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that ``at this point, it is not clear to me that
those offenses rise to the level of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher faces a dilemma familiar to other Democrats. On the one
hand, they do not want to give Republicans a weapon that allows
them to bash a Democratic president for the next several months or
longer. At the same time, they do not want to appear to be letting
him off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a debate about whether (to investigate the
president), this is a debate about how it will it be done,'' said
House Minority leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., ``The way the
Republicans are trying to do this is not right. It is a long,
extended, drawn-out fishing expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats worked into the evening crafting an alternative, which
will likely be offered as an amendment to the Republican proposal.
Sources said the alternative would call for a firm December 31
deadline and would confine the investigation to matters covered in
the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Although the measure has almost no chance of passing, it could
provide a way for Democrats who vote against the Republican
resolution while still going on the record with their support for
an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Oakland, however, said she will vote against
both alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't condone President Clinton's behavior,'' Lee said.
``But I know the country wants us to move forward and work on the
issues, such as eduction, a patient's bill of rights and the
environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
