r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORIST-BARRIER-SFC     10-08 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-BARRIER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVERMORE LAB SAYS BARRIER WILL STOP TRUCK-  BOMBS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    Engineers from the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory said
Wednesday that they have successfully tested what they called a
``terrorist vehicle barrier'' that twice destroyed trucks loaded
with 400 pounds of sand to simulate a death-dealing load of high
explosives.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The barrier, made of two concrete blocks and 10 steel pipes
linked by a necklace of one-inch steel cables, was the brainchild
of Willard H. Wattenburg, a consultant to the weapons laboratory,
who is known for his often off-beat concepts that have actually
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The test Wednesday was the second conducted at the Department of
Energy's nuclear weapons test site 65 miles north of Las Vegas, and
its apparent success led Energy Secretary Bill Richardson to
declare in a statement: ``This innovative terrorist vehicle
barrier, refined and tested by scientists . . . has the potential
for saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept was seen as an inexpensive and easily deployed way
to protect American embassies or troop encampments in nations where
terrorism is likely.
</P>
<P>
   But David B. McCallen, the project's chief investigator,
conceded in a telephone interview Wednesday that the destruction of
a terrorist's load of explosives could well destroy any buildings
near a protected embassy and kill any residents in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``That potentiality,'' McCallen said, ``would have to be
reviewed.''
</P>
<P>
   To McCallen and Wattenburg, a structure like the barrier they
tested would be most useful when deployed in a locale like the U.S.
military housing compound near Dharhan, Saudi Arabia, where a
terrorist truck bomb killed 23 Americans and injured several
hundred others in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although the barrier they tested used 1,200-pound concrete
blocks as anchors to hold down the steel pipes, McCallen said the
anchors could easily be made of anything handy _ empty oil drums
filled with sand or water, for example, or even old vehicles ready
for the scrap heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very easy to construct this kind of barrier
anywhere,'' McCallen said. ``the concept is elegant in its
simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of the two tests, on October 1, a small pickup
truck was driven by remote control at a speed of 36 miles an hour,
and when it hit the barrier it ran over the top for 50 feet,
resulting in a sheared engine, a severed transmission and a crushed
drive shaft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the vehicle was destroyed forever,''
McCallen said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's test involved a smaller barrier and a larger,
one-ton truck. This time, the loaded ``terrorist'' vehicle flipped
over on its roof and was totally disabled, McCallen said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Wattenburg's off-beat ideas, already in use, struck
him after the 1994 Northridge earthquake, when an overpass on the
Santa Monica freeway was destroyed. He invented a bridge made from
the beds of surplus railroad flatcars with columns and footings
built with segments cut from the cars with torches.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, when a flood wiped out two overpasses on
Interstate 5 near Coalinga, Caltrans crews constructed two of
Wattenburg's temporary bridges within two days. Later, when
permanent structures were completed, the crews took Wattenburg's
bridges apart and stored them in kit form in a Caltrans warehouse,
to be ready for other emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of it,'' Wattenburg said at the time, ``is that you
can put the whole thing together like Lego blocks.'' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
