A5892 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MIDAMATEUR09-COX     10-08 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MIDAMATEUR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Mid-Amateur Championship continues
 &HT;    By Bucky Albers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When he was a youngster growing up with 10
brothers and sisters in North Vernon, Ind., John Miller acquired
the nickname Spider because he was always crawling all over
everything.
</P>
<P>
   He is 48 years old now, but Spider Miller hasn't stopped
crawling. Miller, a beer distributor from Bloomington, Ind.,
crawled into the quarterfinal bracket of the U.S. Mid-Amateur
Championship on Tuesday with two more easy victories at NCR Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Five other former USGA champions weren't so fortunate. Danny
Yates, David Eger, Buddy Marucci, Jerry Courville and Buddy
Alexander were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Robert T. Jones Trophy will go to one of the
following eight _ Chip Holcombe, Danny Green, Paul Simson, Sean
Knapp, Randy Haag, Gary Wolstenholme, Steve Sheehan or Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan, medalist in the qualifier, had to go 24 holes to beat
Jeff Kern of Tucson, Ariz., who had won a 20-hole match with Yates
in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Holcombe, 37, of Casselberry, Fla., birdied the 17th hole and
cut down the long-hitting Courville, who missed an eight-foot
birdie putt on the 18th. Haag of San Francisco, who has made it to
the Mid-Am quarterfinals three times, finally got to the semis by
beating Eger, 3 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Marucci lost a 2 and 1 decision to Green of Jackson, Tenn.,
runner-up in the 1989 U.S. Amateur, and Alexander lost, 2 and 1, to
Simson, 46, of Raleigh, N.C., two-time North-South Amateur champ.
</P>
<P>
   Wolstenholme of Great Britain rebounded from 4 down at the turn
to win three straight holes and score a 2-up victory over Michael
McCoy of Des Moines. Knapp, 36, of Oakmont, Pa., took a 4 and 3
victory over Bob Kearney of Houston, who had been red hot.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has buried three opponents. He won, 5 and 4, in the first
two rounds and, 5-3, in the third over Clayton Uselton of
Tullahoma, Tenn. He is 9-under par in three matches covering 43
holes after going 4-under in the 36-hole qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   He is using the same 60-inch, Cobra Tricep putter he rode to the
1996 Mid-Am Championship at Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only one that uses it,'' Miller said. ``That tells you
something, doesn't it.'' The putter was designed to go outside the
shoulder, but Miller runs the shaft through his armpit and out the
back, so he had to bend the shaft to correct the loft.
</P>
<P>
   When Miller brought the putter to the Masters last year, Fuzzy
Zoeller said it looked like a fireplace poker.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters invitation came with his Hartford victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played poorly but I had a great time,'' Miller said. ``Fuzzy
made it special for me. I played every (practice round) with him
and was fortunate enough to play with Arnold (Palmer), Jack
(Nicklaus) and Tom Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played Palmer and Nicklaus, Fuzzy said, `If we can't
beat these two old guys, we're playing (Gene) Sarazen and (Sam)
Snead tomorrow.' They kicked our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is surprisingly long off the tee for a guy with a
5-foot-9, 160-pound frame. ``That's because I work hard,'' he said.
``The other guys have these desk jobs. I'm out there lifting kegs
and loading trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
