r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-SIDE09-COX     10-08 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-SIDE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Using credit cards recklessly shattered Len Rodriguez's life
 &HT;    WITH CREDIT-CARDS
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Five years ago, Len Rodriguez's life was
moving far too fast to allow even a glance at a credit-card balance
that was accelerating faster than his red Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   Roses and limos for dates. Trips to New York and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing for me to go out dancing and spend $300,'' said
the former body-builder. ``All on the Visa.''
</P>
<P>
   The car was an essential part of his self-absorbed lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to impress everybody,'' he said. ``It was a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   With an income approaching $70,000, Rodriguez was certain he
could pay off his bills. Then his income took a sudden, sharp drop,
but the interest on his debt kept compounding.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Rodriguez is typical of problems faced by many
middle-income people who leave themselves nothing to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing saved,'' he said. ``I'd even borrowed on my
credit cards for the down payment on my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who won the title Mr. West Palm Beach, earned most of
his income as a personal trainer based in a Wellington gym. When he
moved to a gym that closed soon after, he was reduced to living on
his county lifeguard's salary of $24,000 while trying to pay off
more than $9,000 in credit-card debts.
</P>
<P>
   He kept up the payments on his house and car but couldn't
stretch to cover even the minimum on his credit cards. He began
ducking calls at home and work. He got friends to say he was out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn to lie,'' he said. ``It's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez checked into claims by several credit-restoration
companies but was put off by the fees and skeptical of their
claims. ``It sounded crazy that I should pay them on top of
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was impressed by Consumer Credit Counseling Service, a
nonprofit agency. He contributed the cost of postage (about $4 a
month), and, in return, the agency negotiated with his creditors
for lower payments. With his minimum reduced to $250 from more than
$400, Rodriguez took extra jobs to begin chipping at the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to look for things in my field so I could use this
as an opportunity to get ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part-time lifeguard duty on Miami Beach meant several 140-mile
round trips each week but also gave him a boost in experience that
allowed him to move from pool to beach duty in his regular job.
That gives him a better shot at advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also filled off-hours and weekends with a variety of
other jobs, including hotel valet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to do anything crazy or illegal,'' he said. ``I
believe the way to pay your bills is to work.''
</P>
<P>
   He made enough progress by last year to marry the woman he'd
courted with all those limos and roses. Last week, he got the first
credit report in four years showing his credit cards have been paid
in full.
</P>
<P>
   He's planning to trade in the Corvette for a family car and has
no plans to go back to gym work, even though it would pay well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a drug addict who's been through rehab,'' he said.
``I need a different environment.''
</P>
<P>
   LEN RODRIGUEZ'S STORY: HOW DEBT TRAPPED HIM
</P>
<P>
   At 36, he was a lifeguard and personal trainer with an income
near $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then: He bought a Corvette for $613 a month, plus $149 for
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   He bought a townhouse that cost $550 a month for mortgage and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   He took $4,000 in cash advances on his credit cards for the down
payment.
</P>
<P>
   He charged about $5,000 for trips, dinners and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   When he changed jobs and went to work for a gym that soon
closed, Rodriguez lost two-thirds of his income. He didn't want to
lose his house or car, but he stopped making the minimum payments
of more than $400 a month on his credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   He also owed more than $1,000 to a department store, which won a
court judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to pay part of his debts, Rodriguez stopped
answering his phone and got friends to lie to creditors.
</P>
<P>
   AND HOW HE ESCAPED
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Credit Counseling Service of Palm Beach County
negotiated lower payments with the credit card companies. Rodriguez
gave the agency $250 a month to pay his credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
   He and his counselor tore up his cards and canceled the accounts
to avoid deeper debt.
</P>
<P>
   His counselor showed him how to make and live within a household
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez changed his lifestyle. He cut out the trips and
dinners and took on several part-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Working weekends and holidays for four years, he gradually
increased his monthly payments and is now free of credit card debt
and up to date on other loans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
