<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT09-COX     10-08 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debt eating away at credit-happy consumers
 &HT;    WITH CREDIT-SIDE
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Buy now, pay never.
</P>
<P>
   That's how more Americans than ever think _ if they think at all
_ when they pay with plastic. It's one of the big reasons we set
records for personal bankruptcies three years in a row, and why
Congress is determined to stop the streak.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been filled with talk about a nation of deadbeats
that seems to contradict widespread elation over a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to be an anomaly, but it isn't,'' said Samuel
Gerdano, executive director of the American Bankruptcy Institute, a
research organization. ``The same consumer spending that helps
drive and sustain the economy is putting families into debt.''
</P>
<P>
   And not just poor families. A new survey by the American Bankers
Association found that 45 percent of credit-card holders with
incomes between $50,000 and $100,000 never pay off their balances.
</P>
<P>
   Many others don't even make the minimum payments and fall behind
on the interest. Debt counseling services across the country are
seeing more middle-to-upper-income clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to see people who were in debt for a small amount of
money: $20,000 or $30,000,'' said Jean Brannan of Consumer Credit
Counseling Service of Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast.
``Now, we have people with over $100,000 in credit-card debts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even people who are already in debt are being bombarded with
credit-card offers, and most have been conditioned to think of
spending as something akin to a patriotic duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem really is that a lot of people are just getting
by,'' said Gerri Detweiler, author of The Ultimate Credit Handbook
and several other books on personal finances. ``Even if they're
making good money, they're not prepared for anything happening
financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything includes divorce, corporate cutbacks, business
setbacks, major medical expenses _ common hazards of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have five or six cards with a balance on each, and
they're not really paying attention to anything except the minimum
monthly payment,'' Detweiler said. ``Then, all of a sudden, they
don't have the same income, and it throws them into a financial
tailspin.''
</P>
<P>
   If that has you punching up your mental calculator, factor in
this:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a combination of lots of debt and not much
savings, you are a candidate right now for bankruptcy,'' Detweiler
said.
</P>
<P>
   The tumble from prosperity is often hard, fast and startling.
Many people make the mistake of confusing available credit with
ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit-card companies are in the business of selling money,''
Brannan said. ``They always want you to buy more.''
</P>
<P>
   Seductive credit offers have played a major part in the debate
over proposals to make it harder to file for bankruptcy. While
conceding that personal debt is an increasing problem, many
Democrats say lenders bear considerable responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Republican majorities passed personal bankruptcy bills in both
houses, although the Senate version passed last month isn't quite
as tough, and both versions backed away from early proposals to
give credit card debts the same priority as child support, Gerdano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both versions would force consumers to seek counseling and
negotiate settlements before asking for court protection, and
that's likely to be part of any compromise bill. It's a step many
people are already taking on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing more people who still have good credit and aren't
behind on their bills,'' said Arne Nielsen, community outreach
specialist for Consumer Credit Counseling. ``That's why they're
alarmed: They're making payments every month, but their credit-card
balance isn't going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Minimum payments required by lenders barely chip at the
principal. A $1,000 credit card charge at 18 percent interest _
less than some department store accounts _ will take nine years to
pay off at $20 a month. Meanwhile, you'll pay about as much as you
borrowed in interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all the time, people keep charging,'' Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   The rising monthly tide has encouraged many to pay off their
high-interest card debts by taking out home equity loans, which are
often tax deductible. One survey showed $26 billion of credit-card
debts have been paid off that way in the past two years, but 70
percent of those card holders immediately started charging again.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a dangerous strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't pay your credit-card bill, the worst that will
happen is they'll call and send you a letter,'' said author
Detweiler, who is also education adviser to the Internet-based Debt
Counselors of America. ``They're not going to throw you in jail. If
you can't pay a home equity loan, you can lose the roof over your
head.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some encouraging news about debt: It isn't rising as
fast as it was a few years ago. Household debt is up about 6
percent this year, which is down from last year's 8 percent,
according to federal figures.
</P>
<P>
   And Americans are generally trying harder to be responsible. The
percentage of cardholders who pay their balances in full each month
is up from 29 percent in 1992 to 42 percent, while the percentage
who fail to make even minimum payments is down to 3.28 from 3.69 at
this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, only 41 percent of households say they spend less than
their income, according the American Bankers Association, and 15
percent spend more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people still look on credit cards as supplementary
income,'' Brannan said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say there is no profile of the modern debtor. Men are
considered less likely to worry about money and security and more
likely to show off, but the spending impulse is nearly gender
equal.
</P>
<P>
   Women are more likely, however, to be caught short by divorce,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're often shocked to find out they're still responsible
for debts no matter what the divorce decree says,'' Brannan said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the least vulnerable are older people who grew up with a
pay-as-you-go ethic and never fell into the plastic habit. Among
the most vulnerable are young people, who are now deluged with
credit-card offers in college but who haven't been taught how to
use credit wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone could benefit from a moment's hesitation before
making a charge, Brannan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to learn how to make plastic feel like money,''
Brannan said. ``We need to feel the same pain of separation when we
take it out of our wallets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-06-98 1532E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
