r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-AGGIES-HALL09-COX     10-08 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES-HALL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aggies' Hall gets carried away
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ If Dante Hall turns out to be the
answer to all the questions surrounding Texas A&AMP;M's hit-and-miss
offense, it's all right with him.
</P>
<P>
   If the Aggies' offensive success hinges on the diminutive Hall
carrying the ball a career-high 36 times, like he did last week at
Kansas, then so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty, 50, whatever. It doesn't matter to me,'' the Aggies'
junior running back said. ``I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   If he can continue duplicating what he did to the Jayhawks,
he'll get it. Hall's 36 carries, exceeding his previous career high
by 14, translated into 177 rushing yards _ 7 fewer than his career
best against Texas Tech as a freshman in 1996. A&AMP;M needed all that
Hall had to offer to rally for a 24-21 victory, and his role this
week against second-ranked Nebraska probably won't be lessened,
even if his carries are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say he can't do it,'' Aggies coach R.C. Slocum said of
another 36-carry day. ``But it would be a real challenge to do that
against a team like Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies' offense has faced a series of challenges all season,
though. A new and relatively untested line, the suspension of
fullback D'Andre Hardeman and Branndon Stewart's struggles at
quarterback are all factors leading to A&AMP;M being ranked last in the
Big 12 in total offense at 279.4 yards per game. A&AMP;M has been
desperately looking for an offensive cornerstone, and Hall is ready
to be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I've been wanting,'' he said. ``I want the
pressure put on me. I couldn't ask for anything better.''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear to be a heavy burden on some relatively small
shoulders. Hall stands only 5 feet 8 inches, and while he packs a
solid 190 pounds on his frame and is hiccup quick, he is also
injury prone. The Kansas game was the first this season he has
played at full health after nursing shoulder and knee problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to carry the ball a lot for us to be successful,
but we'll need to be a lot more balanced against Nebraska,'' said
newly promoted A&AMP;M quarterback Randy McCown. ``We climbed on
Dante's back last week and he carried us, but he'll need help.
Nobody can do it alone.'' Added offensive coordinator Steve
Kragthorpe: ``We have to be careful. We want to get him into a
rhythm, but we don't want to get him beat up. A lot of it depends
on who's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, whose team-high 433 rushing yards rank eighth in the Big
12, is not the Aggies' only weapon at tailback. Sirr Parker, who
also has been nagged by injuries, is capable, although he has
managed only 119 yards on 42 carries.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M historically has tried to balance carries between backs, but
Hall, who has rushed for 2,048 career yards to rank 12th in school
history, is ready to buck tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it ever!'' he exclaimed loudly when asked if his unusually
high number of carries at Kansas is a change of philosophy. ``I
don't know why we've changed, or how long it will last, but I'm not
complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES _ Nebraska quarterback Bobby Newcombe hasn't recovered
from a partially torn knee ligament and backup Eric Crouch has a
hip pointer, Coach Frank Solich said. Solich said Newcombe and
Crouch will dress for practice this week but their participation
will be restricted. The goal for now, Solich said, is simply
restoring both to full strength.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Aggies' 1939 national championship team will
receive commemorative championship rings and be introduced at
halftime of Saturday's game. Among the members of that team are
Austin resident Harold Cowley, who played at Freer High School, and
Wimberley's James N. Thomason, a Brownwood High product. A total of
64 rings will be presented _ 26 to surviving members of the 11-0
team that beat Tulane in the Sugar Bowl, and the remainder to
family members of deceased players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
