<HEADER>
A5897 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UT-LEAKS09-COX     10-08 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UT-LEAKS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT's Leaks paved a path for Williams
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ever since he had the privilege to shake the
hand of Doak Walker and soak up all the genuine humility and
dignity that was the late great Southern Methodist running back,
Ricky Williams has been in awe of the man for whom a stadium was
dubbed and for whom an award is annually presented.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was, quite simply, a hero to the University of Texas
running back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when Williams was asked if he had ever come across
Roosevelt Leaks, the man whose school single-game rushing record he
shattered with 350 yards, he shook his head, and that's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever talked to him,'' Williams said Monday.
``I've seen him before, and I've seen pictures. I heard he was
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaks was at Royal-Memorial Stadium Saturday night. For all but
the last couple of minutes, he was among the 70,681fans who
witnessed the best rushing performance by any Longhorns back since
Leaks ran through an SMU defense a full quarter of a century
earlier for a staggering 342 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Leaks stayed long enough to see his mark fall but was ready to
leave by halftime, which says his stamina isn't what it once was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm good for about a half,'' he said, laughing. ``The young
man can run the rock. I was decent, Earl Campbell was great and
then there's Ricky Williams. He's somewhere between (Walter)
Payton, Jim Brown and Earl. He has that kind of repertoire.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaks' memory of his own play misses the mark, although he says
friends still remind him he fumbled four times (and lost three)
that day in 1973 when he broke Aggie Bob Smith's conference record
of 297 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But Leaks' place in history was already secured. This dignified,
45-year-old father of two (son Prentiss is a linebacker/running
back on Lanier High School's ninth-grade team) broke down defenders
but, more significant, he broke down many invisible barriers for
the UT football program. The University of Texas was one of the
last teams to include black players and had just one on its 1970
national championship team.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Leaks became the first black All-America football
player at a school that has had 14 consensus All-Americans since
that year _ half of them African Americans, including Williams. As
the first black superstar at Texas, Leaks made it fashionable , or
at least acceptable, for people like Earl Campbell, Raymond
Clayborn and Johnnie Johnson to become Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Williams might never have considered Texas had it not been for
this proud, countrified kid who experienced vestiges of racism his
entire life and therefore was prepared for such obstacles in
Austin. The difficulties were pronounced enough, however, that
Leaks considered transferring to Stanford the summer before his
sophomore year. He said he was also irritated because he was listed
third string on a depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really mesh,'' Leaks says of a time when fans and
some of his own teammates had trouble accepting a black star. ``The
type of athlete who came here in the '70s was different. You had to
be tolerant and deal with the racism. I grew up in an atmosphere
where you didn't drink out of the same water fountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, on the other hand, found ready acceptance in a more
cosmopolitan city that has enthusiastically embraced him.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of that rushing record, though, these two Longhorns
will be linked for all time in a way that they already have been,
subconsciously, since Williams arrived from San Diego as a
tattooed, dreadlocked, reggae-music-loving man with little
knowledge of what preceded him here. The pair are more alike than
they are different.
</P>
<P>
   The styles of both were, if not identical, at least cut from the
same explosive, powerful mold. Like Williams, Leaks was a hot-shot
outfielder, hitting .350 as the leadoff hitter on Brenham's 1970
state baseball championship team. Like Williams, Leaks carried
himself with a quiet, largely unemotional demeanor, but Leaks was
painfully private. When then-UT assistant David McWilliams asked
Leaks if he would sign with the Longhorns, Leaks didn't speak. He
nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Writers raved about Leaks' quickness, his upper-body strength
fashioned from his days on his parents' 60-acre ranch outside
Brenham, and the forward tilt he displayed as he ran. He, too, was
a legitimate Heisman Trophy candidate, finishing third in 1973
behind Penn State running back John Cappelletti and Ohio State
offensive tackle John Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Like Williams, Leaks remained in school after his junior season,
although jumping early to the NFL wasn't an option. ``That wasn't
fashionable then,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That was the shame for Leaks, whose right kneecap was crushed
against a teammate's face mask in a spring practice. After major
reconstructive surgery, he defied medical convention that he would
need at least nine months' rehabilitation and returned in time for
Texas' 1974 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   The injury stripped him of his 4.5-second time in the 40-yard
dash and cost him tons of money when the projected first-round
draft choice fell to a fifth-round pick by Baltimore with a signing
bonus of less than $20,000. He never ran for 100 yards in a game
during nine NFL seasons, never came close to a 1,000-yard season,
never made more than the $150,000 salary he was paid by Buffalo in
1983. But he got his college degree in 4 1/2 years, enjoys a
professional career in appraising land and managing properties, and
left a legacy that should not be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   When Leaks arrived in Austin in 1971, he was one of two black
freshman players. Sitting in the stands Saturday night, he could
count 51.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday I was sitting behind some younger (black) players who
had their rings on, which said they had graduated,'' Leaks says.
``When I see blacks getting an opportunity for an education first,
by all means I'm proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes sports commentary four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-07-98 0001E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
