<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5898 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRANTHAM-COLUMN09-COX     10-08 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANTHAM-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Et tu, Linda! Back stabbers are `most toxic of all terrors'
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Treat your friend as if he will one day be your enemy, and
your enemy as if he will one day be your friend.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Laberius, 105-43 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Although Linda Tripp didn't invent betrayal _ Pontius Pilate,
Brutus and Benedict Arnold beat her to the punch _ she certainly
excelled at it.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her deception (complete with wire and tapped phone),
Tripp doesn't deserve all the credit. Monica Lewinsky, after all,
played into her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp falls squarely into the category author Lillian Glass
calls the Smiling Two-Faced Backstabber, in her book, Toxic People.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us find the Smiling Two-Faced Backstabber to be the
most toxic of all terrors,'' she writes. ``In fact, in Dante's
Inferno, the final circle of hell was reserved for perpetrators of
the most heinous sin of all _ betrayal.... These chameleon-like
people are scary, for they change depending on what you need to
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. One minute Tripp chats about diets, haircuts and sex to
Lewinsky as if she's a sorority sister, despite their age
difference. Then, Tripp deals the mommy trump card because that's
what Lewinsky _ childishly confused and insecure, although she was
playing a grown-up game _ needed to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel entirely too maternal towards you,'' the older woman
said. ``When I yell at you, it's out of love.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Linda, it's out of manipulation. Because while Tripp's
methods are textbook, so are her motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep inside, back stabbers resent you but don't have the guts
to confess that they are angry or upset or even envious,'' Glass
says.
</P>
<P>
   Another bull's-eye: Tripp had fallen out of favor with the
Clintons, was angry about being kicked out of the White House and
was most certainly jealous of Lewinsky's power to demand a new job.
Hoodwinking the younger woman meant taking control.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as George H. Green and Carolyn Cotter put it in Stop Being
Manipulated, ``Herein lies an irony. The person who is trying to
manipulate you views you as having greater power than she does.''
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. In reality, the intern had the upper hand, not the
Washington veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, however _ because of inexperience, naivete, just plain
lack of intelligence or a combination thereof _ didn't know this.
Instead, she allowed herself to be victimized, and it's easy to see
why: She craved approval. And assumed a position of weakness to
earn it.
</P>
<P>
   In Clare Booth Luce's 1936 play The Women, Luce satirizes five
ladies who lunch _ and gossip, connive and back stab all under the
guise of caring for one another. On one hand, they seek approval.
But on the other, they secretly despise each other for being so
needy.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Lewinsky felt a boost when Tripp called her a
``Marilyn Monroe vixen'' who would eventually ``come home to an
opportunity to get together with (Clinton).'' But how was Lewinsky
to know what she heard wasn't really encouragement but instead an
egging-on that would backfire?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, regrettably, it's impossible to know because, as
Karen Lehrman writes in The Lipstick Proviso, ``There will always
be malicious women who backstab, who use `sisterhood' as a way to
be resentful, malicious and vindictive.''
</P>
<P>
   But, experts say, there are warning signs that deception _ and
possibly betrayal _ is at hand:
</P>
<P>
   The manipulator becomes almost giddy with power and energy while
the victim becomes depressed and more dependent.
</P>
<P>
   The manipulator elicits personal details from the victim without
revealing any of her own, creating an imbalance in the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The manipulator preys on the fact that she shares a common bond
with the victim. (In the case of Tripp and Lewinsky, that would be
employment in the White House.)
</P>
<P>
   The manipulator _ because of the savvy that comes with age and
experience _ has a personal agenda, while the victim just wants to
``share'' or ``vent.''
</P>
<P>
   The manipulator shifts roles _ from empathizing buddy to
protective mother, for example _ to meet her own needs, not those
of the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line is, betrayal is a fact of life. But, as Riki Robbins
writes in Betrayed!, a victim's first step toward recovery is
forgiveness _ first for herself and then eventually for the person
who tricked her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betrayal means a loss of innocence, especially because it most
often happens to those who are most vulnerable,'' Robbins says.
``The lesson is not to be cynical, but never to reveal too much too
soon. With diligence and faith, the betrayed can learn to trust
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires opening yourself up enough to return to the school
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Monica Lewinsky has learned some hard lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
