<SLUG> BC-MCCOY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In memorandum of the Indians
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Writing an obituary for the Cleveland Indians this
morning wouldn't be prudent, despite a tempting inclination to do
just that after watching the New York Yankees perpetrate something
close to aggravated manslaughter in front of millions of TV
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty, Mighty Yankees not only won their 118th game this
season, tying the all-time one-season record, they put an
exclamation point behind it when their first four hitters singled
against precocious Indians starter Jaret Wright and sent him
seeking the shampoo and soap in the shower before TV showed its
first commercial.
</P>
<P>
   When Game 1 of the 1998 American League Championship Series
ended, it was New York 7, Cleveland 2.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to the Indians, they have the Yankees right where
they want them _ the Indians with their backs plastered firmly
against the Yankee Stadium wall.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat Tuesday was Cleveland's eighth straight in the first
game of a postseason series, dating back to 1995. And in four of
those previous seven, the Tribe came back to win the series.
</P>
<P>
   And now they have to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Escape From New York for Wright. The Yankees were
peeking around a building from a back alley waiting on this guy.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't like the 22-year-old's perceived cockiness after he
beat them twice in last year's Division Series, after he put
together a 4-1 career record against them and especially after he
broke infielder Luis Sojo's left wrist with a spring training pitch
which they feel was intentional.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the night in June when he hit former
Cincinnati outfielder Paul O'Neill and when O'Neill expressed
displeasure, Wright motioned for O'Neill to shut his mouth and walk
to first base.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's night Tuesday consisted of eight hitters and the
Yankees pecked him to oblivion with five singles and a walk en
route to five runs. The first four Yankees singled _ Chuck
Knoblauch, Derek Jeter, O'Neill (for a retribution run) and Bernie
Williams (for another run).
</P>
<P>
   By the time the first inning ended, Chad Ogea was pitching, the
Yankees had a 5-0 lead and had batted around (10 hitters). Nothing
new there. The Yankees batted around an unfathomable 36 times
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   When Wright walked off the mound, with the Beatles' Help
accompanying his long walk to the dugout, the 57,138 fans booed
heartily.
</P>
<P>
   Five runs in the first inning was more than David ``Boomer''
Wells needed. With his baggy uniform making him look a guy wearing
pajamas after an all-night party, Wells put the Tribe to sleep with
no harm done _ two runs on Manny Ramirez's two-run homer run in the
ninth, five hits, one walk, one hit batsman, seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Wells not only marches to the beat of a different drummer, he is
the drummer. His back is covered with tattoos, he wears his
baseball shirt unbuttoned nearly to his navel, he wanted to wear
Babe Ruth's retired No. 3 when he came to the Yankees and teammate
Tino Martinez said, ``Our pitches come from all over. We have a
pitcher from Cuba, a pitcher from Japan, a pitcher from Panama and
we have Boomer Wells, who is from Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, this 35-year-old Martian was 18-4 for the Yankees this
season, shut out the Texas Rangers, 2-0 on five hits over eight
innings in Game 1 of the Division Series and shut down the Indians
without a run for eighth innings on in Game 1 of the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, in the postseason he is out of this world _ 6-1 as
a starter with a 2.48 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati fans remember Wells from the 1995 season when he
helped pitch the Reds to the National League Championship Series
against Atlanta _ then was traded after the season to Baltimore for
outfielders Curtis Goodwin and Travis Valdez _ a deal almost as bad
as the one that sent O'Neill from the Reds to the Yankees after the
1992 season for Roberto Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who completed his sixth straight season of hitting .300
or higher for the Yankees, had two hits, drove in a run and scored
two.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
