<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We're bewitched: `Charmed' is charming
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WB wants you under its spell. And they're using three
cute-looking witches to do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charmed,'' the network's delightfully bewitching new series,
tells the story of three sisters who find out they're witches with
really cool powers. Of course the sisters _ and their powers _ are
nothing alike. Prue (Beverly Hills 90210's Shannon Doherty) is the
hard-driving sister who can move objects with her mind. Piper
(``Picket Fences' '' Holly Marie Combs) is the down-to-earth sister
who can stop time. Phoebe (``Melrose Place'' 's Alyssa Milano) is
the free-spirit sister who can see the future.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they're a supernatural version of Charlie's Angels.
Instead of fighting crooks, our lovely trio battles all kinds of
evil forces. Don't laugh ... that Charlie's Angels comparison isn't
a stretch. Aaron Spelling, who produced that jiggly cop show, also
produces ``Charmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Charmed'' plays like a special effects-laden
morality play about good and evil. Three witches _ good. Mean,
witch-killing warlocks _ evil.
</P>
<P>
   The special effects _ what the kid viewers really care about _
are of Buffy the Vampire Slayer-like quality. There's a lot of
swirling light and good-looking warlocks turning into
not-so-good-looking killers. The dialogue, though, isn't as hip or
in-the-know as Buffy. But that's OK. ``Charmed'' is still funny,
spooky and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   We'd fall under the spells of these three witches any day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
