<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-MONEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT needs more money from state, president says
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In his first major speech since becoming
University of Texas president, Larry Faulkner recently shared his
vision for the future and spotlighted a four-point plan to make ``a
university of the first class'' even better:
</P>
<P>
   Strengthen undergraduate education. Make UT-Austin the nation's
expert on Latin America. Get more involved in public schools. Forge
alliances with the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   And, on top of all that, do a better job in every endeavor, from
teaching to research to service, Faulkner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us make this place more than a university of the first
class,'' he told several hundred faculty, staff, students, regents
and others at a ceremony to celebrate UT's 115th birthday and his
nearly six-month-old administration. ``Let's take it to the head of
the class.''
</P>
<P>
   Decked in an academic robe and tasseled, beret-style hat,
Faulkner's upbeat assessment that UT has the potential to be the
nation's best public university was tempered by his concerns about
state aid to higher education. The state provides 25 percent of
UT's overall budget, with the rest coming from tuition, fees,
private donations, grants and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have reached the inner circle of leading public
universities, but that does not mean that we are able to compete on
equal footing,'' said Faulkner, whose speech received a standing
ovation. ``Some state universities have funded their services and
achievements with strong state support, while others have used high
tuition and fees. UT, on the other hand, operates with relative low
state support and low tuition.''
</P>
<P>
   Although lawmakers significantly boosted aid to higher education
in last year's legislative session, UT's spending per student is
just 70 percent of what the flagship universities in California,
Wisconsin and Illinois spend, Faulkner said.
</P>
<P>
   UT also ranks below its peers in spending on libraries, start-up
money for new faculty and salaries for graduate students, faculty
and staff, Faulkner said.
</P>
<P>
   His friend and predecessor, Robert Berdahl, cited similar
financial worries when he decided to leave UT last year to become
chancellor at the University of California at Berkeley. Berdahl
repeated his concerns Monday night at Texas A&AMP;M University in a
speech on the future of flagship universities.
</P>
<P>
   While state aid is a problem, Faulkner said, UT can do a better
job of managing its resources. He challenged all campus leaders to
evaluate how they spend money and make wise choices.
</P>
<P>
   UT has suffered in the national rankings because it has huge
classes and because too many students fail to graduate. A student
at a symposium to discuss UT's future earlier Tuesday said large
class sizes are a major impediment to learning.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner said it was clearly time for UT to pay more attention
to undergraduate education, especially at the freshman and
sophomore levels, where large classes rule.
</P>
<P>
   The undergraduate experience is so important, he said, because
it ``influences learning, our sense of community, student
retention, institutional loyalty, our reputation among prospective
students and their parents, alumni giving, and, of course, our
ability to achieve our purpose of transforming lives
beneficially.''
</P>
<P>
   Student Government President Annie Holand and others at the
symposium said UT needs to become more caring and nurturing of
students. Holand said she was disappointed that of the hundreds who
attend the symposium, just a handful were students.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner also challenged UT to become the nation's premier
center for teaching about Latin America and educating its students.
Hispanics are expected to outnumber whites in Texas within three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner also said UT must support the high-tech industry to
sustain its growth. Members of Austin's high-tech firms have long
been critical of UT. Of particular concern is a lack of degree
programs at night.
</P>
<P>
   UT has begun to expand the number of engineering and other
scientific courses it offers on evenings and weekends, but Faulkner
said, along with educating technology workers, UT must be willing
to develop partnerships with the industry.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the university must pay attention to those at
the other end of the pipeline: public school students, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of 300,000 18-year-olds in Texas, 130,000 did not graduate from
high school, ``a stunning and sobering statistic,'' he said.
Faulkner did not offer a solution but said UT must ``find ways . .
. to improve the performance of the educational system by reaching
millions of students, millions of parents and tens of thousands of
teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   At the symposium, Morton Meyerson, a UT alumnus who heads 2M
Companies Inc. in Dallas, said if UT fails to do that, ``we might
as well not worry about higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   For the text of Faulkner's speech, log on to www.austin360.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
