<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOAT-CHEESE09-COX     10-08 2023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOAT-CHEESE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Praises flow for chevre product in small dairy
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRIPPING SPRINGS, Texas _ Amelia Sweethardt turns on a faucet.
Out gushes a stream of goats' milk that four days hence will become
award-winning cheese. Call it the pride of Karrot, Angel, Apple,
Megan and others in the small goat herd that earned their oats last
month when Pure Luck Grade A Dairy walked away with four awards at
the American Cheese Society's annual competition in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Amelia's mom, Sara Bolton _ goat farmer, dairy owner and primary
cheese-maker _ was quite surprised: ``When I went to Wisconsin, I
didn't know my cheese was so good. I knew I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the dozen pros who judged the ``blind'' (unlabeled)
competition of 320 entries made by 77 artisan cheese-makers in the
United States and Canada. Comments from the judges' score sheets on
her cheeses read: very clean, creamy, fresh, beautiful, smooth,
good color . . .
</P>
<P>
   There are 150 to 200 goat-cheese makers in the United States.
Some of them have been producing artisan cheeses for 20 years, says
Laura Jacobs-Welch, administrator of the American Cheese Society.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early '90s, the specialty cheese industry has gained
much momentum, she notes, and the goat-cheese makers probably were
the instigators of this popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Although a newcomer to commercial cheese-making, Sara ``did very
well'' in the competition, Jacobs-Welch says. But, she notes, that
it is not necessarily unusual for a cheese-maker to win multiple
awards once he or she hits that certain level of quality and enters
several categories.
</P>
<P>
   Pure Luck has hit that level. Sara says she only entered six
categories. She placed in four.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging on the wall in the dairy is a second-place ribbon for
her chevre in farmstead cheeses, as well as another red for
producing the second best cheese of all chevres in the country. In
addition, her Del Cielo, a soft ripened cheese similar to
Camembert, tied for first in farmstead cheese and also won third in
all soft-ripened cheeses in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty heady stuff for a small Hays County farmer who named her
Del Cielo cheese after a Joe Ely song on the ``Letter to Laredo''
CD. Ely is good company in the early morning hours of a dairy, Sara
says of the demanding life of a cheese-maker who raises goats.
</P>
<P>
   She explains that the ``farmstead `` cheese label means you
produce your own milk. ``A very small percentage of cheese-makers
in the U.S. are stupid enough to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sane cheese-makers, she continues, don't milk goats, cows or
sheep twice a day to get the raw product for their cheeses; they
buy the milk.
</P>
<P>
   Sara, however, has a soft spot in her heart for her goats. A
goat farmer for 20 years, she names them, talks to them, pets them.
In fact, she confesses, ``goats are my first love, over
cheese-making.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband Denny have raised their four children, ages
23 to 9, on raw goat milk. Fifteen of those years she made goat
cheese for her family. Then she bootlegged, producing cheese at
home and selling it to a few folks. About three years ago she
officially went commercial, establishing Pure Luck Grade A Goat
Dairy across the road from the Bolton s' house and organic
herb/flower farm.
</P>
<P>
   Every Monday she and her family/helpers make cheeses in the
small red metal building. They empty the refrigerated holding tank,
in which the 110 or so gallons from her 14 American alpine and
Nubian milking goats have been stored for the week, and pasteurize
the milk. A freeze-dried culture (bacteria) is added to change the
milk sugar to an acid and give the cheese its flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Then they turn on the faucet of the pasteurizer and fill
4-gallon plastic tubs with the milk. Rennet, an enzyme, is stirred
in to help the milk coagulate, the amount varying with the type of
cheese. Within hours the milk forms a large block called a curd,
which is the texture of soft Jell-O.It is ready for cutting or
scooping when a finger dipped into the curd causes it to break
cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   On a normal week, Pure Luck makes 100 pounds of chevre (fresh
goat cheese), 10 pounds of Del Cielo, 24 pounds of feta, 4 to 8
pounds of Claire de Lune (a semi-firm ripened cheese), and 4 to 8
pounds of Ste. Maure (a creamy mold-ripened log-shaped cheese).
</P>
<P>
   For chevre, the curd is scooped into molds. Instead of
traditional chevre molds, Sara substitutes ricotta baskets, which
makes a drier chevre with a pretty shape and size. It sells for
about $4.50 for about 5 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   For feta, she takes a long spatula , cutting the coagulated
block of curd into half-inch squares both vertically and
horizontally. Most cheese-makers have vats and a stainless steel
wire curd cutter to do this step, which releases the whey and makes
a drier cheese. Sara's simple, inexpensive technique employs
plastic tubs and long spatulas. Another contrast of little
cheese-maker vs. big one.
</P>
<P>
   She cuts the Del Cielo cheese curd similar to the feta and then
stirs it occasionally for 45 minutes to release more whey. After
scooping it into molds, she flips it several times as it drains for
24 hours. Then it is removed from the mold, salted and inoculated
with Penicillium candidum and ripened for 10 to 14 days. The
finished product is a creamy, soft round cheese, covered with a
white ``bloom'' or mold, completely edible. It sells for about $7
for a half-pound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to do more Del Cielo, but the molds are $10 a
piece,'' she says . Goat-cheese making is not a cheap operation.
</P>
<P>
   It takes eight goats to produce as much milk as a cow, says Bud
Larsen of Larsen Farm Inc., a fellow Hays County goat-cheese maker
and one of five in Texas. Larsen, who produces about 1,200 pounds
of goat cheese a week, has kind words to say about his competitor:
``Several of us around here have put the Austin Hill Country on the
state map for goat cheeses; Sara Bolton has just put us on the
national map.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sara is a real connected to her animals and her process. She's
a true nature girl. She's staying small to put out an excellent
product. I think it's an excellent operation in all respects.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara says most dairies are larger than hers, but, ``I'm just as
big as I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   If the dairy were the Boltons' only livelihood, she says she
would have to increase in size. And she admits she's toyed with the
idea but decided against it. The dairy is labor-intensive, even
with good longtime help.
</P>
<P>
   She and her family have other financial interests. They farm
eight acres of certified organic flowers and herbs, which they
sell, along with their cheeses, on Saturdays at a farm stand at
their home on Martin Road and at the Westlake Farmers' Market.
</P>
<P>
   Sara, dressed in faded shorts and shirt, apron and tennis shoes,
cuts cheese curds by hand in the dairy as she talks about life as a
small cheese-maker.
</P>
<P>
   However, conscious of food safety, she constantly checks
temperatures with a thermometer and adds chlorine to washing
solutions. The smell of chlorine permeates the room. ``Ninety-five
percent of cheese-making is sanitizing and washing,'' she says,
giving the romance of artisan cheese-making a heavy scoop of
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Sara and her daughter Amelia, 21, work in tandem on tasks. Then
Sara stops to taste a Ste. Maure cheese, praising her daughter's
result, ``Umm. That's good.''
</P>
<P>
   A benefit of having a goat cheese dairy is getting your fill of
chevre. On Thursday evenings, dinner is cheese and crackers, says
Amelia. Along with a neighbor, she coats some of the cheeses in
herbs and spices and wraps the products for Friday distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Pure Luck Dairy keeps very little inventory. Almost as soon as
the cheese is completed, it is delivered by husband Denny, the
bookkeeper- marketer, to such places as Whole Foods Markets,
Central Market, Boggy Creek Farm, Kitchen Door on Lake Austin
Boulevard, Jeffrey's and Si Bon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best,'' Si Bon chef and owner Peter O'Brien says of
the Pure Luck cheese. ``Not only is it the best, but it's awesome
to have them this close. Plus Denny brings us fresh flowers and
fresh herbs. Sara and Denny are great people.''
</P>
<P>
   At his trendy restaurant, O'Brien incorporates the cheeses in
tarts and frittatas, on salads, as a spread on crostinis, in fondue
for lobster ravioli, or, in the case of Del Cielo, serves it by
itself with sun-dried cherries. It's goat cheese chic in the dining
scene of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Sara uses the goat cheeses in enchiladas, spanakopita,
lasagna and cheesecake, and on baguettes, focaccia and pizza. Just
family dinners at the Boltons, home of national award-winning goat
cheeses. Steps In making chevre: Milk goats Collect milk in a
holding tank Pasteurize milk Add freeze-dried culture (bacteria) to
change the milk sugar to an acid to give cheese flavor. Pour into
tubs Add rennet , an enzyme to make the milk coagulate and form
curd. Within hours the cheese forms a large block, called a curd,
about the texture of soft Jell-O. It is ready for scooping or
cutting when a finger dipped into the curd causes it to break
cleanly. Chevre is scooped into molds 12 to 18 hours after the
rennet has been added. ; Pure Luck uses a basket mold because it
makes a prettier shape and size. After draining for 24 hours, the
cheese is unmolded and salted. Salt preserves the cheese, brings
out the flavor and helps the cheese to continue to release whey.
After another 24 hours of draining, the chevre is packed plain or
herbed and packed. Two of Sara Bolton's favorite ways to use
chevre. Pesto Chevre Crostini 1 baguette
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces pesto, basil or sun-dried tomato
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces chevre
</P>
<P>
   Slice baguette into 1/4- to 1/2-inch-thick rounds and place on a
cookie sheet. Spread rounds with pesto. Spread chevre on top of
pesto. Bake in 350-degree oven 5-10 minutes or until chevre is
melted. Serve warm as an appetizer. Variation: Toasted baguette
rounds can be spread with basil pesto chevre and served unheated.
Roasted Veggie Chevre Sandwich
</P>
<P>
   1 baguette
</P>
<P>
   About 9 ounces chevre
</P>
<P>
   6 to 12 tablespoons pesto
</P>
<P>
   3 to 6 roasted red peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 roasted eggplant, scooped from skin
</P>
<P>
   Vertically slice baguette into three sections. Then slice each
section horizontally to make a sandwich. On bottom half of sandwich
spread pesto, using enough to moisten, 2 to 4 tablespoons. Spread
about 2 to 3 tablespoon chevre on top of the pesto. Top with 1 to 2
roasted red peppers per sandwich and roasted eggplant to taste.
Makes 3 sandwiches. Chevre: Pure, white goat's milk cheese, which
can range from moist and creamy to dry or semi-firm. Shapes include
discs, pyramids, logs. May be plain or coated in herbs, spices or
ash. Beyond the basic fresh chevre, the more than 20 varieties
include bleu, Brie and Cheddars. Curd: The semisolid formed when
milk coagulates. Rennet: An enzyme added to milk to make it
coagulate in cheese production. Whey: The watery liquid that forms
when milk coagulates. The eating and freezing of chevre
</P>
<P>
   Fresh chevre can be used like cream cheese or ricotta.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh chevre usually keeps up to two weeks, sometimes more. If
it gets too old, it tends to go sour and is not as tasty.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh chevre can be frozen, although it tends to be a little
more crumbly after thawing. (Aged goat cheeses, on the other hand,
do not freeze well because it kills the aging process.)
</P>
<P>
   For a goat cheese with a natural rind, like a Brie or the Del
Cielo, wrap it in waxed paper and then put it in a plastic bag so
it will not dry out. Use within a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laura Jacobs-Welch, American Cheese Society Calories Proteins
</P>
<P>
   (grams) Fat (grams) Cholesterol (milligrams) Sodium (milligrams)
Fresh chevre 69.4 4 5.5 17.6 83.4 Cream cheese 99.5 2.1 10 30.5
84.5 _ American Dairy Goat Products Association On a normal week,
Pure Luck makes 100 pounds of chevre, 10 pounds of Del Cielo, 24
pounds of feta, 4 to 8 pounds of Claire de Lune and 4 to 8 pounds
of Ste. Maure.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider is the food calendar for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
