<HEADER>
A5905 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-HORSE09-COX     10-08 2049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-HORSE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horse whispering in Turkey
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVANOS, Turkey _ Ercihan Dilari sat coiled in the trim English
saddle, his black leather chaps pressed against the Arabian
stallion's ribs, and his worn cowboy boots anchored in the
stirrups.
</P>
<P>
   A rancher who grew up in the snow-topped volcanic mountains, his
eyes automatically scanned the ancient ghost cities chiseled by
hand into mountainsides and the towering red chimney peaks sculpted
by whipping winds.
</P>
<P>
   On this sub-freezing winter morning, the stallion raised his
head to scent the hard wind funneled through the canyon. His
nostrils flared and he tossed his head as he danced in an impatient
trot.
</P>
<P>
   Dilari easily controlled him by his soothing voice. No spurs, no
whip, no heels digging in the stallion's sides. Just leather gloves
firmly on the reins and a soft ``ssssssss'' to keep him in check.
</P>
<P>
   Dilari suddenly turned in the saddle to look back at me over his
shoulder. He grinned. ``Let's gallop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He gave a signal like a big smooch, and the stallion bolted like
a spark from flint.
</P>
<P>
   Given rein, my black and white Arabian horse Sevda (in Turkish
it means ``desperate love'') was close behind, her unshod hooves
sinking in the soft mud, her neck stretched out, her head high.
</P>
<P>
   She was 900 pounds of churning muscle, sweating and blowing like
her ancestors who raced through here on the Silk Road, the ancient
trade route linking China and the West.
</P>
<P>
   With an unreasonable combination of fine-boned fragility and
fierce power -- a ballerina with the strength of a linebacker --
Sevda's slim black legs scrambled up steep banks and easily leaped
a 6-foot wide ravine.
</P>
<P>
   The golden canyon walls were a blur and every twist in the trail
felt like a hairpin turn in a Grand Prix race.
</P>
<P>
   During four days together, usually spending most of the day in
the saddle, Dilari and I flew across wheat fields; slowly crossed
frozen gullies, the horses' hooves breaking the ice; and waded
through knee-deep brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, we saw cities carved into mountains during Roman
times, shepherds shearing sheep in a canyon, a beautiful nomad from
Algeria who was traveling with two long-haired camels, and two men
in a pub who longed to meet American women.
</P>
<P>
   There's a saying in this part of Turkey that there are three
things that are important in life -- your horse, your gun and your
wife. Horses come first.
</P>
<P>
   On our first morning together, I was asking a lot of questions
as we rode the dusty cobblestone lanes of a small village.
</P>
<P>
   Dilari suddenly volunteered that he and his wife were separated.
</P>
<P>
   He left her, he said, because ``she talked too much.'' I talked
less the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But his horse, Serap (which means something along the lines of
unattainable fantasy in Turkish), kept up a steady conversation as
we rode, whinnying and flapping his lips -- but evidently it was
not too much. Dilari would never leave Serap.
</P>
<P>
   Using his and his partner Ali Karatas' ranch, Akhal-Teke, as a
base, we roamed through Cappadocia in south-central Turkey on
horseback, which was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The name Cappadocia means Land of Beautiful Horses, and horses,
especially the elegant and strong Arabians, have been here at least
since the Persians came from central Asia in 600-300 B.C. Stone
tablets show that the Hittites trained horses here for sport and
war as early as 1400 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Man arrived by horse, and wars were fought by mounted men -- the
Romans in 300 B.C., the Mongols in the 1200s, and the Ottomans, who
for 600 years had armies with horses. Here, they say you're born on
the horse and you die on the horse.
</P>
<P>
   Which probably would be OK with Dilari. He's had lots of hard
riding in these wild valleys, where big white sheep dogs wear
leather collars with 4-inch metal spikes to keep the wolves from
their necks.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is a man who takes horse medicine when he's
sick. And who shares his cup of hot tea with his horse.
</P>
<P>
   In the corrals of his ranch, next to the banks of the Red River
near Avanos, his horses followed him like big labrador retrievers.
When I rode next to Dilari, Sevda would occasionally lay her head
against his leg.
</P>
<P>
   In Cappadocia, the people have a spiritual connection with the
horse. Dilari and Karatas have trained more than 20 Arabian and
cross-Arabian horses from birth, and have three colts who are going
through the gentle two-year process.
</P>
<P>
   No horse on the ranch is ever sold. The men use no whips, no
spurs, no heavy hand, and they have contempt for those who do.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting by a wood-burning stove at a cafe in the village of
Goreme, Karatas _ Dilari's urbane counterpart, who wore a black and
white tweed topcoat and had a British accent _ spoke about his
horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who use whips do it because they want to train a horse
quickly. They don't care about horses. In Cappadocia, we still use
the horse to go to the fields _ they're good friends to us,'' he
said, with obvious feeling.
</P>
<P>
   And of those who say horses aren't smart, he said, ``Those
people are not smart. Horses have fine personalities. They get
frightened, they laugh, they sing. They love each other, and they
love people.''
</P>
<P>
   The training process is done, he said, ``with a lot of time and
a lot of affection.''
</P>
<P>
   Commands are verbal, although Dilari's stallion seemed to know
what Dilari wanted no matter what words he used.
</P>
<P>
   Sevda, too, kept a constant eloquent eye on me during our rides,
and it was so clear what she was thinking _ let's run, let's just
walk, do we really want to walk through this cold water?
</P>
<P>
   On our first day, Dilari and I rode to Cavusin, where men carved
homes, churches, monasteries and stables into the soft rock of the
mountainsides. Rooms were stacked as high as a 10-story building
inside the mountain. Vertical, 4-foot-wide tunnels with footholds,
connected the levels, which required some serious agility to climb.
</P>
<P>
   Built during Roman times, people lived in them as late as 30
years ago, Dilari said, until the government moved them out and
saved the cities for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day, we came across shepherds shearing sheep in a
canyon, clipping the thick wool with big scissors. And we stopped
at a cafe in Goreme where we met a nomad from Algiers, her black
hair wrapped in a yellow scarf. She wore a flowing red skirt and
big, mud-caked black boots.
</P>
<P>
   She took us to see her two camels, odd creatures with foot-long
hair, stabled in a cave. She and her husband had walked more than
2,000 miles from Algeria through war zones with the camels to get
here. The camels were brothers, she said, and she hoped to find
them a mate.
</P>
<P>
   On another day, Dilari and I ambled beside the rushing Red
River, through stands of poplars and apple orchards, and villages
where children rushed out to say hello, and to a 13th-century
caravansary, an outpost on trade routes where caravans could rest
and have protection from robbers.
</P>
<P>
   When I wasn't on the horse, I rode in the warm comfort of the
ranch's BMW, although German engineering couldn't compete with
Sevda. Karatas took me to meet a dozen artists meticulously
hand-painting pottery at the 200-year-old Sirca shop in Avanos, and
we looked at antique and new kilims and carpets in Goreme.
</P>
<P>
   This area is known for the pottery created from the clay from
the Red River. The carpets, made by women in their homes in the
villages, are considered to be the most beautiful in the country,
and are also much less expensive than in Istanbul and in the resort
cities on the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Antiquities abound and a visitor would need at least a couple of
weeks to do them justice. We explored Ozkonak, one of the largest
of the 13 underground cities in the area, built in the seventh and
eighth centuries by Byzantines and capable of sheltering 60,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   And Karatas pointed out a timulus, a pyramid-shaped hill built
in 2,000 B.C. as a burial ground for an important person. There are
hundreds in the area. At the Church of St. Barbara, carved into a
mountain near Goreme, there were simple red designs from the
Iconoclastic period (726-842) and 11th-century frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   At night, we had dinners in village restaurants, where we
pointed to the dishes we wanted _ grilled eggplant, shish kebabs of
lamb and chicken, yogurt soup with mint _ and drank tea.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner was a chance to get to know Turkish people and topics
included America's use of Turkish bases to maintain the no-fly zone
over northern Iraq (Karatas approves); Turkey's new religious party
(troubling to the mostly secular Muslim majority); and Turkey's
exclusion from the European club. (Turkish people are proud that
they always have been and still are a crossroad between the Middle
East and Europe and not aligned with either.)
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Palm Pub in the village of Urgup, where I ran
across the two men who wanted to meet American women _ because
American women are friendly and open and ``not snobs.''
</P>
<P>
   We sat in wing-back chairs in front of a fireplace and they
intensely discussed what they should say if I put them in the
newspaper. I promised I would, so here goes (both men are in their
mid-20s, nice-looking and earnest): Ozgur Akilli, tall, dark hair,
is a musician; and Koray Avci, a blond with wire-rimmed glasses, is
a jeweler. Interested women who are not snobs should send letters
to them at Antikite Aziz Baba, Kayseri Caddesi, No. 28, 50400
Urgup, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   My last morning before I took the plane back to Istanbul, I got
to say goodbye to Sevda.
</P>
<P>
   Snow was falling, and she looked so pretty, her mane tangled and
her coat thick with winter hair. She looked at me and I could have
sworn she was sad that I was leaving. Or maybe it was relief she
wouldn't have this strange American woman on her back. I'll have to
ask Dilari to ask her.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO TO TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   HORSEBACK TRIPS: For more information and for reservations for
horseback trips at Akhal-Teke Ranch, call Equitour, (800) 545-0019;
or e-mail equitour(AT)wyoming.com. Rates per person are $1,210 for
8 nights (minimum of six people, maximum 14), and include
round-trip flights from Istanbul to Kayseri, all meals, horses,
guides and accommodations. Weight limit is 190 pounds. The tack is
English. This trip is for experienced riders. Equitour offers
international horseback riding trips in the U.S., Canada, Africa,
Europe, Australia, India, South and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   You also can arrange special tours. My solo trip was $1,000 for
five nights. I stayed at Buyuk Avanos Oteli, a modern hotel with
TV, mini-bar, a modern bathroom and a very helpful manager (call
011-90-384-511-3577.) I was the only visitor at the ranch during my
winter trip. The busiest times are fall and spring. Summers are
very hot and winters can get brutally cold. But I prefer winter
when there are few tourists in the villages and there's snow in the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   CAPPADOCIA TOURS: Akhal-Teke Ranch and Horse Riding Center also
offers hiking, mountain bike trips, cross-country skiing and
cultural tours of Cappadocia. Contact Akhal-Teke Horse Riding
Center, 50500 Avanos, Turkey; or call or fax 011-90-384-271-2412.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: For more information about Cappadocia and Turkey,
contact the Turkish Tourist Office, 821 United Nations Plaza, New
York, N.Y. 10017; or call (212) 687-2194. The Web site is
www.turkey.org
</P>
<P>
   Photo captions: Photos by CHERYL BLACKERBY
</P>
