<HEADER>
A5906 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELIZE09-COX     10-08 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELIZE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coming full circle in Central America's Belize
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS AND MAP
 &HT;    By Dudley P. Olsson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELIZE _ We live in a treehouse on an airstrip on a tropical
island in Central America. Well, it's not really a treehouse. It's
a wood-framed space atop an airplane hangar, with bamboo walls,
exposed beams and lots of shutters. The fact that I can almost
reach the coconuts outside my kitchen window qualifies it as a
treehouse. The neighbors on either side live in thatched-roof huts.
</P>
<P>
   My husband, Elis, is a volunteer pilot for Wings of Hope, a U.S.
nonprofit that provides air ambulance service for the country of
Belize. It's a big change for us and our two young children. We
used to live in a colonial-style house in the suburbs of Jackson,
Miss., and my husband managed a packaging company.
</P>
<P>
   The flying part isn't altogether new. Elis has been a pilot and
</P>
<P>
   flight instructor for more than 10 years. When I was a reporter
for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, he instructed at Stone
Mountain Airport in Georgia. Flight instructing doesn't pay much,
though, so Elis went back to school to get his MBA. Now, a decade
later, it seems life has come full-circle.
</P>
<P>
   As the sole Wings of Hope pilot here, Elis is on-call seven days
a week during daylight hours, when flights are allowed in Belize. A
typical mission involves picking up a patient in a remote area of
the country and transporting him or her to Belize City, where there
is a modern hospital. At first, he flew a Cessna 205, capable of
taking off and landing on short airfields, but now he is flying a
Piper Cherokee Six that is fitted with a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   I stay home with the kids, take phone calls and do the necessary
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, we had a case involving a small boy from our town
who had ingested poison. When I took the convulsing child, nearly
the same size as my youngest, into my arms so that the mother could
board the plane, I suddenly realized how vital our work is.
Fortunately, the child survived the incident.
</P>
<P>
   We receive a small stipend for food and personal items, and
Wings of Hope covers our housing and other basic living expenses.
For the first few weeks, we got around town on foot or bicycle _ a
challenge with the kids and the heat. So we used our personal funds
to buy a beat-up Yamaha golf cart. The seat covers are coming off
and the gas pedal sticks, but it has made life a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   There are no paved roads in San Pedro, where we live, unless you
count the runway, which between takeoffs and landings serves as a
pedestrian thoroughfare. Recently, I watched a man in a wheelchair
speeding down the asphalt, being pulled along by his dog on a
leash.
</P>
<P>
   Only believe a third of what you read in the newspapers in
Belize and half of what you see with your own eyes, a local
resident told me.
</P>
<P>
   And it's true. There is something mystical and unreal about this
place, with its brilliant rainbows and exotic plant and animal
life.
</P>
<P>
   The island, Ambergris Caye, is known as La Isla Bonita.
Twenty-five miles long, it is the largest of the 200 or more
islands scattered throughout Belizean waters. Just offshore lies
the Belize Barrier Reef, the longest reef formation in the Western
Hemisphere. In the last 25 years, the reef and its rich marine life
have helped to transform San Pedro from a small fishing village
into a thriving tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Belize to most people in the States, and they've either
visited themselves or know someone who has. My brother and his wife
honeymooned on the island last year.
</P>
<P>
   From our window, we watch the small commuter planes take-off and
land every half-hour. The sound of their engines revving up wakes
us at 6 o'clock each morning. At night, the mechanics work on the
engines, so it is the sound we hear going to bed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, a twin engine airplane from the States was parked
in front of our house. Drinking my coffee, I watched as four
Americans, two men and two women, climbed aboard for a day trip.
Later that evening we learned the plane had engine trouble
returning to the island. The pilot lost control, and they crashed
in the jungle. All four were killed instantly.
</P>
<P>
   The incident bothered me for days. I kept making Elis reassure
me again and again that he isn't taking any chances. He says the
flying doesn't scare him. He loves it, and he loves what he's
doing.
</P>
<P>
   I like it here, too, and for the kids, it's a vacation everyday.
We
</P>
<P>
   know we won't be in Belize forever, so we're enjoying it while
it lasts. Who wouldn't like living in a treehouse on an airstrip on
a tropical island in Central America?
</P>
<P>
   FACTS ABOUT BELIZE:
</P>
<P>
   Geography: Belize is a small country of only 8,866 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Bordered by Mexico to the north, the Caribbean Sea to the east
and Guatemala to the west and south.
</P>
<P>
   Population: Approximately 200,000 comprising Creoles
(African-European), Mestizo (Spanish-Indian), Garifuna
(African-Indian), Maya and European.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English is the official language, but Spanish is also
widely spoken. Maya, Garifuna and Creole are spoken in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Government: Belize is a member of the British Commonwealth with
a democratically-elected parliamentary government.
</P>
<P>
   _Source: Belize Tourism Industry Association
</P>
