<HEADER>
A5909 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN11-CO     10-08 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Will a foreign-born ever be president?
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, Oct. 11, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not have been tongue-in-cheek when Czech President Vaclav
Havel suggested that since Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
being foreign-born, could not be president of the United States,
she ought to consider the presidency of her birthplace, the Czech
Republic. There, she is eligible to attain the highest office.
</P>
<P>
   A Czech magazine, The New Presence, already has editorialized
that it is not an absurd idea. Albright, while pleased by the
attention and honor, says she's not interested. ``I love being an
American,'' she is quoted in Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   It was written into the Constitution by the Founding Fathers
that only native-born Americans could be eligible for the
presidency. They also wrote into that document that no foreign-born
could be elected to the House of Representatives until that person
had been seven years a U.S. citizen, or to the Senate until after
being a citizen for nine years.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Constitutional Convention, 1787, there was
great concern about dual loyalties to the new country and to
England, which had just been separated, by force, from what became
the United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, many of the delegates to the Constitutional
Convention were foreign-born, from England, Scotland, Ireland, even
the West Indies. Alexander Hamilton, born on the Caribbean island
of Nevis, was a delegate to that convention. He served as George
Washington's first secretary of the treasury and his face is on the
$10 bill.
</P>
<P>
   While Hamilton did not oppose the constitutional restriction on
the presidency, he was in the forefront to minimize the time for
foreign-borns to be allowed to run for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Through the more than two centuries of this nation's existence,
the issue of a change to that constitutional requirement has had no
swell of support. Indeed, even American-born candidates have been
scrutinized for any possibility of dual loyalty. When John F.
Kennedy ran for president in 1960, a significant issue of the
campaign was whether he, a Roman Catholic, would follow the dogmas
of the papal office over the needs of the United States. Until
Kennedy, no Roman Catholic ever was elected to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   There will come a day, however, when a challenge will be made to
the native-born stipulation. It may not be in the next few decades
but certainly it will come. The rights of immigrants have greatly
been improved in the latter half of this century, and I can see a
time when someone not born in this country, perhaps carried here
when he or she was but months old, would attempt to erase the
stipulation through a constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   To be successful would require an outpouring of lobbying and
votes from naturalized foreign-borns as well as first-generation
Americans. In numbers, that is not beyond reach.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Census Bureau, almost 10 percent of the
population is foreign-born; 25.8 million. Nearly one in three
already has achieved citizenship _ through more relaxed rules than
originally in place.
</P>
<P>
   While this is not the highest percentage of foreign-born
residents in the U.S. _ it was 13.2 percent in 1920 _ the numbers
are growing again. From a low of 5.4 percent in 1960, it has almost
doubled in three decades. And it continues to grow at a rapid pace.
</P>
<P>
   With that growth in numbers and percentage comes a growth in
voting power. The foreign-born influence will grow well beyond the
handful of them presently in the House and Senate. Targeting the
presidency is not beyond expectation.
</P>
<P>
   While Madeleine Albright has a string of political and
constitutional constraints working against her _ female,
foreign-born, Jewish ancestry _ there will come a time when those
no longer will be considered bridles, and a movement will be
started to change the traditions, beliefs and rules.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
