<HEADER>
A5910 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PALMS09-COX     10-08 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PALMS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-GSU president sees security crisis rising from Russia's
turmoil
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ University of South Carolina President John Palms
traveled this week to Moscow and St. Petersburg, where he is
discussing the former Soviet Union's economic and political turmoil
with politicians, policymakers and business leaders. The
63-year-old former president of Georgia State University in Atlanta
is part of a delegation from the Institute for EastWest Studies, a
New York-based organization seeking to foster stability in central
and Eastern Europe. Palms is a physicist who serves as chairman of
the Institute for Defense Analyses, an advisory body to the U.S.
Defense Department. He talked to staff writer Chris Burritt on the
eve of his trip.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the arena of nuclear relations, what is the biggest threat
to peace and safety now that the Cold War is over?
</P>
<P>
   A: What I am really concerned about is the security of the
materials that are being made available by the dismantling of the
Russians' nuclear arsenal. There are about 50,000 warheads that are
being dismantled, and there is a heck of a lot of uranium and
plutonium in about 100 sites in Russia that are not being
adequately protected.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is security lacking?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Russians no longer have the security systems they used to
have, the fences and the security guards. If 100 pounds of uranium
or plutonium disappears, it is easy to make a nuclear weapon if you
have that kind of material. You can make one like we did over
Nagasaki or Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How might terrorists carry out a threat?
</P>
<P>
   A: You could make a weapon ... smaller than a bowling ball. You
could blow something up, or you could blow it up in the desert and
tell the United States, ``Look, we have one of these planted
somewhere and we want this and that to happen. That is a very great
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the political and economic instability in Russia
heighten the threats?
</P>
<P>
   A: No question about it. You've got government workers who used
to preside over these installations that have not been paid. You
have outstanding nuclear physicists, who have not been paid, who
could certainly market their expertise to other countries or
terrorists or dissidents who do not like what the country is doing
right now.
</P>
<P>
   We owe it to ourselves to buy up all that material and get it
out of there. They need the dollars and we need the uranium to burn
in our reactors (to generate nuclear power.) Based on their
inventories, you are talking probably over a 10-year period about
$10 billion to $12 billion, which is a small part of the Defense
Department's budget. We are spending about $400 million a year and
have made commitments over the next 15 years. You could double that
and get rid of it in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What other roles should the United States play to stabilize
this situation?
</P>
<P>
   A: When Russia had a police state and a strong KGB, there was
such terror in the country that nobody dared do anything illegal.
But there is a whole different atmosphere. There is a free-spirit
entrepreneurship. Millions of people have their own businesses now.
</P>
<P>
   But you do not have that security enterprise around sensitive
facilities that you have in this country. They really need to
develop a security-minded culture in this new democracy. They need
these facilities secured, not just physically by fences and
electronics, but they need to train a security force that does not
operate by terror but by a good police force and security like we
have in other countries. We could help them do that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
