<HEADER>
A5926 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEND-GEEWAX08-COX     10-08 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-GEEWAX08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decision to set rates even lower was heartening
 &HT;    RESEND TO REPLACE KILLED ARTICLE, GEEWAX-COLUMN.
 &HT;    GEEWAX-COLUMN HAS BEEN KILLED. PLEASE USE RESEND-GEEWAX-COLUMN.
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The woman was livid. She called the newspaper repeatedly to talk
to anyone who would listen to her rant about interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The vehemence of her outburst seemed peculiar, considering how
tame interest rates are today. In recent weeks, the rates on
business loans, home mortgages and consumer loans have been
drifting lower, leaving millions of Americans in better financial
condition.
</P>
<P>
   So why was this woman so cranky?
</P>
<P>
   Because she is retired and lives on the interest from bank
certificates of deposit and U.S. Treasury securities. When interest
rates decline on loans, they also fall on her savings. Recently,
the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell below 5 percent for the
first time in the issue's 21-year history. For retirees who
remember getting double-digit yields in 1981, these may seem like
hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Though it may not be easy to think coolly when your income is
falling, people living on fixed incomes are mistaken if they
believe they'd be better off having interest rates rise.
</P>
<P>
   Rates go up in response to growing inflation. They shot up in
the late 1970s and early 1980s because lenders were trying to keep
pace with stunning leaps in wages and prices. Clearly, the economy
is in much better shape today than in 1981, when the prime lending
rate was 21.5 percent and the unemployment rate was nearly 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the prime down to 8.25 percent, the rate of
joblessness has fallen to 4.6 percent. Home mortgages are at the
lowest levels since the 1960s. And the good news for retirees is
that they are no longer getting hit with sticker shock every time
they go shopping. In fact, they are seeing many prices fall.
</P>
<P>
   The phone caller refuses to believe that. She is convinced
prices are still shooting up. For medical care and some services,
such as haircuts and dry cleaning, she may be right. But the
evidence is overwhelming that most prices are stable or falling.
For example, retail beef prices are at the lowest levels in years.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture reports that for Choice, Select
and ungraded cuts of beef, store prices averaged $2.54 per pound
during the first six months of this year, compared with $2.71 per
pound five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That price drop is not unusual. This past summer, a gallon of
gasoline fell nearly 18 percent from the summer of 1997, coffee
dropped 11 percent and telephone bills declined 1.1 percent. Many
cars and trucks are being priced at 5 percent below last year's
models. This fall, Georgia Power Co. is seeking permission from the
Public Service Commission to lower rates for electricity; the only
argument is over how much to cut.
</P>
<P>
   But the woman on the phone was not interested in such data
because she is fixated on only one fact: Her income is declining.
She would rather see the great majority of Americans suffer with
higher mortgage payments, more expensive credit cards and longer
unemployment lines _ so she could feel more secure when she counts
her savings at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Her point of view is selfish, but not uncommon. In coming
months, she and others who depend on bank CDs are likely to see
further cuts as the Federal Reserve Board tries to fight global
recession and price deflation. Some savers will be angry, but the
Fed must ignore their complaints. It's time to cut and cut again to
keep our country from joining Asia and Russia in an economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mgeewax(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax is a member of The Atlanta Constitution editorial
board.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
