<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX     10-08 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Tea time and politics in Paris
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It's Sunday, 4 p.m., and tea time for Americans in Paris
who gather
</P>
<P>
   at George Whitman's famed bookstore, Shakespeare &AMP; Co., just
across the
</P>
<P>
   River Seine from Notre Dame Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, 86, has operated his store from this site since coming
to Paris in
</P>
<P>
   1951. The location itself goes back somewhat further, at least
to the 16th
</P>
<P>
   century, when it served as a monastery.
</P>
<P>
   These days it is a place of congregation for those of us who
worship books
</P>
<P>
   and good writing.
</P>
<P>
   But on this particular day, in a cramped third-floor room
crowded
</P>
<P>
   wall-to-wall with some 20 students and writers, the topic at tea
time was
</P>
<P>
   politics, and the devilment thereof. Nobody to blame but myself.
</P>
<P>
   I'd made the mistake of asking a middle-aged poet who recently
moved to
</P>
<P>
   Paris from Kentucky, a natural progression of sorts, what the
talk was of
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Monica.
</P>
<P>
   He all but exploded. ``It's asinine to speak of it,'' he said,
fuming, ``a
</P>
<P>
   ridiculous waste of time, conversation and ink, a subject that
people are
</P>
<P>
   tired of, fed up and disgusted with.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry I asked _ and even more so when for the next hour the
group talked of
</P>
<P>
   nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the younger women, U.S. exchange students living
with French
</P>
<P>
   families, had the most to say. They represented a wide area of
America, from
</P>
<P>
   Florida to Michigan, Washington, D.C., to California.
</P>
<P>
   The quotes here are approximate. I find it all but impossible to
take tea
</P>
<P>
   and notes at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I can't believe America is making such an issue of it. This
is a
</P>
<P>
   private affair. It should be kept private.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My French family is more disgusted with Hillary than Bill.
They can't
</P>
<P>
   understand why she isn't showing more jealousy and outrage. They
say, `I
</P>
<P>
   would look for love elsewhere myself if I were married to such
an uncaring
</P>
<P>
   person.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I feel sorry for Chelsea. Imagine what she is going through.
A
</P>
<P>
   politician's family shouldn't be made part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Blame that on the politicians for the way they campaign,
exhibiting
</P>
<P>
   their families as if they were trophies and show horses. The
image of the
</P>
<P>
   family becomes part of the campaign promises.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``But when did we ever expect politicians to keep their
campaign
</P>
<P>
   promises?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Too bad Clinton didn't get involved with a military woman.
The military
</P>
<P>
   is sworn to protect the president.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Better had he found someone a little older and a little less
tacky.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Instead, he picked the ugliest women on the face of the
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I feel sorry for Monica. Just think how it must be, that
every awful
</P>
<P>
   thing you ever did is laid out on a table for all to see.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Yes, but she was the one who put them there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Excuse me, but I can't forgive her for keeping the dress.
And then, of
</P>
<P>
   all things, sending it to her mother. My mother would have ... I
can't
</P>
<P>
   imagine what my mother would have done to me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It was a message she was sending to her mother. `Look, I've
slept with
</P>
<P>
   the most powerful man in the world.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Well, they never actually slept together. They never took
that much
</P>
<P>
   time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Did you see the latest poll results? When asked, 66 percent
of the
</P>
<P>
   women in Washington said they'd never have sex with President
Clinton
</P>
<P>
   again.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went: Bill and Monica, tea and sympathy, or the lack
thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is
</P>
<P>
   senior writer for Cox Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
