<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Oct. 8, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ A federal judge has ruled that,
for the time being, the city of San Francisco cannot force United
Airlines to comply with the city's domestic partners law. The city
had been threatening to end United's lease at San Francisco
International Airport unless the airline agreed to provide its
employees in domestic partnerships the same bereavement and family
medical leave and travel perk benefits its married workers receive.
By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-TECH-DETECTIVES (Albany, N.Y.) _ DNA testing and other
developments are expanding the job of today's police detective.
``The more the technology advances, the more collection procedures
need to advance,'' says Barry C. Scheck, one of the nation's
foremost legal experts on DNA and a member of O.J. Simpson's
defense team. But not all departments are equipped for contemporary
police work. By BRENDAN LYONS.
</P>
<P>
   ALAMO-DOCUMENT (San Antonio) _ Analysts have authenticated the
age of the paper used by a Mexican army officer to pen his account
of the fall of the Alamo. The diary written by Lt. Col. Jose
Enrique de la Pena, one of Santa Anna's officers, says Davy
Crockett was captured and executed. This is contrary to the Alamo
legend that Crockett died heroically in the Alamo. By CARMINA
DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DIVERSITY (Berkeley, Calif.) _ UC-Berkeley students
announced that college students across the state will soon launch a
petition drive for a state initiative that would allow for
consideration of race and ethnicity in admissions decisions. By
ROBERT SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   FLEET-WEEK (San Francisco) _ Although the once-great presence of
the Navy in the San Francisco Bay Area has been significantly
downsized, Fleet Week will be as big as ever, organizers say. For
18 years, Fleet Week has honored the Navy with ships parading
through the Bay while war planes roar overhead. By JACOB H. FRIES.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE-ANTHROPOLOGISTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ And you thought owning
an RV was all about collecting bumper stickers and driving slowly
uphill. Not according to Dorothy and David Counts, two retired
professors of anthropology who applied their science to the world
of motor homes and travel trailers and found a sub-culture that is
more complex than might appear at first blush. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NBC-CLASSICS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Maybe television executives are
finally realizing that the American public is not an assemblage of
drooling morons needing the equivalent of electronic Ritalin. This
season, NBC wil bring us Shakespeare's ``The Tempest'' and Feodor
Dostoyevsky's ``Crime and Punishment,'' the classic 19th-century
saga of an impoverished man tormented by internal demons after he
commits a pair of murders in Czarist Russia. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   DRIVE-THEATER-REVIEW (Houston) _ Playwright Paula Vogel believes
in letting an idea simmer before bringing it to life on stage.
``This is a play I carried in my head for 15 to 20 years,'' Vogel
said of ``How I Learned to Drive,'' the provocative off-Broadway
hit appearing at the Alley Theater in Houston. ``How I Learned to
Drive'' is one of the most acclaimed new plays in years. By EVERETT
EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   60S-MUSIC-REVIEW (Undated) _ Take a magical history tour and
experience a flashback of '60s sounds with the release of
``Nuggets,'' a four-CD collection of ``garage band'' hits, and
``Zombie Heaven,'' featuring the hits of the Zombies. By BRUCE
WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   BALDWIN-FILM-PROFILE (Undated) _ ``One Tough Cop'' may sound
like a Jackie Chan action picture, but Stephen Baldwin hopes people
will view it as a serious film. Baldwin plays real-life New York
policeman Bo Dietl, who was one of the city's most effective
officers during his years on the force. By LOUIS PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL-DANCE-REVIEW (Houston) _ In costumes of dazzling colors,
dancing with energy and dexterity, the Ballet National du Senegal
showed that the best indigenous folk art always will be
irresistibly exciting. ``Pangols: The Spirit of West Africa in
Music, Song and Dance'' also was intellectually fascinating. By
CHARLES WARD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-SENIORS (Napa, Calif.) _ Thirty years ago, Walter Hall says,
he didn't have the right temperament to be a tour pro. But now he's
a mature 51-year-old ``rookie'' who will tee up with 77 other
so-called ``seniors'' shooting for a $1 million purse at the
Transamerica and offering examples of graceful aging. By SUSAN
FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFC-AFC (San Francisco) _ Five weeks of NFL football are
behind us, and one thing has become clear: Nobody should be
surprised if the AFC starts owning the league the way the NFC once
did. By JEFFRI CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ You are a woman in your
late-40s, and you are getting dressed for work. Because you will be
attending an opera that evening, you must wear something that will
do double duty. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
