<P>
   &UR; By JOHN TAGLIABUE &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Some Italian cities, like Naples or Palermo, have a hard time
being sedate. Ask them to spin a pirouette or dance a tarantella,
and they're in their element.
</P>
<P>
   But Milan is not a tarantella _ it's a slow tango, a cool,
understated place with a measured step, where excitement can mean
strolling to the Galleria Vittorio Emanuele, the glassed-in
