<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-NEW-BERLIN-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER  
 SENIORS EXPLORE THE NEW BERLIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Not tied to a schedule, mature travelers can tour many
destinations in a short period of time _ without having to unpack.
That made the ``one-city-plus-side-trips'' travel schedule the
perfect choice for Kent and Wynne Crombie of Palatine, Ill., who
were celebrating their 30th wedding anniversary.
 &HT;    The Crombies had met in Berlin when Wynne was a teacher for the
Department of Defense and Kent was in the Air Force, so the logical
location to celebrate their anniversary had to be Berlin.
 &HT;    The love birds were prepared to see a Berlin that was quite
different from the one they had loved in their youth. They spent
parts of the first two days checking out old haunts.
 &HT;    The Americans are gone and the PX (post exchange) has been
bulldozed. Their old BOQs (bachelor officers quarters) are now
offices. Only a few years ago Potsdamer Platz, Berlin's pre-war
Times Square, was a mine zone. A viewing platform _ or the Info Box
_ provides a terrific 360-degree view of this massive
reconstruction zone.
 &HT;    The Crombies planned their weeklong trip to allow them to
explore the city one day and then take a daylong side-trip by train
the next. No dodging 100 mph Mercedes on the autobahn for them!
 &HT;    They began by buying a seven-day transportation pass for $27
each for travel among Berlin's three different travel zones in the
city and surrounding countryside.
 &HT;    The Crombies alternated between the S-Bahn, U-Bahn, trams and
buses as often as they wanted. A senior discount does kick in at
age 62, but unfortunately it applies only to a monthly pass.
 &HT;    Berlin's transit system comes with stairs _ and plenty of them _
so the Crombies recommend that visitors set their own pace. By the
end of the day the couple's calf muscles had had a great workout.
Escalators are available at most stops.
 SIDE TRIP TO POTSDAM  
 &HT;    The first of three side trips took the Crombies to Potsdam,
specifically Cecilienhof, where the Potsdam Conference was held in
1945. It was set in a massive Tudor structure built by Kaiser
Wilhelm II during World War I.
 &HT;    The Crombies say that the Big Three _ Churchill, Stalin and
Truman _ might have just taken a coffee break, so impressive is the
room in which their meetings were held. They urge visitors to take
the time to stroll along the cobblestone streets around Cecilienhof
to see the surrounding country mansions even though they have lost
much of their opulence through neglect.
 &HT;    On the way back to Berlin from Potsdam, the Crombies crossed the
Glienicker Bridge _ often called the ``James Bond Bridge.'' It has
become a fixture in many spy novels and movies. Here Francis Gary
Powers gained his freedom in 1962. The walk across this symbol of
the Cold War can be quite a heady experience.
 BORDER CITY VISIT  
 &HT;    The Crombies' next side trip was to Slubice, Poland, a border
city of 18,000. With the border only 90 minutes away, it was an
excellent way to see the former East German countryside while the
train made its way through farmlands and forests.
 &HT;    The Crombies offer one word of caution: Well-dressed seniors are
especially easy targets for thieves in this area where East Germans
and Poles have a high rate of unemployment. A fellow traveler on
the train warned Wynne Crombie against leaving her purse in plain
view.
 &HT;    It's a 25-minute hike from the Frankfurt-on-der-Oder train
station to the bridge crossing over to Slubice, but a cab ride
costs about $3.
 &HT;    The Crombies joined the melange of pedestrians on the bridge:
women with strollers and shopping bags, people walking their bikes
and smokers looking for cheap cigarettes.
 &HT;    For lunch they chose the appropriately named Restauracja Odra,
which is on a main street near the Odra River. They ate a delicious
lunch of goulash soup and roasted chicken with vegetables.
Deciphering the menu required a dictionary: It is in Polish with
German translations.
 TRANQUIL SPREEWALD  
 &HT;    For the Crombies' final side trip, relaxation reigned as they
made their way to the village of Lubbenau, which is about 60
minutes south of Berlin by rail. As the train began its journey,
Berlin's industrial suburbs gave way to pastoral land and the
canals of the Spreewald River.
 &HT;    The Crombies took note of the memorial on the left side of the
street about halfway down the block from Lubbenau's rail station:
``1930-1945. Never Forget: It is better to die standing than to
live kneeling. In memory of the 11 million victims of freedom.''
 &HT;    Boat trips begin at the small boat landing in the center of
town. The flat-bottom gondolas hold 24 people and are poled by a
German version of a gondolier. The gondolas can be tricky to board
if you have a balance problem or are not steady on your feet.
 &HT;    The ride takes travelers through a series of small rivers _
sometimes only 10 feet across _ under a canopy of willows, ash and
birch. Houses lining the banks resemble storybook cottages, like
those from the children's tale ``Hansel and Gretel.'
 &HT;    The narrative is in German, but the Crombies say the visual
effects make up for any missing audio.
 EXPLORING THE CITY  
 &HT;    The trio of day trips did not prevent the Crombies from poking
into some side corners of Berlin. The Topography of Terror, a
series of photographs chronicling the Nazi era, is temporarily
housed in the remnants of cellar rooms once used by the Nazis to
torture their victims.
 &HT;    The Museum at Checkpoint Charlie offers an absorbing display of
the various ingenious escape methods used by the East Germans.
 &HT;    The Crombies also visited Berlin's flea markets for some
extraordinary shopping. The biggest such market is held every
Sunday on the Juni 17th Strasse, just off the Tiergarten. There are
many articles left over from the German Democratic Republic. The
Crombies found lots of old chandeliers, telephones, carved-brass
door handles and Prussian generals' hats.
 &HT;    The Crombies had explored Berlin and made three fascinating side
trips. In between they had the leisure to browse the corner
bierstuben, or pub, and chat with the locals. This gave the couple
a chance to be a part of the new Berlin as they had been part of
the old.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
 &HT;     (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 The Mature Traveler Newsletter  
