A6048 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV11-C     10-08 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: CLINTON FUSES HIS DOUBLE LIVES
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 11
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Personal character, a sage once said, is how you
behave when no one is looking. We already know that, as a private
person, Bill Clinton has flunked his character test. What we do not
know as yet is whether Congress will see fit to remove him for his
bad acts.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since entering the political fray, Clinton has demanded for
himself a ``zone of privacy.'' But Clinton has also repeatedly been
willing to forfeit his claims to a private life if and when he felt
doing so would enhance his public image.
</P>
<P>
   In writing about Clinton, veteran Washington reporter Robert
Shogan observes in a forthcoming book on presidential character
that ``no candidate in modern times had been the target for so much
criticism and controversy because of his personal behavior. And no
candidate before him had been so calculating and determined to use
his personal life and values as a weapon on his own behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Shogan titles his book ``The Double-Edged Sword.'' Judging by
the president's tactics during the run-up to the House impeachment
inquiry, an apt title for his chapter on Clinton might have been
``Trying to Have It Both Ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Employing lofty constitutional allusions, Clinton's lawyers
invoked the right of executive privilege while the president was
seeking to keep his confidants from briefing the grand jury about
his dealings with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting as their main motive the alleged need to protect the
institution of the presidency, Clinton's attorneys held during that
phase of the scandal that you couldn't parse his private life and
his official duties.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House compass swung 180 degrees as the House
Judiciary Committee tooled up for formal impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders now contend that even if the president had
lied under oath to the grand jury _ which Clinton has not admitted
_ he shouldn't be impeached. In lying, such reasoning goes, he did
nothing to harm his constitutional office, but merely sought to
protect his personal privacy by fending off embarrassing questions
about the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   And yet a president does not have to commit state crimes, either
high or low, in order to face impeachment proceedings. As the House
Judiciary Committee's Republican chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde of
Illinois, notes, a Democratic Congress would have likely booted out
Franklin Roosevelt had he imprudently chosen to embark for a
two-month vacation on the presidential yacht the day after Japanese
warplanes bombed Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another thesis missing from the Clinton briefs: Although
impeachment is a big deal, it's not meant to serve as an ultimate
sanction. To remove a president from office, the Constitution calls
for a two-thirds vote by the Senate, following a formal trial.
</P>
<P>
   By that standard, any decision by the House need only meet the
inferior threshold of culpability called for by an indictment.
Perhaps Congress in the end will also wind up having it both ways:
accusing the private man of low crimes but letting the public man
keep his high office.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
