<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBC-CLASSICS-HNS &LR;      10-08 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-CLASSICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEMPEST' IN A TV SET: NBC CULTIVATES CLASSICS FOR NEW SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I know we may not be smart, us television
watchers. That's why TV takes care of us, giving us shows we can
get. ``Baywatch.'' Man, that's deep.
</P>
<P>
   Now NBC is trying to educate us with the Bard and Dostoyevsky.
Whooda they think we are?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe television executives are finally realizing that the
American public is not an assemblage of drooling morons needing the
equivalent of electronic Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   Later this season, NBC will bring us Shakespeare's ``The
Tempest.'' But first comes Feodor Dostoyevsky's ``Crime and
Punishment'' (Sunday 9-11 p.m. Eastern, check local listings), the
classic 19th-century saga of an impoverished man tormented by
internal demons after he commits a pair of murders in Czarist
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The television version, starring Patrick Dempsey as the tortured
Rodya Raskolnikov and Ben Kingsley as Magistrate Porfiry, isn't a
sprawling classic by any means but it certainly is a captivating
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is taking a gamble on bringing such a high-brow literary
epic to the screen (``Noah's Ark,'' ``Alice In Wonderland'' and the
biography of Albert Einstein are also in planning or production),
since American viewers are attuned to equate television movies with
a prurient crime or disease-of-the-week knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That will change, promises NBC Entertainment President Warren
Littlefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see in our lineup any cheerleader stories anymore,''
Littlefield said. ``We can continue to raise the bar. Every one of
the big events that we've done, anytime we've taken a risk over the
last few years with this long-form product, the audience has turned
around and said, `We get it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Literary snobs and elitists will immediately dismiss this effort
as visual Cliff Notes. Yes, some of the nuance is lost in paring a
542-page book down to a prime-time movie, but still captured here
is the essence of Dostoyevsky's tragic tale.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge facing the filmmakers was how to portray
the inner torment of Rodya, whose anguish is often conveyed in the
book via interior monologue.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, rather than doing voice-overs, was to have Dempsey
speak his thoughts as he walked down streets _ actually enhancing
the visage of a man growing mad and talking to himself _ as well as
showing his tormented dreams. The first method proved much more
effective, as scenes of Dempsey writhing on a bed, juxtaposed with
his nightmares, eventually grow repetitive.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey gives a strong performance as one of literature's great
characters, a man alternately brooding, generous and despondent.
Julie Delpy plays his love interest Sonia, whose forgiveness starts
Rodya on a road toward redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley's role as the astute detective may be smaller than
Dempsey's, but it is the most intriguing as he goes about his role
with a veneer of genial befuddlement _ a sort of Czarist Columbo
without the wrinkled trench coat. Porfiry is both a hunter and
savior, a man bent on salvaging Rodya by destroying him. His prey
is not the man, but the man's soul.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty deep stuff, especially for television. But, believe it or
not, network executives, ``Crime and Punishment'' is at its core
nothing if not a great yarn.
</P>
<P>
   It might even get us to read.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
