A6134 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGH-TECH-DETECTIVES-     10-08 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-TECH-DETECTIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O.J. DEFENDER URGES DETECTIVES TO ADOPT HIGH-TECH METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRENDAN LYONS  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With crime rates falling nationally for the past
six years, you might think the job of a homicide detective would
get a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   As the pinpoint accuracy and increasing use of DNA testing is
expanding the job of today's detective, investigators are spending
more time collecting and deciphering scientific data to clear their
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more the technology advances, the more collection
procedures need to advance,'' Barry C. Scheck, one of the nation's
foremost legal experts on DNA, told hundreds of detectives from
around the world who gathered for a conference at the New York
State Police Academy this week.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck, a renowned law professor who was part of O.J. Simpson's
defense team that poked holes in the prosecution's methods of
collecting evidence, was quick to offer advice on how to build
cases through science that would be tough to disprove.
</P>
<P>
   But for some detectives, Scheck's recommendations _ such as
scraping the underside of each fingernail on a victim, and bagging
each sample separately _ clash with the realities of shrinking
budgets and the need for cops to be on the street making contacts
and tracking down witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have to knock on doors, and contacts are more
important than ever before,'' said Maj. Timothy McAuliffe, who
oversees the State Police forensics division.
</P>
<P>
   For homicide detectives like Christopher Jackson, an 18-year
veteran from Brooklyn, the sheer volume of murder cases in his New
York City borough don't afford the police the chance to spend hours
on the science end of gathering evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're doing the volume (of murder cases) we're doing in
the city, you don't have the luxury. As an everyday rule, it's not
practical,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McAuliffe said detectives are realizing the importance of
gathering evidence and trying not to contaminate a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most critical elements in investigations now is DNA,
Scheck told the group.
</P>
<P>
   Citing national FBI statistics, Scheck said in 26 percent of
cases over the past nine years where DNA results could be obtained,
the person who was initially considered the primary suspect has
been eliminated as a prospect through genetic testing.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic scientists have reacted to the technology, expanding
their training programs so that detectives know how to protect
crime scenes and collect evidence without contaminating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, it didn't matter, now a single hair is a gold
mine of DNA,'' said Dr. Michael Baden, director of the State Police
forensics unit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that same technology which is making today's detective job
more demanding also is enabling many cases to be reopened, and
possibly solved.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas J.S. Watson, a detective in Edinburgh, Scotland, said
that techniques he learned during this week's conference sparked
his intent to reopen two unsolved murder cases when he returns
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been one single lecture here where we haven't
picked up something new,'' Watson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
