<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING TIME WITH BRASS ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You are a woman in your late-40s, and you are
getting dressed for work. Because you will be attending an opera
that evening, you must wear something that will do double duty. On
the mend from a respiratory virus that has sidelined half the town,
you still sound and feel like a very old person with tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Although you rarely listen to rock music anymore, you tune to
San Francisco's KFOG. It's 10 a.m., when disc jockey Dave Morey
does ``10 at 10,'' an hour of uninterrupted theme-rock. Sometimes
he plays stuff from the era in which you listened to rock music
every day. Really old stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Morey begins his show with Chase's 1971 stompin' and wailin'
``Get It On,'' then segues into the Ides of March's 1970 hit,
``Vehicle.'' (``I'm a friendly stranger in a black sedan/ Won't you
step inside my car? I've got pictures, candy/ I'm a lovable man; I
can take you to the nearest star.'')
</P>
<P>
   You may be pushing 50 and your head is clogged with phlegm, but
you get what Morey's doing on this day. Brass. Rock songs with big
horn sections. Oh, man. Other than Motown, this is as good as it
gets for the music of your youth.
</P>
<P>
   Next: Two versions of ``Grazin' in the Grass,'' Hugh Masakela's
and The Friends of Distinction's. Then _ it's about time _ Chicago,
the group that was synonymous with big, harmonious, jazz-infused
brass rock. Four cuts off one album, including the kaleidoscopic
``Make Me Smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Who next but the band that brought brass back into the world of
guitar-dominated rock in the mid-'60s? Blood, Sweat and Tears, with
the long version of one of their hottest tunes, ``Lucrecia
McEvil.'' (``They say your mamma was the talk of the sticks/ Ain't
nothin' that your daddy wouldn't do for kicks.'') With each song
you have inched up the volume on your stereo. Between zips, buttons
and belts, you have begun to snap your fingers and do a couple of
dips and turns.
</P>
<P>
   The immortal Jackie Wilson sings the old Sam Cooke hit, ``Chain
Gang.'' But who is that band behind him? Jackie always had great
horns, but ... No time to wonder. Along comes Cold Blood with the
steamiest, grindingest version of ``I Just Wanna Make Love To
You.'' You growl and moan. Go, girl.
</P>
<P>
   Then it happens. Morey plays the title cut from the 1971
Lighthouse album, ``One Fine Morning.'' Nobody plays Lighthouse
anymore. Nobody even mentions Lighthouse. (They're Canadian.) But
this song, featuring the brass and reeds of Keith Jollimore, Larry
Smith, Howard Shore and Pete Pantaluk, always has been your symbol
of what Morey calls ``the golden age of brass rock.''
</P>
<P>
   You have earrings, a string of pearls and your watch in your
hands. Round brushes are twisted into your slowly drying hair. But
you are compelled to crank up the volume some more. You think of
your neighbors, especially Robert who works at home. You feel bad,
but you can't help yourself. You turn the volume higher. The walls
are rattling.
</P>
<P>
   You fasten on your earrings, your pearls and sing along with
Jollimore, Smith and lead vocalist Bob McBride: ``We'll fly the
East, fly the West/ There's no place we can't call our own/ We'll
fly the North, fly the South/ This planet will be-come our home.''
Eee-eee-eee! Pantaluk's trumpet bursts through the lyrics and
rockets toward a long, bone-bleaching screech. You are grinning,
dancing and clapping your hands, stomping your high-heeled shoes on
your hardwood floor and playing an invisible bean shaker.
</P>
<P>
   The song ends on a wonderfully rude trumpet screech, and you
know neither you nor Morey can top that. You turn down the volume
(a little) and listen to the rest of the set: Tower of Power's
``Soul Vaccination,'' then the Beatles' ``Got To Get You Into My
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   You have lost your watch _ somewhere in your own house. Morey
tells you the band behind Jackie Wilson was Count Basie's. (Get
back!) He says he hopes you liked his show. You look everywhere for
your watch. In the wastebasket, the closet, the medicine cabinet,
several bookshelves, under your cereal bowl, in the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   It's gone for now, and you must go to work and the opera without
it. It doesn't matter. Chicago said so, didn't they? Does anybody
really know what time it is? Does anybody really care?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
