<HEADER>
A6153 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-$ADV12     10-08 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-$ADV12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S CRISIS WORRIES THE WORLD
 &HT;    EDs: Suitable for news for kids' pages.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Mon., Oct. 12 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Imagine that your parents suddenly lost their jobs
because their bosses could no longer afford to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that your family could not get its money out of the bank
because the doors were locked and the automatic teller machine
(ATM) was turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that you went with them to the grocery story to get your
favorite breakfast cereal, only to find it was gone from the
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, this is what life is like in Russia today for many
people.
</P>
<P>
   A SHORT HISTORY LESSON: Russia used to be part of the Soviet
Union, a vast country ruled under communism. The Soviet government
ran the economy and provided jobs for its people, but did not allow
them many personal freedoms like travel and public speech and
religion. In 1991, the Soviet Union broke up because it could not
keep its economy going and more and more people were demanding
freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and many other countries once ruled under communism have
tried to change their political systems and economies to become
more like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But in Russia, the change has been slow and the result in August
was an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HAPPENED: Russia has been spending more money than it
brings in. After several difficult years, it appeared that Russia's
economy would grow in 1998, but foreign investors began leaving and
Russia was forced during the summer to borrow billions of dollars
from the United States and others. When that ran out, the crisis
hit on Aug. 17. Seeking a solution President Boris Yeltsin fired
his government, but that only made things worse. After weeks of
turmoil, Yeltsin appointed Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov in
September. He is working on a plan to help the Russian economy and
hoping that the U.S. and other nations will give more financial
aid.
</P>
<P>
   BIG BUT SMALL; RICH BUT POOR: Russia is the largest country in
the world, almost twice the size of the United States. It is rich
in natural resources like oil, gas, timber and minerals, but its
people are very poor. In terms of the country's total output of
goods and services, Russia does not make the list of the world's
top 20 economies.
</P>
<P>
   It has 146.5 million people. But the number is declining as the
death rate outpaces the number of babies born. Poor health-care and
alcoholism means the life expectancy for males is 58 years old; 72
for women.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Soviet Union collapsed, Russia has moved slowly
towards a free-market economy. However, the bulk of the country's
wealth is in the hands of a small number of industrialists and
financiers. Meanwhile, most ordinary Russians have seen their
standard of living drop and many workers wait months for their pay.
</P>
<P>
   AN EXAMPLE OF THE PROBLEM: Pretend you live in Moscow. The
national currency in Russia is the ruble. Every time you babysit or
mow a lawn, you make 50 rubles.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of August, that 50 rubles was worth about $8 (6.2
rubles  &QC;  $1). Now, because the ruble has been losing value in the
bad economy -- a process called devaluation -- the ruble is worth
only about $3 (16 rubles  &QC;  $1).
</P>
<P>
   But the prices of things you want to buy such as t-shirts, video
games and compact discs are rising rapidly, even as the ruble is
falling in value. And you can't raise your price of 50 rubles for
babysitting or mowing because the people who pay you are losing
their jobs and cannot afford to pay more, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Living standards in Russia were never as high as they were in
the United States, so the impact is felt even deeper.
</P>
<P>
   The average monthly household income in Russia in June was 861
rubles, about $137. With the ruble's devaluation since Aug. 17, the
same income of 861 rubles is now worth about $50. Meanwhile,
inflation -- the measure of the increase in the cost of living --
was up 38 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
   FIXING RUSSIA: It won't be easy. The crisis has raised a
fundamental political debate over whether Russia should revert to a
government-run economy as it had during Soviet times, or pursue
meaningful reforms to seek a free-market economy. The U.S. and
other countries are nervous about giving more aid, fearing it will
only be wasted.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA TROUBLES ARE U.S. TROUBLES: From 1946 until 1991, the
Soviet Union and America were involved in the Cold War, where they
sought to influence other countries and they built huge arsenals of
powerful nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economic problems have forced it to cut back its armed
forces, but it remains the world's second largest nuclear power.
Russia has an estimated 22,000 nuclear weapons and caches of
weapons-grade materials.
</P>
<P>
   So, a stable Russia is considered important not only for
Russians, but for the safety of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
