<HEADLINE>
NAVY TO TAKE PART IN FLEET WEEK, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACOB H. FRIES  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although the once-great presence of the Navy in
the San Francisco area has been significantly reduced, organizers
expect this year's Fleet Week to be as big as ever.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 years, ships have paraded through the San Francisco Bay
while war planes roared overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Week ``is an important opportunity for the public to see
their Navy,'' Navy spokesman Lt. Philip Rosi said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Saturday morning, a parade of six ships will sail
under the Golden Gate Bridge and along the waterfront. The two lead
ships, the USS Benfold and USS Ogden, will be open for public
visits Sunday through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Angels, the Navy's acrobatic aerial team, will take to
the skies over the Bay between the Golden Gate Bridge and Treasure
Island both Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always amazed by how coordinated and powerful these
planes are,'' Rosi said. ``They are able to get a real close-up
view of the planes performing. You can feel their roar.''
</P>
<P>
   For some that roar is too much. Every Fleet Week the Navy
receives about 50 calls from people complaining about the noise,
Rosi said, and last year the mayor's office listened to nearly 100
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it,'' Rosi said. ``We listen to everyone's complaint
and explain to them that all Navy airplanes fly according to strict
safety guidelines, which makes some people feel a little better.
But others don't want to hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosi added, ``For every one person who calls to complain,
there's got to be more than 10,000 people on the waterfront loving
the show.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether the Navy can continue to participate in Fleet Week
is not known because of force reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the city continues to invite the Navy, we will continue
trying to come,'' Rosi said. ``But we don't know how many ships
we're going to have, and we don't know where they might be
needed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
