<SLUG> BC-SENEGAL-DANCE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENEGALESE PROGRAM NEVER MISSES A BEAT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CHARLES WARD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In costumes of dazzling colors, dancing with an energy
and dexterity that would send most of us to the chiropractor, the
Ballet National du Senegal showed Tuesday that the best indigenous
folk art always will be irresistibly exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones Hall program ``Pangols: The Spirit of West Africa in
Music, Song and Dance,'' also was intellectually fascinating for
its surprising comradeship with Eastern European ensembles who've
visited Houston in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Senegalese company, described in press materials as the most
important presenter of traditional West African dance, included the
customary range of songs, dances, rituals and contests of physical
daring _ all accompanied by folk instruments, principally drums.
</P>
<P>
   But, since ``Pangols'' is a tribal word representing the belief
that animate and inanimate objects alike have spiritual aspects,
the company also danced episodes in which the spirits ritually
frightened or seduced people.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a weakness for drums would have been in heaven with
the relentless but extraordinarily subtle drumming.
</P>
<P>
   Over a slow pulse that remained constant, no matter how dense or
free the drumming became, the musicians spun webs of rhythm that
allowed dancers to move at two and four times the speed of the
pulse.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers soon revealed a core style. Arms moved freely, often
swinging back and forth, left to right. Feet were spread wide
apart; knees were often bent. That was a marked contrast to the
highly controlled arm motion and closed-feet positions of western
classical ballet.
</P>
<P>
   From these basics, the performers created seemingly nonstop
movement of almost convulsive energy and intensity, which reached
its peak in the finale.
</P>
<P>
   There, dancers and drummers competed for the ``prize'' of wooing
the audience with their astonishing movements and playing.
</P>
<P>
   A typical eye-opener was the man who appeared with a large bowl,
on which he eventually balanced himself and began to dance. For the
tour de force conclusion of his segment, he lay chest-down on the
bowl, raised his legs backward and began to spin himself like a
top.
</P>
<P>
   I particularly liked the lone singer who played the 21-string
kora. Sounding somewhat like a mandolin, it is played with the
bowl-shaped belly against the musician's stomach and the neck
stretching away from the player. With low, middle and high pitches
available, the performer created his own lilting accompaniments to
haunting songs using the distinctively modal scales heard all
evening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ward can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address comments to charles.ward at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
