<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALDWIN-FILM-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SERIOUSLY TOUGH STEPHEN BALDWIN: REAL EMOTIONS ATTRACT ACTOR TO
OFFICER'S STORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``One Tough Cop'' may sound like a Jackie Chan action picture,
but Stephen Baldwin hopes people will view it as a serious film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its feel is a modern-day `Serpico' meets `GoodFellas,' but
leaning much more toward `Serpico,' '' Baldwin said. ``These are
very real emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin plays real-life New York policeman Bo Dietl, who proved
one of the city's most effective officers during his years on the
force.
</P>
<P>
   Dietl was wounded or injured on the job many times, received
citations and awards, and helped solve two of the city's most
brutal crimes, a 1981 Harlem convent rape and the 1984 Palm Sunday
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, which is a fictionalized story based on Dietl's
book, ``One Tough Cop: The Bo Dietl Story,'' the street cop is
caught in a vise. The pressure comes from his boyhood friendship
with Richie LaCassa (Mike McGlone), who is now a leading Mafia
figure. The relationship puts him in several compromising
positions.
</P>
<P>
   He is being investigated by the FBI, which suspects he has Mafia
ties and wants him to plant a microphone on his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Dietl's partner, Duke (Chris Penn), is drinking too much and
running up big gambling debts.
</P>
<P>
   And Dietl is falling for the Mafia don's mistress (Gina
Gershon).
</P>
<P>
   There's more, but the topper comes when a nun on Dietl's beat is
raped, butchered and robbed, and the case becomes a political hot
potato that hinders his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The film has action, but its themes are loyalty, integrity and
perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   When Baldwin read the script, he quickly accepted the role and
began firming up an idea on how to play Dietl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never met Bo until after I read the screenplay and formed
this idea for the character,'' said Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was an opportunity to play a part I could really
sink my teeth into,'' Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a film in which the character he was playing was
not only still living, but also was serving as an executive
producer and adviser on the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bo was sticking around and keeping an eye on me,'' Baldwin
said, grinning. ``But I had a sense of Bo, and I knew what would
work and what wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very generous; he stayed out of my way and answered my
questions. When the time came that, no, he wouldn't have done it
that way, he let me know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a very difficult role, so I told these guys from
the get-go, `If you want me to do this, it's got to be what I
envision. We can alter that collaboratively as we go, but it's got
to be my vision, or you've got to get somebody else.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin, 32, the brother of actors Alec, Daniel and William
Baldwin, was born on Long Island and lives in New York with his
wife and two daughters. He was a model before following his
brothers' career path. He has done more than two dozen films,
including ``Last Exit to Brooklyn'' and ``The Usual Suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Baldwin has played all kinds of roles in all kinds of
movies. Aside from what seems to be a natural irreverence and
hipness, he has not tried to create any sort of screen image.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend told me, `Steve, they can't hit a moving target,' ''
he said with a small laugh. ``I never know what I'm going to do.
I'm getting offers all the time, and I'm always reading stuff. I
usually know if I like something in the first 10 pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said he has two criteria for picking a film role. He
wants to have a good time doing it, and he wants to be artistically
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   `` `One Tough Cop' was a good time because I was challenged, but
it was very difficult to do, a very intense, draining performance
on a day-to-day basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are characters when the only time I'm into the character
is when they say, `Action.' This is a film where I was in character
all the time, when I was performing, when I was home. There's an
aspect of Bo that was living with me all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking around New York City, looking for bad guys,
unconsciously, talking in the accent, feeling a little more
menacing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin was clearly proud of having gained 30 pounds to play the
role, and having lost the weight after the film wrapped. He
mentioned the fact three times in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd walk up a flight of stairs and be out of breath,'' he
said. ``That effects you psychologically. So it was very physically
and mentally debilitating to play the part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One Tough Cop'' is getting a medium-size national release, on
about 500 screens. But the film's production company, Stratosphere
Entertainment, won't be doing a big-budget promotional campaign.
Which is why Baldwin is out on the road, beating the bushes to let
people know what the film is and isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to allow the movie to speak for itself,''
Baldwin said. ``People are telling me it's much softer than they
expect it to be _ not gratuitous violence for violence's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real honest film.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
