<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-60S-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      10-08 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-60S-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
The MAGICAL HISTORY TOUR: EXPERIENCE A FLASHBACK IN '60s SOUNDS 
 
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Energized by the Beatles in the mid-'60s, hundreds of rock bands
in England and the United States fancied themselves as the Next Big
Thing.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't. Most couldn't buy a hit, though some won regional
airplay and fame back when the music business was more flexible and
open.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, such Beatles wannabes were known as garage
bands, so labeled for their customary rehearsal sites. Learning a
few chords as they went along, they turned their energy and
inspiration into fierce and often tuneful pop-rock and psychedelia.
</P>
<P>
   A similar movement arose in Britain, where one group in natty
Beatles-style suits _ the Zombies _ played artful, exquisitely
crafted pop that melded rock, blues, rhythm-and-blues and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Now much of such material from both sides of the Atlantic is
gaining new life, thanks to the four-CD collections ``Nuggets''
from Rhino and ``Zombie Heaven'' from Big Beat.
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``Original Artyfacts from the First Psychedelic Era,
1965-68,'' ``Nuggets'' is an extension of a seminal album of the
same name first issued in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling Stone put the original ``Nuggets'' on its list of the
top 200 albums of all time. Up to now, it's been the only album on
that list never issued on CD. Today it comprises the new
``Nuggets'' collection's first disc, while the other three add 91
more songs, for a total of 118.
</P>
<P>
   This magical history tour spotlights unknowns and one-hit
wonders such as the Seeds, the Electric Prunes, the Standells, the
Remains, and Texas groups Sir Douglas Quintet, the Zakary Thaks,
Mouse &AMP; the Traps and the 13th Floor Elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Enough of them got airplay that a big chunk of ``Nuggets''
should be familiar to children of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Charting singles include ``Talk Talk'' by the Music Machine, ``7
and 7 Is'' by Love, ``Psychotic Reaction'' by Count Five, ``Louie
Louie'' by the Kingsmen, ``Dirty Water'' by the Standells and ``Hey
Joe'' by the Leaves.
</P>
<P>
   More intriguing are rarities from obscure bands who briefly
achieved true genius. Their sole songs here often point the way to
still more riches in reissues of their work.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Lemon Drops, an Illinois quintet that had no commercial
success yet outplayed most bands of its era. Its ``Nuggets'' track,
``I Live in the Springtime,'' blends a potent melodic hook with a
raw, driving energy that's also found on a Lemon Drops collection
from Cicadelic Records.
</P>
<P>
   Better-known groups also merit more scrutiny, such as Love,
whose ``Forever Changes'' album was one of rock's early
masterpieces, and the Beau Brummels, whose haunting ``Laugh Laugh''
arises here.
</P>
<P>
   The Brummels recorded many other strong songs, mixing an early
folk-rock stance that predated the Byrds with the eerie vocals of a
young Sal Valentino.
</P>
<P>
   Valentino still lives in California, where he's worked off and
on in the music business since the 1960s, launching a new Beau
Brummels band four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised we got included in this,'' he said of
``Nuggets.'' ``It's mostly garage bands who were devil-may-care
musically, and we weren't a garage band. We were really trying to
do our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Mojo Men, also on ``Nuggets,'' the Brummels were signed
to San Francisco's small Autumn label.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring national hits with ``Laugh Laugh'' and ``Just a
Little,'' the Brummels recorded about 50 songs, fewer than half of
which were released in the '60s. Today you can find them on a boxed
set from Sundazed, which, like Rhino, champions '60s sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd been on a bigger label, we might have stuck around
longer,'' Valentino said. ``But I'm not complaining. I'm proud of
what we did. We're a part of musical history, which is more than I
ever bargained for.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two acts on ``Nuggets'' enjoyed sustained commercial
success: the Turtles and Paul Revere and the Raiders. The Turtles
are represented here by a nonhit, a straight-ahead rocker called
``Outside Chance.'' The Raiders' tracks, ``Just Like Me'' and
``Steppin' Out,'' were hits.
</P>
<P>
   Former Raiders lead singer Mark Lindsay thinks the songs were
included because they have the same defiant intensity of
garage-band music.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what binds these acts together,'' he said. ``It was a
belief that we really could change the world. It was get-down,
in-your-face music, and I was totally passionate about it _ still
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Raiders had many hits and a much longer career than
most ``Nuggets'' groups, they belong on the album, Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those songs were two of the first noncovers we did,'' he said.
``We'd just come from being a regional (Portland, Ore.) garage band
playing frat parties, and were just cranking it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay met many ``Nuggets'' acts when the Raiders were the
house band of ``Where the Action Is,'' a 1965-67 ABC TV program
that showcased rock groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I got to watch the Seeds do `Pushin' Too Hard,'
'' he said. ``I loved that record. It was simple and dumb, but it
had that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he tries to apply that attitude to a new band he formed
for oldies tours. Paul Revere has toured for many years with a
reconstituted Raiders, and Lindsay said he wouldn't mind a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of the '60s in the '90s,'' he said. ``Music that
turned us on as teen-agers _ with all the hormones and the angst _
can still work for a lot of teen-agers today.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they don't make 'em like they used to, but some young
bands are in the same position as these `Nuggets' groups. They're
regional bands who scrape up the money to cut 500 or so CDs and
avoid the `business' of the music business. I do think it's
improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more '60s music continues to be unearthed, perhaps in
response to the huge commercial and artistic success of the
Beatles' ``Anthology'' project.
</P>
<P>
   One prime example is ``Zombie Heaven,'' a lavish collection of
119 songs by Britain's the Zombies.
</P>
<P>
   The quintet formed as schoolboys in 1961, and by 1964 it had its
first hit, ``She's Not There.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were far more popular in America than the U.K.,'' lead
singer Colin Blunstone said. In the United States, ``She's Not
There'' has had 2 million airplays through the years.
</P>
<P>
   The former Zombies have stayed in touch. With ``Zombie Heaven''
stirring new interest, Blunstone, along with the band's
keyboardist, Rod Argent, and bassist Chris White, recently recorded
a new version of ``She's Not There.''
</P>
<P>
   The group split in 1969, just after recording the ambitious and
oddly spelled ``Odessey &AMP; Oracle''album.
</P>
<P>
   Then a strange thing happened: The farewell album produced a hit
single, ``Time of the Season.''
</P>
<P>
   Today some critics consider the album a classic on the level of
``Sgt. Pepper's'' or ``Pet Sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Now ``Odessey &AMP; Oracle'' is available in two forms: on ``Zombie
Heaven's'' Disc 2 and in a 30th-anniversary edition featuring
stereo and monaural versions of each song, along with three bonus
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zombie Heaven'' collects that and more, with 42 previously
unreleased tracks.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``Zombie Heaven'' parallels the formats of
recently issued Beatles material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zombie Heaven's'' Disc 4 is `Live on the BBC.' Like the
Beatles' `Live at the BBC,' it mixes music played live in the
studio, banter with a radio host and unlikely covers, in this case
Burt Bacharach's ``The Look of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Disc 2, ``In the Studio,'' is comparable to the Beatles'
``Anthology'' albums. It offers demos, rehearsals, tinkering and
false starts _ often followed by sudden brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Disc 1 collects singles and album tracks, including the hit
``Tell Her No;'' the dreamily romantic ``Leave Me Be;'' and ``I
Love You,'' a hit in the United States for one-hit band People.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Blunstone's soft, eerie vocals lace the group's
cool, minor-key arrangements, while Argent plays inspired
keyboards, clearly inspiring the Doors' Ray Manzarek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without being specific about musicians, I am led to believe
that a lot have been influenced by the Zombies,'' Blunstone said.
</P>
<P>
   For all their studio precision, the Zombies also could rock out
as well as any ``Nuggets'' band, as shown on such songs as ``What
More Can I Do'' _ one minute and 37 seconds of dark, driving
brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scene was the same here,'' Blunstone said. ``Everybody
either was in a band or their best friend was in a band. There were
thousands of bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beatles led the way, but the availability of electronic
instruments and the popularity of simple songs made performing
accessible to people of all abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   He said recording was ``much more spontaneous then. You had an
idea, you went into the studio, and you recorded it. Today, you're
talking to lawyers for six months first.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Zombies music has sold ``around the world in significant
numbers'' ever since, Blunstone said, for most mid-'60s bands, fame
was fleeting at best.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was in the wind back then,'' said Lenny Kaye, a
former rock journalist who compiled the original ``Nuggets'' album
before becoming guitarist of the Patti Smith Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very close to what happened during the birth of rock
'n' roll _ the sense that you could carry your guitar out to the
garage and experiment with a three-minute song and become a part of
rock history.''
</P>
<P>
   Most bands probably didn't expect their part of rock history to
last 30 years. But today their reckless, frenetic, fuzz-tone
influences are clear.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '70s, Kaye met many punk groups who were inspired by
the first ``Nuggets'' album. Also, many songs from this new
collection have been covered during the years (Syndicate of Sound's
``Little Girl'' by the Divinyls, the Hombres' ``Let It Out'' by
John Mellencamp).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have picked up the torch and carried it
farther,'' Kaye said. ``The genre has lasted and lived on in ways
undreamed of by its creators. It's become a touchstone for several
musical generations, and I'm proud of my part in that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
