<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR SERVING UP A FULL-PLATE AT TALLADEGA, DAYTONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are waiting for someone or something to inject a little
drama into the NASCAR Winston Cup points chase between Jeff Gordon
and Mark Martin, the next two races probably offer the last and
best shots.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in history, Cup teams will compete in
back-to-back restrictor plate races at the Talladega Superspeedway
and the Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston 500 at the Talladega, Ala., facility originally was
scheduled for Sunday. But the Pepsi 400 at DIS was postponed and
moved to Oct. 17 after wildfires threatened the Daytona Beach
community during the Fourth of July period. As originally
advertised, it will be the first restrictor plate race run at
night.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's the big deal about a ``plate-race?'' A race is a
race, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. Because of several elements peculiar to plate
racing, these two events conceivably could help championship leader
Gordon substantially add to his 174-point advantage, or allow
Martin to pull to within serious striking distance during the
schedule's final three non-restrictor plate events.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the basics that make a NASCAR plate race decidedly
different.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reduce speeds and ensure driver/spectator safety
at the high-banked, 2.66-mile Talladega and 2.5-mile Daytona
racetracks, NASCAR runs its races there with a device known as the
carburetor restrictor plate. The plate is a one-eighth-inch-thick
piece of metal that fits on top of the manifold and under the
four-barrel carburetor of every engine. The four holes in the
plate, which line up with the four holes in the carburetor, have a
NASCAR-mandated diameter of 29/32nds-of-an-inch.
</P>
<P>
   The plate restricts the amount of air being pumped into the
engine through the carb, inhibiting its ability to produce
horsepower and speed when mixed with gasoline. For example, a 358
cubic-inch Chevrolet V-8 engine that normally produces between 725
to 735 horsepower in unrestricted form will crank out ``only'' 425
to 435 horsepower with the plate. As intended by NASCAR, that loss
of revs keeps speeds in the high-180 mph range.
</P>
<P>
   But plate racing also has produced pack racing. The reduction in
horsepower is magnified by a reduction in the ability to accelerate
away from another car in a pinch. Mix in the bumper-to-bumper
drafting that is common on superspeedways, and freight train-like
lines of eight, nine or more cars are common. While that creates
spectacular side-by-side racing lap after lap, it also increases
the probability that one wrong turn of the steering wheel could
trigger a massive wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Ask any Cup driver about his greatest concern during a plate
race and he will tell you it is getting swept up in ``the wreck''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the two restrictor plate races back-to-back as some
medicine that you need to take, and you may as well take it all at
once,'' Martin said. ``Because when you're finished, you're
through.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time through the schedule, Martin finished 38th in the
season-opening Daytona 500 and 23rd in the DieHard 500 at
Talladega. He failed to lead a lap in either event, meaning he did
not collect the five bonus points available.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon finished 16th at Daytona and fifth at Talladega, earning
five points at each event for leading a lap.
</P>
<P>
   That figures into advantage Gordon, who has outscored Martin by
a combined 390-143 in the earlier two plate races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been pretty fast the past couple of times at Daytona and
Talladega, so I feel pretty good about our restrictor plate
program,'' said Gordon, driver of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive
Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``There's always a possibility of a
big wreck happening. If it happens and I'm near it, then I'm going
to be worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, driver of the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus, shaved 25
points off Gordon's lead with his dominating victory at Charlotte
Motor Speedway on Sunday. But over the past 12 races, this pair has
finished within one position of each other eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had the higher finishing position in six of those races.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon _ who never has won a Cup race in October or November _
needs to finish fifth or better in the final five events to lock up
his second consecutive title and third in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your allegiances, the upcoming plate races offer an
increased probability of one of the title contenders getting caught
up in ``the wreck''. And it could be the one that decides the 1998
Winston Cup championship.
THE BUZZ
 &LR; subheds:NASCAR  &LR; agatea:In an effort to upgrade its restrictor
plate program, Roush Racing tested at the Daytona International
Speedway in June. Chief among the concerns for team-owner Jack
Roush were the results posted by rising star Jeff Burton. Driver of
the No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford Taurus, Burton finished 40th at
Daytona and 43rd at Talladega Superspeedway this season. ``We've
got our third set of cars organized, and I don't know if we've got
a good car yet or not,'' said Roush, whose priority remains
steering ace driver Mark Martin to his first Cup championship. ...
</P>
<P>
   Derrike Cope followed his first career pole at Charlotte Motor
Speedway last Wednesday with a season-high 14th-place finish in the
UAW-GM Quality 500. It was the first time Cope, driver of the No.
30 Gumout Pontiac Grand Prix owned by Chuck Rider, has finished on
the lead lap this season. ... Ward Burton, driver of the No. 22
MBNA Pontiac owned by Bill Davis, ended an 85-race streak without a
top-five result when he finished second to Martin at CMS. ...
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan Bobby Labonte has to rate as the odds-on favorite
at the upcoming plate races. Labonte, driver of the No. 18
Interstate Batteries Pontiac, finished second at Daytona in
February and first at Talladega in April. ...
</P>
<P>
   Despite the in-court efforts of The McIlhenny Co., first-year
Winston Cup team-owner Tim Beverley of Tyler will conclude the 1998
schedule with Tabasco sponsorship on the No. 35 Pontiacs driven by
Darrell Waltrip. Beverley bought the team from three-time Cup
champion Waltrip in March, and merged it with ISM Racing and owner
Bob Hancher in July. The McIlhenny Co., the Louisiana-based
manufacturer of Tabasco, has claimed breach of contract on nine
points in its bid to pull financial backing worth a reported
$8.3-million. ``We're finishing the season with Tabasco,'' said
former Texan Kent Johnson, public relations representative for
Waltrip and Tyler Jet Motorsports in Concord, N.C. ``They \RThe
McIlhenny Co.\S went to court to get an injunction against us, but
twice a federal judge in Louisiana threw them out. We're running
the cars and doing everything we can to put The McIlhenny Co. in a
positive light. That's the way we're conducting business.''
 &LR; subheds:Indy Racing League  &LR; agatea:Points leader Kenny Brack needs
to finish eighth or better Sunday at Las Vegas Motor Speedway to
clinch his first Pep Boys Indy Racing League championship. A native
of Sweden, Brack leads Americans Davey Hamilton by 31 points and
reigning series champion Tony Stewart by 41 heading into the 11th
and final race of 1998. If he captures the title at Vegas, Brack
will become the first Swedish driver to win an Indy-style
championship _ not to mention a $1 million bonus from Pep Boys
Manny, Moe &AMP; Jack. Brack, who won two open-wheel, formula pavement
series en route to the IRL, does not exactly fit series founder
Tony George's mold of the driver looking to race in this league.
``I don't know if this series was designed for an America,
open-wheel dirt-racer,'' said Brack, driver of the No. 14 A.J. Foyt
Power Team Dallara/Aurora. ``I never really understood that that
was the case, but maybe it is. I don't really think background has
so much to do with it. If you're a good race driver, you're a good
race driver and your background is whatever. You don't need to come
up through a specific rank to be good in IRL racing. I think people
look at you for what you can do in the series here.''  &LR; subheds:NHRA
 &LR; agatea:Advance ticket sales are up 18 percent for the 13th annual
Revell Nationals, a trend that points to another record-setting
year for the National Hot Rod Association event scheduled for Oct.
22-25 at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis. Total attendance for last
year's three-day meet was 138,500, including a crowd estimated at
slightly more than 63,000 for Sunday's final eliminations. This
year's meet will feature a four-day program, highlighted by the
first appearance of the Pro Stock Trucks. The trucks are scheduled
for two qualifying runs on Thursday, Oct. 22, including a 6:15 p.m.
session that also will include the Federal Mogul Dragsters and
Funny Cars. ``We've previously drawn 65,000-plus on Sunday going
against the Cowboys and the State Fair,'' said Motorplex spokesman
Elon Werner. ``This year, the Cowboys have an open date that
weekend and the state fair will have ended the weekend before.
There should be no conflicts. If we keep selling at the rate we're
selling now, we'll be sold out on Sunday, Oct. 19.'' The week will
begin with the sixth annual Dallas Motorsports Expo in the historic
West End from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. on Wednesday, Oct. 21. The Expo is
free. For ticket information, call the Motorplex at (800) 668-6775.
FAST LAPS
 &LR; subheds:Bodine has made it  &LR; agatea:I can remember a time when
Geoff Bodine was booed with a fervor now reserved only for Jeff
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   It happened every time the Brothers Bodine, from Chemung, N.Y.,
would invade the Utica-Rome Speedway in Vernon, N.Y., for a hot
summer night of NASCAR Modified racing against local heroes Richie
Evans and Jerry Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine made the full-time jump from Modifieds to Winston Cup in
1982, and is scheduled to make his 500th career start Sunday in the
Winston 500 at Talladega Superspeedway. He will become the 19th Cup
driver, and one of only eight active, to reach that milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine has scored 18 victories, 37 poles and won more than $12.5
million in his career, which was topped by his selection as one of
``NASCAR's 50 Greatest Drivers'' earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 500 starts have just flown by,'' said Bodine, 49, who is
not sure he will be retained by team-owner Jim Mattei as driver of
the No. 7 Philips Ford Taurus next season. ``The 500th start won't
mean something to everybody, but it sure does to me. Really, it
didn't sink in what it all meant until Al Larsen, our PR rep, put
together a press kit. On the cover of this press kit is the picture
of this kid _ this cute little kid _ sitting in a \RMicro Midget\S
go-kart his father \REli\S had built for him. I'm not sure what age
he was, but he's holding a checkered flag and has a big smile on
his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that picture it all really sunk in what this 500th
start meant. It meant that little kid had a dream of some day being
a race driver, and that dream came true and he made it.''
 &LR; subheds:Nuts and bolts  &LR; agatea:Robby Unser, son of three-time Indy
500 champion Bobby Unser, is close to locking up IRL
rookie-of-the-year honors. He needs to finish 24th or better Sunday
at Las Vegas Motor Speedway to earn a $50,000 bonus from Sprint
PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Kanaan clinched the Jim Trueman Rookie of the Year award
during the inaugural Texaco Grand Prix of Houston on Sunday. The
Brazilian sealed the Championship Auto Racing Teams honor with two
events remaining.  &LR; subheds:Last words  &LR; agatea:''Any time you go
into a race where the goal is to miss the wreck, that's not what we
look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Burton, on racing in the Winston Cup restrictor plate
events at Talladega and Daytona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
