<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DALLAS-STARS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS AWAIT THE FIRING LINE ERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brett Hull stood 10 feet from an open net against the Tampa Bay
Lightning in a preseason game Monday ... and passed the puck ...
laughing. Scoring a goal just seemed too easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 7-2, c'mon,'' Hull said of the Stars' blowout. ``What
sport is there in that?''
</P>
<P>
   That Hull can be almost apologetic for his team's offensive
prowess is a sign the Stars might be building a monster. The Stars'
Firing Line _ Hull, Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen _ accounted for
11 goals and 12 assists (23 points) in seven preseason games, a
pace that would give them 268 points if all three were healthy for
an 82-game season.
</P>
<P>
   The scary part is that those were the first seven games they've
played together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what they have, it's pretty unbelievable,''
Phoenix Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick said. ``Modano is a great
passer and skater, Hull is a great shooter and Lehtinen is a great
defensive player. Yeah, it's a pretty scary group.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes teammate Keith Tkachuk took it one step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talentwise, they're probably the most talented line in the
league,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, Hull and Lehtinen officially start the ``Firing Line
Era'' Saturday in the season opener against the Buffalo Sabres. As
soon as Hull joined the team as a free agent in the summer, there
were rumblings the Stars had put together a line that could become
a classic in the mold of the Montreal Canadiens' Punch Line or the
Detroit Red Wings' Production Line.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to put too much pressure on them or anything,
but that's a lot of talent,'' Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher said.
``You can only talk on potential right now, but they do have the
potential to be the best line in the league.'' THE THREE STARS
Imagine putting one of the NHL's best pure goal-scorers, one of the
league's top two-way players and one of its top defensive forwards
on the ice at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   That's The Firing Line.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, 27, is in the prime of his career. Third on the Stars'
franchise scoring list with 654 points in 633 games, he is ranked
by ``The Hockey News'' as the eighth-best player in the NHL and his
plus-68 ranking during the past two seasons ranks second to the
Flyers' John LeClair (plus 74).
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, 25, was the Selke Trophy winner last season as the
best defensive forward in the NHL. He finished third in voting for
the award the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's 554 goals rank him 15th all-time in the NHL and he is
third all-time in goals per game at .691. He has averaged 56 goals
per season in his career, most of it with the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's addition could make this the group that puts the Stars in
line for improving on last season's loss to Detroit in the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Greg Adams and Jamie Langenbrunner filled the
opening on the left side, and the Stars' first line had its
moments, totaling 153 points. But that still left too much pressure
on Modano to be the goal-scorer, the one who could finish the play.
And opposing defenses knew that, holding Modano to 21 goals in 52
games.
</P>
<P>
   Hull now is the trigger man. He had five goals in six preseason
games And his ability to score will force opposing defenses to
choose between covering Hull or Modano _ the kind of dilemma that
has made most of the great lines click.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact Brett's shot is so hard, it's going to create some
opportunities for both of us,'' Modano said of himself and
Lehtinen. ``I don't care what you say, people are going to be
waiting for Brett Hull's shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who already has benefited from Modano's slick passing and
on-ice vision, was just as complimentary toward his linemate. When
asked what Modano's strengths are, Hull replied, ``Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to elaborate, Hull just laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Modano might be one of the most all-around skilled guys
in the game,'' Hull said. ``He does it all, it's that simple. He's
effortless, he's Roy Hobbs. He's The Natural.'' SHOOTING STARS The
Firing Line has had only one problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem to want to shoot the puck enough,'' coach Ken
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, Modano and Lehtinen, who combined to average 9.6 shots per
game (Hull 3.2, Modano 3.6, Lehtinen 2.8) last season don't want to
shoot? Certainly, you can't call these guys gun-shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably making a few too many passes,'' Modano said,
``maybe an extra one or two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Or how about six,'' defenseman Shawn Chambers added.
</P>
<P>
   Modano said he's getting to know Hull's tendencies and doesn't
want to appear to be a puck hog. Hull said similar thoughts have
run through his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, one of us is going to have to start shooting
it a little more,'' Hull said. ``But the three of us, don't want to
make it look like `I want to score,' ''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hitchcock and general manager Bob Gainey have talked to the
players about their tendency to over-pass _ and teammates already
are starting to give them ribbing about their unselfish play. But
Modano said the line still is developing, and that the problem will
take care of itself Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come the regular season, Brett won't pass,'' Modano said.
``Don't worry about it.'' STARS IN LINE Hitchcock remembers the
great lines of NHL years gone by. The Production Line of the
Detroit Red Wings, the Punch Line of the Montreal Canadiens _ they
were a part of his hockey youth that helped make the game seem
larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock has the chance to help create the next great trio.
Hull-Modano-Lehtinen has the personality and the potential of
longevity that few other lines in the NHL have. Modano is under
contract for the next six seasons, Hull for the next three with an
option for a fourth. Lehtinen has one-year remaining on his
contract, but the Stars aren't about to let their prized draft pick
of 1992 get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what could happen; we have to go out there and
see,'' Hull said. ``No one can predict the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can get a pretty good picture by looking at the past.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's Punch Line combined a great scorer _ Maurice Richard
_ with a great setup man _ Elmer Lach _ and a versatile scrapper _
Toe Blake. The Production Line of the Red Wings had a great scorer
_ Gordie Howe _ with a great setup man _ Sid Abel or Alex
Delvecchio _ and a versatile scrapper _ Ted Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   The Firing Line has Hull as the scorer, Modano as the setup man
who can also score and Lehtinen as the versatile scrapper. In many
ways, they're also like the Long Island Lightning Co. of Mike Bossy
(scorer), Bryan Trottier (setup man) and Clark Gillies (scrapper)
that helped the Islanders to four consecutive Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Still, each line has to find its own chemistry and setting up
those comparisons creates heavy expectations for the Firing Line.
Hitchcock, who already is downplaying the offensive capabilities of
his top line, said he expects Hull-Modano-Lehtinen to perform as
the No. 1 checking line, squaring off against an opponent's top
scoring line almost every night. That means they have to emphasize
both offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather have them outscoring a line 1-0 than scoring three
goals and giving up three,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Hitchcock will push for two-way play, the Firing
Line will have an eye toward offense. Hull and Modano guarantee it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look around the room and it's nice to see,'' Modano said.
``We never seemed to be a team that put that much emphasis on
offense in the past. But this group should able to score. It should
be fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
