<SLUG> BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-FLETCHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OU BACKUP BECOMING KNOWN FOR RESCUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a brief but distinguished collegiate career, Patrick
Fletcher has played quarterback for Nebraska, Kansas State,
Syracuse and Northwestern, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great help to me,'' he said. ``If I hadn't had
that experience, I probably wouldn't be able to do a lot of the
things I'm doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   All in a year's work in the carefree life of a scout-team
quarterback, which is what Fletcher's job description has been for
the past two seasons at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   He adds modestly, however, that the achievement pales in
comparison to that of his father, Ron, who finally gave up his role
as a starting quarterback at age 52.
</P>
<P>
   They will both be in the Cotton Bowl on Saturday when their
hometown team, Oklahoma, battles Texas in the annual Red River
Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Ron, a Church of Christ minister, will be there to watch
Patrick, the third of his sons to play for OU, do a little
quarterbacking against the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   A sophomore walk-on, Fletcher is an old hand at these affairs,
having attended his first Texas-OU game at age 3. But this will be
the first one he has ever played in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just really excited,'' he said. ``I think I'm having an
anxiety attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety is what Fletcher _ now the Sooners' backup quarterback _
has been dealing out to opponents thus far.
</P>
<P>
   In what is becoming a patented routine, Fletcher arrived in
relief of starter Brandon Daniels last week and threw for 130 yards
in the fourth quarter. He directed two late drives that nearly
unhinged 15th-ranked Colorado in a 27-25 OU loss.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it was not a totally cheery performance, because
Fletcher's first pass was intercepted and returned for a touchdown.
But thereafter, as he has in other appearances, he electrified the
offense and re-established his position as a huge crowd favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick made a youthful mistake early, but those things are
going to happen,'' OU coach John Blake said. ``There are certain
things he can do for us, and he understands and accepts his role,
and that's why he's so useful to us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was reminiscent of Fletcher's performance in the opener
against North Texas, when he relieved Daniels and revved up a
sluggish attack with five consecutive completions, spurring the
Sooners to an eventual 37-9 win. He started the next week against
TCU, but left with a bruised Achilles' tendon and sat out the loss
to California.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back, and in the modest assessment of ol' dad, ``It's
kind of like being able to bring Nolan Ryan in out of the
bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But really, the biggest thing about Patrick is that, any time
you use him, he'll give you everything he's got,'' Dad said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Norman, Okla., Fletcher was part of a family so
OU-oriented that the house should have been painted crimson.
</P>
<P>
   The record book still states that Ron Fletcher threw the longest
touchdown pass in school history _ a 95-yarder in a 36-19 loss to
Florida State in the Gator Bowl at the end of the 1964 season, his
senior year. A few years later, he returned as an assistant coach
(1970-75) before becoming a minister.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick's mother, Pam, works in the OU visitor's bureau. His
older brothers, Ronnie and Paul, played for Barry Switzer and Gary
Gibbs, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, the family dog can sing the fight song.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always known I was going to Oklahoma,'' Fletcher said.
``I was a veer quarterback in high school and I didn't really have
big numbers. I didn't get many scholarship offers, except from
small schools, but it didn't matter. This is the only place that
I've ever wanted to go to school.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he enrolled at OU, took a redshirt year, then settled into
the carefree life of the scout-team quarterback: each week another
dangerous assignment, impersonating the leader of the opponent. One
week, it's Donovan McNabb, the next, Corby Jones. In two years, he
has run virtually every known offense and taken thousands of snaps.
Finally, given a chance after an impressive spring, he won a roster
spot during two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``I think maybe I have an advantage,
because there's not as much pressure on me as there is on Brandon,
and the defense isn't prepared for me. But I've been able to stand
on the sideline and size them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, it's kind of the same thing my dad did here. I guess
you could call it a family tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   During his own playing career, Ron Fletcher was the ``passing''
quarterback on run-oriented teams featuring Jim Grisham, Joe Don
Looney and Lance Rentzel, and was used mainly in come-from-behind
efforts. In later years, however, he gained fame as the perennial
starting quarterback in the annual Varsity-Alumni game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It finally reached a point where most of our guys \Ralums\S
were making so much money in the NFL, they couldn't risk getting
injured in that game,'' he said, laughing. ``So, every year, I
played quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that right up until \Rformer coach\S Howard
Schnellenberger came here and canceled the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a performance of which his son remains in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad did that until he was 52 years old,'' Patrick said.
``And he was still real quick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
