<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINKY-HILLCOUNTRY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUR OF KINKY COUNTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDINA, Texas _ These days, Kinky Friedman lives at the Texas
Hill Country children's camp run by his family. Taking a break from
writing mystery novels and putting the finishing touches on the
soon-to-be-released CD ``Pearls in the Snow,'' a tribute album of
Kinky-penned songs recorded by artists such as Tom Waits, Lyle
Lovett, Willie Nelson and Dwight Yoakam, Friedman took
Star-Telegram writer Jeff Guinn on a Kinky-esque Hill Country tour,
pointing out certain sights and amenities that usually escape the
notice of more traditional visitors to the area. As Friedman noted,
``Lots of people drive through Fredericksburg and think they've
seen everything. They haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, where does the perfect Hill Country tour begin?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't go wrong eating at the Lost Maples Cafe in Medina.
Chicken-fried steak as big as your head, and a lot better-looking
than your head ever was. It's what people want to believe the
typical Texas cafe is like: friendly waitresses, big portions, not
too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Once you've eaten, where to next?
</P>
<P>
   A: You need to visit Medina. As my father says, it's a town
that's slowly been dying for 100 years. Drop into a cafe called The
Filling Station. The walls are decorated with anti-Clinton posters.
Very tasteful. Tell Velma (that) Kinky sent you. Then duck. The
characters that hang out at that place are right out of
``Deliverance.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Arky's Silver Dollar, right off Main Street in
Bandera. They've got sawdust on the dance floor and real country
bands playing. You might see Adolph Hoffner and the Pearl Beer
Wranglers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about places other than bars or cafes?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's a lot. Check out the general store in Utopia. It's
out of a '40s movie. The Cider Mill in Medina is interesting. And
the Frontier Times Museum, there is a place you have to go. It has
a real shrunken head, a two-headed goat and the shoe of a woman
involved in a hit-and-run accident in 1927. These objects delighted
me as a kid, and, because of arrested development, continue to hold
the same fascination for me.
</P>
<P>
   Then take the road from Medina to Vanderpool. You'll probably
see roadrunners. Some people think they're adorable. There are
usually lots of turtles crossing the road. Also armadillos.
</P>
<P>
   But we need to talk about food some more.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why food?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because you can eat really well around here. Go to the Old
Spanish Trail Diner in Bandera. I recommend eating in the John
Wayne room. On the walls in there, they've got over 360 pictures of
John Wayne. ``The Duke!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You haven't mentioned Kerrville yet.
</P>
<P>
   A: Go right to Pampell's Drugstore in Kerrville, the home of the
best Kinky Friedman memorabilia. After that, go to the best
restaurant in the world, Del Norte, for breakfast or lunch. You'll
see real Americans eating there. Del Norte's got the demographics.
There are lots of great places to eat in Kerrville. Joe's Jefferson
Street Cafe. The Cowboy Steak House. La Fours Seafood. You'd think
they couldn't have good seafood in Kerrville, but they can. Plus,
La Fours has a picture of Jesus on the wall that looks just like
Andy Gibb.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
