<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Oct. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall: The House debates and
then will vote on whether to open an inquiry into the impeachment
of President Clinton. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VOTE (Washington) _ A look at the vote and whether in
confirms or refutes the charges of partisanship. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: The conventional
Washington wisdom is that this will go on for a time and then be
shut down when Clinton and the Republicans cut a deal. But is this
Pandora's box, where everything but hope has escaped? By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCENE (Washington) _ The scene on the Hill and
elsewhere. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY (Washington) _ The president's day: speaking on
Medicare, etc. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   Others as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Congressional progress on getting
appropriation bills passed. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CONFIRM (Washington) _ The Senate is preparing to leave
town without acting on dozens of nominees approved by its
committees. The reasons range from dislike of homosexuals to
opposition to the FDA's approval of RU-486, the birth control pill.
It's so late in the session that since any senator can block a
nomination for four days, no one with significant opposition can
get through. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-SENATE (Dateline to kum, Ohio) _ Gov. George Voinovich and
Cuyahoga County Commissioner Mary Boyle are battling it out for
Sen. John Glenn's old seat; Voinovich is the favorite. By Jonathan
P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GOV-POLL (New York) _ How the New York candidates for
governor fare in the lastest N.Y. Times/CBS News poll. By Richard
Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Currency and Markets &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CURRENCY (New York) _ The dollar continues to plunge but then
comes back. It was trading around 111 yen Thursday morning but by
midday stood at 119.50 yen, down from 120.25 yen Wednesday
afternoon. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CURRENCY-IMPACT (Undated) _ What the dollar's fall means to the
economy, already pressured by the stock market's sharp decline. By
Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks fall sharply. At 1:40 p.m., the
industrial average was down 217 points and the Nasdaq index was off
90. Elsewhere, prices fell 5.8 percent in Tokyo and rose 2.5
percent in Hong Kong. They fell 5 percent in Frankfurt, 3.2 percent
in London, 3.4 percent in Brazil and 1.8 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was down 27/32 point, with the
yield at 4.91 percent. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-OUTLOOK (New York) _ Citigroup, formed today by the
merger of Travelers and Citicorp, says losses in global markets are
expected to drive down earnings in the third quarter by 67 percent.
It cites a net loss of about $325 million from Salomon Smith Barney
and a loss of about $130 million from Citicorp's global banking
operations.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND (New York) _ Developments in the bailout of Long-Term
Capital Management, the failing hedge fund. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Financial &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLEAR-JACOR (Dallas) _ Clear Channel buys Jacor for $3.17
billion, plus $1.23 billion in debt assumption. By Allen R.
Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   ZIFF-CUTBACK (New York) _ Ziff-Davis will reduce costs and cut
10 percent of its labor force, as it issues a new class of shares
to track its Internet business, ZDNet. The company will discontinue
three of its publications, Internet Business, Equip and Windows
Pro, and will take a charge of $50 million to $60 million in the
fourth quarter as a result. It expects to sell 20 percent of the
ZDNet shares to the public, while retaining the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ULTRAMAR-PHILLIPS (Undated) _ Ultramar Diamond Shamrock and
Phillips Petroleum combine their North American gas station and
refining units into a joint venture to cut costs in the
increasingly competitive fuel sales business. They will cut 1,000
jobs. Phillips is to receive $800 million from the venture company,
in which Ultramar will hold a 55 percent stake. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DEBT (Mexico City) _ Mexico's highest court, ruling in
favor of the nation's banks, decides that it is legal to charge
interest on the accrued interest on past-due loans. The question
had pitted the nation's crisis-weary banks against millions of
citizens unable to pay off their debts when interest rates
skyrocketed following the peso's collapse in 1994. By Julia
Preston.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RATES (London) _ The Bank of England cuts its benchmark
interest rate one-quarter percentage point, to 7.25 percent, in an
effort to counter the impact of falling stock prices and weakening
domestic demand. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   CBS-REORG (New York) _ CBS announces reorganization. By Lawrie
Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
