<HEADER>
A6287 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-08 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE ABOUT YOU-KNOW-WHAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am sick, sick, sick of Monicagate. I'm tired of hearing about
it. I'm tired of reading about it. I'm tired of talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to read another page of testimony, see another
segment of video, or hear the results of one more poll. Congress
needs to do whatever they're going to do about it and let's move
on.
</P>
<P>
   As a United States citizen, I am embarrassed when the president
of the greatest country on Earth travels overseas and reporters
there inquire about this scandal instead of the state of foreign
relations. As a taxpayer, I am outraged by the amount of time and
money that has been spent on this investigation when our tax
dollars are sorely needed elsewhere. As a parent, I am at a loss
for words when my 11-year-old wants to know ``What's so funny about
the cigar? What did he do with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Enough is enough already!
</P>
<P>
   The political pundits are amazed that so many Americans have
such a cavalier attitude about the affair. Well, we're
shell-shocked. The leaks, speculation, and pontification prior to
the release of the report were tantalizing like the first course of
a four-star meal. Then comes the main entree and it's a big, raw
slab of putrid beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good grief!'' we're screaming. ``We didn't expect all of that!
A burger or a taco would have sufficed.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple facts were enough. I actually imagined stuff worse
than what happened. Which is not to say the facts are not worthy of
condemnation. But perhaps the icy nakedness of this affair has
actually caused the public to become indifferent. There is nothing
left to intrigue or excite us. It's Celine Dion vs. Madonna before
she had the baby.
</P>
<P>
   And who wants to grow up to be president now? Nobody. That
should be a big concern. The future leaders of our country are
watching this spectacle and saying, ``Not in a million years. What
a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   And who caused this mess? The president, yessiree. I agree. But
did we have to smear the mess all over the floor, up the walls, and
onto the ceiling before we cleaned it up?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I do believe that the public has a right to know. No, I do
not know a better way to handle these things. Still, I've just got
to believe that there is a better way. We as a nation have not had
a lot of experience dealing with situations like this. I should
hope that we never become proficient at it because that would
require repetition.
</P>
<P>
   I only hope that once this is over, in whatever shape or form,
we take the time to establish a new protocol that is not based on
Watergate or Monicagate. It should be based on the assumption that
the future president of this country is watching and listening. It
should be designed to protect the status of the office even if we
must condemn the man or woman who holds the office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1884, William Sherman sent a telegram to the Republican
National Convention that said, ``I will not accept if nominated,
and will not serve if elected.'' If we're not careful, the
political conventions of the future won't have to buy confetti,
they'll merely shred all the telegrams and toss the pieces into the
air.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
