<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA STUDENTS PLAN THEIR OWN AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Students in California plan to launch a
petition drive for a state initiative that would allow race and
ethnicity to be considered in admissions to public colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   The California Associated Students Education Initiative has been
organized in response to the decline in the number of minorities
admitted to the University of California system following the Board
of Regents' decision to end racial preferences and the approval in
1996 of Proposition 209, a ballot initiative that banned
preferences in state contracting, hiring and admissions to public
colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students have a moral obligation to not allow diversity to die
silently in the night,'' said Irami Osei-Frimpong, president of the
Associated Students at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Osei-Frimpong and other students said the initiative would
reverse Proposition 209's impact on the state's higher education
system.
</P>
<P>
   While students admit that their initiative would have no impact
on the regents' 1995 decision to end affirmative action at all nine
University of California campuses, they believe it is a good first
step.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of this initiative is to enrich the overall
education that every student in the state of California deserves _
an education that goes beyond the selected text, that provides each
student in the classroom with fundamentally different perspectives
and understanding,'' said Sarah E. Kurien, a Berkeley freshman.
</P>
<P>
   The university system's regents voted to abandon race and gender
as factors in admission, a change that took effect for graduate
students last year and undergraduates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring a group called Students for Educational Opportunity
proposed an initiative that would have overturned Proposition 209,
but proponents were not successful in getting the number of
signatures necessary to put the plan on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Osei-Frimpong said the new initiative would be better organized
than the effort last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Associated student governments are staples throughout the
state, and with 106 Community Colleges, 28 Cal-State universities
and nine Universities of California, we have the most efficient
petition-gathering system in the state. All we have to do is flip
on the switch,'' Osei-Frimpong said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects the petition drive to begin in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
