<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6295 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TROOPER-SUICIDE-2ND &LR;  &UR;      10-08 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROOPER-SUICIDE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... to arrogance.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To his friends, he was fiercely loyal, dry-witted, and generous
to a fault. He did not use profanity in front of women. He showered
girlfriends with floral bouquets and candlelit meals. He enjoyed
the solitude of the cabin he built in Parsonsfield, Maine, where he
hiked and hunted and lived by the light of hurricane lamps.
</P>
<P>
   He brought cannolis from an East Boston bakery to the doorsteps
of his sister's neighbors in Maine to thank them for supporting her
through cancer treatment. Once, when the parents of a friend
stepped off their flight from Kansas, he formally greeted them at
Logan with fresh lobster rolls. ``This is tradition here,'' he told
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an intense, very complex, and gallant man,'' said Robin
Dawson, executive director of the Massachusetts Film Office, who
dated Johnson for years after a messy divorce ended his only
marriage. ``He spoke his mind. Most people gravitated towards him,
but certain personalities resented him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there was a single ignition switch for the despair that ended
in Johnson's suicide, his closest friends and family are convinced
it was thrown on Sept. 8, 1987, when Johnson was called to
investigate a report of a man trying to get through a Delta
terminal metal detector with a large amount of cash.
</P>
<P>
   When confronted by security officials, the man snatched the bag
off the conveyer belt, tossed it to an associate named ``Kevin''
and then stuck his foot in a revolving door to allow Kevin to
escape before Johnson and a Drug Enforcement Administration agent
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson later asked for identification from the agitated
man spewing profanities, he discovered he was staring at James J.
``Whitey'' Bulger of South Boston, the mobster who by then had been
working for years an an FBI informant. Johnson restrained Bulger,
pinning him to a wall. He would later tell friends that he believed
he was among the few people to ever lay hands on Whitey Bulger and
get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal-bound Bulger was accompanied by his
then-girlfriend, Teresa Stanley, who was still carrying a bag
containing $9,923. That money was confiscated. Customs was called.
Bulger and Stanley were allowed to leave. No charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What follows thereafter,'' said Cronin, then Johnson's
commanding officer at the airport, ``is a very intensive effort to
get Bill's arrest report (dealing with Bulger) from the director of
the airport and from people outside. And the assumption is that
because Whitey had been able to do this interference-free a number
of times previously and move money ... they wanted the report to
find out who the informant was.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson told friends that Bulger's brother, William M. Bulger,
then president of the state Senate, applied pressure to retrieve
Johnson's report of the incident. A spokesman for Bulger, now
president of the University of Massachusetts, declined comment.
Johnson refused to release the report, unless officials agreed to
sign a receipt for it.
</P>
<P>
   The events that followed that encounter would later be
chronicled in bulging file cabinets at Johnson's home.
</P>
<P>
   Cronin was transferred to headquarters. Johnson was called to
testify about his run-in with Bulger before a secret grand jury. A
few years later, one of Cronin's successors at Logan stripped
Johnson of his plain-clothes antidrug work and consigned him to
patrolling airport parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Johnson had a confrontation with a superior who was
angered at not being told of Johnson's decision to escort
then-Lieutenant Governor Paul Cellucci around the airport. He was
court-martialed, suspended for four days, and transferred out of
Logan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In between all this, Billy disarms a guy with a knife who was
trying to stab someone,'' Cronin said. ``They give the guy a medal
with one hand and court-martial him with another. Somehow it just
doesn't fit. Billy was far from a saint. And a half a dozen people
will tell you that Billy wasn't wrapped as tight as he should have
been, but I know a lot of people just like him and they're not damn
good street cops. And that was Billy.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Robert Bird, a State Police spokesman, dismissed
suggestions that Johnson ran afoul of his superiors for detaining
Bulger. He said Johnson was court-martialed for serious offenses _
for leaving his post and insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a paramilitary organization, respect for your superior
officers is important,'' said Bird.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, friends say, Johnson's perception that his superiors
had a vendetta against him became as harmful to him as whatever the
underlying truth was. Because without exception, those who knew him
say he tied his demise to what he termed ``a politically
problematic arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so embarrassed, humiliated, and demoralized,'' said
Jane Johnson. ``You're the trooper of the year and then you get
demoted and transferred to Andover? There are people on the State
Police who feel extremely badly that they're still part of an
organization that would let something like this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Komenda, whose ties to Johnson date to their military
duties at the now-closed Fort Devens in Ayer, said there wasn't a
day that went by that Johnson didn't talk about the Bulger case and
how it hastened his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people could accept it and drop it, but he just
couldn't,'' said Komenda, with whom Johnson lived the last weeks of
his life. ``The State Police was his life. He just couldn't accept
that. What he wanted was to be exonerated. He wanted to get back to
the airport, but he knew that couldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, after Johnson talked to his sister about making out
a will, and sent notes of farewell to his closest friends, Jane
Johnson confronted her brother, who had sent her explicit last
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Don't do anything stupid will you please. I need you
here. If you're not going to do it for anybody else, do it for me
because I need you. Please don't do this. Don't even think of this
crazy stuff.' And he said, `Jane, I could die of a heart attack
tomorrow.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Billy Johnson's heart was strong. It was his spirit that was
afflicted.
</P>
<P>
   And so after he penned his final farewell note, and walked into
a verdant field here on Sept. 25, it was left to his youngest
sister to carry out his final requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight for me, Jane,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And she will. She wants the State Police to restore her
brother's name, and acknowledge it mishandled the case against him.
</P>
<P>
   A State Police spokesman said the agency is sorry if Johnson
``died with the perception that the State Police was out to get
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Billy Johnson's hand-written instructions were carried
out to the letter last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want a Massachusetts state trooper in uniform within
100 miles of my funeral. I mean it,'' Johnson wrote. And there was
none.
</P>
<P>
   According to his wishes, his 28-car funeral procession was led
out of Revere by a local police escort. He was buried in a silver
casket with a gold case that held the ashes of his dog, Scout, who
had died earlier. There were no formal eulogies or post-funeral
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   At the grave site, on a sparkling fall morning, a minister
pronounced him a complex man who longed for simplicity, a person of
honor and pride and duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Billy would like me to keep this short,'' Komenda said,
as a six-person Green Beret honor guard snapped to attention.
``Billy was a good soldier, a good state trooper, and a good
friend. We're all going to miss him. Rest in peace, Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, fulfilling his final wish, under the canopy of a
spreading oak tree, a bugler played Taps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
