<HEADER>
A6303 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VILA-2TAKES-ART-     10-08 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VILA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECONSTRUCTING BOB VILA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Inside his comfortable study, a room laced
with rich colors, antique maps, and family photographs, Bob Vila is
working the phone, talking to his office on Cape Cod. Can a
Manhattan dinner reservation at Nobu later in the week be switched
to Le Bernadin, he asks? Done. Can the press be kept at bay during
a location scouting trip to the Virginia governor's mansion the
next day? Good. And can the filming in Massachusetts of a public
service announcement for the US Department of Housing and Urban
Development begin at 10 a.m. _ promptly _ the day after that?
Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   So much Bob Vila, so little time. It was 20 years ago that he
embarked on an unexpected career that has cast him as America's
Handyman, first as host of ``This Old House'' on PBS and now as
star and producer of the syndicated ``Bob Vila's Home Again.''
Meanwhile, he pitches tools for Sears, has had eight books
ghostwritten under his name, was the model for the hit sitcom
``Home Improvement,'' hosts regular how-to segments on CBS's ``This
Morning,'' and is the subject of an obligatory Web site where you
can, among other things, read Bob's Bio and join Bob's Fan Club.
True, there has been a bump or two along the way, but 52-year-old
Robert Joseph Vila remains the guy we think of when we think of a
do-it-yourselfer up on a stepladder in just-bought Dockers and a
Land's End shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name another infotainer who has a higher name recognition
factor,'' challenges Michael Ferrone, who has been Vila's
co-executive producer and close friend for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Martha Stewart and Julia Child certainly come to mind.
Which is fitting, because Vila turns out to be a lot closer to
these two doyennes of style than to that fellow we imagine atop
that ladder. True, Robert Ryley, who does much of the carpentry
work on ``Bob Vila's Home Again,'' says the host of the show can
glaze a mean windowpane if necessary. But Vila holds neither a
trade union card nor a contractor's license. His hands are not
calloused. His library is not filled with how-to books (not even
his own), but with tomes on art, architecture, and food. And while
he sometimes drives a Chevrolet pickup truck _ one of the sponsors
of his show _ he's more likely to be found behind the wheel of his
Mercedes 500.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, home improvement simply isn't Bob Vila's idea
of fun. ``Fixing things is not the way he wants to spend his
time,'' says his wife, Harvard Business School senior lecturer
Diana Barrett. ``He's just not a fix-it person,'' she adds,
recalling that when her husband recently discovered a broken light
socket in their home, he simply told her to call an electrician.
Vila himself sheepishly admits that he was supposed to replace a
clothes hook for 13-year-old Susannah, one of his and Barrett's
three children, this past summer and never got around to it. And
his home ``workshop'' _ yes, it is well-stocked with Sears
Craftsman tools _ serves mainly as a storage area for artwork
created by their 22-year-old son, Christopher, a student at The
School of the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not,'' Vila concedes, ``have an active woodworking
life.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd really rather talk about, say, food, which he did one
recent morning when his wife mentioned another broken light and he
quickly changed the subject to herbed chicken. He spends more time
in his wine cellar than in that mostly abandoned workshop. He talks
glowingly about shopping during the afternoon for something _
Chilean sea bass, for example _ that he and Barrett can cook
together that night, and she says he likes almost nothing better
than to stand back and admire his own well-set table. Hello, Julia.
Hello, Martha.
</P>
<P>
   Vila's desire for the good life can be seen at any of the four
upscale homes he and his family enjoy. In addition to the 1897
shingle-style, mulberry-colored manse here in the leafy
neighborhood of Bill Weld and Yo-Yo Ma, there is also a
neo-Victorian waterfront compound in the gated community of Oyster
Harbors on Cape Cod; a 30-year-old home in Chilmark, on Martha's
Vineyard; and a 1920s Mediterranean-style home in his native
Florida, on the Gulf Coast in Boca Grande. A dedicated boater, Vila
this year took delivery of a 36-foot cabin cruiser designed and
built by sailmeister Ted Hood. Each year he hosts a tarpon-fishing
trip in Florida, an annual outing on which the invitees are
``usually agents and lawyers'' rather than the hammer-and-saw set.
Says Vila's old friend Rikk Larsen, a local software executive:
``What I like about him is that he acknowledges that he enjoys the
trappings of success.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Firestorms and furniture
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Barrett, the reasons for what she calls her husband's
``interest in the process of living in as high a quality way as
possible'' is a reaction to his decidedly middle-class roots as the
son of Cuban immigrants. He lives in a kind of high Victorian
style, surrounding himself with lots of objet d'art such as
antiques, paintings, and old books. ``Bob came from very little, so
enjoys having stuff,'' his wife says. ``Really good stuff. He loves
being able to buy a really beautiful thing and bring it home. And
then he just can't leave it alone. He has to touch it, or move it
around.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Vila has become rich, he is not idly rich. Highly
organized and meticulous _ have you ever seen a hairdo or a beard
so perfectly groomed? _ he remains the micromanager of all he
surveys despite his contention that ``I think I've gotten better at
not having to control every detail of my life.'' He's got enough
energy to bike 50 to 75 miles a dozen or so times each summer. If
the pace slackens during tapings of ``Bob Vila's Home Again'' (and
the boss does his best to make sure it doesn't), he's likely to put
a cell phone to his ear or take a quick meeting with Ferrone, his
co-producer. His travel schedule, which includes endless
glad-handing on behalf of Sears, has him crisscrossing the country
in an assortment of commercial and private jets. One recent
weekend: Cape Cod to Illinois to Michigan to Minnesota to Colorado,
back to Illinois, back to the Cape.
</P>
<P>
   He's in motion even when there doesn't seem to be a reason to
be. ``Whenever he gets tense and nervous,'' his wife says, ``he
moves the furniture around.''
</P>
<P>
   He can be prickly. During TV tapings in particular, even on good
days, he feels the tension. He repeatedly checks his watch. Are we
ready to start? Why not? Are we running late? Why? ``I probably can
be a hard person to work for,'' he concedes. ``I'm easily
frustrated if things that have been committed to fall apart. If an
architect says something will be done and it isn't, I get
frustrated. I admire punctuality. People not keeping to timetables
makes me unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Full-blown firestorms are reportedly rare. ``I've seen him lose
it only about three times,'' says Sarah Beasley, who's worked on
Vila's show since its inception nine years ago and is now its
co-producer. But there's enough of an edge to Vila when he shoots
his show that his wife says she does her best to avoid visiting the
set. ``He's not the same person there as he is at home,'' she says.
``He's much softer, much more interactive when he's at home.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6306 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VILA-ART-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     10-08 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VILA-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... he's at home.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But whether he's one person or two, he clearly enjoys being Bob
Vila. ``I've never known anyone to be as happy with stardom or
recognition as Bob,'' says Dick Holden, who was the camera operator
on ``This Old House'' for several years. Vila welcomes the
horn-honkers, the hand-shakers, and the folks who thrust 2-by-4s in
his face for autographs. He's even pleased and amused that so many
strangers feel compelled to tell him who he is (``Hey! You're Bob
Vila!''). And such attention isn't something that's merely
tolerated. ``It's important to him,'' says Beasley, and her boss
concurs: ``It's ego-gratifying. I mean, they're there to tell me
that they like me, not that I'm a dumb son-of-a-bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   His is such an unlikely tale, after all. Raised primarily in
Miami, he switched from architecture to journalism at the
University of Florida because he couldn't cut the math. He worked
in the Peace Corps in Panama (He still calls himself ``a
child-of-the-'60s Kennedy Democrat.''), protested against the war
in Vietnam, worked in Germany as a freelance editor and later a
stagehand, and came to Boston to study architecture again.
</P>
<P>
   When he realized there was more money in real estate development
and contracting, he slipped into the renovation business. One of
his earliest employers was Diana Barrett, a divorcee who was
studying at the Harvard Business School and had chosen her latest
surname from a local telephone book. Like Vila, she is Hispanic.
(Her father was Colombian, her mother Costa Rican.) Unlike her
husband, she comes from a monied family. The buzz has always been
that she became Vila's financial angel as well as his wife, but she
demurs. ``I've never inherited money,'' she says. For their first
date, Vila built her a fire, put down a rug, and served up a picnic
_ all in a Back Bay building that he was renovating for her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A sideline takes off
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the the late 1970s, Vila and Barrett, now spouses and
business partners, renovated their Victorian Italianate home in
Newton. It became the subject of both a newspaper and a magazine
article, as well as the focus of a WGBH-TV (Ch.2) pilot for a
series about local homes that had been done over. When the show
metamorphosed into a step-by-step home improvement program,
producer Russell Morash thought Vila might make a good host. &UR;  &LR; ``He
(Vila) was a full-grown talent from the first moment,'' recalls
Holden, the cameraman. ``He wasn't at a loss for words, and he had
a comfort level in front of the camera that a lot of people never
achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Vila saw the show as a sideline that might
publicize his business. The rest is television history: how ``This
Old House,'' which eventually dealt with the renovations of several
homes, went from an unknown local production to a national PBS hit,
taking Vila, who initially earned $250 per show, along with it.
When it debuted, some of the fledgling hosts's friends threw him a
party. It's theme: ``Bobby Goes to Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Vila, whose previous television experience consisted of an
appearance in a Peace Corps training video, was loved by the camera
and returned the favor. Holden recalls him as ``a fully grown
talent from the first minute.'' As time passed, the rising star saw
the possibilities of expanding his franchise. He began endorsing
products such as Time-Life Books and Rickel Home Centers. In 1989,
when WGBH asked him to end these lucrative outside deals because
they conflicted with the show's underwriters, he refused and was
fired. (``He moved the furniture about 10 times when that
happened,'' Barrett remembers.) The break-up was bitter, and it
remains so to this day. Vila won't discuss it, except to say, ``A
lot of people didn't behave in a way I expected them to behave.''
Morash, still producer of ``This Old House,'' offers even less: ``I
will talk about anything but Bob Vila.''
</P>
<P>
   (Vila's carpenter/sidekick on ``This Old House'' was Norm Abram,
who lives in Carlisle and still appears on the PBS show. Even
today, many people think of Vila and Abram as a team, and strangers
often ask each about the other. Not only haven't they spoken in 10
years, but they were never close in the first place. ``He was
pretty glitzy, pretty high-end,'' Abram says of Vila. ``I'm not.'')
</P>
<P>
   Picking himself up after his dismissal, Vila created his own
home renovation show and later a small company to produce it under
contract with Sears. ``Bob Vila's Home Again'' is currently seen in
about 180 markets, according to Ferrone, and it is as fast-paced as
its star. Vila usually works without a script, eschews retakes, and
literally runs the show. (Director Chris Gilbert describes his own
role as ``subtle massaging.'') The host interviews heating
contractors here, visits a lighting plant there, and is Bob Vila
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vila goes `Home Again'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is sometimes difficult to tell where Vila leaves off
and his show begins. This is true in no small part because the
program, which often makes use of product discounts and donations,
frequently features the renovation or construction of Vila
properties. Some of these _ a Malibu beach house, for example, or a
Martha's Vineyard Victorian _ were bought prior to restoration and
then sold afterward, according to Vila.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Bob Vila's Home Again'' has also put up a greenhouse
addition on the Vila Cape Cod home, and has remodeled the kitchen
in the Miami house of Vila's sister, Teresa Lopez. Most notably,
the show featured the complete renovation and restoration of Vila's
Cambridge house, which was purchased for $1.05 million in 1996 and
is now valued by the city, post-makeover, at $1.8 million. And the
Boston Leather District condo that is being featured on the show
this season was purchased in May by young Christopher Vila as an
empty shell for $300,000. His father says that the spiffy interior
being added on the show is expected to cost in excess of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Vila was disappointed to learn that the
Hearst Magazines Division was stopping the presses on Bob Vila's
American Home, a magazine based on his show, after just five
issues. But besides his WGBH sacking, this failure represents the
only visible bump in what has otherwise been a smooth 20-year ride.
``I'm Bob Vila and it's good to have you home again,'' Vila
declares with a small and satisfied smile at the end of every show.
Maybe he should simply say, ``I'm Bob Vila and it's good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
