<HEADER>
A6311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-COGSWELLS-BOS &LR;      10-08 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-COGSWELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHRINE TO NEW ENGLAND FOLK ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESSEX, Mass. _ At the end of a country lane here the land
dramatically opens up to reveal a sprawling 18th-century persimmon
farmhouse and adjacent red barn. Beyond these colorful buildings,
lush open fields slope down to fog-embraced marshlands and the
Essex River. Nothing from the 20th century intrudes on these
picturesque 135 acres. Only the music of songbirds and a greeting
from a horse disrupt the silence.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the house, the rooms are filled with American folk art.
Every surface in the eight rooms is covered with 18th- and
19th-century paintings, rugs, pottery, Shaker boxes, decoys,
weathervanes, painted furniture, and ostrich eggs. There are more
than 2,000 objects in all. And they remain exactly where the
owners, who named the property Cogswell's Grant, placed them.
</P>
<P>
   The owners were Nina and Bertram K. Little, who over six decades
assembled one of the world's finest collections of American
decorative arts, or folk art. What is now on view for the public in
the Little's unheated former summer home is the largest collection
of what Nina called ``country arts'' in the setting where it was
originally assembled.
</P>
<P>
   This setting was first and foremost a home _ a retreat and
working farm where the Littles brought their three children during
the summer months. They named it Cogswell's Grant because the land
was once part of a 1636 grant from the town of Ipswich to settler
Jonathan Cogswell. Although every piece of furniture, every
painting, every plate was carefully selected and documented by the
Littles, nothing was off-limits to the children and their friends,
no room was set aside as a showcase for their collection. Every
room _ even the boys' bedrooms _ was part of their collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a wonderful time out there in the summers because it
was a working farm,'' says the Littles' son, Dr. John (Jack)
Little, chairman of the cancer cell biology department of the
Graduate School of Public Health at Harvard University. ``There
were cows and horses, pigs and geese, and hundreds of chickens.
We'd advertise in the Gloucester paper and people would come over
for pick-your-own strawberries and raspberries, corn and
potatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that, as a kid, he didn't realize he was living in the
midst of a prized collection. His parents never conveyed this fact
to their children, who thought they were merely living with the
old-fashioned things their parents enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any `Oh, don't sit on that chair,''' says
Jack, who didn't realize the value of his parents' collection until
he was in his early 20s. ``I don't remember them child-proofing
things. Nor do I remember breaking anything. Wait, I do remember
breaking one of the slats on the sofa in the sitting room. And I do
remember them telling us not to lean back in chairs. But there was
never any feeling of being restrained, and my brother and I were
pretty rambunctious kids.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the house was always full of life and his parents
entertained often, usually hosting antiques collectors and dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents were very warm people so the house was full of
warmth,'' says Jack, who collects antique radios. ``There was
absolutely no sense of a museum atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the only negative response to the collection came from
his son, Fred, when he was 2 years old. He had been put to bed in
his crib in an upstairs bedroom where five large portraits of the
McArthur family from Limington, Maine, hang.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard Fred crying one evening, which was unusual,'' says
Jack. ``So my wife went upstairs and found Fred standing up in his
crib crying and pointing to the pictures. Here was this little kid
with all these huge people staring at him. He was frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   As he should have been. For the McArthurs loom large around the
room, and no one is smiling _ even the three children have the same
dour, watchful, and overburdened look on their faces as their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The only intrusion of modernity in the house is downstairs in
the sitting room _ a small television set, a flashlight, and an
alarm clock. Again, these lay exactly where they were left by the
Littles, who spent their winters in their large home in Brookline.
After their deaths a few months apart in 1993, Nina at age 90 and
Bert at 94, the contents of that antique-filled city home were sold
at Sotheby's for $12.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   No words can describe the rich atmosphere that pervades every
room of their country house in Essex. The Littles decorated the
house to delight the eye rather than for historic accuracy. They
made no attempt to create accurate period rooms. What they did look
for were pieces with documentation and artisans who were local or
lived in New England. And they were adamant that a domestic setting
was the best way to display their collection; both during their
lives and after their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   They've succeeded. They created an enduring image of our rural
New England past that is now available for public consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``What truly makes this collection special is that it remains in
its original environment,'' says Peter Gittleman, director of
education at the Society for the Preservation of New England
Antiquities, which was given the house and its contents by the
Littles. ``Also, the Littles had a real appreciation for every
individual object. They loved the history, the tradition, and the
aesthetic beauty of each piece, and they organized them in a very
compelling way. The house doesn't look like an antiques shop. They
created vignettes for drama and to highlight a specific object.''
</P>
<P>
   The Littles, he says, began collecting when people were trying
to restore pieces to the way they were originally created. But the
Littles respected the entire history of a piece, including any and
all 19th-century additions.
</P>
<P>
   The Littles, who were married in 1925, began collecting after
they bought a small, unrestored cottage in Hudson, where they
escaped on weekends from their tiny Cambridge apartment, according
to Debby Griffith, a Cogswell's Grant guide. The cottage had no
plumbing, heat, or electricity, but the couple enjoyed fantasizing
that they were living in the early 1800s. When the couple started
to look for furnishings, Bert's cousin, who had a farmhouse nearby
filled with country antiques, took the newlyweds to local auctions
and shops.
</P>
<P>
   And their love affair with ``country arts'' began.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they bought Cogswell's Grant in 1937, they were
serious collectors. And Nina had become a serious detective. She
kept meticulous notes on every piece in the house, no matter how
small, and when information was not readily available, she pored
through town records, studied account books, and explored church
yards. With the passing of years, she became a well-respected
self-taught scholar, writing six books and more than 100 articles
for antiques magazines. More important, she gave names and
histories to anonymous New England painters, sculptors, and
craftsmen. Most folk art was fashioned by small-town artisans with
no formal training in the arts, and their works were usually
utilitarian in nature. Her husband, who was director of SPNEA from
1947 to 1979, was Nina's able collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   Together the couple helped make folk art a subject of serious
academic study. Although many critics dismissed the couple as
buyers of junk, today their collection is worth a small fortune and
treats visitors to a window into the everyday life of rural New
England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
