<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING AND ART A GLORIOUS COMBINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gardening is an art and a science, and practitioners usually
lean to one or the other focus. I enjoy the science of it, but I am
drawn, like a moth to flame, to the art.
</P>
<P>
   I say this because I was especially bad at art in school. I
could not draw (still can't), and theory and appreciation eluded me
into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   But the art of gardening cannot be separated and excised. This
is an endeavor that encompasses and interprets the other arts as
well as is informed by and structured through art.
</P>
<P>
   To enjoy the crowded bounty of a perennial border or a starkly
compelling Japanese garden is to appreciate art. To attempt beauty
and balance and meaning in your own garden is to undertake art.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Horticultural Society knows how deeply and
broadly the two are tied. The theme of its next New England Spring
Flower Show is ``Artistry in the Garden,'' and according to Mary
Mooney, show director, there was a fear that the theme might be too
narrow: ``We envisioned four Monet water lily gardens,'' she said,
but when exhibit proposals came in, ``some saw art in the design,
and some in the sculpture, and working with symphony and music in
the garden.'' Proposals were made for literary motifs,
interpretation of art, gardening artistry, and even a Frank Lloyd
Wright garden.
</P>
<P>
   Art and gardening are chicken-and-egg entwined. Early art
depicting gardens gives us a history, if not practical inspiration,
of what was being grown and how. Later art can stand not only as
art, but instruction in color and layout, even exact plantings.
Artists and gardeners, you see, go back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey Repton was a talented English painter who became the
preeminent landscaper following Lancelot ``Capability'' Brown in
the late 18th and early 19th centuries. Repton produced
before-and-after watercolors for his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Also applying art in aid of gardening was the great garden
designer Gertrude Jekyll, a painter whose eyes failed her. Her art
made her an outstanding colorist and led her to strive for unity in
style between house and garden.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous artist-gardener was Impressionist Claude Monet,
who built a garden at Giverny, France, that was his subject as he
explored color and light. Monet collected Japanese wood blocks, and
these inspired the graceful wisteria-covered wood bridge he built
to span the two-acre lily pond he established. In turn, this bridge
and pond became the focus for Monet's art.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Susan Strouse, a painter and sculptor who had a
studio in Waltham, Mass. for eight years and then turned to
gardening. ``I got to the point in my life where everything was
fragmented, so I said, `What do I like to do?''' She likes to be
creative, and she likes to be outside, so now she operates Artful
Gardens, a garden design and installation company based in Jamaica
Plain. ``She also taught an ``Artist in the Garden'' class at the
Arnold Arboretum that I attended this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Strouse took two basic tacks: Paintings can teach garden design,
study them to see through the artists' eyes; and principles of art
can be applied to design.
</P>
<P>
   We learn to look at art, and we learn that contrasting shapes
accentuate form (yuccas and coreopsis, say, or grasses and
elephant's ears). Texture involved shape (ferny astilbe leaves vs.
linear iris blades) and surface (smooth holly leaves vs. hairy
lamb's ears).
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the color wheel, in which the primary colors
red, yellow and blue are separated by the secondary colors of
orange, green and violet. Colors opposite one another on the wheel
provide the most contrast, adjacent colors produce harmony. White
is loud, green is calming, gray is a blender.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through life, I am finally learning art theory and
appreciation. I look at gardens as if they were paintings, I look
at garden paintings as gardens, and I look increasingly at
paintings and sculptures as if they were art and as if I enjoyed
them immensely.
</P>
<P>
   Monet, by the way, had five assistant gardeners. Now that is
inspiring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
