<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN OF DIVORCE NEED LICENSE TO MAKE BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the strongest memories Boston University senior Jamie
Levine has of the early days of her parents' separation is the ride
back to her mother's after a weekend with her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about a 15-minute drive. I wouldn't look at him the
whole way, I'd look out the window,'' says Jamie, who was 6 at the
time. ``If I was crying, he'd tell me not to. He'd say, `I hate it
when you cry, Jamie.' Sometimes I would wait to cry until I got to
my mom's. I'd sit at the bottom of the stairs and wail for half an
hour. Then I'd be OK until the next weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   For children of divorce, going from one house to the other and
back again is intensely emotional. The best rule of thumb for
parents at both ends is not to give it short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the moment when the sense of loss children carry with
them all the time comes to a head,'' says psychologist Sam Osherson
of Cambridge, Mass. ``They see the family that was and long to have
it back. They see the reality of what is, and feel torn in two.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say children who fare best have parents who treat
each other with respect, recognize how important the other parent
is in their children's lives, and send them off expressing
confidence in the other parent's ability to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between saying, `Enjoy your time with
your dad!' and `I hope your father dresses you properly!''' says
psychologist Sharon Gordetsky. The first goodbye gives a child
permission to have a relationship without fear of losing your love;
the second makes her worry: ``Mom doesn't think I'm going to be
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless you have reason to think your child is in danger,
containing your negative feelings is the single best way to help
her, says San Francisco family therapist and divorce mediator
Isolina Ricci. Her book, ``Mom's House, Dad's House, Second
Edition'' (Fireside, 1997) is a must-read for divorced parents.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel angry, stifle it, says Ricci. If you need to cry,
wait until later; otherwise, she'll think she should stay. If your
child cries, be sympathetic but firm: ``I know it's hard living in
two places. This is your time to be with your dad. I'll miss you,
too, but I want you to enjoy this time. That would make me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even preschoolers pick up on nuances like not inviting the
parent in when it's raining or handing over the backpack with a
grunt instead of hello. ``This makes her think it's her job to fix
things,'' says Gordetsky, who is president of the Massachusetts
Psychological Association.
</P>
<P>
   While you want to be respectful and civil, you don't want to be
overly friendly; that can fuel reunification fantasies, even if one
of you has remarried.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10-year-old who insists you walk her to the car instead of
waving goodbye at the door is trying to recapture his family,''
says Gordetsky. During a quiet moment together (not at a
transition), spell things out: ``Do you ever think your dad and I
might get married again? I want you to know that just because we
can be nice to each other doesn't mean we could love each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a grip on your feelings isn't just for your child.
Osherson tells of a father whose preschooler tracked mud through
his house minutes before she was leaving for her mother's. He was
furious. ``The anger and loss and loneliness bubbled up at that
moment,'' says Osherson.
</P>
<P>
   The father was sick at heart for yelling at his daughter as he
was saying goodbye, but something good came out of it: The mud
became a literal reminder for him that parting is a time of
vulnerability not just for a child but for a parent, too, says
Osherson, who adds that fathers have a harder time acknowledging
this than mothers. Osherson is author of ``Wrestling With Love, How
Men Struggle With Intimacy'' (Ballantine).
</P>
<P>
   For some parents, the hardest moment is seeing your children
happy to reunite with someone who makes you so angry. ``It's not
that they are glad to be done with you or are passing judgment on
you or love you less,'' says Osherson. ``It's better for your
children to have a relationship with both parents. Be happy for
that, even if the other parent is late with child support.''
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, you have two transitions to deal with. Your
children have four, and each one has unique characteristics:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Parting. &LR;  Some children worry you'll be glad she's gone,
others worry you'll be lonely. Dispell both fears by being
explicit: ``I'll miss you, but I have things planned. I want you to
have fun, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Make preparations thoughtful but not dramatic: ``Is there
anything special you want to take to your mom's? Anything you want
to share with her?''
</P>
<P>
   If a child of any age is clingy or tearful, be sympathetic but
firm: ``I know it's hard to leave, but you always spend weekends
with your dad.'' Disengage once the other parent arrives, almost as
if you're off the clock, says child psychologist Anthony E. Wolf,
author of ``Why Did You Have to Get a Divorce? And When Can I Get a
Hamster?'' (Noonday, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   To the arriving parent, Wolf's advice is to be patient: ``Don't
cajole the child into leaving. Wait in a friendly, non-hostile
way.'' Neither parent should pick up a child who doesn't want to go
and put him in the car, he says. A child 9 or older who doesn't
want to go may be unhappy about leaving friends (see below) or
feeling disloyal about leaving you. He needs your literal
permission: ``I'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Reuniting. &LR;  Children can feel awkward and shy at first,
whether it's been a long or short time since they last saw you.
Establishing a routine can ease the transition, says child
psychologist Robin Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   Ask them how they want the first 15 minutes to go. Keep in mind,
too, that this transition can take longer than the literal pick up,
indeed, sometimes several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Older children may intially be hostile. This could be about the
divorce, especially in the beginning, but with preteens, it's more
likely about being taken away from friends or feeling like a fifth
wheel because of a new relationship you're in.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf tells parents with weekend custody to go out of the way to
include friends at your house and to accommodate an older child's
social life. Your new relationship may need to be put on hold while
you are with your children. Tell them, ``This weekend is just for
us; we're not including any of my friends,'' and see if the
transition, perhaps the entire time, goes easier.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Parting. &LR;  ``A child leaving a parent who doesn't have primary
custody is feeling a terrible loss at parting. The more reassuring
you can be about next time, the easier it will be,'' says Deutsch,
who is with the Child and Law project at Massachusetts General
Hospital. Validate his sadness in a matter-of-fact way: ``It makes
me sad, too, but it helps to know I'll see you next Friday.'' Allow
him his tears, but shield him from yours.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Reuniting. &LR;  The reunion with the primary custodial parent can
be so problematic that Wolf calls it the Sunday night phenomenon.
He says children tend to fall apart when they walk back into their
primary house: Preschoolers and young school-age children act out,
preteens shut themselves in their rooms, siblings who don't usually
fight, fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of them as having kept themselves together all weekend;
now they feel safe enough to fall apart,'' he says, quickly adding:
``It does not mean something went wrong or that your child is
depressed.'' His advice is to give a child the room he needs to
decompress, even if it takes an hour or two.
</P>
<P>
   When he seems ready, ask a few general questions, enough to show
you care _ ``Did you have a nice time?'' _ but nothing probing:
``What time did you go to bed? What did you eat?'' To a young
child, those questions raise the issue of safety about the other
parent; to the older child, they're invasive.
</P>
<P>
   If children have a litany of complaints about their other home,
it may be because they think that's what you want to hear. ``They
see it as a loyalty issue,'' says Wolf. ``If they like it there,
they're disloyal to you.'' Again, be explicit: ``It's OK to like it
there.'' If complaints keep up, check out anything that sounds
unsafe or abusive; otherwise be sympathetic _ ``It's hard to live
in two places'' _ but don't feel you have to do anything.
</P>
<P>
   Transitions need to evolve as children do. By the time she was
9, Jamie Levine preferred for her mother not to be in the room when
she left or returned. ``My parents were always polite to each
other, but you could see it was uncomfortable. Once I was old
enough to not need her there, it was easier,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _One way to bridge the awkwardness of the transition is to ask
your child to bring a tape or CD to play in the car.
</P>
<P>
   _Stock the kitchen with her favorite food. It tells her you were
expecting her, that she's not a bother or extraneous.
</P>
<P>
   _No matter which house your child is leaving, reassure her that
if she forgets anything, you'll get it to her.
</P>
<P>
   _Temperament affects how a child makes the transition. Tell an
anxious child, ``I will be here when you come back.''
</P>
<P>
   _Do not use pickup and drop-off to talk to your ex-spouse about
finances, custody, or other weighty subjects.
</P>
<P>
   _If you need to disengage to ease the parting, make sure the
other parent knows in advance that's what you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   _Children who have great difficulty making the transition from
one home to the other may benefit from professional help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTERTHOUGHT  &LR; _ After reading my column on babies' play, some
readers expressed concern about babies playing with wadded-up
newspaper. Toxicologist Michael Shannon of Children's Hospital in
boston responds that colored newspaper may have lead-based ink and
is not advisable for children to mouth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
