<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAINAGE TRENCH WILL KEEP STOOP WATER FREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My front stoop and steps are of one-piece concrete, which has
tilted a bit so that the stoop slopes toward the house. Water
collects, and it is an ice hazard in winter. How can I prevent
water from collecting? There's a roof, but plenty of water still
collects.
</P>
<P>
   LISA JESSICK, Easton, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The easiest way is to chip a little trench along the stoop
where it butts into the foundation. Make the trench an inch wide
and an inch or so deep, but make it slope to one side of the stoop.
It may not be easy chipping out that concrete, but the trench will
collect the water and drain it off the stoop.
</P>
<P>
   Another way is to apply a thin layer of Top and Bond, a mortar
that can be put on in thin layers, to change the slope, either to
one side of the stoop or to the steps rather than into the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A mason filled the space between the patio and the house
foundation with mortar. It works well in keeping water out of that
space, but he left a film of mortar on the concrete patio. How can
I remove it?
</P>
<P>
   FLORENCE MISITE, Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The mason should have cleaned up his sloppiness. But you can
do it without too much trouble. Buy muriatic acid in a hardware or
paint store. Mix equal parts acid and water; always pour acid into
water. Paint this solution on the mortar film. It will fizz up;
when it stops fizzing, scrub if necessary with a bristled scrub
brush, and rinse. Repeat if necessary. Wear skin and eye protection
when working with acid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a room of pine flooring and another with pine flooring
that is sanded and finished with an oil-based polyurethane varnish.
Now, the unvarnished pine floor has turned a very dark yellow in
areas exposed to the sun. The floor is extremely light, as it
should be, in protected areas. I would expect some contrast, but
not like this. What went wrong? I don't dare do another pine floor.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CHAPMAN, Scituate, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A varnished floor will darken with age, but from what you
describe, this is ridiculous. In fact, untreated wood will darken
with age. Wood will darken with age even under paint.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect it was the oil-based varnish you used. It was either
defective or just one of those things.
</P>
<P>
   The cure is drastic, because the floors have to be resanded.
Either change brands of polyurethane or apply several coats (up to
six or seven) of water-based polyurethane varnish, which will not
darken or yellow as much as standard varnish. It is not as sturdy
as oil-based varnish, hence the need for many more coats. I
personally don't like water-based varnish, but I do recognize it as
non-yellowing, or at least less yellowing.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with applying water-based varnish is that every
speck of the oil-based varnish must be removed because the two are
incompatible. It says so right on the label.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am refinishing my wide pine floors. Can I do it with a hand
sander or floor sander?
</P>
<P>
   LYNN JONES, West Townsend, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It depends on the hand sander. A little orbital sander will
not work. A hand-held belt sander will, but it is more work than
using a floor sander. This I know because I did two rooms with a
belt sander, having taken up the boards and done them at my leisure
in a neighbor's garage. Leisure, heck, it was miserable. A floor
sander will do a better job (with either, you have to sand three
times with coarse, medium, and fine paper).
</P>
<P>
   But hope springs eternal, and you might compromise by renting a
square plate sander, a floor sander but without the drum, like an
enormous orbital sander. It can be maneuvered with little effort,
and probably creates less sawdust. It might be a little tougher to
sand the low surfaces of an uneven floor, but with perseverance, it
will work, at much less effort than with either of your other
suggestions. Another good thing about the square plate sander is
that it will get into edges and corners, precluding the need for an
edge sander.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-08 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISE A VOICE FOR DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, Sprint will soon be given permission to
put up to nine antennas on a water tank in the Swampscott
neighborhood where my older daughter used to live. The matter is
now before the zoning board of appeals where last week 60 people
showed up to protest having an antenna park in the midst of so many
young families. Sprint is planning to pay Swampscott $36,000 a year
for the right to place these antennas a mere 37 feet from the
nearest residence.
</P>
<P>
   The audience was full of Harvard and MIT-educated parents
anxious to address the dangers of radio frequency radiation. Not
one of them was allowed to speak. The only topics open for
discussion were installation and placement because, by federal law,
cities and towns cannot ban these antennas for environmental or
health reasons, even if every citizen, including those serving on
town boards, is dead-set against them.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to democracy? How did this come about? Why
would Congress take away the right of local officials to act on
behalf of the citizens who elected them? I'm not much of a gambler,
but I'll bet the answer to that question involves a lot of
lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress passed the Telecommunications Act, a piece of
legislation as thick as the Manhattan phone book, filled with
complex deregulation provisions. Hidden deep within its pages, in
section 704, according to B. Blake Levitt, author of
``Electromagnetic Fields: A Consumer's Guide to the Issues and How
to Protect Ourselves,'' was what she calls ``a stealth clause''
designed to seize power from the people. Many of those who voted
for the act were unaware that this section, which had been written
by the telecom industry, would end up preventing citizens from
openly expressing legitimate health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   One can only assume that the telecom industry was afraid that if
people became aware of the many studies linking adverse human
health effects with exposure to radio frequency radiation, they'd
think twice before allowing cell towers to go up in their
neighborhoods. In studies done in nine different countries,
researchers found that those living near radio frequency
installations experienced sharp increases in cancer _ brain tumors,
lymphomas, melanomas, leukemia, and breast cancer _ a higher
incidence of infertility, and other adverse effects, including high
blood pressure, headaches, sleep disorders, and memory loss. Such
data has convinced the Environmental Protection Agency and the
Massachusetts Department of Public Health of the dangers of
wireless transmission.
</P>
<P>
   When I contacted Levitt, whose book won an award from the
American Medical Writers Association, she said she recommends that
antennas be sited at least 1,500 feet from residences, schools, and
hospitals. Marblehead's bylaws require a 500-foot setback. When I
asked her what she thought of 37 feet, she replied, ``That's
outrageous. That's criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are we so willing to be guinea pigs for technologies whose
effects we are just beginning to understand? The answer is that we
all share a modern mindset which considers it reasonable to trade
some degree of human health for profit or convenience. We are all
too willing to place the burden of proof on the victims rather than
on polluters. We've agreed to call poisons ``pollutants,'' and when
they kill, never to use the word ``murder.'' By welcoming
everything new without question, we've legitimized human exposure
to harmful substances, like pesticides, without making sure they're
safe.
</P>
<P>
   Zoning officials are afraid that a community which rejects these
towers for health reasons will soon find itself in court, facing an
industry with very deep pockets. However, the Fourth Circuit Court
of Virginia recently ruled that cities can deny a request for
permission to construct a tower because of ``the complaints of
ordinary citizens that the tower will damage the neighborhood.'' In
fact, said the judge, even when those seeking the permit have
``numerous experts touting both the necessity and the minimal
impact of towers ... which may even amount to a preponderance of
the evidence in favor of the application, the repeated and
widespread opposition'' of the citizenry may persuade a reasonable
mind to oppose the application.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecom Act, he added, should not be interpreted ``so as to
always thwart average non-expert citizens; that is, to thwart
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Congress caves in to corporate pressures, when an industry
tries to silence arguments they cannot counter, when truth is
sacrificed for profit, all that remains is citizen action. I'm
convinced this fight can be won because in Amherst, Gloucester,
Holden, Lexington, Rockport, Sandwich, and Swampscott _ in every
town in the commonwealth where concerned citizens are making their
voices heard _ democracy lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
