<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY MERGING INSTITUTIONAL BROKER GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More changes inside Gary Burkhead's World at Fidelity
Investments.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest mutual fund company said Wednesday it was
consolidating its institutional brokerage group from four business
units to one. Three of the four presidents who headed those units
are now looking for new jobs inside the company; 60 of the 1,100
employees in the group have been told they too must find new jobs
in the company or be laid off by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week the retail marketing unit, which also comes under
Burkhead's purview as head of the company's retail business, told
about 30 employees they would have to find new jobs by the end of
the year or face layoffs. Burkhead was named president of Fidelity
Personal Investments &AMP; Brokerage Group just a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity said Wednesday's consolidation was an attempt to
organize the business better and not driven by cost cutting. But
those inside and outside the company suggested there could be more
to come as Burkhead continues to remake the retail business.
Fidelity says there are no plans for a hiring freeze, despite the
slowing stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reorganization is designed to get closer to our
customers,'' said Robert Mazzarella, president of the institutional
brokerage group.
</P>
<P>
   The group had been made up for four separate units, dealing with
institutional trading, investment advisers, securities clearing,
and technology sales. The units will be consolidated into a single
business.
</P>
<P>
   Tim McKenna will continue to head the capital markets business.
But the presidents of the three other units _ Ray Marcinowski, John
Mulherin, and Mark Wildermuth _ have been told to find other jobs
in the company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reebok repricing options
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for the great stock option repricing extravaganza of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok International Ltd. of Stoughton said Wednesday it would
offer selected employees the chance to exchange their old,
way-out-of-the-money options for a smaller number of options at
current prices and a new four-year vesting schedule. Eligible
employees would be offered four new options for every five old
options under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok executives who are also directors (chief executive Paul
Fireman and executive vice president Paul Duncan) are not eligible.
The company said 3.9 million Reebok option shares would be eligible
for the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok shares, which traded at 48 9/16 a year ago, finished
Wednesday at 13 1/8. Many other companies, which use stock options
as an important carrot to retain employees, have suffered similar
stock-price nightmares. More option repricing plans are sure to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FDIC approves settlement
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directors of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Wednesday
approved a $140 million settlement with creditors of the failed
Bank of New England Corp.
</P>
<P>
   BNE's bankruptcy trustee had sued the FDIC, alleging Bank of New
England Corp.'s banking business had been insolvent before the
company issued new bonds and long before regulators seized it in
1991. The trustee represents bondholders with a total of more than
$700 million in claims.
</P>
<P>
   A US Bankruptcy Court judge still must approve the settlment
with the FDIC. Another suit against Bank of New England Corp.'s
former auditor, Ernst &AMP; Young, is pending.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; From the personnel file: NVest LP has hired Michael Gaffney as the
new chief executive of its Back Bay Advisors unit, which manages
about $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney had been chief investment officer at the New York-based
private banking group of UBS AG, the big Swiss banking company,
until he resigned in August. Gaffney succeeds the retiring Charles
Wallis at Back Bay Advisors.
</P>
