<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SINATRA-BOS &LR;      10-08 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SINATRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMILL SKETCHES SINATRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WHY SINATRA MATTERS 
By Pete Hamill 
Little, Brown, 185 pp., illustrated, $18 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the early '70s, Frank Sinatra considered writing his
memoirs with Pete Hamill. It was a shrewd choice of collaborator.
Who better than a top New York tabloid columnist to appreciate the
singer who, as Hamill puts it, ``defined the glamor of the urban
night''?
</P>
<P>
   Hamill may have been two decades Sinatra's junior, and Irish
rather than Italian. But there was an affinity between them: a
couple of tough/tender, bridge-and-tunnel guys (Sinatra from
Hoboken, Hamill from Brooklyn), high school dropouts who'd scrapped
their way to the big time.
</P>
<P>
   The project fell through _ the idea of what a candid Sinatra
autobiography might read like is almost too terrifying to
contemplate _ but Hamill came away from it with a deepened
appreciation for the man and some excellent, if scattered,
interview material.
</P>
<P>
   That material is sprinkled throughout ``Why Sinatra Matters.''
The book is a valedictory tribute _ an extended essay, really _ in
the form of a biographical sketch that follows its subject up
through the mid-'50s (struggling Sinatra interests Hamill far more
than imperial Sinatra). Along the way, Hamill also finds room for
such germane, if unexpected, material as a minitreatise on US
immigration in the early years of this century; a lambasting of
Prohibition; and a potted biography of Sinatra's favorite arranger,
Nelson Riddle.
</P>
<P>
   The book opens with a marvelous tableau: Sinatra, his friend
Jilly Rizzo, the great sportswriter Jimmy Cannon, and Hamill
arguing the relative merits of Hemingway vs. Fitzgerald as they
close up P.J. Clarke's saloon late one rainy New York night. The
evening ends when Billie Holiday starts to sing ``I'm a Fool to
Want You'' on the jukebox. That was the song Sinatra recorded at
the nadir of his career and the grimmest depths of his relationship
with Ava Gardner. ``Time to go,'' he announces, and that's that.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinatra Hamill knew was intelligent and winning: ``a reader
of books, a lover of painting and classical music and sports,
gallant with women, graceful with men.'' Hamill realizes there
could be _ and frequently was _ another Sinatra: coarse,
swaggering, intemperate. That wasn't his Sinatra, though, and that
character is barely visible in Hamill's fine little book.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we glimpse a man who's articulate and insightful _ as
when he describes his first key influence, Bing Crosby: ``The thing
about Bing was, he made you think you could do it, too. ... Every
time (he) sang, it was a duet, and you were the other singer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamill's Sinatra also has an easy way with an anecdote. ``It was
supposed to be a restaurant,'' he says of the speakeasy his mother
ran in the '20s. ``But it was really a saloon. She didn't call it
Mama Sinatra's, remember; she called it Marty O'Brien's. You're
Irish: would you go to a place called Marty O'Brien's for the
(itals)food(unitals)?''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Hamill gives as good as he gets. It's hard to
imagine bettering his description of Sinatra's looks: ``an
arrangement of knobs and planes that didn't assemble into any
conventional version of masculine handsomeness, but had an enormous
vitality; it was a face that defeated painters and seduced
photographers.''
</P>
<P>
   That final clause is a bit much, nor is it unrepresentative of
Hamill's writing here. Yet this slightly overripe quality
contributes to his book's considerable appeal. Certainly, it suits
Hamill's subject, the singer who made all his own ``the music of
the hours after midnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
