<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_A PREVENTION LESSON: DISCUSS, DON'T LECTURE  
 _BREAST CANCER RISKS: THE KNOWLEDGE GAPS  
 _A COMFORTING FINDING FOR CRANBERRY GROWERS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 A prevention lesson: Discuss, don't lecture
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is a truism that people are more likely to listen if they are
engaged in a discussion rather than subjected to a lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is evidence that the truism, put into practice, may
save lives.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence came from a study of 5,758 heterosexual,
HIV-negative men and women who visited clinics to be tested for
sexually transmitted disease in Baltimore, Denver, Newark, San
Francisco, and Long Beach, Calif. Roughly half the participants
were given one-on-one interactive counseling about how to use
condoms and take other steps to prevent sexually transmitted
diseases; the rest were given brief lectures on preventing such
illness.
</P>
<P>
   The results were dramatic: a year after their visits to the
clinic, there were 20 percent fewer new cases of gonorrhea,
syphilis, HIV, and other sexually transmitted disease in the group
that got interactive counseling, compared with those who got
lectures. The decrease was greater among adolescents and people
diagnosed with a sexually transmitted disease during their first
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Social scientists have long predicted that more interactive
counseling would yield more response from clients, but this study _
published in the current Journal of the American Medical
Association _ was the first to prove that counseling can cut the
incidence of sometimes deadly sexually transmitted diseases. The
study also made clear that counseling sessions of just 20 minutes
are as effective as those lasting 60 minutes, which should be good
news for counselors who typically are pressed for time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message we'd like to get across is that if we did a better
job of talking to people we could have a pretty dramatic effect
with disease,'' said Dr. Mary L. Kamb, a medical epidemiologist at
the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta and lead author of the
JAMA article.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Breast cancer risks: The knowledge gaps
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Education also is paying off with breast cancer, although not as
much as it could, a national survey has found.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of women 40 and older, released this week, found that
after years of intensive focus on the illness, American women worry
more about breast cancer than about heart disease, osteoporosis,
and other common ailments. While that is encouraging, the poll also
had bad news: Most women still do not know many of the key risk
factors for the disease, and most underestimate their own risk.
</P>
<P>
   While all women are at risk of developing breast cancer, the
survey found that one in 10 say they have no risk and 67 percent
say they face only a low to moderate risk.
</P>
<P>
   What puts a woman at risk? Fifty-six percent of those polled
stated correctly t hat family history is a critical factor. But
only 8 percent cited age, and just 7 percent named a previous
breast cancer, both of which are key risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   Ignorance about the illness is especially worrisome among older
women, who are at special risk. Forty-eight percent of women older
than 65 said they face no or low chance of developing breast
cancer. And the older women were less likley than younger ones to
trust their doctors' judgment that they should have annual
mammograms that make it easier to prevent and treat breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discouraging part for those of us trying to tell women
what their risk about breast cancer is is that one basic fact about
breast cancer still has not been communicated: that your risk grows
as you age,'' said Joann Schellenbach, spokeswoman for the American
Cancer Society, which is one of the groups that released the survey
as part of National Breast Cancer Awareness Month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A comforting finding for cranberry growers
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known for years that cranberries help prevent
urinary tract infections. Now, according to a study sponsored by a
decidedly interested party, they know why.
</P>
<P>
   It is concentrated forms of tannins, the compounds used to make
dyes, that do the trick, according to researchers at Rutgers
University who published their findings as a letter to the editor
in the current New England Journal of Medicine. The tannins, or
proanthocyanidins, prevent E. coli bacteria that are the primary
culprits in urinary infections from attaching to cells in the
urinary tract.
</P>
<P>
   That might be good news for Ocean Spray, the Lakeville-based
cranberry juice maker that funded the research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
