<HEADLINE>
THAT'S ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do Internet users watch less TV? The jury's still out. Indeed, a
new Nielsen survey claims to show that Internetters actually spend
more time staring at the box. Hard to believe _ I've certainly cut
down on set time these past few years.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind the Nielsens. The Internet's impact on
broadcasting is far greater than mere ratings points. For one
thing, it's given us a glimpse of the long-promised nirvana,
video-on-demand. Sure, it's lousy video, but that'll change.
Meanwhile, the Internet has spawned a new kind of broadcasting
network that can offer a variety of video and audio programming
unimaginable just a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Internet users already have obtained free copies of
Real Networks Inc.'s RealPlayer or Microsoft Corp.'s Windows Media
Player, the two best programs for tapping into Internet broadcasts.
And soon you'll be able to pave your driveway with copies of
RealPlayer. You guessed it: the software will be included on those
free America Online disks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only thing keeping the Internet from overwhelming
traditional broadcast outlets is lack of bandwidth. Even today's
``high-speed'' 'Net connections aren't fast enough to transmit
sounds and images as good as those on a TV set. Those who used the
Web to watch Bill Clinton prevaricate before a grand jury only
logged on for the novelty of it, or because they didn't have a TV
set in the office.
</P>
<P>
   But in many other respects, Internet broadcasting already has
the edge. There's the on-demand part, for instance. A bunch of Web
sites still have the Clinton video available for viewing; some have
even prepared a ``greatest hits'' collection of the most
interesting parts. No waiting for a rerun or scrolling through a
videotape. Just click and view.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're sick of scandal, the amount of alternative
programming on the Web is approaching infinity. There's live news
from the BBC or CNN, play-by-play audio from college football
games, even on-line jukeboxes where you can punch up a favorite
tune.
</P>
<P>
   Serving it all up are a number of computer networks devoted to
audio and video broadcasting. They're minor players now. But they
could be worthy competitors to the media giants in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the networks you'll have never heard about is San
Diego-based InterVU Inc., 10 percent owned by NBC. InterVU serves
up Internet video, but they don't slap their own brand on the
product. Instead, they provide the videos you can get on Web sites
owned by CNN and NBC, among others. Rather than set up their own
Internet video system, traditional media companies hire InterVU to
handle the messy details.
</P>
<P>
   There is one good reason for lowly consumers to visit the
InterVU site at http://www.intervu.com. They've posted a nice
program that'll automatically download and install nine popular
multimedia players for your PC or Mac, including RealPlayer and,
for PC users, Windows Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Houston, Broadcast.com Inc. has taken aim at the
consumer market. Unlike traditional broadcast networks,
Broadcast.com doesn't produce its own programming. Instead, it
provides a central location (http://www.broadcast.com) where
consumers can connect for free to live news and sports reports, as
well as dozens of radio stations located across the country.
Broadcasters pay Broadcast.com to pump their message to Internet
users worldwide. Lonesome for your favorite Los Angeles radio
station? Broadcast.com has six L.A. stations to choose from, as
well as live police radio chatter for the truly homesick.
</P>
<P>
   So are our PCs about to become home entertainment centers?
Hardly. Instead, we'll see Internet technologies starting to appear
in our TV sets and stereos. Products like WebTV, high-speed
Internet cable modems, and next-generation set-top boxes are
pointing us toward devices that'll have audio and video quality far
better than any PC, while also having the PC's access to limitless
quantities of programming.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, that means we'll have so much more to watch and
listen to than the Big 3 networks or the local radio stations. The
same thing happened in the 1980s, when cable TV took off, and the
broadcast networks have never recovered. How will they cope when
people can watch whatever they want, whenever they want? Stay
tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
