<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE HAS BEEN BLITZING DEFENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It doesn't matter if you're Johnny Unitas or
Bart Starr or Dan Marino. When defenses blitz, it's not a
comfortable situation for a quarterback, who is expected not only
to survive the onslaught of huge bodies bent on destruction but to
make a play. In about three seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Through four games, the Patriots' Drew Bledsoe has faced
blitzing and more blitzing, a not uncommon situation for most
quarterbacks. The difference is that Bledsoe now can make something
happen even when the pressure is at its worst.
</P>
<P>
   Take the fourth-and-6 situation in the first quarter at the
Saints' 37-yard line Sunday. The Saints came with an all-out blitz.
Bledsoe knew it was coming, dropped back three steps, and hit Terry
Glenn on a short slant over the middle. First down.
</P>
<P>
   Some would say mobility is the best weapon in this situation,
but Bledsoe's strength is that he's been able to stay in the
pocket, stand tall, find his receiver, and release the ball
quickly. He's more stationary and sure. No longer are his feet
pitter-pattering in the backfield as if he's panicking.
</P>
<P>
   He's getting more like Marino, who would stave off the blitz and
destroy the opposition downfield.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bledsoe is second in the AFC in third-down passing,
when most of the blitzing occurs _ 28 for 42 (66.7 percent), a
107.8 quarterback rating.
</P>
<P>
   This has been huge for the Patriots, who will likely face the
same type of defense Sunday against the Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at our team and the number of guys we have who can
get open and catch the ball,'' said Bledsoe. ``I think some teams
are saying to themselves, `If we just let him sit back, he'll be
able to find one of those receivers, so why not go after him?' They
think if they can get some pressure on me, I'll throw it to the
wrong guys. As it is, I'll usually have a mismatch somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they come, I usually have a guy open right away. If I make
a poor play, I trust our guys to come down and make a play to break
up an interception.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe appears to be standing in the pocket longer, thanks in
part to excellent protection. When he does get hit, he doesn't
yield, befitting his status as one of the most durable quarterbacks
in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've been hit more after the throw,'' said
Bledsoe. ``It's been an average amount of hits. One big reason I've
been healthy is that our guys are smart enough up front and in the
backfield where rarely will one of those guys come in free unless
he's the guy I'm accounting for and I have to get rid of the ball.
Generally, some guy coming off a block late or some guy who doesn't
have that much momentum, you're not seeing those commercial-type
hits where the ball goes flying and my helmet is twisting off. So
I'm just taking the soft hits, which is why I've been able to stay
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   There are bigger problems this week, which begins a stretch of
three crucial games, including the Jets on ``Monday Night
Football'' Oct. 19, then the Dolphins in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will Bledsoe have to watch for Derrick Thomas, who had
six sacks in one game, but he also must beware of perhaps the best
tandem of cornerbacks in the league, James Hasty and Dale Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're facing one good corner, you usually don't throw it
to one side or the other,'' said Bledsoe. ``But these guys are both
good and talented. It's up to our guys to make the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe again will likely focus on tight end Ben Coates, who can
get open quickly over the middle, and use fullback Tony Carter as a
safety valve. The Patriots are also trying to perfect their screen
passes, which they did last week when Derrick Cullors sprung loose
for a 43-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said Coates, who caught seven passes in the 30-27 win at
New Orleans, will continue to be more involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's healthy, and we felt we hadn't been using him enough in
our offense,'' said Bledsoe. ``We felt we had other guys who could
make plays and we've been using him as protection and as a blocker
_ which is a little bit foolish when he has remarkable takent as a
receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe doesn't expect the Chiefs to show too much blitz other
than on third downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``On early downs, they don't try to trick you,'' he said. ``They
line up and show you what they're going to do. On third down, they
get a little more exotic and blitz you, but they have a lot of
confidence in the ability of their players, so they don't have the
need to disguise things and show you strange schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be quick getting rid of the ball every week. With
Derrick over there and with the talent up front, it puts more
emphaisis on me being precise and getting the ball out of my hands.
At the same time, Derrick will be lined up against Bruce
(Armstrong), and Bruce is a Pro Bowler. The last time Bruce lined
up against him (1995), Bruce handled him pretty well. I'm not going
to be able to hold on to the ball because of Derrick's talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas will move from side to side, so Zefross Moss will also
face him, but the Patriots are preparing for that and will likely
use Carter or Coates to help.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said it's imperative that the Patriots continue to be
effective on first down. Thgat means they'll continue to rely on
rookie running back Robert Edwards, who gained 97 yards on 22
carries against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can run the ball well, that helps us on first down,''
said Bledsoe. If we're second and 4 or 5, then we can play a smooth
game against an aggressive defense like that. If we're second and
10-12 every time, then it gets ugly. Robert is starting to play
like the guy we drafted. He's starting to understand things so he
can play at an instinctive level. He's starting to play with more
freedom. Our running game is still a work in progress and we're
still a passing team and always will be as long as we have the
weapons. Last week we had a lot of effective running plays, and as
time goes on, we'll get better.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to be able avoid the two-minute offense because that
will mean the Patriots are well ahead. But this year it's been
money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to score every time we go to our two-minute
offense,'' said Bledsoe. ``So the logical question is, why don't we
go to our two-minute offense more often? You also take more risks.
You're throwing the ball every down, and it's a more risky style of
offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1455EDT &QL; 
