<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-STUDIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE STUDIES SEEN CLOUDING DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the results of a welfare study began trickling in
to the Massachusetts Catholic Conference last May, the numbers
seemed startling. Rather than having plunged into poverty, a
surprising percentage former welfare recipients admitted they were
``better off'' after going off public aid.
</P>
<P>
   The study was not made public. The Conference said it decided
not to release the positive results because they were inconclusive
_ not because the organization is institutionally opposed to
welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as December approaches, and as some 7,148 Massachusetts
families prepare to be forced off the welfare rolls, analysts are
bracing for two inevitabilities: a battery of welfare reports and a
flurry of conflicting interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an explosion of information,'' said Barbara B. Blum,
director of the Research Forum on Children and Families at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just a huge number of studies on welfare now,'' said
LaDonna Pavetti a senior researcher at Mathematica Policy Research
in Washington. ``There will be lots of differences: the questions
that people are asking are different, the methods are
different...It's going to be very confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two years since the passage of the federal welfare reform
law _ which put a five-year limit on benefits, shifted federal
funds to the states and killed a program supplying aid to dependent
children _ the business of welfare-watching has expanded
drastically. And each new participant has come armed with a report.
</P>
<P>
   There is the Urban Institute, which is currently in the midst of
a $60 million, six-year study of welfare reform, and which over the
last few years has produced no less than 61 research papers on the
topic. There's the Manpower Demonstration Research Corp., which is
preparing more than 20 welfare studies nationwide, at least five of
which are in direct response to the welfare reform law.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the analyses at the local level _ the reports
from the Unitarian Universalist Service Committee, the University
of Massachusetts Center for Social Policy and the Department for
Transitional Assistance, all of which have been made public within
the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   In total, in the last two years, the Welfare Information Network
has recorded at least 158 studies nationwide evaluating
welfare-related programs. Of those, 75 came out in the last two
months _ each with its own methodology, population and point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on who is doing the study and what focus group they
are looking at,'' said State Senator James P. Jajuga, a reform
advocate. ``You can turn a study any way you want it.''
</P>
<P>
   That, analysts say, is a refrain on the rise. This week alone,
two studies of welfare participants raised suspicions of bias. The
first, a Radcliffe Public Policy Institute study of 105 women about
to go off welfare, reported that 80 percent will not be able to
hold full-time jobs because they are taking care of children with
chronic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   That result _ an obviously dire prediction for the December
cut-off date _ prompted immediate spin control by the executive
Office of Health and Human Services, whose spokesman insisted that
the system is ``working.''
</P>
<P>
   And it brought criticism from State Welfare Commissioner Claire
McIntire, who accused the researchers of having entered the project
with a bias and having designed questions with a particular result
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it is a collection of stories and not a research
study,'' McIntire said. ``I think they drew conclusions before they
did the study.''
</P>
<P>
   The prelimiary results of a second study, which was conducted by
a team of Brandeis researchers on behalf of the Massachusetts
Catholic Conference, raised questions about whether the project had
been purposely delayed in order to mask the results, even though
the researchers insisted they were simply holding the study to be
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   The study _ in which 1,000 surveys were mailed to former welfare
participants _ is scheduled to be released later this month. But in
a letter dated May 1, 1998, two of the researchers indicated the
early results were positive, saying that ``For the most part,
people considered themselves either better off or reported no
change in their lives since they left welfare rolls.''
</P>
<P>
   That interpretation, of course, is up for debate - as is the
success of welfare reform itself. For now, the steady stream of
studies will be the only constant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are multi-state, some are focusing on different
populations...There are a lot of studies. There will be lots of
differences,'' Donna Pavetti said. ``But it's going to be quite a
bit of time before we can say anything definitive about the state
of welfare reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
