<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROOPER-SUICIDE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TROOPER'S SUICIDE FOLLOWS FUTILE QUEST FOR HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ As summer faded into fall, the fever that burned
within Bill Johnson seemed to have broken.
</P>
<P>
   Although haunted by an indelible stain on his police career, he
appeared outwardly happy. Retired in Sandown, N.H., he paddled
canoes on placid mountain lakes and sipped beers with buddies at
backyard barbecues. But still, he simmered.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 50, a highly decorated Massachusetts state trooper, was
a spit-and-polish cop whose brilliant career was derailed, he
believed, by a fateful encounter with mobster-turned-informant
James ``Whitey'' Bulger at Logan International Airport in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his recent don't-worry assurances, his one-man crusade
to restore his record, reclaim his reputation and add honor to his
recent retirement, was slowly consuming him.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives say the former two-time recipient of the
State Police medal of merit, a Green Beret veteran of Vietnam who
sketched his life in regimented tones of black and white, urgently
wanted the world to know that he had been wronged for doing the
right thing.
</P>
<P>
   His struggle for redemption tired him out, associates say. And
ultimately it overtook him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' he wrote in a final goodbye to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Late in September, on an afternoon when friends had planned a
cheerful cookout for their down-on-his-luck friend, Bill Johnson,
ever meticulous, wrote out a brief note that contained thanks, the
time of day, and his intended destination.
</P>
<P>
   He walked a quarter mile to a farmer's field _ rolling green
hills framed by 200-year-old stone walls and tall trees turning
pale shades of orange _ and sat down near an oil-stained tractor.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took out his handgun and killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy wasn't a troubled soul,'' said his youngest sister,
Jane. ``The human heart can only take so much. He was driven to
this. This was his only way to get some peace. He was anything but
a coward. He fought and fought. In a strange way, he thought this
was the only way to get some honor back.''
</P>
<P>
   Honor and duty were among his family's philosophical heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of six children, Bill Johnson was born Feb. 25, 1948,
to military parents who, like much of America, celebrated the end
of World War II by coming home, settling down, and having children
that fueled the nation's great Baby Boom.
</P>
<P>
   His father, William A. Johnson Sr., was a decorated World War II
submariner. And, like the silent service he entered, he was a stoic
and distant man. His mother, the former Cornelia Doherty, was a
military nurse who was part of the historic D-Day landing on the
beaches of Normandy in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnsons lived in Revere, just outside of Boston, where Bill
Johnson grew extremely close to his gregarious mother, helping her
care for and educate his brother, Charles, seven years younger and
mentally handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   His childhood was relatively uneventful. He played hockey and
football, worked 25 hours a week after school beginning when he was
14. Despite self-described poor study habits, he won
average-to-good public school grades.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a defining moment in Johnson's young life, it came
at age 19. He was returning home from a job in a restaurant when a
car accident propelled him through a windshield, severely cutting
his face. He needed repeated plastic surgeries. His girlfriend
broke up with him. Depressed for months, he left school and
resolved to distinguish himself as his parents had.
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted in the Army in April of 1967. After basic training
at Fort Jackson, S.C., and advanced training in infantry tactics in
Georgia, he was began the first of three tours of duty in Vietnam
as a Green Beret, primarily in bases along the Cambodian and
Laotian borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever see the movie `Serpico'? Al Pacino? That was Bill,'' said
Bruce R. Cunningham, who now lives in Texas and was then Bill
Johnson's best buddy in Camp B53 in Long Thanh Province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill was a macho sonofabitch,'' said Cunningham, who drank and
raised hell with Johnson during off-duty visits to the barrooms of
Saigon. ``Everything to Bill was black and white. He had a job to
do, and he was dedicated to his beliefs. Bill was a person you
wanted on your side, and he was definitely not a person you wanted
against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a radio operator and a weapons specialist, who
participated in air strikes and did damage assessments. Asked once
about the intense stresses of combat, Johnson recalled his mortal
fear that he might stumble and fall while frantically carrying a
villager to safety as mortar shells exploded around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill liked the idea that he was doing a job that was
dangerous,'' Cunningham said. ``He was a remarkable guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Revere, Johnson's mother began erecting an in-home
shrine to her soldier-son. His family sent him care packages of
cupcakes and bottles of liquor. He sent home silk kimonos and other
keepsakes from Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a hero,'' said Jane Johnson, his sister. ``Everybody
loved him. I remember one year, my mother refused to take down the
Christmas lights on the house for months because she wanted Billy
to come home to see the house all decorated for Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson did return to Revere, he found a changed world. He
once told a counselor about being spat upon and called a ``baby
killer'' by war protesters. He felt a nostalgia for Vietnam, missed
the camaraderie of his Army friends, and grew determined to put his
Special Forces training to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy wore his heart on his sleeve. He was the American
flag and apple pie all the way,'' said Robert Cox, who entered the
State Police Academy with Johnson in November 1974 and graduated
with him nearly four months later. ``Duty and honor meant something
to Billy.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Johnson to make a name for himself as a
state trooper. He won a reputation for a street-smart cop, who
relished his undercover work against drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything isn't done by the book, my friend. When you're on
the street, if you don't know your business, you're a dead man.
Billy knew his business,'' said Michael A. ``Mickey'' Casoli, a
retired Revere police officer for whom Johnson worked when Casoli
ran Revere's vice and narcotics squad. ``He was a tremendous street
cop.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of Johnson's two ``trooper of the year,'' or medal of
merit, awards came in 1979 after he pulled an unconscious truck
driver, his clothes aflame, from a burning truck that flipped over
on Interstate 93 in Woburn. The week before he collected that
reward, Johnson was brutally beaten after a minor traffic mishap in
East Boston by a group of men wielding baseball bats.
</P>
<P>
   It was little wonder then that when Johnson won a coveted
assignment at Logan Airport _ where conditions were relatively calm
and the overtime was bountiful _ he relished it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had this famous walk at the airport _ it was kind of like a
strut,'' said Dana Cook, a Massport police officer and a close
friend who worked with Johnson at Logan. ``He would walk with his
head up constantly. He was a proud guy. If you saw him from 100
yards away, you'd know it was him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dark-haired and handsome in his dress uniform, Johnson reveled
in his work and was undisputedly good at it. Friends, relatives and
co-workers describe a man who lived by rigid rules. He did not
suffer fools gladly. He could bristle at discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could kill you in 15 different ways,'' his former boss at
Logan, Ed Cronin, now a retired State Police lieutenant colonel,
recalled fondly. ``He didn't take correction well. But once you got
through to him, it was, `Yes, sir. No, sir. Three bags full.'''
</P>
<P>
   He once completely cut off a longtime friendship after a buddy
made a derogatory comment about Johnson's beloved pet, a German
shepherd he named Scout. To his critics, he was condescending and
given to arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
