<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     10-08 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... sizable clump.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _A. ursinum is good in shade and is known as the wood garlic
because it likes damp woodlands. The flowers are pink and the
leaves look like those of lily of the valley. Unlike most alliums,
it has a strong onion smell. Deadhead it or you'll have more than
you want. The seeds have an oil that attracts ants, who drop them
about. If you are overrun, you can fight back by harvesting the
bulbs, which are tasty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FALL BLOOMERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are also fall-blooming alliums. These grow from rhizomes
instead of bulbs and must be treated as perennials.
</P>
<P>
   Because they're in active growth all season, their foliage stays
nice and crisp and doesn't turn brown like spring alliums.
Noteworthy among these types:
</P>
<P>
   _A. tuberosum is also called Chinese garlic chives. It's leaves
are edible, while its 2-foot white heads freshen up tired flower
combinations as they weave their way through the late summer
garden. Deadhead it before it goes to seed.
</P>
<P>
   _A. ramosum is Siberian garlic. Its 2-foot purple or white
flower heads bloom in September and October. It will self-seed, but
is a better behaved plant than A. tuberosum.
</P>
<P>
   _A. senescens Glaucum, or German garlic, has blue-gray foliage
twisted into a little whirlpool, like water flowing down the drain.
It has 8-inch tall pink flowers and is often used as an edging
plant, for either perennial or herb gardens.
</P>
<P>
   _A. thunbergii Ozawa is the one to look for because it's the
last to bloom. Its bright violet and red flower heads on 1-foot
stalks contrast memorably with fall foliage. This is the favorite
of Fred and Mary Ann McGourty of Hillside Gardens, a Norfolk,
Conn., nursery that specializes in underappreciated perennials. Its
purplish burgundy flowers with stamens protrude downward. ``In the
bud stage it looks like seven men trying to get out of a boat,''
said Fred McGourty, who plants it in front of euphorbia
amygdaloides rubra, which has purple foliage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BLURRING THE LINE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ornamental allium bulbs are part of the onion genus, the first
plants to be domesticated by man. With these thrifty plants, the
line blurs between the edible and the ornamental.
</P>
<P>
   Not all ornamental alliums are palatable, but they're all
edible.
</P>
<P>
   And the genus includes some of our most flavorful vegetables,
including onions and shallots (A. cepa), leeks (A. porrum) and
garlic (A. sativum).
</P>
<P>
   The line gets really blurred with chive (A. schoenoprasum),
perhaps the single food plant with the prettiest flowers. It is at
home in the ornamental, herbal, or vegetable garden. Cultivation is
remarkably easy, even in heavy clay soil. Just divide to propagate.
The standard form is violet but there are many forms selected for
particularly pretty flowers such as clover pink Forescate. Try
dotting it among chartreuse lady's mantle and magenta bloody
cranesbill geraniums, and snip some of the chive leaves for potato
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Among the tastiest ornamental alliums are rosy-flowered garlic
(A. roseum), whose roots are eaten in Mediterranean countries; A.
senescens, which is used as a vegetable in Japan; drumstick allium
(A. sphaerocephalon), which is eaten in Russia; and A. chinense and
A. tuberosum, which are important vegetables in China.
</P>
<P>
   Allium cernuum, or nodding onion, considered one of the most
beautiful rhyzomic alliums, once blanketed the prairies around
Chicago and was a Native American staple. In fact, that city may
have gotten its name from the Ojibwa words ``she-kag-ong,'' meaning
``wild onion place.'' It's easy to grow in sunny locations with
some moisture. The rose-purple, bell-shaped flowers dangle
charmingly in early summer from 1 1/2-foot stalks that lean
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   So give ornamental alliums a chance. They're easy. They're
versatile. And if you don't like them, you can always chop them up
and put them in soup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHERE TO FIND ALLIUMS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bonny's Garden Center,  &LR; 41 Bay State Road, Cambridge, Mass.
Phone: 617-547-1585. Sells the A. giganteum, Globemaster, and
Purple Sensation, plus the small alliums A. azureum, A. unifolium,
A. neapolitanum, A. sphearocephlum, A. ostrowskianum, and A.
nectaroscordum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hillside Gardens,  &LR; 515 Litchfield Road, Norfolk, CT 06058.
Sells a wide selection of uncommon rhizomic alliums and perennials
on site. Send an SASE for a plant list. Phone: 860-542-5345.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mahoney's at Arrowhead,  &LR; 115 Boston Post Rd., Wayland, Mass.,
sells 11 types of alliums. Phone: 508-358-7333.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Scheepers,  &LR; 23 Tulip Dr., Bantam, CT 06750. Many allium
bulbs. Free color catalog. Phone: 860-567-0830. Fax: 860-567-5323.
Web: www.johnscheepers.com; e-mail: catalog(at)johnscheepers.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; North American Rock Garden Society,  &LR; P.O. Box 67, Milwood, NY
10546-0067. Offers seeds of 150 alliums to members. Web:
mommens(AT)ibm.net; e-mail: www.nargs.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Siskiyou Rare Plant Nursery,  &LR; 2825 Cummings Road, Medford, OR
97501. Sells many rare alliums, especially those for rock gardens.
Phone: 541-772-6846; color catalog $3 with spring and fall
