A6391 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-PARTNERS-HNS &LR;      10-08 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED WINS REPRIEVE FROM SAN FRANCISCO BENEFITS LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge has ruled that the city of San
Francisco cannot force United Airlines to comply with the city's
domestic partners law.
</P>
<P>
   The city had been threatening to end United's lease for a
kitchen and maintenance facility at San Francisco International
Airport unless the airline agreed to provide its employees who have
unmarried domestic partners the same benefits its married workers
get.
</P>
<P>
   United went to U.S. District Court last week to block the action
through a preliminary injunction. On Tuesday, Judge Claudia Wilken
agreed to the company's request.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means that, for now, United can continue operating
out of the facility until the issues surrounding the lawfulness of
the ordinance are resolved. A hearing on the matter is scheduled
for January.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave us exactly what we asked for,'' United attorney
Brendan Dolan said Wednesday. ``We think her action is absolutely
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Aftergut, an assistant city attorney, said he was
disappointed with the decision. Eventually, he said, ``We expect to
prevail. At that point United will have to do what the law
requires.''
</P>
<P>
   City Supervisor Tom Ammiano, chief sponsor of the ordinance,
also wasn't ready to concede defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a skirmish in the battle,'' he said. ``And I think
it's shameful of United to deny bereavement benefits to people who
are deserving.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which took effect June 1, 1997, requires companies
doing business with San Francisco to provide the same benefits to
workers with domestic partners as they give to married employees.
</P>
<P>
   United had a temporary lease with the airport that was set to
expire Monday. The city and United struck a deal in February 1997
that said if the airline complied with the domestic partners law,
the city would extend the $25 million lease for another 23 years.
If United did not meet the requirements, the lease could be
canceled, forcing the airline to find another site off city
property.
</P>
<P>
   While the judge didn't force the city to extend the lease, the
status quo remains until there is a ruling on the larger issue of
whether the law is valid.
</P>
<P>
   United joined a 17-month-old lawsuit by the Air Transport
Association, an industry group that represents the nation's major
airlines. It wants to prevent San Francisco from requiring airlines
to comply with the ordinance. The association contends that only
federal regulators, not a local jurisdiction, can apply mandates on
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Wilken issued a complex opinion on the case in April that sided
with the city on some provisions and the airlines on others. For
example, she said that federal law exempts air carriers from the
health and pension provisions of the equal benefits ordinance. The
city, however, contends that the airlines still must provide other
such benefits as bereavement and family medical leave, discounts
and free flights provided married employees.
</P>
<P>
   Those and several other outstanding issues have been subject to
additional litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Wilken's April opinion did not exempt businesses from other
industries from complying with the law, and this week's ruling on
the United issue doesn't change that. Since the law was imposed,
hundreds of city contractors have begun to offer benefits to
domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   United is the largest tenant at the San Francisco airport and
has more than 50 percent of the passenger traffic there.
</P>
<P>
   United employs 20,000 people in the San Francisco area and
71,000 elsewhere. The company could provide no specific figure for
the number of employees who would be affected by the city's
domestic partners law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
