<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORDUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE COMMITTEE APPROVES NOMINATION OF NORMAN MORDUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Norman Mordue, a state supreme court justice from
Onondaga County, N.Y., cleared a major Senate hurdle Thursday to
becoming a federal judge for the northern district of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee unanimously approved Mordue for
the post. His nomination now goes to the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Lopatto, a committee spokeswoman, said it should pass
easily in the Senate. However, she added that with Congress
expected to adjourn Friday night, the vote may not take place until
the Senate returns next year.
</P>
<P>
   During his confirmation hearing on Monday, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., called Mordue ``a great lawyer, a great judge, a great
citizen, a patriarch of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said, ``You're
an example of what a federal judge ought to be and what a human
being ought to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch added that although he couldn't promise that the full
Senate would approve Mordue's nomination, he believed that ``if
anyone will get through, you've got a pretty good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordue, of Syracuse, N.Y., was born on June 26, 1942, and
received an undergraduate degree in 1966 and a law degree in 1971
from Syracuse University. From 1966 to 1968, he served in the U.S.
Army and received the Purple Heart and other awards for his service
in Vietnam before being discharged as a captain.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to 1982, Mordue served with the district attorney's
office in Onondaga County, first as a clerk, then as an assistant
district attorney. From 1982 to 1985, he was a county court judge
in Onondaga County. Since 1986, Mordue has served on the New York
State Supreme Court in the county.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
