<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6454 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHORS-BERG-SPI &LR;      10-08 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-BERG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BIOGRAPHER, LINDBERGH WAS HERO, VICTIM AND VILLIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A. Scott Berg had accomplished what many biographers before had
failed to do: Secure permission from Anne Morrow Lindbergh to
examine the long-sealed papers of aviator Charles A. Lindbergh and
her own papers, too.
</P>
<P>
   But when Berg first visited the Lindbergh archives at Yale
University, the National Book Award-winning biographer briefly
surveyed the large room packed with materials, then promptly strode
back outside and sat down on a park bench and cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God! Oh my God!'' Berg thought to himself. He expected
there would be a great deal of Lindbergh material, but certainly
not that much, and he was overcome by the knowledge that he would
have to examine all that material by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Just reading it would consume two years of his life. But not far
into the process, Berg's gloom was replaced by a growing sense that
he was witness to ``certainly the most interesting 20th century
American life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lindbergh's life has got everything,'' Berg said in an
interview. ``He was the hero, he was the victim, he was the
villain. And then there was the great mystery about what happens to
Lindbergh after Pearl Harbor, how the most famous person in the
world seems to fall off the face of the Earth. And then there's
also this incredible love story and marriage _ how much more could
you want?
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember calling my publisher one day and saying, `I've got
the stuff of a great book, even without mentioning Lindbergh's solo
flight to Paris, or the Lindbergh kidnapping, or Lindbergh's
politics _ just Lindbergh, the man, the husband, the father, the
child.' I still believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg's monumental new biography is the definitive match for this
great material. After almost a decade of diligent research and
writing by Berg, ``Lindbergh'' (Putnam, 628 pages, $30) is a richly
detailed and deeply nuanced examination of a historic life in all
its complexity.
</P>
<P>
   This is this fall's must-read biography, an all-but-certain
prize winner in non-fiction that already is climbing best-seller
lists. Film rights have been sold to director Steven Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Berg refers to Lindbergh as ``a true American hero,'' ``a man of
conviction and purpose and integrity'' who managed to live a life
of accomplishment and consequence right up until his death in 1974
at age 72.
</P>
<P>
   Berg, who has written biographies of editor Maxwell Perkins and
movie mogul Samuel Goldwyn, knows great lives often have no second
acts, just one singular time that dwarfs all that preceded it and
all that followed. Lindbergh's life, in contrast, is a four-act
drama, with illustrious elements in each.
</P>
<P>
   What Berg is proudest of capturing with this biography is ``the
breadth and depth of Lindbergh's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 48-year-old, Princeton-educated biographer said, ``This
was not just some flyboy who got himself to Paris. This is somebody
who went on to develop commercial aviation, to launch the American
rocket program, to pursue sophisticated medical research. He also
did important work in anthropology and archaeology. Lindbergh is
also someone who took bold, sometimes wrong-headed political
stances, someone who became a superb writer who deservedly won the
Pulitzer Prize and also became one of the most important
conservationists of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Lindbergh's luminescent reputation is forever dimmed by
what he said and what he did in the days leading to World War II.
Lindbergh seemed to squander the vast reservoirs of public hero
worship brought on by his first flight across the Atlantic in 1927
and public sympathy brought on by the horrific kidnapping and
murder of his golden-locked infant son, Charles A. Lindbergh Jr.,
in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   This century's first worldwide media celebrity suddenly seemed,
in deeds and statements, both soft on Hitler's Nazi Germany and
prejudiced against Jews, even anti-Semitic. This was the part of
his research that Berg, who is Jewish, approached with considerable
apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I want to spend a decade of my life with someone if he was
anti-Semitic?'' Berg recalled asking himself. ``Will I be able to
wake up every morning to someone who would have hated me, somebody
who would not have allowed me into his house?''
</P>
<P>
   What Berg discovered about Lindbergh was incriminating in some
ways on these matters, but also far more complex than public
perception.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh's early admiration for Nazi Germany was the result of
inspection missions undertaken at the request of the U.S.
government to ascertain that country's growing aeronautical
capabilities. He was impressed by Germany's amazing resurgence from
the ruins of World War I, plus the purpose and industriousness
abroad in the land that seemed in such marked contrast from what he
saw in France, Britain and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   So that prompted Lindbergh to conclude (in a 1936 letter) that
Hitler was ``undoubtedly a great man'' who ``has done much for the
German people,'' although ``he is a fanatic in many ways.''
Observations like this got Lindbergh in much trouble later,
especially when coupled with his acceptance of a Nazi medal for his
Spirit of St. Louis flight that was presented in a surprise
ceremony at the American embassy by Hitler's notorious deputy,
Hermann Goering.
</P>
<P>
   Berg believes Lindbergh had no option but to accept the medal,
although he could and should have returned it later, especially
once World War II broke out. But Lindbergh never returned any medal
he received in his life because, as Berg observed, ``he was too
thick-headed, just plain Swedish stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh's views of the Jews also caused problems, especially
after a controversial 1941 speech in Des Moines, Iowa. Lindbergh
was the most prominent member of the growing America First
movement, which hoped to keep the United States out of World War
II, a position supported by a vast majority of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh's Des Moines speech included just three paragraphs
about Jews, his only comments on them during months of contentious
debate over whether the United States should enter the war.
Lindbergh thought his comments on Jews were sympathetic, but they
were deeply offensive, including suggestions that Jews were ``not
American'' and were ``other peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg concluded that Lindbergh viewed Jews through a lens shared
by many others at the time, especially those with his Midwestern
upbringing. By some standards, Lindbergh was anti-Semitic, by some
he was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to define anti-Semitism,'' Berg emphasized. ``If that
means someone who hates Jews, Lindbergh was not. He had Jewish
friends; he tried to help Jews escape from Nazi Germany. But if
anti-Semitism means someone who segregates, in his mind or
otherwise, Jews from others or from Americans, or someone who
believed the mantra of the day that Jews controlled the media and
had undue influence, then, yes, Lindbergh was anti-Semitic. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased to find Lindbergh was not a Jew-hater. He was
just an old-fashioned, middle-of-the-road, mid-century gentile
anti-Semite.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg's portrait of Lindbergh is full of such challenging
complexities. Here is a great, yet flawed man who overcame a
distant and difficult family; who failed at school and was largely
self-taught; who married a remarkable woman and remained with her
despite their great differences in personality; who was a loving,
if sometimes-harsh father to five children who grew into remarkable
adults; and who always drove himself tirelessly to challenges
beyond the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh's worthy life is one that truly teaches by example.
</P>
<P>
   As Berg stressed, ``I cannot think of a single person who packed
as much living into a single lifetime as Charles Lindbergh. I think
one lesson that can be learned from him is the importance of making
the most of our days and making them purposeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other great lesson of Lindbergh's life, and this is
especially timely today, is that here is a man who, right or wrong,
always took responsibility for his actions and his words. That
sometimes got him branded a hero, sometimes a villain, but he
always stood by what he said and did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6468 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MONUMENTAVE-TEX     10-08 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MONUMENTAVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARY DISAPPOINTS IN `MONUMENT AVE.'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every city has one, intones the trailer for ``Monument Ave.,''
the new film starring Denis Leary. I'm not sure about that, but I
know that every aisle of Blockbuster has one: a gritty, low-budget
film about a band of small-time hoods trying to keep it together,
their days dissolving into a mixture of alcohol, drugs, fights and
woman-chasing. Directed by Ted Demme, ``Monument'' at least takes
advantage of its Boston location. The tiny, cramped streets, with
the brick row houses, give it a look unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is also the home of the Irish hoods who pounce from one
meaningless petty crime to another _ ``Ladz in the Hood.''
</P>
<P>
   This Irish area of Boston is Leary's stamping grounds (the
comedian grew up on its streets). Sporting projects-trash
muttonchops and looking as if he hasn't had a good night's sleep in
weeks, he cruises the city with a pack of pals, including a cousin
who shipped over from Ireland. Dazed and bleary-eyed, Leary's
cousin doesn't understand the code of the Boston streets: Never rat
out anyone, no matter how much you hate him. It's a plot device,
sure; apparently, in Ireland, the streets abound with innocent
kids.
</P>
<P>
   But Leary's cousin, in his early 20s, is confused, particularly
when one of Leary's buddies is shot down by the local mob boss (the
able Colm Meaney) in front of a bar full of witnesses. And none of
them has a word to say to the detective (Martin Sheen) who rolls
into the crime scene and muses that Boston's bars must have the
biggest johns in the world, since everyone seems to be relieving
themselves in them when a shooting takes place.
</P>
<P>
   It might have made more sense if the kid were bewildered by the
easy violence on American streets, violence that pops out of
nowhere. Instead, he _ and much of ``Monument Ave.'' _ seems to
have been lifted from some old Warner Bros. social-conscience
picture, like ``Angels With Dirty Faces.'' The kid's death is
supposed to rouse Leary from his apathy, but Leary seems almost the
same before as after. Leary works without falling back on his
counterpunching comic rhythms here. He tries to give a
``performance,'' trying to portray a man exhausted from running
around the same track all his life. His aim is touching: He wants
to be taken seriously as an actor, not just as someone who rattles
off wisecracks. Unfortunately, he doesn't have the skills to pull
it off. So a scene in which Leary dares a chowderhead racist to
follow through on the courage of his convictions just comes off as
puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad, because Leary's comic persona came as an undeniable
response to those streets; growing up among guys like the hostile,
dim thugs depicted here made him what he is. ``Monument Ave.'' is
at its best when Leary, sitting around and running lines of coke
with his squad, does a speedy enumeration of all the celebrity
babes he'd like to do, and spews out all the reasons he wouldn't
stand a chance with them. The movie damages its own logic by making
the fabulous Famke Jannsen chase him around (although she's
believably angry). Leary and Demme scored before, in ``The Ref,'' a
devious comedy that Leary dominated by sheer performance technique.
By trying to be true to this lackluster story, he commits a crime _
he robs himself of importance.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Monument Ave.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Denis Leary, Colm Meaney
</P>
<P>
   Director: Ted Demme
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Unrated _ sexual content, adult language, violence and
drug use
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
