<HEADLINE>
CHILI LOVERS WILL BE TEMPTED ... TO SCREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What you're about to read could cause eye irritation, swelling,
certainly tears.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Texas chili lover, you could end up on the floor,
bawling your heart out, grief-stricken as though your pet Chia had
just been hit by a moving van.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to tell you about people who make chili, but not your
normal chili. No, these folks not only put beans in their pot, but
also tomatoes and tofu and ``textured vegetable protein.'' There
are some other things in there, too, but we'll get to those later.
</P>
<P>
   Take a moment to collect yourself.
</P>
<P>
   At noon Sunday, the Fort Worth Vegetarian Society will sponsor
the 10th Annual Vegetarian Chili Cook-off at the Trinity Park Arts
Shelter, otherwise known as the site of Shakespeare in the Park.
Everyone is invited.
</P>
<P>
   It costs $5 to sample the chili. Children are free _ not to
sample, but to take. There will be music, dancing and entertainment
for the kids. There are 20 teams competing in the cook-off. They
have to make 5 gallons of the spicy brew and it must be made
without any animal or dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Take a deep breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this cook-off every year in a different city,'' said
Liz Hutchinson, secretary of the local veggie society. ``Over the
years it has been hosted in Austin, El Paso, Corpus Christi, San
Antonio and Houston. Some cities have had it more than once.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson, who went meatless 13 years ago, swears that the
chili is tasty. She is defiant when it comes to putting beans in
the chili. She says there is ``absolutely not'' anything wrong with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, most people say they don't even notice there
isn't any meat in the chili,'' she said. ``Some of the cooks use
meat substitutes, some don't.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the beans: ``I do want to say that chili is just chili.
If you put meat in it, it's called chili con carne. You have to say
it has beef in it because it doesn't come with beef.''
</P>
<P>
   She does have a point. I've never heard of chili con frijoles,
but then I've never heard of chili con tofu either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think chili originated in Mexico,'' she continued. ``I think
they came up with it because they had to do something to season the
beans.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Hutchinson is right when she trumpets the
health value of meatless chili. No meat means no animal fat, and
that's important to a lot of people. The beans provide the protein.
</P>
<P>
   But about the other stuff these folks put in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they use tomatoes, all sorts of things,'' Hutchinson
said, somewhat reluctantly. ``They use all kinds of vegetables. And
I'm not supposed to say anything about it, but one team I know uses
spinach.''
</P>
<P>
   Good God!
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Hutchinson really didn't want to say it, I think.
But she's a nice woman and I asked. ``What else do they use?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peanut butter,'' she answered. ``Isn't that incredible? A
woman used peanut butter, and she won. She's coming again this
year, and she's bringing the peanut butter again.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that it can be done, Hutchinson offered the
following recipe. Try it if you wish. But it might be wiser to go
to the vegetarian chili cook-off and get professional help before
attempting it on your own.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe, for example, doesn't specify chunky or creamy.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETARIAN QUINTESSENSUAL CHILI
</P>
<P>
   Yields 5 gallons (40 servings)
</P>
<P>
   10 cups beans (20 cups cooked) Can use pinto, black and garbanzo
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds tofu, torn into bite-sized pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tamari
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons onion powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon garlic powder (or more)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   14 tablespoons vegetable oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 large green bell peppers, diced
</P>
<P>
   8 large onions, diced
</P>
<P>
   12 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 cups chunk textured vegetable protein
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   10 to 12 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 tablespoons cumin
</P>
<P>
   Chopped chipotle peppers to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cook beans using package directions. Whip together tamari,
tomato paste, peanut butter, onion powder, garlic powder, 2 cups
water. Add to tofu pieces and mix. Saute in 8 tablespoons vegetable
oil over medium heat until all liquid is absorbed and tofu
well-browned.
</P>
<P>
   In a pan with 6 tablespoons vegetable oil, saute green bell
peppers, onions, minced garlic. Add sauteed mixture with browned
tofu to the cooked beans, adding water as needed. Add textured
vegetable protein, chili powder, salt, cumin and chipotle peppers.
Warm throughout, add seasoning to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 195 calories, 21 grams
carbohydrates, 8 grams fat, 12 grams protein, 0 milligrams
cholesterol, 774 milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a food column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can write to him at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, TX 76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
