<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S NOT ALONE IN WORK-PLACE DALLIANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apparently, President Clinton isn't the only one caught in an
office romance.
</P>
<P>
   Romantic encounters at the office are at an all-time high, which
may explain why some Americans aren't shocked by Clinton's actions.
</P>
<P>
   With the huge increase in women in the work force, the
increasing time spent at the office and a loosening of relationship
rules in corporate America, office affairs number in the millions,
attorney Dennis M. Powers says.
</P>
<P>
   He discusses the trend and its implications, especially in
respect to sexual harassment laws, in ``The Office Romance: Playing
With Fire Without Getting Burned'' (Amacom, 316 pages, $22.95.)
</P>
<P>
   How big are the numbers? Huge.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1994 American Management Association study, 80
percent of managers surveyed have had or known of an office
romance. Other surveys suggest that between 25 percent and 33
percent of employees have had an office romance. A study by the
Bureau of National Affairs suggests that one-third of all
relationships started at or from work. And that study was conducted
10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those number are astounding considering that 20 years ago, most
companies had nepotism and favoritism rules to keep married couples
from working together, Powers writes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 84 percent of companies surveyed said they allow
husband-wife teams. Some companies even encourage the policy. A
whopping 98 percent of companies surveyed permit workers to date.
</P>
<P>
   Powers sees the trend as natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The huge time demands placed on everyone by their employers
have made work the only place to meet people for vast numbers of
Americans,'' Powers writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you add in the opportunity to work closely with someone
at no risk, view them in all types of settings, and be with someone
of similar expectations and education, then you can easily see why
work has become the meeting and dating place of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Many office encounters are more than just sexual flings.
One-half of survey respondents who acknowledged having an office
romance said they ended up in a marriage or long-term relationship,
according to the management association study. That beats the
overall divorce rate, which is up to 60 percent, according to the
Council on Families in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It beats singles bars, blind dates and personal ads, and any
chemistry is given the time to become hotly seasoned,'' Powers
writes. ``These benefits are not one-sided: businesses now are
recognizing the direct link between employee job satisfaction and
company profits with prointeractive policies.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a downside to such romantic encounters, and Powers
includes chapters on sexual harassment laws and what happens when a
relationship ends.
</P>
<P>
   In the former, however, Powers argues that most office
relationships never see the light of an Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission file.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 54,000 sexual harassment complaints filed with the EEOC
over the past six years, less than 5 percent involved a failed
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Yet dangers do exist, and Powers has identified 10, from damaged
professional reputations to conflicts of interest to facing your
ex-lover at work every day. The author draws not only from surveys
and studies, but also extensively quotes the experiences of
individuals, using first names only.
</P>
<P>
   Powers also scrutinizes what companies are doing about the
trend. In some respects, companies dance on a tight rope.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, said Burke Stinson, AT&AMP;T's senior public relations
manager:
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to lose your best employees because they're
having a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other, companies don't want to be involved in sexual
harassment cases or other illegal issues, or in tense and therefore
unproductive environments resulting from failed affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Powers suggests office policies that do not stand in the way of
the inevitable relationships, yet carefully spell out what is
acceptable and what is not.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Powers skillfully guides readers through the land mines
and windfalls of a trend that is clearly permanent.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
