<SLUG> BC-FILM-MONUMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERIVATIVE `MONUMENT AVE.' IS A DEAD END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The air of deja vu is so heavy in ``Monument Ave.'' that it
often plays like a caricature of that most overworked formula of
the American Independent Cinema: the ``Mean Streets'' clone.
</P>
<P>
   It's the old story about a group of boyhood pals who grow up
together in some troubled inner-city neighborhood, move inevitably
into crime and the underworld as adolescents, and end up badly as
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the streets are in the Irish American ghetto of South
Boston, and the hero is Bobby (Denis Leary), a thirtysomething car
thief and low-level hoodlum who still lives at home with his mother
(Marilyn Murphy Meardon).
</P>
<P>
   His pals are: Mouse (Ian Hart), a burglar so lazy and stupid he
tends to fall asleep in the apartments he robs; Digger (John
Diehl), a seedy taxi driver who chaufeurs the rest of the guys
around; and Teddy (Billy Crudup), a speed freak just out of stir.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the stock characters are Jackie (Colm Meaney), the
affable but deadly leader of the local Irish mafia; Hanlon (Martin
Sheen), the Irish cop who tries to help the boys go straight; and
Katy (Famke Janssen), the tough girl with a heart of gold who loves
Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackie has Teddy gunned down (because he may have ratted on
Jackie in prison), it brings a crisis into Bobby's life. Is he
going to swallow the death of his pal and stay safe, or is he going
to make a stand against the vicious gang leader?
</P>
<P>
   The script never makes us care one way or another. Anyway, it's
too busy entertaining us with offensive macho humor and
Tarantino-esque torture scenes, as when Bobby and the guys kidnap,
brutalize and nearly murder an innocent black man who happens to
inadvertently wander into their all-white neighborhood one night.
</P>
<P>
   In the lead, Denis Leary _ unappealing in the best of times _ is
like so much dead air on the screen. His character not only has no
redeeming qualities at the start, he displays no spiritual growth
in the course of the film. There's nothing about the guy to make
anyone want to invest an ounce of interest or sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Even more glaring, director Ted Demme (``Beautiful Girls'')
seems to have no special ``feel'' for this milieu; he never gives
his audience the sense it's getting a privileged look inside a
brutal world that he knows very well. Instead, ``Monument Ave.'' (a
title that goes unexplained in the film) always comes across as a
compilation of regurgitated moments from other, better movies.
</P>
<P>
   Monument Ave. Directed by Ted Demme. Screenplay by Mike
Armstrong. Cast: Denis Leary, Ian Hart, Famke Janssen, Billy
Crudup, Martin Sheen, Colm Meaney. Lions Gate Films. 90 minutes.
Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6476 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-WITHOUTLIMITS-TE     10-08 0634
