<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WITHOUTLIMITS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POWERFUL TALE OF OLYMPIAN ARROGANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Without Limits'' chronicles an aspect of American life we
don't often see in the movies: the quality of earned arrogance.
Steve Prefontaine, as played by Billy Crudup, has a brand of
spiritual superiority that manifests itself as a physical
arrogance: His proud walk, which shows off his supreme belief in
himself. As the premier U.S. long-distance runner of the early
1970s, Pre, as he's called, believes the world is his oyster _ his
plate of oysters _ and he downs them at his leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Crudup makes the cockiness winning, a simple reflection of Pre's
absorption in his athletic performance. He may be arrogant, but
he's a generous guy. As we see in his courtship of the student
played by Monica Potter, he can even be old-fashioned and courtly.
</P>
<P>
   Writer/director Robert Towne is more interested in the tests
that Pre subjects himself to than the races in which he competes.
This may not make for the fiercest melodrama, but it does serve as
an ingenious way to set his actors loose. Especially Donald
Sutherland, who has spent most of the past two decades playing
oversensitive sufferers. As Pre's coach, Bill Bowerman, Sutherland
holds his head up and regards the world as his oyster, too, and
plucks Pre as his pearl. It's a battle of arrogance, and
Sutherland's casual preening is devastating. He shows a control
that's been missing from his work.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Pre and Bowerman wrestle for psychological supremacy is
funny, because both men have towering levels of eccentricity.
Bowerman, at work on what would become the standard in running
shoes _ he was out to design a sole that didn't need metal spikes,
so that it would be lighter and faster _ turns his kitchen into a
novelty store, pouring up batches of rubber into waffle irons and
slapping the homemade soles on shoes; the place looks like some
peculiar cobbler elf's factory.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, though, the material feels underdramatized. However,
Towne outdoes himself as a writer. He has directed two previous
movies, ``Personal Best,'' which also followed athletes in their
downtime, and ``Tequila Sunrise,'' a romantic melodrama. Those
movies captured a kind of arrested adolescence, and it was less
forgivable in ``Sunrise.'' In ``Without Limits,'' by dealing with
so many themes, he doesn't take the time to explicate them properly
and play them out throughout the film. Had he made the struggle
between Bowerman and Pre a little harder and sharper, he might have
given the movie more focus.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, though, that he was hamstrung partially by
choosing a living subject in Bowerman and not wanting to cause him
any pain. (In some ways, with his cool curiosity, Sutherland seems
to be playing Towne.) The performances have a lithe, muscular
power. And there's a funny edginess that Towne has given to the
mating match between Potter and Crudup. He's tickled by her
independence _ she has a strong sense of morality, and of herself _
and it draws him to her. Like a number of other things in the film,
their relationship doesn't quite pay off (she, too, plays someone
who's still living, which must have presented a problem in her
depiction). But Towne shows such a savvy and delicate touch as a
director that stuff from the movie sticks with you, like lines from
a great pop song.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Without Limits''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Robert Towne
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Billy Crudup, Donald Sutherland
</P>
<P>
   Length: 118 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity and adult situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
