<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HOLYMAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLY MAN' CONTINUES EDDIE MURPHY SUCCESS WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy continues to ride his recent success wave with
``Holy Man.'' It's a better-than-average comedy that actually has a
lot to say about how we live (or how we think we should live).
</P>
<P>
   In an odd way, it's an apt companion to the recent ``The Truman
Show'' in that its protagonist spends much of his life with
television and comes to find chronic dissatisfaction with old
habits when faced with real love and responsibility. In this case,
the conduit to a better future is an itinerant holy man named ``G''
(Eddie Murphy).
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Hayman (Jeff Goldblum) was once the top sales executive
for the Good Buy Shopping Network (GBSN) but he's taken a down turn
in the past ``27 months of flatness'' and his new boss, Mr.
McBainbridge (Robert Loggia) is scouting for new blood. Ricky is up
to his ears in debt and the bank is calling daily because his car
payment bounced and he hasn't enough money to pay the mortgage on
his tony Miami pad.
</P>
<P>
   McBainbridge hires a media analyst, Kate Newell (Kelly Preston),
to weigh the station's financial woes and Ricky, who is aware he
may soon be unemployed, makes his play. But Kate's too savvy. One
day, while driving back from lunch, they have a flat tire. Out of
nowhere comes a ``guy wearing his pajamas'' named G, who is on a
spiritual pilgrimage and who realizes Ricky is on a spiritual
spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, G and Kate have become good friends, and the guru
has moved into Ricky's home. Ricky has an idea to put the prophet
on the air to boost sales and make a different kind of profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about making people feel they have to have things even
when they don't want them,'' Ricky tells G. But G has other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring the conflict of innocence and spiritual inner peace
versus the emptiness of money and greed, ``Holy Man'' sidles
through several shifts in tone before it settles for a maudlin
ending that undercuts the potency of its earlier message. It's a
shame the film fumbles at times, and wavers in what it wants to
convey _ ultimately, its payoff is flimsy after such an
enlightening lesson in values.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the idea of a drowning man who is all too aware that
``everybody is anxious and scared; we acquire and waste,'' and who
can't save himself, has been a staple in the movies. ``It's a
Wonderful Life'' and Disney movies like ``Down and Out In Beverly
Hills'' used angels and bums, respectively, to rescue their
floundering film heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy Man'' was written by Tom Schulman, who also wrote ``Dead
Poet's Society,'' and his strength as a screenwriter is the ability
to show the vulnerability in his all-too-human protagonists.
Goldblum has just the right mix of strength and weakness to allow
us to initially dislike Ricky's fake, oozy charm, but to see the
growth that comes after meeting G.
</P>
<P>
   Preston's Kate is really the catalyst for Ricky's change because
she's already in tune with her own spirituality; and Murphy, who is
calmly charismatic, imbues his holy man with a weird dignity that
balances the scales between Ricky's pain and Kate's peace.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Man. Directed by Stephen Herek. Written by Tom Schulman.
Cast: Eddie Murphy, Jeff Goldblum, Kelly Preston, Robert Loggia.
Touchstone Pictures. 113 minutes. Rated PG for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
