<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTENING TO THE SPEWINGS OF BROTHER MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just for the irony of it, I have rechristened the anonymous
caller ``Brother Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years I must have received hundreds of calls like the
one Brother Man left on my voice mail, and I've learned to dismiss
them as the putrid waste products of disadvantaged minds that they
are.
</P>
<P>
   When an old-style crude bigot (not one of the more sophisticated
post-Reagan-era types) starts in laying that ludicrous spiel on me,
I usually either hang up abruptly or find a way to put the creep in
his or her place with humor.
</P>
<P>
   Voice mail has become a really handy device for pusillanimous
bigots. They can put in test calls to determine if the callee is
available. If not, they then regurgitate into one's recording
device.
</P>
<P>
   Usually I just erase the stuff after the opening flatulence. But
in Brother Man's case, I listened to the whole odious oration. I
suppose I did that because I hadn't heard anything quite like it in
a while, and I was amazed to find that there were still some of
those old-fashioned hate-mongers around who let fly with
unvarnished racial malice.
</P>
<P>
   These days, most people who really feel the way Brother Man does
usually coat their vocalized feelings with a thin veneer of
civility. But those are the educated or semi-educated ones.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could have been that Brother Man was not as
ignorant as I first presumed. Maybe he was a fairly well-schooled
person who became so incensed at my column of that day, which
lambasted one of his favorite far-right ideologue politicians, that
he decided to cast civility to the winds and let it all hang out
... to my machine.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, I surmised, he is a good friend, close associate or
strong supporter of that politician, and he felt an obligation to
put my swarthy posterior in its place.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Brother Man hooked me with his classic opening
salutation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil Johnson, you ignorant, half-breed n__ ...''
</P>
<P>
   And it went downhill from there. For three minutes, Brother Man
let fly with every stereotypical aspersion against
African-Americans and Mexican-Americans you ever heard. Of course,
he didn't use those hyphenated ethnic classifications. And he
embellished the nouns he did use with stark, poisonous epithets.
</P>
<P>
   In Brother Man's view, white people had created the greatest
society on earth, and ``since Lyndon Johnson gave you your
freedom,'' African-Americans and Mexican-Americans have messed it
up. He blamed the two ethnic groups for crime, the drug problem,
high taxes, the decline in morals and the ``dumbing down of our
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly incensed about increasing interracial dating
and mixed marriages, declaring that ``black men want white women
because they know they are mentally inferior and they want their
children to be smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right. He actually said that. Although I had heard all of
the other stuff before, that was a new one on me.
</P>
<P>
   I really didn't keep listening to Brother Man because of what he
said. It was the way he said it. He spoke with a fascinating kind
of windup toy inflection and rhythm. It was clear that he was
reading from a prepared text.
</P>
<P>
   I assumed at first that he was simply giving out the official
line of some hate group. But upon reflection I concluded that this
was his personal eruption of venom and that he took great pride in
his authorship.
</P>
<P>
   This was a big moment for Brother Man _ an opportunity to
release something that had been building up in him for years, a
chance to lash out at the source of his life's discontent and
frustration. He perhaps had not become the best that he could be or
grabbed his share of the American dream because, in his view, the
dream had become distorted.
</P>
<P>
   The sources of that distortion, according to Brother Man, were
the hyphenated Americans. It was as simple as that, and Brother Man
craved simplicity to put his unfulfilled aspirations into bearable
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment of understanding, my heart reached out to Brother
Man, and I felt his pain. I prayed then for him _ prayed that
Brother Man would search his heart and mind and appeal to his
Creator for a clearer vision of the purpose of human life and a
better appreciation of what he possesses and what he has done that
is of value.
</P>
<P>
   I prayed further for the relief of Brother Man's existential
anguish and for him to find some meaning in life to replace his
need to take solace in hatred.
</P>
<P>
   And then I punched the button and consigned Brother Man's
diatribe into that great blur of oblivion where all such benighted
outbursts of evil belong.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUGH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     10-08 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUGH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONE TOUGH COP': A COP DISOBEYS ORDERS, AND PAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review.) 
(kd) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to staying on the cutting edge of urban realism,
police movies have increasingly fallen behind television drama in
evoking the texture of urban life. And Bruno Barreto's film ``One
Tough Cop,'' although strongly acted and pungently written (by
Jeremy Iacone), is no exception. Despite a hearty two-fisted
performance by Stephen Baldwin as the tattooed lug of a main
character, the movie feels faintly old hat as well as mechanically
contrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Tough Cop'' is adapted from an autobiographical novel by
Bo Dietl, a highly decorated New York City police detective who
fancied himself a kind of Dirty Harry in the 1980s and was
eventually punished for bending the rules by being exiled from
Manhattan to a remote section of Brooklyn. He was only 35 when he
retired in discouragement from the force.
</P>
<P>
   The story takes off from a notorious 1981 crime in which two men
broke into an East Harlem convent school and raped and tortured a
young schoolteacher. The movie isn't so much about how the
fictionalized Bo helped solve that crime only to be denied official
credit as about its impact on his professional and personal
relationships. The East Harlem incident (in the movie the rape and
torture culminate in the nun's murder after 47 crosses have been
carved into her body) is so highly publicized that a special police
task force is assigned to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Disobeying orders, Bo and his loyal partner Duke Finnerty (Chris
Penn) continue to work on the case, based on a tip from Rickie La
Cassa (Mike McGlone), Bo's oldest and closest friend, a petty
mafioso whose restaurant is officially off-limits to Bo. Bo
nevertheless visits the place regularly, and it is there that he
and Duke brutally grill an informant Rickie has dug up through the
underworld grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Bo's relationship with Rickie, whom he loves as
a brother, is being scrutinized by a pair of icy federal agents who
issue Bo a blunt threat: either he installs a recording device in
Rickie's car or they destroy his career with surveillance
information they have gathered.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Duke, a compulsive gambler and alcoholic who
once saved Bo's life, is accruing thousands of dollars in gambling
debts to Rickie's underworld friends. To cap things off (most
improbably), Bo begins an affair with Rickie's ex-girlfriend Joey
(Gina Gershon), who left Rickie after giving up hope of his ever
leaving his wife and family.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why Baretto chose this material. The Brazilian
director, whose last movie ``Four Days in September,'' examined the
moral ambiguities of radical terrorism in Brazil in the late 1960s,
is fascinated by the excruciating choices facing people in extreme
circumstances. In this movie, the director is unambiguously pro-Bo
and against the manipulative bureaucracies that he lashes out
against.
</P>
<P>
   But ``One Tough Cop'' has more story than it can comfortably
handle, and as it goes along it grows progressively less
believable. So much screen time is devoted to setting up the
conflicts that when things finally unravel, the denouement feels
rushed and anticlimactic. While officially tying up the loose ends,
it leaves you emotionally hanging.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Tough Cop'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has scenes of violence, profanity and
sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRODUCTION NOTES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONE TOUGH COP
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bruno Barreto; written by Jeremy Iacone, based on
the novel ``One Tough Cop'' by Bo Dietl; director of photography,
Ron Fortunato; produced by Michael Bregman and Martin Bregman;
released by Stratosphere Entertainment. Running time: 90 minutes.
This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WITH: Stephen Baldwin (Bo Dietl), Chris Penn (Duke Finnerty), Mike
McGlone (Rickie La Cassa), Gina Gershon (Joey O'Hara), Paul
Guilfoyle (Frankie ``Hot'' Salvano), Amy Irving (FBI Agent Jean
Devlin) and Victor Slezak (FBI Agent Bruce Payne). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
