<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
STONE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ At 40 and recently married, Sharon
Stone seems to be relaxing her tenacious pursuit of stardom and
trying to move away from her femme fatale image. Ironically, she's
finding the diversity of work she's doing more rewarding than ever.
By Bob Strauss. 
. 
IMMIGRANTS-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ Life in the big city can be cold,
lonely and debilitating to the human spirit, even more so for the
modern immigrants who arrive in New York with expectations that the
streets are paved with prosperity. David Riker, a
still-photographer-turned-cinematographer, offers a compelling
dramatization of their existence in his fictional ``La Ciudad,''
which has been chosen to close the Los Angeles Latino International
Film Festival on Sunday. By Bob McCarthy. 
. 
DEVIL-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Bad dialogue plagues ``Love Is the
Devil,'' a portrait of Francis Bacon, the British painter with the
infernally fertile imagination for depicting souls in agony who was
a pretty nasty piece of work himself. What is shocking, at least in
the way writer-director John Maybury presents it in his movie, is
that Bacon was such a lame sadist. 1 { Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
DETROIT-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``Detroit 9000'' (it's the code for
``officer needs assistance'') plays like an entertaining episode of
``Mannix'' with a funky Motown soundtrack. It's not a very good
movie, but it certainly has its share of camp value with its
mushrooming Afros, cheesy chase scenes and outdated lingo. 2 Stars.
By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
MIGHTY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ ``The Mighty'' tries to combine
handicapped-child pathos, murderously dysfunctional family
dynamics, knights-on-horseback fantasy and gritty urban realism _
not always successfully. The film does have some nice things going
for it, like a good bead on what friendship can mean to kids who
don't fit in and a surprisingly effective Sharon Stone in a limited
but tricky single-mom part. 2 1/2 Stars. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
HOLY-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ A jumbled mess of conflicting messages,
``Holy Man,'' starring Jeff Goldblum, Eddie Murphy and Kelly
Preston, means to take both a comic and thoughtful look at
Americans' shop-till-you-drop mentality. But a shortage of material
combined with a syrupy presentation leaves the viewer with a bad
case of brain decay. 1 Star. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
COP-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Supposedly taken from the autobiography
of real ex-New York supercop Bo Dietl, ``One Tough Cop''
nonetheless plays like a formula TV episode. 2 Stars. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
TOUCH-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Although it never overcomes a kind of
narrative ungainliness, ``Touch Me'' gets better as it goes along.
Bridgette (Amanda Peet) is an aspiring actress who makes ends meet
teaching some kind of yogaerobics at a Marina del Rey fitness club.
Before you can say sexual harassment, she's happily hit on by the
club's playboy manager Adam (Michael Vartan). 2 1/2 Stars. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
LOH-THEATER (Johnson) _ ``Bad Sex With Bud Kemp'' is Sandra Tsing
Loh's Wonderland trip through the perils of dating in the '90s for
a single woman in her 30s. Sometimes the action on stage is a bit
too frantic, and cultural references fly off her tongue at a
dizzying rate, sometimes unnecessarily so. But those are minor
quibbles. By Rob Lowman. 
. 
DEAR-STAGE (Los Angeles) _  War has a funny way of turning
strangers into family, both on the battlefield and the home front.
Even Vietnam, the most rawly divisive conflict of this century, now
and then united Americans across sexual, age and ethnic boundaries
in a network of shared compassion, grief and courage. By Reed
Johnson. 
. 
COUNTRY-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Country stars Wynonna, Travis Tritt,
Tanya Tucker and Trace Adkins join forces at Sunday's ``Hollywood
Park Goes Country'' concert that will benefit the Shoemaker
Foundation, a nonprofit organization named for paralyzed jockey
Bill Shoemaker that helps those in the horse-racing industry who've
suffered catastrophic injury. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ You can't go anywhere in the record
business these days without hearing that '80s hair bands are surely
going to be the next big thing. Of course, these Prada-clad seers
were all wrong just two years ago when they predicted techno or
electronica was going to sweep the nation. That bleating,
one-dimensional Euro-noise got swept right out the back door
without selling many records at all. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ For her latest collection of tuneless
wanderings and cliche-ridden musings, Joni Mitchell, the once
mighty singer-songwriter mines the jazz-fusion hybrid that served
so well on landmark '70s albums like ``Hejira.'' Mitchell sings in
a voice that seems to come and go out of a rainstorm, offers
semi-coherent diary jottings that make Tori Amos look like
Hemingway. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
MURDER-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ This week on video we have two prime
examples of where today's Hollywood is finding its ``inspiration'':
``A Perfect Murder,'' which was based on the 1954 Hitchcock movie
``Dial M for Murder,'' which was based on the stage play of the
same name; and ``Lost in Space'' (New Line), which was based on the
campy 1960s television series, which was, of course, based on ``The
Swiss Family Robinson.'' By Rob Lowman. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
