u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT &LR;      10-08 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: A 1915 HORROR CLASSIC; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   83-Year-Old Evil In a Grim Paris
</P>
<P>
   Artistically, the film is a masterpiece. Commercially, however,
there's a bit of risk. ``People have to decide to commit seven
hours,'' said David Shepard, the preservation expert who restored
it. ``That's the roll of the dice.''
</P>
<P>
   This month Water Bearer Films, a New York distributor, is
offering Shepard's new edition of ``Les Vampires,'' Louis
Feuillade's 1915 surrealist silent classic about a band of
murderous brigands, called the Vampires, who assault the
bourgeoisie of Paris not only to gain money and power but also for
the pure kick of terrorizing the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, as was the case when ``Les Vampires'' originally
played in serial form, the production comes in 10 self-contained
episodes, making it possible to start and stop. Taken one by one,
each is a fascinating window on a director with a particular genius
for mixing the fantastic with the realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Feuillade's Paris and environs are cold and leafless, devoid of
the vibrancy the city is famous for, and hibernating in sterile,
crushingly oppressive propriety. In their very emptiness, the
streets throb with menace, perfect settings for the dark deeds that
Feuillade fully expected in life.
</P>
<P>
   Vampires kill without compunction, and employ every weapon from
sexual domination to heavy artillery in what amounts to an all-out
war against the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they are lithe black-clad types in the hooded
terrorist mode, stand-outs in the bland, gray dream world of their
ripe, complacent victims. Just as often, though, they are
innocuous-looking tradespeople and other ordinary citizens fitting
craftily into mundane goings-on, the better to foment conspiracy
and wreak havoc.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Poisoner,'' for example, the Vampire called Venomous, a
chemical warfare expert, and his sexy henchwoman, the first Irma
Vep (the French actress Musidora), infiltrate the household of the
reporter and Vampire-fighter Philippe Guerande, who is about to put
on his own engagement party. Wrapped in white aprons and setting
the table with bored nonchalance, the Vampires cater the event,
lacing the champagne and killing a concierge. As he lies dying, the
man calls out a warning and Guerande packs his family off to a safe
haven (safe for how long?).
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly for an 83-year-old film, ``Les Vampires'' has
survived many perils itself. In 1938, much of it was thrown out and
was actually awaiting trash collection on the street when it was
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the film is in the public domain. Shepard, who did
the restoration work on the acclaimed ``The Art of Buster Keaton,''
released last year, undertook this project with the blessing of
Gaumont, the French company that owned the trademark and some of
the film.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's digital restoration cleaned up many imperfections and
corrected the film's pacing. Tints have been reapplied (many were
lost during various incarnations), titles have been redone and a
symphony orchestra takes over from a lone piano player (who at some
showings was known to hammer away for the entire seven hours) to
provide accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   On four cassettes, ``Les Vampires'' is $99.95. Information:
(800) 551-8304.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The X-Files
</P>
<P>
   Despite a flood of Internet hype about how it would enhance the
television X-plot, Rob Bowman's film goes wandering in other
directions. Having devastated Early Man 37,000 years ago, aliens
are back in business; they've even subverted the Federal Emergency
Management Agency. That brings out agents Mulder (David Duchovny)
and Scully (Gillian Anderson), but by broadening itself for a
general audience, the movie only dilutes the cult intensity. As
Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, that leaves it to the
Mulder-Scully relationship (ever unfulfilled but promising) to
carry ``a middling, unfocused action-adventure with brand-name
appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $22.98. 145 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Days of Disco
</P>
<P>
   In his usual high style, Whit Stillman captures a particular
breed of privileged young woman in that brief time of
free-spiritedness between college and career. ``We look really good
tonight,'' Charlotte (Kate Beckinsale) tells Alice (Chloe Sevigny)
as they approach a disco entrance. ``I'm sure we're going to get
in.'' These aren't wild characters, just tame ones looking for some
fun while they begin their strivings in New York. Once again,
Stillman ``renders his characters' fretfulness in deft, funny and
improbably touching ways'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $104.16 108 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Big One
</P>
<P>
   If Michael Moore had his way, the national anthem for ``The Big
One,'' as he calls the United States, would be ``We Will Rock
You.'' As he's done since his documentary ``Roger and Me'' (1989),
Moore continues to ambush corporate executives with aggressive
questions about their business practices. Is it decent to close
American plants so they can pay Mexican laborers 85 cents an hour?
Why does TWA use prison inmates to make flight reservations? Why
doesn't Steve Forbes ever blink? Moore brings in an eye specialist
to consider that question. ``Do not threaten to call the police or
have him thrown out,'' a company warned its employees in a memo
about him. He's done it all before, but once again he spins ``an
entertaining film out of these same tactics.'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Miramax. $104.16. 96 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide Kings
</P>
<P>
   Four prep school boys (Sean Patrick Flannery, Henry Thomas,
Jeremy Sisto and Jay Mohr) and a friend (Johnny Galecki) kidnap a
Mafia boss (Christopher Walken) in the hope that in return for his
own freedom, he will quickly raise the $2 million needed to release
the recently kidnapped sister of one of the boys. But only Walken
stays cool in a film that desperately wants to be hip. Though
there's nothing wrong with the performances, other principal
characters seem out of step with an ``uneven comic suspense film''
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Artisan. $83.33. 106 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   PENALTY. After a young boy's legs are amputated by an
incompetent doctor, he grows up to become the sadistic Blizzard, a
criminal mastermind portrayed by Lon Chaney, who spends the entire
film with a crazed look on his face. Some silent film fans
attribute the intensity of Blizzard's nasty demeanor to the fact
that Chaney's legs were painfully doubled up for the role and
encased in leather stumps. 1920. Kino. $19.98. 93 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   FAR FROM THE MADDING CROWD and CYRANO. Two productions from
Globalstage, a San Francisco distributor, present theater
productions designed for children age 7 and up. Thomas Hardy's
``Far From the Madding Crowd'' (1998, 132 minutes) about the
attractive Bathsheba Everdene, who runs her farming estate in
19th-century Wessex with fierce independence and who is courted by
many before falling in love with the wrong man, was performed in
England by the Snap Theater. Filmed in Antwerp, ``Cyrano'' (1998,
100 minutes) was performed by the Blauw Vier theater company. Both
productions were made by BBC Resources, a part of the British
Broadcasting Corp. $27 each. Information: (888) 324-5623.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS OF IRON. James Mason, Maximilian Schell, David Warner and
James Coburn star in Sam Peckinpah's only war film, about the
rivalry of German officers on the Russian front, which is available
for the first time in its 130-minute European version. 1976. Hen's
Tooth. $29.99. R.
</P>
</TEXT>
