<SLUG> BC-MXPX-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN ROCKERS GO TO BIG-LABEL HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The big difference between life on an indie label and
life on a major label: It all boils down to cash, baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything costs more money,'' says Yuri Ruley, drummer for
MxPx. ``We look at everything and wonder, `Why does it cost so much
money to do this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it: Money talks. And MxPx, which moved from the
indie world of Tooth &AMP; Nail Records to living large on A&AMP;M Records,
has seen the difference. With the push of the label behind them,
the punky popsters have toured Europe and watched their album,
``Slowly Going the Way of the Buffalo,'' earn a Japanese release.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more connections now,'' Ruley says, calling from
the band's home base in Bremerton, Wash. ``We have label people in
every country. We have international booking agents. It's a lot
nicer now.''
</P>
<P>
   When some indie acts move up the food chain, there is fallout.
Rock-and-roll iconoclasts immediately think sellout when some bands
go to the majors. Making the transition even stranger, Tooth &AMP; Nail
is known as a Christian label.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their premise is that they want to put out music made by
Christians that was good,'' Ruley says. ``A lot of the labels at
that time in the Christian market were, `No, no, no.' They only
wanted stuff that would sell.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole Christian tag seems to be something MxPx is touchy
about. The band's official A&AMP;M bio doesn't mention it, although the
group played the church circuit, like most Christian rockers.
</P>
<P>
   Lyrically, the group's songs tread similar waters to groups like
Audio Adrenaline, even if the message isn't as blatant. Then again,
MxPx's ``Tomorrow's Another Day'' (``But just know this, that God
is faithful / Even if you don't have faith in yourself'') is pretty
hard to mistake for Marilyn Manson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a stereotype about Christian music,'' Ruley
says. ``We weren't ashamed of calling ourselves Christians, but we
didn't want people that hadn't heard our music to judge us, to
think that we were something we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the threesome _ including bassist/singer Mike Herrera
and guitarist Tom Wisniewski _ never felt entirely comfortable in
the Christian-music community.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get stuck in that world,'' Ruley says. ``It's comfortable
there _ you can sell millions and it will be the same people buying
your records. You're not actually growing any. A lot of our fans
thought we were disavowing our faith when we did that (left Tooth &AMP;
Nail), but we were just trying to keep our options open.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the frenetic threesome have managed to successfully work
in the secular world. They were on the Warped Tour and have shared
the stage with Reel Big Fish, No Doubt and Dance Hall Crashers. All
this, and none of the guys has celebrated a 22nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't really been hard,'' Ruley admits, discussing the
band's evolution from alt-Christian heroes to alt-rock faves. ``I
don't think people want to mope about stuff. Our songs are sort of
positive, and the spiritual element is fairly subtle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I'm sure some people (begin ital) do (end ital) want
to mope, but it's been fine for us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
