<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6519 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAR-STAGE-LADN     10-08 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAR-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMS AND BOMBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; War has a funny way of turning strangers into
family, both on the battlefield and the home front. Even Vietnam,
the most rawly divisive conflict of this century, now and then
united Americans across sexual, age and ethnic boundaries in a
network of shared compassion, grief and courage.
</P>
<P>
   One such unlikely alliance is the subject of ``Dear Mrs.
Baker,'' playwright Nancy Anne Baker's stirring, true homage to her
remarkable mother, Marilyn Baker. During the '60s and '70s, Mrs.
Baker, a patriotic suburban housewife and librarian from Fremont,
Calif., became pen pals with more than 50 American GIs serving in
'Nam, after responding to a soldier's letter in a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   After the young soldier began sharing the cookies, books and
puzzles he received, Mrs. Baker found herself exchanging letters
with dozens of servicemen, whose missives she kept in neat
scrapbooks.
</P>
<P>
   As combat took its toll, many of the soldiers went beyond
expressing their gratitude and opened their souls to reveal their
growing pain, horror and disillusionment. Mrs. Baker offered
unconditional support and a long-distance shoulder to cry on, even
while acknowledging she never could fully comprehend the reality
unfolding across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1968, the pivotal year of the Tet Offensive, ``Dear Mrs.
Baker'' hasn't entirely succeeded in shaping this extraordinary
tale into convincing dramatic form. Understandably, perhaps, the
playwright's portrait of her mother lacks a sufficiently sharp
critical edge that would offer some greater evidence of the
``eccentricity'' that Mrs. Baker's neighbors see in her behavior,
which is otherwise as perkily, emphatically normal as her pink hair
ribbon and crisp June Cleaver dress.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Darcy Shean, however, finds a more complex character
than the one written on the page. A woman of great empathy and
humility who could pass for Pat Nixon's younger sister, Shean's
Mrs. Baker possesses a schoolgirl sparkle. An expression of flirty
pleasure comes over her face when she reads the soldiers' letters,
momentarily mingling with her steady maternal warmth. When Mrs.
Baker ponders aloud whether to send chocolate-chip cookies or
snickerdoodles to the Mekong Delta, Shean's understated
self-assurance keeps the line from sounding inadvertently clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Shean gets unusually strong support from the six actors playing
the GIs: Christopher Delisle, Joe Camareno, Charles Mitri, Seth
Walther, Martin George and, best of all, Brian Pope, who brings a
surprising jocularity to his role as a sanguine medical staffer. By
contrast, the three servicemen's mothers detract from the
fascinating central relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Devereux's resourceful staging merges lyrically with
Alex Hajdu's terrific environmental set design, in which Mrs.
Baker's tidy garden melts into the darker foliage of the jungle.
GIs pop up out of trap doors and swing down from overhead thickets
as Devereux's clever tableaux juxtapose Mrs. Baker sewing or
cutting flowers, while her surrogate sons toss grenades and dodge
incoming mortar rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mrs. Baker'' sustains these separate realities, which
never quite touch but bleed together in powerful rivulets. By
evening's end, ``Dear Mrs. Baker'' will have written itself into
your memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
