<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGERS HAVE CHARITY IN MIND FOR HOLLYWOOD PARK CONCERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Tanya Tucker loves it. Travis Tritt says he
doesn't have a lot of time for it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite varying degrees of interest in the racing green, both
country stars will join Wynonna and Trace Adkins in a concert
Sunday at Hollywood Park to benefit the Shoemaker Foundation, a
nonprofit organization named for paralyzed jockey Bill Shoemaker
that helps those in the horse-racing industry who've suffered
catastrophic injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled to be able to play for Shoemaker,'' Tucker
said this week. ``He's super and has always been my favorite
jockey. I've seen him race so many times at Del Mar and Hollywood
Park, and every time I didn't bet on him, I lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Tritt says he enjoys a day in the stands whenever he has time.
But with a new baby and a busy touring schedule, he doesn't get out
to the track as much as he'd like.
</P>
<P>
   Both stars of ``Hollywood Park Goes Country'' are looking
forward to performing on the turf. While there won't be racing
Sunday evening at the park, satellite wagering from Santa Anita
will be available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a fun situation to play outside,'' said Tritt,
whose latest single, ``If I Lost You,'' was rising this week in the
country charts. ``It creates an excitement level, and an energy
starts going back and forth between crowd and performer. It's a fun
exchange when that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shoemaker Foundation was launched in 1991, the year
Shoemaker was paralyzed in an automobile accident in San Dimas. One
of the winningest jockeys in the history of the green, Shoemaker
once dominated the standings at Santa Anita, where he won every
riding championship from 1951 to 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has helped nearly 175 individuals and their
families across the country, said executive director Rod Pitts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only foundation on the West Coast that helps people
in the racing industry from all segments, from jockeys to grooms,''
he said. ``With insurance the way it is today, many of these
medical problems just aren't covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who landed her first hit with ``Delta Dawn'' in 1972
when she was just 13, said a prediction she made about the future
of country radio a few years ago had actually come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the new, younger artists on the radio anymore,''
she said. ``I mean, there's no reason why Merle Haggard can't have
another hit record. I'd like to see some of the older acts get more
involved than they have been. And there are some great new acts out
there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tritt isn't so optimistic. Considered one of the leading new
country singers of the early '90s, Tritt believes each act should
be judged on the merits of their most recent album. At the same
time, he says, commercial country radio is still resistant to
so-called heritage artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an artist who was considered one of the new guys, I see
it from both sides,'' Tritt said. ``The problem is, older artists
don't get a chance simply because of their age or the perception
that they're through. That isn't true in pop music where, for
example, if Rod Stewart came out with a really great album or song,
he'd get airplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if George Jones or Waylon Jennings or Merle came out with
a really great song, they're not going to get played on country
radio because of the perception attached to older artists.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, whose 30th album, ``Complicated,'' was recently issued,
admitted that while it's difficult to guess the future, country
music's traditions will always carry on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain artists will pick up the mantle forever,'' she said.
``Another way to tell is the number of people coming to Nashville.
It used to be Hollywood, but now everyone's heading to Nashville to
be a star.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
