<HEADLINE>
HOW `BAD SEX' CAN BE VERY GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Early in her one-woman show, ``Bad Sex With Bud
Kemp,'' Sandra Tsing Loh explains one of the differences between
men and women.
</P>
<P>
   One of her male friends, she says, tells her that on his death
bed his one regret will be over all the women that he didn't sleep
with.
</P>
<P>
   Loh, on the other hand, says on her death bed her one regret
will be over all the men she did sleep with.
</P>
<P>
   You can see this coming, but it's funny anyway. And it's pure
Loh, as anyone who has heard her five-minute gems on National
Public Radio knows. But you have to wonder if these wry and biting
observations would work in her 75-minute one-woman show.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes, because Loh expands beyond being a mere
monologuist and makes the stage a sort of outer reality for her
inner angst and still keeps it funny. ``Bad Sex'' is Loh's
Wonderland trip through the perils of dating in the '90s for a
single woman in her 30s. It's where she searches for, if not love,
at least a nonhumiliating relationship. The fictional Bud is the
name of a longtime friend who Loh ends up sleeping with.
</P>
<P>
   Painted a hospital green _ very serene or surreal as the case
may be _ the pegboard set by Kevin Adams is ingenious, with props
conveniently sliding, dropping down or folding out as needed. Under
David Schweizer's direction, the lanky Loh freely prowls the stage,
the restlessness and unease she feels about the new dating game
reflected in her kinetic energy. As she acts out her situations _
like the presex ritual of Bud and Loh rubbing legs together
underneath a table after a company softball game _ Loh sometimes
looks like she's performing a bizarre modern-dance movement.
</P>
<P>
   Loh presents herself as the kind of woman ``men fall back on,''
depend on for advice, borrow money from. But wanting more, she
decides to encourage Bud to move beyond the weekly movie stage of
their relationship (with their separate containers of popcorn).
Their first attempt at intimacy ends disastrously. ```This is weird
after all these years,' he says. `I know,' I say, `but I think
you'll like it'.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as the title implies, things do not go well, and Loh stands
there _ in one of her clever turns of phrase _ with ``accusing
breasts.'' Sex between two people can be such a lonely thing, she
sighs.
</P>
<P>
   This letdown sends her on a frantic quest for a man. First to a
video dating service through which she meets Robert Blair, an
architect and a Ralph Fiennes look-alike who is too, too precious.
Then on to an island lesbian fantasy with Jacqueline Bisset before
turning to online sexual chat rooms where she becomes jealous of
her made-up cyber persona, who gets invited to places the real Loh
wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   She follows this with an affair with a younger man, her ``Raging
Bull'' _ Tony ``ride me'' Pony, buff but dumb, and soon becomes
bored. Finally, she pulls out a piano and goes into ``Songs in the
Key of Me,'' her Joni Mitchell-independent woman stage.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she ends up dealing again with Bud and Robert Blair in
an unexpected way _ and in the meantime arrives at a bit of
enlightenment as she emerges from her adventures battle-scarred but
happier.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the action on stage is a bit too frantic as Loh jumps
from role to role. And cultural references fly off her tongue at a
dizzying rate, sometimes unnecessarily so. But those are minor
quibbles.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that ``Bud Kemp'' is a well-written piece of
theater. And though this is a familiar mating/war story, Loh's
force of presentation and smart battle observations make ``Bud
Kemp'' a pleasure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
