<SLUG> BC-COP-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONE TOUGH' FILM TO EMBRACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
Our rating: 2 Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``One Tough Cop'' plays like a particularly
uninspired episode of ``NYPD Blue'' that goes on too long. If your
idea of gritty police fun is spending an evening in a room full of
Andy Sipowiczes, you might get something out of it.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're not interested in self-destructive stupidity or
counting how many expletives can be squeezed into an
hour-and-a-half, you'll likely get bored pretty quick.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly taken from the autobiography of real ex-New York
supercop Bo Dietl, the film nonetheless plays like a formula TV
episode. Dietl (Stephen Baldwin) is brave, hotheaded and, of
course, on the edge. His partner, Duke (Chris Penn), is a reliable
backup, but troubled and doomed. Dietl's childhood best friend,
Rickie La Cassa (Mike McGlone), is, of course, a mob underboss.
Just as predictably, Dietl has an affair with his dangerous pal's
mistress Joey (Gina Gershon) at precisely the wrong moment _ like
there's ever a good time to betray your underworld-connected buddy.
</P>
<P>
   What happens is, a nun is raped and tortured; Rickie helps Dietl
and Duke crack the case, just as some feds are pressuring Dietl to
set up Rickie. Some glory hounds from downtown are out to screw
up/take credit for the real cops' hard, smart work. Oh, and Duke's
gambling debts are rising and he's drinking too much.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the third act comes around, everyone's so mad
they've forgotten how to talk, and just shout cuss words at one
another.
</P>
<P>
   It's like screenwriter Jeremy Iacone somehow got ahold of Steven
Bochco's plot point computer program and printed all the data out
in script form. To his credit, director Bruno Barreto, though a
long way from his Brazilian heyday of ``Dona Flor and Her Two
Husbands,'' gets good urban atmosphere up on the screen and
generally credible performances out of the always-angry ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   But every actor has, basically, the same three notes to play:
get outraged, spout off about tortured concepts of loyalty and make
self-defeating moves. No wonder their voices grow ever louder as
the movie plods along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
