<HEADER>
A6536 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN     10-08 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY TO AVOID `TAMING THE TIGER' 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
JONI MITCHELL/``Taming the Tiger'' (Reprise)
<TEXT>
<P>
   For her latest collection of tuneless wanderings and
cliche-ridden musings, the once mighty singer-songwriter mines the
jazz-fusion hybrid that served so well on landmark '70s albums like
``Hejira.'' Mitchell's atonal guitar chords wash over everything
here while saxophonist Wayne Shorter noodles away in some
pseudo-mystical fashion all the way through several mediocre
tracks. Mitchell herself, singing in a voice that seems to come and
go out of a rainstorm, offers semi-coherent diary jottings that
make Tori Amos look like Hemingway. Avoid ``Taming the Tiger'' and
buy another copy of ``Blue'' instead. 1 { Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DUNCAN SHEIK/``Humming'' (Atlantic)
</P>
<P>
   Can't honestly say I've heard this album, even though I've
played it something like eight times. Every time I give it a shot,
I fall into a deep sleep. Three times on the living room couch,
I've awoken with a start at midnight; twice in the car, I've had to
pull over and look for a shade tree; once, sitting in a
particularly uncomfortable hard chair, I began exhibiting the
symptoms of an electrocution, drool and all. Sheik, whose
atmospheric ``Barely Breathing'' from his 1996 self-titled debut
became a radio staple, is the Captain &AMP; Tennille of the '90s. Dull,
dull, dull. 1 Star. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HARVEY/``Is This Desire?'' (Island)
</P>
<P>
   Proving the de-evolution theory, Polly Jean Harvey's music
gradually becomes more accessible with each release. This album,
her fifth, follows the acclaimed 1995 effort, ``To Bring You My
Love,'' which garnered Grammy nominations and artist-of-the-year
accolades. ``Desire'' offers stark but generally upbeat character
studies of women like ``Angeline,'' the opening track, ``prettiest
mess you ever seen.'' Unlike past discs, Harvey's voice isn't
electronically altered often, and her Delta-inspired phrasing, by
way of the English countryside, lends an earthy feel. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VARIOUS/``VH1 Divas Live'' (Epic)
</P>
<P>
   VH1 brings together Celine Dion, Mariah Carey, Shania Twain,
Gloria Estefan, Aretha Franklin and Carole King for predictable
solo and group performances. If you're an unshakable fan of any
three of these MOR divas, or feel you simply must own yet another
rendering of Dion's shoot-me-before-I-hear-it-again ``My Heart Will
Go On,'' you might get your money's worth. However, anyone else
should pass on these generally overblown star turns. The exception
is any track featuring the great Aretha, a national treasure if
ever there was one. 1 { Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JOHN MELLENCAMP/``John Mellencamp'' (Columbia)
</P>
<P>
   Working-class hero Mellencamp hasn't forsaken his trademark
heartland rock 'n' folk sound on his first self-produced release
for a new label. The initial single, ``Your Life Is Now,'' suggests
all that is still worthy about the fellow, including signature
fiddle, sturdy rhythm guitar and heartfelt vocals. Longtime
Mellencampers will delight in ``Eden Is Burning,'' which revisits
Jack and Diane from '82's ``American Fool.'' Elsewhere, Mellencamp
seasons his meat 'n' potatoes approach with hints of funk, r&AMP;b and
a touch of reggae. 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NIRK FRANKLI/``The Nu Nation Project'' (GospoCentric)
</P>
<P>
   Gospel goes hip-hop. It's not a new story, but few do it better
than spirit-chasing superstar Franklin, who captures both the
intensity and abandon of the best parts of both genres on this
contemporary gospel effort. Best moments include funky opener
``Revolution'' and the star-studded ``Lean on Me,'' featuring
cameos from Mary J. Blige, Bono and R. Kelly. Praise Jesus and pass
the keys to the Jeep! 3 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHISKEYTOWN/``Faithless Street'' (Outpost)
</P>
<P>
   Originally issued on an indie two years ago, this was the
collection that got Raleigh, N.C., alt-country rockers Whiskeytown
noticed. Now a 21-song reissue boasting new artwork and nine bonus
tracks, this terrific disc proves singer-songwriter Ryan Adams is a
writer of many dimensions. The song list is almost entirely
wonderful, touching on a wide array of moods and styles.
``Faithless Street'' is even better than the album that received
the big push. 3 { Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UNKLE/``Psyence Fiction'' (London/MoWax)
</P>
<P>
   This concept album generally falls flat. UNKLE is an aggregation
headed by sample king DJ Shadow and MoWax label chief James
Lavelle, featuring cameos from such heavy hitters as Radiohead's
Thom Yorke, the Verve's Richard Ashcroft, the Beastie Boys' Mike D.
and, unexpectedly, Metallica's Jason Newsted. Unfortunately,
despite strong advance notice, the coldly disjointed and often
overly ambient ``Psyence Fiction'' rarely satisfies. Although
Shadow and Lavelle try, UNKLE is no Massive Attack. 2 Stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TONY BENNETT/``The Playground'' (Columbia)
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Tony Bennett made inroads with younger
audiences with a hugely successful ``MTV Unplugged'' concert and
album. Now he's going for the ``Sesame Street'' kids with ``The
Playground,'' an album of lovingly crafted favorites that include
duets with Kermit the Frog (``Bein' Green,'' ``Firefly''), Elmo and
Rosie O'Donnell (``Put on a Happy Face''). The appeal of this
wonderful recording won't be limited to children, though. Bennett
is in fine voice throughout, and ably backed as usual by the Ralph
Sharon Quartet, he alternates between moods both playful (``The
Bare Necessities,'' ``Dat Dere'') and wistful (``When You Wish Upon
a Star,'' ``The Inch Worm''). It's a tough trick to appeal to all
ages and stages, but Bennett has pulled it off. Beautifully. 3 {
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
