<SLUG> BC-MURDER-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLTWOOD'S SAME OLD SAME OLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When they say there's nothing new under the sun,
you know the film community takes that to the nth degree by
remaking everything that was old under the sun.
</P>
<P>
   This week on video we have two prime examples of where today's
Hollywood is finding its ``inspiration'': ``A Perfect Murder''
(Warner Bros.), which was based on the 1954 Hitchcock movie ``Dial
M for Murder,'' which was based on the stage play of the same name;
and ``Lost in Space'' (New Line), which was based on the campy
1960s television series, which was, of course, based on ``The Swiss
Family Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Hitchcock for inspiration is fairly common. A director
like Brian De Palma has practically made a career out of it,
turning out Hitchcockian films such as ``Obsession'' (1976) and
``Dressed to Kill'' (1980). But with ``A Perfect Murder'' and the
upcoming ``Psycho,'' filmmakers are going directly to the source,
and it also calls for comparisons to the master.
</P>
<P>
   As for old TV shows, there have been so many of them made into
feature films _ from ``The Addams Family'' to ``The Brady Bunch'' _
that the real question becomes ``What hasn't been made into a
movie?'' Considering some of the turkeys that have been foisted on
us recently _ ``McHale's Navy,'' ``Sgt. Bilko'' _ we can only hope
we're at the bottom of the well.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's nothing wrong with dipping into the past to create
something new. After all, Shakespeare borrowed some old plots for
some of his most important plays. But Shakespeare produced
masterpieces, and we are not talking about masterpieces here.
Actually, we'd settle for mildly diverting.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the 1960s TV series it was based on was truly
inane, it's almost surprising that ``Lost in Space'' is a fairly
enjoyable _ although predictable _ film. Maybe starting with a
silly premise is the way to go. The recent failure of ``The
Avengers'' is a perfect example of what not to do. In that case,
the filmmakers took a smart and sophisticated show and sucked out
all the charm while subbing in a bunch of odd special effects that
were suppose to distract you.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers behind ``Space'' were smart enough to keep the
general premise of the TV show and then throw out the rest. Instead
of a cardboard Robinson clan, this family is dysfunctional. John
(William Hurt), the father, works too hard, sending taped apologies
to his kids when he misses key events in their lives. The kids
(Heather Graham as the brainy Judy, ``Party of Five's'' Lacey
Chabert as rebellious teen Penny and Jack Johnson as 10-year-old
Will) are, of course, alienated, and mother Maureen (Mimi Rogers)
struggles to hold them all together. Dr. Zachary Smith (Gary
Oldman) is evil instead of insipid, and pilot Don West (Matt
LeBlanc) is a cocky loner rather than being a clean-cut bore. All
of this makes for better dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yeah, the robot is jazzed up, although it has the same
voice (Dick Tufeld). The action is fast-paced, and there are a
number of dazzling visual effects. All this adds up to a fun
package for any 13-year-old and younger while not boring older
viewers. The lesson here is not to rely on your original material.
Remember back then there were only three networks, and a lot of
stuff that was popular then won't cut it in today's world of
sophisticated content, multichannel TV, computer-generated
special-effects films.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``A Perfect Murder,'' it faced different problems. First,
``Dial M for Murder'' was minor Hitchcock. The director was forced
to film the cat-and-mouse stage play (in 3-D no less) because of
contractual obligations. Second, the play itself is a contrived
Agatha Christie-style knockoff.
</P>
<P>
   In the original, Ray Milland is a playboy married to heiress
Grace Kelly, who is infatuated with mystery writer Robert Cummings.
Fearing he'll lose her and her riches, he plots to have her
murdered. In the update, financier Michael Douglas, whose fortunes
are shaky, is worried that he will lose his rich young wife
(Gwyneth Paltrow) to a virile young painter (Viggo Mortensen) and
so plots to have her killed.
</P>
<P>
   So what have the filmmakers brought to this new adaptation?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Paltrow does have a great wardrobe, and wears it well. Her
Manhattan apartment is exquisitely decorated. The plot twists are
retwisted, but not necessarily for the better. Douglas keeps up a
malevolent presence. And did I mention Paltrow has a great
wardrobe?
</P>
<P>
   ``A Perfect Murder'' is not a bad movie; it's just sort of ``so
what?'' Its most controversial aspect was the pairing of
25-year-old Paltrow with the 54-year-old Douglas, which was also
``so what?'' since they didn't have any overly amorous scenes and
she was falling for a younger man.
</P>
<P>
   But this doesn't answer the question of why anyone bothered to
remake ``Dial M for Murder,'' unless they were fashion
connoisseurs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
