 &HT;    SOUTH IS HARD HIT AS 'SMOG' SPREADS, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    450&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unhealthy ozone pollution is showing up more often,
and Southern states are particularly hard hit, a public lobbying
group reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our findings are cause for alarm,'' said Rebecca Stanfield of
U.S. Public Interest Group, which analyzed air quality data from 41
states and the District of Columbia. ``People will continue to
become sick and die prematurely from air pollution until the
standards are met, and this means polluters need to start cutting
their emissions immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Between April 5 and Sept. 14 of this year, the group found,
there were at least 5,208 violations of the new, stricter ozone
pollution standard issued last year by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   That means that three out of four days in this period, someone
in the United States was breathing unheal
</P>
