<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOG09-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOUTH IS HARD HIT AS 'SMOG' SPREADS, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    450&AMP;add.
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects wording in 2nd sentence of 5th graf, starting ``If
the new ...''
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unhealthy ozone pollution is showing up more often,
and Southern states are particularly hard hit, a public lobbying
group reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our findings are cause for alarm,'' said Rebecca Stanfield of
U.S. Public Interest Group, which analyzed air quality data from 41
states and the District of Columbia. ``People will continue to
become sick and die prematurely from air pollution until the
standards are met, and this means polluters need to start cutting
their emissions immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Between April 5 and Sept. 14 of this year, the group found,
there were at least 5,208 violations of the new, stricter ozone
pollution standard issued last year by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   That means that three out of four days in this period, someone
in the United States was breathing unhealthy air, it said.
</P>
<P>
   The group said the new ``smog'' standard was violated 19 times
more often this year than the old, looser standard was last year.
If the new standard had been in effect in 1997, the number of
violations would have risen 27 percent this year, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution appeared not only more often, but also in some
unexpected places, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   California, long plagued with dirty air, violated the standards
on at least 79 days. But surprisingly, North Carolina was second
with 68 days, said Jayne(cq) Mardock of the Clean Air Network, an
environmental group that contributed to the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have considered it up there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mardock said North Carolina's air quality problems have a lot to
do with its rapid rate of growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got a lot of cars _ a lot of sprawl and new businesses,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas was ranked third with 62 days of unhealthy pollution, and
Georgia was fourth with 55. Other Southern states making U.S.
PIRG's ``dirty dozen'' list were Virginia, ranked 11th with 36
days, and Florida, ranked 12th with 33 days.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio was ranked 10th with 38 days.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new standards, air is considered dangerously polluted
when concentrations of smog reach .085 parts per million over an
eight-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   US PIRG called on Congress and the EPA to take action to reduce
smog from its two primary sources _ the electric power industry and
motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   They urged the EPA to expand its rules requiring summertime cuts
in pollution from power plants in 22 states. The rule should be
nationwide, year-long and should require cuts in other major power
plant pollutants such as sulfur and carbon dioxide, the report
says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report urges the EPA to adopt nationwide
emission standards for cars, trucks and sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution is especially harmful for the elderly, children,
and people with diseases such as chronic bronchitis, emphysema and
asthma, said Dr. Alfred Munzer, director of pulmonary medicine at
Washington Adventist Hospital and past president of the American
Lung Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``For asthma patients, a smoggy summer means missed work,
staying indoors instead of playing outside, and in too many cases,
spending the day in the emergency room instead of at summer camp,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report compiled and analyzed air quality data for 26 states
and Washington, D.C., where such information is available to the
public. It also used limited information from fifteen other states.
Nine states failed to provide enough data to be included in the
study.
</P>
<P>
   Mardock said the report's findings, while severe, probably don't
reflect the gravity of the nation's air quality problem because
many states did not include the months of August or September in
their data. Those months are often some of the worst for smog, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very conservative information,'' she said
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
