<SLUG> BC-SWING-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAYE P. MORGAN FINDS SWINGING DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It's probably due to that pesky Gap commercial, but
``Swing! Swing! Swing!'' is coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   The revue celebrates the booming big-band sound with stars who
were actually alive when this stuff was popular the first time
around, Herb Jeffries and the Sunnysiders among them. Also on
board: Jaye P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Hang on: (begin ital) Jaye P. Morgan? (end ital) The bawdy '70s
game show vet whose career consisted of getting bleeped on ``The
Gong Show''? What's next? Brett Somers as ``Evita?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the public's short memory. Maybe it's that none of
Morgan's songs was all that lasting. But in the '50s, everyone knew
her dark, sultry voice and hits such as ``That's All I Want From
You'' and ``The Longest Walk.''
</P>
<P>
   She will sing some of those in ``Swing! Swing! Swing!'' But
she's bluntly honest about her opinion of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not my concept of great music,'' she says. ``The '50s
were very dull musically. It's a lot like the bouffant hairstyle.
We were very glad once it was out.''
</P>
<P>
   A singer who dismisses her back catalog? That's chutzpah. But
Morgan, 68, has the perspective to separate her personal taste from
what the public expects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a jazz fiend. But I don't judge what I do professionally
with what my personal preference is. I'm a pop singer _ no matter
what I say, that's what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most singers of her time, she was comfortable on TV. When
the hits stopped, she did guest spots and game shows, what most
people remember her for.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do what's available,'' she says. ``It doesn't bother me
that people don't know I'm a singer. The whole key is that I'm
still standing in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what was it like working with Chuck Barris and Gene Gene the
Dancing Machine?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gong Show'' was just nutso,'' says Morgan, who never once
says anything bleepable during our chat. ``It was all irreverent
idiocy _ and I know how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   That playfulness worked in her other slice of TV immortality. On
an ``Odd Couple'' episode, she crooned Felix's tune ``Happy and
Peppy and Bursting With Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all I've done, that's what people remember,'' a bewildered
Morgan says. ``Probably because they've rerun it 450 million times.
People always want me to sing that song, and I do not remember a
word of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there goes one request. Here's another: Any chance that
she'll warble ``Pepper Hot Baby!,'' a 1955 hit where she crowed,
``Count to a hundred, HOO-HA!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so cruel,'' she says in an explosion of giggles. ``I
went in and recorded that song and never sang it again. Thank
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it never hurts to ask. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
