<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-TEEN-ABSTINENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJORITY OF TEENS ARE SEXUALLY ABSTINENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    For the first time in 20 years, a majority of American teenagers
are sexually abstinent, reports the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control.
 &HT;    ''Compared with 1991, the prevalence of sexual experience in
1997 decreased 11 percent,'' said the CDC. What's particularly
amazing is that sexually active male students fell by an even
larger 15 percent, from 57.4 percent to 48.8 percent who are
sexually active. Teen females experiencing intercourse dropped only
slightly from 50.8 percent in 1991 to 47.7 percent.
 &HT;    This is a major turnaround. The percentage of sexually active
girls aged 15-19 had jumped from only 29 percent in 1970 to 57
percent in 1988.
 &HT;    What is behind this remarkable transformation of ethics?
 &HT;    I give credit to the Southern Baptist's campaign called ''True
Love Waits'' under the leadership of Richard Ross, of the Baptist's
Life Way Christian Resources. He developed a campaign challenging
teens to sign pledge cards to remain sexually pure until marriage.
 &HT;    The pledge is eloquent: ''Believing that TRUE LOVE WAITS, I make
a commitment to God, myself, my family, those I date, my future
mate and my future children to be sexually pure until the day I
enter a covenant marriage relationship.''
 &HT;    In the early 1990s when the campaign began, public schools were
beginning to distribute condoms to reduce AIDS. To suggest that
teens might be persuaded to remain sexually abstinent was
considered naive at best or downright laughable. ''It is easier to
break a promise than a condom,'' said critics.
 &HT;    Yet the Journal of the American Medical Association reported
last month that ''Adolescents who reported having taken a pledge to
remain a virgin were at significantly lower risk of early age of
sexual debut. Nearly 16 percent of females and 10 percent of males
reported making such pledges.''
 &HT;    Those percentages translate into 2.5 million teens who have
pledged to be remain pure!
 &HT;    One strategy to motivate teenagers to sign the covenants was the
gathering of hundreds of thousands of signed pledges into a public
display. The first was in 1994 when 211,000 cards were planted for
blocks on the grassy mall between the Capitol and the Washington
Monument.
 &HT;    Why was this significant?
 &HT;    ''Teenagers often feel disenfranchised and routinely ignored by
adults when they have something important to say,'' said Ross.
''The display of pledge cards provides a way for teenage voices to
be heard by adults and the culture.''
 &HT;    The Washington display of signed pledges of purity on the
national mall was a watershed event. ''Before that date, abstinence
was rarely included in the national discourse on teenage sexual
involvement. Hearing that many teenage voices espousing a value
together caught the national attention of adults, educators, policy
makers and even parents,'' he said.
 &HT;    ''Now rarely is there public discussion of teenage sexuality
without abstinence being included as a viable topic of
discussion.''
 &HT;    In 1996, True Love Waits held a ''Through the Roof'' event in
Atlanta when a stack of 350,000 cards stretched from the floor of
the Georgia Dome to the ceiling with many left over.
 &HT;    On Feb. 12, 1999, hundreds of towns will organize their own
displays of pledge cards spanning a local bridge. On one side the
kids will plant a big sign with the year 1999 on it and 2000 on the
opposite side, symbolizing the span from one millennia to the next
with a strong commitment to moral purity by America's youth.
 &HT;    Will the teenagers of your church get involved?
 &HT;    Perhaps not, if your church is not Southern Baptist, Assembly of
God or Nazarene. I have been disappointed that only a few
evangelical denominations have joined this great campaign for
purity. Roman Catholics initially pledged cooperation, but the
number of Hispanic teens who are sexually active has not declined.
Where are the United Methodists, Presbyterians or any African
American denomination?
 &HT;    Any church could launch its own True Love Waits campaign by
using a new manual on how to do so for $14.95 plus shipping. Call
(800) 545-2766.
 &HT;    Challenge your kids to join this great crusade for moral purity.
 &HT;    Two teens recently told the Surgeon General why they signed up
5-6 years ago when they were in junior high. ''I thought it was a
good idea to stay pure for my future wife, so that it (sex) is
something sacred between my wife and I,'' said Brad Tomas. Monica
DePaz hoped by signing it to ``influence another teenager to make
that pledge.''
 &HT;    The Surgeon General was moved to confess he had had ``too little
to say'' about teen abstinence, but will now support chaste
teenagers.
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
