<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following travel features and columns moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLACES AND DESTINATIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOPIARY-GARDENS-HNS (Portsmouth, R.I.) _ Edward Scissorhands
would have felt at home in the Green Animals Topiary Garden
overlooking Narragansett Bay. The artistry the movie android
displayed in turning living plants into fascinating shapes can be
seen here in the spiraling shrubs, geometric forms, ornamental
designs and in the menagerie. By Mark Sommer.
</P>
<P>
   BARBADOS-TRAVEL-COX (Barbados) _ Tourists looking for the
``untouched'' Caribbean are in for a disappointment in Barbados.
There are no volcanoes or rain forests, and hardly any rivers. But
there are plenty of white sand beaches and lots of brighly painted
villages, flowering trees and open pastures. There are also a wide
variety of historic sites, dating back to the 17th century. There
are, for example, fabulous castles and forts to visit. Also, this
small island off South America's northern coast still retains
British influence and customs. Most people have high teas, even in
the middle of hot afternoons. By Shelley Emling.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT-VILLAGE-HNS (Weston, Vt.) _ Vermont can help you go back
to a place you never want to leave. In tiny Weston, for example,
there is an oval village green, an old mill dam, the restored 1797
Farrar-Mansur House and the Weston Priory, a Benedictine monastery
which welcomes the public to daily prayer. There's also the Vermont
Country Store, nostalgia central to southern Vermont. By Kate
Gurnett.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SANCTUARIES-HNS (Florence, Italy) _ Most of the year, a
convent here serves as home to an aging group of Franciscan nuns
and as a residence for young women attending college or graduate
school nearby. Off-season, the convent joins the some 2,000
religious houses worldwide that accept travelers for short stays
and guests for longer periods of quiet reflection. By Cecile S.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MUSEUMS-BOS (Boston) _ Boston has dozens of smaller
museums that cost nothing and are so underattended that visitors
often will find themselves alone. By Michael Kenney.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-WARSAW-BOS (Warsaw) _ The marvel of the reconstruction of
Warsaw is that it doesn't look like Disney. It looks real and
unchanged. By Christine Temin.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NEW-ZEALAND-BOS (Halfmoon Bay, New Zealand) _ New Zealand
is a great place for people who think aerobic exercise is something
pilots do at air shows. By M.R. Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TROUT-BOS (Inchbonnie, New Zealand ) _ Virtually everyone
who ever gets off the train here is met by Ray Grubb; they're all
going fishing. By M.R. Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FOLIAGE-BOS (Newbury, Vt.) _ Foliage, it seems, has only
been around for about 150 years in New England. That's because
before that the trees had all been logged away. By Lois Shea.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ST.PETERSBURG-SPI (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ Often called
``The Venice of the North'' for its architecture, beauty and
setting by water, St. Petersburg was founded in 1703 by Peter the
Great, who created out of a swamp the most northerly of the world's
great cities. The headstrong czar laid the foundation after his
victory over the Swedes in the Great Northern War. Nearly 300 years
later, in touring the city, Americans will feel almost on a
military timetable while visiting such famous attractions as the
Hermitage and the Peter and Paul Fortress. By Joel Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   HOSTELS-MAIN-COX (Undated) _ Two skiers were complaining about
the high price of lift tickets as we stood in line on the side of a
mountain in the exclusive ski town of Breckenridge, Colo. But I
really didn't care how much the lift tickets were because I had
already saved the real money. I wasn't staying in a $250-a-night
condo. I was paying $15 a night at a youth hostel. And that
included breakfast. By Cherly Blackerby.
</P>
<P>
   HOSTELS-RUSTIC-COX (Brunswick, Ga.) _ ``Mom, it's me. In case
you never hear from me again, I am calling from a place called The
Hostel in the Forest in Brunswick, Ga. I'm a little nervous about
staying here overnight. This guy from Germany gave me a tour of the
place _ he's a little scary-looking....'' And so begins one
person's adventure at a bare-bones hostel. By Cara Anna.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NAPA-VALLEY-HNS (Undated) _ I've been visiting
California's Napa Valley for more than 20 years; honeymooned there
once, in fact. And despite the too-often materialistic trappings of
Disneyland, it remains _ in part and certain parcels _ a magical
place for folks like me from the muggy flatlands. By Michael
Lonsford.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMER NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BOOKED-BOS (Undated) _ In Northern Vermont, where trees
are changing to scarlet, gold, violet, and orange, inns are booked
solid. By Cindy Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-HAWAII (Undated) _ Defying trend, Hawaii suffers tourist
slump. By Edwin McDowell. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS-REGULAR FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ Why travel around the world to
find a millennium party? Large-scale celebrations are planned all
over the United States. You can chant in the new century. Drum it
in. Or attend any among thousands of much-touted ``parties of the
century.'' By Harry Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ If all goes well, next week should
be prime time for foliage viewing throughout New England. By Jerry
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS (Undated) _ There is another claimant to the
birth of the burger besides Hamburg, Germany: the village of
Hamburg, N.Y. By Richard Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Snaring the elusive VAT refund.
By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Las Vegas headliners: Monet and Van
Gogh; Philadelphia packages for Delacrouix show; A Cathay Pacific
deal for fall travel to Asia.
