<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   APOCALYPTIC-RAPTURE (Undated) _ In an instant, millions of
people disappear from the face of the Earth, shedding clothing,
shoes, eyeglasses, jewelry. Were they snatched by aliens? Vaporized
by a spontaneous chemical reaction? No, what has occurred is the
Rapture. Jesus Christ has returned to take the genuine Christians
to heaven. So goes the plot of ``Left Behind,'' a series of four
books of apocalyptic fiction that have now sold nearly 3 million
copies _ as many as a John Grisham novel and have now ascended to
the top four slots on religion best-sellers lists. The ``Left
Behind'' phenomenon is one indication of the public's fixation on
the approaching millenium and the widespread anticipation that the
year 2000 portends some Earth-shattering event. By Laurie
Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   WHATDREAMS-HEAVEN-COX _ Heaven is a safe place. Heaven is fun,
full of color, filled with angels, a good place to visit and the
house of God. That's what some kids at St. Ann Roman Catholic
School in West Palm Beach, Fla. think about heaven. Last week, they
drew pictures of what heaven looks like to them. Some of them have
a more mature faith than many adults. A tie-in to the new release,
``What Dreams May Come.'' By Steve Gushee.
</P>
<P>
   WVA-BIBLE-BOS (Union, W.Va.) _ Ministers argue against the use
of the Bible in the classroom. Their concern: The Bible will be
denatured into mere literature. By Mitchell Zuckoff.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHURCH-ADVERTISING-NYT (New York) _ God's messenger these
days is as likely to be a Madison Avenue account executive as a
missionary. Religious advertisements have become savvier, slicker
and certainly wittier than the staid church announcements found on
the religion pages of newspapers. By Nadine Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ Whether or not anyone has cited
the story of David and Bathsheba either to defend or denounce
President Clinton on Sunday morning television, plenty of people
have done so in the Sunday morning pulpits. Quite a few of them
have even called Walter Brueggemann, professor of Old Testament at
Columbia Theological Seminary in Decatur, Ga., for advice.
Brueggemann is the author of a commentary for preaching on First
and Second Samuel, the two books in the Hebrew Scriptures that tell
the story of ancient Israel's transformation from a constellation
of tribes to a centralized monarchy under Saul and David. It is
also where the story of David and Bathsheba appears. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   RABBI-PRAYER-COX (West Palm Beach) _ The rabbi who wrote a
prayer President Clinton used did not write a sermon about him.
Rabbi Jack Riemer may be the only preacher in the country who did
not speak about the president's moral problems on Yom Kippur, the
Jewish day of atonement, last week. ``The purpose of the day is to
focus on our own sins,'' said Riemer. By Steve Gushee.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Boston) _ This is a story about a church,
race and class in American society, and an Episcopal diocese
working to remain a consequential player on the religious
landscape. By Diego Ribadeneira.
</P>
