<HEADLINE>
SUBSTITUTE MAILMAN? TIME TO GO POSTAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURIE NOTARO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The police department was mad at me.
</P>
<P>
   It was all documented in a letter they sent me saying that
because I had ignored a certified letter they had mailed regarding
a false burglar alarm at our house, I now owed them 74 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   This was curious, I thought. I hadn't received or signed for a
certified letter, but it really didn't surprise me. Ever since my
regular mailman _ the best, most dutiful civil servant the
government ever created, who has never once lost a piece of my mail
or shot a fellow worker _ had cut back his hours during the summer,
things had gone horribly awry. The substitute mail people were a
roguish lot, delivering my unemployment checks to everyone in the
neighborhood except me and leaving the rest of my mail on the
ground, if they even came by to deliver it at all.
</P>
<P>
   I've had experiences with nasty mail people before, including
one mailman at my old house who knocked on my door one day during
the holiday season and announced, ``It's Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ho, ho, ho!'' I said back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the time of giving,'' he emphasized, deadpan. ``And I
give to you every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, OK,'' I said hesitantly, getting his hint. ``Hang on!''
</P>
<P>
   I ran into the kitchen to find an appropriate gift and ran back
to the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy holidays,'' I said, placing three cigarettes and a
frozen Hungry Jack waffle in his hand. ``I picked up a big-screen
TV for you, but the pest-control guy spotted it while he was
spraying for fleas, and, well, he promised me he wouldn't dilute
next time and gave me some ointment for the bites.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, my mailbox was overflowing with all the Valu-Paks,
Kmart fliers and Peter Piper Pizza coupons that should have
rightfully gone to Glendale. I decided to shoot back, to play
tough, and left the 10 pounds of post-consumer recycled material
just where the Grinch had left it, refusing to take it into the
house.
</P>
<P>
   The following week, the creaks of the hinges echoed through the
hollow cave of the mailbox as I pulled the door down, and I smiled.
It was empty. I picked up a branch from a dead tumbleweed in my
yard and stuck it in the mailbox, afraid that the nut had put a
scorpion or dog doody way in the back. When I pulled out the stick,
a single piece of yellow paper fluttered to the ground at my feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``THIS RESIDENCE,'' it shouted, ``IS DECLARED VACANT BY THE
UNITED STATES POSTAL SERVICE.''
</P>
<P>
   The mailman had won, and my mail service didn't resume until I
grudgingly presented the mailman with a stun gun and gift
subscription to ``Penthouse.'' After that, I knew better than to
complain or mouth off in person to anyone wearing short black socks
and a visor. Their power is more obscene _ and far more
encompassing _ than Kenneth Starr's.
</P>
<P>
   I attempted to rectify the false-alarm bill by calling the
police department and explaining my mail situation, but they told
me that my only recourse was to write a letter to the alarm unit in
an attempt to get the charges dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   I gave it a shot, writing down all of the bad things the
substitute mailman had done, and just to be sure that there was no
hanky-panky going on, I drove to the post office and mailed it from
there. Three weeks later, I received a reply from a guy named
Harold, who, very simply put, said that he did not believe me.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, my husband and I were coming home from dinner,
and as we climbed the steps to the porch, he looked up and then
pointed. ``What's that?'' he said as we both stared at the huge,
looming object hovering in the rafters of the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a message,'' I said quietly as my husband tried
to reach it. My worst fears were confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a package from J. Crew, containing a cute little sundress
that I thought I'd be skinny enough to wear when I was on my diet.
It was also about two weeks overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's telling me to back off,'' I said to my husband in a
panic. ``He's telling me I've gone too far this time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's telling you?'' he asked me in a whisper. ``If you're
talking to God, would you ask him where I put that Foreigner CD?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The substitute mailman!'' I shouted. ``Don't you understand?
This is a horse's head! He found out about my letter to the police
department! It's a warning! Now, if anyone, even your brother, asks
you to go fishing in a small little rowboat, you say no unless you
want to sleep with the fishes!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Italian talk!'' he replied. ``You know I don't
understand Italian talk!''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I waited to see what would happen. I posted myself
by the window for hours to make sure I saw the substitute mailman
when he came, positive that he was going to try and slip me another
message, like a severed ear wrapped in a yellow vacant-house
notice.
</P>
<P>
   I heard him shuffle up the path. I heard him whistle. I heard
him open the slot to the mailbox. And then a miracle happened. As I
peeked out the window, I saw him standing in my yard. He waved. My
old mailman, the best mailman in the world, was back.
</P>
<P>
   I ran down the porch steps and threw my arms around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're back!'' I cried. ``So many bad things have happened
since you left!''
</P>
<P>
   I told him all about the police letter, the missing unemployment
checks and the J. Crew package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on the roof?'' he asked in disbelief. ``Boy, I sure am
sorry. Makes me feel guilty for all of that time I spent fishing on
the lake this summer. I just got a little Coleman rowboat. It's a
beauty! You should come with me sometime!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, thanks for the invitation,'' I said, trying not to
flinch, ``but I have to spend all of my time working so I can buy
you a big-screen TV for Christmas!''
</P>
<P>
   ``And a Taser?'' he asked with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on my way to the gun store!'' I laughed. ``ZZZZZ!!!'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
