<HEADLINE>
SCOTTSDALE RATED TOPS FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz., - Theresa Romero nestled into a lounge chair
a Scottsdale spa, sipping ice water and awaiting a massage. She was
hard at work, really, laboring to zap stress from her life.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask`` Ladies Home Journal,'' she came to the right place.
</P>
<P>
   The bastion of words for women has dubbed Scottsdale the
nation's least stressful city for women and ranked the city third
overall for women's quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   And, the woman at the city's helm says, who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a wonderful quality of life here,'' Mayor Sam
Campana says. ``It's like a perpetual vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine states that _ in addition to being the nation's
``most chilled-out'' city _ Scottsdale ranks third-highest behind
Ann Arbor, Mich., and Madison, Wisc., for women overall. Phoenix
ranked 81st.
</P>
<P>
   The article, which is to hit newsstands Tuesday, cites low
crime, divorce and unemployment rates and good health practices
among the reasons the city is ideal for women.
</P>
<P>
   The study also considered a ``beauty index,'' in which it judged
cities based on such criteria as the number of potential bad hair
days.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale didn't fare as well in the beauty vain. Blame it on
the bone-dry air and cloudless days, said Margot Gilman, the
article's editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a little humidity for body,'' she said. ``And
sunshine, well, that's bad for the skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Romero, a businesswoman and mother of two who has lived in
Scottsdale her whole life, and her husband, Rene, lounged at
Scottsdale's Stress Less Step to relax.
</P>
<P>
   They think the city's trademark restaurants, resorts, golf
courses and nightspots add to an easygoing lifestyle in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as a city, I'd say this is definitely one of the least
stressful cities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The city also emerged from the study with an additional
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its spectacular setting of desert scapes and mountains, plus
fiery sunsets and a smorgasbord of five-star restaurants, also
lands Scottsdale in our top 10 romantic cities,'' the article
states.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine rated the cities based on crime, jobs, lifestyle,
health, education, politics, child care and economy.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale ranked high in public safety, politics and economy in
particular, Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
   The city also scored big because the mayor, city attorney,
school district superintendent and second in command in the police
department are women, Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at how large a share of the political power
structure was held by women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also considered such factors as the number of
women's doctors, sexual harassment claims filed and crimes against
women reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Women in Scottsdale) should just celebrate where they are and
what they've got,'' Gilman said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
