<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-AFC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFC'S COUP OVER RIVAL CONFERENCE APPEARS TO BE SUCCEEDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five weeks of NFL football are behind us, and
one thing has become clear: Nobody should be surprised if the AFC
starts owning the league the way the NFC once did.
</P>
<P>
   The AFC proved the better conference in January when Denver
upset Green Bay in Super Bowl XXXII. The win stunned many, but
those paying close attention could have seen a subtle transition in
the making, one that is obvious today.
</P>
<P>
   AFC teams have won 15 of the 20 interconference games this year.
That's a winning percentage of 75 percent and a mark that
represents where the league's strength lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people want to try and figure it out,'' said Oakland
Raiders senior assistant coach Bruce Allen. ``But I don't know if
there's a way it can be figured out. Denver is a good team. Kansas
City is a good team. Seattle is a good team. Unfortunately, those
three are all in our division, but there are just good teams in the
AFC.''
</P>
<P>
   There are substantially more good teams in the AFC than in the
NFC. Denver hasn't fallen from its Super Bowl standard.
Jacksonville, undefeated like the Broncos, has been a popular pick
to be playing for the Super Bowl. The Chiefs are strong, Seattle
and Miami are better and Pittsburgh will resolve its problems.
</P>
<P>
   We could go on and on because there are few NFC teams to
interrupt the flow in that chain of thought. Only Green Bay, the
49ers and Minnesota rank among the top 10 teams at this stage. It's
a toss-up as to who else from that conference could be deserving of
a playoff spot when postseason rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay has pulled a Carolina. Atlanta and New Orleans, both
3-1, are operating under smoke screens. And as for the NFC East ...
well let's not even go there.
</P>
<P>
   This is about the AFC right now. It's been a long time since
this conference could stake a legitimate claim to being the
dominant sector. AFC teams finished 31-28-1 in interconference
games last season and 32-28 in 1996. Prior to those two seasons,
the conference was 27-33, 25-27, 27-25, 22-30, 19-33 and 26-26
dating back to 1990. The AFC's best season ever against the NFC was
1979, when it won 69.2 percent of the games (36-16).
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two conferences comes down to two
factors: quarterbacks and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the significance of the signal-caller, let's point
to the Raiders. They're 3-2, with their victories coming against
NFC East teams. Two of the three quarterbacks they faced in those
games (the New York Giants' Danny Kanell and Arizona's Jake
Plummer) already have thrown a combined 15 interceptions. The other
guy, Jason Garrett, is hoping to just keep Dallas afloat until Troy
Aikman returns.
</P>
<P>
   If the Raiders are feasting on NFC mediocrity, just imagine
what's going on with the rest of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NFC has the best quarterback in football in Brett
Favre as well as Steve Young and Aikman, the talent level after the
big three isn't impressive. Minnesota has two good ones in reserve
Randall Cunningham and injured starter Brad Johnson, and Atlanta's
Chris Chandler and Chicago's Eric Kramer are underrated, but
there's little else.
</P>
<P>
   The AFC trots out John Elway, Dan Marino, Drew Bledsoe and Mark
Brunell, and also boasts of a better stable of young talent. Peyton
Manning, Ryan Leaf, Steve McNair, Kordell Stewart (though he's only
completing passes in commercials) and Buffalo's Rob Johnson have
bright futures.
</P>
<P>
   What does the NFC have in its youth movement besides Plummer and
Detroit's Charlie Batch? Tony Banks? Danny Wuerffel? Bobby Hoying?
They'll be holding clipboards by the millennium, which is a nice
segue because it brings us to the men they'll be standing next to.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know where some of the NFC's best coaches went,
just look to the other conference. Miami's Jimmy Johnson and the
New York Jets' Bill Parcells have two Super Bowl rings each from
their NFC tenures, and the last time the 49ers won the Super Bowl,
Denver's Mike Shanahan was calling the plays.
</P>
<P>
   All the NFC has to hang its hat on these days is its heavy
hitters. The Packers and 49ers are still among the top four teams
in football and Minnesota is closing fast. Each has a potent
offense and a coach schooled in the Bill Walsh mind-set, but the
wealth of imagination has spread itself around the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   NFC teams once dominated because they were more physical. They
also won with creative offensive systems that finessed opponents
into frustration. But those factors that helped them capture 13
straight Super Bowls titles prior to Denver's win aren't so
intimidating, and the most of their teams live on the wrong side of
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Broncos told us the balance of power was
shifting in the NFL. Now we're realizing just how much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
