<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall: The House debates and
then votes to open an inquiry into the impeachment of President
Clinton. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: For all the talk
of duty and Constitution Thursday, it was not all that difficult
for the House to open a formal impeachment inquiry into President
Clinton. The more troublesome question is how Congress will bring
to a conclusion the impeachment process that Rep. Henry Hyde called
``this venture, this excursion, this journey.'' By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VOTE (Washington) _ As he opened two hours of debate
over whether the House should initiate impeachment proceedings,
Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the Judiciary Committee, warned
Republicans and Democrats alike that ``too much hangs in the
balance for us not to rise above partisan politics.'' Yet the
quarreling on the House floor was plainly partisan. So was the
258-176 subsequent vote as only 31 of the 206 House Democrats
joined the Republican majority and signed on to the resolution for
an open-ended impeachment inquiry. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCENE (Washington) _ Only in America could the debate on
authorizing an impeachment investigation of President Clinton
