<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GILBERT-ARCHITECTU     10-08 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GILBERT-ARCHITECTURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASS GILBERT AND THE CITY ECLECTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You, too, can stand where Leona Helmsley stood: on
the steps of the only palace in the world where the Queen stood
trial. Or, you can go off in quest of your own personal Elvis
sighting, at the army depot where the newly drafted King shipped
out.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Courthouse on Foley Square and the Brooklyn Army
Terminal, the settings for these momentous civic occasions, are
just two of the seven buildings included in the third annual Open
House, a self-guided tour sponsored by the Alliance for Downtown
New York. This year, the event celebrates the architecture of Cass
Gilbert, a pivotal figure in defining the public face of New York
in the early years of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Or faces, rather, for Gilbert showed that the city's prevailing
civic spirit could wear more than one visage. Gothic,
neo-classical, Beaux-Arts; Georgian, even proto-Modern: the Gilbert
Open House offers a feast of architectural styles, an eclectic
range unsurpassed by any architect in New York before or since.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gilbert did his best to make each building faithful to
its chosen style _ ``as pure as I can make it,'' in the architect's
words _ he also helped fashion New York's image as a wondrous,
latter-day Babel, a metropolis as polyglot in its architecture as
in its surging immigrant population.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert was himself an immigrant, of sorts, a native of the
Midwest who came to New York to hit the big time. After a two-year
apprenticeship in New York with McKim, Mead &AMP; White starting in
1880, Gilbert spent the next two decades building his reputation in
Minnesota until he won a highly sought commission in 1899 to build
the new United States Custom House at the tip of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ship's come in.'' he wrote to his wife. ``She's in the
harbor now!'' And the harbor would never be the same. His buildings
would go on to shape the city in the image of a great mountain to
be scaled by the culturally ambitious, an Everest of desire. With
structures like the Woolworth, West Street and Broadway-Chambers
buildings, Gilbert helped plant the seeds for what Kurt Vonnegut
would later call Skyscraper National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The courthouse is a good place to begin the self-guided tour. A
small survey of Gilbert's career is on view in the lobby, and a
guidebook, with an excellent text by Anthony Robins, is also
available. But I would suggest the Broadway-Chambers Building as a
preliminary stop. Completed in 1900, this was Gilbert's first New
York building. It offers a good introduction to what made him tick.
</P>
<P>
   A pragmatist, Gilbert once described skyscrapers as machines for
making the land pay. But he also believed that beauty was essential
to the proper working of the machine. His buildings both
embellished and sublimated the connection between beauty and money,
the equation that makes New York go around.
</P>
<P>
   How easily New York digests buildings once acclaimed as
masterpieces. Today it's possible to walk right by and not even
yawn. But, on the Broadway-Chambers building's completion in 1900,
the critic Montgomery Schuyler praised it as the finest skyscraper
in town.
</P>
<P>
   Models and drawings were shown that year at the Paris
Exposition, where Parisians were awed by the building's 18 stories
and gave it a prize.
</P>
<P>
   This building type suffered from low esteem. People regarded it,
with reason, as a monster of commerce. Gilbert gave it a reason to
hold its height up high. Architects had already established the
analogy with the classical column, dividing it into the tripartite
arrangement of base, shaft and capital.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert refined the proportions between these elements and
articulated them by using different materials for each: stone base,
brick shaft, terra cotta crown. The brickwork, red flecked with
blue, is especially fine. In contrast with the light-colored stone
and terra cotta, it gives an almost colonial feel to an otherwise
classically conceived structure. Garlands, cornucopias and a
polychrome penthouse arcade garnish the composition.
</P>
<P>
   The building was completed the same year Freud published ``The
Interpretation of Dreams,'' a book that still sheds light on the
sublimation of desire embodied by this building. The craving for
money, represented by height, and the longing for beauty, signified
by classical style, spiral round each other into the sky. This is
architecture for a city that pays top dollar for the most
conspicuous beauty, if not always the best.
</P>
<P>
   At the Woolworth Building, two blocks south, financial gain is
wedded to religiosity as well as beauty, with Gothic tracery that
seeks to render this ``Cathedral of Commerce'' into the
ecclesiastical tradition of Chartres. But how could even
Woolworth's towering spire compete with the soaring skyline then
taking form?
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems a misty architectural shape is taking up into itself
like individual building stones, the skyscrapers, tenements,
thoroughfares, and people; and with the mass of them erecting a
tower higher than any of them, even the highest, toward the sky,''
wrote the critic Paul Rosenfeld in 1925, when the Woolworth
Building, once the world's tallest, was relatively new. But Gilbert
carved some of that tower's most impressive stones.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert was often ornate but seldom opulent. His buildings don't
offer the voluptuous sensuality analyzed by Suzannah Lessard in
``The Architect of Desire,'' her book about her grandfather,
Stanford White.
</P>
<P>
   This may reflect a difference between clients as well as eras.
White's clients wanted to flaunt wealth, Gilbert's preferred to
earn it. In the lobby of the Woolworth Building, a sculpted
caricature shows the merchant Frank W. Woolworth diligently
counting nickels and dimes, while a carving of the architect
clutches a model of his design: beauty for sale.
</P>
<P>
   All those in favor of abolishing the income tax please report to
the Collector's office at the Alexander Hamilton Customs House on
Bowling Green. Through this building passed a hefty chunk of the
federal budget. At the turn of the century, in the pre-income tax
era, the nation's revenues derived largely from customs duty, and a
big piece of it washed up here.
</P>
<P>
   This building was a machine for making the ocean pay, a function
clearly expressed in the ornate decoration of the Collector's
office, with its motif of gilded scallop shells and cornucopias,
punctuated by an occasional pineapple, a symbol of hospitality.
Looking out the window toward Broadway extending north, you feel as
if you're in the one-time inner sanctum of the capital of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Traders declared the value of their cargo at the elliptical desk
in the building's grand rotunda, then shuffled across the corridor
to pay tariffs (the cashier's grilles were retained in a handsome
restoration of the building by Ehrenkrantz and Eckstut in 1994).
</P>
<P>
   This cash cow, the most ornate of Gilbert's Beaux-Arts
buildings, is now home to the Bankruptcy Court of the Southern
District of New York. It also houses the colorful treasures of the
George Gustav Heye Center of the National Museum of the American
Indian.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary critics evidently found it painful to praise
Gilbert's West Street Building (1905-07), as if skyscrapers were
still something to be embarrassed about. The Caliban has become _
if not Ariel _ human, at all events, wrote Claude Bragdon, of a
building that now stands in the shadow of those Caliban Twins, the
World Trade Center towers.
</P>
<P>
   The West Street Building had a rooftop restaurant, too, called
the Garret, nestled beneath Gilbert's mansard roof. But here the
wedding cake top itself looks edible.
</P>
<P>
   An Edwardian, high-rise version of a Loire chateau, this
commercial building once stood at the edge of the Hudson and now
gazes toward Battery Park City. Louis Sullivan would have stopped
at the 16th floor, but Gilbert kept right on going, trimming the
top with a three-story arcade and a row of dormer windows peering
out through Gothic trefoils.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Open House originated with officials of the
U.S. 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals, based in Gilbert's last
building. I have particular affection for the United States
Courthouse. It graces the view from my window. The gilded pyramid
at the top, illuminated after dark, is a friendly neighbor to have
on longer winter nights. During the day, it's pleasing to take out
the binoculars and scan the steps for rogues.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the public will have access to the appeals court on
the building's 17th floor. But the exterior of the courthouse is
more impressive than the spaces inside. Gilbert had designed the
United States Supreme Court building in Washington, and this was to
be its New York counterpart, the focal point of the architect's
unrealized vision for a monumental civic plaza. Yet even here,
justice stretches toward skyline heights, with a tower rising from
a base of colonnades.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though the courthouse's front stairs are a New York
institution, the building is a strangely alien presence: a
Midwestern office building atop a Washington refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Le Corbusier included a picture of the Brooklyn Army Terminal in
his 1925 ``Toward a New Architecture,'' a book that changed the
course of architecture in this century. It is the great revelation
of Sunday's Open House. A pair of poured concrete structures joined
by three bridges, the terminal was designed and completed in less
than a year. Here, toward the end of World War I, men, munitions
and other supplies arrived by train, were unloaded through
cantilevered balconies overhead, and transferred to waiting ships.
</P>
<P>
   Though devoid of period style, the complex is frankly Beaux-Arts
in its massing, proportions and window detail. The plan, which uses
three bridges to connect two warehouses, betrays a classical sense
of organization. So does the axial symmetry of the terminal's most
spectacular space: the atrium where the trains pulled in.
</P>
<P>
   Normally closed to the public, this might be called a cathedral
of industry, and it shows why modernists like Le Corbusier believed
that functional design could rise to the level of high art. A pity
that an opaque canopy now covers the train platform. You must
strain your neck to take in the full impact of the staggered
balconies that rise seven stories above the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   You have to arrive at Pier 11 in Manhattan by 2 p.m. to catch
the free ferry service to the Brooklyn Army Terminal. This is a
shame, because Gilbert's concrete tour de force would be a perfect
climax to the day.
</P>
<P>
   Before boarding the ferry back, you can salute Elvis, or at
least a picture of him that hangs in the Terminal's lobby. Bye,
bye, Birdie.
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Here is a schedule of the Cass Gilbert Celebration
events. All are in Manhattan, except a museum exhibition and house
tour at the Keeler Tavern Museum in Ridgefield, Conn. The
exhibitions feature photographs, renderings and text related to the
architect's life and career. Unless noted, admission is free; a
guidebook is available today for $3 from the Alliance for Downtown
New York, 120 Broadway, between Cedar and Pine Streets; on Sunday
the books can be purchased at several sites listed below. General
information: (212) 835-2789.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
