<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUET-THEATER-REVIEW-A     10-08 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUET-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEE, WHAT A NIGHT FOR ROMANCE: YOU, ME AND THE MOONLIGHT (RIBET) 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marcia has some serious boy problems. She's gaga for
Mike, the handsome new crooner over at that slick dive, Noam
Pearlstein's Pearl Onion. Although he's taken a shine to Marcia,
too, Mike is the weak, silent type, and here's where it all gets,
well, a little slimy. Mike's weakness isn't vodka or cocaine, fast
cars or easy money. It's frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, frogs. When he eyeballs a mangled pile of amphibious
roadkill during a moonlit stroll with Marcia, Mike's studied aplomb
deserts him, and he's on that squashed frog like a man on a date
with his dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The distracted Marcia, played by a deliciously seductive Erin
Quinn Purcell, doesn't notice at first what Mike (the inspired
Gregory Jackson) is up to. But when she pivots and takes in the
sight of Jackson squatting and chowing down minced frog, it's a
delirious moment, an example of comedy of the gross-out variety,
yet carried off with a beguiling urbanity and style.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of comic impertinence at which the Adobe
Theater Company excels, and which bubbles forth with effervescent
glee in ``Duet!,'' the downtown troupe's offbeat lampoon of the
American way of mating.
</P>
<P>
   The show, written by ackson and Ms. Purcell, who directed it
with help from Jeremy Dobrish, Adobe's artistic director, is a
delightful sendup of that wholesome staple, the boy-meets-girl
story, and at the same time a bewitching spoof of the tacky
Hollywood and Broadway values that over they years have made that
story such a wonderfully easy target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duet!,'' subtitled ``A Romantic Fable,'' was a major success
for Adobe last season, in a short run at the Ohio Theater in SoHo,
and now the production has been remounted at the Actors' Playhouse
in the West Village for an open-ended run.
</P>
<P>
   The little troupe, which gained a following among young
audiences with its smart, low-rent conceits and disarming,
spectator-friendly innovations _ like rolling onto the stage a
pay-what-you-can bar before and after performances _ took a big
risk with this show; it accepted the backing of a major Broadway
producer, Dodger Endemol Productions, whose current ventures
include such far-from-downtown spectaculars as ``Titanic'' and
``Footloose.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, though: no fancy-schmancy triple-decker sets have
been added. The Dodgers, as they are known, have not tampered with
a winning formula, and so ``Duet!'' has lost none of the
seat-of-the-pants feel that made it such a gem on Wooster Street.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it looks more down-market than it did before, which
is not on the whole a great thing: the Actors' Playhouse is a
strange little theater on Seventh Avenue, with low ceilings and a
vaguely unwelcoming ambiance, which the Adobe people seek to combat
with beaming ushers who thank you for coming and all but seem
poised, like flight attendant trainees, to load you down with
blankets and pillows.
</P>
<P>
   This eagerness to please is part and parcel of the company's
charm. What sets Adobe apart is its ability to harness the youthful
esprit, the comradely elan, of college theater and buff it to a
more professional gloss. Thus ``Duet!'' gets away with silly bits
so purposefully sophomoric they make you laugh in spite of
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pearl Onion, for instance, when a tap-dancing candy girl,
played as a ditzy second banana with terrific timing by Kathryn
Langwell, breaks into a version of ``Anything Goes'' in Cantonese,
there's a funny subtext. This surely is a production in which
anything is meant to go.
</P>
<P>
   The straitlaced, rubber-faced Jackson, who takes a page from
Steve Martin's comic book, and the voluptuous Ms. Purcell,
platinum-blonded-up to resemble a latter-day Marilyn, lead the
merry ensemble through a fractured version of an overwrought stock
story, the girl who falls for the guy with the terrible secret.
</P>
<P>
   It all begins with an encounter of the Kismet variety at the
Pearl Onion: Marcia falls in love the moment Mike begins to sing,
ever so eerily, a song that gives the barest hint of an unhealthy
self-involvement, ``My Echo, My Shadow and Me.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From there, ``Duet!'' spins wittily and nattily from one
vignette to the next, parodying the conventions of the dating game.
Naive Marcia invites Mike to meet her parents, who are as bizarre
as they come. Dad (Frank Ensenberger) is a catatonic dropped in
front of a television set; Mom (Derin Basden) is a dipsomaniac who
gets way too comfortable with her daughter's beau.
</P>
<P>
   There's a hilarious re-creation of a roller-coaster ride,
accomplished with a couch, a horizontal bar and a few synchronized
jerks of the body, and a terrific mime show of a
sweet-as-cotton-candy date, accompanied by insipidly jaunty movie
intermission music.
</P>
<P>
   But Marcia's bliss is short-lived thanks to Mike's distasteful
culinary habits. Whether it's wearing unironed shirts or feasting
on swampy entrails, men really are savages, aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   As much as it's intended to poke fun at modern romance,
``Duet!'' supplies a funny, running commentary on modern
entertainment. Beginning with the sleazy hamminess of the Pearl
Onion, presided over by the oily Noam Pearlstein (Henry Caplan)
doing his abysmal magic tricks, the production plays continually
with our collective show-biz sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma''-style dream sequences, burlesque comics, B-movie
melodramatics and even the Muppets come in for some delectable
ribbing; an exotic dancer in a leopard-spotted bikini (Beau Ruland)
gyrates cheekily with phallic snakes and spears in a pre-show
warm-up act. And it's all treated so good-naturedly that the comedy
never comes across as harsh or jaded.
</P>
<P>
   While the designer Steven Capone does admirable work with a
minimal set _ his retractable translucent moon is lovely, and the
hoot owl that terrifies Marcia is a clever surprise _ a few of the
production's incidental elements have not transferred as well.
</P>
<P>
   Caplan looks a little too callow as the buffoonish lounge maven,
and the play's final scene, involving the visitation of a host of
plagues and disasters, is both dimly lighted and badly staged. But
with a company this droll, you're quick to forgive the lapses.
What's a shot or two off the mark when so much of the evening is
on? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DUET!
</P>
<P>
   A Romantic Fable
</P>
<P>
   Written by Gregory Jackson and Erin Quinn Purcell; directed by
Jackson, Ms. Purcell and Jeremy Dobrish. Sets by Steven Capone;
costumes by Daryl A. Stone; lighting by Paul Ziemer; sound by Chris
Todd; original songs by Michael Garin; production supervision,
Harris Production Services; production stage manager, Sarah
Bittenbender; general manager, Dodger Management Group. Presented
by the Adobe Theater Company. At the Actors' Playhouse, 100 Seventh
Avenue South, Greenwich Village. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Beau Ruland (Exotica Dancer), Henry Caplan (Noam
Pearlstein), Kathryn Langwell (Lydia Fishback), Erin Quinn Purcell
(Marcia), Gregory Jackson (Mike), Frank Ensenberger (Lud, Stump,
Cop and Supervisor), Derin Basden (Shadow, Mrs. Wolf, Woody, Boss
and Doctor) and Chris Klimkoski (Percussionist).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6716 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHMENT-INQUIRY-E     10-08 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-INQUIRY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS CONGRESS GOING TOO FAR? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 From the Economist magazine  
  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week beginning
October 10, 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American public, if opinion polls are to be believed, would
like the Lewinsky affair to be forgiven. Some of Bill Clinton's
supporters would have liked him to have resigned, in order to hand
power smoothly to Al Gore and to bring the Clinton presidency to an
honorable close.
</P>
<P>
   Given that he hasn't, they think it would be wrong for Congress
to impeach him, as they consider his crimes and misdemeanors to
have been low ones rather than the high sort demanded by the
Constitution as grounds for such a punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign leaders have queued up to express their astonishment
that America is spending its time arguing about sex, lies and
videotape while the world economy spirals earthward.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Judiciary Committee of the House of Representatives
voted this week to recommend that an impeachment inquiry be
launched, and the full House has voted to accept that
recommendation, with support from quite a few Democrats as well as
the Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   Might the public, and the supporters, and the foreign leaders be
correct? Surely Congress, particularly its Republican majority, is
going too far?
</P>
<P>
   To take that view is to misunderstand what President Clinton has
done and, as so often, to let sex blur the issue and cloud the
mind. With so much known about the salacious details of a sad
relationship, it has come to seem as if the issue is whether a
president is entitled to some privacy.
</P>
<P>
   On this view, his affair was ``inappropriate,'' as he has
admitted, but so are many affairs. His judgment was poor, but so is
that of many brilliant and otherwise resolute men when it comes to
matters of love and lust. He lied, in public and in sworn
testimony, but he did so as a man trapped by right-wing enemies and
intrusive prosecutors, desperate to protect his privacy and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   If you are satisfied with that account, you may think that
impeachment is an absurdly disproportionate punishment. But before
examining whether that account is in fact adequate, one awkward
point also needs to be kept in mind. Even on this sympathetic
account, Clinton has broken the law -- a law he swore to uphold
when taking the oath of office at his two inaugurations.
</P>
<P>
   So, at the very least, he needs somehow to be punished.
Otherwise, a signal will be sent to every American that some sorts
of law-breaking are acceptable, or that there is one standard for
the high and mighty and another for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, under the Constitution, for Congress to
mete out that punishment it needs first to hold an inquiry. Having
done that, it could well, as ex-President Gerald Ford suggested
this week, deliver Clinton a rebuke rather than impeaching him and
removing him from office. Such a compromise may even be Clinton's
own hope. But to get to that point, a proper and open process has
to be gone through.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, it would be best if that process were short. But to
understand why even that cannot be guaranteed, as well as why an
inquiry is justified for other reasons, it is worth questioning
whether the sympathetic account of Clinton's conduct is really as
adequate as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this account becomes plain when you move beyond
what happened to consider how it happened. None of it -- the
affair, the lies, the alleged obstruction of justice, the two sets
of sworn testimony by Clinton -- happened quickly, as if with a
rush of blood to the head. It all happened slowly, which implies
that most, perhaps all, of his actions were calculated. The
testimony was well planned. He knew well in advance that Monica
Lewinsky was becoming embroiled in the Paula Jones case. There was
time to think, to discuss alternative courses extensively with
advisers, to find jobs for her.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sex sounds as if it was carefully calculated. All in
all, this does not feel simply like a story of foolish decisions by
a cornered, passionate man.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, after hearings, Congress will decide that that is
indeed the motif of this story. But the reason why Kenneth Starr,
the independent counsel, was originally appointed was the suspicion
of a pattern of obstructive and evasive behavior; and Clinton's
behavior when the Lewinsky affair merged with the Paula Jones case
did, on the face of it, fit that pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the suspicion endures that such behavior may also have
manifested itself in matters other than sex -- matters that even
his sympathizers might consider more serious. It is that, combined
with the Lewinsky evidence, which offers ample cause for an
impeachment inquiry, one with a chance of flushing out evidence of
other offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this will end with an impeachment, let alone removal
from office (a separate action, by vote of the Senate) it is too
early to say. The constitution is vague enough to support a view
that his crime is too low for an impeachment -- or that by
betraying his trust and breaking his oath of office Clinton has
done more than enough to deserve to be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the adopted cliche of congressmen of both parties, it is
right to ``take a deep breath'' and begin the inquiry. The only
irresponsible action would be to stop now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
