<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME IS GOLDEN FOR SENIOR GOLFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ Thirty years ago, all Walter Hall wanted was a
PGA Tour card. Four times, he tried qualifying school. Four times,
he failed.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, was he ever lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the right temperament then to be a tour pro,''
said Hall, who turned to a career in sales for Brown-Rogers-Dixson,
a North Carolina appliance distributor. ``I was too young, too
immature, too temperamental.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the 51-year-old ``rookie'' tees it up with 77 other
``seniors'' shooting for a $1 million purse at the Transamerica and
offering examples of graceful aging. Reminding us that timing is
everything, they bring a range of success stories much wider than
the tree-lined fairways at Silverado Country Club:
</P>
<P>
   John Jacobs, the golf school magnate, leads the Senior Tour in
driving distance with an average of 284 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Don January, who'll turn 69 next month, is the oldest player in
the field and has won $62,861 while playing in 17 events this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Duval, who turns 52 on Friday, is better known as father of
PGA Tour star David Duval than as the Senior Tour's No. 17 money
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Gary McCord, the CBS golf live wire and ``Tin Cup'' star, never
won on the PGA Tour. He turned 50 in May and has a sponsor's
exemption at the Transamerica to generate ticket sales on a weekend
when the tour's top trio _ Hale Irwin, Gil Morgan and Larry Nelson
_ are absent.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, Morgan and Nelson represent that category of player most
likely to succeed on the Senior Tour _ the former PGA Tour star.
There'll be a few of those entered in the Transamerica _ youngest
among them John Mahaffey, who notched 10 PGA Tour victories before
he turned 50 on May 9; winningest among them Gene Littler, 68, who
won 29 PGA tournaments from 1954 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Another category of players with promising horoscopes comprises
those who played on tours around the world. Some of them at the
Transamerica include Hugh Baiocchi (South Africa), Peter Oosterhuis
(Europe), Jose Maria Canizares (Europe) and Kurt Cox (Asia).
</P>
<P>
   But of the top 31 money leaders last year _ and 31 is a magic
number out here, where the top 31 gain full exemptions into the
tournaments of the subsequent season _ nine of them had made
livings in places like the insurance business (Jay Sigel) and the
auto assembly line (Tom Wargo).
</P>
<P>
   One of the top 31 so far this year is Hall, who comes to
Silverado looking for nothing more than his first victory. He
earned a conditional exemption with his 11th-place finish at
Q-school last year and looks like a lock for the full exemption
this year, with $609,153 and a ranking of 20th, between Wargo and
Ray Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Hall had regained his amateur standing after those ill-fated
attempts to go pro 30 years ago, and in 1985 he won the Carolinas
Mid-Amateur. Five years ago, he decided to prepare for the Senior
Tour and enlisted a sponsorship group of 13 that ensured he would
never have to sleep in his car after he turned pro again in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He also enlisted the support of his wife, Carol, and daughter,
Holly, which didn't keep him from getting homesick during two years
of play on the Asian Tour and another (1996) on the Hooters Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The travel has been the hardest thing,'' Hall said. ``But it's
worked out great. Holly is in her fourth year in college now, and
my wife is able to travel with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wanted to draw a road map ... it's turned out
sweet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
