<HEADLINE>
`HOLY MAN' MAKES A COMIC SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You're watching one of those home shopping stations
and you've already bought the food storage system and the cubic
zirconian dinette set and the young-forever mystery goop. What's
left to buy? How about a little enlightenment to complete the
package?
</P>
<P>
   You don't expect to find spirituality on junk-for-sale TV, but
that's what you get in ``Holy Man,'' a cute comedy which asks the
question: can you have a higher state of consciousness and non-stop
shopping at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Goldblum stars as Ricky, the hustling head of an
infomercial network who is about to lose his job for committing the
only sin in the salesman's bible: flat sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky needs a savior. He finds one literally in the mysterious G
(Eddie Murphy), a kind of wandering, zen, comic mystic.
</P>
<P>
   In a last ditch attempt to save his job, Ricky puts G on the
air. But instead of selling beauty aids and chain saws, G talks to
America about how unimportant all that material stuff is compared
to true inner peace.
</P>
<P>
   And the sales start rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   The more G tells people they don't need junk, the more junk they
buy because he alleviates their guilt over wasting their time and
money.
</P>
<P>
   As the zen pitchman becomes American's favorite guru, Ricky has
to face his own truth: will he sell his soul for success?
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy Man'' is a fun movie without being outrageously funny.
</P>
<P>
   Director Stephen Herek (``101 Dalmatians'') puts together a
smart comic match, then twists it. Murphy's high-energy antics,
which served him so well in ``The Nutty Professor,'' should blend
hilariously with Goldblum's dead-pan drolleries.
</P>
<P>
   But the director and writer Tom Schulman (``What About Bob?'')
make a strange decision: they mellow out Murphy's mania and put
Goldblum in the lead role.
</P>
<P>
   They get away with it because the set up is funny enough. But
they don't take full advantage of the talents of their two stars.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy needs to dazzle. He plays extraordinary characters like a
comic genius. But he doesn't play ordinary straight men nearly as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Goldblum is a better comic counterpuncher. He shines when he
reacts to the star with acerbic one-liners, but you don't want him
carrying the plot and the comedy. That's why he was funnier in
``Jurassic Park'' than in ``Holy Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Holy Man'' has too much Goldblum and not enough
Murphy, it's still an amusing, enjoyable light comedy with a few
hilarious infomercial spoofs.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``Holy Man'' contains nothing objectionable for
9/10ths of the movie. Then they drop in a couple of mild
profanities for no reason at all. I get the feeling that Hollywood
producers and the movie ratings board aren't even aware any more of
what much of America considers to be profanities. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
