<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES: DE KOONING INVASION; ARCHER LOVES WARHOL; MOTHERWELL
MECCA; NEW NAME AT THE MET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The work of Abstract Expressionist painters is all
over Manhattan this fall. Last month the Whitney Museum of American
Art opened its Mark Rothko retrospective, and on Nov. 1 the Museum
of Modern Art will present its Jackson Pollock show. Now Willem de
Kooning is getting all kinds of attention too.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Tuesday, two of his monumental bronze sculptures,
``Standing Figure'' (1969-84) and ``Reclining Figure'' (1969-82),
will be shown at the Doris C. Freedman Plaza at the East 60th
Street entrance to Central Park and in Bryant Park. The sculptures
are from the artist's estate; their installation was organized by
the Public Art Fund, a nonprofit institution that presents
contemporary art in public places.
</P>
<P>
   Other de Kooning exhibitions will each be devoted to a different
part of his career. Matthew Marks and Lucy Mitchell-Innes, the
dealers handling work from the artist's estate, have organized a
two-part exhibition, ``Willem de Kooning: Drawings and Sculpture,''
which will be in Marks' Chelsea gallery at 523 W. 24th St. and in
Mitchell-Innes &AMP; Nash, Ms. Mitchell-Innes' gallery at 1018 Madison
Ave. The double show, from Oct. 31 through Dec. 19, will have 80
drawings and 10 or more sculptures, most of them small, made
between 1960, when the artist moved to East Hampton, and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the drawings were studies, which de Kooning kept for
himself,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   Also opening on Oct. 31 is ``Drawing Seeing/Seeing Drawing,'' at
the Drawing Center, 35 Wooster St., in SoHo. Organized by Klaus
Kertess, an independent curator, it will include 70 works and will
focus on four groups of drawings created between 1958 and 1970. The
show will travel to the Addison Gallery in Andover, Mass., then to
the Wexner Center for the Arts at Ohio State University in
Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Each show has its own personality. The Drawing Center show
includes works borrowed from private collections and museums. None
is for sale. The gallery shows will present works from the estate;
all are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The three de Kooning shows follow the exhibition of his work at
the National Gallery of Art in Washington in 1994 and the show of
works from the 1980s at the Museum of Modern Art two years ago. Now
many de Kooning fans are waiting for a full-scale retrospective of
the artist's drawings and sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   For Fun and Profit
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Archer's name is commonly associated with Britain's
Conservative Party and with his best-selling thrillers, not with
the art world. Yet for seven years Lord Archer has been an avid
collector, primarily of Warhols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went mad and started buying all over the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, Archer estimated, he had 42 paintings and 285
prints by Warhol as well as 83 signed David Hockney prints dating
from 1954-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put together groups of 10s,'' he said, referring to his
Warhol prints. Warhol would frequently make his prints in
portfolios of 10, and Archer has tried to assemble complete
portfolios of such iconic Warhol images as flowers and soup cans.
</P>
<P>
   But like a Wall Street speculator, as fast as Archer buys, he
sells. On Oct. 20, about 60 works will go on view at the Peter
Gwyther Gallery, a new gallery on Bruton Street in London. Prices
will range from $1,000 to ``very high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Archer isn't hoping to cash in just on recent rising Warhol
prices; he's also a partner in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Experts at London auction houses said they were familiar with
Archer's collection. While no one was willing to speak for
attribution, some experts said Archer had approached them about
auctioning his works at Sotheby's or Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not true,'' he said. ``But I did talk to them about a
charity auction.''
</P>
<P>
   Only some of Archer's Warhols and Hockneys will be offered this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm planning to keep my favorites,'' he said. ``I'm tempted to
hold on to the 10 Campbell's Soup cans and the black Marilyns. I've
gotten very attached to them.''
</P>
<P>
   A Motherwell Lode
</P>
<P>
   The Art Gallery of Ontario in Toronto is fast becoming a mecca
for Robert Motherwell's works on paper. This month the museum
acquired 74 works: 69 on paper, four paintings and a collage.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous trustee gave the museum the money to buy the works,
which are said by experts to be worth $1.5 million. They came from
the Dedalus Foundation, the Manhattan-based organization
established after the Abstract Expressionist's death in 1991 to
distribute works from his estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that Motherwell was a central figure in 20th-century
art who was especially influential in Canada,'' said Matthew
Teitelbaum, director of the museum, adding that the foundation
approached the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase consists of almost half a century of the artist's
drawings and is the most complete archive of the artist's works on
paper. Among the highlights are works from the artist's signature
series, ``Elegies,'' dating from 1949 through 1977, and a group
from 1942-47 that show the artist's early interest in Surrealism.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is planning several Motherwell exhibitions with its
new holdings, Teitelbaum said. In a year it plans to mount a show
of drawings by Motherwell, de Kooning and the English artist
Patrick Heron. It will deal with how artists return to drawing when
they get older.
</P>
<P>
   The Guard Changes
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Barnet, who for eight years was the associate
curator of European sculpture and decorative arts at the Detroit
Institute of Arts, has recently become the Michel David-Weill
Curator in charge of the Metropolitan Museum's department of
medieval art and the Cloisters. He succeeds William Wixom, who
retired in August after 19 years at the museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
