<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6780 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     10-08 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: `LITTLE VOICE'; DEMI MOORE; CHUCKY GETS LUCKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Mari Hoff is quite disagreeable, with an overheated
sexual appetite, an appallingly salty tongue and an over-the-hill
figure. Ray Say, her boyfriend in this working class English town,
isn't much better: he books strippers at a local club and cruises
the streets in a hulking, red Oldsmobile convertible. And then
there's L.V., for Little Voice, Mari's grown-up but waiflike
daughter, who is so crushed by her mother's demands and the death
of her father that she has retreated to her bedroom to stew, squeak
out an occasional word and sing the show tunes her father loved,
like a diva.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarkable ability to belt out the songs of performers like
Judy Garland and Shirley Bassey becomes the instrument for
discovering the wounded humanity in this unlikely bunch in ``Little
Voice,'' which is to open in December.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the movie is reminiscent of ``Brassed Off,'' the tale
of how a brass band formed by a group of miners in England brought
some solace to their otherwise grim lives.
</P>
<P>
   And it's no coincidence, since both were written and directed by
Mark Herman, who is staking a claim as the man who finds magic in
even the meanest circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty evil bunch, really, this lot,'' said Herman in a
telephone interview. ``They're pretty greedy, especially at the
end. Ray is pretty revolting. But there is redemption for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie stars Jane Horrocks (Bubble in the British television
show ``Absolutely Fabulous'') as the silver-throated L.V., Brenda
Blethyn as Mari and Michael Caine as Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Herman has brought his signature touches to the movie, but it
was something of an accident that he has made it at all. The film
is based on a play by Jim Cartwright, ``The Rise and Fall of Little
Voice.'' Herman said he went to the play on opening night in London
only because he had friends performing. ``I usually hate the
theater, but I was knocked out by this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was propitious because, he said, he was struggling
with what to do after the success of ``Brassed Off.'' Herman said
he had had just a few months to produce the script. The movie,
which was filmed in the northern England seaside town of
Scarborough, was shot in nine weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Although he insisted that he was faithful to the play's spirit,
Herman took license in several respects. For one, he came up with
the idea that Bill (Ewan McGregor), the young man who is courting
L.V., would have an interest in homing pigeons, with the roost on a
hilltop overlooking the town an excuse to get the characters, and
the camera, out of Mari's house.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, he brought a fairy tale quality to the
end, with the characters finding something positive in catastrophe,
not just horror.
</P>
<P>
   And then, Herman added, the actors brought new things to the
movie, never more evident than in a scene in which Ray is trying to
lure L.V. to do a nightclub act with the tale of a bluebird finding
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was remarkable because we had to shoot that on the wrong
day and so people weren't able to prepare,'' Herman said. ``But
Michael was so pleased. He did these seven-minute takes just like
that. He just knew. The performances were better than I had
envisioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's Who?
</P>
<P>
   Marie is a widow and a literary critic who lives in the south of
France with her two children and dreams of an alter ego, Marty, a
New York literary agent who is unwilling to get attached to a man.
They both fall in love. Or is Marty the one dreaming of Marie to
express her unfulfilled longings?
</P>
<P>
   Both characters are played by Demi Moore, in ``Passion of
Mind,'' her first movie in two years and that rare film, a thriller
of the mind. Filming has just begun in New York and will move
shortly to France.
</P>
<P>
   The script was written by Ron Bass, who also wrote the recently
released ``What Dreams May Come.'' But the choice of Alain Berliner
as director underscores the nature of the film as an inner journey.
Berliner is a Belgian whose last film, ``Ma Vie en Rose,'' about a
boy who believes he is really a girl, won a Golden Globe award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like `Ma Vie en Rose,' we must decide which life to
choose eventually,'' Berliner said. ``It's a choice we all have to
make someday, dreams or reality. In this movie, she ends up
choosing, and you understand why.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's like a puzzle of memory.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the striking qualities of the movie is that though it
deliberately blurs dreams and reality, it is written in a very
straightforward, almost austerely realistic manner. Stellan
Skarsgard, who plays Marie's French lover, said this approach was
underscored by the unusual quality of the dialogue, adding that the
heart of the movie was in the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie is really written for actors, with dialogue that's
kind of different,'' said Skarsgard, who talked over a cellular
phone while arguing with a taxi driver in his native Stockholm.
``There's no small talk with my character. His dialogue is written
in a very condensed way. He's so frank, so straightforward about
everything. I'll see if I have the courage to play it completely
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Skarsgard, who played the math professor in ``Good Will
Hunting'' and more recently was a spy in ``Ronin,'' said that was
why the part was so challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always something ambiguous about the characters I
play,'' he said. ``I always try to look for something good as well
as bad. My character is a good guy, but I can't see making it all
black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   Skarsgard said he did not want to reveal too much about the
plot, except to say, ``You should wonder until the last page what
is dream and what is reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Berliner emphasized that the point was not to create a fanciful
fiction, but a story that, hopefully, the audience will truly
relate to.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my own life, I had to choose between dreams and reality,''
he said. ``Where am I? I'm in reality right now.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Doll He Isn't
</P>
<P>
   It seemed long ago that Chucky ruled the roost in the world of
horror. Chucky, of course, was the nightmarish, supernatural serial
killer who slashed his way through ``Child's Play'' in 1988 and in
a sequel before petering out with ``Child's Play 3'' in 1991. It
seemed the world had had enough of a malevolent doll possessed by a
murderer's soul.
</P>
<P>
   But never underestimate the Lazarus-like powers of malevolent
dolls. Chucky is back, sort of, in a spiffed-up 1998 version. Now
he's got a girlfriend (Jennifer Tilly), a sex drive and a sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bride of Chucky,'' to be released Oct. 16, is a sign of the
times. It has been produced by the same cast of characters who
developed the original franchise, but this time they have delivered
a sendup in an effort to tap into the revived interest in the
horror genre by an irreverent and hip new generation that has taken
to wisecracking films like ``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did
Last Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The title alone kind of makes you smile,'' said David
Kirschner (above), a producer. ``And you get lines like, `Chucky
gets lucky.' Every 18-year-old can relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Basically what we said was, yes, there's horror,
yes, Chucky's frightening, but he's funny now. It's kind of a
psychotic muppet movie.'' As it happens, Kirschner began his career
as an illustrator for Jim Henson, creator of the Muppets.
</P>
<P>
   You know this is not the old doll when Tiffany, his girlfriend,
tries to conjure his dismembered parts back to life by reciting
incantations from a book, ``Voodoo for Dummies.'' She may be a
murderer herself, but she is not without a touch of class; her hero
is Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Chucky and Tiffany have a troubled relationship, not helped when
her soul migrates into a doll, too. But they do have moments of
bliss, doing what dirty-minded dolls do with their clothes off.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was written by the creator of the franchise, Don
Mancini, but a new director, Ronny Yu, was brought in from Hong
Kong. Yu recently directed ``The Bride With White Hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Kirschner said, the producers worked
hard to insure the movie had an R rating, as did the previous
films.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have an R rating you're going to lose your 16-,
17- and 18-year-old crowd,'' he said. ``They want to see the
excitement and the chases and the kill. That's what the rating
signifies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
