<HEADLINE>
DISNEY PLANS ESPN SPORTS BAR IN TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walt Disney and its subsidiary, the cable sports
network ESPN, announced plans Wednesday to open an upscale sports
bar called ESPN Zone in Times Square next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The 42,000-square-foot restaurant and bar at the northeast
corner of 42nd Street and Broadway would enlarge Disney's already
considerable presence in Times Square, which includes a store and a
theater. For ESPN, which has an Internet site and recently began a
magazine, the move represents another effort to make its brand name
more visible and diversified.
</P>
<P>
   The first ESPN Zone opened in Baltimore this summer and has been
used by ABC, also owned by Disney, for its Monday Night Football
halftime show. But according to Disney officials, the Times Square
location will become the flagship, and the enterprise could become
a chain. ESPN and ABC expect to do live broadcasts from the New
York restaurant, they said, using customers as part of their studio
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The ground floor will house Studio Grill, where patrons can eat
$8 hamburgers and $20 steaks while sitting in replicas of the sets
ESPN uses for Sportscenter, NBA2Night and Baseball Tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, discriminating couch potatoes will be able to select
from a variety of televised games on one of 13 immense screens
while ensconced in leather reclining chairs with speakers in the
headrests. The top floor will have a variety of sports-related
games.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Disney said they were not concerned about opening
so close to the Official All-Star Cafe, a sports-themed chain with
a location at 45th Street and Broadway.
</P>
</TEXT>
