<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINTAGE-PHOTO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY REVIEW: VINTAGE PRINTS NOT ALWAYS SUPERIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For anyone interested in exploring the pros and cons
of vintage prints _ those made within a few years after a negative
is created _ exhibitions of work by Ansel Adams, Brett Weston and
Gordon Parks, now at three Manhattan galleries, make intriguing,
sometimes contradictory arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ansel Adams: Vintage Prints,'' at Alan Klotz/Photocollect,
includes prints made in the 1920s through the '50s and makes a
persuasive case that these early prints are better than many
soaring landscapes that Adams mass-produced in the late 1970s and
early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Like other members of the select f/64 group, so named because
they set their lenses to that aperture to get the near and the far
equally sharp, Adams made contact prints from large negatives to
maintain even greater clarity. The early prints are therefore small
(roughly 7 by 9 inches), but the largeness of his vision is more
evident in them than in many of his bigger, later ones.
</P>
<P>
   Adams could turn a simple patch of ground into a bewitching bed
of wondrously delicate wildflowers, as he did in ``Trailside, Near
Juneau, Alaska'' (circa 1948). And ``Nevada Falls,'' circa 1928, is
alive, tactile, with many shades of gray between the brilliant
white and glistening black. Certain photographic papers before the
1960s had high levels of cadmium and silver, which, photographers
say, allowed for warm tones and a wide range of grays.
</P>
<P>
   But vintage prints are not all equal. To one side of ``Nevada
Falls'' is ``Rushing Water, Merced River,'' which looks colder,
flatter and thinner. Next to it is ``Water and Foam,'' which was
printed the same year as ``Rushing Water'' but is fuller and
richer.
</P>
<P>
   Among the grouping of trees and mountains are Adams' self-styled
Parmelian prints of the '20s, which have a distinctive creamy tone
and parchment-like texture. ``Sierra Juniper,'' in particular, is a
standout, the pencil-thin lines down the tree trunk marvelously at
odds with the sheer massiveness of the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the shortcomings in many later prints is the
prominently displayed 1950s print of a 1932 image, ``Pine Cone and
Eucalyptus Leaves, San Francisco.'' The print is amazingly flat and
lifeless, as though Adams were incapable of tonal subtleties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brett Weston: Vintage Photographs,'' at the Edwynn Houk
Gallery, spans the period from 1929 through the early '70s and
includes many images that have not been previously exhibited. It
generally shows this artist, who was overshadowed by his famous
father, Edward, at his best. But here, too, the vintage prints are
not uniformly great.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Brett Weston's early prints have a subtle warmth and an
ardent attention to detail: paw-print-like marks on cracked earth,
almost three-dimensional floaters on the water's surface, ridges on
sand dunes that are gently registered as far as the eye can see and
even where the eye normally can't, in deep shadow. ``Forest,
Netherlands'' (circa 1971) would have been an unremarkable close-up
of tree trunks if not for the tree trunk in the middle of the frame
that, positioned just so, looks as though it were solarized.
</P>
<P>
   Weston can make peeling paint sing, which he did in ``Cracked
Paint, Garrapata, California'' (1954). In ``Lily Leaf'' (1930), he
compared the close-up of a lily stem and leaf to the full curves of
a luscious fruit.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the prints he made in the '70s and '80s are harsh
and lifeless; a 1973 ``Mendenhall Glacier,'' for sale at an auction
house this week, resembled an alien landscape with crumpled metal
for mountains and inky black for water. At the gallery, ``Highway
North of Santa Fe, New Mexico'' is a 1938 vintage print, but it
feels like a later print; it's cold, and the boldly black road
cutting across the image is jarring.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, a later print of ``Car Window, Deluxe
U.S. Company, San Francisco,'' in the gallery's office, is almost
indistinguishable from the 1936 vintage version in the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vintage Gordon Parks: 50 Years in Black and White,'' at the
Howard Greenberg Gallery, together with ``Half Past Autumn,'' a
Parks retrospective at the Museum of the City of New York, makes
the strongest argument that the work of certain artists is best
seen in their vintage prints.
</P>
<P>
   At the gallery, one gets used to shadows yielding more details,
to a gorgeous delicacy, to crisp details and a full range of tonal
grays, to the photographer's nuanced, warm engagement with his
subject.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the later prints, at the museum, are of generally
poorer quality. The flaws are highlighted because clearly better
prints _ warm, detailed, nuanced _ are shown next to prints of
images from the same period that are coarse, lacking many details
and overwhelmed by a dominant muddy black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Place de la Concorde, Paris'' is so deficient _ harsh sky,
weakly defined background buildings and foreground cars,
rain-slicked roads a dull black _ that a reproduction of this image
in a 1948 issue of Life magazine, placed nearby, can intimate a
crisply magical wet evening in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Parks' 1950 photographs of street beggars in Portugal are
heartbreakingly tender. A print at the gallery of a beggar girl
holding a baby who is peeking curiously at the photographer matches
the photographer's empathy with an understated, gently detailed
esthetic. The print of the same image at the museum is coarser. And
a beatific ``Beggar Woman and Child, Estoril, Portugal'' is so
reduced to dull black, grays and white that one craves a vintage
version.
</P>
<P>
   Some attribute the coarser qualities of modern prints to
photographic papers that have lower silver content and, for
environmental reasons, no longer have cadmium, a heavy metal. But
many photographers working in black and white manage to tease
incredible tonalities out of existing papers, of which there
remains a good range.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is more likely a dichotomy in the way a
photograph is viewed: as art or as a representation of an image or
idea.
</P>
<P>
   For Parks, Greenberg said, photography was for reproduction; it
was never about photography as art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The print was not the issue,'' Greenberg said. ``The negative
is the issue, and he's always guarded his negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Parks' black-and-white prints have been made at the
Time-Life photo lab, and although he has no difficulty exhibiting
and selling the modern prints, the question raised by ``Vintage
Gordon Parks'' remains. If viewers have seen prints at their best,
what purpose does it serve to reproduce prints that are a shadow of
what they can be?
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is a mistake to equate vintage with superior. And an
emphasis on age and, more recently, provenance can result in a
myopic obsession with the photograph as ``object.''
</P>
<P>
   At its best, the notion of vintage prints encourages the kind of
close attention to what is in front of us that is only for the
good. Because it is only by really looking that a later print might
end up being judged superior to an early one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ansel Adams: Vintage Prints'' remains at Alan
Klotz/Photocollect, 22 E. 72nd St., through Oct. 24; ``Vintage
Gordon Parks: 50 Years in Black and White'' at the Howard Greenberg
Gallery, 120 Wooster St., through Oct. 24, and ``Brett Weston:
Vintage Photographs'' at the Edwynn Houk Gallery, 745 Fifth Ave.,
through Nov. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
