<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     10-08 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIEF REVIEWS OF SOME NEW MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of
new or noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in
New York City. (Star) denotes a highly recommended film or series.
Ratings and running times are in parentheses.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Playing
</P>
<P>
   ``ANTZ,'' starring the voices of Woody Allen, Sharon Stone,
Sylvester Stallone, Gene Hackman and many others. Directed by Eric
Darnell and Tim Johnson (PG, 83 minutes). Computer animation has
advanced to the point where it can make a cute romantic couple out
of Allen and Ms. Stone.
</P>
<P>
   This and other surreal tricks are shown off in a funny,
ingeniously animated insect picture that often reaches the
anthropomorphic cleverness of ``Toy Story'' and shows off Allen's
sharpest comic timing with one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Antz'' winds up overplotted in bizarrely grandiose ways,
with the threat of genocide invoked for a jarring change of pace.
Must every child-friendly adventure film, even one with
considerable potential to delight grown-ups, boil down to a
struggle for world domination? Surely a threat of bug spray in the
picnic basket would have done the trick (Janet Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE GOVERNESS,'' starring Minnie Driver and Tom
Wilkinson. Directed by Sandra Goldbacher (R, 114 minutes). It is
the early 1840s, and Rosina (Ms. Driver), a headstrong young
Sephardic Jewish woman living in London, poses as a Gentile to get
a job as a governess for the Cavendish family on a remote Scottish
island. Falling in love with the skittish, devoutly Christian head
of the household (Tom Wilkinson), a gentleman inventor with whom
she has a stormy affair, she becomes his collaborator in the
invention of photography.
</P>
<P>
   The ravishingly handsome film works on several levels: as a
proto-feminist fable, a meditation on still photography and its
relation to real life, and a portrait of lovers whose religious
difference becomes an unbridgeable emotional gap. Ms. Driver holds
the picture with a solid performance that falls short of great
(Stephen Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``LOLITA,'' starring Jeremy Irons and Dominique Swain.
Directed by Adrian Lyne (R, 137 minutes). At last, Lyne's fine,
deeply felt adaptation of Nabokov's diabolical masterpiece can be
seen in the large-screen format it truly deserves. Why go out?
Because the detail and texture of this lavishly produced film shine
theatrically in ways that weren't possible on Showtime, and because
the film's mostly unalloyed subtlety (except in its opening and
closing sections) rewards a closer view.
</P>
<P>
   Lyne's direction is the best work of his career. Irons' splendid
performance conveys a tragicomic blend of ardor and conscience,
while Ms. Swain plays the title role as a startlingly unpredictable
adult-child hybrid. For a culture so dangerously obsessed with
youth and beauty, this haunting ``Lolita'' is a fascinating sign of
its times (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``NEXT STOP WONDERLAND,'' starring Hope Davis and Alan
Gelfant. Directed by Brad Anderson (R, 111 minutes). Will Erin (Ms.
Davis), an attractive, introspective night-shift nurse, and Alan (
Gelfant), a plumber and aspiring marine biologist who was obviously
meant for her, collide on the streets of Boston and live happily
ever after?
</P>
<P>
   The set-up of this romantic comedy about dating in the 90s may
seem cliched, but the witty, beautifully acted and edited film
refreshes the genre with the acuteness of Anderson's observations
about people and middle-class urban life in general.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis creates a wonderfully complex portrait of an
idealistic introvert coping with loneliness, disappointment and
pressures from all sides, including (in the movie's funniest
scenes) some ardently self-centered suitors who answer a personal
ad. A rich Brazilian bossa-nova score gives the movie the mood of
bittersweet longing (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``ONE TRUE THING,'' starring Meryl Streep, Renee
Zellweger and William Hurt. Directed by Carl Franklin (PG-13, 120
minutes). This film adaptation of the novel by Anna Quindlen _ a
former columnist for The New York Times _ about an ambitious New
York journalist forced to move back in with her parents to care for
her dying mother strikes a sad and universal chord.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Streep and Ms. Zellweger are beautifully matched as a
mother and daughter who achieve a grown-up understanding during
this anguished time. But the movie treads the line between soap
opera and serious drama and has far too many cute and sentimental
touches.
</P>
<P>
   Its structure _ the story is told in flashbacks that make the
mother's death a kind of whodunit (she dies from an overdose of
morphine) _ also cheapen the movie without ruining it (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``PECKER,'' starring Edward Furlong, Christina Ricci, Martha
Plimpton and Lili Taylor. Directed by John Waters (R, 87 minutes).
Waters, the Trash King of Baltimore, does his best to puncture New
York art-world pretensions in a film whose biggest joke is its
title, though plenty of winking smaller jokes are here, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flavor of Month Causes Tizzy in Art World'' reads a headline
summarizing the career of the title character, a Baltimore
shutterbug who just won't quit snapping friends and neighbors. In
the film, fame and fortune threaten Pecker's trashy esthetic and
gross-out chic. Waters' own style hasn't had to sacrifice these at
all (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``PERMANENT MIDNIGHT,'' starring Ben Stiller and
Elizabeth Hurley. Directed by David Veloz (R, 85 minutes). As Jerry
Stahl recounts in his 1995 memoir, drug addiction turned him into a
skittish, distracted, hugely self-involved individual. Since he
happened to be working as a television writer in Hollywood, no one
really noticed.
</P>
<P>
   The film version of his story plunges fearlessly into the
self-inflicted humiliations that went with this story. In a
first-rate, rivetingly caustic performance, Stiller plays a man on
a fashionably decadent slide all the way to rock bottom. The
character's clearest sign of dysfunction is his inability to
appreciate Elizabeth Hurley as his ravishing, high-powered wife
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``RONIN,'' starring Robert De Niro, Jean Reno, Stellan
Skarsgaard, Natascha McElhone and Jonathan Pryce. Directed by John
Frankenheimer (R, 121 minutes). Directing like a world-weary
Hitchcock with a taste for the breathless car chase, Frankenheimer
propels this tale of intrigue through its tightly plotted paces so
expertly that he even makes an action hero of De Niro.
</P>
<P>
   European in both its brooding tone and beautiful French
settings, this story of double-dealing mercenaries in pursuit of a
metal suitcase features a tough, expert cast and some sensational
action sequences. Frankenheimer directs them in fast, efficient,
no-frills fashion because no extra frills are needed (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``ROUNDERS,'' starring Matt Damon, Edward Norton, John Malkovich
and John Turturro. Directed by John Dahl (R, 120 minutes). Though
this tale of poker fever finally adds up to less than meets the
eye, what does meet the eye (and ear) is mischievously
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Martin Scorsese's brand of irresistible lowlife and
aided by a splendid rogues' gallery of a cast, the director of
``The Last Seduction'' takes his audience into a poker demimonde of
abundant color. As the actors make the most of rascally roles
(Malkovich has a field day with a Russian accent), the story leads
to settings as varied as the Elks Hall in Binghamton and a Russian
Turkish bath. Dahl may not have new thoughts on the gambler's life,
but he makes this guided tour worth the trip (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SAVING PRIVATE RYAN,'' starring Tom Hanks, Matt Damon,
Tom Sizemore, Jeremy Davies, Edward Burns and Adam Goldberg.
Directed by Steven Spielberg (R, 168 minutes). Spielberg's soberly
magnificent new film is the finest war movie of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Turning back the clock to restore passion and meaning to the
genre, he works in a spirit of urgent communication to look at war
as if it had not been looked at before. Tour-de-force battle scenes
are frank without sensationalism, and the same great storyteller
who made you believe there was an extraterrestrial hiding in the
closet has made this an irresistibly vibrant, gripping tale.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks continues to astonish with admirable modesty, and the rest
of the casting is comparably inspired. As he did with ``Schindler's
List,'' Spielberg has made a landmark film of devastating power
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER NEVER CRIES,'' starring Leelee Sobieski,
Kris Kristofferson, Barbara Hershey and Anthony Roth Costanzo.
Directed by James Ivory (R, 120 minutes). Working without a classic
at hand, the Merchant-Ivory team adapts a novel by Kaylie Jones,
James Jones' daughter, into a colorful panorama weakened by
autobiographical sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   With no real narrative shapeliness and a loosely anecdotal pace,
it vividly recalls the coming of age of a sensitive young woman who
(though well played by 14-year-old Ms. Sobieski) remains a more
slender, peripheral figure than the film's ambitions require.
Moving from Paris to America, it succeeds more at evoking detail
and atmosphere than in finding the heart of her story (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY,'' starring Cameron Diaz,
Ben Stiller and Matt Dillon. Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly
(R, 119 minutes). Sometimes Western civilization declines in
deliriously funny style. Hence this proudly obnoxious comedy is a
hoot in every sense, deserving a smidgen of disapproval and a whole
lot of helpless laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Set in motion by a prom, a crush and a cruel, cruel zipper, this
paean to low humor works ridiculously well because it never stoops
to being mean-spirited or (despite all appearances) authentically
inane. The principal cast is bright and appealing, with Ms. Diaz at
her most beautiful and blithe.
</P>
<P>
   Do note that this film strives hard for something to offend
everyone, and that a tolerance for the Farrellys' zit jokes is
unfortunately required (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``WHAT DREAMS MAY COME,'' starring Robin Williams, Cuba Gooding
Jr. and Annabella Sciorra. Directed by Vincent Ward (R, 106
minutes). If the gothic-romantic special effects in this turgid pop
fable set in the afterlife are some of the trippiest ever devised
for a serious drama, this sudsy fantasy about married soul mates
who meet after death never comes emotionally alive.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is at his fake-sincere worst as the world's most
devoted husband who dies in a car crash and goes to heaven. Ms.
Sciorra is simply blank as the wife who commits suicide and must be
rescued from hell. Gooding, glaringly miscast, plays Williams'
angelic guide (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``WITHOUT LIMITS,'' starring Billy Crudup, Donald
Sutherland and Monica Potter. Directed by Robert Towne (PG-13, 118
minutes). In telling the story of the mercurial track star Steve
Prefontaine, a screenwriter known for enriching screenplays with
unruly, unpredictable life creates a surprisingly resonant
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Crudup's charismatic performance as a runner with the
attitudes of a rock star, this can be watched as one more sports
film, complete with exciting race sequences. But it's not truly
about winning, losing or even playing the game; instead, Towne
considers the philosophical distance between the brash Prefontaine
and his formidable coach, Bill Bowerman (expertly played by
Sutherland). The film's wisdom lies in its thoughtful way of
balancing these two (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``YOUR FRIENDS AND NEIGHBORS,'' starring Jason Patric, Ben
Stiller, Aaron Eckhardt, Catherine Keener, Amy Brenneman and
Nastassja Kinski. Written and directed by Neil LaBute (R, 100
minutes). Three men obsessed with one another's sexual performance
are at the core of this second film from the director of ``In the
Company of Men.''
</P>
<P>
   The new movie is so blunt at times, and so unrelievedly talky
and dark at others, that it cries out for the velvet glove of
``Manhattan,'' a much more seductive film about sexual opportunism
and urbane cruelty. Yet even when LaBute's material feels mannered
or unremittingly sour, it sustains a psychic ferocity that commands
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The intricate web of lies, failures and brutal revelations here
is strong stuff, and it's the work of an original filmmaker who
takes no prisoners (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   ``G.W. PABST.'' In the midst of a comprehensive retrospective of
23 of the surviving 30 films of the celebrated director G.W. Pabst
(1885-1967), the Museum of Modern Art is offering a particular
treat for filmgoers Friday night at 6 and 8 p.m. It consists of a
screening of two Pabst films, ``Pandora's Box'' (1928) and ``Diary
of a Lost Girl'' (1929), each starring Louise Brooks, the
entrancing American actress whose artistry was most fully realized
not in Hollywood but in the films she made for Pabst in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pandora's Box,'' Brooks plays the amoral Lulu, created by
Frank Wedekind, who inspired ``Lulu,'' the Alban Berg opera. In
``Diary of a Lost Girl,'' Pabst's last silent film, Brooks plays a
pregnant girl who escapes to a brothel after her parents exile her
to a reform school.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the museum will show six Pabst films beginning Friday.
Continuing through Oct. 31, the series at the museum, 11 West 53rd
Street, Manhattan, is free with museum admission: $9.50 for adults;
$6.50 for students and those 65 or older; free for visitors under
16 accompanied by an adult. Pay what you wish on Fridays from 4:30
to 8:30 p.m. Screening information: (212) 708-9400 (Lawrence Van
Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
