A6829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MINISTERS09-C     10-08 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MINISTERS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINISTERS SAY MANY BLACKS WANT CLINTON TO STEP DOWN
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three black ministers called Thursday for President
Clinton's resignation, saying the public is mistaken in believing
all African Americans support the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black people that I talk to in churches across this nation
are deeply disappointed in the behavior of the president ...and
many want him to resign,'' said Bishop Earl Jackson Sr. of Exodus
Faith Ministries of Boston and president of the Samaritan Project,
a former branch of the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, however, feel that if they dare to voice their
reservations about Mr. Clinton, they will be attacked by the
liberal thought police,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The minister's statements came as the House voted to open an
impeachment inquiry against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election in 1992, Clinton has generally won raves from
the African American community for appointing several blacks to
prominent positions. Throughout the Monica Lewinsky scandal,
African Americans have continued to back the president, public
opinion polls show.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jackson argued that what Clinton has done is
``manipulate the black community with emotionalism and symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said while ministers forgive Clinton for his actions in
the White House, the president should still resign because he is a
bad role model for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appointment of a few black cabinet officials or a highly
visible visit to Africa does not change the life of one black child
in America,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Melvin Johnson, a pastor at Heart of Christ Community
Church in Brazoria, Texas and Bishop John Witherspoon of the Holy
Spirit Full Gospel Ministry in Milwaukee offered letters of support
for Jackson's position.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers said they hoped their statements would encourage
other conservative blacks to voice their opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our community is divided along lots of lines,'' Witherspoon
said at Thursday's press conference. ``A lot of ministers have
mixed emotions. A lot of people are in love with Bill Clinton and
don't want to speak out.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
