<HEADER>
A6854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATISSE-ART-REVIEW-80     10-08 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATISSE-ART-REVIEW-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRI MATISSE SCULPTURE: SIDELINE ILLUMINATES MATISSE'S MAIN LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though he is celebrated as one of the 20th century's
great painters, Henri Matisse (1869-1954) was also a sculptor of no
small talent. True, he turned out vastly more paintings than
sculptures, once declaring to an interviewer that for him sculpture
was ``a break from painting.'' And with a few exceptions, the
bronzes he made were small. But despite his statement that he made
sculpture ``as a painter,'' some of Matisse's works in this medium
rank among the 20th century's greatest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is plenty of play back and forth between his work
in these two mediums. ``I took up sculpture because what interested
me in painting was a clarification of my ideas,'' he said. ``It was
done for the purpose of organization, to put order into my feelings
and to find a style to suit me. When I found it in sculpture, it
helped me in my painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he tackled the same subjects in both, it was inevitable
that one medium should feed the other. In his vast volume on
Matisse (1984), the French art critic Pierre Schneider surmises
that the artist was intrigued by the materiality of sculpture, the
depth, volume and weight that he could not find in painting.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample evidence of his mastery in ``Henri Matisse:
Sculpture'' at C&AMP;M Arts, touted by the gallery as the most complete
exhibition of Matisse sculptures in New York since the Museum of
Modern Art's survey in 1972. On view are 26 bronzes and a plaster
cast, more than a third of his entire sculptural output. The show
covers work done from 1900 to 1930, although Matisse continued
making sculpture until 1949, when he turned to the large-scale
cutouts of his last years.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest bronze here is a Rodinesque figure called ``The
Serf'' (1900-03). A half-human-size representation of a man, arms
cut off and head humbly bowed, ``The Serf'' takes its heavily
modeled surface and even its forms from Rodin. (In fact, it is
clear throughout the show that although Matisse disparaged Rodin's
work, his own owes a great deal to it.) The figure echoes that of
``Male Model,'' a Cezannesque painting that Matisse did around the
same time. The salient contrast between the sculpture and the
painting is that in the canvas, color, perspective and other
painterly devices establish a force between the figure and its
background. The sculpture, a solid presence with weight and mass,
cannot rely on these painterly tricks but must hold its own in real
space.
</P>
<P>
   As a thoroughgoing modernist, in contrast to Rodin, Matisse
thought of sculpture as self-referential, that is, it should not
express anything but its own substance, an object in space eloquent
only in terms of its materiality. And he saw sculpture as a process
rather than a representation. As pointed out by Jack Flam, the art
critic and historian who wrote the lucid text for the show's
catalog, Matisse made ``The Serf'' the painting's equivalent by his
intensity of modeling, at times deeply gouging the surface of the
sculpture, at others manipulating mass abstractly to create a play
of light and shadow. But whereas Rodin gave his sculptures
underlying anatomical detail and emotional rhetoric, Matisse _
while at times referring to muscle, bone and flesh _ focuses solely
on the physical stuff of the clay.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast to the stolid figure of ``The Serf'' is ``La
Serpentine'' (1909), one of Matisse's most innovative sculptures.
It was taken from a photograph of a cushiony nude who stands
frontally with legs crossed as she leans on a studio balustrade. In
``La Serpentine,'' the nude holds the same pose, but she is pared
down to an exaggeratedly skinny, tall plantlike structure with
rubbery arms, big feet and thick lower legs topped by slender
thighs. Her columnar torso is slightly twisted as she rests one
elbow on a pillar.
</P>
<P>
   Matisse liked to compare the body to a tree in that both are
made hostage to the earth by gravity. His figures thus tend to be
bottom heavy. ``La Serpentine,'' with one leg seemingly rooted to
the ground, is no exception. But on the other hand, space moves
freely around and through the figure to give it a light, airy
persona. It connects directly with one of the cavorting celebrants
in his painting of the same period, ``Dance (II)'' (1909-10), where
the figures relate to space in a similar way. Despite its
emaciation, ``La Serpentine'' is charged with sexual energy; it has
been noted that the pillar the figure leans on is phallic.
</P>
<P>
   Given the ``discovery'' of African art among his colleagues in
the early 1900s, it's not surprising that Matisse incorporated it
into his work. African sculpture appealed to him because, he said,
it was based on the material in which it was carved ``according to
invented designs and proportions.'' And its stylized forms helped
free him further from European sculpture of the past, with its
insistence on credible anatomy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``Two Negresses'' (1907-08), for example, he translated a
photograph of two young African women facing each other, each with
an arm around the other's neck, into a blocky, rectilinear
sculpture. The African stylization of the heads, the rounded,
deeply cloven buttocks of one reflected in the separated circular
breasts of the other, echo the work of certain African cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decorative Figure'' (1908), another African-influenced piece,
depicts a woman perched gingerly on a cube, one big, splayed hand
resting on a rock, the other touching her crotch. Her legs and hips
form a series of rhythmical curves. Her sensuous torso, breasts
high, swings slightly out of axis with her legs and her rigidly
vertical head, creating a dynamic compositional tension. If you
look at the back of the sculpture, and with Matisse's work it is
always rewarding to do so, you see that although in facing the
viewer she seems comfortably seated, one of her buttocks is
slipping off the cube, and other dorsal details are deliberately
out of sync with the front. But the figure, playing off straight
and sinuous, rounded and geometric forms, can't be faulted for
energy.
</P>
<P>
   Heads play a major part in this show, particularly the series of
five women's heads made between 1910 and 1913, called the Jeannette
group after the model who posed for the first two. Moving from
near-realism to the stripped-down, almost surreal essence of a
face, they illustrate Matisse's struggle to separate sculpture from
portraiture. In ``Jeannette V'' the face has become a grotesque,
pared of most of its hair, with one bulging eye and the other
simply a socket. Part of its skull seems also to be missing.
Possibly inspired by an African sculpture Matisse owned, its
daringly severe reductiveness forecasts much that was to come in
20th-century sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Two slightly more realistic heads are ``Henriette II'' (1927)
and ``Henriette III'' (1929), both portraying an African woman. The
first is the more interesting: smoothly modeled with exaggeratedly
plump facial contours and thick lips, suggesting Art Deco style, it
reflects the simplified, pared-to-essence drawing mode that became
quintessentially Matissean. As a tour of Matisse's
three-dimensional work, this show is also a vivid essay on
20th-century efforts to move sculpture from an art of the pictorial
to an art of process. It's a wonderful experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
