<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMS: TAKING THE CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note that this item use to appear in the Arts &AMP;
Leisure for Sunday. It will now be available on Friday in the
Weekend section. The article will move twice a month.)  
 (af) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSH HOUR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Chan, Chris Tucker, Tom Wilkinson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brett Ratner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 94 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese detective named Lee (Chan) looks imploringly at a
little girl. ``Will you practice your kicks and eye gouges?'' he
asks. Actually, it's Lee who employs foot and fist to recover his
young friend, the daughter of a diplomat escorting a priceless art
collection to the United States, after she is kidnapped in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On these shores, and in this kind of movie, detectives also need
an incompatible partner to clash with and later grow fond of. That
would be Carter (the falsetto-voiced Tucker), frenetic bad boy of
the LAPD, who somehow survives his big mouth to be of value in
Lee's marshall-arts battles with a standard-issue Hong Kong crime
lord. Now, let's smash some art objects. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE This is a karate comedy, acrobatic and light-hearted.
Yes, kicks, punches and occasional bullets have their effect, but
the violence is hard to take seriously. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Plenty of street jive, with Carter continually making
reference to posteriors _ his and everybody else's. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-7 They might enjoy some of the silly business (even if
they don't fully understand it), but the film is inappropriate for
small children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 8-10 Parents could deem the film unacceptable on grounds of
violence and general rowdiness. But most children have seen far
worse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP There's no burning reason either to take them to
or keep them away from this movie. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A NIGHT AT THE ROXBURY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will Ferrell, Chris Kattan, Loni Anderson, Dan Hedaya, Molly
Shannon, Richard Greico &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Fortenberry &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 83 minutes  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerking their heads in unison, as is their custom on NBC's
``Saturday Night Live,'' Ferrell and Kattan portray the very dim
Butabi brothers, who bash about the Los Angeles club scene, plowing
into women on the dance floor and blurting things like, ``Hey, you
guys want to make out or what?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely candidates for admission at the chic Roxbury, the boys
ride past the gatekeepers on the coattails of Greico, the former
star of ``21 Jump Street,'' who plays himself. Nocturnal adventures
ensue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Useless idiots!'' screams their father (Hedaya), who by day
employs the pair in his fake-flower shop. Dad's on target there,
but given enough wiggle room in a movie scenario, even idiots can
get girls and make good. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE A few slapstick swats and pratfalls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX The boys have simulated sex with several women, and there is
constant talk of sex in all its forms (or quite a few of them). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A stream. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 This is a borderline age for this film. Given the sex
and profanity, parents beware. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Not to endorse loose behavior, but there really
is no lasting harm in a film that is intended for teen-agers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANTZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An animated film about ants with the voices of Woody Allen, Dan
Aykroyd, Sharon Stone, Danny Glover, Gene Hackman, Jennifer Lopez,
Sylvester Stallone, Christopher Walken and others &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Eric Darnell and Tom Johnson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 83 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not given to heroics but feeling compartmentalized as, in his
words, the middle child in a family of five million, the worker ant
Z (Allen) expresses his newly liberated individuality by leading a
billion of his downtrodden fellows against the evil ant General
Mandible (Hackman).
</P>
<P>
   As chief of the warrior class, the general plans to eliminate
the workers in an effort to upgrade the colony. Read ethnic
cleansing. Z's reluctant fortitude eventually impresses Princess
Bala (Ms. Stone), but he had better get unstuck from that wad of
gum on the bottom of a sneaker. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The ant army takes on a horde of termites, leaving a
corpse-strewn battlefield. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None per se, but with Allen in top vocal form, mild innuendo
occasionally surfaces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE Mandible talks a good game, but what he intends is
genocide. That warrants discussion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 They'll be intrigued by the animation and the great
massed ranks of ants (which are impressive), but the story is too
involved and the warfare could frighten some young children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-8 By this age, they should be on board with the story,
but parents should be ready with clarifications of plot and
explanations of Mandible's behavior. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-11 This is a good age for the film, though older children
may have begun to consider themselves too sophisticated for
animated fare. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP Most will have moved on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
