<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SONGWRITERS09-COX     10-08 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONGWRITERS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SMALL BUSINESSES WIN RIGHT TO AVOID FEES FOR BACKGROUND MUSIC
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington, (e) entertainment and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory for business owners and a defeat for
songwriters, Congress has approved a bill to exempt restaurants and
other small businesses from paying license fees for background
music.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairness in Music Licensing act, sent to President Clinton
late Wednesday for his expected signature, creates exemptions for
restaurants and bars smaller than 3,750 gross square feet and
retail businesses of 2,000 square feet or less.
</P>
<P>
   Larger businesses can also avoid the music fees if they contain
no more than four TV sets or six speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Songwriter groups argued the bill would unjustifiably deny
artists royalties for their songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this music licensing legislation, which seizes the
private property of copyright owners, the United States government
has severely penalized America's songwriters, composers and
publishers,'' said Marilyn Bergman, an Oscar-winning songwriter and
president of the American Society of Composers, Authors and
Publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only will our earnings be reduced, but so will the
creative incentive for future generations of songwriters,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the small businesses had argued that they
should not have to pay fees for copyrighted music played on the
radio and TV in their places of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years we have been working for a level playing field
between small businesses and the music licensing monopolies,'' said
Herman Cain, CEO and president of the National Restaurant
Association. ``This effort represents the first time in 22 years
that our copyright laws have been modernized.''
</P>
<P>
   The licensing measure was passed as part of the Copyright Term
Extension bill, which will extend the length of U.S. copyrights
from an author's life plus 50
</P>
<P>
   years to 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners also won the right to dispute copyright
infringement claims on a local level rather travel to a court in
New York, as current law requires.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
