<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-AIDA-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY OFFERS AN `AIDA' WITH A MORPHING PYRAMID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By SUSAN ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Disney Co.'s latest venture into musical theater,
``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,'' by Tim Rice and Elton
John, opened at the Alliance Theater here on Wednesday night before
a glittery audience that was equal parts native Atlantans and
Disney movers and shakers, including Michael Eisner, the company's
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1871 Verdi opera about the conflicted love between
a Nubian slave girl and an Egyptian soldier, the show is Disney's
first from-the-ground-up theatrical venture. Its current Broadway
hits, ``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``The Lion King,'' both
originated as animated films.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of its development, ``Elaborate Lives'' is not as
technically complex as those shows. But it depends upon a huge,
ever-morphing piece of Disney magic, a six-ton pyramid that broke
down about halfway through the evening. Most of Act II was
performed without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four different types of technologies inside it,''
said Peter Schneider, president of Walt Disney Theatrical
Productions. ``There are little parts that break, bolts that don't
fit. But it's not a big deal to us. We're just going to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   They have been trying to do just that in the six weeks of
Atlanta rehearsals and previews, but with mixed success. ``I've
seen it twice now,'' said a theater board member, Jennings Hertz
Jr., ``but I've never seen it when the pyramid worked the whole way
through. The show has great potential, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the extended standing ovations, one before the show
and one after, no one seemed to care much about a piece of
technology rumored to cost nearly as much as the Alliance's entire
annual budget of $10 million. ``This show has done for the Alliance
the same thing the Olympics did for Atlanta,'' said the theater's
chairman, Kenneth Bernhardt. ``It has put us on the national
scope.''
</P>
<P>
   Covering the opening night performance for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, the critic Dan Hulbert wrote, ``If the show
comes nowhere near Disney's `Lion King' in authentic feeling _
well, hardly any musical does.''
</P>
<P>
   The themes of ``Elaborate Lives'' _ enslavement, biracial
romance _ are said to have brought Disney to the Alliance and
specifically to its artistic director, Kenny Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrival here nine years ago, Leon has transformed the
Alliance Theater into a sometimes controversial but rarely dull
artistic institution focused on diversity. As the programming has
expanded to include the work of playwrights like Pearl Cleage and
August Wilson, the number of black subscribers has grown to 20
percent from 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This play furthers the mission of our theater,'' Leon said.
``I felt very strongly that I had something to say about it as an
artist.'' He said that he had been involved in the casting in New
York and that his creative input had been welcome.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Little else about ``Elaborate Lives'' belongs to the Alliance,
other than the box-office receipts from its sold-out run here
through Nov. 8. The only Atlantans in the 28-member cast are three
children in the ensemble, and virtually all the actors are from
Broadway or Off Broadway. Both the director, Robert Jess Roth, and
the writer of the book, Linda Woolverton, are ``Beauty and the
Beast'' alumni, as are the choreographer and the set, costume and
lighting designers.
</P>
<P>
   So other than diversity, why Atlanta? ``Why not?'' said Disney's
Schneider. ``With any show, one tries to find the right artistic
process with which to develop it. With `Lion King' we went to
Minnesota; `Beauty and the Beast' we went to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth said: ``The actual physical space of the Alliance is
amazing. It's got a Broadway-size stage and an 800-seat,
intimate-feeling house, so to work out a new musical, that's the
best of all possible worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will say where the show is going from here. There is
still creative work to be done, according to both Rice and Roth,
and the pyramid remains an expensive thorn in Disney's side.
``Chicago is a possibility,'' said Roth.``So is London; so is New
York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
