<SLUG> BC-TAUSCHER-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAUSCHER JOINS REPUBLICANS IN SUPPORT OF IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Ellen Tauscher was one of 31 Democrats to vote
Thursday for the Republican-sponsored impeachment inquiry into
President Clinton's role in the White House sex scandal and its
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher, who represents a San Francisco suburban swing district
in the East Bay, said her decision ``was based on my conscience and
on my reading of the Constitution.'' The accusations against
Clinton of obstruction of justice, witness tampering and making
false statements require an impeachment investigation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher, who appeared uncharacteristically somber during two
hours of House debate about impeachment procedures, first voted for
a Democratic alternative that would have limited the scope and time
of the inquiry. That alternative failed, 236 to 198, splitting
mostly along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher then supported the Republican measure because, she
said, the alternative would have been no inquiry at all. The GOP
measure authorizing a broad inquiry with no time limits was
approved by a 258-176 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is very important that I can be in a strong
independent position to make sure that Congress handles this in a
fair, due-process oriented way,'' Tauscher said. ``I have more
power to do that if I support the inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was disappointed with the Republican leadership for
limiting debate to two hours before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could have had an opportunity for respectful
listening of each other,'' Tauscher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid this is all about the Nov. 3 election, not about
the Constitution and not about the presidency,'' Tauscher said.
``It's about pigeonholing members of Congress, one way or another,
by forcing people to do what they believe is right and abandoning
their colleagues and their party.''
</P>
<P>
   She expressed regret at the sharp partisanship of the debate,
saying she was ``ashamed that we spent today looking like there was
no grace, no comity, no consensus and, basically, encouraging the
partisanship label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't proud of my colleagues and the performance we were
giving. We looked like a house divided, we didn't look like we were
putting the American peoples' best face on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., who voted for the Democratic
alternative, said on the House floor that the Republicans were
``inconsistent'' because they elected Rep. Newt Gingrich as speaker
of the House in 1995 after he had been charged with lying under
oath about his political affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why the double standard, which exults the speaker and moves to
impeach the president?'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi sat on the eight-member ethics panel that in 1997 fined
Gingrich, R-Ga., $300,000 for ethics violations. The panel found
that Gingrich committed tax violations in connection with a college
course he taught and also determined he misled the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., who chairs the House Democratic
Caucus, said on the floor that Thursday's vote will ``lower the
threshold for which a president can be distracted and harassed from
his constitutional duties.''
</P>
<P>
   Fazio said impeachment proceedings should be approached with ``a
deep and abiding respect for the Constitution and the presidency. I
believe the Republican majority has squandered that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
