<HEADER>
A6928 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-ONETOUGHCOP-TEX     10-08 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ONETOUGHCOP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONE TOUGH COP': SNOOZE, YOU WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some reason, cop movies lend themselves to some of the most
generic titles in cinema. We've already had, in large black block
letters on white backgrounds, ``Cop,'' ``Cop &AMP; 1/2,'' ``Cops and
Robbers'' and ``One Good Cop.'' Now ``One Tough Cop'' joins them on
the shelf. Eventually, Meryl Streep will star in ``One True Cop,''
and we can all be done with it.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that a bad title doesn't necessarily mean a bad
movie. In the case of ``One Tough Cop,'' you would be wrong.
Although the movie is based on the autobiography of New York cop Bo
Dietl, its press material includes a note saying that many of the
characters and events have been ``modified.'' That's a relief.
Nobody's life should have THIS many cliches.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie's world, Dietl _ whom a doe-eyed Stephen Baldwin
plays as if he'd just been roused from a nice nap in the
hairdresser's chair _ apparently lives a life of stock characters
and hackneyed situations. The boss believes that Dietl's a great
cop, but that he's also a pain in the posterior. Dietl's partner
(Chris Penn) is a lovable lug who drinks and gambles too much
(considering the people he gambles with, his story could be called
``One Dumb Cop).''
</P>
<P>
   Dietl's best friend is a mobster (Mike McGlone) who grew up with
him _ because, don'tcha know, even though they're from the same
neighborhood, they wound up on different sides of the law. That
friendship catches the attention of two FBI agents, who are so
deadpan and robotic that they make Scully and Mulder look like the
guys from ``A Night at the Roxbury.'' One of the agents is played
by Amy Irving, in what may be the worst performance of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Director Bruno Barreto (also Irving's husband), who received an
Oscar nomination for last year's ``Four Days in September,'' takes
himself very seriously. As he did in ``Four Days,'' Barreto
confuses objectivity with dispassion. Even when Dietl and his
partner investigate a savage attack on a nun _ and solve it in less
time than murders are solved on ``Law &AMP; Order'' _ Barreto doesn't
get your blood boiling. He knows how to wield a camera, with some
smooth and fancy crane shots, but the end result is that you feel
like you're watching an episode of ``NYPD Blue'' or ``Homicide''
that doesn't require Dramamine. Or drama, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four Days,'' which was much less generic, benefited from an
unusual story and a heartfelt performance by Alan Arkin as a
kidnapped U.S. ambassador to Brazil. Most of the cast of ``One
Tough Cop'' looks like it's joining Baldwin in his slumber party.
Gina Gershon tries to wake the movie up a little bit, as a woman
who comes between Dietl and his gangster friend, but her role is so
underwritten, her screen time amounts to moments between hitting
the snooze button.
</P>
<P>
   If the movie wasn't so full of itself, it would merely be
boring. But its self-importance makes it irritating _ journalists
have even received a ``Get Tough on Crime'' brochure tying its
release to National Crime Prevention Month. Here's a tip: It'd be a
crime to shell out seven bucks on this.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``One Tough Cop''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Bruno Barreto
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Stephen Baldwin, Gina Gershon, Chris Penn
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, violence and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
