<SLUG> BC-FILM-HOLYMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY VEHICLE DERAILED BY HOLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Holy Man,'' in which Eddie Murphy plays a mischievous mystic
who performs miracles for a home-shopping network, is one of those
movies that's kinda fun until you start thinking about it.
Unfortunately, its overlength gives you plenty of time to do just
that _ to think about things, such as the way the movie has (very)
vague echoes of 1976's classic ``Network.'' It's ``Home Shopping
Network'' _ the cubic zirconia of media satires.
</P>
<P>
   Which, really, would be OK _ some of the movie's best moments
come in the shots it takes at home-shopping and infomercials, and
at the celebrities who hawk wares on these shows (many of whom show
up in amusing good-sport cameos). Like some sort of
alternative-universe channel-surf, however, it becomes boring and
conventional when it strays away from home shopping to focus on its
main story, another tale of a troubled hotshot who finds his soul.
</P>
<P>
   That hotshot would be one Ricky Hayman, played by Jeff Goldblum
in his typical dry-and-nervous mode (Goldblum may be the only
person in the world who gets the jitters without perspiring).
Accurately dubbed ``Nervous Ricky,'' Hayman is a
home-shopping-network exec whose network is tanking, apparently so
badly that he fears he'll become the best-dressed homeless person
in history. He's so off his game that he can't even get his playboy
smarm to work on Kate (Kelly Preston), the cute and spunky
troubleshooter the network owner brings in to right the sinking
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Murphy as G, a pajama-clad prophet who profoundly affects
Ricky and Kate. You don't have to have seen the movie's ubiquitous
trailers to know that eventually, G will go on the air at the
network and that his anti-materialism message will reverse the
net's misfortunes. He even gets ``prime time'' _ what is that at a
home-shopping network? One in the morning? In the movie's world,
EVERYONE watches home shopping, as if broadcast networks and other
cable channels didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   This may be Murphy's gentlest performance _ G makes Dr. Dolittle
look like Dr. Kevorkian _ and it's oddly off-putting. Despite G's
penchant for practical jokes, Murphy seems not just restrained but
repressed; he's so becalmed here, and looks so different with his
shaved head, that you almost forget that he's Eddie Murphy. Perhaps
this should be a relief after the potty humor that marred ``Dr.
Dolittle'' and ``The Nutty Professor,'' but for some reason, it
doesn't quite work.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the inevitable romance between Goldblum and Preston,
who's charming but also seems restrained, especially after her
blistering performance as Tom Cruise's no-nonsense fiancee in
``Jerry Maguire.'' Like too many movies, this one hits the
relationship button just because it's a way of starting the movie's
third act.
</P>
<P>
   Director Stephen Herek, whose mixed-bag career includes such
guilty pleasures as ``Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure'' but also
such lightweight profit-takers as ``101 Dalmatians,'' simply lets
things ramble on too long. As G engages in his on-air antics _
which we want to see _ Herek switches back too frequently to
reaction shots from the network's control room, which generally
involve someone describing G's actions like a bad play-by-play
announcer. It's distractions like these that detract from the
movie, and make you aware of its flaws.
</P>
<P>
   And of its _ to use an oxymoron _ benevolent hypocrisy. It's
such a good-natured movie that you almost don't notice that G's
anti-materialism message is the opposite of what Hollywood
generally stands for. Leave it to a Disney-owned picture to create
a character who says that the spiritual is more important than the
corporeal, and makes people rich by doing so. Talk about your
profits without honor.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Holy Man''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Stephen Herek
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Eddie Murphy, Jeff Goldblum, Kelly Preston
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ a few swear words and some off-color humor
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
