A6966 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      10-08 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TEXAS DEMOCRATS VOTE FOR GOP IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reps. Nick Lampson and Jim Turner, both freshmen
Democratic House members from Texas, were among 31 Democrats who
voted for a Republican-sponsored impeachment inquiry into President
Clinton's role in the White House sex scandal and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Lampson later said he voted for the wide-ranging inquiry because
``the American people deserve a quick, fair and truthful
impeachment investigation of the president that brings this matter
to a close.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampson initially voted for a Democratic alternative that
limited the scope and time of the inquiry. However, when that
proposal failed, 236 to 198, splitting mostly along party lines,
Lampson then supported the Republican measure.
</P>
<P>
   He said he voted for the Republican plan ``to ensure that we are
able to move ahead in completing the investigation of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have said before, it's time to move forward with the
issues that matter most to working families _ strengthening the
economy, protecting our children and improving education,'' Lampson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who also voted for the unsuccessful Democratic option
and then for the Republican alternative, said after the vote that
Congress has a ``constitutional duty to proceed with the inquiry
into the allegation contained in the report sent to us by the
office of the independent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote to proceed with the inquiry is not a vote for
impeachment _ it is a vote to allow both the president and his
accusers to have their day in court,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said proceeding with the inquiry ``will not be a pleasant
task and it must be done impartially with the utmost care and
diligence. The American people want this matter behind us, it is
the responsibility of Congress to conclude this investigation in a
fair and just manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The wide-ranging inquiry that the House approved by a 258-176
vote Thursday makes Clinton the third president in history to face
the threat of removal from office by Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
