<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-HOLY-COX     10-08 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HOLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No sale: Murphy's `Holy Man' pitch lacks quality control
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When New Age home shopping guru G (Eddie Murphy) gives his TV
viewers an instruction, they pour out of their homes into the
evening air, determined to follow his bidding. It's the blatant
``Network'' moment in ``Holy Man.'' But instead of Peter Finch's
``I'm mad as hell and I'm not gonna take it anymore,'' G's mantra
is a soft-minded reflection of the movie: ``Just go look at some
grass.''
</P>
<P>
   In this comedy/drama/something-or-other, Murphy's drapery-clad
character drifts into the lives of Good Buy Shopping Network
producer Ricky (Jeff Goldblum) and media analyst Kate (Kelly
Preston), who's been hired to do something about Ricky's droopy
sales. In the words of Ricky's boss (Robert Loggia), the job is
about ``making people feel they have to have it when they don't
really want it.'' That applies equally to dinette sets, welcome
mats and cheesy, 2-karat gold bracelets.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that G, whom Ricky improbably invites to live with
him after a car-accident encounter, is the answer to all problems.
Whenever he goes on camera, his presence is so Zenfully refreshing
that people buy whatever he's hawking. Even when he tells them not
to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Good idea here. Lousy follow-up. The movie shows Jewish
scholars, Catholic priests and other religious leaders claiming
that G is one of their sect. That's easy to believe, because G
spouts a Cliffs Notes version of faith that can be more easily
traced to a Hallmark store than to any place of worship. In the
wake of ``What Dreams May Come,'' this is the second Hollywood film
in two weeks that boils spirituality down to, basically, ``Give
somebody a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, ain't nothing wrong with that. But it would help if the
movie were entertaining. From scene to scene, the soundtrack goes
from manic yuck-yuck chords to soul-stirring strings in its uneasy
bid to find a tone.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's high points are satiric clips of some of the
network's spots, including good-natured cameos from folks like
James Brown, Dan Marino, Florence Henderson and Morgan Fairchild.
If you think Fairchild's much-plugged scene getting an electric
face zap is indicative of the movie, don't be fooled. The jokes are
mild and far between.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be fooled by Murphy's top billing. His screen time is
surprisingly limited. The movie is about Ricky and Kate's
transition from scummy yuppie values to smell-the-flowers
enlightenment. Goldblum, as usual, is a twitchy, neurotic pro; his
prolonged reaction after he thinks he's just drunk someone's urine
is classic. Preston fares less well in a role that requires her to
be, well, blond.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Murphy. He's charming, as always. But fans of ``The
Nutty Professor'' and ``Doctor Dolittle'' shouldn't come expecting
to find him at his quicksilver, risque best. (The movie is rated
PG, but it's too bland for kids.)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem is that G is a literal blank, with no given
background or character trait besides a generalized West Coast
beatitude. In this movie, he exists solely to bring the white folks
together. Alerting them to problems they didn't know existed,
pointing them in the right direction, he's hardly human. He's not
Goldblum and Preston's guru; he's their spiritual Lassie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy Man''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eddie Murphy, Jeff Goldblum and Kelly Preston. Directed
by Stephen Herek. Rated PG. One hour, 53 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An unholy mess.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
