   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT-TALKS _ Hundreds of environmental journalists from
around the country are meeting in Chattanooga this weekend to talk
about how the media covers issues like sprawl, transportation and
the environment. Ted Turner, who is funding a foundation to examine
issues of sprawl in metro Atlanta, will give a speech to kick off
the conference. And one of the first topics (on Friday) will be the
plans for a high-speed train from Atlanta to Chattanooga. (Soto,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   GOV-DEBATE _ ORLANDO _ Jeb Bush and Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay face
off for the first of three debates between the two gubernatorial
candidates. Sponsored by Florida News Network and patterned after a
town hall meeting, the debate will draw questioners from studio
audiences in Orlando, Jacksonville, St. Petersburg and Miami.
(Crowley, Palm Beach Post). 25.
</P>
<P>
   ARTIFACTS _ MIAMI _ A 2,200-year-old mummy head wrapped in a
wool turban, an 800-year-old arm with a blue tattoo and a
1,800-year-old gold-filled fox-shaped headdress are among 208
artifacts heading back to Peru. The items will be formally returned
to the Peruvian government Thursday, 3 1/2 years after a U.S.
Customs agent stumbled across them at a Miami International Airport
warehouse. Some of the artifacts will be on display at the Florida
International Museum in St. Petersburg. (MToner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY-ENROLLMENT-INCREASE _ As some private universities
report record enrollment this fall, the Texas Higher Education
Coordinating Board releases university and college enrollment data,
showing an increase over last year. Texas is believed to be
experiencing the front-end of an enrollment increase that is
expected to surge after 2000. Nationally, enrollments are also are
trending upward. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-INSURANCE-DEBATE _ Texas insurers and consumer advocates
debate proposed property insurance benchmarks with Insurance
Commissioner Elton Bomer. Meanwhile, State Sen. Rodney Ellis
scheduled a news conference to discuss insurance redlining.
(Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WATER-RIGHTS _ Austin and other cities near the Colorado River
will not need to search for new sources of water until 2090 if
state regulators approve a $75 million purchase of water rights.
(Lindell, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UT-MONEY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In his first major speech since
becoming University of Texas president, Larry Faulkner recently
shared his vision for the future and spotlighted a four-point plan
to make ``a university of the first class'' even better. (Roser,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
