<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `One Tough Cop' uses one old plot
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From its wet city streets to its climactic bloody Pieta, ``One
Tough Cop'' plays like a generic, cable-ready police procedural.
That makes a couple of things about it especially surprising.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was made by a good director, Bruno Barreto (``Four
Days in September''). Second, despite its familiar, pulp-fiction
tale about the thin line between organized crime and cops on the
take, the movie is inspired by actual events. That just goes to
show that life can sometimes play like a mediocre TV movie.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Baldwin, starting to get the Baldwin brothers' curse of
chunkiness, plays New York police Detective Bo Dietl. He's a great
cop, but there's a problem: His best childhood friend is Richie
(Mike McGlone), who happens to be an underboss in the Florio crime
family.
</P>
<P>
   Since cops and crooks aren't usually best pals, Bo draws the
attention of a couple of FBI agents, who think he's on the take. It
doesn't help that Bo's partner, Duke (Chris Penn), is a gambler
deep in hock to a Florio loan shark (Paul Guilfoyle).
</P>
<P>
   The movie also throws in the case of a raped, mutilated nun (a
real-life event, which also inspired Abel Ferrara's ``Bad
Detective''). But the film's main badge-or-brotherhood crisis
centers on the men and their strained loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin turns in a competent performance, but he's one of those
actors with dead eyes; nothing seems to be going on inside his
character. Penn's hotheaded loser may remind you of Edward Norton's
character in ``Rounders.'' Just as in that movie, Baldwin's
continued forbearance of his partner's recklessness comes to seem
less like loyalty, more like stupidity. We lose sympathy for both
of them.
</P>
<P>
   McGlone is fine, but as soon as his girlfriend (Gina Gershon in
a tissue-thin role) starts to make eyes at Baldwin, you can bet
somebody will use the words ``Judas'' before the flick is over.
That's the trouble. ``Cop'' plays like a movie you've already seen
a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   Director Barreto shoots with solid skill, but he doesn't do any
favors for his real-life wife, Amy Irving. She turns up as one of
the stiff-lipped, humor-impaired feds. As she snarls lines like
``Dietl, we know you're dirty'' and ``Say goodbye to your career,
Dietl,'' you'll mainly be impressed that she keeps a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   ``One Tough Cop''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stephen Baldwin, Chris Penn and Mike McGlone. Directed
by Bruno Barreto. Rated R for strong violence and language. One
hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: One cliched movie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
