<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-LOLITA-COX     10-08 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LOLITA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest `Lolita' short on steam
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roman Polanski once said that the difference between eroticism
and pornography is simple: ``Eroticism is when you use a feather;
pornography is when you use the whole chicken.'' Since Adrian
Lyne's new version of Vladimir Nabokov's novel ``Lolita'' isn't
erotic and certainly isn't pornographic, perhaps you could say Lyne
used a rubber chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he should have. It might've picked things up.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing we see onscreen is the credit ``Showtime
Presents,'' a blatant reminder of the film's checkered history.
Made by Lyne several years ago for $60 million, ``Lolita'' became a
cause/scandal when American movie studios decided to pass up
distribution rights. After knocking around Europe _ and pretty much
getting knocked by the European critics _ ``Lolita'' was finally
picked up by the cable TV channel Showtime and aired several times
in August. It was also, before its television debut, screened
theatrically in Los Angeles to make it eligible for the Academy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Now the film is being picked up nationally and in Atlanta,
thanks to art-house exhibitor George Lefont, a longtime believer in
letting local moviegoers decide for themselves whether or not they
want to see something potentially ``controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the picture's past. What is presently onscreen is
neither a triumph nor a travesty. The 1962 Stanley Kubrick version,
a frisky black comedy starring James Mason and Peter Sellers, is a
better movie.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are several things to recommend Lyne's take on
Nabokov's tale of a 40-ish college professor, Humbert Humbert
(Jeremy Irons), who falls in love with his landlady's (Melanie
Griffith) adolescent daughter, Lolita (newcomer Dominique Swain).
Frank Langella also appears in the small role of Clare Quilty,
another man who knows _ and appreciates _ a nymphet when he sees
one.
</P>
<P>
   Irons, who can look more soddenly doleful than any other actor I
know, is quite effective as the middle-aged Humbert, caught in the
grip of his Lolita obsession. His voice-over readings of Nabokov's
prose are a treat, caressing such passages as Humbert's famous
incantation, ``Lolita. Light of my life, fire of my loins. My sin,
my soul. Lo-lee-ta.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith fares less well, serving mostly to remind us how deftly
Shelley Winters handled the same role in Kubrick's film. However,
young Swain _ she was 15 when filming began _ is rather good as
Lolita. In early scenes, she captures the preteen's instinctive yet
still unconscious flexing of her sexual power. Never as obvious as
Kubrick's tarty Lo, Sue Lyon, Swain has a gawky yet sensual appeal
that seems just right.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Lyne shows so little affinity for the material _
aside from recognizing its name value _ that he gets in his actors'
way. His attempts at comedy are woeful but, luckily, sporadic. Far
more of a problem is his gauzy, Victoria's Secret style and
sledgehammer approach. We get to see Lolita sucking on something _
a popsicle or an ice cream soda straw _ far too often. The repeated
close-ups of Irons _ a sallow, haunted slave to lust _ aren't just
unflattering; they're overkill.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an overlong, sometimes sluggish film. If you're
interested, check it out for yourself. But check your libido
outside. For Lyne, ``Lolita'' is truly a love story in which love
means never having to say ... jailbait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lolita''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jeremy Irons and Dominique Swain. Directed by Adrian
Lyne. Rated R for aberrant sexuality, nudity and brief violence. 2
hours,5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Too much Adrian Lyne, not enough Vladimir Nabokov.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
