<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER09-COX     10-08 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lear,' `Crime' present matchup of crazy men
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sunday night, if you can tear yourself away from the peanuts
'n' Crackerjack appeal of Game 4 in the Braves vs. Padres series,
there's a showdown that sounds more like a Great Books seminar than
a night of television: Dostoevski's ``Crime and Punishment'' vs.
Shakespeare's ``King Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Match of the Crazy-Man Classics. In this corner,
wearing grimy black clothes and a scraggly beard and wielding an
axe, Raskolnikov, the tortured student who murders a pawnbroker. In
the other corner, wearing a battered crown and a haunted 100-yard
stare, Lear, the mad monarch who divvies up his kingdom
prematurely, and suffers greatly for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lear,'' starring Ian Holm, is the season premiere of
``Masterpiece Theatre'' (PBS-check local listings), from which we
expect such challenging works. But ``Crime and Punishment'' (9 p.m.
EDT Sunday on NBC) is from the same network that brings you
``Suddenly Susan'' every week, and is part of NBC's experiment in
classing up its act a little: First ``Gulliver's Travels,'' then
``The Odyssey,'' and next up, a loose adaptation of Shakespeare's
``The Tempest'' on Nov. 27. Next thing you know, Joey and Chandler
will be debating Kierkegaard and ignoring the ugly naked guy.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Gulliver'' and ``Odyssey,'' ``C&AMP;P'' was made by Robert
Halmi, the Hungarian showman-producer. Shot on location in Budapest
(standing in for 19th century St. Petersburg), it's a surprisingly
faithful adaptation of Dostoevski's great novel that is also, not
surprisingly, unable to capture the novel's richness. It stars
Patrick Dempsey (``JFK: Reckless Youth'') as the guilt-ridden
Raskolnikov, Ben Kingsley as his persecutor, Magistrate Porfiry,
and Julie Delpy (``An American Werewolf in Paris'') as Sonya, the
good-hearted prostitute (she's straight out of Dostoevski, not a TV
invention) who's finally Raskolnikov's redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime and Punishment'' moves too fast at first, as if afraid
viewers will click away. When it finally settles down, it tries
mightily to capture the dementia of Raskolnikov's interior
monologues as his guilt binds him to Kingsley's pursuit, but
succeeds only partly. In the end, it's a Classics Illustrated comic
come to life, a better expenditure of your time than most TV
movies, but still a pale shadow of the book.
</P>
<P>
   If the rhythm of ``Crime and Punishment'' seems frazzled at
times, the camera movement in ``King Lear'' is almost nonexistent.
If this BBC TV adaptation of Britain's Royal National Theatre
production were any more visually minimalist, it would be radio.
Sets are stark, sometimes barren, and costumes nondescript and
utilitarian, which puts all the emphasis on the faces and the
language.
</P>
<P>
   At 66, Sir Ian Holm (``Chariots of Fire'') is at a great age to
play a great Lear: old enough to convince, robust enough to handle
the physical demands. (Unlike the London stage version, he does not
strip himself naked in the storm for TV.) His king is a seething,
sputtering Lear, and although he commands the stage, the supporting
cast is so deep and strong that ``Lear'' works even when Holm is
off.
</P>
<P>
   The play's most memorable scenes _ the chaos and dehumanization
of the storm scene, the blinding of Gloucester _ are almost
unbearable to watch.
</P>
<P>
   If, God forbid, the Braves are too far down to come back in
Sunday night's game, and it's a more refined agony you seek, turn
to the granddaddy of all pain, ``King Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   Grades: ``Lear'': A
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime'': B-
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Halloween treat
</P>
<P>
   Those who really know their monster movies may not be blown away
by the new documentary ``Universal Horror'' (8 EDT tonight on
Turner Classic Movies).
</P>
<P>
   It's too geared to a less savvy audience, people who don't
already know that a Spanish-language ``Dracula'' was filmed
concurrently, at night, on the same sets used by Bela Lugosi for
his ``Dracula.'' However, they'll still appreciate the huge
collection of clips and the astute commentary by such well-versed
horror experts as Ray Bradbury and David Skal.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Kevin Brownlow and narrated by Kenneth Branagh (two
more classy choices), the special spotlights Universal during the
'30s and '40s when the studio imprinted its images of
Frankenstein's Monster, Dracula, The Mummy and The Wolf Man on the
national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   As Skal points out, ``Ask somebody to draw a picture of
Frankenstein, they draw a picture of Boris Karloff. Ask any
8-year-old to talk like Dracula, they talk like Bela Lugosi.''
</P>
<P>
   The program strives to be all-inclusive in its delineation of
the history and impact of the horror movie. The good news is, it
includes such greats as James Whale. The bad news is, well, it
cheats. Long sections are devoted to horror classics like, say,
``King Kong.'' A classic, yes. But one made by RKO. Sometimes,
Universal's archives seem less important than Ted Turner's.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, ``Universal Horror'' is a Halloween treat for both
buffs and neophytes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
