<SLUG> BC-GAYS-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY GROUPS SQUARE OFF WITH RELIGIOUS RIGHT OVER TV ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new TV ad campaign that says gays and lesbians
can change their sexual orientation through Christian faith touched
off another battle between gay rights groups and religious
conservatives Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives held a news conference to display two
60-second commercials for which they plan to buy air time at
broadcast outlets around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials, similar to full-page ads that the groups began
running in newspapers this summer, depict men and women who say
they were formerly homosexual and that through Christianity they
now live as heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are sponsored by the conservative Family Research
Council, the Concerned Women for America, the Center for Reclaiming
America and several ministerial groups that seek to alter the
behavior of gays.
</P>
<P>
   In one ad a man says, ``The dream that I thought could never
happen, having a wife and kids, has finally come true.'' At the end
of the ad, seven people who say they had been gay proclaim in
unison that ``we are living proof'' that Christianity can change
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   In the other ad the mother of a former homosexual says, ``Just
because you love your children, it doesn't mean you approve of
everything they do. Sometimes they make bad choices.'' She advises
parents to let such youngsters know ``that there is hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ads end with the words, ``It's not about hate. It's about
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a later news conference, gay rights activists argued that
hate is at the core of the new TV spots.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Garry, executive director of the New York-based Gay and
Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation, said the ad sponsors ``are
showing their hand to the entire country and their message isn't
really about `hope' or `healing' or `understanding,' but rather
about intolerance, deception and moral bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Besen, associate director at the Washington, D.C.-based
Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian
political organization, said the ads were part of a
``misinformation campaign by the far right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conversion therapy is a kind of snake oil for the soul,''
added Elizabeth Birch, HRC executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Garry said she was asking television stations not to run the
ads, which also were denounced by Candace Gingrich, a lesbian
activist and House Speaker Newt Gingrich's half-sister.
</P>
<P>
   Caitlin Ryan, author of a book called ``Lesbian and Gay Youth:
Care and Counseling,'' said that religious immersion won't ``cure''
homosexuals. ``There is no evidence conversion therapy works,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical groups have said that attempts to change an
individual's sexual orientation may do more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 the American Academy of Pediatrics reported that
``therapy directed at specifically changing sexual orientation ...
can provoke guilt and anxiety while having little potential for
achieving changes in orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the American Psychiatric Association said that ``any
person who seeks conversion therapy may be doing so because of
social bias that has resulted in internalized homophobia.'' It also
said that ``gay men and lesbians who have accepted their sexual
orientation positively are better adjusted than those who have not
done so.''
</P>
<P>
   At their news conference, the conservative groups introduced
people who said Christianity had helped them change their
lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Yvette Cantu, a policy analyst with the Family Research Council,
said she had been a lesbian but found the lifestyle unfulfilling.
``Fortunately, I met people who were not afraid to tell me the
truth about my lifestyle, not only about its damaging effects, but
that I could be free from it,'' Cantu said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnston, president of Kerrusso Ministries in Newport
News, Va., said he renounced homosexuality nearly 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Changing one's orientation ``is not something that happens over
night,'' Johnston said. Success is when ``God gives you the
strength not to act on destructive desires.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the gay groups' news conference, three gay men and a
lesbian said they had tried unsuccessfully to become heterosexual
through years of Christian faith.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Smith, a lawyer in Washington, D.C., said that after six
years of trying to change, ``the truth is that I am still gay. God
made me this way. You can't change who God made you to be.'
</P>
<P>
   Birch said the Human Rights Campaign rejects claims by the
religious groups that ``thousands'' of men and women have become
heterosexual through Christianity. She said the HRC will begin
investigating such claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
