<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall: The House debates and
then votes to open an inquiry into the impeachment of President
Clinton. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: For all the talk
of duty and Constitution Thursday, it was not all that difficult
for the House to open a formal impeachment inquiry into President
Clinton. The more troublesome question is how Congress will bring
to a conclusion the impeachment process that Rep. Henry Hyde called
``this venture, this excursion, this journey.'' By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT (London) _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
confers on Kosovo with the NATO allies in Brussels, dispatches
envoy Holbrooke back to Belgrade, then meets with Contact Group
(including Russia) in London. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-KOREA (Tokyo) _ With the South Korean president in Tokyo,
Japan makes its first written government apology for its actions
during the 1910-45 colonial-era in Korea. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CONFIRM (Washington) _ As it prepares to adjourn for
the rest of the year, the Senate has not yet acted on dozens of
nominees approved by its committees, including the proposed
commissioner for the Food and Drug Administration. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   HARE-KRISHNA-ABUSE (Undated) _ In its own official journal, the
Hare Krishna movement has published an unusually candid expose
detailing widespread physical, emotional and sexual abuse of
children who were sent to live in the group's boarding schools so
that their parents could travel around soliciting donations for
their guru's books in airports and on the streets. The Hare Krishna
movement is now openly acknowledging that the legacy of abuse has
led many Hare Krishna children and their parents in this country to
abandon the faith. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ For six weeks, investors have lulled
themselves into thinking that the worst was over, that the selloff
that had wracked financial markets around the world had largely run
its course. That notion was shattered Thursday as stock prices
plunged and the strong dollar fractured. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-LITERATURE (Paris) _ Jose Saramago, a 75-year-old
Portuguese writer who took up literature relatively late in life
and whose richly novels soon won him a following of loyal readers
across Europe and vocal admirers in the United States, was awarded
this year's Nobel Prize in Literature by the Swedish Academy in
Stockholm. By Alan Riding.
</P>
