<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTIFACTS-COX     10-08 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIFACTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peruvian artifacts returned after 3 years
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A breathtaking collection of pre-Columbian artifacts,
smuggled out of Peru three years ago and seized by Customs agents
in Miami, were returned Thursday to the Peruvian government _ the
latest in a series of moves by U.S. authorities aimed at curbing
the growing international traffic in illicit artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 200 artifacts, incuding parts of human mummies,
gold icons, feathered headdresses and 1,000-year-old cotton
textiles were looted from at least a half-dozen archaeological
sites in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, which was being shipped through Miami to an
antiquities broker in Switzerland, represents the largest seizure
of pre-Columbian materials ever in the Southeastern United States.
Although the museum-quality pieces are considered priceless by
archaeologists, the street value of the items is estimated at more
than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``International traffic in items like this now ranks behind only
the smuggling of narcotics and arms,'' Deputy U.S. Attorney Carol
DiBattiste said at formal ceremonies returning the items to the
Peruvian government. ``We hope this sends a message to those who
might be tempted to engage in this illegal trade in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Customs officials acknowledge, however, that the seizure of
artifacts was largely a matter of luck. Customs agents in Miami
were actually looking for illegal drugs in February 1995 when they
searched a 4-foot-high packing crate labeled ``Peruvian
handicrafts'' _ declared value of $2,764 _ on the tarmac at Miami
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The crate, shipped from Lima, Peru, was being transferred to a
holding area for a later flight to Switzerland, when agents pried
the lid open and found box after box of carefully packed artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky in two respects,'' said Customs inspector Wayne
Russell. ``Ordinarily, when we look for drugs, we start breaking
things open to see what's inside them.''
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of Peruvian archaeologists, authorities eventually
identified material taken from sites representing at least seven
prehistoric Peruvian cultures, some of them dating back to 200 B.C.
A half-dozen items were looted from one of Peru's first
archaeological sites, the royal tombs of Sipan, more than a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have been less fortunate in their efforts to track
down the people behind the smuggling opeation. Peruvian police have
been looking for more than a year for the man who shipped the
crate. And Swiss police investigated the art broker to which the
crate was being shipped, but declined to take further action.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, Peruvian Counsel General Carlos Cornejo,
noting that Peru's cultural heritage is being spirited out of the
country at an alarming rate, praised the efforts of Customs agents
for the return of the ``truly magnificent'' items representing some
of Peru's earliest cultures.
</P>
<P>
   By international agreement, the United States is obligated to
return all Peruvian artifacts it seizes, but 40 choice pieces will
remain temporarily in the United States to be exhibited at the
Florida International Museum's exhibit on Peru's prehistoric
cultures, which opens in St. Petersburg on October 23. It's an
unexpected addition to the exhibit that museum officials say they
hope will dramatize the illicit traffic in artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami seizure is the second high-profile case involving
smuggled Peruvian artifacts this year. In July, U.S. authorities
returned an 1,800-year old gold armor plate, valued at $1.6
million, that had also been looted from the tombs of Sipan.
</P>
<P>
   Two Miami men pled guilty to smuggling charges after an FBI
``sting'' operation caught them trying to sell the gold plate in a
hotel parking lot in downtown Philadelphia. A Panamanian diplomat,
who the FBI says smuggled the piece into the United States via
diplomatic pouch, has been indicted, but has never arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
