A7025 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-NASA-HNS &LR;      10-08 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN SAYS HE'S BACK INTO SPACE AS A SCIENCE PASSENGER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Sen. John Glenn took issue Thursday with
those who have questioned NASA's decision to include the
77-year-old former Mercury astronaut as a member of its next space
shuttle crew.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is one of seven astronauts in training at the Kennedy
Space Center this week for the countdown and lift off of the
shuttle Discovery on Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   When the nine-day science mission launches, Glenn will become
the oldest human to fly in space, eclipsing the milestone
established in 1996 by Story Musgrave, who flew his sixth shuttle
mission at age 61.
</P>
<P>
   Musgrave retired in 1997 after three decades in NASA's astronaut
corps when managers told him not to expect future missions. Earlier
this month, he characterized Glenn as a ``legislative passenger''
on the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just disagree entirely with that statement,'' Glenn said at
Discovery's launching pad. ``I'm not back as a legislative
passenger. I'm back as a science passenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the basis on which I was selected and the basis on
which I have trained,'' Glenn said. ``If there are others who have
a different view of that, well, I just ask them to look at what
we've been doing and look at the experiments in detail.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to his hometown newspaper in Lexington, Ky., earlier
this month, Musgrave said that Glenn had taken a ``part-time''
approach to space. ``My record is: I cared about space enough to do
it for 30 years. I did not leave for greener pastures, then come
back as a passenger.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who became the first American to orbit the Earth in 1962,
says he left NASA three years later because the Kennedy
administration did not wish to risk the loss of a historical figure
as it raced the former Soviet Union to the moon. This year, he will
retire from the U.S. Senate after four terms.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn also chastised the news media on Thursday, saying it is
too focused on his participation on the upcoming shuttle flight at
the expense of the scientific research that is planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to report on the personal aspects of this thing, but
this is science at its very best, out there on the cutting edge,''
Glenn said. ``I'd invite you to get out there and report some of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's crew plans 83 different experiments over its nine
days in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was named to the crew in January and will participate in a
range of research projects intended to reveal whether there are
similarities between the physical stresses of spaceflight and
aging. They include bone and muscle tissue losses, difficulty
sleeping and degradation of the body's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Other experiments will look at changes in plant germination in
the absence of gravity and the potential exploitation of
weightlessness for the production of anti-cancer and anti-viral
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A satellite called Spartan the crew plans to deploy and retrieve
will also study subtle changes in the sun that influence the
Earth's climate.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery commander Curt Brown's crew arrived here Tuesday night
for three days of training. For the first two days, the shuttle
crew has rehearsed the procedures they would follow to escape the
launch pad if an emergency erupted while they were waiting to lift
off.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, they plan to don the pressure suits they will wear
for their lift off Oct. 29 and board the shuttle Discovery to
rehearse the final hours of their countdown. The exercise is
conducted prior to every shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat this just like it's a launch,'' said NASA's Steve
Altemus, who supervises countdown activities here. ``We are all
kind of excited, at least me personally, with the opportunity to
launch a national hero, a space pioneer.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
