</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN OFFICIAL CALLS FOR END TO STRICT RE-ELECTION LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The newly installed governor of Zacatecas called
Thursday for the abolition of one of Mexico's most sacred
doctrines: that top officeholders, beginning with the president,
may not run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Ricardo Monreal Avila also said that politics in Mexican is
changing rapidly and that voters are more likely to make ballot
decisions based on the candidate rather than the political party.
</P>
<P>
   Such a trend enabled Monreal to bolt the long-dominant
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) this spring and run on the
ticket of the center-left Democratic Revolution Party (PRD) before
he actually joined the party.
</P>
<P>
   Monreal, who took office in the central state of Zacatecas on
Sept. 12, told foreign correspondents at a wide-ranging breakfast
meeting in Mexico City that he formally enrolled in the party only
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we must eliminate the anti-re-election clause
from the Mexican Constitution,'' Monreal said. ``That principle
comes from the days of the Porfiriato and has no place in modern
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The Porfiriato is the popular reference to the 40-year rule of
Mexican dictator Porfirio Diaz, whose ouster in 1911 sparked the
nearly 20 years of killing and political turmoil known as the
Mexican Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, mayors, local and federal deputies may
serve more than one three-year term _ but not consecutively.
Governors, federal senators and the president serve six-year terms
and may not be re-elected to the same post.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts are now calling for an end to the
doctrine, arguing that it actually works against the democracy it
was meant to foster.
</P>
<P>
   Monreal said that the changeover should be phased in slowly,
beginning with the federal Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think that the term for mayors should be lengthened to
four years,'' he said. ``As it is now, a mayor no sooner begins
working than his term expires, and the next person comes in to
dismantle what the former began.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRD is developing the election strategy that made Monreal,
once a popular PRI national deputy, the party's first elected
governor.
</P>
<P>
   After a falling out with PRI leaders over who would head the
party's ticket in the Zacatecas elections, Monreal resigned and
became the PRD's ``external candidate,'' pledged to the party
platform without actually being a member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
