<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-MISSOURI-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY SPECIALISTS INSPECT FLOOD-RAVAGED AREAS IN KANSAS AND
MISSOURI TO ASSESS WHETHER FEDERAL DISASTER RELIEF IS WARRANTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Six teams of emergency specialists inspected
flood-ravaged areas in Kansas and Missouri on Wednesday to assess
whether damage from Sunday's deluge warrants federal disaster
relief.
</P>
<P>
   It then will be up to the governors of Kansas and Missouri to
ask President Clinton for a declaration of emergency to provide
federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   A federal emergency declaration would provide loans and grants
for homeowners, renters and businesses as well as temporary housing
assistance. Other programs may become available depending on the
declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Federal emergency management officials could not say how long it
would take for them to inspect eight counties in Missouri and four
counties in Kansas. But Warren Pugh Jr., a regional director for
the Federal Emergency Management Agency, said action was possible
as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If a disaster is declared, officials will publicize a toll-free
number where people can get information about all relief programs
that are available.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Administration, which is participating in the
assessment, may offer low-interest loans to homeowners and
businesses independent of a federal emergency declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Both states and Kansas City already have declared emergencies
and the Red Cross is offering assistance.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday one FEMA inspection team toured businesses on
Southwest Boulevard. Another walked through the Village Green
apartments on the north bank of Brush Creek and came up with a
preliminary count of 101 flood-damaged units.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors checked foundations for damage and noted the height
of water lines on the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we're not seeing much, but with our experience we
know what damage we're looking at,'' said Tim Burke, a FEMA
investigator with 24 years' experience in disaster evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors spoke with relatively few individuals, but they could
see evidence of their plight in the piles of flood debris outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Village Green residents Felicia Smith and Leona Stewart both had
applied to the Red Cross for lodging assistance on Tuesday, but
were told someone first needed to look at their damaged apartments.
</P>
<P>
   They were still waiting on Wednesday when they spoke with Chuck
May of the Missouri State Emergency Management Agency, who was part
of the FEMA team. May took their names and numbers and promised to
follow up with the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has had to move her three children to a motel. Stewart
located temporary shelter but could stay only three days.
</P>
<P>
   Another Village Green resident, Phillip Binns, said he believes
state officials should ask for federal help. Binns also would like
the Army National Guard to help in the search for missing victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are some of our loved ones and friends floating around
out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri governor or lieutenant governor has authority to
call out the Guard without a federal emergency declaration, but
state officials said that is a last resort because most Guard
members have other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some communities wanted the Guard to come in to help with
debris removal, but the Department of Transportation said they
could do that,'' said Susie Stonner, spokeswoman for the Missouri
State Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Stonner added that the Missouri Water Patrol and the Highway
Patrol are assisting in the search for missing persons.
</P>
<P>
   The federal and state assessment teams are inspecting sites in
Johnson, Wyandotte, Leavenworth and Douglas counties in Kansas. In
Missouri they are looking at sites in Jackson, Platte, Clay, Cass,
Lafayette, Carroll, Chariton and Saline counties.
</P>
<P>
   Teams first began inspecting the hardest-hit areas in Kansas
City and Kansas City, Kan. At least one team also planned to visit
Carrollton, Mo., which had up to 10 inches of rain Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency officials issued a reminder that flood insurance is
available for homeowners or renters in most area communities
through the National Flood Insurance Program.
</P>
<P>
   It is not necessary to live within a 100-year flood plain to
purchase flood insurance. People within a 100-year flood plain with
federally backed mortgages, however, are required to buy flood
insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
