<SLUG> BC-ESCAPEE-FREE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WHO ESCAPED FROM PRISON IN 1976 WILL NOT BE SENT BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMYRA, Mo. _ In 1976 it took Sandra Blount only minutes to
escape from the jail in this small town. It took her until
Wednesday to be truly free.
</P>
<P>
   That is when a Circuit Court judge chose not to send the
Sedalia, Mo., woman back to jail. Blount, held on bad-check
charges, had escaped from jail because she was concerned about her
children. She had lived undetected until June.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert M. Clayton II on Wednesday sentenced Blount, 55, to
two years of unsupervised probation and 80 hours of community
service. The judge said two decades of guilt and fear had been
enough punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said you've probably been on a kind of probation for
the last 22 years,'' Clayton told Blount. ``I think there's
certainly some truth to that.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the sentence, Blount took off her glasses and let
the tears flow. She hugged her husband, Fred, and sobbed: ``It's
over; it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount had kept the escape a secret from her husband of 18
years. He found out in June when the FBI tracked Blount down and
police arrested her.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest shocked much of Sedalia, where Blount had developed a
network of friends. She was beloved at the Rest Haven nursing home,
where she worked as a cook. Her Husband was stunned, too.
</P>
<P>
   But he stuck by her. He drove six hours round-trip for half-hour
visits while she was in the Palmyra Jail. The couple went into debt
to pay Blount's bail and phone calls to the jail.
</P>
<P>
   Often his support was silent _ on Wednesday, he lovingly rested
his hand on Blount's shoulder while she received last-minute
instructions from her attorney. The Blounts had always said their
marriage was ``for better or worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship is a lot stronger than it's ever been,''
Blount said. ``It's always been strong, but now we don't have
anything to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton cited the support of Blount's family and friends as
reasons for the sentence. He also cited the ``most glowing report I
have ever seen,'' from a Sedalia parole officer who advised against
jail time.
</P>
<P>
   That report from Sandy Lefevers acknowledged that Blount showed
``poor judgment'' for not turning herself in. The report also noted
that Blount was ``remorseful and cooperative'' and had not received
even a speeding ticket since her escape.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said: ``Obviously you have been very successful in the
last 22 years and been a good citizen. I don't think putting you in
jail is going to deter anyone from trying to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some in Sedalia thought Blount should have been sent back
to jail. In Palmyra, Marion County prosecutors had pursued the case
aggressively. Prosecutor Thomas Redington, however, did not argue
for jail time Wednesday. He declined to comment after the
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The Blounts are shaken but grateful they're still together.
Financial donations have helped them move into another home. They
plan to stay in Sedalia, and they look forward to recapturing their
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   As Blount walked out, she said she realized that a painful
chapter of her life was ending. It was a chapter that began with a
rash decision by a scared woman in the jail down the street from
the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I can finally say that all this is over,'' Blount said.
``I don't know that I'll ever come back here again. But I have good
and bad memories. This is where it started, and this is where it
ended. It ended good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to try to get on with our lives,'' she said.
``It's time to move forward and stop looking back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
