<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-DEREGULATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASTER PACE ON NATURAL GAS DEREGULATION IS URGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ A top federal energy regulator has declared this
period the ``dog days'' of deregulation and is urging a much faster
pace to bring competition to the natural gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Hoecker, chairman of the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission, said progress in deregulating energy markets _ both gas
and electric _ had been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, we can't be altogether sanguine by our progress,''
Hoecker said earlier this week. ``But the competition genie is
clearly out of the bottle, and I believe there is no going back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoecker spoke to more than 300 state regulators and utility
executives from around the country who met in Pittsburgh this week
to discuss whether to give natural gas customers more choice in
selecting a supplier for the fuel and how to do so. Advocates say
such moves could save consumers money.
</P>
<P>
   Hoecker told the conference, which ended Wednesday, that
bringing more competition to the natural gas industry was a chore
that regulators must complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly not for sissies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The conference focused on customer choice and other ways
utilities might better serve their customers. Several industry
officials said the issue of how to benefit consumers had received
new interest since a series earlier this year by The Kansas City
Star about the natural gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series exposed the flaws,'' said Nicholas Bush, president
of the Natural Gas Supply Association, based in Washington.
``They're talking about these issues now.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-part series looked at deregulation of the natural gas
industry and how it has affected consumers. One conclusion was that
most utilities could do more to protect consumers from the sort of
gas price spikes that occurred two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the series looked at how the use of price indexes
magnified the spikes. Price indexes are compiled by trade
publications that ask buyers and sellers at what price they buy or
sell the fuel. The indexes are then used by buyers of natural gas,
including utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Gorak, a Baltimore lawyer who was on a conference panel
discussing the volatility of natural gas prices, said the indexes
could explain at least some of the natural gas price swings.
</P>
<P>
   Reform may be on the way. Hoecker said his agency was working on
a plan to use the Internet for a daily auction to set costs for
transporting gas through interstate pipelines. One possibility is
that the Internet could eventually be used in a similar way to help
set a price for natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly in the mix of things,'' Gorak said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state regulators, who have much of the responsibility
for deregulating local utilities, are looking at ways to reduce
price swings. One possibility is the use of options or other
financial instruments to put a limit on how much prices can
increase. Utilities in Missouri and Kansas and in about four other
states are doing that now.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly the biggest issue at the energy conference was
customer choice, the name for giving consumers a choice of gas
suppliers. Supporters say such a plan can reduce gas bills 10
percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Others think, however, that going from a fully regulated
monopoly to a more freewheeling environment should be done with
extreme caution to ensure reliability of supply and avoid consumer
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Gas Service, for example, is asking that the rules be
relaxed slightly to allow medium-size users to shop for gas. But in
Kansas and Missouri, smaller commercial and all residential
customers are still obligated to purchase gas from a utility.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gas Energy recently started a campaign with the
Consumer Energy Council to educate its customers on customer
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Crumpton, a commissioner with the Missouri Public Service
Commission, said the state would approach customer choice carefully
after looking at how other states fare.
</P>
<P>
   Many shared Crumpton's impulse to move slowly, questioning
whether potential savings have been overstated. Only about a
half-dozen states have deployed large-scale customer choice
programs for their residents, and several others have pilot
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Among states moving aggressively toward customer choice is Ohio,
where savings averaging 10 percent have been achieved for more than
70,000 consumers. John Partridge Jr., an executive with Columbia
Gas of Ohio, said consumer choice was viable.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh, where the natural gas industry was founded more than
a century ago, recently started a consumer choice program, and city
officials said it was saving consumers money.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Laffer, the father of supply-side economics, weighed in
on the issue of deregulating natural gas during his keynote address
at the conference by warning not to phase it in but to deregulate
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it right,'' Laffer said. ``Do it now, bang.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
