<HEADER>
A7055 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      10-08 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME THINGS DON'T NEED CHANGING, BUT REFORMERS, IMPROVERS ARE
EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: I was saddened to read a dispatch from France the other
day telling that Paris authorities next week will put in service a
new Metro line served by driverless trains traveling between
stations at twice the speed of trains on the older lines.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the New York or London subways, the Metro already is
a model of efficiency, and certainly of cleanliness. But in the way
of progress, I suppose it is only a matter of time before this new
means of moving passengers metastasizes throughout the whole Paris
network.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the 242 people needed to run a conventional line of
the same length, the announcement said, all 13 trains on the new
line can be operated by only four persons from a computerized
command post above one of the stations.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman explained that Metro drivers no longer will be
cooped up alone in an operator's compartment. Instead, they will be
free to circulate on the platform and through the trains, mingling
with the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   This dismays me on a couple of counts.
</P>
<P>
   I don't doubt for a moment those drivers are fine company and
splendid conversationalists, but when I lived in Paris I did not
take public transit in the hope of forming a social relationship
with a Metro employee.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, while redundant safeguards surely have been built
into the automated system, machines _ even computers _ have been
known to err.
</P>
<P>
   It always reassured me to know there was a living person sitting
right up front in the lead car, looking through the windshield with
something personally at stake if he happened to notice another
train's headlight approaching on the same track.
</P>
<P>
   The design of the station platform itself also will be
different. A plastic barrier will separate waiting riders from the
track, its doors sliding open to admit them when the train has
halted in place.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose is to prevent careless travelers from falling onto
the rails, or the melancholy and the deranged from deliberately
flinging themselves down into that deadly defile.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is very tidy, I suppose, but it does create a
problem for those Parisians yearning to divest themselves of the
burdens of this world.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since wire nets were placed just below the upper platforms
of the Eiffel Tower to catch jumpers, the Metro has been the
preferred method of public self-destruction. It is fast and, above
all, it is certain.
</P>
<P>
   Take away the tower and the Metro track, and in a country where
the private ownership of guns is rare what's left? Poison
mushrooms, bad wine, tainted shellfishand of course the river _ the
ageless Seine, into whose cold embrace the desperate and the
lovelorn have been throwing themselves for as long as French poets
and novelists have been writing.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, that's the news I got the other day from Paris. And by
and large, like the glass pyramid at the Louvre, the news was a
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the obvious truth that some things in this world
don't need changing, the reformers and the improvers are
everywhere. The rest of us are just riders aboard a train without a
driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
