<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7076 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAPALM-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      10-08 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPALM-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMEN PROTEST USE OF NAVY NAPALM TO BURN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS
IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH RENDON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of gallons of napalm processed at a Deer Park, Texas,
plant south of Houston are being used to burn hazardous materials
in Port Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   Two Texas congressmen have sent letters to the U.S. Navy about
the incineration of the processed Vietnam-era napalm. They are
concerned because when the jellied gasoline was sent to Texas,
officials indicated it eventually be used as fuel for cement kilns.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, about 5,000 gallons of the napalm _ blended with other
solvents at the GNI plant _ were sent by truck on Wednesday to the
Chemical Waste Management facility located about seven miles west
of Port Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   The burning using the recycled napalm, which has the consistency
of fuel oil, started Thursday morning and is expected to end
Friday. It is a considered a test burning.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Reeves, vice president of regulatory affairs for GNI, said
ChemWaste is using the napalm mixture as a fuel during its
incineration process. The plant, he said, has a rotating kiln for
burning solid hazardous materials. When the materials are burned,
there are gases that are not destroyed and require a second burn.
It is during the second burn, known as the after-burn, that the
napalm is being used, Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gary, manager of the Chem Waste plant, was out of the office
Thursday and could not be reached for comment. ChemWaste was one of
three Texas companies that were vying for the $9 million napalm
contract when it was awarded to GNI.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said Chem Waste is not capable of burning all the napalm
that is recycled by GNI.
</P>
<P>
   The first 22,000-gallon shipment of napalm was sent by rail in
July to the GNI plant from the Fallbrook Naval Weapons Support
Facility in California.
</P>
<P>
   The detonators had been removed from the 3.4 million gallons of
napalm stored in canisters since the 1970s. The canisters, however,
started to leak and posed an environmental threat, which forced the
Navy to seek a disposal plan.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said GNI has not received any more of the jellied
gasoline since the initial shipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor will we until we have firm contracts and consistent
outlets. As soon as that happens we'll start receiving again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said several companies, including cement kilns, are under
consideration for contract to receive the processed napalm. The
recycled napalm could be used in cement kilns as an alternative to
fossil fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anybody that I can name, but there are several
others that are under consideration for contract. I realize on the
surface it doesn't look like it's moving along very quickly but
under the surface there is a lot of activity going on and a lot of
people are looking at samples,'' Reeves said. ``Hopefully in the
few short weeks, sooner I hope, there will be more information
about other outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Yocum, spokesman for Columbus, Ohio-based Battelle
Memorial Institute, which holds the main napalm recycling contract,
said GNI has been unable to find a cement kiln that wants the
recycled napalm.
</P>
<P>
   Yocum said he thinks no cement kiln has agreed to take the
napalm because of the publicity surrounding the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, it's been a very hot potato. That is my guess as
to why the cement kilns have backed away because it is an excellent
fuel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Reeves said no Texas company was being considered to
receive the recycled napalm.
</P>
<P>
   Texas congressmen Kent Bentsen and Gene Green, both Houston
Democrats, have sent letters to Navy Secretary John Dalton about
the incineration.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen told Dalton he was concerned the processed napalm would
be burned at Safety Clean (formerly Laidlaw) which is adjacent to
GNI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such action would be contrary to repeated assurances the Navy
has provided to the public, the city of Deer Park, the State of
Texas, and to me that the napalm would not be incinerated at this
facility,'' Bentsen wrote. ``It would severely undermine public
confidence in this project and the credibility of all involved and
raise significant new questions about public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said, however, ``There is no truth to the rumor that this
material is being shipped to Laidlaw for burning.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen wrote that the Navy had never mentioned the napalm being
used at hazardous waste facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Green wrote that the option of incineration as a proper method
for disposing of the napalm was never discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Pirie Jr., assistant secretary of the Navy, responded
to Green saying that since there were no contracts with cement
kilns, the napalm would be used as incinerator fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The napalm would be used in lieu of natural gas, or other new
fuels, to destroy hazardous wastes,'' he said. ``Although not our
first choice, and more expensive than the kiln option, using the
blended fuel as an alternative fuel for an incinerator meets our
goal of recycling.''
</P>
<P>
   Port Arthur City Manager Steve Fitzgibbons said there have not
been any protests against the shipping of the napalm product to the
Chem Waste facility although many residents expressed concern when
an informational meeting was held earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Combs, a spokesman for U.S. Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Beaumont,
whose district includes Port Arthur, said Lampson was disappointed
the recycled napalm was not being used at cement kilns, as
originally announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this is just a sample test and a small amount of the
product, he feels it is wise to see what this sample tells us and
then go from there,'' Combs said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
