<HEADLINE>
MAKING IT WITH THE BIG FROMAGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The president looked at me and our eyes locked. The gesture
was both imperial and flirtatious, his profile was that of a Roman
proconsul about to march on Rome. He commented on the dress I was
wearing, comparing it to the color of the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From an anonymous novel, ``A Friend From Bygone Days,''
published in France last week, about an affair with Francois
Mitterrand. A French commentator quoted in the Times of London
said, ``If all Mitterrand's former mistresses start writing books,
then it's a jolly good thing he commissioned the tres grand
bibliotheque.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIKE TYSON'S RAGE AND REASON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an angry, profane but moving interview in the latest Playboy,
 &UR; Mike Tyson &LR;  reveals his self-awareness. Interviewer  &UR; Mark &LR; 
 &UR; Kram &LR;  begins by asking whether some of Tyson's recent jobs,
refereeing pro wrestling, for example, demean his image.
</P>
<P>
   ``What image do I need to worry about?'' answers Tyson. ``I've
been in prison. I've been convicted of rape. I've had problems in
and out of court. Are you kidding me? I do what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Kram asks Tyson about a string of promoters and handlers who
made money from his career. ``Listen,'' says the boxer, ``I have
opinions about these guys, but I want to say it to their faces, not
behind their backs. And I don't want any sympathy from anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said he expects ``the worst to happen to me in my life. I
expect people to f_ me and treat me bad. That's just what I expect.
... I expect that one day somebody, probably black, will blow my f_
brains out over some f_ B.S. ... I expect that to happen in my
life. No one gives a f_ about Mike Tyson. If someone accuses Mike
Tyson of a horrible crime, they say, `Yeah, he's capable of that.
Mike probably did it.' Nobody's fighting a crusade for my black
ass.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown achievements: The Saint  &UR; John Coltrane &LR;  African
Orthodox Church on Divisadero Street in San Francisco is featured
in next week's People magazine. As to other local institutions,
 &UR; Warren Hinckle  &LR; has become a senior citizen. Hinckle celebrated his
60th birthday on Wednesday night at the Washington Square Bar &AMP;
Grill with party animal  &UR; Jack Davis &LR;  and  &UR; Ron  &LR; and  &UR; Linda &LR; 
 &UR; Fimrite &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Barbie &LR; , the slut: The latest issue of Country America
includes an ad from Mattel for Rendezvous Barbie: ``From her black
fishnet stockings to her geometric shaped mask, to her platinum
updo with multicolored strands of hair woven through it, this is a
Barbie doll unlike any you've ever seen.'' There's no word yet on
the availability of Ken in a motel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; _ The royals are throwing two big shindigs _  &UR; Prince Charles &LR; '
50th birthday party and  &UR; Peter Phillips &LR; ' (he's  &UR; Princess Anne &LR; 's
son) 21st birthday party _ on November 14, and  &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR; 
will be forced to attend one and not the other. The Mail says
``(this) is the first public evidence of current tension between
senior royals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STAMP THAT TAKES A LICKING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Stamp collector  &UR; Agostino Crotti &LR;  of San Francisco forwards a
letter to the editor of the weekly Linn's Stamp News, &LR;  complaining
about recently issued presorted standard-rate Green Bicycle stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The face of each shows a modernistic drawing of a bicycle
mechanism with the bold words, ``Presorted STD.'' This picture,
writes a Washington stamp collector, ``looks more like a
gynecologist's instrument than a bicycle. Recent generations of
citizens will distinctively understand STD as `sexually transmitted
disease.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `I came rushing into the house to get ready. I cast my circle,
began the spell, and all of a sudden I realized I'd forgotten to
turn off the radio. I'm thinking, what do I do? Do I stop? Do I
start over? Finally, I decided to clear my mind and continue the
spell. It was very general: Bring me somebody. Two weeks later, I'm
dating that radio station's DJ. There was no other reason I'd have
dated him. He was a jerk. We had nothing in common.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kirsten Rostedt, a 31-year-old law student and witch, tells
Marie-Claire about the first time she cast a spell.
</P>
</TEXT>
