<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST-REPAIR-ART-AZR     10-08 1629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-REPAIR-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATION PROCEDURES AID BREAST RECON STRUCTION  
 (ART ADV: PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Losing a breast to cancer is devastating. Some women
call it an amputation _ chilling words.
</P>
<P>
   But today's state-of-the-art techniques can reconstruct breasts
lost to cancer with amazing cosmetic results. Many surgeons are
using breast conservation procedures that cut away less in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Few radical mastectomies, in which the breast and considerable
tissue underneath the arm _ to eliminate involved lymph nodes _ are
removed, are performed today. Removal of tissue beyond the breast
causes significant pain and discomfort, often restricting a woman's
arm and shoulder movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one of the most persistent problems post-mastectomy,''
says Scottsdale, Ariz., surgeon Dr. Robin Staerkel.
</P>
<P>
   For patients who must have a mastectomy, the preferred operation
is the modified radical mastectomy, in which just a few nodes are
removed along with the breast. Surgeons no longer need to remove a
large wedge of the breast. Instead, they make an incision and scoop
out the tissue, while leaving most of the outer skin. This is
called ``skin sparing'' and makes reconstruction easier.
</P>
<P>
   Also common today is the lumpectomy, or breast conservation, in
which only the tumor and some lymph nodes are removed. Surgery is
followed by radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown no difference in long-term survival rates
between mastectomy and lumpectomy where the latter is deemed
appropriate, says Dr. Barbara Pockaj (pronounced POCH-Kye), a
surgeon at Mayo Clinic Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only about half of eligible women receive the more
conservative procedure, she says. Pockaj vigorously promotes
conservative techniques, believing they are just as successful and
enhance a woman's psychological outcome.
</P>
<P>
   When scarring can be kept to a minimum, she says, ``it's less of
a reminder when you wake up in the morning that you've had
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The new thinking, she says, is ``less is more.''
</P>
<P>
   Why don't more surgeons practice conservation?
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors who have been working in the field for many years
are comfortable with time-honored procedures, even though
statistics support newer methods, Pockaj says. Conservation surgery
is also more difficult to perfect.
</P>
<P>
   But some doctors insist that taking the whole breast is the only
way to ensure there will be no recurrence of the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Women who are not good candidates for breast conservation
include those with multiple tumors, women with connective tissue
disease, and pregnant women who cannot undergo radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Age makes no difference, Pockaj says. She has performed
conservation surgery on an 87-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women are very happy with breast conservation,''
Pockaj says. ``The public demands it.''
</P>
<P>
   Removal of lymph nodes also has benefited from new technology.
Complications of extensive node removal include pain, swelling of
the arm, decreased range of motion and localized fluid retention.
Surgeons often feel most comfortable removing more nodes than will
prove ultimately necessary _ just to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a technique called sentinel lymph node biopsy can spare
women some discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   The pioneering operation was discussed in a recent issue of the
``New England Journal of Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Pockaj explains how the procedure works:
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before breast cancer surgery, the surgeon injects a
radioactive substance at four points around the tumor. After the
tumor has been removed, a blue dye is injected in the space left by
the tumor. Using a hand-held gamma ray counter and visual
observation of the trail of dye, surgeons can locate the ``hot
spot'' _ the lymph node that is first in line to absorb cancer
cells from the tumor. This is called the sentinel lymph node.
</P>
<P>
   That node and just a few others can be removed, reducing
devastation. Nodes removed are immediately examined for traces of
cancer. If tests are negative, no further action is taken. If tests
are positive, more nodes can be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Late this year, a study of the procedure will get under way,
sponsored by the National Cancer Institute and involving about
4,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so remarkable,'' says Staerkel, the Scottsdale surgeon.
``It's very exciting to have that technology available.''
</P>
<P>
   Once cancer surgery has been completed, reconstruction of the
breast can begin. Results after a mastectomy can be dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   One method used at the Mayo Clinic is called a ``tram'' flap and
uses tissue taken from the abdomen to rebuild the breast. A wedge
is removed from the abdomen and is burrowed underneath the skin up
to the breast. Blood supplies can be kept intact.
</P>
<P>
   Pockaj says the procedure works well, but it is not without
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Leighton, a Scottsdale plastic and reconstructive
surgeon, does not favor the tram flap procedure, believing it can
restrict movement in the majority of breast reconstruction cases. A
piece of mesh is inserted into the abdomen where the tissue has
been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Staerkel is also hesitant to recommend tram flaps, saying the
operation is a long one and that patients who are obese or who
smoke are not good candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Because a major artery maintains the blood supply to the tram
flap, smokers could find that artery soon clogged with plaque,
compromising its function. In obese women, there is an excess of
fat in the abdomen, and outcome of the operation can be poor.
</P>
<P>
   In all patients, removing part of the muscle and skin from the
abdomen can leave a weakened abdominal wall that could develop a
hernia, according to literature published by the Mayo Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   But Leighton says tram flaps have advantages. Because the
patient's own tissue is used to rebuild the breast, the patient
avoids complications of implants, including rupture, deflation and
hardening of the breast.
</P>
<P>
   He agrees patients do well over time.
</P>
<P>
   Tram flaps are especially appropriate after radiation, when the
skin has been rendered somewhat fibrous.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Leighton prefers using expanders to stretch the
skin of the breast, then inserting a saline (salt solution) or
silicone implant. Silicone, he believes, is not health-threatening
and proves softer and more natural feeling than saline.
</P>
<P>
   Expanders can be inserted under the muscle of the breast at the
time of surgery, giving the woman some sense of a breast when she
wakes up. A small valve allows the expander _ also called a saline
balloon _ to be filled at the rate of about two ounces of fluid
each week for two months.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the valve can be removed and the expander left
intact to serve as an implant. Or a new implant can replace the
balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Staerkel likes the idea of inserting something into a woman's
chest at the time of breast cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women do wake up with a vision of themselves and not as
amputations,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Once the breast contour has been restored, Leighton goes to work
creating a nipple.
</P>
<P>
   It's a small but important part of a woman's self-image,
Staerkel says. ``It's so devastating to lose a nipple.''
</P>
<P>
   Removing the nipple is unavoidable. As the hub of the milk
ducts, it always harbors cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   New nipples once were made from tissue from other parts of the
body _ the groin, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Leighton prefers using scar tissue from the mastectomy
incision, which is more erectile and makes a firmer and more
natural-looking nipple. Six weeks later, the patient returns to
have an areola _ the colored area encircling the nipple _ tattooed
on. Results can be remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Patients are ``totally, 100 percent pleased,'' he says of
reconstructive work.
</P>
<P>
   Another technique now being used for breast reconstruction is
called a purse-string or drawstring incision. The surgeon excises
the nipple and areola with a circular cut and removes the entire
breast, saving the outer skin. The opening is closed in a
drawstring fashion. An implant then can be inserted.
</P>
<P>
   When the new nipple is created, it is attached over that
incision and virtually covers the scar.
</P>
<P>
   Leighton prides himself on other ways of hiding scars. Even when
the incision stretches across the breast, he gradually _ over
several years with more than one operation _ can move the scar down
until it is hidden underneath the breast.
</P>
<P>
   Leighton is sensitive to women's emotional needs after breast
cancer surgery, noting that patients need not only their breasts
repaired but also their self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still devastated, they're still depressed,'' he says.
``Starting the reconstruction immediately really helps.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reducing risk &QL; 
Preventing breast cancer is difficult. A woman's greatest risk
factors are her gender and advancing age _ tough odds to beat.  &QL; 
Luckily, fewer patients are suffering advanced disease, thanks to
education and the more frequent use of mammograms. Mammograms,
which take X-ray pictures of the breast, can aid in early cancer
detection. &QL; 
Women ages 50 to 69 have a reduced death rate if they have an
annual mammogram. Women 40 to 49 also might have a lower death
rate, but the reduction is less. &QL; 
Dr. Barbara Pockaj, a surgeon with Mayo Clinic Scottsdale, offers
these tips to reduce the risk: &QL; 
- Follow a low-fat diet with plenty of vegetables, especially
broccoli and cauliflower. &QL; 
- Include soy products in your diet _ tofu, tofu cheese, soy milk. &QL; 
- Maintain proper weight without wide fluctuations. &QL; 
- Reduce alcohol consumption. Liquor may be good for the heart, but
it's bad for the breast. (Of course, the leading cause of death in
America is heart disease.) &QL; 
- Get plenty of exercise. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
