<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS, WHITE HOUSE WORK LATE INTO NIGHT HOPING TO STRIKE
SPENDING DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With an eye on the clock, congressional and White
House negotiators met late into the night Thursday hoping to strike
a deal on a spending package that would avert an election-year
government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   But while both sides continued to talk compromise, lawmakers
were busy preparing a temporary spending measure that would keep
federal agencies operating past midnight Friday when another
stopgap funding bill expires.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Republican leaders said they were prepared
to drop some of their policy demands in order to reach basic
spending agreements on the remaining appropriations bills for the
1999 fiscal year. But it seemed clear that no deal would be reached
before Congress' scheduled adjournment deadline of Friday, and
members resolved to work through the weekend to finish up their
work.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to smooth over differences with the White House so he can
send members home to campaign for re-election, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., advised Republicans to abandon any
policy positions that turn out to be obstacles to reaching final
agreements with the president and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a money agreement, if there is a policy dispute,
pitch it,'' Lott said he told his negotiators. ``There will be
people back here next year who can fight policy battles.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton met with his budget team to review
the progress made thus far in negotiations with the Republicans.
Facing an impeachment inquiry, he said ``the most important thing''
he could do now was ``to work in the next few days to cross party
lines'' in hopes of reaching a compromise spending agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that he intends to stick to some of his priorities,
especially on education and environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to pass a budget that protects the (budget)
surplus and still will save Social Security, that keeps the
American economy going amidst all this economic turmoil in the
world, that protects instead of damages the environment, and that
gives the kind of priority to our elementary and secondary
education that it so clearly needs,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But he indicated a willingness to give on some issues to avoid a
government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will require us to put progress ahead of partisanship ...
and I hope we can do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday, Congress had passed only six out of 13 major
appropriations measures, but Clinton vetoed one of them _ the $60
billion farm bill _ because it was nearly $4 billion short of the
$7.3 billion he requested in emergency relief for farmers and
ranchers hard hit this year by droughts and floods.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said the farm bill would be rolled together
with at least five other appropriations measures today and placed
in one large catchall spending measure, called an omnibus bill,
that will likely be approved Friday by the House and Senate. At the
same time, Congress also will pass another temporary spending
measure that will keep government agencies running through early
next week just in case Clinton ends up vetoing the omnibus bill.
</P>
<P>
   The omnibus measure is likely to include funding for not only
the agriculture department, but for education, interior, labor,
justice and health and human service operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chances are we're going to be here through at least Sunday.
So, we need to be ready with a (temporary spending) bill to keep
the government open,'' said one Republican aide familiar with the
budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well this weekend, Lott said that he hopes
congressional leaders will be able to place the traditional
end-of-session phone call to Clinton telling him that Congress has
finally concluded its work for the year and is headed home. Asked
what he would say, Lott replied, ``You're in luck, Mr. President,
we're leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leader said he though negotiations were ``moving
along pretty well,'' with the administration. By Thursday night,
for example, the two sides had resolved some sticky issues. Among
them was agreement to provide $18 billion to prop up the
International Monetary Fund's lending coffers. But lawmakers were
still working out some differences over loan guidelines and other
reforms they want the IMF to initiate in return for the funding.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the negotiators also agreed to give Clinton
more than $1 billion for a program that provides heating fuel to
the poor, more than $1.2 billion for child care grants to the
states, and some $870 million for youth summer job programs.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the progress, there were still a number of problems.
The White House, for instance, was pushing for a provision in the
treasury and postal bill that require federal medical plans to
cover prescription contraceptives. The Republicans have stripped
the provision from the bill, but Clinton has threatened to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Obstacles to an agreement also included a Republican provision
in the foreign aid bill that would ban U.S. aid to groups abroad
that promote abortion. Republicans also were pushing legislation
that would prohibit using so-called sampling techniques to estimate
the nation's population in the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Other sticking points included GOP provisions that would
prohibit the development of national elementary education
proficiency tests and that would make it easier for U.S. growers to
hire Mexican workers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
