<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OKS IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY BUT DELAYS HEARINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For only the third time in history, the House of
Representatives on Thursday approved an impeachment inquiry against
a sitting U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   The 258-176 vote culminated a day of partisan floor debate on
what should be done about allegations that President Clinton
committed perjury and obstruction of justice in the White House sex
scandal and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about sexual misconduct any more than Watergate
was about a third-rate burglary,'' said House Judiciary Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., one of many lawmakers Thursday who
invoked the scandal that led to the House's last impeachment
inquiry vote 24 years ago. That episode forced the resignation of
President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lying under oath is important or it isn't,'' Hyde said. ``If
some people can lie under oath and some can't, let's find that out.
But if the same law applies to every body equally, that's the
American tradition... It's an onerous, miserable, rotten duty, but
we have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the resolution empowers the Judiciary Committee to
formally begin its investigation and to issue subpoenas, interview
witnesses and hold public hearings. After the vote, Hyde said the
committee would delay hearings until after the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton becomes the third president to be the target of an
impeachment inquiry. Andrew Johnson was impeached by the House but
the Senate failed by one vote to convict and remove him from office
in 1868. In 1974, the Judiciary Committee voted to impeach
President Richard M. Nixon but he resigned before the matter went
to the full House.
</P>
<P>
   During the floor debate Thursday, House Democratic Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., tried in vain to enlist GOP support for an
alternative Democratic proposal that would place a Dec. 31 deadline
on the inquiry and require the House to first define what is an
impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has ``let us all down,'' Gephardt said, but the
investigation of Clinton ``has hurt our nation and hurt our
children. We must not compound the hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   After Republicans voted down the Democratic alternative,
236-198, the House then passed the Republican resolution that has
no limits on time or subject matter. As a practical matter, it
expires with the end of the 105th Congress in January and would
have to be reauthorized when the 106th Congress is sworn into
session that month.
</P>
<P>
   Both votes reflected the tricky election-year politics
surrounding the impeachment debate. Only five House members voted
against both measures, in effect saying they wanted no inquiry
whatsoever. They were all Democrats: Rep. John Lewis of Georgia,
Rep. Cynthia McKinney of Georgia, Rep. Paul Kanjorski of
Pennsylvania, Rep. Bob Filner of California, and Rep. Jose Serrano
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   After the Democratic version went down, a total of 31 Democrats
voted for the Republican measure. Most were conservatives from
swing districts. Five of those voted against their own party's
measure, but in favor of the GOP resolution. They were: Rep. Gene
Taylor of Mississippi, Rep. Paul McHale of Pennsylvania, Rep.
Virgil Goode of Virginia, Rep. Lane Evans of Illinois and Rep.
William Lipinski of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most difficult decision I've had to make (but) I
feel good about what I did,'' said Rep. Chris John, D-La., a member
of the Blue Dog Coalition of fiscally conservative Democrats who
voted for the Democratic measure and, after it failed, then for the
Republican resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt this is truly the right thing to do for closure and to
set a standard so that if we go through this again in 20-30 years,
we know what `high crimes and misdemeanors' means.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the Constitution's criteria for impeachment,
along with treason and bribery.
</P>
<P>
   After the votes, Democrats played down the number of defections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was being asked (by reporters) if ... we could keep that
number below 50,'' said Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., author of the
Democratic alternative. ``The fact is that 31 Democrats supported
the (GOP) resolution, but 85 percent of Democrats in the House
supported our position.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton said after the vote he was
``fine,'' adding ``I have surrendered this. This is beyond my
control.'' Clinton expressed hope Congress could move forward with
an inquiry that is ``fair,'' ``timely,'' and ``constitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have been through a lot on this and I
think that everyone deserves that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, some Republicans said the evidence already
contained in the report on the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal
submitted by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr last month may be
strong enough to warrant the next step in the process: Approval of
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, if further examination showed grounds for impeachment
were substantiated by the evidence, my vote would be for articles
of impeachment,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., a conservative member
of the Judiciary Committee. ``But I wouldn't say anything is
inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, however, members expressed chagrin over
what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect more of a circus spectacle,'' said Rep. Zoe
Lofgren, D-Calif., a Judiciary Committee member who had argued that
Clinton's misconduct with Lewinsky did not rise to the level that
she said should be reserved for impeachment: high-level wrongdoing
that puts the constitutional system in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd expect the kind of outrageous behavior we've seen
already.''
</P>
<P>
   The floor debate was marked by strained parliamentary politeness
on both sides, interspersed with temperamental outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued that the Republican measure would allow
Congress to conduct a ``fishing expedition'' of unlimited duration
that could include not only the Lewinsky matter, but such other
elements of Starr's four-year probe of Clinton as the Whitewater
land deal, the firings in the travel office and the procurement by
Clinton operatives of FBI files of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a process, Mr. Speaker,'' said Rep. William
Delahunt, D-Mass., a Judiciary Committee member. ``That's a blank
check.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also played up public exhaustion with the Lewinsky
story, arguing that other pressing needs were being neglected.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., went through a laundry list of world
problems _ the crisis in Kosovo, Saddam Hussein in Iraq, the
faltering global economy, families that cannot pay medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're talking about Monica Lewinsky!'' He added: ``The
president betrayed his wife. He did not betray his country. God
help this nation if we fail to recognize the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, however, stressed a more limited goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not make any charges,'' Hyde said at the outset. ``We do
not make any charges. We simply being a search for truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said: ``Closing our eyes to
allegations of wrong-doing constitutes a breach of our
responsibilities as members of Congress. Let history judge us as
having done our duty to uphold the rule of law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
