<SLUG> BC-CIA-SPIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPYING OUT THE JOB MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ If you have ``superior intellectual ability,
toughness of mind and a high degree of personality,'' there's a job
waiting for you, particularly if you speak Farsi or other difficult
languages.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few drawbacks: You can't talk about your work
outside the office. In many cases, you can't even reveal where you
work. And, by the way, you might have to take the occasional
lie-detector test.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the new CIA recruiting drive, launched last month by
the spy agency, which has been suffring in the tight job market.
After enduring years of staff shrinkage from cuts and brain drain,
the CIA is scouring college campuses for well-educated officers and
even offering signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Large ads in The Economist and other publications promise ``the
ultimate international career,'' filled with ``fast-moving,
ambiguous, and unstructured situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clandestine Service Trainee Program, for example, needs
people who can place moles in foreign governments and exploit the
criminal underworld. As the ad phrases it, ``Operations Officers
spearhead our intelligence collection efforts and are actively
involved in seeking new sources of information.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's Directorate of Operations, which oversees
clandestine work, plans to increase the number of its officers by
30 percent in the next seven years, according to spokesman Mark
Mansfield. He won't say how many new hires this involves, because
the directorate's current roster is secret.
</P>
<P>
   They also need employees to monitor terrorism, weapons
proliferation, the drug trade, and states such as North Korea and
Iraq. ``Some people have the mistaken impression that the agency
had a loss of mission in the wake of the Cold War, but nothing
oculd be further from the truth,'' Mansfield said. ``The mission
has grown more complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to beef up the agency started under former director John
Deutch and have expanded under George Tenet, the current CIA
director. In a speech to agency employees in August, Tenet promised
a recruitment program ``that parallels the very best in private
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The CIA has long advertised for employees, but this campaign is
notable for its hard sell, due in part to the way the agency's
image has been tarnished by scandals over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The recruiting ad features the words integrity, intellect, and
common sense, written over a photo of a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is impressed. Photocopies of the ads have drawn
laughs among former CIA employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``PC-hood has struck home, even at the agency,'' concluded a
former CIA officer with the pseudonym Edward G. Shirley. ``The use
of a smiling 21-year-old black women as being a typical agency
recruit is new, and that's simply a reflection of the institution's
desire to appear `with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the agency will not say whether the woman is
black or white, and it is not clear from the ad. Nor would
Mansfield disclose the name of the agency that designed the ad. He
did say that the CIA is making a special effort to recruit women
and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   It is about time, said Richard Shultz, an &UR;  &LR; international
security expert at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at
Tufts University. Shultz was part of a group of academics and
retired intelligence officers who in the 1980s wrote a report
urging the CIA to improve its recruiting and diversify its
workforce.
</P>
<P>
   After obsessing for years about everything Soviet, the agency is
now more active in Asia, Africa, and the Mideast, ``where, to be
sort of blunt about it, white guys don't fit in,'' said Shultz &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield said the agency must compete vigorously with
investment banks and consulting companies that seek the same
employee profile: personable, multilingual, computer-literate,
willing to live abroad. The CIA is particularly interested in
engineers, biochemists, economists, and people fluent in Farsi,
Arabic, and the languages of the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mansfield, college recruiters, ads, and the
agency's Web site generate more than 100,000 inquiries and 30,000
resumes from job seekers every year. The agency has streamlined its
hiring so that background checks that used to take six months can
now be done in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of headhunters out there ready to pounce on
strong candidates,'' Tenet said in a speech in August. ``To delay
is to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency &UR;  &LR; has decided to focus on just 60 colleges that have
proven records with the CIA or substantial numbers of minorities &UR; . &LR; 
They include Harvard, MIT, and Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is also trying to overcome misperceptions that have
hampered it in the past. For example, someone who experimented with
drugs years ago is not automatically disqualified as an applicant
today. ``We look at how recent and frequent the drug use was,''
Mansfield said.
</P>
<P>
   The credibility of the agency has suffered from the cases of
Aldrich Ames and Harold Nicholson, both convicted double agents who
spied for Moscow, said Abram Shulsky, a former staff member of the
Senate Intelligence Committee and author of ``Silent Warfare,'' a
book about intelligence gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough has come out like the Ames case that has made the
agency look unattractive,'' Shulsky said. During the Cold War,
recruiting was easier because ``part of the attraction was that you
belonged to a really elite institution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the agency has lost its luster, it has had trouble recruiting
on the Ivy League campuses that used to provide a steady stream of
new officers, Shulsky said. ``In a sense, they're sort of forced
out to the more open job market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
