<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Friday, Oct. 9 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact
Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNDATION-BRISTOL-MYERS (Los Angeles) _ Update on the
controversial proposed deal between managed care specialist
Foundation Health Systems and Bristol-Myers Squibb. By Ben
Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ESPN-STORES (Los Angeles) _ Walt Disney Co. has new plans for
its ESPN brand. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PACAMERICA-MONEY (Los Angeles) _ The value of their stock may be
hovering in the dollar range, but stockholders in PacificAmerica
Money Center Inc. are still likely to get $6 a share when Fremont
General Corp. buys the company, PacificAmerica said Thursday. By
Enrique Rivero. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BURB-BURGLARS (Los Angeles) _ Thirteen youths from Saugus, an
middle-income L.A. suburb, have been arrested _ and seven more are
suspected _ in a burglary ring with victims from Los Angeles to San
Diego. The kids, accused of taking guns, liquor, jewelry and
electronics, say they did it to buy drugs. By Stacy Brown. (Will
move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LAX-BRADLEY (Los Angeles) _ Tom Bradley was eulogized this week
as Los Angeles' most beloved mayor, and now several Los Angeles
City Council members _ Richard Alarcon, Nate Holden and Mike
Hernandez _ propose renaming Los Angeles International Airport in
his name. However, the mayor's office, at least one airport
commissioner and other officials are saying LAX amounts to a
well-known brand name, and it would be confusing to change it. They
say there are other appropriate ways to honor Bradley's memory. By
Patrick McGreevy. (Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a''
national news file.)
</P>
