</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SLEEP-DEPRIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF SLEEP IMPAIRS SURGEONS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surgeons who go without sleep for 24 hours will have impaired
performance similar to a motorist who is driving drunk, said an
author of a study released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ara Darzi, a surgeon and professor at the Imperial College
School of Medicine at St. Mary's in London, said his study examined
the ``psycho-motor'' skills of surgeons after a full, disrupted or
sleepless night, and found their performance on simulated surgical
tasks declined with less sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surgeons awake all night made 20 percent more errors and took
14 percent longer to complete the tasks than those who had had a
full night's sleep,'' said the study published in The Lancet, a
British medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   While Darzi likened sleep-deprived surgeons to drivers with a
blood alcohol level of .10 percent, the legal driving limit in
England, he said in a phone interview that his research did not
actually include anyone with such blood alcohol levels.
</P>
<P>
   He said he made such a comparison because the diminished
performance of surgeons who go without sleep is ``not different
than if you have a blood alcohol level of .10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at six surgeons who, on average, were 30 years
old and had five years of training. They were asked to complete
various skills that simulated laparoscopic surgery, which is the
procedure involved, for example, in common gall bladder or appendix
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The participants' skill levels were tested on six nights and
then the following mornings after they had a full night's sleep,
three interuptions or no sleep at all.
</P>
<P>
   This British study comes six months after a report in the
Journal of the American Medical Association, in which medical
residents reported spending an average of 56.9 hours on call in the
hospital each week and 70 percent said they had seen a colleague
working while impaired, most often because of lack of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of that study, which involved more than 1,100
second-year residents, said the results highlighted the need to
improve working conditions for medical residents. Those who seek to
reform medical training point out that truck drivers and pilots are
not allowed to work on such little sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Darzi said it is impossible for him to say exactly if or how
patient care is affected by surgeons, who often take on 36-hour
shifts and grueling hours during their residency training.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
