u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-INDIANS-YANKEES-B     10-08 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELATEDLY, KOBLAUCH TAKES THE BLAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Brainlauch. Blauch Head. Chucklehead.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch made both the front page and the back page in
all the New York tabloids Thursday morning, and none of it was
complimentary. Even the august New York Times compared him to Bill
Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   Restraint? Well, nobody called him the Big Creep.
</P>
<P>
   But recognizing that no one was likely to cut him any slack,
either, the Yankees second baseman Thursday took what may have been
the most honorable course available to him, and certainly the one
that was most face-saving, in the shrill aftermath of violating
baseball's code of high crimes and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch stepped in front of his accusers at a press conference
Thursday afternoon and admitted, unequivocally, that after further
review, he was guilty as charged. While he still feels the umpires
erred, Knoblauch said he shouldn't have argued with them about
their failure to call interference on Travis Fryman of the Indians
in the 12th inning of Wednesday's game. Not when the ball was still
in play and Indians were flying around the bases. Not when it cost
the mightier-than-thou Yankees Game 2 of the American League
Championship Series to the Indians, whose general manager had
jokingly likened his team's chances in this series to the
Washington Generals' odds against the Globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I screwed up,'' said Knoblauch, who added he came to
that conclusion after watching televised replays of the bunt play
on which he and the umpires disagreed as to whether Fryman
interfered with first baseman Tino Martinez's throw to first by
running inside the 3-foot lane allotted to runners down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up the play, and I feel terrible about that. You
know, I should have went and got the ball, regardless of what the
outcome of the umpire's call was. I basically screwed up the play
and feel bad for that, and I need to apologize to my teammates and
my manager and the Yankees and all the Yankee fans. Bottom line, I
screwed up that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch might have spared himself some grief had he admitted
as much on the night in question instead of defiantly saying that
he'd probably do it the same way, given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But an apology still would have come too late for the Yankee
Stadium crowd of 57,128 that booed him when he came to bat in the
bottom of the 12th inning, after the Indians took advantage of his
failure to react and scored three runs, breaking a 1-1 tie and
taking this best-of-seven series back to Cleveland tied at a game
apiece with the next three in Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees outfielder Paul O'Neill took issue Thursday with the
crowd venting at Knoblauch, who came to New York last winter in a
trade with the Twins and is on the verge of signing a contract
extension that reportedly will pay him $9 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was embarrassed for New York,'' said the tightly wrapped
O'Neill, who is not known for blushing easily. ``To see someone
booed in the middle of the playoffs after we'd won four playoff
games in a row, that caught me by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yankee Stadium is a fun place to play, but Thursday I didn't
agree with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch said he understood the fans' reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were booing me for screwing up the play,'' he said, ``and
you can't fault them for that. They're going to react to what they
see, and you know, I screwed it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch said he decided after replaying the play ``over in my
head hundreds of times'' to meet the media Thursday, unprompted by
his agent, teammates, or the Yankees' public relations apparatus.
That impressed his manager, Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it was very hard with all that went on last night,
but it wasn't necessary for him to apologize,'' Torre said. ``We're
all in this thing. We don't get a chance to rehearse. We make
mistakes and have to live with them, have to work through them, and
I think that's what makes you tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you judge a good team _ when they can bounce back
from bad things that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was asked if he would be remembered for this play
above any other, much like Buckner is dogged by Mookie Wilson's
ground ball in the 1986 World Series that went through his legs,
allowing the Mets to win Game 6 and, ultimately, the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``if I never play another game, this will be
what I'll be remembered for. But hopefully, we can wipe that out
tomorrow. Hopefully, it will be a long career in New York, and
hopefully, a lot of good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go out there tomorrow and when I leave this room, there
won't be any added pressure on me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
