<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON09-COX     10-08 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SHRUGS OFF IMPEACHMENT TOPIC
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday's House vote to
begin impeachment proceedings against him left his fate up to
Congress, the American people and, ''ultimately, in the hands of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless one or another passes judgment, Clinton vowed to remain
engaged in an 11th-hour battle with Congress over budget
negotiations centered on farm aid, education, tax cuts and
emergency international assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone miss the point, Clinton used a top-level budget
strategy session as the background for responding to the historic
House impeachment action.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have surrendered this. This is beyond my control,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I can do, is to do my job for the American people,''
Clinton told reporters at a brief photo opportunity before the
White House meeting. ''And I'm working in a way that I hope will
restore their trust in me by working for the things that our
country needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government expects to spend about $1.7 trillion in
the coming year. That spending is directed by Congress through 13
separate appropriations bills.
</P>
<P>
   With the 105th Congress expected to adjourn this weekend,
however, more than 100 separate spending issues remained unresolved
between the White House and Congress, which had sent, as of late
Thursday, only four of the 13 bills to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has signed two, not yet acted on one and vetoed the
fourth _ the agriculture appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved by Congress contained $4.2 billion in aid but
cut, among other things, Clinton's request for spending that
Republicans considered non-emergency, including $120 million for
research and another $60 million for rural development.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both the structure of the money and the amount were inadequate
to deal with what has become the worst farm crisis for a decade,''
said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ''They need to do more
work on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's veto returns the bill to Congress either for an
attempt to override the veto _ considered unlikely _ or
negotiations leading to more aid.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas, White House officials said, negotiations between
administration officials and Republican leaders appeared close to
bearing fruit.
</P>
<P>
   On one major point, Clinton has asked Congress for $18 billion
in additional funding for the International Monetary Fund, charged
with helping to maintain stability in global currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   With one-fourth of the world in recession, and another quarter
rapidly moving that way, the IMF's pool of emergency bailout money
has been largely depleted. If the United States deposits another
$18 billion, other member nations will chip in roughly $82 billion
more, giving the IMF an additional $100 billion to manage economic
crises around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has approved Clinton's request, but the House
approved only $3.5 billion and has sought to make the additional
money contingent upon specific IMF reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he favors certain reforms, but opposes holding
up the additional funding over the issue of IMF governance.
</P>
<P>
   ''The IMF needs the money right now,'' said a White House
official. ''The crisis is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are also under way concerning a proposed tax cut in
the face of anticipated budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans have approved an $80 billion tax cut over five
years, but as many as 10 Senate Republicans have refused to go
along with it. While some say it's too small, others have
contended, as does Clinton, that any budget surpluses should be set
aside until Republicans and Democrats can agree on ways to shore up
the financially threatened Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Talks late Thursday were centered on a far smaller tax cut,
perhaps as low as $6 billion, that would extend a set of
business-oriented tax preferences such as credits for companies
that invest in research and development.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton portrayed himself as working hard and remaining
above the fray, his spokesman chastised the House vote for an
impeachment inquiry as partisan and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart stressed, however, that the impeachment process would
not distract Clinton from his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in the middle right now of the traditional crunch time
of business here in Washington,'' Lockhart said. ''We don't have
the luxury of being distracted ...We're going to be doing the
people's business, fighting for a budget, fighting for the
president's
</P>
<P>
   priorities in the appropriations process.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
