</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NEXT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT STEP   ON LONG ROAD IS UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that the House has voted for an impeachment
inquiry, what happens next?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: Nobody really knows.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-authored measure approved Thursday by the House
was so broad that the Judiciary Committee's inquiry could last for
years and could look at any action by President Clinton, including
matters unrelated to Clinton's relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most significant questions about the inquiry haven't
been resolved, such as whether Lewinsky or Clinton will be called
to testify. Nor is it clear whether the committee's investigative
hearings will be held in closed session, or whether the proceeding
will be conducted mostly in public.
</P>
<P>
   There will a hearing this month on a constitutional question,
but the real work will begin sometime after the Nov. 3 elections.
The inquiry will be controlled by Republicans, and there is not a
lot that Democrats can do to stop it, unless the elections result
in an unexpected Democratic takeover of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a long time, a year to go, unless Democrats
do real well at the polls and Republicans decide to compromise,''
said Representative Martin Meehan, the Lowell, Mass., Democrat who
sits on the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There are innumerable scenarios that could unfold. These range
from a quick, post-election inquiry on the Lewinsky matter and a
possible vote on articles of impeachment, to a lengthy
investigation into many areas, including the Whitewater real estate
deal, the firing of the White House travel office staff, the
improper use of FBI files, and campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   However the inquiry proceeds, it is far from clear whether the
House will ultimately vote to impeach the president, and even less
clear whether the Senate would come up with the two-thirds vote
required to convict and oust him.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the inquiry is expected to follow the outline
of the report presented to the House by independent counsel Kenneth
W. Starr, which focuses on allegations that Clinton lied about and
tried to cover up an affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike with Watergate, when a Senate committee uncovered much
information during dramatic hearings, most of the information in
the Clinton-Lewinsky case has been explored and written about at
length in the Starr report. Thus, the Judiciary Committee might
focus on reinterviewing key witnesses and deciding whether to draw
the same conclusions as Starr. That would require the committee
staff to interview Lewinsky and might lead to her public testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But such an appearance is fraught with peril for Republicans.
While many GOP members have said the impeachment proceedings are
``not about sex,'' one of the points made in the Starr report is
that Lewinsky and Clinton disagreed about whether the president
touched certain parts of her body.
</P>
<P>
   That is important because Clinton has maintained he was
``legally accurate'' when he swore that he did not have sexual
relations with Lewinsky. Clinton based his assertion on the
argument that the definition of sexual relations used in his
testimony in the Paula Jones sexual-harassment lawsuit did not
include oral sex performed on him.
</P>
<P>
   But the definition would have included the touching of
Lewinsky's breasts and other areas. Lewinsky said Clinton did touch
these parts of her body, while the president has denied it. Clinton
Thursday declined to say whether he would voluntarily appear before
the committee.
</P>
<P>
   So are Republicans going to try to determine whether Clinton
lied when he denied touching parts of Lewinsky's body? As Abbe
Lowell, the chief counsel for the Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee, said earlier this week, the case for impeachment is
based on ``who is telling the truth about who touched who, when and
where.''
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans don't call Lewinsky as a witness, Democrats may
try to have her testify because she has said no one told her to lie
about her relationship with Clinton. But Democrats cannot call
Lewinsky to testify without Republican permission.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also might try to get Starr to testify to ask about
alleged leaks from his office about grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   David Schippers, the Judiciary Committee's Republican counsel,
said this week that there are 15 possible impeachable offenses. The
committee could narrow or expand that list.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, meanwhile, has told the Judiciary Committee that he can't
rule out the possibility that he might find more impeachable
offenses and forward his findings to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Representative Dan Burton of Indiana, chairman of
the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee, has said he
will forward his findings about alleged campaign-finance abuses by
Democrats to the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee chairman, Henry J. Hyde of
Illinois, while pledging Thursday not to conduct a ``fishing
expedition,'' made it clear he might expand the inquiry. ``I cannot
say that we will never address other subjects, nor would it be
responsible to do so,'' Hyde said. ``If substantial and credible
evidence of other impeachable offenses comes to us, as the
independent counsel as suggested, the Constitution will demand that
we do our duty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
