<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-IMPEACH (Washington) _ The House votes 258-176 to
authorize a historic impeachment investigation into President
Clinton's role in the White House sex scandal and its aftermath. It
is the third time in U.S. history that the House has voted for an
impeachment inquiry. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TAUSCHER-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif.,
was one of 31 Democrats to vote for the Republican-sponsored
impeachment inquiry into President Clinton's role in the White
House sex scandal and its aftermath. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Freshmen Reps. Nick Lampson and Jim
Turner, both Texas Democrats, were among 31 Democrats who joined
House Republicans to vote for a GOP-sponsored impeachment inquiry
into President Clinton's role in the White House sex scandal and
its aftermath. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN (Washington) _ With an eye on the clock,
congressional and White House negotiators hope to strike a deal on
a spending package that would avert an election-year government
shutdown. But lawmakers were drafting a temporary spending measure
that would keep the federal agencies operating past midnight
Friday, when a stopgap funding bill expires. By GREG McDONALD.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-ADS (Washington) _ Gay rights groups protest a new
conservative TV ad campaign that says gays and lesbians can change
their sexual orientation through immersion in the Christian faith.
The gay groups say evidence of such change is only anecdotal and
that efforts to change can be psychologically harmful. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MORDUE (Washington) _ Norman Mordue, a state Supreme Court
justice from Onondaga County, N.Y., wins Senate Judiciary Committee
approval to become a federal judge for the northern district of New
York. His nomination now moves goes to the full Senate. By MARK
HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-NASA (Cape Canaveral) _ Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, takes
issue with those who have questioned NASA's decision to include the
former Mercury astronaut as a member of the next shuttle crew.
Glenn, 77, is one of seven astronauts in training at the Kennedy
Space Center for the shuttle mission scheduled at the end of this
month. By MARK CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NAPALM-TEXAS (Deer Park, Texas) _ Thousands of gallons of napalm
processed at a plant south of Houston are being used to burn
hazardous materials in Port Arthur. Two Texas lawmakers have sent
letters to the Navy expressing concern about the incineration of
the Vietnam-era napalm. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION-LAW (Mexico City) _ The new governor of the
central state of Zacatecas calls for the abolition of one of
Mexico's most sacred doctrines: that top officeholders, beginning
with the president, may not run for re-election. Proponents of the
change say the law hampers the democracy it was meant to foster. By
PHILIP TRUE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-AL (Cleveland) _ The Cleveland Indians have been to the
World Series two of the past three years and are the reigning
American League champions. They are appearing in their third AL
Championship Series in the past four years, yet they were given
little or no chance against the mighty New York Yankees. They
return home tied 1-1 against the Yankees. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-NL (Atlanta) _ The San Diego Padres will try to take a 2-0
lead over the Atlanta Braves in Game 2 of the National League
Championship Series. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
