<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMBER FEELING PERVADES IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate majority leader Trent Lott tried to downplay
Thursday's impeachment inquiry vote, calling it ``procedural,'' but
for other lawmakers it was emotional business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard the words `impeach William Jefferson Clinton,' it
was a sinking feeling that hit me hard in the gut,'' said
Representative Mary Bono, Republican of California.
</P>
<P>
   When Bono rose to deliver her speech, it was with a quaking
voice and a visibly nervous demeanor. Other Republicans were at
turns somber, defiant and even, jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Republicans made a pact that they wouldn't cheer or
clap when their party members spoke. But they did give House
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois a hero's
reception.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the aisle, party faithfuls awarded the
impassioned speeches of their leaders, Representatives Richard
Gephardt of Missouri and David Bonior of Michigan, standing
ovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the opportunity to stop this daily mudslide into the
nation's living room,'' Bonior said, to much applause.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mood off the floor, especially among Democrats, was
somber. Representative Marty Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat and
Judiciary Committee member, said Democrats had moved past their
anger toward Clinton and were now simply saddened by the turn of
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realize this is not just about Clinton anymore,'' he said
after speaking on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Still, frustration and anger spilled out because Democrats had
to accept a two-hour time limit on debate. Representative Bill
Hefner, Democrat of North Carolina, cut off after 20 seconds,
banged the lecturn with his fists and stomped away.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Eliot Engel, Democrat of New York, rose and said
only, ``I find it ironic that I only have 20 seconds when the
Republicans want an unlimited amount of time to conduct their
fishing expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the public clamored for an opportunity to witness the
making of history, standing in the pouring rain for hours in a line
so long it wrapped around one-quarter of the Capitol building.
Capitol police, who said they had never seen such a line, rotated
people into the usually-deserted galleries above the House chamber
in 15-minute intervals.
</P>
<P>
   Among the onlookers were some who were more than familiar with
the proceedings: former congressmen Tom Railesback, a Republican
who sat on the Judiciary Committee during the Nixon impeachment
proceedings, and Robert Garcia, a New York Democrat indicted during
the Wedtec scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the audience was one of President Theodore Roosevelt's
grandsons, Matt Drudge, an Internet muckracker collecting material
for his Drudge Report, and country and western crooner Charlie
Pride, swinging through on tour that began in Lubbock, Texas. Of
the proceedings, Pride, dressed in a black felt suit and a maroon
shirt, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about nonpartisan but it seems to me they're all mad
at each other. I think it's overplayed. And I don't understand all
this procedure ... If I was a good songwriter, I'd make something
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a Massachusetts Democrat,
pumped Pride's hand and explained the particulars of parliamentary
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   And if Pride didn't have a tune in mind to sum up the day,
Moakley did: ``We're all going to be singing `Who's Sorry Now.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
