<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      10-08 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EXTRAORDINARY NOW HAS BECOME ORDINARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  WASHINGTON _ The debate has sharpened, but Washington's
capacity for shock has dulled.
</P>
<P>
   And so the House's formal decision Thursday to undertake
impeachment hearings for only the third time in the nation's
history _ to begin, as House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J.
Hyde of Illinois put it, ``a search for the truth'' _ provided no
surprise, prompted no gasps of astonishment, set forth few ripples
in the country or the capital.
</P>
<P>
   In nine months, the extraordinary has become ordinary; the
historic, routine.
</P>
<P>
   Sex with an intern in the White House, the erosion of
centuries-old presumptions about the presidency and presidential
privilege, the release of grand-jury testimony that in any other
case would be sealed forever, the conclusion by an independent
counsel that a twice-elected president of the United States
``criminally obstructed the judicial process,'' the broadcast of
taped presidential testimony about genital contact _ any one of
them in any other year would be cause for consternation, even
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But in less than a year's time, each of them has become
front-page news, the salacious and the serious mixing in a toxic
brew that has contaminated public life, endangered venerable
institutions and alienated the governing class from the public it
is meant to serve.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Thursday's the debate in the House chamber offered
one of those rare moments, seldom occurring more than once a
decade, when the lawmakers' speeches were high-minded and
high-toned, delivered for the verdict of the voters and for
history. The tone was sober, the proceedings grave, the result
portentous.
</P>
<P>
   And as the lawmakers cast their votes, there was the
unmistakable recognition that a barrier was being breached, that
the 435 men and women who had grown accustomed to casting ballots
on appropriations bills and deregulation initiatives were suddenly
about to tread on different, forbidding ground. A president and the
presidency hung in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the similarities between Thursday and the last
time such a resolution was debated end.
</P>
<P>
   There was a partisan edge to what Democratic Representative
Charles E. Schumer of New York called ``a serious and solemn day''
on Capitol Hill, and that foreshadowed a bitter fight once the
House Judiciary Committee opens deliberations on actual
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Watergate days, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Peter
W. Rodino Jr., a New Jersey Democrat, labored long and carefully to
win the confidence of moderate Republicans, an achievement that
lent legitimacy to the assault on Nixon and eventually led to the
president's resignation. But there is no middle ground in the
Judiciary Committee, nor in the House.
</P>
<P>
   When the Republican rebels stormed the gates of the House in
1974, the casualties weren't the Democratic liberals the newcomers
assailed, but the Democratic moderates who were in closely balanced
congressional districts. The GOP revolution did more than replace
Democrats with Republicans. It removed the middle ground from the
House. The new House was at once more conservative and more liberal
than the old House.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 105th Congress is about to become known as the
Impeachment Congress, much as the 93rd Congress was. But the road
to impeachment is easier to tread today because it was traveled so
recently.
</P>
<P>
   For 106 years between the administrations of Andrew Johnson and
Richard M. Nixon, Congress battled with the White House, fighting
over spending priorities, struggling over wars, bickering over
treaties, sometimes even questioning the motives and morals of the
chief executive _ but never resorting to the ultimate step of
trying to impeach the president until the Watergate scandal
convulsed the country.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just a quarter-century after the last impeachment drama,
Congress is doing it again.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lawmakers who will determine the destiny of
President Clinton _ including Representatives John Conyers Jr. of
Michigan and Charles B. Rangel of New York, both Democrats, and
Senators Trent Lott, Republican of Mississippi, and Paul S.
Sarbanes, Democrat of Maryland _ played major roles in the
near-impeachment of Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Watergate crisis, the impeachment hearings, the
Nixon resignation and the ascension of President Ford are all
within the lifetime of every lawmaker on Capitol Hill. None of the
principals in Watergate _ Senators Howard H. Baker Jr. and Sam
Ervin, Representatives M. Caldwell Butler, Barbara C. Jordan,
Robert McClory, Tom Railsback and Rodino _ had any personal memory
of the impeachment of President Andrew Johnson. For all of them,
impeachment was an arcane procedure, inserted in the Constitution
to be used almost never.
</P>
<P>
   But the weapon, used in the past with trembling hands, has been
unsheathed twice within memory. Thursday the House picked it up
again. Like so much else after this year of upheaval, impeachment
is not a taboo anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
