<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY SEEK DEATH PENALTY FOR AFRICA BOMBING SUSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors said Thursday that the government
was seriously considering asking for the death penalty for two of
the suspects arrested after the bombings of the U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania in August.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion was made in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
during an arraignment that for the first time assembled three
defendants being held in New York. Federal authorities are
continuing an investigation into the bombings and the activities of
Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile suspected of masterminding the
attacks and other acts of terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty will seriously be considered in this case,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Patrick Fitzgerald told Judge Leonard Sand.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald was referring to Mohamed Rashed Daoud Al-'Owhali and
Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, each of whom was taken into custody in Kenya
in late August, and flown to New York to face charges. Each has
been charged with separate counts of murder in the deaths of more
than 220 people in the attacks. The charges carry the death penalty
if the government decides to seek it.
</P>
<P>
   The third defendant, Wadih el Hage, who has been described as
the former personal secretary to bin Laden, is charged in a
conspiracy to attack U.S. citizens abroad, a count that carries a
maximum sentence of life in prison. He was arrested in Arlington,
Texas, and transferred to New York.
</P>
<P>
   All three men entered pleas of not guilty Thursday before Sand.
Odeh, speaking through a translator, added, ``Not guilty at all.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Neither the defendants' lawyers nor the prosecutors would
comment after the brief hearing. Each defendant smiled and spoke
softly with his lawyer before the hearing, and none of the three
displayed any noticeable reaction to Fitgerald's announcement that
capital punishment was under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The issue first arose when Sand asked about procedures to insure
that capital defendants are assured of having lawyers with
experience in death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   Before the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, Mary Jo White, can decide
to seek the death penalty, she must receive authorization from
Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The three men in court Thursday were arraigned on charges issued
in a new indictment returned Wednesday. A fourth defendant, Haroun
Fazil, who is suspected of leading the attack on the embassy in
Nairobi, was also charged in the indictment this week. He remains a
fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not address his case in court Thursday, but the
charge against him also carries the death penalty if he is captured
and the Justice Department seeks it.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's hearing, Sand also asked that prosecutors
investigate whether el Hage can receive greater access to a
telephone. His lawyer, Bruce McIntyre, has complained that his
client has been told that he could make only one phone call every
30 days to his family in Texas. Fitzpatrick said he was making
contact with prison officials and was confident that an arrangement
would be worked out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
