<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.AMERICA-POLLUTION-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH AMERICA POLLUTION FALLS DESPITE RISE IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ One of the first detailed studies of environmental
pollution across North America shows a slight decrease in the
amount of hazardous substances being released into the air, water
and soil, but the improving record of U.S. industry was largely
offset by hefty increases in pollution by Canadian companies.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Wednesday in Montreal, does not include
conditions in Mexico because usable information still is not widely
collected, nearly five years after implementation of the North
American Free Trade Agreement required such environmental
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The continental study was conducted by the Commission for
Environmental Cooperation, which includes representatives from the
United States, Canada and Mexico. It estimates that in 1995 about
20,000 manufacturing plants reported that they had produced more
than 2.8 billion pounds of hazardous substances, including known
carcinogens, that were released directly into the air or water, or
were transferred to landfills.
</P>
<P>
   That amount represents a decline of 1.5 percent across North
America, and is considered an important step toward slowing the
spread of dangerous substances across international boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   But when broken down by country, the figures give a slightly
different picture of North America. Pollution produced by
industries in the United States declined 2.1 percent in 1995 from
1994, while in Canada the amount of pollution released or
transferred increased 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Methanol, ammonia, zinc, nitric acid and toluene made up almost
half of the pollutants released in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The report also indicates that while the United States has far
more industrial sites, Canadian plants, on average, emit almost
twice as much pollution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lisa Nichols, a program manager for technical cooperation at the
environmental commission, said it was not clear why Canadian plants
produced higher average pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report is not expected to cause much controversy in
the United States, it is likely to raise environmental concerns in
Canada about the weakness of the system of provincial environmental
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially there has been an assumption that the Canadian
performance is as strong as the U.S., but part of what makes this
report so significant is the extent to which it shatters that
national myth,'' said David Winfield, research director at the
Canadian Institute for Environmental Law and Policy, a nonprofit
organization in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   When the commission released similar results in its first report
last year, local governments and industries in Canada said it was
unfair to compare general statistics on pollution among unrelated
industries in different states or provinces.
</P>
<P>
   This year's report is also expected to focus attention on the
lack of progress Mexico has made toward meeting the requirements of
the environmental side agreement that President Clinton tacked onto
the NAFTA legislation in 1993 to get it approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said they had started collecting information
on industrial pollutants last year but still had a long way to go
before they compiled a list comparable to those monitored in the
other two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Morales, an official with the National Institute of
Technology in Mexico, said some Mexican industries had objected to
the inclusion of certain hazardous substances on the list of about
200 pollutants that will be tracked. Since NAFTA took effect in
1994, the Mexican government has feared that environmental
regulations could be used in a way that harms domestic industries.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Emerson, senior economist for the Environmental Defense
Fund, said he was disturbed by the lack of progress in Mexico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
