<SLUG> BC-MARKET-DROP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK PRICES GYRATE, DOLLAR TUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Includes budgeted JAPAN-YEN)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors fled to the ultimate safety of short-term US Treasury
bills Thursday as US stock prices gyrated, the dollar tumbled
again, and talk of a worse-than-expected slowdown in the US economy
shook financial markets worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term Treasury bills had their biggest gain in more than
six years. But prices on the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, a
haven in past weeks for anxious investors, fell sharply. Traders
said shorter-term securities stand to gain the most if the Federal
Reserve, as many expect, cuts interest again next month rates to
counter a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, after plunging as much as 277
points, recovered to close at 7731.91, down 9.78 points, or less
than 1 percent. The Nasdaq Composite index, a barometer of the
risky high-tech industry, pared a 105-point loss, ending down 43.49
points, or 2.97 percent, for the day.
</P>
<P>
   World stock markets were also down, from a 2.69 percent fall in
London's FT-SE 100-stock index to a 4.98 percent plunge in
Frankfurt's DAX index. The Nikkei 225 index in Tokyo plunged 5.78
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and investment professionals said it was not yet
clear whether the market turmoil was a result of rising pessimism
about the US economy or a more technical financial event that would
burn itself out.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that investors who for years had borrowed money
in Japan at extremely low interest rates in order to invest in
higher-paying dollar-denominated securities or hot European stocks
have begun unwinding those positions. The reversal by so many
institutions of a popular arbitrage strategy put downward pressure
on the dollar and other US markets, said Jonathan Francis, head of
global strategy for Putnam Investments in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've been seeing in the last several weeks, in the
equity, the fixed income, and the foreign exchange markets is those
last big entrenched investors are getting blown out of that
trade,'' Francis said. ``There may be several more weeks of
volatility yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Other economists believe that something more fundamental may be
unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the plunge in the dollar is principally related to the
expectation that the US economy is going to cave in, not
necessarily into a recession but cave in on growth in coming
months,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist for Primark Economic
Decisions in Boston. ``This factor is, for any country's currency,
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   The activity Thursday in financial markets followed a day in
which the US dollar fell sharply against the yen. On Wednesday, the
US dollar plunged 8.8 percent against the Japanese yen _ its
biggest decline in 25 years _ as hedge fund investors retreated
from their bets on US rates.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily leveraged hedge funds sold US-dollar positions,
analysts said, as banks refused to extend loans to fund their risky
strategies a day after the Fed's chairman, Alan Greenspan, hinted
at further interest-rate cuts. To spur the economy, the Fed last
week trimmed the key overnight lending rate by a quarter of a
point, to 5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar tumbled another 2 percent Thursday. During late-day
trading, the dollar stood at 118.85 yen, up from 121.33 yen
Thursday, though it had hit a low of 111.6 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The US government's bellwether 30-year bond fell 2 points, or
$20 per $1,000 bond, driving the yield up 13 basis points to 4.99
percent. The decline in bonds brings three-day losses to 4 14/32
points, or $44.38 per $1,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Thompson, who heads global fixed-income investing for
State Street Global Advisors in Boston, said the bond rout was due
to sales by Japanese and other investors who are ``sell when they
see the US dollar weaken.''
</P>
<P>
   The safest place for investors was in three-month bills, which
staged the biggest rally since July 1, 1992. Yields were driven
down 24 basis points to 3.87 percent on a bond-equivalent basis.
Yields on two-year notes _ the most actively traded Treasuries _
fell 6 basis points to 4.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Respected Wall Street forecaster Abby Joseph Cohen, of Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co., weighed in with pessimists by lowering her estimate
for operating profits for the companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index. The change, she wrote in a note to clients, reflect
``more subdued expectations for global growth in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen does not expect a recession, but sentiment is becoming
increasingly bearish.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. two days ago became the first prominent
institution to forecast recession in the United States in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And Ralph Acampora, a one-time bull and analyst for Prudential
Securities, predicted that the Dow could sink as low as 6500,
compared with a bottom of 7400 he predicted earlier. Acampora, a
longtime bull, turned tail on August 4 by predicting a bear market
for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   At its low Thursday, the Dow was down 20 percent percent from
its July high.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Marston, a professor of international finance at the
Wharton School, said that he believes the unwinding of complex
institutional positions is part of a move ``back to basics.''
However, he said the danger in declining equity markets is that
they may slam consumer spending, the economy's biggest engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look forward into 1999 can we count on consumer
confidence staying up there when we have a market that has gone
down so sharply and we have such an uncertain political
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In their darkest moment, investors have begun to fear that ``the
threat to the world isn't inflation _ it's deflation. That is a big
threat,'' said State Street's Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to perpare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
