<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSE-RACING-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINES HAVE SKIP AWAY, AND MILLIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random thoughts from the press box:
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn and Sonny Hine have cashed two of the biggest gambles in
racing history. Not only did they spend $800,000 to supplement Skip
Away into his winning 1997 Breeders' Cup Classic, but they also
turned down numerous offers to sell him as a young horse. Given the
opportunity to become instant millionaires, they chose to keep Skip
Away because, as Sonny put it, ``What would we do with the money?
Buy more horses.'' Now they're millionaires a dozen times over, and
they still own their horse.
</P>
<P>
   Handicappers at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie might as well be
whistling in the wind if they gamble serious money based on
quarter-horse performances in which running times are drastically
affected by ``tailwinds'' and ``headwinds.'' Would that be a gentle
evening breeze, or a gale like we saw on opening night? Lone Star
needs a device to measure wind velocity, like other quarter-horse
tracks have.
</P>
<P>
   The still-unidentified buyer of leading 2-year-old Worldly
Manner is going to great lengths to avoid publicity. But there are
clues. The buyer is alive, which rules out Elvis, and we know that
the purchase price was in the neighborhood of $5 million, which
eliminates everyone who has recently invested in a hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas left the quarter-horse game for thoroughbred
racing in the early 1980s, and has since trained winners of almost
every major race in the country. So why did he show up at Lone Star
last night with a pair of quarter horses? He has never won the
All-American Futurity, and he says that is one of his remaining
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Racing is suffering from an epidemic of illegal use of
performance-enhancing drugs, and three trainers in Florida faced
suspensions because their horses tested positive for ... bee
pollen. Or rather, for the 50 parts per million of caffeine that
the bee pollen contained. They got off the hook, but go figure.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Wall Street Journal market analyst picked Churchill
Downs as his No. 1 stock pick. Not a bad idea. Word on the street
all year has been that Churchill Downs, which also owns Indiana's
Hoosier Park and Kentucky's Ellis Park, is interested in acquiring
a major winter track. At first it was rumored to be Gulfstream
Park, but now the favored target is said to be Fair Grounds in New
Orleans. Fair Grounds chief Bryan Krantz said he has not been
contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Cavonnier hasn't run since hurting a tendon in the 1996 Belmont
Stakes, but he's coming back this month. Da Hoss hasn't raced since
he won the 1996 Breeders' Cup Mile, and he runs tonight. Why not
bring Cigar back? He's sound, except for where it counts most at
stud.
</P>
<P>
   Blueprint for a slow horse: Listen Lady raced four times and was
beaten a total of 78 1/2 lengths, yet some pedigree wizard decided
to make her a broodmare to pass her genes to future generations.
Her most famous foal is Zippy Chippy, now forcibly retired by
Finger Lakes stewards after he decided to crown an 0-for-85 career
by refusing to leave the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughbred jockeys and trainers are mostly a breath of fresh
air compared with the participants of other professional sports.
But quarter-horse people are nicer still, even though they lose so
many photo finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Daily purses at Fair Grounds were more than $200,000 two years
ago, topped $230,000 last year and are projected at about
$240,000-$250,000 for the 1998-99 season. If Lone Star can show
that kind of upward mobility, plus an improved racing surface,
they'll be going places.
</P>
<P>
   There are quarter horses whose names don't include the words
``Dash,'' ``Cash,'' ``Victory'' and ``Easy,'' but there aren't many
in this country, and they don't seem to run as fast.
</P>
<P>
   Sportsman's Park outside Chicago is remodeling its facility to
offer car racing, and plans to run horses on a dirt strip placed
over the asphalt. Horse owners and trainers are concerned, but they
shouldn't be the track's biggest problem. Horsemen love to complain
about racing surfaces, but they are amateurs in the crybaby
department compared with the NASCAR boys.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar and now Skip Away. Both ridden by Jerry Bailey. Good
horses make good jockeys, but is that a coincidence? Probably not.
Hoofbeats Skip Away's big day Skip Away goes for history tomorrow
in the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup. If he can defeat Gentlemen
again _ and he will be heavily favored _ he will become the first
North American racehorse to exceed $10 million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar has the record at $9,999,815. Skip Away has $9,506,360,
and a victory will put him at a little more than $10.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Six horses were entered in the mile-and-a-quarter race, which
will be televised live on KXAS/Channel 5 from 4-5 p.m. as the
centerpiece of the Breeders' Cup Preview. Other Belmont Park races
to be shown on the telecast are the Champagne Stakes for
2-year-olds and the Turf Classic Invitational for older grass
runners.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away has won the Gold Cup the past two years. Only the
great gelding Kelso won it more than twice _ he did it five times
(1960-64), and by today's purse standards, that would have been $3
million right there.
A shot at $5 million Churchill Downs and Breeders' Cup Ltd. have
received approval from the Kentucky Racing Commission to jointly
offer a $5 million guaranteed pick-six pool on Breeders' Cup day.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 7 wager, to be called the Ultra Pick Six, will include
the last six of the seven Breeders' Cup races, excluding the
Juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   On four occasions this summer, tracks in Southern California
have offered guaranteed pick-six pools ranging from $1 million to
$3 million. But nationwide betting always exceeded the guaranteed
amount, so the tracks or their insurance companies never had to put
up money. The Breeders' Cup wager should be no different; with no
guarantee, the pick-six handled $3.3 million last year, and that
figure should at least double.
No phone betting allowed Texas residents who had phone betting
accounts in Pennsylvania, New York and Connecticut have been cut
off at the request of the state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys general of six other states _ Utah, Hawaii, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Mississippi and Georgia _ made similar
requests, but no horseplayers live in their states anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star Park president Bob Kaminski confirmed that the Grand
Prairie track sought to pull the plug on area residents betting on
races through phone accounts. He pointed out that Lone Star
receives no revenue from phone bets on out-of-state tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Phone betting is legal in eight states, but most tracks in other
jurisdictions haven't seemed concerned about the competition. You
Bet, a company offering wagering plus live race video and audio on
its computer site, says it is accepting business from horseplayers
in 40 states.
Big racing weekend With the Nov. 7 Breeders' Cup races at Churchill
Downs approaching, this is a huge weekend for prep races.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away, of course, is prepping for the Classic, which he will
try to win for the second consecutive year. Other top Classic
contenders in action are Awesome Again, favored in tomorrow's
Hawthorne Gold Cup; and Touch Gold, who runs Sunday in the Fayette
Handicap at Keeneland, perhaps against Super Derby winner Arch.
</P>
<P>
   Among other big races and favorites at Belmont tomorrow are the
Champagne, for 2-year-olds (Lemon Drop Kid, Tactical Cat); the
Frizette, for 2-year-old fillies (Things Change, Oh What a
Windfall); and the Beldame, for fillies and mares (Sharp Cat). Also
tomorrow is Santa Anita's Oak Leaf for 2-year-old fillies
(Excellent Meeting).
</P>
<P>
   Other races Sunday include Keeneland's Alcibiades, for
2-year-old fillies (Silverbulletday); Belmont's Turf Classic
Invitational (Buck's Boy, Dushyantor, Cetewayo); Santa Anita's
Norfolk, for 2-year-olds (Darling General); and also at Santa
Anita, the Lady's Secret Breeders' Cup Handicap, for fillies and
mares (Magical Allure).
Buzz With the announcement of the $5 million Breeders' Cup
pick-six, Santa Anita's $2 million guaranteed pool tomorrow has
gotten lost in the shuffle. It will cover races five through 10.
... The 6-year-old Gentlemen will try Skip Away again in the Jockey
Club Gold Cup for what might be the final race of his career. He
will be running with blinkers for the first time. Gentlemen outran
Skip Away in 1997, but not this year. ``When he was at his best, I
wouldn't have traded him for any other horse,'' trainer Dick
Mandella said. ``I haven't had that this year, so now I'm grasping
at straws trying to find that one thing that will get him over the
hump. Putting blinkers on was something \Rjockey\S Corey
\RNakatani\S mentioned, and I figured, `Why not?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop is almost ready to resume training after minor
throat surgery Sept. 27, and could make the Breeders' Cup Classic,
trainer Elliott Walden says. ... Da Hoss makes his comeback tonight
in the Cliff Hanger at The Meadowlands. Victory Gallop and Da Hoss
are owned by the Preston brothers from Houston. ... Lone Star
2-year-old filly champ Arrested Dreams was being pointed to the
Frizette, but will miss the race because of sickness. ... Hurricane
Georges peeled off an 80-foot strip of roof from the Fair Grounds'
new grandstand, but the rest of the New Orleans track was unharmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
