<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUILLEN'S ZEST FOR LIFE SHINES THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Changing leagues after 13 years in one place would be
hard for anybody, but it was even harder for Ozzie Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Guillen is a social animal. He talks to his
teammates. He talks to the opposing players. He talks to the
opposing manager. He talks to the opposing coaches. He talks to the
umpires. He even likes to talk to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard,'' says the man who has always been one of the
league leaders in sock exposure. ``I was in Chicago for 13 years. I
spent more time there than I did in Caracas. I knew everybody. I
definitely missed the American League at first.''
</P>
<P>
   What he most definitely does not miss is sitting in front of a
television set watching everyone else play in October. In those 13
years as a member of the Chicago White Sox, he participated in six
postseason games. He is now a member of the Atlanta Braves, who
have become a death-and-taxes type of postseason inevitability in
the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie is 34 and he has no illusions about being a regular. His
job here is to back up starter Walt Weiss, pinch hit (he slapped
Dan Miceli's first pitch for a pinch single in the eighth inning of
Game 1 in the NL Championship Series Wednesday), and just be Ozzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got another job here,'' he explains. ``I'm in charge of
the dugout and the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Care to elaborate, Oz?
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys on the bench are going to get the same money and the
same ring as the regulars if we win, so we should do everything we
can to earn it,'' he maintains. ``If a guy comes in after making a
good defensive play, he should hear about it. There is nothing
worse than being on a team with a dead bench. I don't let that
happen around here.''
</P>
<P>
   His season began with the Orioles, but suffice it to say that
didn't work out. He went 1 for 16 in 12 games before deciding he
couldn't stand it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in and asked for my release,'' he explains. ``I said,
`Mr. (Kevin) Malone (the assistnat general manager), `I'm not doing
anything for this ball club. You need another pitcher or a catcher
more than you need a backup infielder. I would be very easy to get
rid of.'''
</P>
<P>
   And that was it. He was prepared to go back home.
</P>
<P>
   Many miles to the north of Caracas, a mini-crisis was brewing.
The Braves had a couple of hurting shortstops, Weiss and Rafael
Belliard. Bobby Cox sent out an SOS via his general manager, John
Schuerholz. Ozzie Guillen, a superfluous item on a floundering
Baltimore team, was suddenly a desirable commodity on one of
baseball's elite clubs. If anyone doesn't believe that success in
this business is so often defined as being in the right place at
the right time, here is Exhibit A in defense of the premise.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie would have taken anything he got just to be on this
particular ball club. He wound up getting 264 at-bats and he made
good use of them, hitting a respectable .277 while doing his usual
solid job in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ozzie Guillen saved our rear ends,'' says Cox.
</P>
<P>
   He needed a while to get acclimated, and it really didn't have
anything to do with changing leagues. ``For me, the first 10 or 20
at-bats were like spring training,'' he says. ``After a couple of
weeks, I felt more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   He was never a star but he was good enough to hold down a
regular job for more than a decade, which is a pretty good
distinction. He peaked as a hitter at .288 in 1994, when he flirted
with the league lead in batting for much of the first half of the
year despite hitting ninth. He was a very good fielder, a
base-stealing threat in his prime, and a very solid professional.
</P>
<P>
   He was, as they say, a tough out, and he very nearly caused mass
coronaries in Boston eight years ago. For it was Guillen who hit
the line drive down the right-field line on which Tom Brunansky
made the diving catch into the foul pole with two outs in the ninth
to save the 1990 AL East title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard a crowd go from so loud to so quiet to so loud _
all in the space of two seconds,'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Guillen has been a VGG _ Very Good Guy. He has a
zest for life and a true passion for the game. A lot of people are
happy that he has this last opportunity to savor spotlight games
and situations with a team like the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this game,'' he says. ``If you come from where I come
from, you would treasure every day you can put the uniform on. I
hate it when guys treat the whole thing like a business. You've got
to enjoy the game. And you've got to respect the game. And you've
got to understand the game. There are going to be a lot of 0 for
4s, no matter how good you are.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise to him that the Braves play in October every
year. ``They are professional,'' he says. ``If you need a strike,
they throw a strike. If you need an out, they get an out. They know
how to play the game here. The focus is on winning, nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year? Who knows? This whole experience is a bonus, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of happy guys here,'' Guillen says, ``but I
don't know of anyone happier than me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
