<HEADLINE>
WAC SPLIT NOT PRIORITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having returned triumphantly from their almost-secret mission to
the Central Pacific, the SMU Mustangs are now off to the land of
frozen sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the local dialect has it, Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   It is also roughly the midpoint of the 16-team Western Athletic
Conference's last year, possibly an apt moment to get Mike Cavan's
views on one of the weightier issues of our time.
</P>
<P>
   And so, someone asked the SMU coach for a few words on how the
Mustangs' chests would swell with pride at the opportunity to hold
aloft the banner of the True WAC in the lair of those unprincipled
secessionists in Laramie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they're part of the group that's leaving?'' he said, in
the manner of one responding to a luncheon guest's breathless
revelation that his granddad once met your great aunt Hilda.
``Well, all that stuff has been a little hard to follow. To be
honest, I don't really know which group is leaving and which one is
staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I haven't been here long enough to figure out who the 16
teams in the league are, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is, we just got a win \R28-0 against Hawaii\S, and
we need another one. And we're going up there to play a team whose
only loss was by seven points to Georgia _ in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have to fly into Cheyenne and then ride a bus for about
two hours to get to Laramie. And on Monday, they said it snowed up
there and it was minus-7 \Rdegrees\S or something like that, and
the roads were bad, and The Gap was closed _ whatever that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, to tell you the truth, I haven't really given much thought
this week to the WAC splitting up.''
</P>
<P>
   A common refrain, it seems, among the schools of what we might
call the WAC East. TCU (3-1, 1-0) is standing upright and looking
pretty good. Everyone else is feeling a bit woozy.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa, for example, received an odd memento from the Big WAC's
last year _ a second consecutive road game at Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever positive tidbits that might have crossed the Golden
Hurricane's path this year, luck isn't one of them. In the past two
games, Dave Rader's offense has produced 775 yards and nine
turnovers, and Tulsa has lost both. Now comes the news that,
because of scheduling considerations, there will be another road
trip into the nest of the WAC's best team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Rader said, ``at least it can't be any worse than last
year,'' which is a bit like Noah saying, ``Gee, I bet it never
rains like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dropping into Fort Collins last year, the Hurricane was met by a
blizzard. After an 18-inch snowfall, the game was delayed until
Sunday. When it finally was played, Tulsa committed turnovers on
its first six possessions and lost, 44-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one of our favorite memories,'' said Rader, whose team is
2-2 (0-1 in the WAC) after a promising start.
</P>
<P>
   Rice will journey to the West Coast for its first engagement
with San Jose State, which will be, along with the Owls, part of
the remaining WAC next year.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the two teams have given snaps to six different
quarterbacks and lost six times, but both are 1-0 in league play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had an off-week, which was probably a good thing,''
Rice coach Ken Hatfield said. ``We've had three tough losses in a
row \Rincluding a 59-21 rout by Texas\S, and we're just trying to
get some people well. We've got two new quarterbacks and we've just
tried to give them as many reps as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just kind of looking at this as the start of a second
season, and we still have a win in the WAC.''
</P>
<P>
   The Owls lost quarterback Jeremy Bates (knee) in the second game
of the year, and are hoping junior Chad Richardson can run the
spread option well enough to make them a contender. The backup is
Corey Evans, a true freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the new air of uncertainty, halfback Michael Perry,
the WAC's leading rusher last year, is recovering from an ankle
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the Spartans, 52-14 losers at Virginia
last week, have problems stopping the run. Just what every spread
option team loves to hear.
Quick Hits World of hurt at CSU While Tulsa may seem in dire
straits this week, there is a flip side to the coin: Few premier
teams have ever been as decimated by key injuries as Colorado
State.
</P>
<P>
   When the season began, the Rams were the pick of the league and
the WAC's only ranked team. With 15 starters returning from an 11-2
squad _ including two 1,000-yard backs _ Sonny Lubick's crew seemed
almost invincible.
</P>
<P>
   The only missing ingredient _ a quarterback _ was discovered in
the opener on national TV, when senior Ryan Eslinger directed an
impressive win against Michigan State in East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Rams (4-2, 2-1) have looked like a MASH unit.
Both running backs are hobbled, and one _ Kevin McDougal _ might be
on the threshold of missing most or all of the rest of the season.
One of college football's toughest players, he has played every
week with a shoulder injury. Last week, on the final carry of a
155-yard day, he suffered a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be out for a while _ a long while,'' Lubick said.
``He's a tough kid, with an incredible pain tolerance. We've just
gone through every week not touching him in practice, and then he
just plays his normal game and blocks out the pain. But it's
looking like he'll be out for a while now.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon Washington, the other starting running back, has a
sprained ankle. Linebacker Nate Kvamme, an All-America candidate,
has a bad knee. Two weeks ago, Eslinger ran out of bounds and was
flattened by a Nevada-Las Vegas tackler, departing with a
concussion, although he returned last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's been a little rough,'' Lubick said, ``but I guess
this happens to everybody.'' The Buzz Although Air Force (4-1) is
3-1 in WAC play, the /real'' prize is the Commander-In-Chief's
trophy, and the first round of that service academy quest will be
played this weekend against Navy. As it happens, the Falcons lead
the nation in rushing (302.8) by a hair over the Middies (302.3),
both running the spread option. ``So,'' said Air Force coach Fisher
DeBerry, ``it'll probably end up with each of us throwing 25
times.''... At the beginning of the season, UTEP's Charlie Bailey
said he believed his team was a lot better than recent editions of
the Miners. It is _ but it's still 0-4. UTEP lost big to Texas
Tech, but has since played three heartbreakers, losing late to
Oregon, New Mexico State and Colorado State. ``We need a break,''
Bailey said. ... Assessing his team's 31-21 loss to Fresno State,
BYU coach LaVell Edwards had no problem pinpointing the cause: ``We
had a jillion turnovers,'' he said. This week, the Cougars play
UNLV (0-5), which has lost its games by an average score of 42-12.
``Well, I guess this is the best time to be playing them,'' Rebels
coach Jeff Horton said. ``If you really believe that.'' ...
Although SMU might dread the upcoming weekend, Wyoming's Dana Dimel
isn't counting on a tap-dance win. ``They have two quarterbacks
/RChris Sanders and Josh McCown/S they seem comfortable with, and
two outstanding tailbacks /RRodnick Phillips, Kelsey Adams/S,''
Dimel said. ``I don't see any difference between this team and the
one they had last year _ except that to some extent, they have been
a victim of the schedule. To me, they look to be as good as anyone
on our schedule.''
</P>
</TEXT>
