<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH09-COX     10-08 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House launches impeachment investigation
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For only the second time this century, the House of
Representatives launched a wide-ranging impeachment investigation
Thursday against a popularly elected president.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 258 to 176, the Republican-led House made President
Clinton the first chief executive to be threatened with removal
from office since Richard Nixon faced impeachment proceedings in
the Watergate scandal in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report about Clinton's
conduct in his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky and his
effort to conceal it is the jumping off point for the inquiry. But
the House put no limits on topics the House Judiciary Committee may
examine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States is the trustee of the
nation's conscience,'' Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), the committee
chairman, said. ``We are entitled to explore ... the circumstances
that have been alleged to compromise that position.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Rep. Robert Wexler (D-Fla.), one of
Clinton's staunchest allies, countered, ``The president betrayed
his wife. He did not betray the nation. God help this country if we
fail to recognize the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   After four hours of debate and votes that mainly lacked the high
drama the occasion would suggest, the House directed the committee
``to investigate fully and completely whether sufficient grounds
exist for the House of Representatives to exercise its
constitutional power to impeach William Jefferson Clinton,
President of the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a brief statement to reporters after the vote: ``I
hope that we can now move forward with this process in a way that
is fair, that is constitutional and that is timely. ... It is not
in my hands. It is in the hands of Congress and the people of this
country _ ultimately in the hands of God. There is nothing I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally I am fine,'' Clinton added. ``I have surrendered
this. This is beyond my control. I have to work on what I can do. I
trust the American people. They almost always get it right. They
have for 220 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, just 31 Democrats voted for the Republican-drafted
resolution. A procedural vote that was, in effect, a show of
support for a Democratic alternative that called for a more limited
investigation, failed 198-236.
</P>
<P>
   In a Congress notable for the fractiousness of its Republican
majority, GOP lawmakers voted unanimously for the broad impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Georgians John Lewis and Cynthia McKinney were among just five
Democrats who voted against both measures, opposing any further
investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who labored
all week to minimize Democratic defections, expressed the anger and
resignation many Democrats feel about the situation that has pushed
substantive legislation to the periphery of the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question today is not whether to have an inquiry,''
Gephardt said. ``The question today is what kind of inquiry this
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats worried that Republicans would drag out the
investigation for electoral purposes and, using well-worn campaign
rhetoric, accused the majority of putting aside legislation on
education, health care and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also voiced fears that Republicans would expand
the inquiry to include the Clintons' failed Whitewater land deal,
the firing of the White House travel office staff, the transfer of
900 FBI files to White House personnel -- matters that Starr has
had under investigation for more than four years -- as well as the
export of sensitive missile technology to China and illegal foreign
campaign contributions in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   When Gephardt, in his speech on the House floor, listed these
subjects as potentially part of the investigation, many Republicans
murmured, ``That's right,'' then broke into applause.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats who voted for the broader inquiry said they
have concerns about the GOP's political aims. ``But I take Henry
Hyde at his word,'' said Rep. Charles Stenholm (D-Texas), one of
the 31 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for the most part, hewed to their argument that the
Constitution establishes an impeachment process. The House is
merely following that process, which was triggered by Starr's
report.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans seized on Gephardt's comments and the paucity of
Democrats who favor dropping the matter completely to put a
bi-partisan spin on the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde expressed hope that Thursday's vote would provide the
foundation for heightened cooperation in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a better chance for non-partisanship to rear its
lovely head now that this is behind us,'' he said at a news
conference following the vote.
</P>
<P>
   As he has pledged for the past week, Hyde said he would try to
wrap up this stage of the investigation by the end of the year, a
date the Democrats tried and failed to include in the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's investigative staff will begin almost immediately to
interview potential witnesses for hearings that would not take
place until after the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution approved Thursday gives Hyde and Rep. John
Conyers (D-Mich.), the panel's ranking Democrat, the power to
decide to issue subpoenas. But should they disagree on a subpoena,
the GOP-controlled committee would vote whether to issue, which
could come into play if Democrats wish to summon Starr or Lewinsky
and Republicans do not.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting articles of impeachment and other formal impeachment
proceedings, if the committee determines they are necessary, almost
certainly would not take place before a new Congress is sworn into
office on Jan. 3, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the 105th Congress ends on Jan. 3 and lawmakers in
the 106th Congress would have to vote to re-start the impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich refrained from taking a partisan role in
the debate, although he voted for the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich presided over the entire proceedings and looked on
impassively as two Democrats, Barney Frank of Massachusetts and
Nancy Pelosi of California, raised Gingrich's ethics case in
discussing whether to investigate Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said Republicans were being inconsistent in their
treatment of Gingrich, re-elected as speaker last year despite
admitting to providing misleading information to the ethics
committee, and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The California Democrat, who was a member of the ethics
committee, accused the Republicans of a double standard ``which
exults the speaker and moves to impeach the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the few comments Gingrich made during the debate was a
plea for quiet in the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few debates more important and more serious than
that which we're currently having,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans retain their House majority in November and
Gingrich is re-elected as speaker, he would be likely to preside
over an impeachment debate, if there is one.
</P>
<P>
   No president who has won election in his own right has been
impeached, although the Judiciary Committee voted articles of
impeachment against Nixon in 1974 and the Democratic-led House
seemed certain to follow suit. Nixon resigned before the House
could act.
</P>
<P>
   The full House has impeached only one president, Andrew Johnson,
in 1868. He succeeded to the office from the vice presidency with
the assassination of Abraham Lincoln in 1865. The Senate fell one
vote shy of removing Johnson from office.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
