<SLUG> BC-MARKET-TURMOIL-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS' PILINGS OF STABILITY DRIFT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For six weeks, investors have lulled themselves into thinking
that the worst might be over, that the selloff that had racked
financial markets around the world had largely run its course.
While times might still be tough, the prices of stocks, bonds and
other financial assets had largely taken the bad news into account.
</P>
<P>
   That illusion cracked Thursday as the value of the dollar
remained low, interest rates rose and the prices of hundreds of
stocks plunged even as the main stock market gauges showed minimal
losses. One after another, the pilings that have lent a measure of
stability to the markets over the last several weeks have been
swept away.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, things might not look so bad: the Dow Jones
industrial average, the stock market bellwether, finished the day a
mere 9.78 points lower, at 7,731.91. But beneath that relatively
calm result was a day of turmoil during which the Dow fell as much
as 274 points before climbing back in the last two hours of
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Even greater damage occurred in the Nasdaq composite index,
which measures the performance of many of the fastest-growing
technology companies. The index dropped 43.49 points, or nearly 3
percent, to 1,419.12 _ its lowest closing price in 16 months. Over
the last two weeks alone, the Nasdaq index has fallen nearly 20
percent _ a spectacular implosion in such a short time.
</P>
<P>
   That greater upheaval reflects a significant shift in the mood
of many investors on Wall Street and around the globe. Gone are the
expectations, analysts said, that the United States can avoid the
economic slowdown that has already gripped much of the world. While
many economists on Wall Street still call a recession unlikely, the
fact that they are including its potential in their forecasts means
that most bets of continued unbridled expansion are off.
</P>
<P>
   Also washing away are some of the last remaining expectations of
brisk growth in corporate profits, of companies using much of their
excess cash to buy back their own shares, and of individual
investors riding to the rescue and buying more stocks each time the
market dips.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more confusion in the marketplace now than I've ever
seen in my career,'' said Henry Herrmann, president and chief
investment officer at Waddell &AMP; Reed Financial, a mutual fund
company based in Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of confusion has just got the vast majority of
portfolio managers cross-eyed,'' said Herrmann, who has worked in
the investment business since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the situations that have confused him and others is
the ``flight to quality'' that has taken place among stock and bond
investors. The shift has left blue-chip stocks and U.S. Treasury
bonds performing relatively well while every other category of
assets has been hammered.
</P>
<P>
   The latest victims have been the highly visible Nasdaq stocks,
whose steep fall stems in large part from heavy selling by foreign
investors. Those investors have been some of the biggest buyers of
American stocks over the last two years as the value of the dollar
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, with the dollar reversing its course and becoming
cheaper in relation to the yen, the mark and other foreign
currencies, overseas investors are finding that not only are their
American stocks worth less, but they also get less of their home
currency for each dollar when they convert their investments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, those Americans who have come to expect a U.S.
recession have begun to measure its possible effect on technology
companies. Those manufacturers that sell equipment to businesses in
America and around the world are more likely to be hurt by an
economic slowdown than are the large consumer product companies
that make up much of the Dow industrial index.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a slowdown in the purchase of capital goods by
companies, the technology companies will be affected more
dramatically than a lot of the blue chips,'' said Robert Freedman,
chief investment officer at the John Hancock Funds. ``At the same
time, people will still be eating and drinking and going to the
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Several specific events also led traders to take a decidedly
dimmer view of things on Thursday. First, the Bank of England cut
its benchmark interest rate by a quarter-point, to 7.25 percent.
But much as with the quarter-point cut in rates by the Federal
Reserve last week, equity traders and analysts judged the move to
be too little to aid slowing economies around the world,
particularly in Europe. Financial markets in Europe fell sharply,
with the major stock indexes down 2.7 percent in Britain and 5
percent in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates generally rose Thursday, with the yield on the
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond climbing to just below 5 percent,
up from 4.72 percent on Monday. In addition, short-term rates have
fallen below long-term rates in the days since the Federal Reserve
cut its benchmark rate. The level of short-term rates generally
indicates that bond traders expect further cuts by the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. stock markets, two influential analysts adjusted
their outlooks, further adding to the market's gloom. Abby Joseph
Cohen, the investment analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. who has been
the market's most voluble cheerleader over the last three years,
made comments about corporate earnings growth that to many
listeners had a slightly negative tone.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Cohen did not throw in the towel on her relentlessly
optimistic forecast, she at least threw in a washcloth, cutting her
estimates of 1998 and 1999 earnings for the companies in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, implying that the current
economic squeeze would extend well into next year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Acampora, who tracks market indexes and other statistical
measures at Prudential Securities, also lowered his estimate of how
low the Dow might fall.
</P>
<P>
   It was Acampora who caused a stampede out of stocks in early
August, when the Dow industrials were still above 8,700, with his
prediction of a bear market. Thursday, he said he thought the Dow
would trade as low as 6,700, well below his previous floor of
7,400. To get to that level, the Dow would have to fall more than
13 percent from Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Greg Smith, Prudential's chief investment strategist
and a colleague of Acampora's, recommended that investors increase
their cash holdings to 20 percent of assets from 5 percent. Most of
that cash, he said, should be raised by lowering bond investments
to 25 percent of a portfolio from 35 percent, with stock
investments falling to 55 percent from 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two other stabilizing factors also appear to be gone from
beneath the relatively calm surface of the stock market. Mutual
fund investors, who have lent the stock market a strong measure of
stability for the last four years, demonstrated in August _ the
last time the market fell sharply _ that they will withdraw money
from stock funds when performance turns down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with small stocks continuing to fall sharply, financial
analysts say that funds specializing in shares of small companies
are experiencing growing levels of investor withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   Also, traders speak of fears that one more remaining source of
liquidity for the stock market is drying up: corporate stock
repurchases. With credit becoming harder to come by for many
companies, those corporations that have been actively buying back
shares to finance option packages and for other uses might be less
likely to spend any spare cash they have, at least over the short
run.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves many traders fearful that the stock market will get
more choppy, with big swings during the day, like Thursday's,
becoming even more common. Investors, they say, should be ready for
more choppy seas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
