<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALOU NO MIRACLE WORKER
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-LBPT (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since Bob (Don't Call Me Rocky) Graziano was propped up by
Rupert Murdoch's top local executives, Peter Chernin and Chase
Carey, to be their top Dodger stooge, the organization has inspired
more laughs than a Jay Leno monologue and made more bumbling
decisions than a Russian economist.
</P>
<P>
   They claim Graziano and his hand-picked toady, Kevin Malone, are
now minding the Dodger operation, but I swear Laurel &AMP; Hardy have
been resurrected and are in charge of dispensing histrionics.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, forget a moment the mindless Mike Piazza trade, or the
mid-season cashiering of Bill Russell and Fred Claire, or the first
dumping of loyal Dodger coaches like Mark Cresse and Reggie Smith,
or the second dumping of loyal Dodger coaches like Manny Mota and
Joey Amalfitano, or the demotion of interim manager Glenn Hoffman
despite his 47-41 record, or other such brainless indiscretions
that I'm sure has Walter O'Malley doing cartwheels in his casket.
</P>
<P>
   I can't think of anything more hilarious than the current
spectacle of Laurel &AMP; Hardy err Graziano &AMP; Malone scurrying down to
the Dominican Republic to beg 63-year-old Felipe Alou to accept
their multimillion dollar offer to manage the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Alou?!
</P>
<P>
   Oh wow, he's the answer to all the Dodger problems the lack of a
first-class center fielder, the lack of a catcher who can hit, the
lack of a legitimate third baseman, the lack of a marquee pitcher,
the lack of a reliable relief pitcher, the lack of a first-class
shortstop, the total lack of team chemistry, etc., etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   Please!
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing against Felipe Alou. Actually, he was one of my
favorite players when I spent a good portion of my teenage years
passionately rooting for the San Francisco Giants. And I'm sure
he's done commendable work with a Montreal Expo team long hampered
by financial shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   But he's no miracle-worker, no genius, no divine savior whose
presence in Los Angeles will magically transform the Dodgers into a
pennant contender.
</P>
<P>
   If Malone is serious about upgrading the Dodgers, he should have
retained Hoffman and invested all those millions he's willing to
blow on Alou to acquire a quality free agent in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Malone, in a typical grandstanding maneuver of flying
all the way to Santo Domingo, reportedly offered the Dodger
managerial job to that self-styled genius, Jim Leyland, whose
superior knowledge and deft insights resulted in 54 victories
against only 108 defeats for the Florida Marlins this season.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Leyland rebuffed Malone's overture, so Malone has decided
to go after Alou, a nice man who reportedly has voiced private
reservations about going to work for the Dodgers with Tom Lasorda
looming in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Tommy.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered guy is being blamed for everything these days
short of Hurricane Georges and Monicagate.
</P>
<P>
   And I find that reprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   I still like Tommy Lasorda, even though he has instituted a
fatwa
</P>
<P>
   against me in the wake of my printing those harsh anti-Lasorda
quotes from Bill Russell after Russell was fired.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if Kevin Malone is determined to turn the Dodger
manager's office into Leisure World, why doesn't he show some real
courage and bring back Tommy Lasorda?
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda hasn't exactly hidden his desire to manage again, and
he's an established name with a proven record, even a Hall of Famer
with four National League pennants and two World Series titles to
his credit.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lasorda is every bit the manager Felipe Alou is, and he's
only eight years older. ..
</P>
<P>
   Will someone explain to me in detail why UCLA's top rusher,
Jermaine Lewis, has been suspended for Saturday night's game
against Arizona?
</P>
<P>
   UCLA would only reveal that Lewis got into a fight, and that the
guy he was fighting with wound up with stitches and wound up
reporting the beef to campus police.
</P>
<P>
   But everything else is shrouded in typical big-time collegiate
athletic cover-up murk, except for the inevitable
my-guy-says-he's-innocent comments from the suspended athlete's
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Is Jermaine Lewis a malevolent instigator, or an innocent
victim?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure that notorious stonewalling UCLA athletic director,
Pious Peter (Principle) Dalis knows, but the public certainly
doesn't. And doesn't the public have a right to know, since it,
after all, UCLA is a state-subsidized university?. ...
</P>
<P>
   I've seen bonehead plays by baseball players before, but none
more outrageous than the one committed Wednesday by the New York
Yankees' second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who allowed the Cleveland
Indians to score what turned out to be the game's winning run in
the 12th inning on a play in which became too preoccupied with
arguing with the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be surprised if the suddenly quite mortal Yankees, who
badly miss the potent bat of Darryl Strawberry, are able to come
back from Knoblauch's unforgivable folly against the resilient
Indians. ...
</P>
<P>
   I've seen bad umpiring but Ted Hendry's erratic work behind the
plate in that second Yankee-Indian game was the worst I've ever
seen. ...
</P>
<P>
   I always get the distinct impression that no one enjoys
listening to Bob Costas work a baseball game more than Bob Costas.
...
</P>
<P>
   This San Diego Padre team has a resolute toughness that the
Atlanta Braves notably lack. ...
</P>
<P>
   Please, anything, another recycled Don Rickles joke from Tom
Lasorda, a TV reprise of Todd Donoho, even a handshake from Al
Davis, rather than the Padres and Indians in the World Series,
which indeed might happen to tarnish what has been a glorious
baseball season. ...
</P>
<P>
   Swimming great Susie Atwood phoned the other tell to say that
superstar maitre d' Dancing Barry Clifford wants his many followers
and my readers to know that he's shifting from Kelly's to
Spaghettini's but doesn't want it known that he inspired Susie to
call me with such an epic revelation. OK, I'll keep it a secret.
...
</P>
<P>
   I watched the Poly-Fontana game on Fox last Thursday in its
entirety, and I don't see how the nation's No. 1 rated high school
team, De LaSalle of Concord, could keep up with Poly's incredible
speed that is superior to most major college teams. ...
</P>
<P>
   Oh, If Only Kenneth Starr Knew Dept.: ``Can you believe I might
wind up facing greater punishment than President Clinton?'' said a
solemn John Morris the other day, the Mum's proprietor whose
establishment faces a 45-day suspension from Alcoholic Beverage
Control for staging a smoker a couple of years ago in which a
couple of ladies performed illegal lap dances.
</P>
<P>
   How awful! But why shut Morris' joint down for 45 days and
deprive 60 workers of their income? Why not make a graphic example
of Bobby Rahal's best friend and the Florenz Ziegfeld of Pine
Avenue (I mistakenly referred to Morris the other day as the Andrew
Lloyd Webber of that great thoroughfare when, instead, I meant to
compare him to the founder of Ziegfeld Follies). Why not close off
Pine Avenue and string Jolly John Morris up on a lamppost and stone
him for such a heinous crime against nature?
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous!
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't the ABC have enough to worry about these tense hours
with all those terrible smoking violators than to turn John Morris
into a modern day Sacco &AMP; Venzetti?. ...
</P>
<P>
   I don't bet, but I'd take UCLA and lay the 6{ if I did against
the Wildcats. ...
</P>
<P>
   Yes, And He Also Returned A Louis XIV Bed Because It Was Too
Small, And Asked For A Louis XV Dept.: Wise guy Lakewood Mall
Jewelry Connection jokester Kevin (Dizzy) Diehm, on Chuck
Knoblauch's gaffe: ``His biggest stumbling block is the one under
his hat.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Opposites indeed do attract, for if there ever was a person just
the opposite of me, it's my beloved Brit, so insufferably prim and
proper, so disgustedly fair-minded and honest, so intolerably naive
and innocent, so incomprehensibly sober and understanding that I
know I've been touched by an angel a year after walking down the
altar of eternal bliss. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
