r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-JENKINS-LBPT     10-08 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-JENKINS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENKINS SOARS OVER SEATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As local columnists weigh in on whether it was the greatest play
in the 100-year history of University of Arizona football, and as
it's shown on national TV over and over, and as U of A professors
begin their classes with a discussion about it, Gracie Jenkins
rather sheepishly has a confession to make.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't see it happen.
</P>
<P>
   As her only child, Ortege, was soaring over Seattle on Saturday
night his team's fate and his own well-being very much up in the
air Gracie was at a girlfriend's home in Long Beach, unable to
summon up the courage to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting on the couch with my head down, my eyes closed
and my hands put together I was praying,'' she said. ``Now, we know
God doesn't discriminate, but whatever edge was possible we wanted
to have and I just couldn't bring myself to look.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my friend shouted `All right,' I looked up and saw him in
the end zone. I had to see the replay and when I did, I was glad I
didn't see it (live). All I could think was `Thank God he landed on
his feet.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, 'Cats always do.
</P>
<P>
   By now everyone has seen the play. Ortege Jenkins drops back to
pass, sees all his receivers covered and then tucks the ball away
and runs up the middle. As he closes in on the goal line, three
Washington players converge on him - free safety Brendan Jones and
linebackers Lester Towns and Marques Hairston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was only one way to get in,'' said Jenkins, a
third-year sophomore from Jordan High.
</P>
<P>
   And so, as he reached the 4-yard line, he closed his eyes and
jumped. The Huskies hit him low, sending Jenkins, who is 6-foot-2,
214 pounds, head over heels. Miraculously he landed on his feet and
importantly it was in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got hit, all I was thinking about was keeping my eyes
closed and making sure I landed on my front side and not my head,''
said Jenkins, whose first name is pronounced Or-TEEj but also
answers to O.J. ``When I hit the turf I didn't know if I got in
until I looked over and saw the side judge signaling touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The stunning play, with four seconds left, lifted Arizona to a
31-28 win over Washington its first win in Seattle in 10 years and
sets up Saturday night's showdown between the No. 10 Wildcats (5-0)
and No.3 UCLA (3-0) in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be the college play of the year,'' said Keith
Smith, with whom Jenkins shares the quarterback job. ``I've never
seen a play like that. That's something you only dream about doing
and it was so clutch. He wanted it way more than the three guys
trying to stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   The play capped an 80-yard drive in the final 2:53 in which
Jenkins converted three third-downs with passes and also caught a
22-yard pass the first of his career from Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, though, was sacked at the Washington 9-yard line on
second-and-goal and Arizona was forced to use its final timeout
with 12 seconds left. When Jenkins came to the sidelines, the first
thing coach Dick Tomey told him was to make sure he got two passes
off. In other words, don't run and don't pass to anyone who's not
in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The play was designed to go to the Wildcats' top receiver,
Dennis Northcutt. But he was double covered in the left corner and
not open. The second option was tight end Mike Lucky, who ran a
crossing pattern with Northcutt, but was also covered.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, whose seven-step drop took him back to the 20-yard
line, noticed the middle of the field open up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he dropped back there and started to run, it was `Oh, no.
Throw it away,''' said Arizona assistant head coach Duane Akina.
``Then, it's `God
</P>
<P>
   Damn, I love that kid.'''
</P>
<P>
   So what if the play wasn't smart? It was audacious. It was
daring. It was fearless. It was, well, O.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about O.J.,'' said Northcutt. ``He's
unpredictable. He can make the plays, but you don't know what it's
going to be. That's his style it's the kind of person he is.''
</P>
<P>
   And always has been, says his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of those children you had to watch because he's
never met a stranger without talking to him,'' said Gracie Jenkins.
``We took a trip up north on train when he was a little boy and all
of a sudden he disappeared. I found him in the viewing coach
talking with about four or five men about football. They said,
`This kid really knows the sport.' He's always been outgoing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of sports, where athletes routinely duck reporters
when things don't go well, Jenkins is the anti-Albert Belle he
loves the attention, good or bad.
</P>
<P>
   He approached an Arizona beat writer earlier this season to ask
why he hadn't talked with him after a game in which Jenkins
struggled. And Jenkins has been known to walk off the field
reciting his stats after a scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   When Jenkins was a senior at Jordan, where he was a two-sport
star, he read an item in the Press-Telegram suggesting that
Compton's Jeff Trepagnier, now at USC, was the best leaper in the
Moore League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing Compton the next day,'' said Jenkins. ``Jeff
came down the court and I gave him two lanes to show me what he's
got. I'm saying, `If you're gonna dunk on me, go ahead and dunk on
me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins followed Trepagnier up and pinned the ball against the
backboard. A few moments later, Trepagnier had another opportunity.
Again Jenkins blocked it. ``They called a foul on it, but ask
anybody,'' Jenkins said proudly. ``There was no foul.''
</P>
<P>
   As he stood along the foul lane, Jenkins looked over at the
offending reporter and, with his broad smile, pointed to his legs
as if to ask ``Who's got the best hops in the Moore League now?''
</P>
<P>
   It's odd, then, that Jenkins is taken aback by all the attention
his leap has brought.
</P>
<P>
   The play was shown on Monday Night Football. A photo of Jenkins,
upside down in mid-flight, was featured in Sports Illustrated this
week, and he has had dozens of requests for interviews, including
the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates have kidded him that he'll win an ESPY for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' Jenkins said. ``I was just out there trying to get
us the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, who was a seldom-used reserve on Arizona's top-ranked
basketball team last year, said it is no accident he leaped into
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he tried to go through a pair of Washington State
players, including his former Jordan teammate Lejuan Gibbons, and
was stopped short of the goal line on a two-point conversion on the
final play of Arizona's 35-34 overtime loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big thing letting that happen to myself,'' Jenkins
said. ``I really questioned myself why I didn't get airborne. That
was on my mind, to be honest with you. I knew this time there was
going to be no other way to get in. I just figured I had a chance
to make it happen so I took it, went after it and got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it turned out to be un-flipping believable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
