<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7241 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-870&AMP;A     10-08 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-870&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-DAY)
</HEADLINE>
  
 HOUSE VOTES ALONG PARTY LINES TO BEGIN BROAD IMPEACHMENT
INQUIRY  (See also CLINTON-IMPEACH, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-VOTE,(sw) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a civil if sometimes harshly phrased debate
that lasted more than three hours, the House of Representatives
voted largely along party lines on Thursday to launch a full-scale,
open-ended inquiry into possible grounds for the impeachment of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry, which will lead ultimately to another House vote to
decide whether Clinton should stand trial in the Senate, was
authorized by a vote of 258-176, with 31 Democrats breaking ranks
with the president. Some at the White House had feared wholesale
defections. They did not materialize, and from that Clinton could
snatch some shred of consolation, but Thursday's developments
nonetheless deepened the crisis shrouding his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the third time in the Republic's 222-year history
that the House had voted such a step, and the Founding Fathers, the
Constitution and the long shadow of precedent were cited by both
sides as the debate unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic representatives complained bitterly that Thursday's
proceeding was unfair because they were given too little time to
speak, and Joe Lockhart, Clinton's spokesman, said that so far the
whole process had been ``infected with politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton himself was less confrontational. At a
late-afternoon photo session, he said of his fate: ``It is not in
my hands; it is in the hands of Congress and the people of this
country, ultimately in the hands of God. There is nothing I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   After imploring his fellow members to pay heed to ``that still,
small voice that whispers in our ear, `duty, duty, duty,''' Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee,
opened the debate by reminding everyone that for now, ``We don't
make any judgments. We don't make any charges. We simply begin the
search for truth.''
</P>
<P>
   What lies ahead, he added later, ``is an onerous, miserable,
rotten job.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the Democrats, the House minority leader, Rep. Dick
Gephardt of Missouri, said that Clinton `` has deeply disappointed
the American people. He's let us all down.'' But Congress ``must
not compound the hurt,'' Gephardt said, urging his colleagues to
opt for a shorter, narrower investigative process so the American
government could deal with the economic and political problems of
``a dangerous world.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Gephardt said, the country may spend ``three, six,
nine, 12 months, two years, in suspended animation.'' His colleague
in the Democratic leadership, Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, raised
the specter of a Congress ``mired in hearings, tangled in testimony
and grinding its gears in partisan stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress is expected to recess this weekend for the next three
weeks. During that time, the Judiciary Committee and its staff will
decide a number of strategic questions, such as whether to call
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky as witnesses. Then, after the mid-term
elections on Nov. 3, Hyde said, the hearings will begin.
</P>
<P>
   The elections will send a political signal to Capitol Hill.
According to opinion surveys, the public wants Congress to put the
Clinton controversy behind it. But if the Republicans should gain
four to six seats in the Senate and six to 10 seats in the House,
as electoral analysts think possible, that might give a strong new
impetus to the investigation of the charges brought against Clinton
by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has only seven states on his campaign schedule so far,
an indication of his diminished influence as a leader of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats who voted on Thursday with the Republicans
clearly did so because they are locked in close election races and
feared seeming blindly supportive of the president. Among them were
Reps. Leonard Boswell of Iowa, Jim Maloney of Connecticut and Ellen
Tauscher of California.
</P>
<P>
   Others were conservative Southern Democrats, such as Reps.
Charles Stenholm of Texas, Bud Cramer of Alabama and Gene Taylor of
Mississippi. Some of them face difficult re-election fights, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   No votes were necessarily indicative of how members will vote
when the House comes to consider articles of impeachment. Indeed,
that question may not even come before the House as now
constituted. It goes out of existence on Jan. 3, 1999, to be
replaced by the new body that is to be elected next month.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said again on Thursday that he hoped to finish the House's
work by the end of the year, but he has always been careful not to
make any promises.
</P>
<P>
   Only two Democrats, Reps. Paul McHale of Pennsylvania and Dennis
Kucinich of Ohio, spoke on the floor in open support of the
Republican resolution. The first congressional Democrat to call for
Clinton's resignation, McHale cited Franklin Roosevelt's maxim that
``the presidency is primary a place of moral leadership.'' Clinton,
he said, had lied repeatedly and would still by lying had he not
been confronted ``by a mountain of irrefutable evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenging the president's statement that his relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky was ``inappropriate,'' McHale said it was in fact
``predatory, reckless and breathtakingly arrogant for a man already
a defendant in a sexual harassment suit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two Floridians summed up the sharply differing arguments of the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, a Republican from Lakeland, said that any
conduct by a president that ``undercuts the integrity of office''
constitutes an impeachable offense. Then he asked: ``If perjury and
obstruction of justice do not undermine the integrity of office,
what offense would?''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking next, Rep. Robert Wexler, a Democrat from Boca Raton,
said Congress needed to talk about Kosovo and Saddam Hussein and
overcrowded classrooms and the ``crumbling'' global economy, not
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president betrayed his wife,'' Wexler said. ``He did not
betray the country. God help this nation if we fail to recognize
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no one spoke in defense of Clinton's sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of Democrats, notably members of the Black Caucus,
who have been among the president's staunchest advocates from the
start, spoke passionately against the Republicans' investigatory
methods and proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters of California denounced the release of
``tawdry and trashy thousands of pages of hearsay, accusations,
gossip and telephone chatter'' that came nowhere close, she said,
to proving impeachable offenses. Rep. Charles Rangel of New York
warned the Republicans that they would not win the November
election ``by hounding the president.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. John Lewis of Georgia, a venerated hero of the civil
rights movement of the 1960s, accused the Republicans of trying to
defeat Clinton through impeachment because they had failed to do so
at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are watching,'' he said angrily, his voice
rising to a shout. ``Beware the wrath of the American people, Mr.
Speaker. Beware!''
</P>
<P>
   Black members were not the only hard hitters. Rep. Nancy Pelosi
of California attacked Republicans for seeking to impeach Clinton
after allowing the speaker, Rep. Newt Gingrich of Georgia, to
survive with a mere reprimand for giving false information to the
ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the debate, the House chamber was about a quarter
full, with perhaps 110 members present at any one time. That is
more than attend routine debates, but surprisingly few, considering
the momentousness of the occasion. Staff members milled in the
aisles, chattering, and Gingrich, who was presiding, several times
appealed for order and asked people to sit down.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., intervened to suggest that leaders of
both parties ``send out messages to the members that whatever
they're doing they ought to drop it and get their tails in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Decorum never quite collapsed, but there was whistling and
cheering, as well as applause, after some speakers finished their
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the galleries were the country singer Charley
Pride and fromer Rep. Tom Railsback, R-Ill., who played a central
role on the Judiciary Committee when it recommended the impeachment
of President Richard Nixon in 1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
