<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONAQBS-SIDE-L     10-08 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONAQBS-SIDE-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH, JENKINS MAKE PERFECT PAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILLY WITZ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Moments after he survived a gravity defying, head-over-heals,
don't-try-this-at-home touchdown run to beat Washington, Ortege
Jenkins had a much tougher encounter.
</P>
<P>
   On his way back to the sidelines, Jenkins was tackled by the man
who wants his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped up and kneed him in the stomach, then I fell down,''
Keith Smith said. ``I didn't know what was going on. Everybody was
going crazy. I couldn't believe he beat Washington on the last play
of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As the photo on today's sports front shows there's No.12 in the
background, the first one to celebrate nobody was happier about
Jenkins' touchdown than Smith.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a competition for the quarterback job has
evolved into a job-sharing arrangement that has left Jenkins and
Smith quite content.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Dick Tomey names a starter each week, but both
have split time. Smith has started the last four games and while
his numbers are slightly better, Tomey turned to Jenkins at the end
against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``OJ and I truly believe that we can do it together,'' said
Smith, who considered transferring after last season. ``We both
believe in our abilities, but if we treat everything negatively,
we're not going to get anything out of it. Now, we're battling, but
it's more of a team concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Both have proved themselves as starters.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a junior from Newbury Park, won the job as a freshman and
set a school record by completing 60.6 percent of his passes and
accounted for an NCAA freshman-record 502 yards of total offense
against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, a sophomore from Jordan High in Long Beach, took over
last year when Smith was hurt and threw for a Pac-10
freshman-record 19 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great relationship on and off the field - that's why
it works so good,'' Jenkins said. ``We know how to work together.
At first I had my doubts - you always do. But it's good now. I
don't see any reason why anything should be changed because we're
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (5-0) is ranked 10th, its highest since 1994. It's also
worth noting that two of the last three Rose Bowl champions - USC
with Brad Otton and Kyle Wachholtz and Ohio State with Stanley
Jackson and Joe Germaine - have used a two-quarterback system.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, though, has shown the two can co-exist on the same
field. On the Wildcats' winning drive against Washington, Smith
lined up at tailback and Jenkins went in motion. The ball was
snapped to Smith who, displaying the hands of a former minor league
shortstop, scooped it up and fired to Jenkins for a 22-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll do more of that soon,'' said Smith, who
played running back and receiver last season. ``OJ and I will do
whatever it takes. We don't care anything about our stats. We love
winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
