<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7258 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT-520&AMP;A     10-08 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EMBARKS ON ANOTHER ROUND OF TALKS WITH YUGOSLAV PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also KOSOVO-REFUGEES)  
(js) 
 BY ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a delicate dance of diplomacy and threats, the
Clinton administration on Thursday embarked on yet another round of
negotiations with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic while
accusing him of ``cosmetic gestures'' that would not be enough to
head off NATO air strikes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke was dispatched back to
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, to try again after three days of largely
fruitless talks with the Yugoslav leader that ended on Wednesday.
The negotiations so far, a senior official said, had been ``the
grimmest ever'' between the two men _ a bleak description given
their often bitter wrangling over ways to end the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Milosevic now
had ``but a few days''to withdraw about 15,000 Yugoslav Army
soldiers from Kosovo along with large number of special police
units or face military action from NATO.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also issued a warning Thursday. ``We would far
prefer to secure President Milosevic's compliance with the will of
the international community in a peaceful manner,'' he said. ``But
NATO must be prepared to act militarily to protect our interests
and to prevent another humanitarian catastrophe in the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has not won agreement on military strikes
from other NATO countries. Several NATO governments _ among them
Germany, Italy and Denmark _ are still hesitant about undertaking
alliance military action without an explicit Security Council
mandate, which appears almost impossible to get.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she was confident that if Milosevic continued to
prevaricate, all NATO governments would vote for military action.
However, she did not say when that might happen.
</P>
<P>
   NATO ambassadors meeting in Brussels on Thursday gave final
approval to an operational plan for air strikes worked out by
military commanders in recent weeks, officials said. But a
so-called activation order, the approval needed to put that plan
into action, seems unlikely to be agreed upon until the weekend, at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Russia continued on Thursday to oppose any use of force at a
meeting in London of the contact group on Yugoslavia, which
includes the United States, Russia, Britain, France, Germany and
Italy. The members tried to put on a determined show of unity by
formally approving Holbrooke's new mission, and issued a statement
insisting on Milosevic's compliance with a Security Council
resolution passed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's main demands will be those laid out in the
resolution: an end to all military and police operations in Kosovo,
the verifiable withdrawal of forces, free access to Kosovo for
international relief organizations and the opening of negotiations
with Kosovo's ethnic-Albanian community, which accounts for about
90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Cook, the British foreign secretary, said Milosevic would
be given an ``ultimatum.'' But U.S. officials studiously avoided
that term, calling it the ``U word,'' and no deadline was set for
the compliance of the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Milosevic would be taking a substantial political risk by
accepting Holbrooke's demands. As one senior official remarked
Thursday in a reference to discussions on ending the war in Bosnia,
``he could throw the Croatian Serbs and Bosnian Serbs overboard
when he had to, but abandoning the Kosovo Serbs is unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, the center of Serbia's medieval-era civilization and
site of several exquisite Eastern Orthodox monasteries, is widely
regarded by the Serbs as the womb of their nationhood, a place
whose surrender is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Through emotional exploitation of the region's history and myth
and by quashing the province's autonomy in 1989, Milosevic built
the foundation for his rise to power. The ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo now want more than the autonomy they once had; they want
independence and are using guerrilla tactics in its pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared clear Thursday that America's strategy for ending
the fighting in Kosovo, which has already left more than 250,000
people homeless, was rooted in the attempt to mount an entirely
credible threat of force even as NATO's unity remained less than
complete and Russian opposition to military action vehement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to meet Germany's chancellor-elect, Gerhard Schroder,
in Washington on Friday for talks that will center on overcoming
German concerns. As for Russia, Albright said America hoped to
``work with them on a joint compliance.'' But she added that, ``If
force is necessary, then we will not be deterred by the fact that
the Russians do not agree with that.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior diplomat reported a tense exchange during the Contact
Group meeting between Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and
Albright. The Russian minister expressed his view that Milosevic
was prepared to cooperate, and the secretary of state retorted that
the Yugoslav president was ``a congenital liar''.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said publicly that, ``Time and again, Milosevic has
promised us to do things he had no intention of doing.'' She added:
``Even in the last two weeks, even as he made cosmetic gestures in
the direction of compliance, his forces committed some of the worst
atrocities of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   But after weeks of intense diplomatic effort to reach even the
uncertain degree of Western unity now achieved, it appears unlikely
that the United States would shelve the threat of force. With
winter coming on, it is clear to everyone that this is a last
chance to avoid a season of terrible suffering in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Holbrooke would meet with Milosevic on Friday and
might remain in Belgrade into the weekend. Many U.S. embassy staff
have already been withdrawn from the Yugoslav capital in
preparation for possible air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has pledged radar-avoiding B-2 bombers and
F-117A attack jets to a NATO force of up to 430 warplanes that
would hit Serbian military targets, officials said. The B-2 bomber,
which is capable of dropping 40,000 pounds of satellite-guided
``smart'' bombs, has never been used before in combat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
