<SLUG> BC-IMF-WORLDBANK-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAID TO FACE BRUNT OF GLOBAL ECONOMIC CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
wound up their annual meetings on Thursday saying that the United
States will bear most of the burden of helping Asia and the rest of
the developing world get out of a recession.
</P>
<P>
   America's relatively strong economy will draw in the exports of
crisis-stricken countries at the same time that foreign demand for
U.S. goods is weakened. As a result, the United States'
balance-of-payments deficit will soar, with IMF forecasts showing
the U.S. deficit rising sharply from $155 billion in 1997 to $236
billion this year and $290 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One implication of that rising deficit is that a steady increase
in competitively priced imports can, over time, lead to an erosion
of U.S. market share and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the 15-member countries of the European Union and
Japan will continue running substantial payment surpluses with
exports far in excess of imports.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Japan's finance minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, struck
a note of quiet desperation when he described his country's failure
to recover economically, saying at the annual meeting that,
``despite steady implementation of the latest economic policy
package, the largest ever, our economic situation is still
extremely severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan seems set to remain in deep recession this year with only
a minute recovery next year. Its already massive payments surplus
of $94 billion last year is expected to reach $131 billion this
year and $135 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In his final address and press conference on Thursday, Michel
Camdessus, managing director of the IMF, said the world was making
progress toward resolving the crisis that has gripped much of the
global economy since the collapse of some of Asia's leading
economies last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could have happened more than has happened,'' he said.
``We are dealing with a monumental task.''
</P>
<P>
   The 182 countries represented at the meetings endorsed his
proposals for tackling five ``major shortcomings'' in the
international financial system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   These included a lack of transparency about economic details
throughout the world that impeded sound policy making; weak
financial systems; unrestricted and volatile flows of capital
around the globe; a reluctance to make private banks and other
financial institutions pay part of the costs of the crisis; and
better regulation of world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is now ``confident'' agreement will be reached
between the Clinton administration and Congress to give the IMF
about $18 billion in new financing as part of a $90 billion effort
by several countries to recapitalize the fund.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The meeting endorsed Clinton's call for a new standby loan fund
linked to the IMF that would bolster the financial defenses of some
countries before they came under attack from investors.
</P>
<P>
   Camdessus said agreement is also close on new steps to shore up
Brazil's shaky economy that would include an announcement by
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso later this month of new
austerity measures in return for a new a package of loans from the
IMF and other donors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while the world economy was still sailing ``stormy,
uncharted waters,'' Camdessus said the recent cut in interest rates
by the Federal Reserve, and Europe's low interest rates, showed
that central bankers are striving to preserve economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth must be sustained. Inflation is not a danger,''
Camdessus said. Early on Thursday, the Bank of England cut a key
interest rate by a quarter point.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, while this year's annual meeting undoubtedly
produced a plethora of ideas on mending the world's damaged
monetary system and a positive avalanche of pledges to do so, it
has not yet resulted in any concrete action.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of both the IMF and the World Bank put the best
possible face on the outcome despite the lack of specific action
and the vagueness of many of the pledges made by member countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have undoubtedly moved a long way forward in identifying
the steps needed to establish a more durable global economic system
and for addressing the crisis,'' Camdessus said.
</P>
<P>
   With millions of people being pushed back into abject poverty
throughout the developing world by the economic downturn, the World
Bank president, James Wolfensohn, expressed satisfaction that
governments now recognized that more must be done to protect people
from the social costs of the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
