<P>
   DAYTON AMISH PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Daily News is offering a package of seven stories
about how the way of life for the 40,000 Amish in Ohio, the world's
largest Amish population, is shifting from agricultural to
commercial. From rural to suburban. From slow to fast-paced. From
simple to complicated. Stories will move on the Cox Wire and photos
and graphics that accompany the text will be posted in the NATIONAL
folder on the Cox server Wednesday, Oct. 7. If you need additonal
information, e-mail Pat Thomas, project editor for the Amish
package and Dayton's Deputy Features Editor, at
pattithomas(at)coxohio.com or call her at (937) 225-2441. Here are
the budget lines for the package:
</P>
<P>
   AMISH _ HOLMES COUNTY, Ohio - (Main bar) Amishman Atlee Miller
stroked his beard and looked out over the hills where he has lived
his austere beliefs for 72 years. He saw
</P>
<P>
   cornfields, horse-drawn buggies and the plain white houses of
his people. ``Some of us are weak,'' he said. ``But most of us are
strong, able to resist temptations - electricity, motorcars - which
can lead to sin.'' Then his pager went off. The electronic beep
alerted Miller to his next buggy tour for patrons at a posh inn.
</P>
<P>
   (Charlise Lyles, Dayton Daily News). 41.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-TYPES _ There are several ``orders'' or types of Amish. A
glossary of who's who and who believes what. (Charlise Lyles,
Dayton Daily News). 7.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-BUGGY _ Driving a buggy is a daily death-defying act of
faith.
</P>
<P>
   (Charlise Lyles, Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-FARM-TOURISM: Rising land prices and a lucrative tourist
trade are threatening the traditional farming way of life the Amish
have followed for generations. (Charlise Lyles, Dayton Daily News).
50.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-SCENES: Vignettes of life among the Amish. (Charlise
Lyles, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   AMISH-RACHEL and AMISH-RACHEL2 _ Twinned stories about two
teen-age Amish girls. One who has already committed to the austere
life of the church and one in ``Rumspringen,'' the running around
period allowed some Amish before they commit to a life of
simplicity. (Charlise Lyles, Dayton Daily News). (Each story is
about 21 inches.)
</P>
<P>
   PERSPECTIVE/OPINION
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASIA _ WASHINGTON _ Throughout his ordeal in the Monica
Lewinsky scandal, the one thing has literally saved the Clinton
Presidency has been the strength of the U.S. economy -- a virtual
juggernaut for the last five years. But that armor is showing some
chinks: lower exports; higher unemployment; slower job growth.
Small wonder then that the president is screaming louder than ever
for Congress to fund the IMF; and that he is ignoring a nuclear
headache in the Indian subcontinent to ward off the Asian flu in
the Pacific Rim. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: For Perspective/Opinion/Insight sections.
</P>
