<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Anyone trying to define the cuisine of the Pacific
Northwest needs to look beyond the oysters and salmon, the
Starbucks and the micro-suds. On an epicurean visit to the city, we
discover a vibrant explosion of Pan-Asian cooking styles and
organic markets (often served by Asian and Hispanic farmers). At
the perennially hot Pike Place Market, we forage for peavines and
purslane, raspberries and wild mushrooms _ and fall in love with
some of the saltier nooks and crannies like Emmett Watson's Oyster
Bar and the Athenian Inn. We take a Saturday morning stroll through
the University Hill Organic Market (10 kinds of potatoes at a
single stall!) and turn a compost pile at one of the exuberantly
decorated P-Patch gardens, where land-locked locals are growing
their own herbs (visitors are welcome to take walking tours). And
of course, no trip to Seattle would be complete without seeing the
jumpin' salmon at Ballard Locks. Quotes from local foodies like
seafood and organic-farming expert Jon Rowley, Mexican cookbook
writer Marilyn Tausend and others. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH COLOR PHOTOS and PAGE LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-MINIREVIEWS _ Minireviews of Pan-Asian restaurants
(Blowfish, Etta's Seafood, Wild Ginger), local hangouts (Emmett
Watson's Oyster Bar, Athenian Inn, Chinook's) and Shiro's, a sushi
bar that many consider the best restaurant in the city. Will
mention a couple of other cool places. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35-40.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GOING _ Going Places (travel notes) column. (Thrasher,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   CLONING _ As an Illinois teen, Steve Stice would huddle by sheep
as they struggled to give birth. More than two decades later, Stice
is still captivated by the miracle of it all. In January, he
awaited the birth of two Holstein calves that were particularly
special to Stice: Not only did he clone them, but they were the
first in the world to carry a genetic marker he had spliced into
their DNA. Now, Stice is leaving his New England farm for the
University of Georgia. His arrival could make Georgia a leader in
cloning animals for more efficient food production and ``pharming''
- using genetically altered animals to produce medicine through
their milk. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50 WITH GRAPHIC
and PHOTOS.
</P>
