<SLUG> BC-MIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 MIT Media Lab Cooking Up New Inventions   By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 Cambridge, Mass.  
 
A kitchen counter that knows how to cook. A stuffed toy chicken
that kids can use as a computer interface. PCs that sense when
you're having a rough day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Media
Laboratory opened their doors yesterday for a rare glimpse at their
vision of the future, showing off inventions that could change how
we work, play, create and even how we communicate with one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers now don't have much to do with life,'' said Michael
Hawley, an assistant professor of media technology at MIT, who is
heading the 3-day-old Counter Intelligence project to bring
computing power into the kitchen. ``What if a food processor had a
real processor in it? What if PostScript were for pasta?''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the kitchen lab, researcher Niko Matsakis is getting a
recipe for chocolate chip cookies from a digital countertop. When
he pours the chips into a pan, the counter tells him when he's
poured the right amount and instructs him to mix the milk with the
chocolate. Eventually, the device will take him through the recipe,
making sure he uses the right ingredients in the right amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the lab is an eggplant engraved with a picture of
Martha Stewart _ the product of a laser cutting machine that uses
PostScript software to write and draw. Hawley's students also have
used the laser cutter _ a machine the size of a photocopier that
carves plastic and other hard materials _ to print words on
crackers. Hawley imagines that children might learn to read from
crackers, cookies or maybe even pasta.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Lab, founded in 1980, is known for its work on such
key technologies as multimedia and digital video as well as for the
freewheeling atmosphere that has sparked playful creations like
robotic Lego toys that kids can program and wearable computers
embedded in eyeglasses, jewelry and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The lab's open house was part of a meeting of the News in the
Future consortium and its corporate sponsors, which include
Chronicle Publishing Co., which publishes The Chronicle. This
group's research has spawned, among other things, paper with
electronic ink that can change with each day's news and name tags
that help groups interact.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Blumberg is using a plush chicken toy to make it easy for
children to interact with computers. Manipulating the chicken moves
an animated character on a computer screen. &UR;  &LR; If they want the
on-screen chicken to fly, they flap the toy chicken's wings. If
they want the animated chicken to stand on its head, they turn the
toy upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell a kid to make the chicken (on the screen) run,
they'll just do it. There's no pressing a function key or space
bar. There's no joystick,'' said Blumberg, an assistant professor
of media arts and sciences. ``You want the interface to match the
thing it's controlling.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a kid-friendly interface, the chicken and other
animal toys could let kids control a character in a cartoon or
learn about wildlife, Blumberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Picard, associate professor of media arts and sciences,
is working on toys, too _ toys that can sense human emotions. By
measuring how hard or often a ball is bounced, she and her students
hope to be able to ``tell if it's being bounced happily or being
abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Picard is doing similar work with personal computers. A computer
using a camera to see your facial expressions, a microphone to hear
what you say or how you say it, and a sensor to tell how hard
you're hitting the keyboard may be able to respond. If it knows
you're cursing and pounding a key because you can't print, for
instance, it could tell you that co-workers have also gotten angry
when they tried to print or it can give you information on other
ways to print the document.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're willing to give the computer continuous feedback, it
can improve itself, pass information to another person or maybe
even show empathy in the appropriate situation,'' said Picard, who
also hopes to figure out how to make e-mail express emotions
without using smiley faces.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the lab's work is likely to make computers even more a
part of everyday life. But it is just as devoted to making
computers more useful _ or more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the Responsive Environments Group built a sneaker
that has 17 sensors and a minuscule computer and measures how the
foot moves and makes musical sounds depending on what occurs.
Eventually Joseph Paradiso, principal research scientist in the
group, hopes to figure out how to make it possible for dancers to
make music.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Gershenfeld, who runs the Physics and Media group, is
building such useful devices as a medicine shelf that knows if
you've got the right prescription and can signal your doctor when
you've taken it. Each pill bottle contains a computing device that
costs just a penny, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gershenfeld and his students also have built a device that lets
you transmit data such as your business card through a handshake.
Their work on a magic trick for performers Penn and Teller led NEC,
which builds controllers for air bags, to build a device that can
tell if a child's car seat is facing the front or the back of the
car. The device is designed to keep air bags from harming children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
