<SLUG> BC-PC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 New PCs To Sell For $500   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
While other personal computer makers are scrambling to turn a
profit on sub-$1,000 systems, newly formed Emachines is about to
introduce a fully equipped PC _ including monitor _ for less than
$500.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's several hundred dollars less than entry-level systems
from Compaq, IBM, Hewlett-Packard and Packard Bell.
</P>
<P>
   By establishing a beachhead at $500, Emachines hopes to lure
first-time buyers who until now couldn't afford a PC. It's also
targeting consumers who are considering second and third PCs for
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five hundred dollars is the magic number for opening up the
next wave of adopters in the home,'' said Steve Dukker, chief
executive of Emachines, a joint venture of two Korean companies
that is based in San Francisco and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The $499 eTower 266 features a 266 MHz Cyrix processor, a 2.1
gigabyte hard drive, 32 megabytes of memory, &UR;  &LR; a 56K modem, a CD-ROM
drive and a 14-inch monitor. The computer is available without the
monitor for $399.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the first people in the market to produce a low-priced
PC that isn't made up of last quarter's leftover components, or
last year's mistakes,'' said Dukker.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dukker, Emachines already has orders for all
200,000 PCs it plans to produce by the end of the year. The systems
will go on sale at Best Buy and Office Depot stores by
mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are taking Emachines seriously for a couple of reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ The company has formidable backing. It's owned by two
well-established South Korean companies _ TriGem, a maker of PCs
and motherboards, and Korean Data Systems, a leading maker of PC
monitors. Both companies manufacture products for big U.S. computer
makers.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's being run by Dukker, a computer retailing veteran and an
expert on the consumer market. Prior to joining Emachines, he was
senior vice president of merchandising for Computer City, and
before that he held a similar post at CompUSA.
</P>
<P>
   After CompUSA announced its acquisition of Computer City in
June, KDS executives invited Dukker to meet with them in Seoul,
figuring he might be in the market for a new job.
</P>
<P>
   He met with officials of KDS and TriGem _ both companies he had
worked with in the past. Emachines was born shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were looking for my guidance as to how they could take
their expertise in high-volume, low-overhead production and make
the best use of it in the U.S.,'' Dukker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling,'' he told them, ``is that we're really ready to
enter the time of mass-produced, low-priced PCs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dukker hopes that by selling large numbers of computers,
Emachines can keep inventory to a minimum and make a profit despite
the new system's low price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Emachines is planning to introduce several other computers,
including a 300 MHz eTower for $599 (including monitor), an
ultra-light notebook for under $2,000 and an entertainment device
for playing games and watching DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   Early next year, the company also will start selling a PC with a
built-in monitor and a sleek design like the Apple iMac, for under
$700.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts give Emachines a good chance at early success. But
there is little doubt that other companies, including Packard Bell
and CTX, will drop their entry level prices below $500 next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emachines has a six-month to one-year lead on branded
rivals,'' said Van Baker of Dataquest. ``Their ability to sustain
beyond that depends on how committed TriGem and KDS are.''
</P>
<P>
   Also unclear is how much in the way of technical support
Emachines will be able to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is not just selling the box but also providing service
levels that people require, especially first-time buyers,'' said
Schelley Olhava of International Data Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
