<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 It's Time for Lofty Earnings Projections to Come Back to Earth   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
It's the earnings, stupid.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all due respect to Clinton campaign gurus Paul Begala and
James Carville _ the men responsible for keeping then-Governor
Clinton fixed on the economy during his first triumphant run for
the presidency _ this stock market's latest swoon is about
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Or it has been the reluctance of financial analysts to slash
their profit estimates to a point where they actually reflect the
chaotic economic world in which the rest of us live.
</P>
<P>
   I know. It sounds like you've heard some of this song and dance
before. Earnings, Asia, Russia and Monica have been the top four
reasons why the market has soared or sunk since August's initial
thermonuclear disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But ever since Asia caught its nasty strain of financial flu in
July 1997, Wall Street has been remiss in not telling investors
that their favorite companies are not going to make as much money
as people would like to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting slammed again because there's a growing
perception that earnings estimates are still too high,'' says Chuck
Hill, research director for First Call in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Profit-reporting season has only just begun, and it's not likely
to get a whole lot more fun before its over. Public companies are
required to report their quarterly earnings within 45 days of the
end of their fiscal quarter, which is September 30 for most
companies whose fiscal years run concurrently with the calendar
year.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings estimates for the third quarter are showing their
steepest revisions (meaning analysts have lowered their
projections) for any quarter since the 1990-91 recession, Hill
says. At the beginning of the third quarter, the average earnings
growth rate for Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies was expected to be
10 percent. Now, analysts estimate profits will shrink by 1.4
percent. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's chief complaint is that financial analysts at brokerages
(the ones who advise clients to buy, sell or hold) have been slow
to slash their earnings projections to levels that truly reflect
the economic pain inflicted throughout much of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts ``tend to bring their numbers down only a
quarter at a time,'' says Hill, whose firm specializes in tracking
profit projections and earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   They needed to be less optimistic. Hindsight is 20/20, but Hill
says it was fair to assume that many big-caps (usually considered
to be stocks with market capitalizations over $5 billion) were not
going to continue to grow profits 20 to 30 percent each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The economic woes of Asia are deep. And no matter what your
isolationist neighbor across the fence thinks, anemic economies
throughout that continent are spanking some of investors' favorite
big-cap stocks, such as Coke and Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing, now, is for analysts to rachet down their
earnings projections not for one quarter but for the next three to
four quarters so the market doesn't continue to disappoint
investors again next January and April.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, analysts are still looking through rose-colored
glasses. They estimate that fourth-quarter earnings will rise 10
percent. And they project that they will increase 15 percent in the
first quarter of next year and 19 percent for the second quarter of
1999. And while it's true that projections tend to get fluffier the
farther out you look, these estimates are out of the ballpark, Hill
says.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. Dan Coker, an emerging growth strategist with
Schroder &AMP; Co. in New York, agrees. ``It's pretty sad that it took
investors more than a year to realize that (the domestic impact of
the Asian economy) would hit,'' Coker says. ``(But) big-cap
investors have been in la-la land.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Coker has a bias toward small-caps (stocks with market
capitalizations under $1 billion), and he believes that smaller
companies will eventually have their day once big-caps establish a
firm bottom to the market. Of course, heaven knows when that day
may come.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, investors are going to be focused on earnings,
echoes money manager Elaine Hahn, president of Hahn Capital
Management in San Francisco. She also believes that earnings
estimates ``have yet to see a substantial markdown for 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   And as long as there is too much fluff in projections _
especially among the widely held big caps _ there will still be
future seasons of earnings disappointments ahead. ``And that's not
a good stage on which to spark a rally,'' Hahn says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
