<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NGUYEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A&AMP;M FOOTBALL STAR IS BUSY MAN ON CAMPUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ It's a big week on the Texas A&AMP;M
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow is the showdown for the No. 18 Aggies against No. 2
Nebraska, the highest-ranked team to visit Kyle Field in 15 years,
and a rematch of the 1997 Big 12 championship game.
</P>
<P>
   And, though star middle linebacker Dat Nguyen has been absorbed
as usual in pregame preparation, other things bid for his concern.
Like one of the graduate-school courses he's taking in pursuit of a
master's degree in marketing to complement the bachelor of science
degree he received in August from the college of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're reading a lot about the history of successful
companies and how they got started,'' said Nguyen, who envisions
one day starting his own enterprise. ``It's very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   That one of his closest friends should be so engrossed in such
matters during a week like this is no surprise to safety Rich
Coady, Nguyen's roommate during Aggies road games.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see the way Dat plays football, the effort he puts into
it,'' Coady said. ``But that's his lifestyle, too. He works hard at
everything he does.''
</P>
<P>
   By no means is football all there is for the most recognizable
A&AMP;M player in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find a more intense guy playing football,'' said
John Thornton, assistant athletic director and adviser to Aggie
Athletes Involved, a community service-oriented organization. ``But
though football is an extremely important part of his life, Dat is
not totally defined by the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the football player. But you also have the student
who graduated early, now the graduate student and a guy who is as
involved in community outreach as much as anyone I can remember in
eight years. And that's not to mention the things he and his family
have had to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you,'' Thornton said. ``If the Dat Nguyen story doesn't
bring a tear to your eye, you're not breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nguyen family's flight from war-torn Vietnam when his mother
was pregnant with Dat, the youngest of six children, has become
part of the lore surrounding the youngster who once considered
leaving A&AMP;M because of the disappointment of being redshirted his
freshman year. Instead of packing his bags, however, he became one
of the most honored players in A&AMP;M football history.
</P>
<P>
   His unusual strength and drive come from his family and from
within.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are really a big part of what I do, because of the
things they've been through,'' Nguyen said. ``I can never be in the
dumps long regardless of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think back to my parents leaving Vietnam _ not knowing what
to expect, not speaking any English, having five kids _ and it
picks me up and makes me work harder. Everyone in my family \Rtwo
brothers, three sisters\S is having a successful life. That really
drives me.''
</P>
<P>
   He, in turn, has stimulated others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dat has been an inspiration as much as any player I've ever
seen,'' coach R.C. Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   His model permeates every exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasize leadership among other things in Dat's degree
plan,'' said Joe Townsend, associate dean for student development
in the college of agriculture. ``He leads by example. Other
students see the effort he puts out and it affects them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Dat to graduate in 4.5 years is exceptional. Only 22
percent of the students at A&AMP;M graduate in four years, and most of
them are not football players. And he is a fabulous person.
Confident, not cocky. Appreciative of the chance to get an
education. What he tells you, you can take to the bank. And just by
being around him, you wouldn't know \Rhis stature as a player\S.
He's not one who looks for fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen cannot, however, avoid acclaim. He doesn't try.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who doesn't hesitate any time anybody asks him for
an autograph or to pose for a picture,'' tight end Dan Campbell
said. ``He's easily the most recognizable player on the team. But
he's happy to be in the position he's in, to maybe help somebody
out in some small way. He's so humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he carries himself makes some of us a little mad
because he does everything so right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen shrugs and laughs _ which he does often _ when asked
about how he has handled recognition, and the attendant loss of
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes my day when I can put a smile on a kid's face. I'll
go out of my way to do that any day,'' he said. ``Football is going
to end some day. So I don't try to take advantage of the image of
I'm a football player, I'm Dat Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a regular student. One of 100 guys who play on the
football team. One of 46,000 students who go to school here. I'm
just one of everybody. I think one of the reasons I haven't gotten
caught up in all the publicity is that I have my own friends away
from football. I was lucky to see the big picture early. I didn't
lose touch with people. I've gained friends and been able to focus
on every segment of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Nguyen is not one to dismiss what he calls the
roller-coaster ride of his collegiate experience, the places he has
been or the people he has met because of his love of the game of
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every kid in the world would love to trade shoes with
me right now,'' he said. ``I'm one of the lucky ones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
