<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-COLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH'S FIRST IMPRESSION LASTING FOR A&AMP;M RECEIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Chris Cole, prospective Texas A&AMP;M
football signee, gathered his family in the living room to listen
to coach R.C. Slocum's recruiting pitch. But the words never
flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got ready to talk,'' Slocum said, ``but something didn't
smell right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole was the first to spot the problem, which had spread across
the sole of Slocum's shoe. While walking to the door, the A&AMP;M coach
had stepped in an unauthorized deposit left on the lawn by a
passing pooch.
</P>
<P>
   Apologies ensued. Moments later, Slocum was on his knees with a
towel, removing the remnants from the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have really impressed them,'' said Slocum, rolling his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he did. As Slocum scrubbed, Cole said he saw a human
side to the A&AMP;M coach he did not notice in fellow recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Man, he doesn't mind getting dirty. ... That's my
coach, right there,''' said Cole, who has stepped up this season to
become the crunch-time target of the Aggies' passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into a game this week against No. 2 Nebraska (5-0, 1-0
Big 12), Cole has accounted for 59 percent of the receiving yards
and 100 percent of the touchdown catches for the 18th-ranked Aggies
(4-1, 1-0).
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coaches say Cole, whose 23 receptions almost triple the
total of the team's No. 2 pass-catcher (Leroy Hodge with eight),
must continue producing at a high level for the team to have enough
offensive balance to upset the Cornhuskers at 2:30 p.m. tomorrow at
Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is on a roll right now,'' Slocum said. ``The more big
plays you make, the more you expect to make them. It's a cyclical
thing. And we'll need all the big plays we can get against
Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole made three huge ones in a 28-9 victory against North Texas,
hauling in touchdown strikes of 60, 35 and 52 yards. He finished
with career highs of six catches and 174 yards. In the team's 24-21
victory against Kansas last week, Cole grabbed a team-high five
passes for 51 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is the guy A&AMP;M has been looking for since Albert
Connell,'' said quarterback Randy McCown, likening Cole to the
Washington Redskins' receiver who left A&AMP;M in 1996 after averaging
more catches per season (49) than any player in school history.
``All you have to do is throw it somewhere close to him and he'll
go up and get it. He makes big-time catches.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not always been that way. Cole, a junior, grabbed only 13
passes in his first 14 games at A&AMP;M until turning a corner late in
the 1997 season. During the Aggies' final five games, he caught 16
passes for 175 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That triggered an off-season challenge from Steve Kragthorpe,
the Aggies' offensive coordinator who also oversees the team's wide
receivers. Kragthorpe urged Cole to start showing more leadership,
now that he was an upperclassman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hit home with me,'' Cole said. ``Last year, I was just a
kid running around out there. Now, I'm more focused and my
confidence has grown. I want to be the guy we look for on third
down. I want to be the guy who makes things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole (6-foot, 186 pounds) has become all of that, and more, to
the Aggies' passing game. Of the team's 58 completions, 23 have
gone to Cole. Of the 656 passing yards, 387 belong to Cole. His
average of 16.8 yards per catch is more than five yards better than
the team mark (11.3).
</P>
<P>
   Most important, tailback Dante Hall sees a correlation between
Cole's grabbing three touchdown passes on Sept. 26 against North
Texas and the Aggies' ground game producing its first 100-yard
rusher the next week against Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris was a huge factor in that,'' said Hall, who romped for
177 yards and three touchdowns against the Jayhawks. ``He can
stretch a defense. People know if they crowd the line to stop the
run, he can make them pay.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they soil his carpet accidentally, Cole holds no grudges.
Just ask R.C. Slocum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
