<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN DELAYS, SCATTERED CROWDS JUST TIP OF GAME 1 ICEBERG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Winning and losing in the playoffs, that's what
baseball should be all about, not some pursuit of a glamorous
record.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire knew that as well as anybody when he said over and
over he envied Sammy Sosa for being in a position to make the
playoffs with the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the Houston Astros acquired Randy Johnson on
July 31, it was obvious the National League playoffs would be
something special and that's proved true, especially after the San
Diego Padres' thrilling 3-2, 10-inning victory against the Atlanta
Braves that ran into early yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
   And it's only getting started now that the Braves face the
sobering reality of being upset in the National League Championship
Series for the second consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that will grab some people's attention around here.
Wednesday night's announced crowd of 42,117 _ 9,000 short of a
sellout _ was the smallest in Braves postseason history, a sure
sign Atlanta's success is starting to be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Many more thousands refused to sit through the two-hour rain
delay. When Game 1 finally started at 10:16 p.m. Atlanta time, too
much of the upper deck at Turner Field was empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rain took something away from the crowd,'' Braves
third baseman Chipper Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more dismaying was Ted Turner and Jane Fonda, not to
mention Jimmy and Rosalyn Carter _ familiar figures here come
playoff time _ were nowhere to be seen. The Los Angeles Lakers'
Shaquille O'Neal showed up, but what else does he have to do
besides walk a picket line?
</P>
<P>
   Those who stayed home to agonize over the NBA lockout missed a
superb baseball game, starting with a brilliant seven-inning
pitching duel between the Braves' John Smoltz and the Padres' Andy
Ashby.
</P>
<P>
   But that was only a tasty appetizer, and by the time the game
was over, almost everybody had forgotten about Braves right fielder
Michael Tucker's terrific catch at the warning track to take a
fifth-inning, two-run double away from Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   More memorable was Ruben Rivera's eighth-inning exploits after a
leadoff double against Smoltz. He raced to third on Ken Caminiti's
fly ball to right-center, just beating center fielder Andruw Jones'
throw with a headfirst slide.
</P>
<P>
   He then scored the go-ahead run on Jim Leyritz's one-hop
grounder to the left of the mound. Reliever Dennis Martinez looked
Rivera back to third, then lobbed a throw over to first. Rivera
broke for home, first baseman Andres Galarraga came off the bag to
take the throw, then threw wildly to the plate, allowing the run to
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make a perfect throw and I hurried it,''
Galarraga said in the gloomy Braves clubhouse afterward.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been enough, but the Braves rallied in the
ninth against Padres closer Trevor Hoffman, who was almost
unbeatable during the regular season. Andruw Jones' sacrifice fly
made it a 2-all game.
</P>
<P>
   But the 20,000 or so fans who stuck around to the end watched in
horror as Caminiti ruined the Braves' comeback with a home run off
reliever Kerry Ligtenberg in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Much was made before the series about the matchup of Hoffman vs.
Ligtenberg, but, as Hoffman said, ``We didn't look good, that's for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg's performance earned him a place of honor in Braves
postseason history. For all the praise heaped on Atlanta's starting
pitching, Braves fans agonize more over a list of relievers who
have given up crucial home runs in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   There was Charlie Leibrandt giving up an 11th-inning home run to
Minnesota's Kirby Puckett in Game 6 of the 1991 World Series, and
Jeff Reardon, who gave up Ed Sprague's game-winning home run for
the Toronto Blue Jays in Game 2 of the 1992 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Mark Wohlers, a particular favorite here. He
allowed a critical home run to Lenny Dykstra in the 1993 NLCS and
the infamous three-run shot to Leyritz in the Game 4 loss to the
New York Yankees in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Ligtenberg threw great, except for one pitch,''
Braves manager Bobby Cox said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's weak throw on Leyritz's ball was a bigger sin, just
not as spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Those who showed up and stayed up Wednesday night will debate
that well into the off-season. But there will be more to come.
</P>
<P>
   Much more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
