<HEADLINE>
BIG 12 HIRES WEIBERG AS COMMISSIONER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Kevin Weiberg, with his Midwestern roots and experience
with one of the nation's top conferences, was chosen as the Big 12
Conference's new commissioner yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Weiberg, deputy commissioner of the Big Ten Conference, was the
unanimous selection of the Big 12's presidents who met here
yesterday. He had his final interview with the presidents yesterday
morning and was given the job later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin was the best person for the job,'' said Kansas
Chancellor Dr. Robert Hemenway, chair of the presidents. ``Part of
the value of his experience is that he has been with a very
successful conference. Obviously, that's attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a very clear vision and very innovative ideas for the
conference going into the next century. He's extremely articulate.
He's relatively young and brings a certain degree of youth and
vigor to the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiberg and Virginia athletic director Terry Holland were the
two finalists interviewed by the presidents. Ohio Valley
commissioner Dan Beebe and Sun Belt commissioner Craig Thompson
were interviewed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Weiberg agreed to a three-year contract and is scheduled to
begin in early January. Hemenway declined to discuss the financial
terms, but said Weiberg would be paid a salary commensurate with
commissioners of the other major conferences. Former Big 12
commissioner Steve Hatchell, who resigned in April, earned $212,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Weiberg, 42, has spent nine years with the Big Ten Conference.
He was born in Anthony, Kan., attended college at Kansas State and
Western Illinois University and has worked at Wichita State and
Maryland before joining the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin has been here nine years, and there were few things I
didn't do without his counsel,'' Big Ten commissioner Jim Delany
said. ``He's been part of our operations, planning and execution
and I think we've been pretty successful. It's a great hire for the
Big 12.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
