<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DOAK-MEMORIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER'S SPIRIT, DECENCY LAUDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For one final moment, the young boy who grew up in
Highland Park and became a national football legend came back home
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it must have seemed to an estimated 900 friends and
admirers who filled Highland Park Presbyterian Church to pay final
tribute to Doak Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, 71, the former SMU All-American and Pro Football Hall of
Fame inductee, died Sept. 27 of complications from a January skiing
accident that left him paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   And when the memorial service was over, old friend and teammate
Raleigh Blakely smiled and posed a simple question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you suppose it is that after 50 years, so many people
still care about Doak Walker?'' Blakely said.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus was that the feeling for Walker wasn't for a guy
who scored a lot of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps best expressed in a poem sent by another former
teammate, Kyle Rote, which spoke of ``the seeds of decency you have
sown throughout your life ...''
</P>
<P>
   It was a theme that predominated eulogies delivered by
sportscaster Verne Lundquist, family friend Rod Hanna and former
SMU Vice President Bill Lively, one of the founders of the Doak
Walker Award.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the stage near the pulpit were two objects
illustrative of Walker's life _ his 1948 Heisman Trophy and a
cowboy hat.
</P>
<P>
   Glancing down, Lundquist said, ``This is really more about the
hat than the award.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna, a resident of Steamboat Springs, Colo., read a few of the
6,000 faxes and telegrams that poured into the hospital after
Walker's injury. ``The Doak we knew seemed almost untouched by fame
or celebrity,'' he said. ``Human relationships meant more to him
than awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Lundquist recalled that the last time he saw Walker, during the
summer, he was attending a friend's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was one of his closest friends, and Doak insisted on
attending the funeral, despite his own problems,'' Lundquist said.
``They buried her on her ranch ... and the last time I saw Doak, he
was sitting in his wheelchair in the shade of a barn, paying his
last respects to a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Lively spoke of how the man who had once inspired a generation
as ``an All-American hero'' was equally inspiring during his final
months, never losing ``the indomitable spirit that characterized
his life.''
</P>
<P>
   As friends including Tom Landry, Darrell Royal, John David Crow
and David McWilliams filed out of the church, Kansas City Chiefs
owner Lamar Hunt recalled that he was once ``just one of those kids
who wanted to grow up and wear No. 37 and be like Doak Walker.''
</P>
<P>
   For all concerned, the mood of the day was perhaps best
characterized by one of the faxes Hanna read, which said simply:
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember ... and I thank you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
