</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' ROAD IS LONG, INCLUDES MANY MILES OF EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Mention the negative side of his reputation, the
stuff about being selfish or locker-room trouble, and Brett Hull
smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things don't bother me,'' he said yesterday at
StarCenter. ``I know me, and I know where those lies came from, and
I know they're not true.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the mini-war Hull once had with Mike Keenan, his
former coach in St. Louis, there is also another NHL mark against
Mr. Hull's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all my stigmas,'' he said, flashing a slow grin, ``there is
one I can't defend. Eleven years in the league and I've never been
on a \RStanley Cup\S winner. For that one, I have no argument.''
</P>
<P>
   But through free agency last summer, has Hull now found a
solution to that one ``problem''?
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to a great city, to play for a class
organization,'' he answered. ``But as much as anything, I wanted to
be here because you can have the best of everything, plus, be on a
team that can win the Stanley Cup. What more can you ask for in
this business?''
</P>
<P>
   Things have moved so rapidly in five seasons. It was 1993, when
out of nowhere _ meaning Minnesota _ a National Hockey League team
showed up on our unsuspecting doorstep. Strangers from Zamboniville
had entered the Chicken-Fried Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 20 years old at the time,'' said defenseman Richard
Matvichuk, ``and I can remember wondering what the heck was going
to happen to us. We didn't know anybody, and no one knew us. None
of us had any idea if this would work or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny now, because players on other teams are always
telling me how I'm lucky to be playing in one of the premier places
in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   And a mere five years later, here's a recognized superstar like
Hull showing up in Dallas after deciding the Stars are his Stanley
Cup ride.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations runneth over.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a hockey publication in North America, or a Las
Vegas odds board, that doesn't list the Stars as either the best
team, or second best to Detroit, in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be the club that has everything, including more
scoring power with Hull and, yes, finally a bona fide alley fighter
in newcomer Brent Severyn. Little does Severyn know how popular
he's about to become in all local precincts. As the geeky hockey
purists scoff, the real people will love Severyn just as they once
did Shane Churla.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Nieuwendyk is healthy again _ give that a couple of
weeks _ then all pieces will be in place. And the first of many
Reunion Arena sellouts will be tomorrow night when Buffalo visits
for the regular-season opener.
</P>
<P>
   So on the eve of the much anticipated moment, what words of
coaching wisdom did Ken Hitchcock have?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget to enjoy the scenery,'' was Hitchcock's answer
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The what?
</P>
<P>
   ``A long road begins Saturday, a road that will have a lot of
scenic stops along the way, and some ugly sights, too,'' said
Hitchcock. ``Travel each mile one at a time, and be sure to
appreciate the scenic view while also keeping the ugly things in
proper perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation _ don't rush the playoffs. Take nothing for granted
in six months of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   And Hitchcock also doesn't mind stressing that point. For
example:
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk said on a radio talk show earlier this week, ``Nothing
else matters except winning the Stanley Cup. That's the only
objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Matvichuk countered with, ``everything I said on the
radio the other night _ that's off the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Those comments went out on 50,000 watts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' answered Matvichuk, laughing, ``it's off the record
for newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Hitchcock happened to be listening to the radio that night.
Yes, he and Matvichuk talked the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point is that for now we really can't control that part of
our destiny,'' Hitchcock said. ``Injuries change so much, as we
found out with Joe \RNieuwendyk\S in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to approach this is to be thankful that we are
one of several teams that appear to have the best chance to
contend. And then, as a united hockey club, we have to go out and
prove ourselves night after night, and also hope to have some luck
in certain areas, such as injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the route, the road to the Stanley Cup starts tomorrow
night. And so do miles and miles of expectations in what is now a
hockey town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
