<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CRIME-640&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRIME AND PUNISHMENT' PUTS NBC ON THE HIGH ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times and channels.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago it was ``Mother May I Sleep With Danger,'' ``Dead
Eyes,'' ``She Cried No'' and too much Tiffani-Amber Thiessen.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, it's Patrick Dempsey (``Can't Buy Me Love'') and
Oscar winner Ben Kingsley in Fyodor Dostoyevsky's ``Crime and
Punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Change has come to the NBC movie division.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking it was a supernetwork that made its own rules, NBC got
arrogant a few years ago and committed grievous crimes against the
viewing public.
</P>
<P>
   But it wanted to get caught, and it was. NBC confessed,
admitting that its movies weren't up to snuff. It took its
punishment and now is attempting a redemptive flood of high-quality
TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is Raskolnikov, the tortured protagonist of ``Crime and
Punishment.'' Maybe not tortured, exactly. The comparison goes only
so far. Raskolnikov had a conscience. NBC merely follows the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers were encouraging for ``Gulliver's Travels'' and
``The Odyssey,'' so the NBC moviemakers are trying their luck with
Dostoyevsky and, next month, a spruced-up version of Shakespeare's
``The Tempest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime and Punishment'' figured to be the most daunting
challenge of the bunch. It's a dense novel in which the heady
action is just that _ heady. Most of what counts takes place
between Raskolnikov's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Raskolnikov (Dempsey) is an impoverished student in St.
Petersburg whose notion that he is extraordinary and immune to
society's laws leads to his murdering a repulsive pawnbroker and
the pawnbroker's sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not ashamed of what I have done,'' Raskolnikov tells
himself afterward. ``I will not let guilt betray me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley is Porfiry, the police investigator, a role slightly
inflated from the book. French actress Julie Delpy is Sonia, a
prostitute who becomes a sort of redemptive figure for Raskolnikov.
</P>
<P>
   The first piece of disappointing news, and it's not wholly
disappointing, is that no TV movie is going to re-create the book's
pungent claustrophobia. Joseph Sargent, who directed from a script
by David Stevens, probably felt compelled to give the movie
breathing space. The result is a touch of Classics Illustrated
airiness.
</P>
<P>
   And second, Dempsey can't bring a virtually impossible screen
role to full boil. To his credit, he has the feel of the classic
Raskolnikov _ moody, cold and prideful, yet kindly at heart. Still,
Raskolnikov is a terrifically complicated character whose motives
aren't easily conveyed. Dempsey seems to drag us across the
emotional map without really settling on Raskolnikov's
psychological terrain.
</P>
<P>
   But there are overriding reasons to appreciate ``Crime and
Punishment.'' For one thing, it's beautifully filmed in Hungary,
which seems to have become a kind of Hollywood East. (The accented
English in the film is more influenced by Hungarian than by
Russian.)
</P>
<P>
   For another, the supporting roles are wonderfully cast _ not
with familiar TV names but with the right actors for the parts.
Richard Bremmer, for one, is exactly right as Arkady Svidrigailov,
the self-serving sensualist who lusts for Raskolnikov's sister,
Dounia (Lili Horvath).
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the movie is an honest shot at a classic novel. The
makers of this movie resist the temptation to reduce the story to a
cat-and-mouse game between Raskolnikov and Porfiry, killer and cop.
</P>
<P>
   That tack has been taken before, but it's not Dostoyevsky. His
is a tale of transgression _ an individual stepping outside the
circle of humanity, suffering the consequences and finding
regeneration.
</P>
<P>
   The movie concludes sentimentally, but still with enough power
to reward viewers. I do hope the audience is there. This is an
effort to do well by doing good, a concept the TV networks sorely
need to relearn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ Mike Wallace and CBS News probably were trying to do good 21
years ago when ``The Homosexuals'' aired as a groundbreaking TV
documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Seen today, it's a mishmash of bad science and bad sociology,
and a reminder of how far we have (or in some cases haven't)
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   The program, controversial in 1967, will be shown twice Saturday
on the CBS Eye on People cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's a certain ``Reefer Madness'' hilarity in hearing
psychiatrists spew theories, later discredited, about
homosexuality. But the pain inflicted by those theories, and by the
majority's censure of homosexuality, is achingly apparent, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch out for shows called ``The Secret Life of (Whatever).''
Usually the ensuing ``secrets'' would be news only to Martians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Life of Cats,'' a ``National Geographic Explorer''
installment (Sunday on TBS) is full of such secrets as the
revelations that cats are night hunters and that they have amazing
senses of balance.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the program has a purpose _ to show that cats are
capable of an astonishing amount of damage to birds and small
mammals, and should be neutered and controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers for a good purpose, but hiss to National Geographic for
being uncharacteristically disingenuous.
</P>
