<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-INSURANCEDEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insurance firms continue fight for records secrecy
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN,Texas _ Texas insurance companies are returning to court
today to maintain the secrecy of reports that show where they have
sold and canceled policies.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, according to a lawmaker and a consumer advocate
trying to get them, would prove insurers have rules and guidelines
that illegally prevent poorer and minority Texans from getting
affordable insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Reeves, an attorney for State Farm insurance, today will
ask state District Judge Suzanne Covington to issue a temporary
restraining order preventing the consumer advocate, Birny Birnbaum,
from getting the reports.
</P>
<P>
   State courts have already deemed the reports secret. But under a
court order and state law, legislators have access to confidential
information as long as they and their staffs sign confidentiality
statements and use the information for ``legislative purposes''
only.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lon Burnam, D-Fort Worth, last month asked the Texas
Department of Insurance to give him the so-called quarterly market
reports showing where, by ZIP code, insurers have sold and canceled
policies. Burnam has said he's going to hire Birnbaum, a former
insurance department official, to help analyze the complex reports.
That's sparked a great uproar from insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the capability to analyze that,'' Burnam said
Thursday. He said the court action against Birnbaum ``interferes
with my ability to do my job and the right of my constituents to
have me analyze this data.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnam said he has sought other people with the expertise to
deal with the data but has found no real options.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said the court action is being filed on behalf of a
number insurer companies and trade groups.
</P>
<P>
   She added that as an employee of the insurance department,
Birnbaum improperly released similarly secret company records _ a
charge he has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves would not say insurers are concerned Birnbaum would
illegally release the ZIP code information, but said courts have
ruled the information secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the business of telling Representative Burnam or
any lawmaker who they can hire. Our concern is that Mr. Birnbaum is
making an effort to circumvent a court ruling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum said he is not trying to get around the court order.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum also said he did not spark Burnam's interest in the
records, but has agreed to help review the data.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one who is as knowledgable about it as I am,''
Birnbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one else who can help a legislator, who can
develop the type of analysis and the legislation he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-08-98 2137E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
