A7338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-CARTER-COX     10-08 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-CARTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No qualms for Quincy Carter
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS _ It's hard to imagine where the University of Georgia's
football team would be without Quincy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it's tough to envision where Auburn and
Tennessee might be had the Bulldogs' sensational freshman
quarterback stuck with his original plan.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Carter, then a senior All-American at state
champion Southwest DeKalb High, gave Auburn coach Terry Bowden a
private commitment to play for the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hush-hush deal,'' Carter says.
</P>
<P>
   The deal wasn't hush-hush enough, however. Tee Martin, another
highly regarded quarterback considering Auburn, heard about it. He
spurned the Tigers and committed to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, when Carter switched to Georgia Tech, Auburn was
left with the lesser regarded Ben Leard of Hartwell.
</P>
<P>
   A pattern of changing plans had begun. Carter never arrived on
the Georgia Tech campus, signing a minor-league baseball contract
with the Chicago Cubs that included a no-football clause for four
years.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in the minor leagues, Carter was ready to return
to football last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I was thinking about football,'' Carter said. ``My
full concentration was supposed to be on baseball, but I would be
at the plate thinking about third down. It was a little difficult
for me. I knew for me to be a better baseball player, football had
to be in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, after Carter struggled in his second year of minor
league ball, his agent, Lonnie Cooper of Atlanta, persuaded the
Cubs to allow the outfielder to play both sports. Carter says he
didn't want to return to Georgia Tech, citing a soured relationship
with Yellow Jackets coach George O'Leary and the fact that Joe
Hamilton had established himself as the starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   So Carter contacted three schools.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke with Tennessee offensive coordinator David Cutcliffe,
but the Vols already considered Martin the heir apparent to Peyton
Manning.
</P>
<P>
   He called Florida State offensive coordinator Mark Richt, who
had Dan Kendra and Chris Weinke in the Seminoles' plans.
</P>
<P>
   And he called Jim Donnan at Georgia, where starter Mike Bobo was
about to complete his eligibility and contender Daniel Cobb's
health was in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``After talking with Coach Donnan, I knew where I wanted to
go,'' Carter said. ``It was pretty evident where I was going. It
wasn't a big recruiting deal or anything. I just felt most
comfortable at Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Four games into this season, Carter is a comfortable fit for the
Bulldogs, who are 4-0 and ranked seventh entering Saturday's SEC
showdown against No. 4 Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan had believed this might be a rebuilding year for the
Dogs. But Carter's early play has elevated hopes in Athens, so much
so that Georgia could make a serious run at its first SEC title
since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't factor in how good Quincy was going to play,'' Donnan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter leads the SEC and is third nationally in passing
efficiency. He has thrown for 957 yards and six touchdowns with
only one interception and a 71 percent completion rate. He's also
the team's third-leading rusher with 111 yards and two scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way my coaches presented the offense to me _ they kind of
spoon-fed it to me little by little each week _ was great for me,''
Carter said. ``But I'm in awe by it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter didn't seem in awe during his biggest test _ a date at
No. 6 LSU last week. He threw for 318 yards and two touchdowns on
27-of-34 passing
</P>
<P>
   ``God has given me a lot,'' he said. ``I have innate, God-given
talent. But I can't really account for this. ... I couldn't have
imagined being the starting quarterback at Georgia (this season).''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who turns 21 on Tuesday, isn't your typical freshman. He
immediately took a leadership role on the team. He directs a Bible
study every Tuesday in his dormitory room at Georgia's McWhorter
Hall. And he's taking classes for the first time in three years,
while juggling practice and media interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everything goes much faster now,'' Carter said.
``I'm always on the go, whether it's watching film, going to class
or studying. My leisure time is pretty much gone. But it's better
than sitting on the couch for six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Success in football wasn't supposed to come this fast for
Carter, who hadn't played competitively since 1995. He couldn't
practice at Georgia last spring because of restrictions placed on
his release from Georgia Tech. Carter wasn't named the Bulldogs'
starter until three days before the Sept. 5 opener against Kent,
although Donnan had circled his name as early as last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected him to play good,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's teammates don't seem too surprised either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees things so well,'' safety Kirby Smart said. ``I think
he can see people out of the back of his head. He just dodges and
weaves and creates. He's a creator.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
