<HEADER>
A7339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ATL-GASCENE-COX     10-08 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ATL-GASCENE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia won't stay normal with Vols coming to town
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. - From all outward appearances Athens has been close
to normal all week.
</P>
<P>
   But starting as early as sundown today, it wouldn't dare to
pretend normalcy. Nonchalance will give way to football fanaticism.
The sane and nonplussed will stay inside their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The campers and RVs will begin arriving and setting up in the
huge parking lot just off Stegeman Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will have readied its facilities for its Game Day
production at the Tate Student Center.
</P>
<P>
   The pubs and bars and restaurants in town will be hopping - some
adding extra staff to handle the extra crowds expected this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Georgia-Tennessee game is the best and biggest
excuse partiers have had here recently to let it fly. There is no
reason to suspect they will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game where business booms,'' said Jamie
Lotfon, owner of three Locos pubs/restaurants in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   It's his location off Baxter Street just up from several UGA
dorms that will probably create enough mass to form a small star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have up to 20 people working there,'' said
Lofton. ``We'll open at 10 and close at 2 a.m. We have ordered as
much (food and beer) as we can put in the coolers and hope it lasts
through the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   On most days, a bar keep and a couple of waitresses are at the
location off Baxter Street that is popular with locals as well as
students.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton said teams like Tennessee are especially good for
business because a) Many Vols fans live within driving distance and
2) as students they either had friends at UGA or visited here and
know the layout of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember three or four years ago our place would be
practically dead on Saturday night even with a home game. That's
changed, especially with the success of the team. We expect a crush
all weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown at the upscale Harry Bissett's New Orleans Cafe &AMP;
Oyster Bar the crush is expected and the excitement building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened in1986 and the only thing that compares to this
would be the year Florida came here (1995). It's going to be crazy
here,'' said manager Jim White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure that around about 7 o'clock, the wait for a table
will be about an hour and, people will wait,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   White said his experience has been that in addition to the 9,500
Tennessee fans and the Georgia fans who will get into 86,117 seat
Sanford Stadium there will be the hundreds, perhaps thousand who
will come to Athens with hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised how many people will come here hoping to
get a ticket and how many people will come here just to be in
Athens for this game. They'll sit in a bar and watch it on
television.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic activity level, which is going to be a plus no
matter who wins, will gather steam as the night wears on if the
Bulldogs win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, if Georgia wins Georgia fans will be partying all
night. They won't care how much they are spending. If they lose,
Georgia fans tend to be more somber, spend less. Of course,
Tennessee fans, if they win, will want to hang around and yell,''
said White, who figures to be in a no-lose situation.
</P>
<P>
   Art Jackson, Director of the Downtown Development Authority,
said the game time and status of both teams is a merchant's dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that both teams are so good means even if the weather
was bad, the stands would be full. But the weather is supposed to
be good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game time (3:30) is perfect for merchants. They do not
like like 12 or 1 (p.m.) starts. They know people will come early
to park...then shop, eat and then go to the game. ``
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia-Tennessee game, said Jackson, is becoming a cash cow
for downtown Athens. He reports that The Grill, a 24-hour
restaurant on College Avenue, had its highest revenue date ever for
the Tennessee game two years ago. Only the free outdoor concert by
Widespread Panic last spring came close.
</P>
<P>
   The UGA Athletic offices have been swamped by callers all week.
Media request for press box space and interviews with athletes and
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Associate Director of Athletics Claude Felton said he's still
working on ways to accommodate the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for bar stools right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyoming game attracted ``about 180 to 200'' total press
including radio, TV, still photographers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   So far this week, Felton has a CBS crew of 75, ESPN Game Day
crew of 40 and 128 TV and still photographers. On top
</P>
<P>
   of that will be 200 newspaper and magazine reporters.
</P>
<P>
   This little SEC tuggle is attracting reporters from: Sports
Illustrated, USA Today, The New York Times, New York Post and New
York Daily News, the Washington Post, Boston Globe, Chicago
Tribune, Los Angeles Times, Houston Chronicle and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yea, tickets. The fact is that this game as been a
sellout since last March, according to UGA Assistant Athletic
Director Freddie Jones. But that hasn't stopped people from
calling, trying, begging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been here 16 years and the only thing that comes close
is the year Florida played here (1995). It's been unbelievable.
Everyone wants tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if a game has been sold out for months, who are these
people calling? People who just now got interested and didn't know
any better?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say 90 percent of the calls we get are from people who
already have tickets but want one for a friend or relative.
Businesses call. Some elected officials. They know the situation. I
guess they feel they have to make that one last try. The fact is
there are none. Don't get me wrong. This is a great siutuation to
have. I hope it's like that for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the other approach - street capitalism, where
opportunists welcome the inquiries of the desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Some are ``letting `` their tickets go for as little as $75
each. There are actually people willing to pay $150 for a ticket.
Some say the value per ticket is even higher. The practice of
scalping is against the law.
</P>
<P>
   On campus Thursday afternoon, junior Brian Williby, a
21-year-old from Savannah, said there's ``no way I would sell my
ticket. But I know two peope who sold their's for $80 each.''
Wiliby said the two had a commitment out of town this weekend,
otherwise they'd be at the game..
</P>
<P>
   At the Tate Student Center handwritten posters showed potential
commerce. Students were making their tickets available to ``best
offer.'' Some were willling to trade their Tennessee tickets for
Florida tickets.Scalping brings up the caveats of buying from
anyone other that the UGA ticket office. There are some who
probably remember all too well buying counterfeit tickets to last
year's Auburn game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say to anyone that if you buy from anyone other than us,
you are taking a chance,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The first big risk is buying a student ticket. Jones said a
person might possibly slip in, but people at the gate are going to
ask to see a student ID. The student ticket is distinct from the
nonstudent ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Georgia officials have pretty much undercut
counterfeit tickets although it's possible someone may try that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hologram on this year's ticket that is darn near
impossible to duplicate. The 'Georgia' on the ticket is a hologram.
We've tried to copy it three different ways and we couldn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are buying on the street, look at the ticket carefully
before handing over any cash.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
