<SLUG> BC-FBC-ATL-GTRAIL-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Ticket sales remain concern for Bourne
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA TECH NOTEBOOK
</P>
<P>
   CARROLL ROGERS
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bourne, Tech's associate athletics director in charge of
ticketing, is not pretending to be happy with the announced
attendance of 35,724 at last week's Duke game at Bobby Dodd
Stadium. He's just not especially surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we'd be between 35,000 and 40,000,'' Bourne said.
``When you have 16,000 season tickets, you're relying on a strong
walk-up gate (and) a lot of factors affect that _ the weather, the
time of day. I think (against Duke) it was time of day. Atlanta is
a difficult market (for) a noon game, we have a lot of competition,
people are tied up in a lot of events, whether it's ALTA or youth
sports programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I want it to be more? Sure. Do I want to find a way to
fill the stands? That's priority No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech drew even less for Duke than for non-ACC games against New
Mexico State (36,382) and Boston College (38,229), when Tech
students weren't in school yet. Take the 8,000 student tickets out
of the Duke total, and the crowd was 27,724.
</P>
<P>
   Tech has done some ``little things'' to help attract fans in the
last year. Last season TVs were installed under the East stands for
fans in the upper part of the lower level to get a better look at
the entire field. This season Papa John's pizza was brought in.
Tech uses more venders selling in the stands and more concession
stand areas.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the Duke attendance, the little things aren't
making much of a difference. But Bourne said it's too soon to tell,
adding ``A good test will be Wake Forest (Nov. 21).''
</P>
<P>
   That will be Tech's final home game of the season. There are
several thousand tickets left for next week's Virginia game, which
is usually a good draw, and it's homecoming. The Florida State game
on Oct. 24 has been sold out since the summer; many of those
tickets are bought by FSU fans in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman tackles
</P>
<P>
   After three years of Keith Brooking and Ron Rogers topping
Tech's tackle list, it's odd to see free safety Travares Tillman's
name at the top. He's leading the Yellow Jackets with 27 tackles.
Coach George O'Leary isn't concerned though that a member of the
secondary is the top tackler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travares Tillman is a very, very good football player,''
O'Leary said. ``I hope he's involved in a lot of tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a sign that the defense is reaching its goal of
spreading around the responsibility. Bunched right near Tillman are
Jason Bostic (23), Delaunta Cameron (23), Matt Miller (22), Matt
Uremovich (21) and Jesse Tarplin (19).
</P>
<P>
   New-look defensive fronts
</P>
<P>
   For the last two games, Tech has been using some sets with three
down linemen to go along with its four-linemen base defense and the
occasional five-linemen sets. Defensive coordinator Randy Edsall
said it's part of the plan to keep offenses off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take an aggressive approach on defense,'' Edsall
said. ``There are certain things you can do to create problems for
an offense in their blocking schemes. . . . We're trying to get the
most out of our talent .
</P>
<P>
   Two steps away
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Rogers needs two yards rushing to reach the 1,000-yard
mark for his career. He's trying to join Charles Wiley (1,389) to
give the Jackets two 1,000-yard teammates since William Bell and
Jimy Lincoln in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
