<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-POLL-ART-470(2     10-08 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-POLL-ART-470(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the president.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Vallone has little money left for that or any other message.
His campaign treasury reported having less than $250,000 last week,
compared with more than $9 million for Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The poll suggests the possibility of a landslide for Pataki,
which he and his aides hope might propel him into contention for
national office in 2000. They are acutely aware that a lopsided
victory in a state where Democrats outnumber Republicans 3-to-2
would raise Pataki's stature within the national Republican Party.
Only 1 in 5 New Yorkers said they would like to see him run for
president or vice president, however.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York City, usually the safest of havens for
Democrats, the governor is running virtually even with his
challenger, at 36 percent to 39 percent for Vallone. Four years
ago, he got just 27 percent of the city vote against Gov. Mario
Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   In the downstate suburbs, which have been the swing vote in
recent elections, Pataki holds a 5-to-2 lead. And upstate, the core
of his support, he outpolls the Democrat by 5-to-1. Upstate,
Golisano runs even with Vallone, at 11 percent apiece, while Ms.
McCaughey Ross has 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Pataki, a state senator, ran as the anti-Cuomo,
revealing little about himself other than his intention to cut
taxes and enact the death penalty, and relying on voters'
disaffection with Cuomo after 12 years. Even as he was winning the
race, many people had little impression of the Republican, or even
had a negative one. His image suffered from his close association
with D'Amato, who had plucked him out of obscurity to be the
Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year in office _ and, to a lesser degree, his
second _ Pataki pushed through unpopular budget cuts in areas like
health care, education and mass transit. Unions and Democrats waged
an intense public-relations campaign against him, including
broadcast advertisements likening him to Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, Pataki has done a remarkable job of washing away
those impressions. He has replaced them with a warmer image of
himself, built on the 1996 environmental bond act, tax cuts, large
increases in state spending in the last two years and a
multimillion-dollar advertising campaign this year that has
portrayed him as likable, nonpartisan and trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that nearly as many New Yorkers now judge Pataki
to be moderate as consider him conservative, and 1 in 8 actually
regards him as liberal.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1994, two weeks before he was elected, just 18
percent of registered voters had a favorable impression of Pataki.
In April 1995, three months after he took office, 27 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   But in this most recent poll, 46 percent viewed him favorably
and, perhaps more striking, just 18 percent viewed him unfavorably.
Sixty-three percent of registered voters said they approved of
Pataki's performance as governor.
</P>
<P>
   He even trumps Vallone on a question on which Democrats usually
prevail. Sixty-one percent of voters said Pataki ``cares about the
needs and problems of people'' like them, up from 40 percent in
April 1995, compared with 37 percent who said Vallone cares about
them.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone's troubles are reflected by Mary Hossman, 60, of
Woodside, Queens, one of the people surveyed. She has friends in
common with Vallone and praises the work he has done in city
government. A Democrat, she plans to vote for her party's nominee
for the Senate, Rep. Charles Schumer, in his bid to unseat D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   But she also intends to vote for Pataki. ``Originally I was
voting for him because of the death penalty,'' she said in a
follow-up interview. ``That made me take interest in him in 1994.
Then I just think he did a really good job. The economy is better
and the general quality of life is better.''
</P>
<P>
   The challengers in the gubernatorial race point to evidence that
beyond Wall Street, the state's economy lags well behind the
national boom, and complain that Pataki has somehow fooled people
into believing that New York is doing better than it is.
</P>
<P>
   The poll suggests that New Yorkers know their state's problems
but do not blame the governor. While two-thirds of New Yorkers
described the state's economy as ``fairly good,'' just 9 percent
rated it as ``very good.'' Twenty-two percent of New Yorkers judged
the state's economy as ``fairly bad'' or ``very bad.'' That
compared with a Times/CBS News national poll taken in August that
showed 61 percent of Americans rate the national economy as
``fairly good,'' 25 percent said it was ``very good'' and 12
percent said it was fairly or very bad.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's experience mirrors that of Cuomo, who was first elected
governor in 1982 and won re-election in a landslide in 1986. Each
man was first elected in a tight contest that reflected stark
regional divisions, took office in the aftermath of a recession,
and then benefited from a strong economy and greatly broadened his
base of support in his first terms.
</P>
</TEXT>
