<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GATECH-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Claybrooks boosts defense
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defensive end Felipe Claybrooks is about the last player on
Georgia Tech roster you'd expect not to have a signature post-big
play celebration.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was on Saturday against Duke, the always flamboyant
Claybrooks, sacking the Duke quarterback and looking confused. He
took a few high steps around the backfield and also took a moment
to look for somebody to hug or something to do to express his
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Claybrooks is Georgia Tech's emotional evangelist, the one who's
up, whether it's on the scout field, during a scrimmage, or on the
sideline in a game. As he describes it, he's ``off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   But with his performance against Duke, in which he came off the
bench for a pair of sacks, seven tackles and a pass breakup, he was
the one needing some direction in cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how to celebrate,'' Claybrooks said. ``One day
I'll have something patented for Felipe Claybrooks. It'll look a
lot better. All I could do was jump around.''
</P>
<P>
   Claybrooks is one of the primary beneficiaries of Tech's new
rotating defensive front, where being on the third team doesn't
guarantee there will be no playing time. In the process, he's
giving this team more than just an emotional boost.
</P>
<P>
   The redshirt sophomore started out this season as a second-team
defensive end. He sprained his ankle in the Boston College game.
That week Nate Stimson was moved from tackle to end, dropping
Roderrick Roberts to second-team end and Claybrooks to third
string. But after a talk with defensive line coach Lance Thompson,
Claybrooks, one of Tech's best pass rushers, was re-assured: get
healthy, work hard and you'll play. That's also about the time
coaches loosened their grip on defensive line substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really afraid of not playing,'' Claybrooks said. ``I'm
more worried about not playing how I'm capable of. When you come
off a game like this, they know you can do it. Now you have to
continue to perform and excel.''
</P>
<P>
   Claybrooks had gotten only five snaps against Boston College and
didn't play in the New Mexico State game because of his ankle. He
played 15 snaps against North Carolina, had two tackles and drew a
holding penalty. Against Duke, he played 41 snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has to work on his run game and controlling the point
of attack,'' Tech coach George O'Leary said. ``But I see him
getting better and better. I think he played the best of the lot
Saturday against Duke. As he plays more and more, he could end up
pushing someone for a starting job.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his enthusiasm, O'Leary and the coaches like it, as long
as it's not unsportsmanlike. It's a good thing because for
Claybrooks it would be hard to contain, this enthusiasm which might
be hereditary.
</P>
<P>
   Claybrooks was born to Phyllis Person, who named her second son
for Felipe Alou, her favorite Atlanta Brave, and admittedly cried
like a baby when the Braves lost in the 1992 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   She had her hands full with Claybrooks as a youngster, when he
would used his energy to aggravate his classmates, his brother and
his mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little hyper during elementary school,'' Phyllis
Person said. ``I had to go to a lot of meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time he got into football and basketball, Claybrooks
had learned how to channel his energy and share it with his
teammates. He once managed to bring an entire gym full of people to
their feet playing basketball his junior year at Decatur High when
he made a length-of-the-court shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got stupid,'' Phyllis Person said. ``Everybody in the gym
went absolutely crazy, even the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Like her son on Saturday, Person wasn't quite sure what to do
when Claybrooks came up big with a sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't jump up and run up and down the stairs like I
wanted to,'' Person said. ``I couldn't scream, shout and hug him
like I wanted to. I just said 'Yes!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
