<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-WINNERS-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BAD NAMES IS GOOD NEWS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Ind.)   (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basically, two winning themes emerged in a quarter so dismal
that gains of less than 2 percent could catapult a mutual fund into
the top 10 among domestic diversified stock funds: plays on falling
interest rates, and an overall search for safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard Wellesley Income fund, with a combination of stocks
and bonds that neatly tied together both themes, ranked seventh
among diversified domestic stock funds; its quarterly return was
1.65 percent. Many of its stocks are utilities, which have come
into their own after struggling in red-hot markets.
</P>
<P>
   Another winner, the Copley Fund, took 10th place with a return
of 0.97 percent, also helped by a heavy weighting of utility
shares. Among purer plays, Strong American Utilities, up 4.89
percent, ranked fourth among specialized funds.
</P>
<P>
   And a newfangled investment, Barr Rosenberg Market Neutral,
ranked sixth among diversified funds, with a return of 1.9 percent.
It aims for a steady return regardless of what happens in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of the four funds talked about how they coped and
what might lie ahead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a good portfolio all along,'' said William H.
Reaves, who runs Strong American Utilities, with $216.5 million in
assets. ``We've just come into a period when the sun is shining on
our stocks for a change.'' Among the fund's holdings are shares in
electric utilities (38.5 percent), telecommunications (34 percent),
energy (13 percent) and gas utilities (8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The climate for utilities stocks has been particularly good, he
said, because the slowing earnings growth trend of industrial
companies and falling interest rates have made the dividends paid
by utilities companies more attractive. As of Sept. 30, the fund
yielded 2.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Reaves said he had been building his position in electric
utility stocks throughout the year, ``as the deregulation process
moves along in state after state.'' One favorite is Ameren, now 7
percent of the fund's portfolio. Ameren, based in St. Louis, yields
6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another large holding, 7.1 percent of the portfolio, is Nipsco,
a natural-gas and electric company based in Merrillville, Ind. ``We
see good dividend growth and 8 percent per-share earnings growth
over the next three years,'' Reaves said.
</P>
<P>
   In telecommunications, his largest position is Ameritech (8.1
percent of the portfolio). ``We expect dividend payments to
increase about 6 percent a year, and earnings per share at 12
percent,'' he said. Other favorites: Bell Atlantic (7.2 percent)
and the SBC Corp. (6.6 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Reaves expects the good times to continue for utilities ``as
long as we have slow growth and until the trend of interest rates
turns up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barr Rosenberg Market Neutral, with $310 million in assets, has
also been shining. William Jump, the portfolio engineer, aims to
buy stocks he thinks are undervalued and then ``neutralize'' the
risk by selling short (that is, selling borrowed shares of) an
equal amount of stocks he sees as overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   If the prices of the shorted stocks fall, as expected, the
borrowed securities can be replaced with shares that cost less.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the combination is intended to produce a fund with the
same risk levels as intermediate bonds, but with higher returns.
``Our goal is to beat Treasury bills by 5{ percent to 6 percent a
year, which is about 10 or 11 percent in the current interest-rate
environment,'' Jump said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7358 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-WINNERS-2TAKE     10-08 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-WINNERS-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Jump said.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't stand out in good markets,'' he said, but ``this
is a prime environment for our fund.''
</P>
<P>
   No single holding contributed to the fund's relatively strong
performance this quarter; Jump juggles more than 700 long positions
and another 700 shorts. ``Our returns aren't driven by individual
home runs,'' he said. ``They're driven by lots of base hits.''
</P>
<P>
   All that trading pushes up the fund's turnover rate to about 200
percent, more than double that of the average stock fund. That
means transaction expenses will be high, and investors may receive
a big chunk of short-term gains, taxable at ordinary income rates,
at year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Jump focuses mostly on small and midsize companies. ``That's
where we find the greatest inefficiencies in pricing,'' he said.
About 90 percent of the fund's holdings are companies with market
capitalizations of less than $2.8 billion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if we did something brilliant,'' said Earl E.
McEvoy, who manages the fixed-income portion of the $8.1 billion
Vanguard Wellesley Income fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``When interest rates come down and the economic outlook slows,
Wellesley does well on both the stock and bond sides,'' McEvoy
said. Wellesley's portfolio is 60 percent to 65 percent invested in
bonds; the balance, in stocks, is run by John R. Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley holds long bonds, mostly corporate (80 percent of its
bond total), with the balance in Treasuries. It has an overall
duration of nine years, meaning that the value of the bonds
increases 9 percent for every decline of one percentage point in
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   This quarter, rates fell by roughly one-half percentage point,
so Wellesley's bonds gained about 4.5 percent, McEvoy figured.
</P>
<P>
   What Wellesley chose not to own also helped bolster its showing
this quarter: junk bonds, emerging-markets debt and mortgage
securities.
</P>
<P>
   On the equity side, Wellesley's holdings include utilities, 33
percent of the stock portfolio, and energy and financial stocks, 14
percent each. ``Because their dividends look stable,'' McEvoy said,
utilities are ``almost like bonds in some people's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund's biggest gainers for the quarter were Amoco, up 29
percent; Consolidated Edison, which rose 23 percent, and AMP, up 22
percent.. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A tough stock market is good news for Irving Levine, manager of
the $87.5 million Copley fund, which has about 55 percent of its
portfolio in telephone, gas and electric companies, which pay the
high dividends many investors seek in uncertain times. The
next-largest chunk (12 percent) is in oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's biggest gainers this quarter were BellSouth (up 12
percent), Ameritech and Florida Power and Light (10 percent each).
</P>
<P>
   Levine chooses his stocks carefully, then holds on. He estimates
that the fund's turnover rate for 1998 will be just 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his strong showing, Levine has a gloomy outlook for the
market. ``I think we're going to have _ not tough sledding anymore,
that's finished _ but we're certainly going to stay down at these
levels until the problems in Asia level off and Russia gets back on
its feet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Copley is also an industrial corporation that wholesales
imported handbags and shoes. As such, it can exclude 70 percent of
its dividend income from tax, so the fund pays taxes itself and
does not make any distributions to shareholders. Shareholders pay
taxes on gains only when they redeem shares.
</P>
<P>
   For most investors, this structure creates tax-adjusted returns
that are about three percentage points higher than comparable
returns on other funds, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
