<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFECTORS-COX     10-08 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFECTORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough choices lure 31 Democrats from fold
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Charlie Stenholm (D-Texas) said it was among
the ``top most difficult'' votes of his 20 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Taylor (D-Miss.) called it about the easiest, pretty
``cut and dried,'' he said in his Mississippi drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris John (D-La.) said it was a ``juggling game,'' but in
the end he, too, voted for the Republican resolution to open an
impeachment inquiry on President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Caught between conflicting party loyalties and in some cases
difficult re-election battles at home, 31 Democrats voted with the
Republican majority to begin only the third presidential
impeachment inquiry in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats who left the fold come from all parts of the
country, representing both conservative and liberal views in their
party.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some notable similarities. Nearly half, 14
members, are white, Southern Democrats representing districts with
conservative, rural constituents. More than half also belong to a
conservative group of Democrats known as the Blue Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the group of defectors are freshmen, most of whom
were elected in 1996 with a 1-2 percent margin over Republican
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Many, such as Stenholm, are engaged in tough re-election fights.
Stenholm said he wrestled with this vote as he has few others.
Though not a lawyer, he said he read everything he could about the
legal standards of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   His constituents, he said, are divided on the issue, with 50
percent saying Clinton should be impeached and 50 percent saying he
shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no right political vote for me,'' Stenholm said. ``If
you vote for it, you've got explaining to do, if you vote against
it, you've got explaining to do. The key for me ... is how I do the
explaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who voted for the GOP impeachment resolution said they
felt no pressure from the Democratic leadership or the White House
to cast a different vote.
</P>
<P>
   But some were clearly upset with the political pressure they
felt at home.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ellen Tauscher (D-Calif.), a freshman elected in 1996 with
49 percent of the vote, said her Republican opponent this year has
made Clinton an issue. ``It's all he talks about,'' she complained.
</P>
<P>
   She said she voted for the resolution to put an end to the
controversy as soon as possible, even as she lashed out at the
Republican majority. ``The Republicans have become the party that
is the Kinko's of kinky sex,'' she said. ``All they want to do is
embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), a Democratic whip and one of five
Democrats who voted against both the Republican resolution and the
Democratic alternative, said he understood the predicament faced by
Democrats in ``marginal districts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to walk a fine line and not do anything to depress
their Democratic vote, but not do anything to turn away moderates
and independents who may vote for them,'' Lewis said. ``We want
(Democrats) back here (in Congress). We don't want people to fall
on their swords.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Moran (D-Va.), who is seeking re-election in a solidly
Democratic district, said in a Washington Post article published
Thursday that a strict Democratic party-line vote ``will unfairly
tag our party as wanting to short-circuit what should be a
legitimate search for the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``If the public thinks that Democrats want to
stonewall this process, we will not be serving the best interests
of the party, the president or our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they cast what will be undoubtedly viewed as a
conservative vote, the Democrats who voted for the GOP resolution
also were quick to note that the vote did not represent a vote to
impeach Clinton, a refrain most are likely to repeat to Democratic
voters back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't view this as a vote for impeachment, but for a
process we have to go through,'' said freshman Rep. Nick Lampson
(D-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   Not all Democrats, however, had to be brought kicking and
screaming to vote for the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Retiring Rep. Paul McHale (D-Pa.), who has called for Clinton to
resign, delivered a harshly worded speech to the House. McHale
asked and was permitted to speak on the time allotted to
Republicans, not Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot excuse ... misconduct because we happen to belong to
the same party as the president,'' said McHale, noting that he
voted for Clinton in both 1992 and 1996. ``His actions were not
`inappropriate.' They were predatory, reckless and breathtakingly
arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, some analysts and House Democrats predicted
that the number of party members voting for the Republican
resolution would exceed 60. But the Democratic alternative of a
more limited inquiry, made in the form of a vote to recommit the
GOP resolution, allowed virtually all Democrats to say they were
voting for an inquiry _ just not the one pushed by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And while there was no arm-twisting from the White House or
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.), Democrats did apply some
subtle pressure prior to the vote. At a Democratic caucus meeting,
the leadership brought in two Democratic pollsters to share a
recent poll suggesting that Democrats who vote for the inquiry
could depress Democratic turnout Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't win,'' said Rep. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.), who voted
against the GOP resolution. ``But we did darn good. We did a lot
better than many people expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Moran, D-Va., meets reporters on Capitol Hill Wednesday
Oct. 7, 1998 after attending a Democratic caucus. Moran, explaining
his yes vote for impeachment hearings against the president in a
morning newspaper opinion piece, said that for Democrats to oppose
an impeachment inquiry in lockstep would
</P>
<P>
   unfairly tag our party as wanting to short-circuit what should
be a legitimate search for the truth.'' (AP Photo/Dennis Cook)
</P>
<P>
   DENNIS COOK / Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   After attending a Democratic caucus, Rep. Jim Moran (D-Va.)
explains his vote for an impeachment inquiry to reporters
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   VOTING WITH THE GOP
</P>
