<HEADER>
A7371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GADEL-COX     10-08 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgians split on party lines; Bishop sticks with Democrats
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It came as no surprise Thursday that all eight
Republicans in the Georgia delegation voted to open an impeachment
inquiry into allegations against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was somewhat unexpected, however, that Democratic Rep.
Sanford Bishop, the wild-card vote, decided against supporting the
GOP resolution.
</P>
<P>
   As the only member facing a serious election challenge in a
conservative district, many expected Bishop to support the
Republican measure calling for an open-ended inquiry into
allegations that Clinton committed perjury, obstructed justice and
abused his presidential powers in an attempt to conceal his affair
with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bishop stuck with his Democratic brethren and voted
against the Republican resolution, which passed 258 to 176. Bishop
supported the unsuccessful Democratic alternative calling for a
more limited inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have been politically expedient and voted for the
Republican resolution,'' Bishop said in a statement after the vote.
``But I could not in good conscience put my personal and political
interests ahead of the well-being of the people of the 2nd District
and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Political factors might not have been entirely absent from
Bishop's decision, however. The 2nd District is more than one-third
black. Blacks have overwhelmingly said in public opinion polls that
they do not favor a continuing investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's other Democrats, Reps. John Lewis and Cynthia
McKinney, voted against both resolutions _ in effect saying no to
any type of impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has had enough,'' said Lewis, who as chief deputy
whip refused to help his party leaders build support for their
alternative because even it ``went too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a stinging rebuke that she delivered against the
president only three weeks ago, McKinney on Thursday said the
president's conduct does not rise to the level of an impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The facts, McKinney said, boil down to this: A man cheated on
his wife and lied to his wife and the nation about the
relationship. Impeachment proceedings should be reserved for the
most serious of crimes, and lying about sex does not rise to that
level, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process passed by the House of Representatives today is
nothing more than a sex witch hunt _ a wide-ranging investigation
with no limits, no rules and no time completion,'' McKinney said.
``The Republicans seem hell-bent to investigate rather than
legislate.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Lewis, McKinney said the president has been punished enough
by having to look at himself every day in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Republican support for the impeachment inquiry was widely
expected, and all eight Georgia Republicans were already on record
as supporting an inquiry before Thursday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mac Collins (R-Ga.) was quick to note that 430 House
members, both Republican and Democratic, voted for some type of
impeachment inquiry. The parties differed only on how the inquiry
should be framed, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's resounding answer by members of both parties was that
the House must fulfill its constitutional responsibility to
investigate the president's actions and determine if he has
committed `high crimes and misdemeanors,''' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.) joined Democratic calls that the
inquiry be concluded quickly. ``We cannot continue down this track
for much longer,'' Chambliss said. ``It must come to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nathan Deal (R-Ga.), a former prosecutor from North
Georgia, said the inquiry should be approached with ``care and
caution.''
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia Republican Bob Barr, the vote was a moment to
relish. Almost one year after he first introduced a resolution
calling for Clinton's resignation, he was finally seeing strong
support for an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost surreal,'' Barr said. ``This is a moment of
history, a moment of truth that all Americans can be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Jack Kingston said two Democratic parties appeared to
be emerging from the vote's outcome, one dedicated to Clinton and
one dedicated to truth. ``I'm trying to keep restrained and keep
the lynch mob mentality out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.), who as speaker often refrains from
voting, cast his vote for the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.), who is also a member of the GOP
leadership, said the country is going through a grieving process
over the president's admitted lie about Lewinsky. ``Most of the
nation is still in denial and wants it to go away,'' Linder said.
``But this is starting to sink in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
