<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-RAMIREZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMIREZ GAMBLE PAYING OFF FOR CLEVELAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ In the spring, ``The Sporting News'' designated
Cleveland Indians right fielder Manny Ramirez as ``one of the 10
worst fundamental players in all of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassment did not stop there.
</P>
<P>
   That national publication ranked Ramirez No. 1 among baseball's
clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Hargrove, whose Indians face the New York Yankees
in Game 3 of the American League Championship Series at 7:08
tonight at Jacobs Field, volunteers this response:
</P>
<P>
   Get a clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny Ramirez works hard daily _ offensively and defensively _
and has really done a tremendous job,'' said Hargrove, ``in making
himself one of the top two right fielders in the American League
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez will likely emerge as the
league's most valuable player for this season, but the Indians can
make a case for this shy, 26-year-old native of the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who hit .294 with 45 home runs and 145 runs batted in,
produced an MVP-type season without the embarrassing errors or
base-running gaffes that haunted him earlier during his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really pushed him and rushed him,'' Hargrove said of
Ramirez, whom the Indians recalled from the minor leagues during
September 1993. ``There were a lot of people who wrote and said
that we were crazy. They might not have been that far wrong, but we
felt that we had to do that to make our club better. I think we've
been proven right in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently, you get a kid learning to play the game at the
major-league level. You're going to see a lot of lapses, and that _
I think _ is as much as anything you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's shyness often prevents him from discussions, and he
eluded the national media here yesterday with success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen less and less of those,'' Hargrove said of
Ramirez's mental lapses. ``Then, they crept up and reared their
ugly head in the division series on a couple of balls that Manny
hit that were normally out. He didn't run real hard to first base.
One of them he got a single out of, and the second one was a close
play at second base for a double.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ramirez hit .357 (5-for-14) with two home runs and
three RBI during the Indians' four games with the Red Sox in the
division series. That, though, does not compare with what Ramirez
did for the Indians after first baseman Jim Thome went on the
disabled list Aug. 8 with a fracture to his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez replaced Thome as the Indians' cleanup hitter and hit
.281 with 10 home runs and 29 RBI during the 35 games Thome missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big void to fill,'' said Richie Sexson, who
replaced Thome at first base during that period. ``That was 100 RBI
and 40 home runs gone from our lineup right there. I think what
Manny did helped this team. His production doubled, and that's
exactly what we needed. What he was doing was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   That performance became another reason Indians general manager
John Hart and Hargrove defend Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too easy of a target when you see Manny make a
mistake,'' Hargrove said. ``All of a sudden, everyone goes: `Oh,
that's just Manny.' Well, that's not just Manny. Everybody else
makes those mistakes, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has just keyed on Manny because that's kind of been
his track record, but I think a lot of other people who see him on
a daily basis think that he's really grown out of that stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say Ramirez stepped onto another.
</P>
</TEXT>
