A7388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSITY-ENROLLMENT     10-08 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSITY-ENROLLMENT-INCREASE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College enrollment increases statewide
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Preliminary college enrollment figures show the
first notable increases in Texas since 1992, signaling the start of
a college-going boom predicted to hit nationally in the next few
years, education officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to see the beginning of the baby boom echo,''
said Jacqueline King, director of federal policy analysis for the
American Council on Education.
</P>
<P>
   Along with an increase in the population of college-age
students, immigration is causing enrollments to swing upward.
</P>
<P>
   ``States with high immigration, such as Texas, are seeing it
first, and they are going to feel this the hardest,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every sector of higher education in Texas, public and
private, posted enrollment increases this fall, bringing the
state's total to 950,639 students, up 1.7 percent over last year,
according to data released Thursday. The numbers are likely to go
down slightly as some students drop out, said Ray Grasshoff, a
spokesman for the Texas Higher Education Coordinating Board.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Texas undoubtedly will end up with overall enrollment
increases above 1 percent for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   If the uptick continues over the next decade as predicted, there
will be implications for taxpayers, students and parents across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Policy makers likely will seek more money to finance higher
education as schools try to meet the demand for everything from
classroom space to dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   Public and private universities were overwhelmed this fall by
more students than expected, causing many schools to scramble for
dormitory space. Southwestern University in Georgetown and St.
Edward's in Austin were among those posting record enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, private school enrollments shot up 3.6 percent, to
102,489 students, while public colleges and universities added 0.9
percent more students than last fall, bringing enrollment to
399,812. It was the first public university increase since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Community colleges, which are expected to experience the most
dramatic percentage increases early in the next century, saw their
enrollments rise 2.09 percent, to 422,284 students. The increase at
Austin Community College was a modest 25 students, for a total
enrollment of 25,821.
</P>
<P>
   State forecasters are predicting enrollment will grow in the
range of 100,000 to 130,000 students by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big boom,'' said David Gardner, deputy assistant
commissioner of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, college enrollment is expected to rise from 14.5
million this fall to 16.08 million by 2008, according to
projections by the U.S. Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner and King, however, cautioned that such predictions are
difficult to make and depend on a variety of factors. For example,
distance learning courses, the increasing cost of tuition and the
high school graduation rates of Hispanics, which are below those
ofAnglos and blacks, could all make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expected to grow, but how much will depend on how
successful we are . . . in improving the academic prospects of
Hispanic Americans,'' King said. ``If those folks are not educated,
we're going to be in big trouble'' as a society.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
