<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VOTE-ART-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 31 EXCEPTIONS, A PARTISAN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., Fla., Tenn., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: See also CLINTON-IMPEACH, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-SCENE,
CLINTON-DAY, DEMS-DISSENT) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opening nearly three hours of debate over whether
the House should initiate impeachment proceedings, Rep. Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., chairman of the Judiciary Committee, warned Republicans and
Democrats alike Thursday that ``too much hangs in the balance for
us not to rise above partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the quarreling on the House floor was plainly partisan. So
was the subsequent vote of 258-176, as only 31 of the 206 House
Democrats joined the Republican majority and signed on to the
resolution for an open-ended impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   By sticking together, House Democrats may find it easier in the
final weeks before Election Day to portray the inquiry as a
partisan witch hunt. They can also keep their distance from an
embattled President Clinton by reminding voters that they had
backed a more limited impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that the American people, I think, got a real
eyeful of what this is all about today: a partisan vote, a
termination of debate,'' said Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., who is on
the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lofgren added that voters ``have a chance to do something
about it Nov. 3.''
</P>
<P>
   While White House officials were heartened that not enough
Democrats defected to make the vote appear bipartisan,
congressional Democrats said they were spurred by a desire to unite
the party, not to help Clinton. They repeatedly noted that 85
percent of the party caucus voted together.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Democratic pollsters Stanley Greenberg and
Celinda Lake, made public on the eve of the vote, concluded that
most voters favor a congressional inquiry but that Democratic
candidates could be hurt by supporting the broader inquiry proposed
by Republicans. ``If this election is about Clinton and his
behavior, we lose,'' said an official in the Democratic
congressional leadership, speaking on the condition of anonymity.
``If it's about the partisan way the Congress has handled this, I
think we do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the vote was no great triumph for the president: The
reality is that 429 representatives voted for an impeachment
inquiry in one form or another _ and that Clinton is only the third
president to be subjected to an inquiry that could lead to his
removal from office. Asked whether the House action represented a
victory for the White House, Rahm Emanuel, a senior adviser to the
president, replied dryly, ``I would not use that word.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressing the point that there was little reason for jubilation
at the White House, some Republicans went as far as to describe the
voting as bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote, in essence, was a bipartisan vote in the sense that
everybody but five members _ all but five _ voted for some form of
a resolution of inquiry,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla. ``And
while we wish we could have been on the same sheet of music about
the particulars, I think everybody recognizes the matters are
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   While no lawmaker rose to defend Clinton _ and many on both
sides offered scathing criticism of his conduct _ the oratory from
the two parties was strikingly different.
</P>
<P>
   As they cheered one another on, Democrats mocked the Republican
leadership for not giving them adequate time to make their case
(some Democrats were allotted only 20 seconds). And they attacked
Republicans for demanding, as Rep. Robert Scott of Virginia said,
``an inquiry that cannot end,'' instead of tending to important
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi of California was among the Democrats who
recalled that Speaker Newt Gingrich had been fined and reprimanded
by the House in 1997 for ``lying under oath'' to the House Ethics
Committee about his use of tax-exempt groups for political
purposes. ``How inconsistent, then, Speaker, for this same
Republican majority to move to an impeachment inquiry of the
president for lying about his personal life,'' Ms. Pelosi said, as
Gingrich presided over the debate.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, Republicans insisted that the president's
conduct was no trivial matter, and that the only way to spare the
country any more grief from the scandal was to move ahead
expeditiously with hearings. They also reminded Democrats that a
vote for the Republican proposal was not a vote to impeach _ only
to proceed with the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about keeping political score,'' said Ed Bryant,
R-Tenn., a member of the Judiciary Committee. ``We are here
protecting our Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde responded to Democrats' complaints that he had not granted
them adequate time to review the pertinent documents by noting that
Republicans on the Judiciary Committee came to his office to devote
a total of 114.59 hours to reviewing materials while Democratic
members spent only 21.81 hours.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the vote, Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., who is second
to Hyde on the Judiciary Committee, put forth this plea: ``I would
ask my Democratic friends to be as bipartisan today as the
Republicans were back in 1974.''
</P>
<P>
   But he had little success, perhaps because Thursday's
proceedings could not have been more unlike those of February 1974,
when the House, by a lopsided vote of 410-4, granted the Judiciary
Committee broad powers to embark on an impeachment inquiry into
President Nixon. That debate lasted only one hour and was
relatively cordial in tone, in part because Republican leaders in
Congress supported the resolution of the Judiciary Committee
chairman, Rep. Peter Rodino. And in those days the Democrats held a
50-seat majority; the Republican edge now is a slim 21 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were certainly partisan in many, many ways,'' John Rhodes,
the Arizona Republican who was minority leader at the time, said in
an interview Thursday. ``But Republicans did not dig in their heels
and try to sabotage the effort. We didn't hate each other. And we
didn't assume that just because somebody didn't agree with us that
he was no good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
