<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCENE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drama to high for Drudge to put drain on scene
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _The historic day finally came and guess who came to
Capitol Hill to talk to Republicans about their agenda?
</P>
<P>
   None other than Matt Drudge, the fedora-wearing, online gossip
maven who is responsible for several of the more notorious
``leaks'' in the Clinton-Lewinsky saga.
</P>
<P>
   A self-styled modern-day Walter Winchell with his internet
Drudge Report, a daily staple of many Washington insiders, Drudge
was invited by Georgia Republican Rep. Jack Kingston to talk to a
group of Republicans who set the morning congressional agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was merely coincidental,'' said Kingston about Drudge's
presence on the very day that the impeachment inquiry vote was
being cast. ``On the day of the Starr report, we had Bob
Woodward,'' he said, referring to the Washington Post reporter who
broke many of the stories that led to the resingation of former
President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge used the opportunity to walk the hallways of Congress,
taking off his hat to show respect to members. When Georgia
Republican Bob Barr saw him, it was a true celebrity moment, with
Barr asking him to come over for a tete a tete later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is high drama, high drama,'' Drudge said of the House
debate. ``Better than any Broadway show in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   But to many of the veterans in the Capitol Hill press corps, the
historic day of voting ended up being fairly anti-climatic. Given
the Republican majority in the House it was forgone conclusion that
the GOP resolution would pass.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was even relaxed by some standards, despite the
partisan rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a deep drag on a cigarette during the two hours of debate
on the measure, Republican Conference Chairman John Boehner calmly
said that this was the most important vote short of going to war.
</P>
<P>
   But then, where were all the fiery speeches, the passionate
elocutions?
</P>
<P>
   They were there, Boehner said. But he did say that perhaps it
wasn't as electric as other debates because nearly every hiccup of
the Clinton-Lewinsky affair had already been reported, discussed
and dissected for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the vote on the Gulf War, I saw guys go to the well of
the House with tears in their eyes saying it was the most difficult
vote of their lives,'' Boehner said. ``We're not sending men and
women to war but this is the beginning of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   That is something that Barr can only smile about. After all,
Barr, who has been known to invoke the ``I'' word at every
opportunity, was the first to call for the impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Barr said he just sat smiling, thinking to
himself how funny life is. Last November Barr introduced a
resolution calling for impeachment proceedings and that was even
before the Lewinsky controversy erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect that the Minority Leader will come over to
congratulate me, but it is nice to hear all these Democrats calling
for an impeachment inquiry,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   All day, reporters moved in clusters gathering impact from
members as tourists looked on from galleries at the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Maher, a tourist from California, said the debate made her
wince. ``I am just plain and tired of all this stuff coming out,''
she said. ``It's just sex, sex and more sex.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the debate turned to cattle calls and applause as each
side tried to score points. Noticeably absent was anyone from the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion did attract members from the other chamber. Sen.
Arlen Specter, (R-Pa.), came to the House floor to watch. ``I think
it's coming our way,'' Specter said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
