u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-DISSENT-ART-NYT &LR;      10-08 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DISSENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAGMATISM MAY EXPLAIN SOME CROSSOVER VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the 31 Democrats who voted for the Republican
proposal Thursday, political pragmatism might have had as much to
do with their decision as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   All but six came from the South and Midwest. They are the ``Blue
Dog'' Democrats who often tilt Republican on economic issues and
sometimes on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, about a half-dozen or so, are in fiercely
competitive re-election races, where any surprise could send them
back into private life. They do not want to risk inspiring negative
campaign advertisements on television by appearing too soft on
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of those 31 Democrats explained their votes in speeches
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at stake is really the rule of law,'' said Rep. Paul
McHale of Pennsylvania, delivering one of the day's more critical
speeches. ``When the president took an oath to tell the truth, he
was no different at that point from any other citizen, both as a
matter of morality and as a matter of legal obligation. We cannot
excuse that kind of misconduct because we happen to belong to the
same party as the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Kucinich of Ohio said, ``I rise today, not on behalf
of Democrats or Republicans, but as an American who is deeply
concerned that our country bring closure to the charges against the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   All but five of the 31 Democrats voted for both the Democratic
and Republican resolutions, signaling to their constituents just
how serious they were about an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   They, like their colleagues, took pains to underscore the fact
that the vote was not a call for impeachment, rather an endorsement
of a fact-gathering process. But many of them also said they
wanted, or needed, to be on the winning side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who could count knew the Democratic proposal wouldn't
pass, and the country is waiting to see if the Congress is going to
go forward with hearings,'' Kucinich said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite days of hand-wringing, and in a few cases subtle
arm-twisting by fellow Democrats and the White House, these
Democrats said they did not feel right voting against the
Republican proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tim Roemer, D-Ind., who helped form a coalition of moderate
New Democrats, said he wanted to endorse the Republican plan
because it was modeled after the bipartisan Watergate resolution.
</P>
<P>
   On the more conservative end of the spectrum, Rep. Chris John,
D-La., who has no opponent this year, said he was concerned about
the Democrats' effort to put a time limit on the inquiry. The
Republican plan is open-ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to go to the next step,'' John said. ``That's
the way to end it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another conservative Democrat, Rep. Jim Turner of Texas, said he
had made his vote known on Wednesday, and since then had been
fielding telephone calls both praising and condemning him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approached this on a personal level,'' Turner said. ``Once
we received the Starr report, it was like being handed a football.
We've got to do something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few Democrats who voted for the proposal had more immediate
concerns. Few of them chose to talk about their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Leonard L. Boswell, D-Iowa, and a new member, faces a tough
fight in a swing district. Boswell has supported a ban on a
late-term abortion procedure and a constitutional amendment on flag
burning.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., has found that his liberal voting
record has become a liability, and has had difficult re-election
races.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Etheridge, D-N.C., sits in the middle of a
Republican-leaning district and faces an opponent who broadcast
anti-Clinton television advertisements just after the Lewinsky
scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Cramer of Alabama and Rep. Gene Taylor of
Mississippi are among the last white Democratic Congressmen from
the Deep South. By voting for the Republican proposal, they hope to
ensure their political survival. Cramer came within 1,200 votes of
losing in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, who represents a conservative
district, has also tried his best to disassociate himself from
Clinton. His campaign tag line is, ``Our congressman. Our values.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, four of Texas' 17 Democratic Congressmen voted for the
Republican plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia Democratic delegation also broke ranks with the
party in large numbers; four of its six members voted for the
Republican proposal.
</P>
<P>
   As one of only two members in the 29-member democratic
California delegation who voted for the Republican plan, Rep. Ellen
Tauscher, a moderate, said her opponent had tried to capitalize on
Clinton's troubles to hurt her. Ms. Tauscher said she agonized over
the decision but, in the end, decided not ``be painted into a
corner'' by looking like she opposed an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also believe we have to do the right thing and be thoughtful
and sober about the Constitution,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
