<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE PLUNGE ON NASDAQ HITS 15-MONTH LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sparing only a couple major markets, stock prices
tumbled around the world on Thursday in emotional and often panicky
trading, reflecting investor fear that recession might be spreading
from the Far East to Europe and might eventually grip the United
States. But then Wall Street suddenly reversed course and produced
a late-session comeback in the third-heaviest trading session on
record.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks slumped 20
percent from its mid-July peak _ the amount that has come to define
a bear market _ it bounced back to halve its loss, which amounted
to a moderate 1.16 percent. The rally also lifted the index back
above the low it set in the Aug. 31 market wipeout.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery of the blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average also
was strong, ending with a decline of just 9.78 points after having
fallen 274.20 at midday. Nasdaq stocks, battered for much of the
year, also improved during the afternoon but the chief index still
lost another 2.97 percent for the day to make a 16-month low. The
Nasdaq has fallen 12 percent in the last four trading days.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks had dropped sharply in Japan and Europe, with Tokyo's
Nikkei down 5.8 percent, erasing Wednesday's advance. Major indexes
fell 4.98 percent in Germany, 4.45 percent in France and 2.69
percent in Britain. Brazil's exchange, which finished marginally
higher, and Hong Kong's, which rose 2.5 percent, were the only
markets that escaped damage. ``Today you can cut the fear with a
knife,'' said Alfred Goldman, chief market strategist for A. G.
Edwards in St. Louis. Some of the selling, he added, was with
little consideration of price.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the depressed mood on Thursday morning was attributed to
Abby Joseph Cohen, the widely followed Goldman Sachs strategist,
who trimmed her profit estimates for S. &AMP; P. companies by $1.50, to
$49, for this year and by $2.50, to $52.50, for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said her lowered expectations would have
``little direct impact'' on stock returns because of the lowered
profits would be offset by lower interest rates and lower
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   At Prudential Securities, Greg Smith, its chief investment
strategist, recommended that investors quadruple cash allotments to
20 percent of their portfolios, while Ralph Acampora, the firm's
technical analyst, sharply reduced his target ranges for the S.&AMP;P.
and the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 p.m., however, investors seemed to decide that emotional
selling had made many stocks seem like bargains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be at a pretty important turning point,'' suggested
Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch. He said it
was typical of the final stages of a downturn for dispirited
investors to try to wring some profit from shrinking portfolios by
selling stocks that had resisted the decline, such as drug
companies.
</P>
<P>
   After what McCabe called this final ``capitulation,'' the market
tends to come back, as seemed to happen during the afternoon. Merck
traded as low as 121| before rallying to close at 127, up 1 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Financial companies had remarkably sharp reversals, with J.P.
Morgan up 5], to 79~ after trading as low as 72[, Merrill Lynch up
4} at 42{ after being as low as 35} and Bankers Trust recovering
from 45 to finish at 54{, up 5 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the newly minted product of the Citibank-Travelers
merger, finished at 32{, up }, after trading at 28{. ``We need a
big, hard down day to sort of clear the selling pressure,'' Richard
Cripps, chief strategist at Legg Mason in Baltimore, said during
the morning shortly after canceling a business trip in light of
further declines overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 13 of the 30 Dow industrials managed gains on
Thursday, with Kodak up 2 7/16, to 80 1/16, right behind J. P.
Morgan. The biggest Dow loser - without which the index would have
rose - was General Electric, down 3 7/16 to 71 9/16 as
third-quarter sales were lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Among Nasdaq stocks, Dell Computer swung wildly before losing 2[
to 48 7/16, Microsoft shed 2 15/16 to 91 3/16 and Yahoo dropped 9
9/16 to 104 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange totaled 1.11 billion
shares, with 2,651 stocks closing lower and 615 higher. A total of
933 issues made new lows for the year compared with only 45 new
highs.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the S. &AMP; P. index was 11.24, to 959.44, barely
above the 957.28 Aug. 31 low. At its worst yesterday, however, the
index stood at 923.32, 22.2 percent below its high on July 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
