<HEADLINE>
BMW M ROADSTER: PLACING LIMITATIONS ON POWER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even Michaelangelo had off days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So it's not unthinkable that BMW, the master sculptor of
automotive handling and performance, could haplessly chip off the
nose _ or, more precisely, a toe _ while trying to perfect its
two-seat David, the Z3 Roadster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The engineers responsible for the M Roadster, a high-performance
variant of James Bond's shark-gille convertible, are also the one's
who engineered the M3 coupe. The M3 is widely regarded among the
string-back glove set as the world's best-handling four-seater.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the M3's bone and sinew was transplanted into the
smaller, lighter M Roadster, including the company's 3.2-liter
in-line six-cylinder engine at 240 horsepower and 236 foot pounds
of torque, disk brakes more than 12 inches in diameter, and
beautiful 17-inch alloy wheels wrapped with ultra-low-profile
Michelin tires. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of which seems like a recipe for turning the Z3 roadster _ a
glib and lively touring car _ into a masterpiece of a road-spanking
sports car.
</P>
<P>
   But the M Roadster, with an average sticker price of $45,000, is
not perfect. Under the lash of extreme driving, it is surprisingly
discombobulated. The problem is simple: BMW, in its desire to keep
the ride supple for American motorists, has sprung this car a touch
too softly for its additional power and weight _ at 3,080 pounds,
some 300 pounds heavier than the original 1.8-liter Z3. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you let off the fuel before a corner, the nose dives,
transferring hundreds of pounds of weight to the front wheels and
leaving the rear wheels less weighted and more likely to slide. The
M Roadster's rear trailing-arm suspension, with less range of
motion than the coupe's multilink setup, further complicates
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than sliding progressively in a hard corner, the
nine-inch-wide rear tires grip fiercely until the moment they break
traction and then lunge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, under the influence of an over-excited accelerator
foot, the car squats, lifting the front wheels and making steering
response go all wispy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The variable-assist power steering feels light and fussy,
fighting its way back to center during long high-speed turns and
requiring frequent midcourse corrections. The car's short wheelbase
_ 96.8 inches _ amplifies those corrections into moments of
breath-holding polar inertia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the M Roadster feels twitchy and unrelaxed, less
likely to pluck the heart-strings of enthusiasts than let loose a
load of butterflies in their stomachs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, if the problem is simple, the fix is simple: firmer
springs and shocks. Several after-market tuners offer just such
suspension kits, which emulate the firmer suspensions of M
Roadsters bound for the European market.
</P>
<P>
   The European M Roadsters produce a volcanic 321 horsepower,
making the American version, with 240, seem tame by comparison. But
it sure doesn't feel tame. The American M Roadster comes off the
line as if it has been swatted by a very angry Mark McGwire, going
from 0 to 60 miles an hour in about 5.5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   A marvelously elaborate speeding ticket awaits you at the end of
14 seconds, when you cross into three-digit territory. Anywhere in
between, the free-revving six-cylinder, mated to BMW's slick
five-speed manual transmission, stands ready to provide blasts of
acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   In most other respects, the M Roadster is similar to the Z3 that
for three years has beautified our highways. The interior is
gussied up with a two-tone leather package and set off by chrome
bezels around the instruments and the shift column. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ground-hugging body cladding, dual exhausts and chrome
side-grille accents identify the M as an M, though the effect is
pretty subtle. The power top is standard and works fast and well,
though it has an odd feature that requires the driver to depress
the brake while it is operating.
</P>
<P>
   Traction control is not available on the M Roadster. The radio
reception is inexplicably spotty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What BMW doesn't know about suspensions hasn't been discovered
yet, so the setup of the M Roadster is quite deliberate; it
suggests that rather than pursue hard-core enthusiast drivers, BMW
seeks the approval of a broader market. As choices go, that was
probably very smart, sensible and safe. Alas, those words don't
begin with ``M.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: That's ``M,'' as in ``medium cool.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
