<HEADLINE>
31 DEMOCRATS JOIN REPUBLICANS AS HOUSE VOTES FOR IMPEACHMENT
INQUIRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided House of Representatives launched an
open-ended impeachment inquiry against President Clinton on
Thursday, pushing his presidency to a new level of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The 258-176 vote, with 31 Democrats joining all Republicans,
clears the way for the House Judiciary Committee to begin televised
impeachment hearings later this year into Clinton's effort to
cover-up his affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Before voting to begin the inquiry, only the third in U.S.
history, the Republican-controlled House rejected a Democratic
proposal to restrict the investigation to the Lewinsky matter and
to end it by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Thursday authorizes the House Judiciary Committee to
take whatever time is needed to investigate the president. It
places no limits on the scope of the inquiry, which would allow
examination of Clinton's business dealings and campaign fund
raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make any judgments. We don't make any charges. We
simply begin a search for truth,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde, an
Illinois Republican who chairs the Judiciary Committee. ``I will
use all my strength to ensure that this inquiry does not become a
fishing expedition.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who reportedly did not watch the televised debate, said
after the vote that he has ``surrendered'' to whatever hand
Congress intends to deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we can now move forward with this process in a way
that is fair, that is constitutional, and that is timely,'' Clinton
said. ``It is in the hands of Congress and the people of this
country _ ultimately in the hands of God. There is nothing I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   White House fears of a wholesale defection by Democratic
lawmakers did not materialize. Thirty-one Democrats, mostly
first-year members facing tough re-election challenges,
representatives of conservative districts and southerners, voted
with the Republicans for the open investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Democrats voting for the GOP resolution were from
Texas _ Reps. Ralph Hall of Rockwall, Nick Lampson of Beaumont,
Charles Stenholm of Abilene and Jim Turner of Crockett.
</P>
<P>
   Despite lofty arguments from both sides about adhering to the
Constitution and rising above partisanship, the historic debate was
laced with recriminations from Democrats and piety from
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It opened with Democrats complaining that the Republican refusal
to extend the time set aside for discussing the resolution pointed
toward a partisan, perhaps unfair, investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership has placed an incredibly unfair gag
rule on a constitutional debate of historic proportions,'' said
Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Waco. ``If this gag rule is the first test of
the Republicans' fairness in this inquiry, they have failed the
test.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde seemed perplexed by the hostility saying he supposed ``it
would be too much for me to expect you to appreciate'' that the
debate time had been doubled from one hour to two hours in response
to complaints from Democrats, who wanted four hours. Before it was
over, the debate had passed the three-hour mark.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde and Rep. John Conyers, the senior Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee, exchanged bitter words when Hyde suggested that
Republicans had taken more seriously their job of reviewing
evidence of the Clinton-Lewinsky cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, which was forwarded to the House a month ago by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr and placed in a locked room, had
been examined a total of 114 hours by Republican members of the
Judiciary Committee and less than 22 hours by six of the 16
Democrats on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers quickly jumped to his feet. ``That really contributes to
the comity of this body. And I'm sure it's an interesting statistic
that everybody ought to know about,'' Conyers said before striding
from the chamber. Outside, he said, ``Wasn't that a cheapie?''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the charges in Starr's report were too serious
to ignore. Starr accused Clinton of lying, obstructing justice and
abusing his presidential power in an effort to conceal his affair
with Lewinsky. The charges grew out of Clinton's deposition in a
sexual harassment lawsuit brought by Paula Jones, in which he
denied engaging in sex with Lewinsky. The Jones lawsuit was later
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The president's ``chief responsibility is to uphold the laws of
this land; he does not have the privilege to break the law,'' said
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, a Sugar Land Republican who is the
only member of the House leadership to call for Clinton's
resignation. ``This is about right and wrong and upholding the
constitution and the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Florida, said if House members had
declined to investigate Clinton's affair and cover-up ``then we
have undermined our Constitution and we have undermined our system
of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the speeches fell along partisan lines. Rep. Paul
McHale, a Pennsylvania Democrat who also called for Clinton to
resign, declared that the president's testimony in the Jones
lawsuit ``attempted to cover up a sordid and irresponsible
relationship by repeated deceit under oath.'' McHale said Clinton's
actions with Lewinsky were ``not only inappropriate, they were
predatory, reckless, breathtakingly arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of Democrats said no impeachment inquiry was
needed. Their main complaint was that without limits, the
Republicans would not conduct a fair investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question isn't about impeachment; it's about the November
elections,'' said Rep. Charlie Rangel, D-N.Y. ``The Republicans
wouldn't touch impeachment with a 10-foot pole. They want to hound
the president for the next two years, and use impeachment as the
issue in the November elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Florida, called the Republican push for an
impeachment inquiry ``an American inquisition'' aimed at
discrediting Clinton. ``The president betrayed his wife,'' Wexler
said. ``He didn't betray his country. And God help us if we fail to
recognize the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., drew a round of partisan cheers and
hisses from the opposition when she accused Republicans of a double
standard. She looked straight at House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who
was presiding over the debate, and reminded him that in early 1997
he had admitted lying under oath to the House Ethics Committee and
had not been deposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that lying is wrong. But why the double
standard?'' Pelosi asked. ``How inconsistent, Mr. Speaker, for this
Republican majority to move to an impeachment inquiry of the
president about his personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Summing up the Democrats' position, and the enmity between the
two parties, Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said: ``Our problem is
that we don't trust each other.''
</P>
<P>
   When he expressed concern that Republicans might try to expand
the Judiciary Committee investigation to include Whitewater,
alleged misuse of FBI files, firings in the White House travel
office and campaign finance abuses, GOP members of the House broke
out in cheers and applause.
</P>
<P>
   Only twice before has the House begun a presidential impeachment
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, President Richard Nixon, a Republican, resigned after
the House Judiciary Committee approved articles of impeachment over
his role in the Watergate scandal. In 1868, President Andrew
Johnson, a Democrat, was impeached by a Republican-controlled House
angry over his removal of a Cabinet officer. After a trial in the
Senate, the Republicans fell one vote short of removing him.
</P>
<P>
   The Nixon case grew out of a politically inspired burglary of
Democratic headquarters at the Watergate building, an upscale
office-residential complex near the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   In the next several days, the Judiciary Committee staff will
begin planning hearings and drawing up lists of witnesses, possibly
including Starr, Lewinsky, and her former friend, Linda Tripp,
whose secret tapes of Lewinsky's telephone conversations triggered
Starr's investigation of the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Eight weeks ago, the president apologized for his sexual affair
and asked the nation for forgiveness in hopes of ending the threat
to his presidency. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
