family secrets, was commissioned by the Roundabout Theater company
and stars Holly Hunter. Ms. Henley, 46, who was born and brought up
in Mississippi, helped advance Ms. Hunter's career as an actress;
Ms. Hunter, 40, who comes from Georgia, helped solidify Ms.
Henley's success as a playwright. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
HUNTER-HENLEY-THEATER-1, 10-8 -- Holly Hunter as the pregnant
Floral in ``Impossible Marriage'' by Beth Henley. Ms. Hunter has
appeared in six Henley plays and on Thursday she will open in the
seventh, ``Impossible Marriage,'' a production by the Roundabout
Theater Company at the Laura Pels Theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
CANBY-THEATER, 10-8 -- Everett Quinton, left, as Lady Enid
Hillcrest in the revival of Charles Ludlam's spoofcomedy ``The
Mystery of Irma Vep,'' with Stephen DeRosa as the unsympathetic
maid. The director is Quinton, who costarred with Charles Ludlam,
the playwright, in the original production. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo) Eds: Please note that this photo can also be used with
``Theater Notes.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
