<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YIELD FOR 30-YEAR RISES TO 4.99 PERCENT IN A MIXED SESSION FOR
TREASURIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities ended sharply mixed Thursday,
with selling by hedge funds battering the long end of the market
even as shorter maturities were bolstered by weakness in equities.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said shorter maturities were up on expectations
of slower growth and further rate cuts by the Federal Reserve. Some
others said a widely publicized decision by Greg Smith, a
Prudential Securities strategist, to raise cash allocations in
investment portfolios might have helped the shorter-bill sector.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond fell 2 3/32, more than two points for a second
consecutive day, to a price of 107 23/32. The yield, which moves in
the opposite direction, rose to 4.99 percent, from 4.86 percent on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bills and shorter-term notes also gained, with the
bond-equivalent yield on a one-year bill down to 3.92 percent.
Among other long-term issues, the yield on the 10-year note rose to
4.57 percent, from 4.39 percent the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis C. Hynes, chief market strategist at R.W. Pressprich &AMP;
Co., said that Thursday's trade in bonds was certainly tied to
hedge funds liquidating speculative investments in Japanese yen, as
the yen gained on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unwinding by hedge funds has now overtaken the
flight-to-quality bid in Treasuries,'' Hynes said. ``The need to
unwind yen trades is the most dominant thing in the market right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that because the yen had rallied, it put severe pressure
on those investors who had bet on a weaker yen, a higher dollar and
a stronger Treasury market. ``When the yen rallied, the short yen
positions became unprofitable and that forced the unwinding of the
trade, which now goes in reverse, starting with the sale of
Treasuries,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
