<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/08/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- NY-STOCK-EXCHANGES, 10-8 --
Officials are working to keep the three top stock exchanges in
lower Manhattan. The search for new homes for the financial
industry has become a high-stakes, real estate version of musical
chairs, as the New York, American and Nasdaq Stock Exchanges, which
are also being wooed by New Jersey, try to extract subsidy packages
and New York developers maneuver to get a piece of the business.
(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- REPUBS-DISSENT, 10-8 --
When it came time Thursday for the House to vote on an impeachment
inquiry drafted by Democrats, with a deadline and limited scope,
every Republican opposed the measure. Except Rep. Jay Dickey of
Arkansas, a three-term conservative. Dickey, explained his support
for the Democratic option as a matter of conscience, principle and
independence. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- DEMS-DISSENT, 10-8 --
Rep.Tim Roemer of Indiana is among the Democrats who voted for the
Republican proposal for a full-scale inquiry into possible grounds
for the impeachment of President Clinton. Roemer, who helped form a
coalition of moderate New Democrats, says he endorses the
Republican plan ``because it is modeled after the bipartisan
Watergate resolution.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- CLINTON-VOTE-2, 10-8 --
Henry Hyde of Illinois, chairman of the House Judiciary Committee,
discussing the House vote for a full-scale inquiry into possible
grounds for the impeachment of President Clinton, at a Republican
news conference Thursday. Also in attendance were Reps. Mary Bono
of California, Lindsey Graham of South Carolina, James Rogan of
California and Bob Barr of Georgia. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- CLINTON-VOTE-1, 10-8 --
Both parties held news conferences Thursday after the House of
Representatives voted largely along party lines to launch a
full-scale, open-ended inquiry into possible grounds for the
impeachment of President Clinton. Speaking for the Democrats were,
from left, Reps. Robert Scott of Virginia, William Delahunt of
Massachusetts, Charles Rangel of New York and John Conyers Jr. of
Michigan. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- CLINTON-SCENE, 10-8 --
Purposeful in their stride, members of Congress walk to the Capitol
Thursday to vote for an inquiry into the impeachment of President
Clinton. The inquiry, which will lead ultimately to another House
vote to decide whether Clinton should stand trial in the Senate,
was authorized by a vote of 258-176, with 31 Democrats breaking
ranks with the president. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TOKYO -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- JAPAN-SUSHI-BOS, 10-7 --
Auctioneers selling fish at the Tokyo Central Wholesale Market,
where the stakes can be just as high as at Sotheby's. Or, at least,
they used to be. As Japan muddles through its recession, even
sushi, the ultimate Japanese gastronomical obsession, is taking a
bite. Next to rice, fish is perhaps Japan's most basic foodstuff,
and the decline in fish sales has paralleled the nation's economic
slump. (Indira Lakshaman/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MILAN, Italy -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- MILAN-FASHION-2, 10-8 --
Today's designers display an unending fascination with materials,
changing their surfaces and draping and cutting them in ways that
alter the proportions of the garments. Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's black
seamless top, beaded sash and flared seamed organza pants. From Jil
Sander's, a white quilted gathered jacket and crisp trousers. (Dan
Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MILAN, Italy -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- MILAN-FASHION-1, 10-8 --
The abandonment of nudity in fashion, no matter how fleeting it may
be, has sent designers on a quest for other kinds of excitement.
From left to right: Prada's blue gathered top and lavender skirt
with mirrors. Prada's moch!Am+Qher jean jacket, hip bag and
mirrored skirt. Jil Sa~HI hiddeny3]5''oP
</P>
