   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- NY-GILBERT-ARCHITECTURE-2,
10-8 -- The Rotunda at the United States Custom House, designed by
Cass Gilbert, one of seven buildings included in the third annual
Open House, a self-guided tour sponsored by the Alliance for
Downtown New York. This year, the event celebrates the architecture
of Gilbert, a pivotal figure in defining the public face of New
York in the early years of this century. (Chester Higgins Jr./New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- NY-GILBERT-ARCHITECTURE-1,
10-8 -- The interior of the Brooklyn Army Terminal, designed by
Cass Gilbert, one of seven buildings included in the third annual
Open House, a self-guided tour sponsored by the Alliance for
Downtown New York. This year, the event celebrates the architecture
of Gilbert, a pivotal figure in defining the public face of New
York in the early years of this century. (Chester Higgins Jr./New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- HOME-VILA-BOS, 10-08
-- Bob Vila, in his kitchen, embarked on an unexpected career 20
years ago that has cast him as America's Handyman and launched him
as a cottage industry. Despite TV's growing home-improvement
industry, Vila, 52, remains the guy we think of when we think of a
do-it-yourselfer up on a stepladder in just-bought Dockers and a
Land's End shirt. (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- SWAN-AS-THEATER-2, 10-8 --
Adam Cooper, left, leads the male corps of Swans in Matthew
Bourne's inspired reconception of Tchaikovsky's storybook ballet
``Swan Lake,'' at the Neil Simon Theater. Poor old Tchaikovsky's
score may have been pushed around over the last century, with
interpolations and cuts, but the essential plot line of the 1895
``Swan Lake,'' choreographed by Marius Petipa and Lev Ivanov, has
remained the same. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LONDON -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- SWAN-AS-THEATER-1, 10-8 --
Matthew Bourne, the 38-year-old British modern-dance choreographer,
at London's Piccadilly Theater. Bourne's inspired reconception of
Tchaikovsky's storybook ballet ``Swan Lake,'' may not be as
spectacular or profound as the 19th-century original, but it is a
polished entertainment. ``I've never been trying to compete with
classical ballet,'' says Bourne. ``What I'm doing is telling a
story.'' (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- DUET-THEATER-REVIEW, 10-8 --
From left, Erin Quinn Purcell, Derin Basden and Gregory Jackson in
``Duet! A Romantic Fable.'' ``Duet!'' spins wittily and nattily
from one vignette to the next, parodying the conventions of the
dating game. As much as it's intended to poke fun at modern
romance, ``Duet!'' supplies a funny, running commentary on modern
entertainment. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LONDON -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
CALLOWAY-BEARSLEY-ART, 10-8 -- Stephen Calloway, organizer of an
Aubrey Beardsley retrospective at the Victoria and Albert Museum,
in his Georgian terrace house in south London. ``People reinvent
Beardsley to fit their own ideas,'' says Calloway, 47, an art
historian and design consultant. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DENVER -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
APPALACHIAN-SPRING-DANCE, 10-8 -- Terese Capucilli, a veteran of
the Martha Graham Dance Company, rehearsing ``Appalachian Spring''
with the Colorado Ballet, which will perform the work in Denver.
This is the first time that the ballet created in 1944 with a
commissioned score that won Aaron Copland a Pulitzer Prize, will be
performed by any troupe outside the Martha Graham Dance Company
itself. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
RIDGE-THEATER, 10-8 -- Members of the avant-garde Ridge Theater are
Laurie Olinder, left, Bob McGrath, Fred Tietz, Bill Morrison and
Howard Thies. The Ridge Theater is an avant-garde company with the
charm of ex-hippies who have made a name in experimental theater
for staging multimedia spectacles with tidy, Swiss-watch precision.
(Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
HUNTER-HENLEY-THEATER-2, 10-8 -- The playwright of ``Impossible
Marriage,'' Beth Henley, at the Roundabout Theater. The play, about
family secrets, was commissioned by the Roundabout Theater company
and stars Holly Hunter. Ms. Henley, 46, who was born and brought up
in Mississippi, helped advance Ms. Hunter's career as an actress;
Ms. Hunter, 40, who comes from Georgia, helped solidify Ms.
Henley's success as a playwright. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
HUNTER-HENLEY-THEATER-1, 10-8 -- Holly Hunter as the pregnant
Floral in ``Impossible Marriage'' by Beth Henley. Ms. Hunter has
appeared in six Henley plays and on Thursday she will open in the
seventh, ``Impossible Marriage,'' a production by the Roundabout
Theater Company at the Laura Pels Theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 11 --
CANBY-THEATER, 10-8 -- Everett Quinton, left, as Lady Enid
Hillcrest in the revival of Charles Ludlam's spoofcomedy ``The
Mystery of Irma Vep,'' with Stephen DeRosa as the unsympathetic
maid. The director is Quinton, who costarred with Charles Ludlam,
the playwright, in the original production. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo) Eds: Please note that this photo can also be used with
``Theater Notes.''
</P>
