<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7438 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-NEUTRAL-ART-2     10-08 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-NEUTRAL-ART-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING THE TRACK OF AN INDEX, WITH SOME WIGGLE ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11)  
 (af)  
 By MARY CONNORS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors torn between choosing an actively managed mutual fund
and an index fund often overlook a third, lower-profile option: a
so-called sector-neutral fund. Such funds try to offer some of the
virtues of indexing, with the hope that a manager's stock-picking
skill will lead to index-beating results.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea is simple. The portfolio of a sector-neutral fund
mimics the sector, or broad industry, weightings of an index that
it tracks. Within those sectors, however, a manager is free to
choose whatever stocks he likes.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, how do sector-neutral funds perform against their
indexed and actively managed siblings? There is no easy way to
tell. Neither Morningstar Inc. of Chicago nor Lipper Analytical
Services of Summit, N.J., two leading fund research firms, tracks
them as a category. Moreover, many fund companies do not even
advertise their funds' sector-neutral approach.
</P>
<P>
   But led by a smart stock-picker, such a fund can theoretically
deliver returns that outperform its index and its peers. This is
especially likely during periods of extreme market valuations,
according to Robert Stovall, president of Stovall/Twenty-First
Century Advisers, a New York money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   In a pricey market, a sector-neutral manager can dump a stock
that is included in an index and that is trading for, say, 34 times
earnings and replace it with one in the same sector that has a
lower valuation and is thus likely to outperform.
</P>
<P>
   In a cheap market, by contrast, such a manager can pick the
fastest-growing stock, regardless of its price.
</P>
<P>
   Absent hard performance data, experts also talk about one key
perceived advantage to sector-neutral investing over active
management: It eliminates the possibility, perhaps the likelihood,
that a manager will make a big bet on an industry group that blows
up. That is a particular worry during rapidly rotating markets, in
which sectors can rise and fall in quick succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most portfolio managers are hurt by rapid rotations not
because they have picked bad stocks but rather because they have
made poor industry-sector weighting decisions,'' said Richard
Bernstein, chief quantitative strategist at Merrill Lynch, in a
conference call to brokers last March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that sector weights nearly always have a larger
influence on portfolio performance than does individual stock
selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Sector neutrality does not, however, ward off overall
volatility. In some cases, the neutral approach can temper the
market swings that are typical for a fund's benchmark, but it can
never neutralize them.
</P>
<P>
   Like an index fund, a sector-neutral fund may be more volatile
than an actively managed portfolio because a manager typically will
not be able to overweight stable stocks like utilities even if he
expects stormy markets.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of sector-neutral funds agree on one point: Long-term
success rests on the manager's ability to pick the best stocks.
Aside from that, different strategies can be adapted to the
sector-neutral technique.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Toole, manager of the Dreyfus Premier Mid-Cap Stock fund,
has been sector-neutral for 15 years. He simply considers it a less
risky approach to active management. O'Toole uses the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 400-stock index as the benchmark for his fund _ but fewer
than half of the 400 medium-capitalization stocks in the benchmark
make the cut in the portfolio. And index equities represent only 45
percent of his fund's value.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only own the best-performing stocks in each sector of the
index,'' O'Toole said.
</P>
<P>
   The process seems to work for O'Toole. Dreyfus Premier Mid-Cap
Stock returned 17.3 percent, annualized, over the three years ended
Sept. 30, versus 10.8 percent for the average mid-cap blend fund,
according to Morningstar, and 16.4 percent for the S&AMP;P 400.
</P>
<P>
   For funds that track an inherently more volatile index, however,
the sector-neutral philosophy can work more as a safety net.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Turner Small Cap Growth, an aggressive-growth
fund that is closed to new investors, swapped indexes _ going from
the broadly diversified Russell 2500 to the Russell 2000 _ to skew
toward smaller-capitalization stocks. Its new index is also more
heavily weighted to the technology, health care and consumer
sectors, and will be more volatile as a result.
</P>
<P>
   But its guarantee of sector neutrality is reassuring to
investors leery of small-cap risk, said William Chenoweth, who
managed the fund from its 1994 inception until May 1998 and is now
lead portfolio manager for Nicholas-Applegate Mid Cap Growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can go to sleep at night and not worry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's 12.7 percent loss for the year through Sept. 30 is
smaller than the 16.4 percent loss of the average small-cap growth
fund, according to Morningstar. Over the period, the Russell 2000
fell 16.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Sector neutrality may also offer advantages for investors
looking to minimize the tax bite often caused by fast sector
rotation, said Hugh M. Neuberger, director of quantitative analysis
at Wood, Struthers &AMP; Winthrop.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that gives an edge to the Winthrop Growth fund,
which he manages. Its annual turnover is just 30 percent, compared
with 120 percent for the average growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   Neuberger holds just 60 stocks and uses the S&AMP;P 500 as his
benchmark _ but with a twist. Because of the fund's growth bias, he
excludes the electric and gas utility sectors, but he keeps the
weightings of all other sectors within two percentage points of the
benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   His fund returned 20.2 percent, annualized, for the three years
ended Sept. 30, versus 17.6 percent for its average peer fund,
according to Morningstar, and 22.6 percent for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who take a circumspect view of sector-neutral funds
is Jeffrey S. Molitor, director of portfolio review at the Vanguard
Group, the index fund giant. He says sector-neutral managers take
bets that investors are not aware of.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they usually invest in fewer stocks than the number
represented in their benchmark, he said, and while their sector
weightings may be closely aligned with an index, their average
market capitalizations _ another key variable _ often are not.
</P>
<P>
   Most sector-neutral funds also do not have the rock-bottom
expense ratios of the cheapest index funds. And even as
sector-neutral investing manages to reduce some downside risk, it
also limits upside potential because it precludes overweighting in
fast-growing sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while sector-neutral funds can try to pick safer
stocks within a risky sector, they cannot eliminate their exposure.
So when a particular sector crashes, the funds will, to some
degree, follow their indexes off the cliff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to live with it,'' said Robert E. Turner,
chairman of Turner Investment Partners, the investment firm that
runs Turner Small Cap Growth and five other sector-neutral funds.
When a sector is down 7 percent and Turner's holdings in the same
sector are down just 5 percent, ``that's a victory,'' Turner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
