A7454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-DISSENT-ART-NY     10-08 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DISSENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONE REPUBLICAN SUPPORTS DEMOCRATIC INQUIRY PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Texas, Okla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(See also CLINTON-IMPEACH, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-VOTE,
CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-DAY, DEMS-DISSENT) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich urged him not to do it. So
did an angry Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House Republican whip.
But Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark., did not listen.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time Thursday for the House to vote on an
impeachment inquiry drafted by Democrats, with a deadline and
limited scope, every Republican opposed the measure. Except Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey, a three-term conservative who has nettled Gingrich
before, explained his support for the Democratic option as a matter
of conscience, principle and independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted so badly for us to have a bipartisan effort in this
matter,'' Dickey said in an interview in his Capitol Hill office
after Thursday's votes. ``I was surprised when I didn't see more of
my colleagues join me'' in supporting the Democratic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey said he backed the Democratic plan not for its specific
provisions but because it put the House on record in favor of a
formal investigation. Dickey said he also felt obliged to vote with
the Democrats because he had sponsored legislation to rein in the
scope and budget of federally appointed independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Dickey said he wanted to show his constituents in
Arkansas that he would make up his own mind on solemn matters like
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to show my constituents I wasn't afraid to go against
my party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some people in his district may still be mad at Dickey even
though he also voted for the Republican inquiry. Seventy-two
percent of his constituents want the president to resign or to be
impeached (down from 88 percent before Clinton's videotape
testimony was broadcast), the congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey has bucked the House Republican leadership before, and
has paid the price. Two years ago, Gingrich canceled a fund-raiser
in Arkansas after Dickey refused to support a spending bill that
the speaker wanted.
</P>
<P>
   As Dickey watched in amazement Thursday as every one of his
Republican colleagues rejected the Democratic plan, he said he did
not waver. Indeed, he warned his party leaders of his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``DeLay was very upset, and Newt said it was the wrong vote, but
it was a matter of conscience,'' said Dickey, who also consulted a
close friend, Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be objective, not subjective,'' added Dickey,
who worried aloud that his vote may be misinterpreted as an ``ego
trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey, a 59-year-old lawyer and former travel agent and Taco
Bell restaurant owner in Pine Bluff, Ark., has defied the odds
before. He contracted polio in college but recovered fully enough
to become the top-ranked tennis player at the University of
Arkansas in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 Dickey became the first Republican to win the 4th
Congressional District of Arkansas, which occupies the southern
part of the state, including Clinton's boyhood stomping grounds.
But he has no sympathy for the president, even though the two men
have known each other for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me once when I was a businessman,'' Dickey said,
``but we disagree on most all issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
