</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-REORG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS NEWS DIVISION CUTS ABOUT 7 PERCENT OF WORK FORCE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: N.Y., D.C., Calif., Texas, Fla.)  (jw) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As part of a broader corporate cost-cutting effort at
CBS Inc., the network's news division laid off about 7 percent of
its staff Thursday, but closed no bureaus and dismissed no
correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   The savings to the company will amount to close to $40 million,
or about 10 percent of the CBS News budget, according to people
familiar with the budget who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   CBS News issued layoff notices to about 120 people, most of them
in administrative or support positions, from a staff of about
1,600. Executives took pains to describe the reductions as a
reorganization rather than across-the-board cutbacks. Several
producers and correspondents said that this appeared to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heyward, president of CBS News, had been researching ways
to save money since midsummer, under a directive from CBS corporate
executives to all division heads to move CBS toward profitability.
All the networks except NBC lost money last year, and are expected
to do so again this year, largely as a result of higher prices they
have had to pay for entertainment shows and for football games.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News and NBC News have laid off some people, too, but they
have not announced how many.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are consolidating management functions in our hubs in New
York, Washington, Los Angeles, London and Tokyo,'' Heyward wrote in
a memorandum to the news division Thursday. ``This means fewer
people in Dallas, Miami, Tel Aviv and Moscow, but our core news
gathering strength in those places remains intact and is expected
to increase elsewhere as this system evolves.''
</P>
<P>
   The new system, as Heyward described it in an interview, relies
upon advanced satellite, cell phone and computer technology to link
correspondents and producers in the field to supervisors in the hub
cities mentioned in the memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors in the hub cities will coordinate assignments. Most
reports will be transmitted to those cities and edited there, as
well, rather than by editors sent, with equipment, to locations
where a news event is happening.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller CBS News bureaus, in Dallas or Miami, for example,
will lose management staff _ such as a bureau chief, deputy bureau
chief and clerical staff. Instead, the bureau will have at least
one three-member ``coverage team,'' consisting of a correspondent,
camera person and producer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many producers in the larger bureaus such as
Washington (whose staff was virtually untouched) will now be
expected to work for any CBS News program, as the news cycle
requires, rather than to work for only one program, such as ``The
CBS Evening News'' or ``CBS This Morning,'' as had been done in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Also, separate assignment desks for the Northeast United States,
the national desk and the foreign desk will be consolidated into
one assignment desk, responsible for dealing with all requests for
reports or elements for reports from CBS news programs.
</P>
<P>
   Al Ortiz, the executive producer of ``The CBS Evening News,''
said, ``It puts a greater burden on producers of stories to plan a
bit more, since you won't be in the edit room to look over every
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he said, those in the field ``have to use their
laptops _ send scripts faster and provide more detailed instruction
about how to organize or cut a story'' to colleagues assembling
stories in the hub-city operation.
</P>
<P>
   About six weeks ago CBS Inc. said it would cut between 200 and
300 jobs by the end of 1998, including those in the news division
that were cut Thursday. No layoffs in other divisions were made
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DEBT-450&AMP;ADD-N     10-08 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEBT-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO GETS GREEN LIGHT TO CHARGE INTEREST ON INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The Supreme Court ruled late Wednesday that it was
legal for Mexico's ailing banks to charge interest on interest. The
decision upheld a practice that is bread-and-butter basic to
banking worldwide and showed just how obsolete many of Mexico's
business laws are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have to go back and re-invent our entire financial
system,'' said a relieved Carlos Gomez y Gomez, the head of the
Mexican Banking Association.
</P>
<P>
   The high court ruling provoked protests from bank debtors who
had hoped to get judicial backing for a campaign to pay only the
principal and minimum interest on their debts, which ballooned when
interest rates soared to more than 80 percent during an economic
crisis in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Supreme Court justices resolved a conflict
between two sets of outmoded laws _ a Commercial Code written in
1890 that authorizes compounding of interest, and a broader civil
code dating from 1928 that outlaws the practice. The civil code was
enacted after the Mexican Revolution of 1917, when private business
was regarded with suspicion and legal priorities were to protect
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``An injustice was done to the highest institution of justice,''
said Salvador Rocha Diaz, a federal senator who is also a business
lawyer. ``The court was forced to decide this fundamental issue
based on laws that do not reflect reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In an argument so convoluted that only experts could make out
its meaning, the court determined that the statutes allowing banks
to charge interest on back interest would prevail. Banking
officials said that only some countries in the Islamic world now
bar the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like Alice in Wonderland; it seems so unreal that they
didn't sort this out 100 years ago,'' said Damian Fraser, director
of research in Mexico for Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez y Gomez acknowledged that Mexican banks have been
routinely charging interest on past due interest for about 20
years, even though it was unclear whether it was legal. The banks
have also been compounding interest in favor of depositors with
savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But after the crisis three years ago left many debtors reeling
under unpayable loans, their lawyers began to burrow into the
statutes to find ways out. Of about 1 million mortgages outstanding
in Mexico, some 170,000 are in litigation, according to Banking
Association figures.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to one of its basic sources of income has been
hanging over the financial system since late last year, at a time
when the banks were just getting back on their feet. Overall
capitalization had reached 17.6 percent, putting Mexican banks well
above those in most other Latin American countries, and past due
loans had finally begun to decline.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Interest rates have climbed again since July in response to the
instability of the global markets, prompting Gomez y Gomez to
recommend recently that banks should not make new loans and
customers should not seek them. This week the rate on benchmark
28-day Treasury bills, known as CETEs, was 36.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The banks are also under siege politically since the government
fumbled an attempt to refinance its $65 billion bank bailout.
Opposition groups have tied up the government's proposal in
Congress, arguing that it asks struggling taxpayers to rescue
wealthy but incompetent bankers.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual protest, members of a national debtors group
called El Barzon stood up in silence in the Supreme Court chambers
during hearings Thursday and turned their backs on the justices.
The justices ordered them removed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANGLADESH-FLOODS-NYT     10-08 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANGLADESH-FLOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOODS BREED HAVOC AND DISEASE IN BANGLADESH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Monsoon floods that lasted three times longer
than any other in Bangladesh's history have finally receded and
millions of people have begun cleaning the muck from their homes.
But the country is still struggling to cope with the aftermath:
hunger, disease and homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   A full picture of the devastation is beginning to emerge as
researchers and government workers fan out into severely affected
areas that were largely cut off. The floods lasted more than two
months and inundated two-thirds of the impoverished country, where
120 million people live.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates that 10,000 miles of roads, 14,000
schools and a million homes were heavily damaged. More than 2
million tons of rice that would have been harvested this year were
either wiped out or never planted, a fearsome loss in a country
where two-thirds of the children are seriously malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   As the mighty Padma, Jamuna amd Brahmaputra rivers have fallen
below the danger level in the past two weeks, leaving behind a
filthy sludge that nourishes disease, the number of people
afflicted by diarrhea has soared to more than 1 million, officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   The official death toll now stands at 918 _ mostly from
diarrhea, cobra bites and drowning _ but epidemiologists say that
number may rise to several thousand as reports come in from
outlying areas.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and relief workers say adequate food and
medical supplies are arriving in Bangladesh through the port at
Chittagong. The challenge is to speed distribution to the rural
areas, where most people live.
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh's prime minister, Sheik Hasina Wazed, met Tuesday
with her Cabinet ministers and instructed them to hasten the
distribution of food-ration cards to 4 million households, many of
whom lost their ability to make a living when the floods swamped
their crops, drowned their cattle and destroyed their seed stocks.
</P>
<P>
   She also ordered that a food-for-work program to rebuild damaged
roads begin by Saturday and that a much larger reconstruction
program get under way immediately, putting money in people's
pockets and food on their tables. She has asked for $880 million in
foreign aid and has received pledges of about $129 million, the
government says.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of international relief agencies praise Sheik
Hasina's administration for removing bureaucratic obstacles, but
they also worry that it is taking too long for the rice and wheat
to pass through four levels of government to the smallest
administrative unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machinery at our disposal is a good one,'' said Werner
Kiene, representative of the United Nations World Food Program in
Dhaka, the capital. ``But we need to give it more speed, and the
food needs to be pushed through this machinery.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the difficulty of treating people with diarrhea is
not a shortage of the inexpensive life-saving solution of water,
electrolytes and sugar that replenishes depleted bodily fluids, but
delivery to sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   In many areas that are still partly flooded, the waters are now
too shallow for boats to cross but the roads are still too muddy
for wheeled vehicles to pass, said A.K. Siddique, an epidemiologist
with the International Center for Diarrheal Disease Research in
Dhaka. ``We are entering the most vulnerable period, when
inaccessibility is the main constraint,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
