<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STOCK-EXCHANGES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. CITY AND STATE STRIVE TO KEEP STOCK MARKETS IN MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Working against deadlines imposed by New York's
financial markets, city and state officials are scrambling to
complete a series of complex deals that would create new
headquarters for the New York, American and Nasdaq Stock Exchanges
in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the deals could cost the city and state more
than $700 million, mainly in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The search for new homes for the financial industry has become a
high-stakes, real estate version of musical chairs, as the
exchanges _ which are also being wooed by New Jersey _ try to
extract subsidy packages and New York developers maneuver to get a
piece of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are optimistic that they can cobble together an
agreement to buy five parcels, diagonally across Broad Street from
the New York Stock Exchange, where a new trading floor and a
billion-dollar headquarters would be built. The outline of a deal
would need to be in place by the Nov. 4 board meeting of the
exchange, which has said it would consider a move to Battery Park
City or New Jersey if the city is unable to secure a location in
the financial district.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, city and state officials are trying to forge
an agreement this week with the National Association of Securities
Dealers, which owns Nasdaq and is acquiring the American Stock
Exchange, for a new headquarters for those exchanges on an empty
lot in Tribeca, in Battery Park City or at 42nd Street and the
Avenue of the Americas, near Times Square. The NASD, which met
Thursday in New York, is also considering two waterfront projects
in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a game of musical chairs,'' said Mary Ann Tighe,
executive managing director of the Insignia/Edward S. Gordon real
estate company, ``but now it looks like everybody is going to find
a place to sit down.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges are bargaining for a lot more than cuts in taxes.
The markets, particularly the New York Stock Exchange, are also
pushing the state and the city to provide cash to offset the cost
of constructing a modern trading operation.
</P>
<P>
   To clinch the deals, the city and state may have to provide $700
million in cash, tax breaks and low-cost electricity, an immense
sum but less than half the estimated cost to taxpayers of the
proposed baseball stadiums for the Yankees and the Mets, taken
together.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the city cannot afford to lose the New York Stock
Exchange, and that a deal with Nasdaq and the American Exchange
would be a coup for New York: moving the NASD headquarters and
several hundred employees from Washington to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the flight of the financial industry in New York, during
the last 15 years officials have granted nearly a billion dollars
in tax breaks and other incentives to investment banks and other
institutions. The financial industry accounts for only 5 percent of
the jobs in New York, but tax revenues linked to the industry
generated most of the city's $2.1 billion budget surplus last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     10-08 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP AWAY DESERVES TO TAKE THE CAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Skip Away is not generally recognized as one of
the all-time great thoroughbreds, it can only be because his career
lacks a single, defining achievement, something like the
record-tying, 16-race winning streak that made Cigar a household
name.
</P>
<P>
   Something like the record Skip Away is about to set.
</P>
<P>
   Should Skip Away, ridden by Jerry Bailey, defeat Gentlemen and
four others in the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park
in New York on Saturday, he would win $600,000 for owner Carolyn
Hine and become the first horse to crack $10 million in career
earnings. His new total, $10,106,360, would break the record of
$9,999,815 set by Cigar in 1992-96.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he runs as good as he looks,'' trainer Sonny Hine said this
week, ``he'll be awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Should he lose, he would get one more chance at the record, in
the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic Nov.7 at Churchill Downs,
before his scheduled retirement to stud.
</P>
<P>
   Losing is a possibility, even though the 5-year-old has won nine
races in a row and is a 2-5 favorite for the 1\-mile race in which
each horse will carry 126 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen's trainer, Richard Mandella, is pulling out all the
stops to get the 6-year-old back to the 1997 form that was good
enough to beat Skip Away in the Pimlico Special. Mandella fitted
Gentlemen with blinkers for the first time Monday at Belmont and
the result was a best-of-the-morning 58 3/5-second clocking for a
5-furlong workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm just desperate to get him one notch closer to that
('97 form) rather than admit he's just not as good this year,''
Mandella said.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen will be ridden by Corey Nakatani. The rest of the
field: Running Stag, ridden by Ray Cochrane; Fire King, Frank
Lovato Jr.; Wagon Limit, Robbie Davis; and Pacificbounty, Gary
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Cup is one of five preps Saturday at Belmont for the
Nov.7 Breeders' Cup races at Churchill Downs. Nakatani will ride
Sharp Cat in the Beldame and Lazy Lode in the Turf Clasic for
trainer Wally Dollase. Gary Stevens will ride Dushyantor in the
Turf Classic for Bobby Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   A Gold Cup upset by Gentlemen would be poetic. It was Mandella's
Dare and Go who beat Cigar when he went for a 17th straight victory
_ to break Citation's modern record for consecutive wins _ in the
'96 Pacific Classic at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does it this weekend,'' Mandella said of Skip Away,
``he'll have earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, high earnings are all relative, dependent on
longevity and timing as much as on greatness. Of North America's
top 12 career money-winners, 11 raced in the past 10 years,
enjoying the full effects of purse inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is John Henry, whose $6,597,947, earned in
1977-84, once was twice as much as any other horse's bankroll and
is now fourth on the list. John Henry would be the all-time
earnings champion if we adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it will be good to see Skip Away break eight figures. He
doesn't need the money, but he needs the distinction.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: Bob Baffert-trained Excellent Meeting, the easy Del
Mar Debutante winner, looks like a ``single'' for bettors in the
Oak Leaf Stakes for 2-year-old fillies, part of the $2
million-guaranteed pick-six at Santa Anita on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Director of racing Tom Robbins said the Oak Leaf wasn't put
earlier in the card, making room for a more competitive race in the
pick-six sequence, because of its stature as a Grade I race.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Del Mar Futurity runner-up Daring General heads the
Norfolk for 2-year-olds, and 3-year-old Magical Allure faces older
fillies and mares in the Lady's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   Add guarantees: A $5 million pick-six guarantee is planned for
the Breeders' Cup, covering every race except the Juvenile. It's an
attempt to reverse the trend that has seen bets nationwide on the
Breeders' Cup pick-six decline steadily since it debuted as a
pick-seven with more than $8.5 million wagered in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   This year's will be advertised as the ``Ultra Pick 6.''
</P>
<P>
   A grand old man: Everett Nevin, a California racing fixture who
was still serving as director of racing at Ferndale this summer at
age 92, died Thursday in Napa, Calif. He'd suffered a stroke a few
days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin's son, Dennis, is a California steward.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery deepens: Worldly Manner, the Del Mar Futurity winner
purchased from John and Betty Mabee by a still-anonymous buyer, was
shipped from Bob Baffert's barn at Santa Anita to Niall
O'Callaghan's at Churchill Downs over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And then, the Racing Form reported, the 2-year-old was vanned
out of the Churchill barns Tuesday, passing the gates under an
assumed name. His destination not announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Form quoted a source revealing only that Worldly Manner
might not run in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile and would approach the
May 1 Kentucky Derby in ``a way you wouldn't consider
traditional.''
</P>
<P>
   New look: The biggest changes in the Daily Racing Form under new
editor and publisher Steve Crist will be in evidence in Saturday's
edition.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new features: a national statistics page, 12
past-performance lines instead of 10 for horses at major tracks,
and, coming later, yearling auction prices for 2- and 3-year-olds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
