A7480 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     10-08 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOVIAL JOE DIVERSIFIES _ SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The reality is that, for better or worse,
journalist Joe McDonnell has re-invented himself. From now on, the
AM-1150 all-sports radio afternoon drive-time host is the jovial,
jocular jokemeister Joe McDonnell.
</P>
<P>
   Try to contain your laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Once convinced that breaking stories and giving listeners the
inside dope on local teams was the best way for him to succeed in
this medium, McDonnell now says the way to survive in today's radio
climate is to diversify.
</P>
<P>
   So in the last five months, hard-hitting news hasn't been
completely replaced by sophomoric pranks. It just seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I've taken so much criticism in the last five
months,'' said McDonnell. ``But at the same time, I'm getting three
times more positive response. I disagree that it's
lowest-common-denominator radio. I think we're getting the more
intelligent listener now because we're going after a broader
base.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for McDonnell's show, and for the station, have finally
started to materialize, although new station program director Mike
Thompson points out they still rank 23rd in the city with the men's
25-to-54 audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's Thompson's feeling that McDonnell's adjustment is ``nothing
more than coming back to being himself. Joe can go either way with
breaking stories and having fun. Why can't he also do both?''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Thompson: ``I don't ever want to hear a talk-show host call
himself a journalist. Red Smith was a journalist. We have knowledge
and opinions and we try to figure out what the listeners want to
hear. It's not about callers and guests. It's the host interacting
with the listeners.''
</P>
<P>
   A trend continues in sports-talk radio across the country to
skew programming more toward ``guy-talk radio'' _ more locker room
humor (even if it's female bashing), more goofs, contrived
controversy and, in a sense, appealing to the lowest common
denominator.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, all-sports WIP has succeeded with a
``guy-talk'' approach that was featured in a recent segment of
HBO's ``Real Sports.'' The premise was that sports seemed less
frequently discussed than other risque subjects that guys may talk
about over a beer.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, the all-sports station where Thompson worked before
coming to L.A. was known as ``The Ticket.'' A local media columnist
referred to it as ``The Schicticket.''
</P>
<P>
   And going back to the sports-talk genesis in L.A., the demise of
then-KMPC came for a variety of reasons, but one of them was not
attracting enough listeners with more news-topic-minded hosts like
McDonnell, Jim Lampley and Fred Wallin.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe breaking stories and pounding Del Harris into the ground
was more noble, but for McDonnell, it attracted only a small but
loyal core audience. McDonnell thinks that element, which is how
XTRA-AM (690) drive-time host Lee Hamilton (not his real name)
survives, can be incorporated within his drive-time afternoon show,
but not be the focal point.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the humor portion of this story.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, McDonnell played a tape of an Adolf Hitler
speech, in German, that he introduced as Bobby Hull's response to a
story that he made pro-Nazi remarks recently during a tour of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, McDonnell staged an interview with someone
claiming to be a former employee of Fox's Rupert Murdoch, who owns
the Dodgers. The ``guest'' claimed, among other outrageous things,
that Hideo Nomo had been traded because he refused to learn
English.
</P>
<P>
   Stop, my sides are splitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a mistake in judgment on my part,'' admits McDonnell
of the latter after receiving an immediate negative response from
the Dodgers, who changed to AM-1150 for game coverage last season.
``But in my opinion, it was harmless. It was funny for those who
got it. I think it speaks more about how our society in general is
too sensitive about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   So if the bottom line is sports-talk has slid back three rungs
on the evolution chart because craziness has overtaken credibility
_ leaving the befuddled listener to determine what's real and what
isn't _ McDonnell doesn't consider this selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have enough credibility to last a lifetime,'' said
McDonnell, 42, who recently became more lean and less mean by
losing 200 pounds. ``But really, this is just full-circle for me. I
was doing this nine years ago at KFI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is not to break stories but to keep people informed
and entertained. We're not KNX or KFWB. Journalism looks great on
the mantle, but it doesn't get you anywhere in ratings. And that's
the name of the game.'' &QL; 
A HIT TOO CLOSE TO HOME
</P>
<P>
   One of the perks Cammi Granato has as the Kings' new radio
analyst is semi-frequent reunions with her older brother, Tony, the
former Kings right wing who plays for the San Jose Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Kings faced the Sharks in an exhibition game last
Saturday in West Valley City, Utah, Cammi Granato, working just her
seventh game in on-the-job training, found out in a scary moment
what it's like when you just can't talk.
</P>
<P>
   Seven minutes into the third period, Tony crumbled to the ice
when he was hit just below the left cheekbone by a deflected puck
in front of the net. He missed 19 games last season with a broken
jaw on a similar play and is also continuing a comeback from a
brain tumor. When he immediately went to the locker room, it took
everything for Cammi not to pull off her headset and run down to
her brother's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony doesn't fall to the ice easily, so when I saw that my
heart dropped,'' said Cammi. ``The play went into the corner, so
(play-by-play man) Nick Nickson didn't see it right away. It was
very hard to refocus on the game. Right away, I at least wanted to
call down to the locker room to see how he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony took four stitches and came back five minutes later. The
puck caught him flat and missed his jawbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to stay in the locker room and change, but he
told me later he came back out because he knew that would make me
feel better,'' Cammi said.
</P>
<P>
   Cammi Granato makes her regular-season broadcasting debut when
the Kings open in Edmonton on Saturday night. In addition to
KRLA-AM (1110), the Kings radio network includes KHJJ-AM (1380) in
Palmdale/Lancaster, KBET-AM (1220) in Santa Clarita and KTRO-AM
(1520) in Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' 7 p.m. opener is part of a rare NHL TV doubleheader
by KCAL-Channel 9, which will also do the Ducks' opener in
Washington at 4 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
Fox taking the ``Catcher Cam'' to new heights during these baseball
playoffs. There's nothing more dramatic than having a catcher keep
the contraption on as he's taking a throw from the outfield and
tagging a runner at the plate (check the Cleveland-Boston series).
So far, San Diego's Carlos Hernandez has worn it in the NLCS.
Here's hoping Atlanta's Javy Lopez does the same. Thanks again to
the guys at Burbank's Areal-Video Systems. &QL; 
Fox Sports News' hiring of Rex ``The Wonder Scoop'' Hudler for
postseason coverage. &QL; 
David Letterman's Top 10 list of NBA player demands includes: No.
7. For the love of God, no more Shaquille O'Neal albums. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
NBC's think-tank tandem of Bob Costas and Joe Morgan, who are about
as relaxing and endearing on the ALCS games as the network's promos
for ``Dostoevsky's Crime and Punishment.'' Case in point: Game 2 is
tied 1-1 in the bottom of the eighth, Derek Jeter at the plate, and
Costas is debating Morgan about the definition of a baseball purist
vs. a baseball traditionalist. Smart-talk is great _ once in
awhile. But for these two cerebral giants, it's like listening to
``Point-Counterpoint'' on everything, with Costas all but bursting
out with: ``Joe, you ignorant second baseman...'' As much as Bob
Uecker was criticized last year for breaking in with inane
comments, we now appreciate the levity he once brought to the
telecast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
