<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors optimistic regarding Strawberry recovery
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The news gets better for Yankees outfielder Darryl
Strawberry. Doctors said Thursday that he should make a full
recovery and return to baseball next year.
</P>
<P>
   The hope stems from tests that show only one of 36 lymph nodes
removed from Strawberry last week had any evidence of the tumor.
Strawberry is scheduled to leave a New York hospital this weekend
and will start chemotherapy treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Score critical after wreck
</P>
<P>
   Former Indians pitcher and broadcaster Herb Score was seriously
injured Thursday when his car pulled in front of a tractor-trailer.
Score, 65, is in critical condition at Aultman Hospital in Canton,
Ohio, with hip, head and pelvic injuries. . . . October continues
to be a struggle for Yankees first baseman Tino Martinez. Back in
1995 when he was playing for Seattle and faced the Yankees in the
divisional series, he hit .409 with one homer and five RBIs. He's
since a combined 19-for-108 (.176) with one homer and four RBIs.
``It's very frustrating,'' said Martinez, who is 0-for-9 in the
ALCS this year. ``I feel good, I'm relaxed and, all of a sudden,
I'm trying to make things happen that are not there. I'm swinging
at 3-2 pitches that are out of the zone. I'm striking out on bad
pitches. I'm trying to do too much instead of letting things happen
and unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's office is reportedly upset at Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner, who threw baseball's public relations staff
out of the team's offices Wednesday, saying he needed the space for
an accountant. But the Yankees said baseball officials made their
own decision to move out of the office to a quieter work space.
Also, the Yankees and Red Sox were fined an undisclosed amount for
not following postseason media guidelines, such as working out on
off days. . . . After what happened in Game 2, Steinbrenner said
the American League should be stripped of its authority over
umpires. ``You bring the officiating under the commissioner's
office,'' he said. ``It doesn't belong under the league offices,''
he said. Like many, Steinbrenner said umpires used in the
postseason should be based on merit and not seniority. ... At
Yankee Stadium, New York fans taunted Cleveland's David Justice
with chants of ``Halle Berry, Halle Berry.'' Berry, an actress, is
Justice's ex-wife and word in the tabloids is they are considering
getting back together.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
