<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klesko's dash: It's `hero or zero' time
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Those who thought Ryan Klesko ought to have his head
examined after daring to go from first to third on a Javy Lopez
single Wednesday night got their wish. Klesko had X-rays taken on
the side of his face to see if his nose was broken after his
booming collision with third baseman Ken Caminiti's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko said the X-rays were inconclusive and he may need more.
He's been sore, his left nostril has been bleeding and he's had
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   So how's he breathing? ``Through one nostril,'' Klesko said.
``I'm just glad I'm back in the lineup. I thought I broke it.''
</P>
<P>
   The left fielder added, ``Even if it is broken, it's OK. As long
as it's not crooked, what can you do? I just hope no one taps me on
it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko blamed his helmet, explaining that as he slid in
headfirst, his helmet came down.
</P>
<P>
   Just what was he thinking? ``It's a lot easier to score on
(Trevor) Hoffman from third than from second,'' he said. ``That's
one of the plays where if you don't risk it, it's 'What is he
doing?' It's all hero or zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko didn't realize that anything was wrong until he looked up
at the umpire and tried to ``give a little help'' on the call.
``That's when things started to get fuzzy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Making Glavine's case
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Glavine and Hoffman the frontrunners for the Cy Young
award, Greg Maddux said he'd pick Glavine for his second Cy. ``I
think you've got to go with wins,'' said Maddux, who will pitch
Saturday in San Diego. ``That's why you play. You don't play the
game to strike guys out, you play the game to get guys out. You
just play to win. And Glav (20-6) won more games than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux noted that Glavine is throwing better against lefties
than ever before. Left-handers are hitting .245 against Glavine in
220 at-bats, right-handers .235 in 630.
</P>
<P>
   Long haul, not long ball
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was just 21 years and four months old when he hit
his 50th career homer _ making him the third-youngest in major
league history to reach that mark, ``I don't call myself a home run
hitter,'' said Andruw Jones. The center fielder, who his 31 this
season and now has 54 in his career, added a third-inning homer
Wednesday to tie the game at 1. ``I call myself an all-around
player,'' Jones said. ``I do whatever I need to do to help the team
win the game. If I need to hit a home run, I hit a home run. If
somebody make a mistake, you hit the home runs. I'm not like (Mark)
McGwire, or (Sammy) Sosa or (Andres) Galarraga; I can't hit them
every day. I can, but I don't look to do that. I just go out and do
my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming out pitching
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield was going for a strike
out, not a knock out when he threw the first pitch before
Thursday's game. Holyfield's throw was over the inside corner to a
right-handed batter. But if there'd been a real batter, and he'd
hit him, who better in a brawl?
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Jack Wilkinson and Thomas Stinson contributed to
this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
