<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' heartbreakers holding a reunion
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So many have taken turns driving spikes through the
postseason Braves that there's now enough of them to hold a
full-blown reunion.
</P>
<P>
   They gathered at Turner Field this midweek, in the mood to trash
the place and relive old glories. There seems to be a powerful bond
between those who have denied the ``Team of the '90s.'' They even
wear the same uniform, with Padres writ large across their heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, My Name Is Jim Leyritz,'' read one name tag at the
gathering. It was across the street, where cars and armed
highwaymen now park, that Leyritz hit his home run ultimately
turning the 1996 World Series away from Atlanta, toward New York
Yankee clutches. Since then, he has been passed around like a bad
cold, only to show up back here as the Padres' designated
bail-bondsman.
</P>
<P>
   Never think for a moment that Leyritz would treat his infamous
eighth-inning home run off Mark Wohlers as an accident of fate.
Popping a couple more out against Houston in the division series
just past, he believes himself a master of the moment. When the
Padres acquired Leyritz from Boston in late June, he proclaimed,
``Somewhere down the line (the Red Sox) are going to miss me being
there. When it comes down to crunch time, hopefully those kids will
come through for them. I know I would have. I've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Braves were starting to get over him, he comes
back, head shaved for that always attractive death row look. During
Wednesday's Game 1 of the National League Championship Series, he
stepped up as a pinch-hitter and created problems even though he
didn't get the ball out of the infield. It was his dribbler that
set in motion Andres Galarraga's two errors that pushed across one
of San Diego's three runs. He can pummel, or he can prickle.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's Game 2 starter, Kevin Brown, is another of the great
foils in Braves history. It only intensifies the irritation that he
is a neighbor, with his Macon and Georgia Tech connections.
</P>
<P>
   As a Florida Marlin, of course, the great grump Brown twice beat
the Braves in the last NLCS. When the Marlins blew up, Brown landed
in San Diego. There is no getting rid of Brown, he's the kudzu
growing on the Braves reputation.
</P>
<P>
   A new face to the gathering is Andy Ashby, who pitched so well
in Game 1 of this NLCS, and was 2-0, with a 1.80 ERA against the
Braves this season. According how this series unwinds, he could be
a permanent member of the Braves-bashers, invited back for all the
mixers and golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Morris, Kirby Puckett, Ed Sprague, Lenny Dykstra and Livan
Hernandez were unable to be here, and they send their regrets.
</P>
<P>
   There's a basic problem when a franchise's list of
heart-breakers is threatening to grow longer than its roster of
heroes. It tells you that here in October where every move is
subject to DNA analysis, the Braves often have broken beneath the
scrutiny. Entering Thursday's Game 2, there was the great need for
someone in a Braves uniform _ maybe even someone other than a
pitcher _ to make the dramatic play, to stand tall when it mattered
most. Maybe Chipper Jones could stay with a tag this time, or drive
in a run or three. Or Galarraga might stir from his autumn daze.
Just to make this party interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
