<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gwynn spokesman for media-shy team
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For what might generally be considered playing for a
small-market club, the San Diego Padres tend to be a media-shy
bunch. Most of them sought shelter in the player's-only lounge
rather than venture into the clubhouse after winning Game 1, and
that speaks volumes about their accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   A major exception is Tony Gwynn, the club's elder statesman and
resident philosopher. Gwynn didn't go to bed until 5 a.m. after
Game 1 and was back at Turner Field by noon Thursday, offering his
baseball pearls before and after Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   _On the postseason: ``You get in the postseason and the first
thing that jumps out _ TV controls everything. ... You know they
want to see Atlanta-New York. You can't worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   _On a sub-par 1998 season by his lofty standards: ``This is one
year where I got to convince myself I can still play. I struggled,
but I think I know why. I don't think it's age. I don't think I'm
there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   _On when he'll know when to retire: ``I can't say I have to do
this and this. It's not numbers. I'll know. You hope you're man
enough to step up and say it's time to go. ... I'd ike to play
through 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   _On his post-playing career: ``I thought a few years ago that I
might want to be a GM. Not anymore. The game is changing ... but I
believe I should be in the game somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   What pressure?
</P>
<P>
   First, left-hander Sterling Hitchcock found himself matched up
with Randy Johnson in Game 4 of the NL Division Series _ and won.
Now, in Game 3 of the NLCS, he draws four-time Cy Young winner Greg
Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no pressure on me,'' Hitchcock said. ``I'm not supposed
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn ready
</P>
<P>
   With a strained left quadricep suffered Wednesday night on a
Chipper-Jones line drive, Greg Vaughn understands why he can't play
the outfield. But he made it very clear to manager Bruce Bochy that
he's ready to swing a bat.
</P>
<P>
   So would he be able to pinch-hit in a couple of days?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be able to pinch-hit in a couple of hours,'' he said
prior to Game 2. ``I've been a quick healer in the past and I can
tolerate a lot of pain. The only thing is in the outfield, I don't
want to be the reason for us to lose the ballgame because I can't
run to get a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres medical staff thinks the injury will keep Vaughn out
``possibly three to four days, but it could be up to 10 days,''
said manager Bruce Bochy. He said he'd check with the doctors to
see if Vaughn can hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be OK, but I feel like I let the team down because I
waited until this point in the year to get hurt,'' Vaughn said.
``They depend on me to be out there with them to go to war, and I
can't go to wa ... right now.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 starter Kevin Brown, born in McIntyre and living now in
Macon, has the strongest Georgia ties, but he isn't the only Padre
hailing from the state. Probable Game 4 starter Joey Hamilton
spends his offseason in Atlanta and Wally Joyner is a Redan High
graduate. ... Technically, the Padres continued their late-inning
dominance by taking Game 1, 178-0 since late in the 1996 season
when leading after eight innings. Padres closer Trevor Hoffman blew
a ninth-inning save opportunity, but Ken Caminiti's 10th-inning
homer nailed down the win.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
