<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prices at root of fan apathy?
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a lovely night for baseball _ 62 degrees,
14-mph winds blowing left to right _ but Game 2 of the National
League Championship Series Thursday began with many, many empty
seats at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   There was no threat of rain like the night before, when the
weather helped produce the smallest playoff crowd in Atlanta
history, 42,117.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, Atlanta's reputation as being indifferent or
apathetic to the postseason is being examined. It's a story as old
as David Justice, the former Atlanta outfielder who once chided the
town for sleeping through World Series games.
</P>
<P>
   One local sports talk radio station has already had Mayor Bill
Campbell on live trying to stroke the city's psyche. But the bulk
of the mayor's chat may represent part of the problem: He asked his
studio hosts what he should bet the mayor of New York on the World
Series. Like many Atlanta fans, he appears to be already looking
ahead to a matchup with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger truth may be economics. ``There is a little fan
apathy,'' fan Jan Watson said. ``They expect us to win. I was kind
appalled to hear that these games weren't sellouts. But (Major
League Baseball) raising the ticket prices didn't help any.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the NLCS cost $45 and $75.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is a serious Braves fan. She has season tickets in the
upper deck and showed up Thursday night in her lucky Indian
headdress. But she said she had to come up with more than $1,000
for two tickets to the playoffs and Series. In cash. No credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very good job and can afford these, but some people
can't,'' she said. ``The deadline for ordering the postseason
tickets is Sept. 4 and the refunds for games that are not played
you don't get back for eight weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons for poor fan turnout: Day games have been a tough
sell in Atlanta, and, some say, the Braves just win too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you ever get used to winning,'' David Yuhasz
said, but the fans do have their limits when it comes to
inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Yuhasz fought the traffic, then the rain, went
so far as to pay to park and then bailed out of going into the
stadium. ``I was betting on a rainout and getting to use those
tickets again,'' he said. ``If they'd had a fireplace in here, I'd
have come in and curled up to go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   He, too, said baseball is pricing itself out of fan support. ``A
family of four getting the most inexpensive seats ($35 each) would
have to spend $140, then maybe $100 on top of that for food. That's
a lot of money for a family outing when they could call Domino's or
Pizza Hut and order a pizza for twenty bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
