<SLUG> BC-BBN-TUCKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Like most postseason series, this one is on the pitchers
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Vaughn hit 50 home runs this season, more than
anyone in the National League except those two guys who chased,
caught and passed Roger Maris. He is, you'd surmise, a significant
piece of the San Diego Padres' team.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, when word came Thursday that Vaughn possibly would be
sidelined for the rest of the NLCS, you didn't sense a dramatic
shift in the balance of power between the Padres and the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Nor even a subtle one.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty percent of San Diego's team home-run total was deleted
from the lineup with one strained left quadricep muscle, suffered
by Vaughn the night before. Bad break for the Padres, yes, and
certainly one that made it easier for Tom Glavine to navigate the
middle of their batting order Thursday night. But this series does
not hinge on sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   It hinges, as do almost all postseason series, on the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Houston had the most prolific offense in the National League
this season, yet did nothing against San Diego in the Division
Series. Sammy Sosa hit 66 home runs in the regular season, yet hit
nothing against the Braves in the first round. The Yankees managed
one run in 12 innings against Cleveland Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you know October baseball works. This is old hat around
here, as attested by all those empty seats in the upper deck in
right field. Whichever team pitches the best wins, provided that
team also makes the plays defensively, executes a few little things
offensively and has a modicum of good fortune here and there.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-homer hitters are, in a word, optional.
</P>
<P>
   ''The teams that are in postseason, they have the dominating
pitching in their league,'' Bobby Cox was saying before Thursday's
game. ''And you're running up against an outstanding starter every
single night. Guys like Pedro Martinez, (Kevin) Brown, (Greg)
Maddux, (John) Smoltz, (Tom) Glavine, (Andy) Ashby, they don't give
up runs even during the regular season. Nothing honestly changes
much during the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that the starting pitchers with the marginal stuff and
lofty ERAs are home for the winter _ along with a lot of power
hitters whose teams didn't have enough pitching to get to the
second week of October.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that neither Mark McGwire nor Sosa are still
playing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how this San Diego team compares offensively with last
year's Florida team, Greg Maddux said: ''Really, all the teams are
the same that you face. Everybody has one or two guys that can run,
one or two guys that hit for power, one or two who hit for average.
Some righties and some lefties thrown in there. ... And I think
this whole pitching staff believes that good pitching will beat
good hitting any day of the week, regardless of who you're
facing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's ability to play defense, not his ability to swing a
bat, will solely determine when or whether he gets back in the
lineup. Bruce Bochy, the San Diego manager, said heprobably will
miss three to four days, possibly up to 10 days. That diminishes
the Padres' offense, sure. But it doesn't diminish their chances of
winning this series, which hinge on who's pitching, not who's
playing left field.
</P>
<P>
   And so, with Vaughn's 50 homers on the bench, Brown and Glavine
went at it Thursday night, just as Ashby and Smoltz did on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
