A7631 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-DWIGHT-CO     10-08 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DWIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dwight has 2 gears: fast and warp speed
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You knew someone like Tim Dwight. He was the little
kid in grade school who always seemed to be in motion, talking all
the time, driving everybody nuts.
</P>
<P>
   There was a scab on his forehead, his nose, somewhere. Half the
class wanted to beat him up, but nobody could catch him. If they
did, he'd battle to the end.
</P>
<P>
   He was the pest.
</P>
<P>
   Well, tiny Tim has grown up _ sort of. He's the smallest Falcon
at 5-feet-8, and 181 pounds, nearly juvenile as ever, and still a
pest of sorts. But now it's NFL teams he's driving bananas, as a
rookie kick returner, wide receiver, running back and even passer
for the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight was named NFC special-teams player of the week after
returning the opening kickoff 93 yards for a touchdown in last
Sunday's 51-23 blowout of Carolina. For good measure, he threw a
22-yard pass to quarterback Chris Chandler, and carried the ball
two times for 7 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes all out on every play,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves
said. ``He hits that crease at 90 mph, and he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things haven't changed much in Dwight's 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   He's always been fast: ``In sixth grade, he went to (AAU track)
nationals,'' said his father, Tim Sr. ``He would have won (the 200
meters), but he fell out of the blocks ... got up and finished
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight's always lived his life at high speeds, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to try to get a bit of an `edge' once in a while,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So a couple years ago, he jumped off a 90-foot cliff into the
Wisconsin River. ``It was higher than I thought,'' he said. ``On
the way down, I was like, `Oh ... my ... God!' ``
</P>
<P>
   We're talking a change of pace here, a guy who, despite a
$225,000 signing bonus as a fourth-round draft choice out of the
University of Iowa, drives a friend's very beat-up 1987 Isuzu
``Pup'' pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   After practice Wednesday, Dwight was doing back flips _ with no
hands!
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a wild character,'' recalled Jacksonville rookie
running back and former Iowa teammate Tavian Banks. ``He'd come to
practice with his face painted. I remember he jumped out of a
four-story dorm (three, Dwight said) into a snow bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to wrestle (former Iowa teammates) Scott Slutzker (a
6-4, 250-pound tight end with the Saints), and Ross Verba (a 6-4,
304-pound tackle with the Packers). He had a few moves, then it
would be over, he'd get flattened, and he'd get up talking trash.
He's just hyper.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight said that's not quite accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not hyper; I couldn't control myself. I was just active,''
said Dwight, who, according to his father, refused training wheels
while learning to ride a bike. ``I couldn't sit around the house. I
liked being outdoors, playing sports, being with my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons like Dwight.
</P>
<P>
   When he showed up in June, with a scab on his nose from a
``scrap'' with a friend, Chandler gave him the nickname ``Mutt.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, does it fit. Dwight often dresses like he's getting ready
to rake leaves, needles people ceaselessly, gives kidney shots to
unsuspecting reporters, drives that truck, and with a prematurely
receding hairline and very little, very short blond hair, he looks
the part.
</P>
<P>
   But this mutt can haul.
</P>
<P>
   He used his speed _ good enough to qualify for the NCAA meet in
the 100 (top time of 10.31 seconds) and 200 (top time of 20.99)
meters _ to set a slew of school records at Iowa. He has a season
of track eligiblity left, and will run next spring while finishing
his sports-management degree.
</P>
<P>
   He led the NCAA last year with a 19.3-yard punt return average
and three TDs. While at Iowa, he returned five punts for TDs,
rushed for six TDs and an 8.7-yard average, threw for two TDs,
caught 127 passes and 21 TDs, and occasionally played defense.
</P>
<P>
   He caught a 44-yard TD pass in the opening game, a 19-14 win at
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And he's doing other things. Two weeks ago, he debuted in the
Falcons' backfield, rushing two times at San Francisco for 7 yards,
and running a reverse for 5 yards. He also got a new scab on his
nose.
</P>
<P>
   With running back Byron Hanspard out for the season with a knee
injury, Dwight, who's the same height and three pounds heavier than
Tampa Bay running back Warrick Dunn, will continue to work a little
at halfback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to use him that way because he's
explosive,'' Reeves said. ``He's a heck of a football player, and a
tough son of a gun. But he's got to learn to dodge some of those
guys instead of running over them (or trying to hurdle them).''
</P>
<P>
   True to his Midwestern roots, and a good bit like his father, a
high school history teacher, head track coach and football
assistant, Dwight was raised polite, sincere, and straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   After living his entire life in Iowa City, he said, ``I love
Atlanta because people are nice. Plus, I can go out and people
don't know me. I tell them I'm a construction worker, or a
third-grade teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight has always had that wide-open throttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have wooden steps going to the basement with openings
between the steps,'' said his grandmother, Betty Tiemeier. ``(When
Dwight was a boy) the boys were down there, and all of a sudden,
Tim's cousins came up and said, 'Oh, Grandma, come down quick.
Timmy's stuck!'
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he could get his head through the steps. Grandpa
had to go down and get the crowbar and pry the step loose to get
him out.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't pry the Dwight family loose from the TV on Sundays.
They'll charter a bus for family and friends, and drive it to St.
Louis when the Falcons play the Rams on Nov. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, they gather around the TV at Tim's parents' home
in Iowa City. They went a little nuts last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought a satellite dish, and got the NFL package,'' his
father said. ``We're real strong on family. We have a lot of
relatives and friends over. We cook up a big pot of chili, and have
a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional when Timmy took that kickoff back. We
were all jumping up and down, and (Dwight's mother) Nancy gave me a
hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
