<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chiefs eye erratic Bledsoe
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The good news for the New England Patriots is that
Drew Bledsoe got through the first three games of this season
without throwing an interception. The bad news is that the
sixth-year veteran may have picked the most inopportune time to
have his erratic persona surface again.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe tossed three interceptions last week and the Pats needed
a last-minute field goal to edge underdog New Orleans. Now fast
forward to Sunday, when the Patriots face Kansas City in this
weekend's best matchup. If last week represented one of those dips
which have characterized Bledsoe's rollercoaster career, he could
have a difficult time getting back over the hump against the
opportunistic Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year in and year out, we pride ourselves on taking (the ball)
away from people,'' said Chiefs cornerback Dale Carter, whose
third-quarter interception was the turning point in last Sunday
night's ``Monsoon Bowl'' victory over Seattle. ``It's just a
mindset with us. We create a lot of opportunities for our
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the previous 10 seasons, the Chiefs led the league in
turnover differential, with a plus-96 mark. Not surprisingly, coach
Marty Schottenheimer's club enters the game at Foxboro Stadium with
an NFL-best 16 takeaways in '98. That total includes 11 fumble
recoveries, tangible evidence of the emphasis coordinator Gunther
Cunningham placed on stripping the ball in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Patriots and Chiefs figure to be no worse than
wild-card teams, there is a sense of urgency for both franchises
this week. New England could open a solid lead in the AFC East over
the next few weeks as rival Miami faces a daunting schedule. The
Chiefs probably would fall two games behind undefeated Denver in
the AFC West if they lose to the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaches have stressed wrapping up the ball at all times,''
said Robert Edwards, the former Georgia tailback who has
re-energized the New England rushing game. ``Against the Chiefs,
that's a must. Those guys have very busy hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the ``bests'' for this weekend:
</P>
<P>
   _ Upset opportunity: Starting with the marquee Chiefs-Patriots
game, the possibilities abound. Atlanta could dump the flagging
Giants. Chicago will have as many expatriate fans at Sun Devil
Stadium as the Cardinals. The Jeff George-less Raiders may struggle
at home against San Diego. But we like the Bengals, who have only
beaten the Steelers once in the last seven meetings in Cincinnati,
to prevail. An already shaky Pittsburgh offense is reshuffling the
line again. That could be a treat for Bengals coordinator Dick
LeBeau, who once plied his zone-blitzes in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual matchup: When people note Carolina linebacker Kevin
Greene ``knows all the tricks,'' it's a polite way of saying the
league sack leader bends the rules. And Dallas offensive tackle
Erik Williams has led the NFL in holding and
illegal-hands-to-the-face penalties the last two years. It could be
Flag Day at Texas Stadium on Sunday when the two square off on
passing downs. On Monday night, watching Jacksonville tackle Tony
Boselli block Miami speed-rusher Jason Taylor will be interesting.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy play: The Tennessee secondary is a step slow and
Baltimore wideout Jermaine Lewis is a flat-out sprinter. Ravens
quarterback Eric Zeier will hook up for at least one bomb to Lewis
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grudge match: If George Young were still the Giants general
manager, it would spice up Dan Reeves' return to New York. Instead,
Bengals quarterback Neil O'Donnell will feel some heat from his
former Steelers teammates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Division game: The Saints probably can't match up with San
Francisco's three wide receivers. But innovative New Orleans
defensive coordinator Zaven Yaralian could keep things close for a
while by creating pressure on Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
