<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road Atlanta fans begin arriving for Petit Le Mans
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The world of sports car racing, temporarily
headquartered near Braselton at Road Atlanta, must be sending
telegrams back to Europe and the Far East marveling at how Don
Panoz controls the weather.
</P>
<P>
   While the Braves were a washout until the wee hours of Thursday,
the first practice for Saturday's Petit Le Mans had near perfect
weather Thursday afternoon. Bright sunshine, nice breeze, no need
for a sweat towel around the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many fans were on-site yet, but the Johnson family of
Marietta has already staked out the second-best site at the track.
The Porsche tent about 50 yards away has the best.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnsons, Ivy III, Gayle, sons Ivy IV, Jimmy and Mi-chael,
are at Road Atlanta for the weekend with two family tents and a
screen tent serving as the kitchen. The site is two feet from the
chain link fence opposite the area known as the ``esses.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where cars running 100 or so miles per hour uphill from
turn one have to brake, downshift and zig-zag down to about 50 mph,
trying to stay in control and not hit anybody and then hit the
accelerator again. It gets hairy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where all the wrecks happen,'' said Ivy III. ``This is
the best kind of racing I've ever seen. It's a lot better than
NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: ``It'll take until about next Thursday to get our
hearing back.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ever sees the field go all the way around a road course,
there are too many hills, but there is a huge amount of space along
the fence and around the infield of the 2.6-mile course.
</P>
<P>
   Those who haven't been at Road Atlanta since July are astonished
at the changes. There is a new, huge paddock and pits area on the
infield side of the track where the Le Mans cars are staged.
</P>
<P>
   Early arrivals got some early thrills by watching practice
sessions Thursday. The 24 Hours of Le Mans winning No. 26 Porsche
911 GT showed its speed and agility as drivers Uwe Alzen of
Germany, Yannick Dalmas of France and Scotland's Allan McNish took
their turns and ran up a fast-lap speed of 124.79 mph. The No. 5
Panoz, driven by Eric Bernard, Paris, Johnny O'Connell, Phoenix and
Jamie Davies of England was the fourth-fastest at 121.24 and No. 4
GT1, driven by David Brabham, England, Andy Wallace, France and
Scott Pruitt of Granite Bay, Calif., was seventh-fastest at 119.72.
The hybrid V8/electric Panoz GT1 had a best lap of 117.47, good
enough for 10th-fastest of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
