<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOBAL TURMOIL MAY SLOW NATION'S BUOYANT ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   The financial markets were jittery as more investors began to
fear the country cannot avoid the economic slowdown that has
gripped much of the world. The value of the dollar dropped further,
interest rates rose and the prices of many stocks fell.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 7,731.91, lower by
just 8.78 points after being down as much as 274 points during the
day Thursday. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 11.24
points, or 1.16 percent, to 959.44, while the Nasdaq index dropped
43.49 points, or 2.97 percent, to 1,419.12, its lowest close in 16
months.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury securities ended mixed, with selling by hedge funds
battering the long end of the market even as shorter maturities
were bolstered by weakness in equities. The 30-year bond fell more
than two points for a second consecutive day, while the yield rose
to 4.99 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England cut its benchmark interest rate by
one-quarter of a percentage point, reflecting concern about global
financial turmoil and fears of recession among British exporters
and manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   NO TAXES FOR CYBERSPACE PURCHASES
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted overwhelmingly to make cyberspace a tax-free
zone for most transactions for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE DEALS MICROSOFT A SETBACK
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge dealt Microsoft a setback in its antitrust trial
preparations by denying the company access to the interview tapes
and transcripts for a new book written by two business school
professors.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES ROSE 4.5% LAST MONTH
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales at stores open at least a year rose 4.5 percent in
September with discounters reporting strong gains, while department
stores had only slim gains.
</P>
<P>
   CBS NEWS CUTTING 120 EMPLOYEES
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heyward, the president of CBS News, has laid off about 7
percent of the network's staff, or 120 workers, in an effort to
save $40 million, or about 10 percent of the CBS News budget.
Competitors ABC News and NBC News have also reduced their staff,
but have not announced by how many.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. TO BEAR MOST OF IMF BURDEN
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund and the World Bank wound up
their annual meetings saying that the United States will bear most
of the burden of helping Asia and the rest of the developing world
get out of a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Congressional leaders presented the Clinton
administration with a list of lending conditions that they want
imposed on the IMF in order for Congress to approve $18 billion in
new money for the fund.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL ELECTRIC PROFIT RISES 13%
</P>
<P>
   Third-quarter profit rose 13 percent at General Electric,
matching expectations. Sales rose 9.8 percent, less than the 15
percent to 20 percent increase predicted.
</P>
<P>
   OIL COMPANIES FORM JOINT VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Petroleum and Ultramar Diamond Shamrock are forming a
joint venture called Diamond 66 that will run 10 refineries and
more than 12,000 gas stations in 36 states and six Canadian
provinces.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN COURT APPROVES INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Supreme Court decided that it was legal for that
country's banks to charge interest on interest, a practice that is
bread-and-butter basic to banking worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   $2.8 BILLION STOCK TAKEOVER OF JACOR
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel Communications is buying Jacor Communications, the
broadcaster for Rush Limbaugh, Dr. Laura Schlessinger and other
radio personalities, for $2.8 billion in stock. The combined
company would rank third in radio revenues, behind CBS and
Chancellor Broadcasting, and second in number of stations.
</P>
<P>
   EIGHT STATES IN TOBACCO TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The $198 billion national settlement being negotiated by lawyers
for the tobacco industry and eight states would allow cigarette
makers to absorb part or all of its costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
