<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-HNS     10-08 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The National League Championship Series is far from
locked up, but the San Diego Padres are doing some serious fiddling
with the dead bolt.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All along, the Atlanta Braves have said the key to winning the
best-of-seven series was whether they could beat Padres ace Kevin
Brown. Maybe they should try the spare key.
</P>
<P>
   Brown slammed the door on the Braves with still another
masterful postseason pitching performance, tossing a three-hit
shutout to lead the Padres to a 3-0 victory Thursday night at
Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres own a 2-0 lead in the series and could clinch their
first NL pennant since 1984 in front of the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The series shifts to Qualcomm Stadium for Games 3 and 4, and 5,
if necessary, beginning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This constitutes new ground for the Braves, who never had
dropped the first two games of a series during their dominant
stretch of postseason play in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the Killer B's and Co., the Braves had no luck
unlocking the mystery of Brown, who lowered his ERA to a
microscopic 0.38 this postseason. He has 32 strikeouts and has
allowed just eight hits in 23 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter Tom Glavine allowed only one run, but he pitched
around trouble all night and was no match for Brown, who also was
2-for-4 at the plate and scored an insurance run for the Padres in
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine walked five batters in the second and third innings,
escaping bases-loaded predicaments each time. At one point, he
threw eight consecutive pitches without a strike.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as much a case of Glavine being wild as it was his
refusal to give in to opposing hitters. Four of the walks during
that stretch were issued to Ken Caminiti and Wally Joyner _ the
Nos. 4 and 5 hitters in the Padres' batting order.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the lineup started a two-out rally in the sixth
inning when Glavine finally ran out of ways to escape trouble.
Chris Gomez, Brown and Quilvio Veras hit consecutive singles, with
Gomez scoring on Veras' base hit up the middle to give the Padres a
1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres had runners in scoring position in four of their six
innings against Glavine. It was a laborious night for the Braves
lefthander, who threw 83 pitches in the first four innings and 121
for the game. Glavine allowed six hits and walked six before
turning the game over to reliever John Rocker to start the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown retired nine of the first 11 batters he faced and didn't
allow a hit until Chipper Jones' one-out single in the fourth
inning. He only allowed a pair of harmless singles the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres cushioned their lead against rookie reliever Odalis
Perez in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown got things started with a leadoff single and scored on a
single by Veras, who was 3-for-4 with a double. Veras scored the
Padres' final run on Joyner's infield single with the bases loaded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0492 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7669 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-AGGIES-HNS &LR;      10-08 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ Looking back on the previous time Texas A&AMP;M
played Nebraska, the Aggies described the experience as
humiliating, embarrassing, sickening.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I hated every second of that game,'' center Seth McKinney
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts your pride when you get slaughtered like we did,''
said tight end Dan Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months later, the Aggies describe another chance to play the
Cornhuskers as ``fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Little would seem to have changed in the teams since December.
A&AMP;M is ranked 18th, a solid team built around a strong defense and
a skilled but unspectacular offense. Nebraska is No. 2, with all
the usual strengths despite one narrow escape against Oklahoma
State in a Big 12 game.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the Aggies get the Cornhuskers in Kyle Field. For
all of the Aggies' much-repeated troubles against top-10 teams _
they have lost all nine games against top-10 opponents this decade
_ they seldom have faced a national power in College Station. The
last visit from such a high-ranked team was 15 years ago, when
Texas was No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest game all of us have seen around here in a
while,'' said Cameron Spikes, a senior offensive lineman from
Bryan. ``It's the biggest one I can think of in A&AMP;M's history.
Having played them once before and playing them at our house will
be a big plus for us. It's just fun. We have the biggest
opportunity right in front of us to beat one of the best teams in
college football for the past 10, 20 years. If you can't get
excited to play this type of game, you shouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Excitement has not been a problem. For other programs, a bowl
trip is unique. A conference-championship game, a relatively new
addition to college football, would be a novelty for most programs.
But for A&AMP;M, getting a top-ranked team in Kyle Field brought
feelings rare even with the assorted bowl and championship games
the Aggies have played in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking more forward to this game than if it was just some
other team coming in here this week,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said
Tuesday. ``The day-to-day preparation will be fun, the meeting with
the coaches will be fun, and I think our practices will fly by this
week. Playing this type of game is really what it's all about. I've
got more friends and cousins coming out of the woodwork wanting to
see the game this week. It intensifies everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment is most striking because it represents such a
turnaround from the A&AMP;M attitude the previous time the Aggies met
Nebraska. The Cornhuskers rolled to a 54-15 win. They led 37-3 by
halftime and didn't need even that long to put away the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caught them last year when they were smelling the national
championship,'' Slocum said. ``They had lost the year before in the
conference-championship game. Their coach (Tom Osborne) was going
to retire. They had everything going their direction, along with
being a very talented football team. They were a good football team
hitting on all cylinders when we played them. We got off to a bad
start and really never made a contest out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say we were in awe or intimidated, but the
game was pretty much over before it started.''
</P>
<P>
   But his players demurred. It was instantly over, they conceded,
but they had to admit the reasons their coach did not want to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little bit in awe,'' A&AMP;M quarterback Randy McCown
said. ``That was the first time we played a team like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into that game against a team used to playing a game
of that magnitude,'' A&AMP;M running back Dante Hall said. ``It was new
to us playing that type of team and a championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies insist the experience changed them. Hurt at
first, they said they were hardened and will be different when
Nebraska sees them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that happened to us, we were embarrassed,'' Campbell
said. ``We came in, and we worked. We recognized what they did to
us, and that's what we want to do to people. Ever since that time,
we've tried to practice at the level we think they've been working
at. And I think our work level is a lot better than it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Spikes, ``All the guys thought we could play with them, and
we prepared well. We were ready to go. But out there in the first
quarter, we were wide-eyed. `That's Nebraska and this is us in the
Big 12 championship.' We kind of took the first quarter off, and it
showed. With the four wins under us and the way we played Florida
State, we have the confidence knowing what it takes to play the
better teams in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said evidence could be found in the Aggies' subsequent
games. A&AMP;M led UCLA and Florida State at halftime. And though the
Aggies could not hang on to win either game, they were far more
competitive than against Nebraska. And neither was at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys competed in the second half and some of the
aura of their team may have wore off a little bit,'' said Slocum,
who is 50-5-1 at home in his 10 seasons as A&AMP;M coach. ``Then, we
played a good UCLA team and I didn't see any of that. I didn't see
any of that when we played Florida State. I think maybe that
(playing Nebraska in the Big 12 title game) helped us grow a little
bit. Since that time, we have played several good teams, and I
think we'll be a little more relaxed going into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest difference could be that A&AMP;M will be at home.
Because of the renovations to Kyle Field, capacity will be only
about 58,000, more than 20,000 off the Kyle Field record.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies insist the smaller crowd will still be a huge
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes us feel 100 percent better playing at Kyle Field than
somewhere else,'' Spikes said. ``Everybody's cheering for you
except for the 3,500 Nebraska fans. Everybody is on your side, and
everybody wants you to win. This crowd will be so intense and so
lit up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
