<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALCS-KNOBLAUCH-HN     10-08 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-KNOBLAUCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
CLEVELAND _ Chuck Knoblauch spent Thursday morning watching replays
of the costly mistake that seems to have turned an entire city
against him.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Later in the day, he did the only thing he could: apologize and
take full responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of possibly holding a 2-0 lead in the American League
Championship Series, the New York Yankees enter tonight's Game 3 at
Jacobs Field tied 1-1 with Cleveland following the costliest goof
of Knoblauch's eight-year career.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests that one memorable play can define a career.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Bill Buckner is doomed to infamy for letting a grounder
go through his legs in the 1986 World Series. If the Yankees go on
to lose the ALCS to Cleveland, the image of Knoblauch _ frozen at
first base, arguing, with the ball lying a few feet away while the
lead run scored _ will forever be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up. I screwed up the play, and I feel terrible about
that,'' Knoblauch, the Yankees' normally dependable second baseman
and Houston native, said Thursday. ``I should have gone after the
ball, regardless of what the outcome of the umpire's call was. I
basically screwed up the play and feel bad. I need to apologize to
my teammates and my manager, the Yankees and all the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's teammates were more than willing to forgive and
forget. But as he has begun to learn in his brief time in the Big
Apple, fans and the media aren't as charitable.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers rarely show mercy _ even to their own.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-year playing career in Minnesota left Knoblauch
unprepared for the attention he has received following Wednesday's
game-turning mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly portrayed as a villain, he was loudly booed when he
stepped to the plate in bottom of the 12th inning. It didn't get
any better Thursday. Among the headlines in the New York tabloids:
``Brainlauch,'' ``Blockhead,'' ``Blauchhead,'' and ``Cryin'
Shame.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching the replays over and over in his hotel room,
Knoblauch said he understands the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing it from their perspective, they were booing me for
screwing up the play,'' said Knoblauch, acquired by the Yankees
last February from the Twins. ``You can't fault them for that, and
they're going to react to what they see. When you screw up a play
and it costs us the game, that's the kind of treatment you're going
to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the play could not have been worse for Knoblauch,
who has failed to live up to the high expectations surrounding his
trade. He encountered bouts of throwing lapses in 1998 and did not
hit as he had in previous years, finishing with a career-low .265
average.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always this way. In his Rookie of the Year 1991
season, Knoblauch was part of making someone else the goat.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 7 of that year's World Series against Atlanta, Knoblauch
and Twins shortstop Greg Gagne tricked Braves baserunner Lonnie
Smith, causing Smith to hesitate near second base on teammate Terry
Pendleton's long double in the eighth inning of a scoreless game.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the infielders' deception, Smith had to stop at third
base. The Braves failed to get him home, and the Twins won the
World Series with a 10-inning, 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cleveland scored the go-ahead run in the 12th
inning when Knoblauch, covering first base on a sacrifice bunt,
didn't chase the ball after Tino Martinez's throw hit Travis Fryman
and bounced about 30 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of retrieving the ball, Knoblauch began complaining that
Fryman had interfered with the throw by running out of the runner's
lane.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Buckner's infamous play, Knoblauch said he doesn't
believe The Play is what people will remember him for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I never play another game, this is what I'll be remembered
for,'' Knoblauch said. ``But hopefully, we can wipe that out
(tonight). Hopefully, I'll have a long career in New York with a
lot of good times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees held an optional workout Thursday afternoon in
chilly drizzle at Jacobs Field. Few players attended the workout,
but Knoblauch felt compelled to address the national media.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be good times and bad times, and you've got to face
the facts one way or the other,'' he said. ``That's the type of guy
I'm trying to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether from his teammates or the Indians, both sides understood
what Knoblauch was going through.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland general manager John Hart, who lost out in the bidding
war for Knoblauch during the offseason, said his first season in
New York has done nothing to change a favorable impression.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing with New York, Knoblauch had expressed interest
in playing for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't pay the price. It wasn't out of lack of love. We
thought Chuck Knoblauch would have been a good fit in Cleveland,''
Hart said. ``He's always impressed me as a down-and-dirty player
with talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre said, ``He made a mistake. He
overreacted to the umpire and underreacted to the ball. But you
can't do anything about yesterday. You've got to move on. The only
thing you can do is learn from it. That's something you hope only
happens once in a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the harsh treatment in the press, Indians manager Mike
Hargrove had a solution for Knoblauch: ``If he wants to come play
for us, he's more than welcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
