<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOV-DEBATE-COX     10-08 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOV-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush brushes off jabs MacKay throws during Florida debate
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Waving a copy of legislation allowing school
prayer, Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay demanded to know during a statewide
television debate Thursday night whether Jeb Bush would veto it.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who said he had ``no intention of acting like a southern
gentleman,'' also took jabs at Bush about his support of school
vouchers, his opposition to abortion rights, his business career,
his campaign contributions and his lack of government experience.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Bush, the frontrunner in the campaign for
governor, simply shrugged off MacKay's attacks. When handed a copy
of the prayer legislation, Bush just chuckled and said
dismissively, ``Wow, good.'' Bush also refused to directly answer
the question, saying only that he would give any such legislation
careful thought.
</P>
<P>
   When the hourlong debate ended, MacKay said he hoped that Bush
felt the sting of MacKay's undaunting attack on his political
record. For his part, Bush said with a laugh, ``My mother has been
more mean to me than he was tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKay stayed the aggressor throughout the debate, which aired
opposite the NBC ratings hit Friends. MacKay's goal Thursday night
was to highlight the issues he believes will turn voters against
Bush. MacKay, despite stumbling during his opening statement and
often appearing ill-at-ease, stuck to his script.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who seemed smooth and comfortable during the debate, was
determined not to get embroiled in a shouting match. He stuck to
his favorite themes about leadership with vision and bringing new
ideas to government. He rarely challenged MacKay directly but when
he did, he attempted to portray MacKay as out of touch with average
Floridians.
</P>
<P>
   The format, questions from studio audiences in four cities, did
not allow for follow-up questions or any real give-and-take between
the two candidates. MacKay wore glasses and some observers said
that MacKay, 65, appeared much older on television than the
45-year-old Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Several times MacKay responded to questions from the audience by
asking about campaign contributions Bush has received from oil
companies. MacKay demanded to know what the oil companies have been
promised by Bush. MacKay suggested that Bush might allow offshore
oil drilling along the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opposes offshore oil drilling and said that voters do not
need to worry about his contributions from oil or other interest
because ``my principles are rock solid.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKay told viewers, ``You have seen a clear choice here. A
choice between someone who has proven experience.'' And he warned
that Bush is ``someone who is very articulate but whose business
record raises more questions,'' about his ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush countered by saying MacKay may have more government
experience but he has put it to little use. ``The current
administration has had eight years to make things happen,'' he
said. ``Leadership is not about how many years you have in
government. It's about vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush came into the debate strengthened by poll numbers that his
campaign believes make it nearly impossible for MacKay to defeat
him in November. Bush's advisers expected MacKay to lash out at
Bush during the debate but were confident that no matter what
happened, as long as Bush did not make a major blunder, the debate
would have little impact on the outcome of the election.
</P>
<P>
   Not only behind in the polls but well behind in campaign
advertising dollars as well, MacKay wanted to use the debate to
stimulate excite his core base of support and take some of the
luster off Bush. By generating excitement about this debate, MacKay
hopes he can build momentum leading into the next two debates.
</P>
<P>
   A similar strategy worked for Gov. Lawton Chiles four years ago,
when by the third and final debate, Chiles sent Bush reeling and
won the election by 62,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is far from over,'' said Frank Greer, MacKay's media
adviser. ``Lawton Chiles was behind in the polls four years ago and
if MacKay does well in the next three debates we'll turn this thing
around. A lot of people are just now starting to focus on the
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the debate, both Bush and MacKay came separately to
the television studio to study the position of the podiums, the
cameras and lights and to discuss strategy with media advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's media adviser, Mike Murphy, complained that the podiums
were too close together. At his insistence, the podiums were moved
another 15 inches apart. MacKay's adviser, Greer, had no concerns
about the set.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, nursing a bronchial infection, arrived in Orlando just
before noon with his wife, Columba. MacKay arrived in Orlando with
his wife, Ann, about an hour earlier and went directly to the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Bush attended a post-debate rally with
hundreds of supporters at the downtown Marriott, which Bush had
made his headquarters hotel.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay returned to the Radisson where he had a conference call
with hundreds of supporters attending debate parties in 100
locations around the state, including one at the home of state Rep.
Lois Frankel, D-West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and MacKay confront each other again on Tuesday when they
will participate in a statewide radio debate that will be aired at
11 a.m. from Orlando. Their final climatic debate will be a
statewide television debate on Oct. 20 broadcast at 7 p.m. on NBC
stations. That debate will be moderated by Meet the Press host Tim
Russert.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's debate will air three times on the Sunshine
Network: 7 a.m. Sunday and Monday, and 5 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
