<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC LIVES: JUDITH KAYE, TIM ZAGAT, PAMELA HARRIMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JAMES BARRON with ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A View of Legs Beneath the Robes
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORk _ It is, Chief Judge JUDITH KAYE declared with the
deliberateness one might find in an on-the-one-hand,
on-the-other-hand ruling, ``not your typical, everyday judicial
photograph.'' She also called it ``striking'' and ``not the
photograph I'm going to choose for the courtroom when I leave the
bench.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a full-color Annie Leibovitz photograph of Judge Kaye,
seated at the bench in the Court of Appeals, the state's highest
court, in Albany. It fills two pages in the November issue of
Vanity Fair in an article about 200 women the magazine calls
``legends, leaders and trailblazers.'' Among them are two justices
of the U.S. Supreme Court, SANDRA DAY O'CONNOR and RUTH BADER
GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that the photograph showed a lot of leg,
Judge Kaye said, ``That was not deliberate.'' She said her only
goal in posing for Miss Leibovitz had been ``to make the court more
human.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She came to the court on a day when the court was not in
session,'' the judge said, ``but we were having a press conference
on court reorganization. I took center stage at the press
conference, but as soon as she wandered out, everyone started
paying attention to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Four-Star Takeout For a Special Client
</P>
<P>
   Normally the pristine, pricey restaurant JeanGeorges doesn't do
takeout. But Thursday, a squadron of waiters and chefs carried
lunch for 40 across Columbus Circle to the office of the Zagat
restaurant guides.
</P>
<P>
   TIM ZAGAT, who publishes the guides and paid for the meal, said
that ordering in was a longstanding tradition at deadline time: the
1999 New York City guide is to be published next Friday.
``Sometimes you find out that Bouley's food didn't travel very
well,'' Zagat said. ``That was last year. He was way downtown. By
the time the stuff got here, it was cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagat had no complaints about the food JEANGEORGES VONGERICHTEN
sent over, which included crab salad with mango, cumin crisps and
grainy mustard; loin of lamb dusted with black trumpet mushrooms,
and tarte Tatin.
</P>
<P>
   And the bill? ``I haven't seen it yet,'' Zagat said. The
estimate from Vongerichten was $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not including tip.
</P>
<P>
   Scoffs and Sarcasm For Harriman Film
</P>
<P>
   If Pamela Harriman were alive, she might be miffed.
</P>
<P>
   At an invitation-only screening of the made-for-cable film
``Life of the Party: The Pamela Harriman Story'' (based on
Christopher Ogden's biography of the late U.S. ambassador to France
and longtime benefactor of the Democratic Party) the audience
laughed at the lines spoken by the actress playing the woman once
colloquially known as one of the world's greatest courtesans.
</P>
<P>
   First the Ogden character (played by John O'Hurley, who played
J. Peterman on ``Seinfeld'') asks, ``Is it true that Averell left
you $145 million?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Harriman _ played with hair-sprayed, lusty blondness by
ANN-MARGRET _ responds, ``Frankly, I didn't focus on that.'' The
audience guffawed.
</P>
<P>
   RICK FRIEDBERG _ who is married to the film's producer, FRANCINE
LEFRAK _ played a federal judge. At the screening, he whispered
ominously to his seatmate, ``What you can't necessarily attain in
politics you can find in film.'' (For several years Friedberg had
the title of, no kidding, director of advance at City Hall.)
</P>
<P>
   After the screening, the 400 guests drank white wine and
reminisced about Mrs. Harriman, who died last year at 76.
Bandleader PETER DUCHIN, who had his dust-ups with Mrs. Harriman,
sounded somewhat less than gracious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I profoundly wish the swimming pool scene had been longer,''
Duchin said, referring to the place of Mrs. Harriman's death.
``There should have been more glub-glub-glub.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
