u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-08 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN EXPERT VIEWS THE KNOBLAUCH PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes planning is overrated, and good TV benefits
from serendipity.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the former umpire Steve Palermo was the guest of
NBC's Bob Costas in the Yankee Stadium broadcast booth for Game 2
of the American League Championship Series between the New York
Yankees and the Cleveland Indians. Palermo and his wife, Debbie,
were visiting the city, and Palermo is friendly with Costas. ``I
keep his number with me and if there's a chance for a rules
interpretation, I call him,'' Costas said.
</P>
<P>
   Through 11-plus innings, Costas and Joe Morgan handled the
calls, until Travis Fryman's bunt led to a contretemps that called
for an umpire's touch.
</P>
<P>
   Palermo watched the play unfold, then observed as Costas and
Morgan parsed it in numerous replays: Fryman sacrificed, ran inside
the baseline, was plunked in the back by Yankee first baseman Tino
Martinez's throw and advanced to second base as the ball rolled
toward right field and Enrique Wilson scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd seen the replays and I asked, `Do you want to go on?'''
Costas said Thursday. ``He said, `Sure.' He wasn't anxious to
disagree with a colleague, but his intent was to look at the play
and analyze it as an umpire would.''
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, Palermo rendered his verdict: Fryman was guilty of
interference and should have been called out by the home-plate
umpire, Ted Hendry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule calls that one or both feet must be on the line or
inside the 45-foot lane,'' he said. ''If you are astride the line,
you are to be called out. If you're outside the box entirely, then
you ought to be called out.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Costas if umpires will not make the call unless the
interference is blatant, he said, ``There's no such thing as
intentional or unintentional interference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you think Fryman should have been out?'' Costas asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Palermo said.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after, Palermo said he was not reluctant to
critique Hendry's noncall, but added that a broadcaster has more
tools, and time, to assess a play while an umpire has only one
quick chance to invoke judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to criticize my colleagues,'' said Palermo, who
spent the 1995 and 1996 seasons analyzing the Yankees part-time for
the MSG Network. ``But hopefully, you can educate people as to
what's going on down on the field. What I said was from up here,
this is how I would have ruled. Ted Hendry doesn't have the view
from above. When you're an umpire, lots of things are exploding in
front of you all at once. It was a difficult call to make. I'm not
shouting, `How can you not make the call?' That sounds so easy.
It's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Palermo understood the defense of Hendry, mounted by Jim Evans,
the umpires' crew chief, that Fryman had a right to be in fair
territory when the ball hit him because first base is in fair
territory. ``It's common sense that he has to come into fair
territory,'' Palermo said. But, as he said during the game: ``From
the time he leaves home plate to the time he arrives at first base,
he was entirely inside the line. So you determine he has to be
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan was more equivocal than Palermo. Morgan focused his
analysis more on the failure of Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees'
second baseman, to chase the rolling ball rather than stand around
and demand an interference call.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan acknowledged that Fryman ran where he shouldn't have. Had
Martinez's throw hit Fryman when he was out of the running lane,
Morgan said, he should have been called out. But it hit him in fair
territory, as he approached first, a gray area that even Palermo
said the rule book offers little guidance on.
</P>
<P>
   Palermo's cameo role raised the question of why more umpires
have not become announcers. Certainly, there have been articulate
umpires capable of doing the job, but Palermo and the late Ron
Luciano were the only ones to cross over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another side of the game to hear explanations from an
umpire,'' Palermo said. ``You can say things that make fans say, `I
didn't know that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Costas offered another view: ``If you had an umpire on a network
broadcast, ideally he's there as the third man in the booth,
commenting less frequently than the main analyst, not because
umpires don't know baseball, but if you find a former player or
manager, their direct experiences cover more aspects of the game
than an umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   Off camera, Costas said, Palermo suggested that one reason
Hendry's strike zone ``seemed portable'' Wednesday was that
pitchers David Cone and Charles Nagy ``throw pitches with
late-breaking action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, an umpire can give up on a pitch the way a batter
can,'' Costas said. ``He wasn't critical of Hendry, he was just
giving insight into something an umpire faces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
