<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-FUND-INVESTIGATE-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PROSECUTORS ACCUSE PAROLE OFFICIAL OF PERJURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A member of the state parole board has been charged
with repeatedly lying when questioned about whether the board gave
preferential treatment to an inmate whose family contributed to
Gov. George Pataki's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a federal indictment unsealed Thursday, the parole board
member, Sean McSherry of Chester, N.Y., was accused of misleading
investigators and a grand jury looking into the release of a
teen-age gang member serving time for violent felonies who was
freed by the board at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager's father is a prominent Korean-American minister
in Queens who enlisted the help of a Pataki aide to win the release
of his son and contributed $1,000 to the Pataki campaign. Others
linked to the minister gave several thousand dollars more to the
campaign, officials involved in the case said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment lays out the first charges in the investigation
by the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn, which has placed several
members of the Pataki administration before a grand jury examining
the campaign's fund-raising practices. The inquiry began in January
after the parents of another inmate complained to the authorities
that a volunteer fund-raiser had offered to help their son win
parole in exchange for campaign contributions but had not kept his
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki administration officials have vehemently denied that
anyone received favors from the state government in return for
contributions. On Thursday, Pataki's re-election campaign accused
the U.S. attorney, Zachary Carter, of playing politics with the
case, questioning why the indictment was announced less than a
month before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   McSherry, 46, pleaded not guilty at his arraignment in U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn to an eight-count indictment charging
him with perjury, obstruction of justice and making false
statements. He declined to comment, but after the proceeding, his
lawyer, Mark Spund, assailed the indictment as ``totally without
merit,'' and echoed the campaign's criticism of Carter, who was
appointed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is a politically motivated indictment prior to
an election, and we look forward to a speedy trial and his
vindication,'' Spund said. Carter declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's Democratic opponent, Peter Vallone, the New York City
Council speaker, called the indictment evidence of what he said
were the Pataki administration's troubled ethics. ``By now, Al
D'Amato and George Pataki surely understand that their insatiable
appetite for money inevitably leads to corruption,'' Vallone said.
</P>
<P>
   A former assistant district attorney in the Bronx, McSherry was
appointed to the parole board by Gov. Mario Cuomo, a Democrat, in
1989 and re-appointed by Cuomo in 1994. He is a member of the
Conservative Party and a friend of the party's leader, Michael
Long, who is a close adviser to Pataki.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McSherry is on a medical leave of absence from the 19-member
parole board. Long said McSherry had been hospitalized for a
``slight breakdown'' caused in part by the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials involved in the case who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said prosecutors were looking into whether McSherry lied
in order to protect more senior officials on the parole board or
elsewhere in the Pataki administration. But prosecutors have
declined to discuss who else is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The gang member, John Kim, was released by a parole board panel
in a 3-0 vote in April 1996 after serving four years of a
4-to-12-year sentence. He had pleaded guilty to a string of violent
robberies in Queens. Although he had a clean record in prison, the
Pataki administration had been tightening its standards for
releasing violent criminals on parole. In 1996, more than 60
percent of the violent felons who qualified for a parole hearing
were denied.
</P>
<P>
   In Kim's case, the prosecutors who had put him behind bars
strongly objected to his release.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's father, Nam Soo Kim, is pastor of the Full Gospel Church
of New York, one of the city's largest Korean-American churches. He
sought the help of a friend, Grace Koh, an adviser to Pataki on
Asian-American affairs, who wrote and called the parole board on
Kim's behalf. Nam Soo Kim has said his contribution was not
connected to his son's parole.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he got help from Yung Soo Yoo, a Korean-American
businessman who had raised money for the Pataki campaign in 1994
and was named by Pataki to his transition committee. Yoo wrote the
parole board saying that he would hire John Kim upon his release,
according to the inmate's father.
</P>
</TEXT>
