<SLUG> BC-NY-KNOBLAUCH-JEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNFORGIVING NEW YORKERS RIP YANKS' KNO-`BLOCKHEAD' 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In German, Knoblauch means: a) garlic; b) someone who
makes incredible mental mistakes at the worst possible times; c) a
person who, having erred, should be pitied; d) the second coming of
Bill Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to the dictionary, is garlic. But for many
New Yorkers, the name Chuck Knoblauch is probably better defined by
the other descriptions, as well as a few others that are not
printable.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch is the New York Yankees second baseman who, as anyone
who has turned on a television or seen a tabloid cover in the last
24 hours knows by now, made a monumental mental error Wednesday
night during Game 2 of the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   During a disputed play in the 12th inning of a 1-1 game,
Knoblauch did not retrieve the baseball, stubbornly arguing with an
umpire while the Cleveland Indians' Enrique Wilson rounded the
bases to score the run that put Cleveland ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It was not just the kind of play that disappointed fans. It was
the kind of play that left jaws dropping, a blunder that seemed
more suited to Charlie Brown _ another Charles tagged with the
nickname ``blockhead.''
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, New Yorkers took up what their city has raised to
a fine art: piling on the goat of the hour. Some took pity on
Knoblauch, saying that people make mistakes all the time, and that
to vilify him would send a bad message to children. Others, though,
blasted his blunder as unforgivable, saying that he did something
no Little Leaguer would have got wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think it would almost be a reflex by now, so it's
hard to have sympathy'' said Louis Tuchman, a tax lawyer at Kaye,
Scholer, Fierman, Hays &AMP; Handler, who has attended Little League
games as a parent. ``In the tax world, it's kind of like getting
all your tax extensions, signed and sealed, and not putting it in
the mailbox. Or how about this: it's like doing the work for a
client and not sending out the bill. What are you, nuts?''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch did apologize to his teammates and Yankee fans
Thursday at a news conference, saying that he could understand why
people were so angry at him because ``I screwed up.'' The news
conference was at Jacobs Field in Cleveland, a site where he might
receive a warm, albeit sarcastic, reception for Game 3 on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   But actions speak louder than words, and unless Knoblauch
becomes the second coming of Mantle or Ruth and carries the Yankees
to an expected victory in the World Series, his play on the field
figures to be the talk _ or rather, the shout _ of a town that has
been obsessed with this remarkable, record-destroying Yankee team.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers would not have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about New York is supercharged, and in a place
where there's this much tension, there's a greater need for a
catharsis,'' said former Gov. Mario Cuomo, who played semi-pro
baseball before delving into the blood sport of politics. ``Fans go
to ball games to purge themselves of all kinds of emotions. And
booing is very much a part of that experience. So I'm not surprised
at the reaction to Knoblauch.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was pretty vicious, in some arenas. The New York
Post screamed, ``BLOCKHEAD'' and ``CHUCK BRAINLAUCH.'' Newsday
declared, ``Chuck It Up to Stupidity.''
</P>
<P>
   At Paragon Sports in lower Manhattan, a salesman who declined to
give his name said that he had sold seven ``Knoblauch'' jerseys
Thursday. Not.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you, kidding? No one wants to be near that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sports radio station, WFAN-AM, Knoblauch was not exactly
a fan favorite. Yes, the talk-show hosts tried to be civil, saying
that the Yankees had missed many great scoring opportunities in
Game 2, and that a loss was just a loss for a team that has been by
far the best in baseball this year.
</P>
<P>
   And yet one host, Steve Somers, couldn't resist saying:
``Knoblauch deserves to get spanked. He had more of a presence of
mind to blow a bubble than to retrieve the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Other callers invoked the memory of Bill Buckner, the
much-maligned former first baseman for the Boston Red Sox, who, to
the delight of New York Met fans, lost a routine ground ball
through his legs, giving the Mets a victory in Game 6 of 1986 World
Series. But while Buckner's gaffe was physical, Knoblauch's was
mental _ something that callers found less excusable.
</P>
<P>
   All this invective from New Yorkers did not square well with
Boyd Trolinger, however.
</P>
<P>
   Trolinger was a close friend of Knoblauch's when they played
baseball on the same high school team in Houston: Chuck as a star
shortstop, Boyd as a first baseman. And he said that anyone who
doubted Knoblauch's baseball talents did not know a man who grew up
as the son of a prominent baseball coach, and has lived and
breathed baseball ever since he was a toddler.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't find a baseball player who knows the rules
better,'' said Trolinger, 31, who is now a doctoral student in
Native American history at Texas Tech. ``I never knew Chuck to do
anything to betray his friends or his team. He would never have
done anything consciously to jeopardize the outcome of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a good number of people who have been associated with
competitive baseball seemed to commiserate with Knoblauch, who is
considered one of the best second-basemen in the game, despite a
mediocre season, his first in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gannon Sr., whose namesake son was a member of the Toms
River East team that won the Little League World Series
Championship last month, said that one of the lessons that the
parents imparted to their children was that baseball is a team
sport, and no one play makes or breaks a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
