<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO MAY HAVE LIMITED ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the first puck drops for the Kings on
Saturday night in Edmonton, there's a strong possibility a healthy
Ray Ferraro will be watching in street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   As wrenching as that may seem for a 34-year-old center with two
40-goal NHL seasons on his resume, Ferraro sounds as if he's come
to terms with the limited role he is expected to have with the
Kings this year.
</P>
<P>
   This has not always been the case. Coach Larry Robinson said
Thursday that Ferraro, a career 333-goal scorer, has more readily
accepted the utility role than he might have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it has to do with your family and your age
and not wanting to be uprooted and enjoying your surroundings and
enjoying the people you play with,'' Robinson said following a
Forum practice at which Ferraro skated on a line with Steve McKenna
and Roman Vopat, who have scored 10 NHL goals between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to be as fair as we can with Ray and up-front
about what his status is and what we expect from him. That's all we
can do. Ray has come in here with a great attitude. He played well
in the exhibition games and in practices he's been working his butt
off. That's all you can expect of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro said: ``I told (general manager Dave Taylor) last week
my No.1 priority was to stay here. I don't want to go anywhere. I
like the guys, I like the staff, and I want to be part of this
team. If I have to be patient to get my chance to play, then I just
have to make sure I'm ready when the time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro was left unprotected in Monday's NHL waiver draft, and
went unclaimed. Given his age, his salary ($1.75 million) and the
fact that he was riddled with knee problems last season, his
availability in the draft and the lack of interest were not
surprising, even to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells me there are some serious questions of whether I can
play anymore,'' Ferraro said.
</P>
<P>
   He is hoping to prove he can. But if he ends up not playing
much, there's a strong possibility Ferraro will end his 15-year
career after this season. A career in broadcasting appears to await
Ferraro, who has previously done work for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is, I just love sports, not just hockey,''
Ferraro said. ``I'm one of those guys who can remember somewhat
needless sports drivel and I like to talk about the game. So it's
not really a stretch for me to get in front of the camera. I'm not
nervous. That's half the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg update: Time is almost up for the Kings to sign Aki Berg.
The 21-year-old defenseman, playing in his native Finland because
of a contract dispute, must sign before the Kings open the season
Saturday or he will be lost for the year. After the season starts,
he'd have to clear waivers before rejoining the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are believed to have offered Berg a one-year contract
for $625,000. Berg made $425,000 in base salary last year, but he
and his agent, Larry Kelly, believe he should be paid at least the
$825,000 he earned when factoring in the $1 million signing bonus
he received from the Kings after they drafted him in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
