</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SURVIVOR-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-TIME SURVIVOR HAS NO USE FOR SELF-PITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two years ago, a story swept like a bad fire through
the breast cancer community:
</P>
<P>
   Amy Langer, the vivacious and popular executive director of the
National Alliance of Breast Cancer Organizations and herself a
breast cancer survivor, was in a car accident and had lost her
legs. She had pulled her car over to the side of a road and another
car had crashed into her, severing both legs at the knees. Her
husband and 4-year-old child were with her.
</P>
<P>
   All true. But before we get to the subject at hand _ a project
Ms. Langer would rather discuss than her accident _ a few more
stories about Amy Langer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Langer's first words to her husband as she awoke from
surgery were: ``Oh, my God, Charlie! Kindergarten applications!
We've got to get on this immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   While still hospitalized, Ms. Langer had a fax machine
installed, because it was August, when her organization completes
plans for Breast Cancer Awareness Month, October.
</P>
<P>
   She is not crazy about people who plant themselves in her path
and do the misty-eyed, urgent, ``But how are you _ really?'' thing,
probably because Amy Langer in a wheelchair has more energy than
most New Yorkers do on their feet: She makes three or four trips to
Washington a month. She oversees a $4 million annual budget. But
she doesn't shy away from references to what she calls ``my
disability'' either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very complicated having prosthetic legs built if you need
knee joints, but it's also fascinating,'' Ms. Langer, 44, says at
her Upper East Side brownstone, where she is wearing a sweater and
a full, long skirt that is disturbingly limp below the knees.
``I'll be taller. That's one of the good things about this. I have
others. Never ruining your shoes in the rain, never having to see
the subway again.''
</P>
<P>
   And, after giving her cup of coffee to a photographer who has
offered to carry it up the stairs, ``The thing about this
disability, it makes coasters of all my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Langer's preferred subject: the Save the Day campaign, next
Friday, to raise money for mammograms for underserved women.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in decades, deaths from breast cancer are
going down for white women and Hispanic women _ 1.9 percent a year
for the last few years,'' Ms. Langer says. ``But the death rate for
black and Asian women is rising. That has to do with income. A poor
woman can't get the best care. That's unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Langer was not a poor woman when she was diagnosed with
breast cancer at 30, back in 1984. A graduate of Yale with an
M.B.A. from Harvard, she was a senior vice president at Lehman
Brothers. She earned so much money that she is a little embarrassed
to reveal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many zeros,'' Ms. Langer says. ``Many.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not worry about her health. Ms. Langer's mother had died
of ovarian cancer when Ms. Langer was 20, but it was not known then
that breast and ovarian cancer are sometimes genetically linked.
Still, as Ms. Langer had cystic, lumpy breasts and there was cancer
in her family, her doctor ordered a mammogram.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Langer enacts the scene: fast-track woman, waiting. ``I go
to the office,'' Ms. Langer says, ``and sit with my papers spread
all over every seat, underlining things with my yellow marker.
`Squeeeek, squeeeek, squeeeek.' I have the test done and go back to
my papers. `Squeeeek, squeeeek, squeeeek.' Then it was _ '' here
Ms. Langer mimes a grim nurse with a beckoning finger _ ```You.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Langer did not hide the fact that she had cancer. She left
copies of articles about breast cancer on her desk, and one
colleague, prompted to have a mammogram, found a cancerous lump.
Ms. Langer realized how powerful education could be.
</P>
<P>
   She became executive director of Nabco, as it is known, in 1990,
the same year she married Charles Andrew Langer, a businessman. On
Aug. 11, 1996, there was the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in upstate New York, on one of those roads where you
see a car every five miles,'' Ms. Langer says. ``Our son had fallen
asleep in his car seat and we pulled over to put him on the back
seat. I went to the trunk to get a blanket and I got hit by a car
going 50 miles an hour. The driver had fallen asleep. I never lost
consciousness. When the ambulance crew came, I was giving them
directions: `I have lymphedema in my left arm, don't give me
anything there, watch the transfusions.' Later, when I could get
around, I went to the helicopter evacuation crew to thank them.
They said: `Oh, it's you! You didn't shut up until they put you in
the operating room. That's how we knew you were going to be OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Ms. Langer has not had rough days. ``I
loved to dance,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to walk on prosthetic legs was difficult. It was also
difficult when the producer for a television news program broke a
promise to show her only from the waist up. ``I looked really
weird. I was very upset,'' she says. ``I called my therapist and
she told me it probably wasn't as bad as I thought. She came over
and watched it with me and afterward, she said: `You're right. It's
bad.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Langer did not turn down the news program when she was asked
to return. She and her husband dug out her prettiest high boots and
weighed them down with Beanie Babies. Ms. Langer had the boots
glued to the stage in front of her wheelchair. Then she went on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-08-98 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981008.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-08 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
