u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-INTERNET-NYT     10-08 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION INTERNET SHOPPERS: NO NEW TAXES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Wyo., Ore., Ark., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted overwhelmingly Thursday to make
cyberspace a tax-free zone for most transactions for the next three
years, following the House in trying to help incubate a new engine
of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it grow out of its infancy before we let the tax man put
his teeth into various parts of its anatomy,'' said Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., in debate Wednesday. But Sen. Dale Bumpers,
D-Ark., who voted against the bill, complained in debate, ``I'm for
computers, I'm for technology, but I'm not for allowing them to
erode the tax base of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, the Internet Tax Freedom Act, had bipartisan support,
with many senators showing great optimism about the Internet's
prospects, even if they were uncertain about how it worked. The
Clinton administration likes it, too, taking a more anti-tax
position than some conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate versions call for a study panel and a
moratorium on new Internet taxes by state and local governments,
but the bills have to go to a conference committee to resolve minor
differences. The bill, which was passed 96-2, was backed by many
Internet companies and, after much negotiation, even the National
Governors Association acquiesced, despite its members' hunger for
sales tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the bill sought to treat sales of merchandise on
the Internet in the same way that phone or mail-order transactions
were treated. Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., the main Senate sponsor,
called it ``technological neutrality.''
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 jurisdictions could impose taxes, the supporters
noted, saying that given the decentralized nature of the Internet,
several might try on any given transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from merchandise, the bills try to block taxes on
information. Eight states, including Connecticut, already tax
Internet access, and their taxes would be grandfathered in if the
states affirmed within a year that they intended to tax Internet
access. But ``bit taxes,'' fees on electronic commerce based on the
volume of digital information transmitted, would be barred.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's main sponsor in the House, Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif., said it was based on a simple principle that information
should not be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said taxes on Internet transactions were acceptable if they
were the same as taxes imposed ``if it were conducted in a more
traditional manner, such as over the phone or through mail order.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, few consumers pay taxes on phone or mail-order
transactions, either. Generally, companies that sell goods by
catalog or over the Internet are supposed to collect sales taxes
and send them to the jurisdiction that the purchaser lives in if
the selling company has a store or other substantial presence in
the purchaser's state.
</P>
<P>
   But the study commission will face difficult questions. Wyden,
for example, raised the case of someone who accessed America
Online, which is based in Dulles, Va., to order a box of fruit from
a grower in Medford, Ore., paid for it with a credit card from a
bank in California and had it shipped to a relative in Boston.
Others pointed out that the Internet often defied borders; someone
in New York, for example, could pay a service provider for access
to the Internet but use the service on a laptop in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman argued that leaving the Internet alone need not create
tax winners and losers. ``The reality is, electronic commerce has
the potential to expand the winner's circle,'' he said. He cited a
hardware store in Hartford, Coastal Tool and Supply, that had first
gone on the Web because its retail sales had been hurt by the
opening of a large chain store nearby. Now, he said, ``sales have
grown almost 500 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Michael Enzi, R-Wyo., a former mayor of Gillette and a
former co-owner, with his wife, of a shoe store there, said that
denying local governments the ability to tax Internet transactions
would create ``electronic loopholes'' and deny tax revenue to the
governments most responsible for providing services. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
