<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-TV-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX OFFICIALS TELL OF TALKS ON A DEAL WITH LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives from the Fox Broadcasting Co. said Thursday that they
have been negotiating with representatives of Monica Lewinsky to
buy rights to her account of her affair with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would include a primetime interview on American
television, a separate interview to be broadcast internationally
and a book.
</P>
<P>
   If completed, the deal, first reported Thursday in Variety,
would pull together several divisions of The News Corp., Fox's
parent company: the interview would be conducted as an
entertainment show on the Fox network, the book would be published
by HarperCollins and the international interview would be carried
by BSkyB or some other broadcaster owned by The News Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Variety reported that Ms. Lewinsky would be paid $3 million for
the package, but one Fox executive, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, called the figure ``way out of line.''
</P>
<P>
   A Lewinsky spokeswoman, Judy Smith, would not comment on the
report of talks with Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fox executives said they did not believe that any deal
with Ms. Lewinsky was close to completion because other bidders
were still active and Ms. Lewinsky was known to be seeking an
intermediary to negotiate whatever deal she pursues.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Tyrer, a spokesman for the Fox Broadcasting Co., said the
company would have no further official comment beyond confirming
that ``discussions are taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Fox executive who spoke on condition of anonymity said
Fox had firmly decided that any interview the network conducts with
Ms. Lewinsky would be done through its entertainment division,
because no news division could legitimately pay for an interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
